<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HAWKS-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHISTLE BLOWS ON KNICKS' STREAK AS HAWKS WIN DEFENSIVE BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An irate Jeff Van Gundy nearly spun to his knees in
disbelief. He had just watched the New York Knicks scramble to make
up for their unsightly effort Wednesday night, and now he was
hearing a whistle that sounded like fingernails across a
chalkboard.
</P>
<P>
   He cringed and screamed, ``No, no, no, we've worked too hard for
this. No.''
</P>
<P>
   Referee George Toliver just ignored him and walked away. He was
sticking to his call that came after an unlikely 3-pointer by Larry
Johnson cut the Atlanta Hawks' lead to 1 point with 9.5 seconds
remaining. Just before the inbounds pass by the Hawks, Toliver saw
Allan Houston grab the wrist of Steve Smith and called him for a
dead-ball foul.
</P>
<P>
   And that foul cost the Knicks dearly. The Hawks went on to to
win a game that played out like a demolition derby, 76-73, and
broke the Knicks' three-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   The loss punctured the feel-good mood of the Knicks, whose hold
on the eighth and final playoff spot trembled just a bit. With four
games left in their season, the Knicks (24-22) hold a half-game
lead over Charlotte and will play a very hot Philadelphia team
Thursday night at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks lost a little breathing space Friday night, and Van
Gundy lost his temper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it was a foul or wasn't, I've never seen that call in
10 years in a close game,'' Van Gundy said, referring to the
dead-ball foul, which, in the last 2 minutes of a game, results in
a free throw and the opposition's possession of the ball. ``George
Toliver is a good guy, but that's not an NBA call.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bad call. First of all, it wasn't a foul. The whole
game was like a locked-up game. If the question is, do you make it
be decided by letting the ball be inbounded and then you call it,
yes. But that's not an NBA call right there.''
</P>
<P>
   The call resulted in a free throw by Steve Smith. When the Hawks
retained possession, Smith was purposely fouled and sent to the
line with 7.8 seconds left. He hit both free throws and finished
off a three-point swing to give the Hawks a 72-68 lead.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough. A wild 3-pointer by Latrell Sprewell fell with
5.5 seconds left to once again cut the Hawks' lead to one point,
but it was too little too late. The Knicks, who sent the Hawks to
the line 43 times in the game, including 21 times in the fourth
quarter, had nothing left to give.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I did enough to have that foul called,'' Houston
said. ``But you hate to place the blame for a loss on a call. It
was pivotal. But we shouldn't have been in that position.''
</P>
<P>
   They were in a tough spot. Although Sprewell was thriving in an
offense that he took over, and scored 29 points, the ball stopped
moving as well as it had been in the Knicks' previous two games
without Patrick Ewing. The Knicks, who had 20 turnovers, got sucked
into running and gunning with no plan.
</P>
<P>
   Houston was out of sorts, hitting just 4 of 11. And Johnson made
just 2 of 10 shots by trying to maneuver around Dikembe Mutombo,
who scored 18 points and altered dozens of shots. Still, the
Knicks, who held the Hawks to 31 percent from the floor, had a
chance to recover from their messy night. But the whistle, in part,
stopped them.
</P>
<P>
   ``George got the guy holding onto his wrist under the basket,''
the head referee, Bernie Fryer, explained afterward. ``And in that
situation, in the last 2 minutes of the fourth, it's an away from
the play foul.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Only in the end did the Knicks put together a run after trailing
by as many as nine points early in the fourth quarter. After the
two teams combined for just 19 third-quarter points _ an NBA low
for the third quarter points since the 24-second clock was
introduced in 1954 _ the Knicks trailed by five points entering the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks got the better end of the nightmarish quarter, leading
by 52-47 entering the fourth quarter. Harassed by the Hawks,
Sprewell scored only two points. Obviously, he was not the only one
off his mark. Houston missed all five of his shots as the Knicks
shot 25 percent in the third quarter and committed five turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   True, these were two defensive teams. But there was no
accounting for the thoughtless turnovers both teams were making.
And it didn't just begin in the third quarter. The third was only a
manifestation of what began at tipoff.
</P>
<P>
   To a point, Sprewell rescued the Knicks in the first half. But
he could not completely make up for the advantage the Hawks had
with Mutombo. Without Ewing to counter the hulking presence of
Mutombo, the Knicks had a difficult time patrolling him without
getting into foul trouble. Mutombo, who scored 12 points in the
first half, put Chris Dudley into foul trouble after just 10
minutes on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   As damaging as Mutombo was, Sprewell was even more devastating.
Taking advantage of an assortment of Hawks _ from Tyrone Corbin and
Alan Henderson to Anthony Johnson and Steve Smith _ Sprewell spun
and drove by them all on his way to 13 trips to the free-throw
line. He hit 11 of 13 from the line and was 3 for 4 from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sprewell failed to get his teammates involved, they
seemed almost happy he decided to take over. Johnson was
struggling, going 0 for 5 in the first half, and Houston was of no
use in the first quarter, turning the ball over four times. Houston
spent most of the second quarter on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five days ago we were given up for dead,'' Van Gundy said
before the game. ``We're a little closer, but we're no sure thing.
We felt good the last time we went on a three-game winning streak
and then went on a four-game losing streak. If you have even a
little less focus, you drop back down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
