<SLUG> BC-CAR-CAL500-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR RELATIVELY COMPETITIVE CIRCUIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LOUIS BREWSTER  
 Inland Valley Daily Bulletin  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ NASCAR has long prided itself on being family
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The sanctioning body features as many children and women as
drivers in its numerous commercials. So it shouldn't come as a
surprise that three father-son combinations and six sets of
brothers will compete this weekend in the NASCAR tripleheader at
the California Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Two families will be represented by three brothers. The
father-son combinations represent the latest generation into stock
car racing. In the case of the Petty clan, it's four generations.
Kyle Petty, son of NASCAR's all-time winningest driver, is slated
to drive in the Winston Cup NAPA California 500 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Petty will be working the ABC broadcast for the
Busch Grand National Auto Club 300, which will feature 18-year-old
Adam Petty. Young Adam is not only following in the footsteps of
his father, but grandfather Richard and great-grandfather Lee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty cool,'' said Kyle of the family connection.
``There are plenty of Richard Petty fans in Southern California and
I think they'll be rooting for Adam.''
</P>
<P>
   In Dale and Dale Earnhardt Jr., not only are two generations
represented, but also champions from both series. The elder
Earnhardt, fresh from last Sunday's DieHard 500 victory at
Talladega (Ala.) Superspeedway, has won seven Winston Cup
championships, tying Richard Petty for the record.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jr., defending champion of the California Busch race,
joined his father in the trophy room by claiming the Busch
championship last season. Dale Jr., who has raced brother Kerry in
Busch races this season, follows in the footsteps of father Dale
and his late grandfather, Ralph, one of NASCAR's pioneers.
</P>
<P>
   The Jarrett family will also be well represented. Patriarch Ned
is best known for his television coverage. Son Dale will race in
both the Winston Cup and Busch events. Grandson Jason is scheduled
to compete in Saturday's feature race.
</P>
<P>
   The Wallace and Bodine families also will be out in force. Rusty
and Kenny Wallace are Winston Cup regulars. Rusty, who posted his
49th career win at Bristol (Tenn.) Motor Speedway three weeks ago,
drives the No. 2 Miller Lite Ford entry; Kenny is in the No. 55
Square D Chevrolet. Mike Wallace, a regular in the Craftsman Truck
Series, will race in the Winston West event. He won the series
opener this year at Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the three Bodine brothers, who were involved in a family
dispute that attracted national attention, are Winston Cup
tourists. Brett is the driver-owner of the No. 11 Paychek Ford;
older brother Geoffrey is in the No. 60 Power Team Chevrolet. Todd
Bodine, youngest in the family, is a regular in the Busch series.
Although he'll be driving the No. 66 Phillips 76 Chevrolet for
Saturday's race, he won the inaugural California Busch race in July
1997 while driving the No. 36 Stanley Works car.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining four sets of brothers are all part of the Winston
Cup brigade. They are Darrell and Michael Waltrip; Terry and Bobby
Labonte; Jeff and Ward Burton; and crew chiefs Robin and Ryan
Pemberton.
</P>
<P>
   The Labonte and Burton brothers are pretty close in age, the
same can't be said for the Waltrips. At 52, Darrell (No. 39 Big
Kmart Ford) is 17 years older than Michael (No. 7 Philips Ford).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're closer now than we've ever been. We weren't close at all
when he started,'' said Darrell, who won his first driving title
(1981) before Michael started in Winston Cup (1985). ``I was in my
prime at the time and trying to take care of my own career.''
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Waltrip has won 84 races in his career and three driving
championships. Michael is searching for his first victory in 403
career starts.
</P>
<P>
   The Labontes are seven years apart and a lot closer on the
track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work together a little bit more than some guys,'' said
Terry, at 42, the oldest of Bob Labonte's sons. ``We actually get
along, not like some other brothers in this sport.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be a swipe at the feuding Bodines, who have since
patched up their differences exposed during the first Brickyard 400
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The Burtons staged a spirited duel in Las Vegas earlier this
year, but it was Jeff, 31, who outlasted Ward, 37, to claim the
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racing has brought us closer,'' said Ward, who will drive the
No. 22 Pontiac for Bill Davis Racing. But he can recall a time when
they were too close, on the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were at South Boston. I had just moved up to late model
stock. I guess that was 1987, and Jeff had been there for a couple
of years,'' Ward said earlier this year. ``A guy named Bobby Moon
out of Lynchburg (Tenn.) was leading the race. I had been gaining
on him and was about to take the lead with 15 to go when a caution
came out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff had caught up, he was running third. Once they threw the
green flag, we had run about one lap. Jeff had about six inches up
underneath me, and I came down and we both wrecked. To make a long
story short, once I got out of the car, I got him by the throat and
was picking him up in the air when I saw my dad coming. That's when
I got back to my pits.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
