<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PADRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT PADRES, 3-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The feeling of hitting a game-winning home run, Mike
Piazza said on Wednesday night after hitting one, is indescribable.
His came off Trevor Hoffman in the bottom of the ninth inning and
it gave the New York Mets an improbable 4-3 victory over the San
Diego Padres at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great feeling,'' Piazza said after drilling a
first-pitch fastball into the bullpen in right field for a two-run
homer that turned a 3-2 deficit into a victory. ``You go deaf from
the crowd. And to see your teammates like that, it's a thrill.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially for someone who had been struggling with his timing.
No wonder Piazza thrust both arms in the air as he ran up the
first-base line. And all he could see when he approached home plate
were white shirts. Rey Ordonez nearly tackled Piazza, who said he
emerged from the scrum with his shirt torn off.
</P>
<P>
   And the crowd of 22,581 left the stadium chanting team slogans
with glee.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? Not only had the Mets won despite stranding 12 runners,
but they had also left at least two on in every inning from the
fourth inning on. And after Armando Benitez was finally charged
with his first runs of the season after nine scoreless appearances,
on came San Diego's ace closer, Hoffman, who saved 53 games in 54
chances last year. The Mets were staring at their fourth straight
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   It had been nearly three years since the Padres had lost a game
they led after 8 innings. San Diego was 181-0 in such situations
since July 24, 1996, 85-0 last season, 7-0 this year. But Hoffman
is not so automatic anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the things prior to this don't amount to a hill of beans
right now,'' said Hoffman, who allowed a single to John Olerud
through short one pitch before Piazza hit the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself fortunate,'' said Piazza, who is now 4 for
10 against Hoffman with 3 homers and 9 runs batted in. ``The worst
thing about it is that we have to come right back tomorrow. I wish
we had a few days to enjoy it. But hopefully it will get us
going.''
</P>
<P>
   The late heroics saved Al Leiter, who took a 2-1 lead into the
seventh that could very easily have been more.
</P>
<P>
   From the fourth through sixth innings, the Mets, who lead the
league in men left on base, left seven runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   With the bases loaded in the fourth, Ordonez grounded into an
inning-ending double play that not even a head-first dive into
first base could prevent.
</P>
<P>
   With runners on first and second and one out in the fifth,
Olerud _ who had previously homered and singled _ sliced a fly to
left for the second out, and Piazza popped to first, swinging at
the first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   With the bases loaded and one out in the sixth, Leiter took five
straight pitches and was called out on strikes, before Rickey
Henderson, like Piazza, popped to first on the first pitch that
they saw.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Mets were 1 for 6 with runners in scoring position
through six innings, the only productive hit being Edgardo
Alfonzo's shattered-bat double down the left field line that broke
a 1-1 tie in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   So when the Padres put runners on first and second with nobody
out in the seventh, Leiter probably wished his team had managed
something more from those wasted opportunities. And when Ruben
Rivera moved the runners to second and third with a ground out,
Leiter's chance to lose the lead increased.
</P>
<P>
   But the veteran left-hander bore down and struck out San Diego's
No. 8 hitter, Damian Jackson on a high fastball. Then, with Eric
Owens pinch-hitting for Sterling Hitchcock, Leiter induced Owens
into hitting a grounder to second, and now it was the Padre hitters
who were unable to cash in opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   It wound up costing them the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
