<SLUG> BC-LA-SCHOOL-REFORM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESPONSE TO NEW L.A. SCHOOL ACCOUNTABILITY PLAN MIXED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVID R. BAKER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- A new policy that could strip some low-performing
Los Angeles schools of their administrative independence provoked
cautious support and anxious questions Wednesday among educators.
</P>
<P>
   Many wondered how the plan would work but few questioned its
underlying principle -- that schools should be responsible for
student achievement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a problem with being held accountable for student
performance. That's my job,'' said Earl Edward Barner, principal of
Los Angeles High School.
</P>
<P>
   Barner's is one of 30 schools citywide currently on academic
probation. Under a policy approved by the city's Board of Education
on Tuesday, those schools could lose their authority to make many
administrative decisions -- including personnel and spending
decisions -- if their students' Stanford 9 test scores don't
improve.
</P>
<P>
   Should even that step fail to boost scores, those schools could
face ``reconstitution,'' the takeover of the school by the
district.
</P>
<P>
   Olive Vista Middle School in Sylmar and Pacoima Elementary
School are the only San Fernando Valley schools listed by the
district as being on academic probation. The principal at Olive
Vista Middle School, Charles Baldwin, declined to talk about the
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Gonzales, principal of Pacoima Elementary, said
Wednesday his school had recently been taken off probation, but
district officials said the school remains on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders expressed qualified support for the plan Wednesday
but wondered about the details. The policy approved Tuesday
contained only broad directives, they said.
</P>
<P>
   While agreeing with the plan's basic premise, Eli Brent, head of
the district's administrators union, said the district should first
give principals greater leeway to make changes at their schools
before administrative powers are taken away.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to hold the principal responsible, which I
agree with, you have to give them the authority to do something
about it,'' Brent said.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the district's teachers union, who had
threatened to file an unfair labor practice grievance over the
proposal, said his organization would hold off on its threat until
it had further discussed the plan with the district. Day Higuchi of
United Teachers Los Angeles said he wanted teachers to be part of
assessment teams that would go into failing schools and figure out
how to fix them.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
