<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARTOYS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SNEAK PREVIEW OF `STAR WARS' TOYS
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JAIMEE ROSE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lucasfilm is fending off reporters by the dozen. The Internet is
buzz ing with rumors. Fans are plotting to be first in line.
</P>
<P>
   And we aren't talking about the movie. Frighteningly, this is
just about the toys.
</P>
<P>
   At 12:01 a.m. Monday, the new Star Wars playthings will descend
upon the country with a nearly deaf ening marketing roar.
</P>
<P>
   The toys have been under security that rivals that of precious
jewels. The stolen pictures on the Internet aren't supposed to be
there, the toys for sale on eBay aren't supposed to exist yet, and
you're not supposed to know most of what we're going to tell you in
this article, either.
</P>
<P>
   As they work up to the national release of Star Wars: Episode I
_ The Phantom Menace on May 19, the folks at Lucasfilm want to keep
the mystique. And they want May 3 to be like Christmas for Star
Wars fans, rather than a day of disap pointment for spoilers who
opened their gifts early.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers have been scared silent by rumors that if the goods
are dis played, advertised outside the store or even breathed on
before Monday, Lucasfilm and/or Hasbro, the chief manufacturer,
will withhold all fu ture shipments.
</P>
<P>
   But at 12:01 a.m. Monday, all mysteries will be revealed when
the store wars begin. Retailers across the country, including Toys
`R' Us stores in the Valley, are planning to take advantage of the
first minute of the first date the embargo is lifted. They can
unveil then, and only then, what the industry expects to be the
largest, and most successful, line of merchandise in the history of
toys.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a sneak peek, mostly due to two folks: local collector
Oliver Hirsch, who found a naughty Chan dler Kmart that sold toys
early, and Dallas Web junkie Philip Wise, who found his own Star
Wars toy manu facturing sources in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   The big news: The toys can talk . . . to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro's new 3}-inch action fig ures feature COMMTECH technol
ogy. Each includes a microchip that, when paired with a COMMTECH
reader (sold separately for about $30), allows the figures to speak
up to four lines of dialogue from the movie with each other.
</P>
<P>
   The action figures, created by Hasbro, will cost about $7 each,
and there will be about 25 of them. They include characters unique
to Episode I: young Anakin Skywalker, new droids and the evil Darth
Maul. There will also be Qui-Gon Jinn, a Jedi Master; Queen
Amidala, the leader of the good side; and Jar Jar Binks, a new
space creature ex pected to obtain a cult following a la Boba Fett.
</P>
<P>
   There also will be new and younger versions of old friends:
Obi-Wan Kenobi, a brassless C-3PO and even a Jabba the Hutt that
oozes slime.
</P>
<P>
   Lucasfilm spokeswoman Jeanne Cole said the staff at Skywalker
Ranch, especially George Lucas himself, is having a heyday with the
talking figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recently had them all out at lunch, seeing what they
said,'' Cole said. ``He (George Lucas) thought they were great. He
has all the toys.''
</P>
<P>
   A fleet of vehicles is also on the way, including pod racers,
which play a big part in the movie; Trade Federation Droid
Fighters, the vehi cles of the evil side; and Queen Amidala's Royal
Starship, which will be about 4 feet long and cost $100.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a new conventional lightsaber, there will be a
double-bladed lightsaber (used by Darth Maul in the movie) that
will go for about $35.
</P>
<P>
   Lego will offer microprocessor-based droid-development kits that
allow kids to create functional, mov ing versions of R2-D2 and
other droids. There will also be a whole Lego line of Episode I
scenes and vehicles toy kits.
</P>
<P>
   Thinkaway Toys has created Star Wars piggy banks that feature
ani matronic technology. The banks will be topped by three figures
_ Obi-Wan Kenobi, Qui-Gon Jinn and Darth Maul _ who will come to
life at the drop of a coin, arguing and engaging in lightsaber
duels.
</P>
<P>
   There also will be card games, board games and video games,
in-line skates, bedding and fruit snacks.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the original Star Wars toys released in 1977, these new
toys won't be hard to come by, though some stores will limit
customers looking to buy more than two of each toy. This is bad
news for col lectors, who won't be able to make fortunes off rare
toys, but good news for fans who want their share of the loot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a goal to keep our toys in stock,'' said Hasbro
spokeswoman Holly Ingram. ``We've tried to make our production
forecast meet what we think demand is going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Philip Wise, a 40-something Star Wars fan in Dallas, has had
pictures, prices and dimensions of the new toys up on the Fandom
Menace Web site (www.fandommenace.com) for weeks. Wise, like most
people who've landed unauthorized ad vance samples, got the toys
from a contact in Hong Kong, where they are produced. He logs more
than 22,000 hits per day from fans want ing to take a peek.
</P>
<P>
   Lucasfilm's reaction to this Inter net phenomenon and to other
sites dedicated to spreading Episode I ru mors is not anger at
spoiling the surprise, as one might think.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had to decide long ago that we would sit and watch it
with with wonder and amusement,'' Cole said. ``The people who crave
that information are our fans, and none of this excitement would be
there without them.''
</P>
<P>
   Webmaster Wise concurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing the stuff early has gotten a lot more excitement
going,'' he said. ``As much as Lucasfilm prob ably wishes (the
pictures) never showed up, I think it's created a lot of buzz for
them.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
