<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA LAWMAKERS VOTE TO MOVE BACK PRIMARY DATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lawmakers voted Wednesday to delay Arizona's 2000 presidential
primary by three weeks, a move opponents say is a blatant attempt
to help Sen. John McCain's campaign that would also reduce the
state's political clout nationally.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal surfaced suddenly Wednesday in a hastily called
conference committee on an obscure bill relating to ballot stubs. A
McCain campaign aide, Wes Gullett, watched from the back row of
seats in the room.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers said Gullett had pushed the date changes for much of
the session. The bill still faces final votes in the House and
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   McCain could not be reached for comment, while campaign aides
ducked questions about the senator's position on the change.
</P>
<P>
   The primary is currently slated for Feb. 22, placing Arizona in
a strategic position just after early contests in Iowa and New
Hampshire but before critical tests for large numbers of delegates
March 7 in New York and California.
</P>
<P>
   The new date would be March 14, a day when six Southern states
are scheduled to hold primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe Arizona would drop off the political map if the
date is pushed back into the heart of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once California goes, that's really the state in the West.
Obviously, Arizona wouldn't get as much attention from
candidates,'' said Bruce Merrill, an Arizona State University
pollster and professor of journalism. ``You're not going to get
near the interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the change, including Sen. Marc Spitzer, R-north
central Phoenix, said the date would allow more people to
participate in the primary because March 14 is one of four dates
for elections in Arizona, meaning more people would be aware of the
election.
</P>
<P>
   In January, a McCain representative defended the move to a
``Republic'' reporter in much the same language, saying the senator
favored moving the primary to a date that would be ``least
problematic for Arizona voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Hull also favors the switch.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents were quick to accuse McCain of engineering the date
change, suggesting that a loss in Arizona would cripple his
campaign and that the senator doesn't want to expend resources
defending his own state.
</P>
<P>
   Several recent polls show that in Arizona McCain trails Texas
Gov. George W. Bush by as many as 8 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   ``(McCain) set his sights on California. He's willing to throw
Arizona overboard. It's absolutely wrong,'' said Sidney Hoff Hay, a
political consultant who is working for presidential contender Alan
Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has said that he believes the winner of the California
primary will win the party's nomination. He has made repeated
visits there and plans a vigorous campaign in the Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could our own senator sell out his state for his own
political ambitions? You ought to question whether that kind of
person should be leading this country,'' Hoff Hay said.
</P>
<P>
   Another opponent of the switch, Sen. Scott Bundgaard, said
moving the date would cause most candidates to ignore the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then there's no competition from other candidates for John
McCain and his moderate ideas,'' said Bundgaard, R-Glendale.
Bundgaard is supporting Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's very obvious this change is being made simply to
satisfy John McCain, and they are taking every step to ensure the
possibility that he's victorious in this state. By eliminating
competition, by moving the primary date, it enhances his chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, McCain was one of the people behind the early
primary date. McCain and former Gov. Fife Symington hoped that
Texas Sen. Phil Gramm would win the state, launching his bid for
the GOP nomination. But Gramm was gone by the primary after poor
finishes in Iowa and New Hampshire, and billionaire publisher Steve
Forbes ran away with the race.
</P>
<P>
   Moving the date will be controversial with GOP party activists,
who voted in January to keep the date in February. Mike Minnaugh,
the state GOP chairman, said he stood by that vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party's position was pretty clear in January,'' Minnaugh
said. ``If it goes into March, we'll still have a lot of
excitement, but not as many candidates here.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodie Londen, a former state GOP chairwoman who helped in the
drive for the early date, called the move ``the dumbest thing we
could do.'' She said she understood why McCain wanted the primary
moved to after California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he'll win Arizona,'' said Londen, who is
supporting Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic state chairman Mark Fleisher said the primary
change had nothing to do with McCain's campaign. Democrats have
pushed the March date since 1996 because party rules forbid a
Democratic primary before the first Tuesday in March.
</P>
<P>
   They sat out the 1996 primary. Vice President Al Gore faces
former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley in the 2000 race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that has anything to do with it,'' Fleisher said
of the McCain campaign. ``We're the ones who pushed real hard not
to do it in February. It benefits us to have it on the 14th.''
</P>
<P>
   But rival GOP campaigns expressed concern that McCain was
rigging the process in his home state. Bert Coleman, Forbes'
Arizona campaign coordinator, called the change ``extremely
peculiar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, Steve Forbes will participate in the
Arizona primary regardless of when it is,'' Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Dan Quayle had a similar response, saying the
for mer vice president ``just needs to know the date, and he'll be
here to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill's fate is uncertain. Senate President Brenda Burns said
late Wednesday that she opposed the bill but would not block it if
a majority of Republicans favored it. Democrats will likely support
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not support moving the primary. The position we have is
so good _ we're before California,'' Burns said, adding that she
supports McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not believe that John McCain will lose Arizona.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
