<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DOESN'T RISE FROM ASHES
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fire gets our attention. All heat and light. But then the flames
subside and the smoke dissipates. The em bers cool. Ashes crumble
to dust and scatter in the wind. And we forget.
</P>
<P>
   The name Jermaine ``J.R.'' Miguel Jr. means nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Just about a year ago, the little boy was in all the papers. He
was the first story on all the local TV broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Outside his grandparents' mobile home in Chandler, he came
across a couple of teenage boys making pools of lighter fluid on
the ground, then lighting them.
</P>
<P>
   The older boys would later say J.R. tripped on a barbecue grill
on which they were preparing to cook hot dogs, and his clothing
caught fire. But the story fell apart. The coals in the grill
weren't hot.
</P>
<P>
   What actually happened, investigators later said, is that one of
the boys taunt ingly dangled the 7-year-old over a pit of fire, and
dropped him.
</P>
<P>
   J.R. was burned over 60 percent of his body and spent most of
the next six months in the burn unit of Maricopa Medical Center.
Between then and now, J.R.'s mother, Lori Sumatzkuku, has lost
count of the number of operations her boy has been through.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't know how many times she's traveled between here and
Shriners Hospital in California, where J.R. has his surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   She tries hard not to remember the dark moments in the hospital
when the faces of nurses and doctors told her the tiny, bandaged
boy in the bed may not make it.
</P>
<P>
   DISRUPTED FAMILY LIFE
</P>
<P>
   ``Before this happened, we were a reg ular family with three
kids and jobs and a life that was like everybody's, you know?'' she
says. ``We don't know what that life is like anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   They've returned recently from Califor nia, where doctors had to
cut and stretch J.R.'s grafted skin, a procedure he'll go through
again and again, well into his 20s.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to plastic surgeries. In addi tion to the looks. The
uncomfortable stares. The turned heads of those who can't bear to
look.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a wonderful boy,'' Lori says. ``But his life is going to
be hard. It is hard.''
</P>
<P>
   So is the life of his family.
</P>
<P>
   Lori has had to give up her job as a secretary with the state of
Arizona. And, while the Shriners take care of the actual
operations, the expenses of caring for a burn victim are
considerable.
</P>
<P>
   The medication that kept J.R. alive, for instance, has caused
him to lose most of his hearing. According to Anna Nebel of the
non-profit Foundation for Burns and Trauma, each of the hearing
aids J.R. now needs costs more than $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, which can be reached at (602) 230-2041, is
accepting donations for J.R. and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``On top of all they're already going through,'' Nebel says,
``this family must suffer through a justice system that doesn't
seem to take a crime like this se riously enough.''
</P>
<P>
   A YEAR IN A LIFE
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the boy who dropped J.R. into the fire
pleaded guilty to at tempted aggravated assault. Late last month,
he was sentenced to a year in jail, community service and
probation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son got a life sentence of pain and suffering when the kid
who did this to him gets a year?'' Lori says. ``That's not right.
After that year, he will be fine, his life will be normal, and J.R.
will go for operation after operation. And have to deal with all
the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   She worries about her other children, who don't receive the
attention she used to give them, and which they deserve, be cause
of all she must do for J.R.
</P>
<P>
   She worries about her burned son's ability to overcome all he's
been through and lead a normal life.
</P>
<P>
   She worries that the same thing could happen to another family.
</P>
<P>
   She worries, because she understands that whatever heat and
light another newspaper article may bring to the trag edy of her
son, it won't last.
</P>
<P>
   The glow subsides. The warmth cools. The paper crumbles to dust
and scatters in the wind. And we ask, J.R. who? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 0112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
