<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7436 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-KENTUCKYDERBY-HNS     04-29 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-KENTUCKYDERBY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN TRUEX  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Bob Baffert entered Excellent Meeting in
Saturday's Kentucky Derby and Friday's all-female Kentucky Oaks.
But after pulling a lucky draw Wednesday for post position, he is
expected to let the big bay filly run for the roses.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Had he drawn unfavorably in the 20-horse field, the white-haired
trainer might have settled for the Oaks. But after securing the No.
6 position, Excellent Meeting probably will get her chance to be
the first filly since Winning Colors in 1988 to win America's most
famous horse race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been training her for the Derby,'' Baffert said. ``A lot
had to do with the draw. Right now I'd say she will run in the
Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Excellent Meeting has the same owner (John Mabee) and
trainer as General Challenge, the two will form a betting entry.
They became the morning-line favorite at 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert's third horse, Prime Timber, is the second choice, by
himself, at 7-2. He probably would be the morning-line chalk if
Excellent Meeting, winner of five Grade I stakes, were not entered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's training the best she's ever trained,'' Baffert
said. ``She loves this track; she's handling the turns really
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Kent Desormeaux, who could have ridden a talented colt, Aljabr,
in the Derby, accepted a ride on Excellent Meeting, whether in the
Derby or the Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Pegram, owner of last year's Derby winner, Real Quiet, and
the champion juvenile filly, Silverbulletday, did not want the
latter running in what he called ``a 20-horse Roller Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   So Silverbulletday, who is also trained by Baffert, will race in
the 1-mile Oaks. ``At a mile and a quarter, Excellent Meeting is
the best horse in the country,'' Pegram said.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's draw, the connections of each horse chose their
own post positions after the order of selection was determined by
lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Desert Hero got first pick, and trainer Richard Mandella chose
No. 7 for a horse who likes to run a length or two off the pace.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Zito, choosing 11th for Adonis, surprised some observers by
taking the rail, with positions 2-11 already filled. The rail is
considered potentially troublesome, since a horse might get jammed
against it.
</P>
<P>
   But Zito explained: ``General Challenge hadn't selected yet; I
don't want to be near Baffert.''
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to stay away from two colts who are sometimes unruly
in the starting gate.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert chose post 14 for Prime Timber, even though he could
have been closer in at 12 or 13. For General Challenge, Baffert
took post 15, which is the first slot in the auxiliary starting
gate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prime Timber gets fidgety in the gate, so I took 14 so nobody
would be on his outside,'' Baffert said. ``General Challenge takes
a step or two to get in gear, and I wanted some open space for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert also preferred outside to inside, so his horses ``would
not have to be in the gate too long.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Nafzger, who drew 17th with Vicar, chose the 18th hole,
which allowed Wayne Lukas with the 18th pick to claim No. 17 for
Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to be late loading, so I went with 18,'' Nafzger said.
``I don't think it matters much whether you're 17, 18 or 19. I
think we have enough speed to get right into the heat of it
early.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas, who put one of his horses, Cat Thief, in the 11th post,
said: ``Carl was generous enough to take one outside of us. We came
out better than I thought with the second horse.''
</P>
<P>
   The significance of post position is always debated, but it
becomes more important the larger the field.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Eddie Plesa, who has the second post for Saturday,
scratched Three Ring out of the Florida Derby when he drew outside
position. ``If we had drawn the 2 post in the Florida Derby,'' he
said, ``we would have run in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Three Ring has morning-line odds of 20-1 but is considered the
second-best filly in the Derby. Excellent Meeting is the filly who
is feared.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's earned her way into the Derby,'' Baffert said. ``She's
good enough to win.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the other horsemen was disputing that contention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
