<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7441 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      04-29 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
When the Rockets watched the less-than-entertaining film of last
week's game against Dallas, the problem was obvious.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The film was running, the Mavericks were running the Rockets
were not.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of the expected cakewalk over one of the NBA's
doormats, the Rockets walked around and got cake thrown in their
faces in a 109-95 loss at Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called defensive intensity,'' Rockets guard Brent Price
said. ``It's just a matter of getting back (on defense), hustling
to make them make harder shots. They were getting easy shots _
layups, dunks and fast breaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where the games are won. If you establish yourself
defensively, and everyone runs back and matches up to take away
those easy baskets, they have to score in the half-court offense,
and it's a lot tougher for them.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not tough that night for the Mavs, who outscored the
Rockets 24-5 on fast-break points.
</P>
<P>
   There was a complete turnaround for the Rockets in their last
outing against the Los Angeles Lakers on Monday as they ran out to
an 18-0 halftime advantage on fast-break points and finished with a
26-4 edge in a 22-point win.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem (against Dallas) was definitely team defense.
That's all it was,'' Rockets guard Cuttino Mobley said. ``We have
to come out and set the tone on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Mobley ignited the Rockets with 12 points and a pair
of steals in the first quarter, when they built a 14-point lead on
the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to do the same thing I did against LA,'' Mobley said.
``I need to continue it each game. We woke up. Now, we've just got
to go and play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets believe the Mavericks caught them napping last week
and made them pay for it. But not only did the Rockets lack the
intensity needed to win, Dallas played one of its best games of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you play like they did every night, you will have the best
record in the league,'' Rockets center Hakeem Olajuwon said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavs, while far from being a playoff contender, have been
much better of late. With a win over Vancouver on Tuesday, Dallas
guaranteed itself its first winning season at home since 1989-90 _
the last time the Mavericks made the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas is 17-29 this season, with seven of those victories
coming in April. The Mavericks have wins this month over San
Antonio, Phoenix, Minnesota and the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   What distinguished the win over the Rockets was that it was the
lone victory of the bunch to come on the road. Dallas is one of the
league's weakest road teams, with a 3-19 mark away from Reunion
Arena. Only Denver (2-22) and Vancouver (1-22) are worse.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets are the only team with a winning record that Dallas
has managed to beat on the road this season (the other two wins
were against the Warriors and Clippers), and the victory at Compaq
Center snapped an 11-game road losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully it won't happen again; that better not happen
again,'' Rockets forward Charles Barkley said. ``Dallas just kicked
our butts last week. We really can't do anything about that. We
just have to come out ready to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets failed to do that the last time the Mavericks were
in town. Dallas scored 61 points in the first half _ the most the
Rockets have given up in the first two quarters all season _ and
shot a blistering 53 percent from the field for the game. This from
a team making 43.2 percent of its shots this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played well,'' Barkley said. ``They could have beaten
anybody that night.''
</P>
<P>
   There were some superlative performances from the Mavericks.
Rookie Dirk Nowitzki, who is shooting 40 percent and averaging 7.7
points, lit up the Rockets for 22 points on 10-of-13 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon and Scottie Pippen said the Rockets entered the game
with little respect for the Mavs' ability to pull off such a win
and were put in their place as a result.
</P>
<P>
   In this lockout-shortened season, teams can afford few such
lapses, and waiting for wake-up calls could prove costly.
Fortunately for the Rockets, the loss to the Mavs, which started a
three-game skid that included setbacks to the Clippers and Suns,
has not been extremely costly.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets, who have five games left, remain in control of the
fourth playoff seed in the Western Conference, meaning they would
have the home-court advantage in a first-round postseason series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's not always a bad thing to have the rug pulled
from under your feet a little bit,'' Price said. ``Then you can
say, `Look, we need to focus on our internal problems and what
we're doing on the court as a team and not look ahead.' I don't
think you're going to see us _ at least I hope not _ taking any
team for granted after we got beat by Dallas and the Clippers.
Hopefully, that was an eye-opener for us, and we're not going to
let anything come back and bite us again like that.''
</P>
<P>
   If they paid attention to the film, the Rockets know that if
they see it coming, they had better start running.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
