</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-BREWERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT BREWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Chan Ho Park is revered in his native Korea, where
his popularity equals, if not exceeds, that of Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   He can do nothing about that pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Park is also pitching for a contract. He won't be eligible for
free agency until after the 2001 season, but the Los Angeles
Dodgers wish to lock him into a long-term deal.
</P>
<P>
   He's alleviated that pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago Park said he won't sign a contract during the
season. Two days ago his agent told the Dodgers he wouldn't even
discuss a contract until the season ends. And after leading the
Dodgers to a 3-2 win Wednesday against the Milwaukee Brewers, Park
admitted a burden was lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Park (2-2) bounced back from his last start, in which he was
shelled for 11 runs, to pitch 62/3 innings of two-run ball. He also
delivered a two-run double in the sixth inning off loser Steve
Woodard (2-2) to provide the tying and winning runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The contract) was bothering me because I was trying to show
them I was good, but it was wrong,'' Park said. ``I still thought
about it a little bit, but I don't get pressure from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Park will earn $2.3 million this season and is eligible for
salary arbitration in November and after the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers offered Park a four-year, $20 million deal during
the offseason, but it was refused. Park and agent Steve Kim are
seeking a four- or five-year deal worth approximately $30 to $36
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agreed to wait until after the season to talk,'' Dodgers
general manager Kevin Malone said. ``We still want to do something
long-term with Chan Ho. We want him to have a big year.''
</P>
<P>
   Park said he wants to remain with the Dodgers, and with
negotiations in the past _ and future _ he looked more like his old
self, challenging hitters inside and aggressively using his
fastball. He allowed an RBI single to Jeromy Burnitz in the first
and consecutive doubles to Marquis Grissom and Geoff Jenkins in the
second, and shut the Brewers down the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers left fielder Gary Sheffield, ejected in the ninth for
arguing a strike call, had an RBI single in the third before Park
defied the Dodgers' modus operandi and delivered a hit with a
runner in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   After catcher Todd Hundley was intentionally walked for the
second consecutive time, Park hit Woodard's 1-0 fastball off the
wall in center field to score Raul Mondesi and Hundley and give the
Dodgers a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God for (Park)'s bat,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson
said. ``I know he was fighting himself a little early. He gave us
just what we needed. We needed him to get him his confidence again.
I needed for him to give me about seven innings. He was more free.
Everything was sharper, in and out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (11-10) won back-to-back games for the first time
since April 9 and 10, and the formula was perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Like the previous day, Milwaukee took an early 2-1 lead and the
Dodgers scored twice in the sixth to go ahead 3-2. And for the
second consecutive day the Dodgers used a left-hander out of the
bullpen to record the last out of the seventh inning _ Onan Masaoka
this time _ had Alan Mills pitch the eighth and used Jeff Shaw in
the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``In spring training, when you looked at it, that was the
blueprint,'' Shaw said after recording his sixth save. ``Use the
left-handers to get to Mills to get to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
