<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7447 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  PM-BUDGET-NYT     04-29 1992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For THURSDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Thursday, April 29.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TOWN (Surdulica, Yugoslavia) _ Story from the town where
roughly 20 civilians, including children, were killed in NATO
attack that hit residential area. The attack destroyed 3 houses in
one place, 10 in another, many damaged. Plus other developments,
including the dismissal by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic of
Vuk Draskovic, the deputy prime minister. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis on the
Clinton administration's efforts to have Russia bail out NATO with
a Kosovo solution. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NJ-PROFILING-MOTELS (Trenton, N.J.) _ In an effort to catch drug
smugglers who travel through Newark International Airport, the New
Jersey State Police have quietly enlisted workers at dozens of
motels to tip them off about suspicious guests, according to people
who have participated in the program. By David Kocieniewski.
</P>
<P>
   GAMBLING-COMMISSION (Washington) _ A federal commission is
preparing to send Congress and the president sweeping
recommendations for the gambling industry, including a moratorium
on gambling expansion and some form of federal regulation of the
giant casinos on Indian reservations.
</P>
<P>
   TEEN-BIRTHS (Washington) _ The teen-age birth rate, which has
been dropping steadily for six years, has dipped so sharply that it
has helped push the nation's overall birth rate to the lowest point
since the government began keeping records in 1909, according to
data by the National Center for Health Statistics. By Sheryl Gay
Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA-DUKE (Metairie, La.) _ On the surface, the special
election to be held here Saturday is about who will replace Robert
Livingston. But the undercurrent is whether this will be the race
that finally cures the state, and the Republican Party, of the
angst generated by David E. Duke. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   STARWARS-SIDEWALK-SITTERS (Los Angeles) _ The new Star Wars is
coming out and kids are sleeping at Mann's Chinese Theater until
May 19. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-CONTROL (Undated) _ On the increasing splits in the
gun-control lobby over the best way to tighten gun laws, especially
in view of President Clinton's proposals on Tuesday. By Barry
Meier.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHIP-HACKER (San Francisco) _ When privacy advocates first
sounded alarms in January about a serial number that Intel Corp.
had embedded in its new Pentium III processor, the company quickly
responded by distributing software that enabled owners of Pentium
III computers to hide the number. But it now appears that the
problem is not solved. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   MCKESSON-AUDIT-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ In what is sure to become
fodder for shareholder groups who oppose frequent mergers, McKesson
HBOC Inc., the nation's largest drug wholesaler, announced
Wednesday that it would have to restate earnings for the last four
quarters after discovering improperly recorded sales from its
recently acquired software business. By David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   STEEL-COMPETE (Weirton, W.Va.) _ Workers here and in other steel
towns say they are fighting for nothing less than their jobs, their
way of life and the fate of the American steel industry. The have
taken their pain to Washington, promoting a measure that would
impose quotas on imported steel and roll back imports to pre-1998
levels. But critics deride quota legislation as dangerous, illegal
and unnecessary. Not only do they say it would cost American
consumers an estimated $6 billion, but it comes at a time when the
American economy's demand for steel is at an all-time high. By
Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Locator map
has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MULLEN-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The largest remaining independent
agency in New England remains independent no longer. Mullen
Advertising, a creatively focused shop in Wenham, Mass., said
Wednesday that it had agreed to sell a majority equity stake to
Lowe Group in London, part of the Interpublic Group of Companies.
By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   FOREIGN-AID-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ Treasury Secretary Robert E.
Rubin's proposal for reforming international financial
institutions, announced on the eve of this week's gathering of the
world's finance officials in Washington, was greeted mostly with
yawns. His ideas were described as modest or cautious _ tinkering
in a financially hazardous world that cries out for bold
architectural overhaul. By Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Washington) _ William Safire on the suspected
theft of U.S. nuclear weapons secrets.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TONY-AWARDS (New York) _ Questions over what qualifies for a
Tony Award: At a time when producing on Broadway has become
prohibitively expensive and a top rung Tony can mean the difference
between long life or quick death, the theater world is already
awash in award controversy, even before next Monday's announcement
of who the actual nominees are. By Robin Pogrebin.
