<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7450 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     04-29 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
AFTER one inning Wednesday night, it seemed clear the Astros had
erred.
</P>
<P>
   What, we asked ourselves, was Chris Holt doing in the starting
rotation? And why in the world was Scott Elarton languishing in the
bullpen?
</P>
<P>
   To the untrained eye, Holt had thrown like a dolt, allowing the
Diamondbacks to bat around while taking a 3-0 lead. The five hits
and one walk added to the eight hits and two walks he surrendered
in his previous start, an aborted one of 4 innings in Cincinnati,
did not a pretty picture paint.
</P>
<P>
   You do the math please. Those kind of numbers terrify me.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there sat Elarton, a picture of calm and confidence
on the bench. The Ordained One who was deemed untouchable even for
Roger Clemens was in possession of a zero-point-zero-zero ERA and a
2-0 record through six appearances. He was busily attempting to
make a mockery of the spring training decision to relegate him to
middle-relief Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   He was still miffed, to be sure, but he was no longer
verbalizing his disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Which is good because the debate became a great deal more
clouded as the long evening wore on (and on and on). Holt's
deceptively disappointing first inning was followed by five
perfectly commendable innings _ two hits allowed, no runs _ and the
Astros rewarded him for his diligence and resilience by claiming a
5-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   A 5-3 lead that Elarton promptly blew in the time it took him to
pitch to four batters. Single, single, sacrifice, double: Arizona
5, Houston 5. Just like that, a reality check for the (soon-to-be)
Great Scott.
</P>
<P>
   Holt, for his part, remains winless at 0-3 after losing all of
last year to shoulder surgery. But his ability to personally stave
off catastrophe against the Arizonans ensured he won't get yanked
from the rotation any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   He has proved deserving of our patience for as long as he keeps
his wits about him because, medically, his arm is fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``No pain, none at all,'' he insisted. ``They don't have me on
any kind of pitch count. I could have stayed in the game. But he
(manager Larry Dierker)'s the boss. I don't question his
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Dierker: ``I liked Chris' stuff, even in the first inning.
He could very easily have escaped it without giving up a run. If
he's happy with the way he pitched, then I'm happy, too. We've just
got to take him from throwing the ball well to getting a few wins
under his belt. The only thing that would concern me is his
becoming frustrated with his record.''
</P>
<P>
   It could happen. Holt admits he retired to the clubhouse after
the first inning and let a bit of steam off. He raised enough Cain,
in fact, to draw the attention of Craig Biggio and Mike Hampton all
the way back in the dugout. Both came to pay him a consoling visit,
if for no other reason than to ensure he didn't destroy their
lockers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Biggio) reminded me it's a nine-inning game,'' Holt said,
``and Hampy told me, `Hey, dude, it's OK. This team can score some
runs for you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton was right on about the runs. He was wrong, however,
about the worrying part, although Holt was taken off the hook at
the end. For a guy with an 8-16 major-league record, there are
worse things than a no-decision.
</P>
<P>
   Elarton, to be fair, didn't do himself any damage, either. It's
not like anybody really expected him to post a 0.00 for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto Billy Wagner, although he had trained us to assume a
disaster of Wednesday's force-five magnitude shouldn't be possible.
Yes, ultimately, Billy the Kid took the loss with a capital,
bold-faced ``L,'' glumly watching his also previously pristine ERA
go from nada to a lotta _ 6.43 _ in a ninth inning that was every
bit as dreadful as it looked.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Holt's first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy got behind the hitters,'' Dierker said, ``and had to
bring the ball over the middle of the plate. You know what can
happen when you do that.''
</P>
<P>
   So, once again, the Diamondbacks batted around. Wagner never
could get an out, much less get out of the inning. The five
visiting Snakes he faced stung him with either a hit or a walk, and
by the time the carnage was complete all scored. The Astros were in
a 10-5 hole that looked more like a bottomless pit.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the crowd of 19,605 had fled before the Astros added a
meaningless sixth run in the bottom of the ninth. Those who stayed
did so mostly to boo and hiss.
</P>
<P>
   And the Astros were blown out in a game in which they socked
three home runs over one span of five at-bats. There was not a bit
of relief to be found on the pitching staff this sad night. I won't
upset you any further by providing the particulars of Jay Powell's
mop-up mishaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good bullpen,'' Holt argued. ``There's nothing wrong
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   A remarkably magnanimous attitude under the circumstances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
