<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES BOW TO RANGERS, 8-6 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Don Zimmer has maintained all along that he
never wanted to manage the New York Yankees, that he is doing so
only because Joe Torre, a close friend, asked him to take over. He
must have been wondering on Wednesday night if it is worth the
aggravation, after an 8-6 loss to Texas and an unhappy exchange
with a coach that prompted a post-game team meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat snapped the Yankees' six-game winning streak, but
even so, the Yankees are 13-6 under Zimmer; with Torre recovering
from prostate cancer surgery and close to returning to the dugout
as manager, Zimmer is on the verge of completing his goal of
delivering the Yankees back into the hands of Torre with a record
reflective of their talent.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer's aggravation might have provided a foundation for what
occurred on Wednesday evening. At some point during the loss,
Zimmer and Jose Cardenal, the Yankees' first-base coach, engaged in
an angry exchange.
</P>
<P>
   it is not known exactly what spurred the incident, but Zimmer
has been adamant about taking charge of the club, through Torre's
authority; any comment questioning a move or strategy would not
have been received well.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees relievers Mike Stanton and Jeff Nelson blew a 4-3
lead in the bottom of the seventh inning, allowing five runs in the
bottom half of the inning, and a late rally fell short. Zimmer
typically addresses members of the news media almost as soon as he
returns to the manager's office, but on Wednesday night, reporters
waited some 15 minutes. Inside, Zimmer held a team meeting,
speaking to the team as a whole, but others said he also seemed to
be addressing the coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   When the meeting ended and reporters were allowed into the room,
clusters of players spoke in whispers; Paul O'Neill, Derek Jeter
and Chuck Knoblauch talked quietly, as did the catcher Joe Girardi
and Chad Curtis. Zimmer spoke to reporters without ever letting on
about the team meeting, or the exchange with his coach, but after
reporters departed, players intermittently ducked into Zimmer's
office and closed the door _ O'Neill, and then Jeter, who both like
Zimmer very much as a person and most likely offered him support.
</P>
<P>
   After a while, Zimmer sat in the office alone, his legs propped
up on the desk, silently looking off in the distance, and he would
not discuss what took place in the meeting, which left some players
somewhat astounded and confused.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our business,'' he said. ``As I say, if we wanted you
in, we would've invited you.''
</P>
<P>
   But Zimmer's tenure as interim manager has been fraught with
pain and frustration. His right knee, which required surgery in
March and forced him to undergo constant treatment, has hobbled
him; with his pain growing acute in recent days, Zimmer spoke of
possibly undergoing knee replacement surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer scrapped with George Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal
owner, at the end of spring training about what role pitcher Hideki
Irabu should assume, and on Wednesday, Zimmer suggested to
reporters that he would have no input into who would be taken off
the roster once third baseman Scott Brosius is activated off the
15-day disabled list on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer may be nearing the end of his career, in his 51st year in
baseball. He acknowledges that he is in constant pain, and that if
his pain doesn't dissipate, Zimmer has said he may walk away from
the game for treatment. Torre could be back as manager as soon as
this weekend, but perhaps not until next week.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, the Yankees led by 4-1, after scoring three
runs in the top of the fifth inning. But in the bottom of the
fifth, a strained left quadriceps began to bother Orlando
Hernandez, the Yankees' starter, and he had to come out after the
sixth inning, with a 4-3 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton was summoned to start the seventh inning, and Lee
Stevens fought off an inside fastball and blooped a single to left.
Royce Clayton followed with a hit, Stevens taking third; Stanton
grimaced, disgusted. The right-handed-hitting Roberto Kelly
pinch-hit for Tom Goodwin, but with the switch-hitting Mark
McLemore and the left-handed-hitting Rusty Greer due to bat, Zimmer
decided to stick with Stanton, his only left-handed reliever.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly laced a run-scoring double, tying the scire and sending
the possible go-ahead run to third. The Yankees' infield moved in,
and the Texas runners had to hold when McLemore grounded out. But
Stanton fell behind Greer three balls and no strikes, and Zimmer
ordered an intentional walk, filling the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson then replaced Stanton to face Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came down to the fact that I'd rather take a chance with
Nelson pitching and the big guy hitting,'' Zimmer said, referring
to Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers' right fielder slammed a two-run single and Todd
Zeile doubled home two more runs, giving the Rangers a four-run
cushion, and the Yankees more reason to believe their bullpen will
need help before the start of the playoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
