<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SANDERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' SANDERS LIKELY OUT 4-6 MONTHS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deion Sanders underwent surgery Wednesday on his injured left
big toe and is expected to begin an aggressive, four- to six-month
period of rehabilitation in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said he wasn't prepared to
speculate on when Sanders will return, but said the All-Pro
cornerback might miss all of training camp and perhaps the start of
the season. Jones also said the injury will preclude Sanders from
playing wide receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to prepare our team like Deion is not going to be
there,'' Jones said. ``It's what we did when Deion was playing
baseball when we signed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are going to do is not speculate in any way where he
is medically as we start the season. Consequently, to be sound, we
have to prepare ourselves not to have Deion.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Hamilton performed the surgery in New York City,
described Sanders' injury as a ``rare and unusual variation of turf
toe,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   The injury, suffered in the first quarter of the Cowboys' 35-28
victory against the Arizona Cardinals on Nov. 15, interrupted
perhaps Sanders' finest NFL season. After a brief appearance the
next week against Seattle, Sanders missed the remaining five
regular-season games before returning to play in the playoff loss
to Arizona on Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, expected in Dallas this afternoon, played extensively
in the Pro Bowl on defense and as a punt returner. Sanders and
Jones came under scrutiny because Sanders took part in the game,
but Jones said Sanders did not worsen the injury by playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing we have seen, or from any indication from his doctors
or from the surgery showed additional injury,'' Jones said. ``He
was in rigorous exercise before the surgery, as an alternative to
the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Hamilton) said the thing giving Deion the problem was the
initial injury. Nothing he saw Deion do in the postseason or in
rehab impacted the need to have the surgery today.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders injury _ known medically as a hyperdorsal flexion of the
first metatarsal joint _ is to the volar plate in his left big toe.
The volar plate is under the sesamoid bone; there was a tear of the
tissue inside the medial sesamoid bone.
</P>
<P>
   Jones also did not speculate about Sanders' future with the
Cowboys. Sanders' contract expires after the 1999 season. In the
past, Jones has adamantly expressed his vision of seeing Sanders in
a Cowboys uniform for the remainder of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be inappropriate and we don't have the information to
speculate how this might affect our plans now or later on in the
season contractually,'' Jones said. NEWTON LIKELY GONE
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys offensive lineman Nate Newton has likely played his
final game with the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drafted two offensive linemen as well as free-agent
lineman. We are looking fundamentally where we are at on the
offensive line,'' Jones said. ``Right now, we have decided, and we
explained to Nate, we will be going into quarterback school and
training camp without Nate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are scheduled to begin quarterback school tomorrow.
Jones did not rule out a possible return by Newton in some
capacity, but said he is giving Newton, 37, every opportunity to
pursue free-agent offers during the off-season. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
