<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CLAYTON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAYTON DONATES $100,000 FOR SCHOLARSHIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ For much of his life, Royce Clayton has been
well aware of the sacrifices made for him and others like him to
play baseball; from the humble beginnings of the Negro leagues to
Jackie Robinson's historic journey across the color line.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, however, it was Clayton making a sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers shortstop announced that he will make a
$100,000 donation for an endowed college scholarship through the
Jackie Robinson Foundation. Clayton is the first active baseball
player to endow a college scholarship with the organization named
after Robinson, who became the major leagues' first black baseball
player in 1947 when he signed with the Brooklyn Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you know about Jackie's life, the more you are
inspired by his strength, determination and courage in the face of
racism,'' Clayton said before the Rangers-Yankees game last night.
``African-American ballplayers have the opportunity to play in
major-league baseball because of him, and I believe the best way we
can continue to honor his life is to give opportunities to
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those on hand to announce the endowment were Robinson's
widow, Rachel Robinson, who founded the nonprofit foundation in
1973; Clayton's parents; and the first recipient of the endowment,
Antoine Brown, a 19-year-old Chicago native who plans to major in
computer science at Washington University in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   This is not Clayton's first venture into public service. He has
established a foundation in his hometown of Los Angeles to benefit
sickle cell disease patients.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton's involvement with the Jackie Robinson Foundation began
in 1998 after he had a two-hour meeting with Rachel Robinson in New
York City. Clayton talked about his fondness for Jackie Robinson's
contributions to the game, and about how Clayton might make a
difference in his era.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is totally dedicated to the idea'' of the endowment, Rachel
Robinson said of Clayton. ``The idea of giving back in this way was
nothing new for him. He was just looking for a vehicle in which to
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Toni Clayton, Royce Clayton's mother: ``I'm glad he
understands about giving back, and sharing what he has with others.
It makes you feel proud that the lessons you taught in life have
stuck.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 0137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
