<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7455 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-DBACKS-HNS     04-29 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-DBACKS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The hits just kept on coming to the tune of one of the Astros'
worst-pitched games of the season.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Arizona Diamondbacks provided the beat with their relentless
bats, which blended harmonically Wednesday night with the
persistent booing of a small but vocal gathering of 19,605 at the
Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' bullpen gave up its first blown save of the season,
turning a two-run lead into a five-run deficit in a span of three
innings. When the music finally stopped, the Astros found
themselves on the wrong end of a 10-6 decision.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks third baseman Matt Williams atoned for a
career-worst three-error game by breaking a 5-5 tie with a
bases-loaded single off Billy Wagner in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect anyone to stand up and applaud when I pitch
like that,'' said Wagner, who allowed five runs on three hits and
two walks while failing to record an out.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time Wagner allowed more than three runs in an
outing in his career and only the second time he failed to record
an out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was bad,'' he said. ``It was just one of those nights
when things didn't work out. You can't expect to do it every time,
but the way I get paid, I should be able to do it every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner, who also walked in a run with the bases loaded, had a
streak of seven scoreless innings before Williams' clutch hit. But
Wagner wasn't the only Astros reliever to say goodbye to a streak.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Elarton watched his streak of 11 shutout innings fall by
the wayside, blowing a 5-3 lead for starter Chris Holt in the
process. The Diamondbacks scored seven runs on six hits off the
Astros' two hottest relievers. The three hits Wagner (0-1) allowed
in the ninth matched the total number against him for the season
prior to Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holtie needed to get that win, and I wanted to hold the lead
for him,'' Elarton said. ``I just didn't do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's 10 runs and 14 hits were the most the Astros have
allowed in a game this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't pretty,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``I
thought we were pretty much in the driver's seat with a 5-3 lead
and Scott and Billy being fresh. They're human; they're going to
have games when they don't pitch so well.''
</P>
<P>
   It appeared Holt was headed for one of those games after the
first inning, when the chances of his lasting six innings seemed
about as good as the Titanic's making a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks sank their teeth into Holt, scoring runs on
Luis Gonzalez's bloop double and a pair of singles by Travis Lee
and Tony Batista. Holt was ripped for five hits in the inning, but
the damage could have been much worse. He induced a groundout from
Diamondbacks pitcher Andy Benes to escape the inning with the bases
loaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to do a better job in the first inning,'' Holt said.
``I have to treat it like it's the middle innings.''
</P>
<P>
   That pretty much set the tone for Holt's next two innings, when
he danced effortlessly around one-out doubles in the second and
third. He didn't allow a hit over his next three innings, and the
only other batter who reached base against him did so on an error.
Unfortunately for Holt, his rebound was wasted in defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little frustrating, because I knew I had good stuff,''
Holt said. ``I felt fortunate to go six innings, and we were still
in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' fourth set of back-to-back home runs this season
tied the score in the third inning. Holt drew a leadoff walk and
strolled home on Derek Bell's line-drive homer to left-center. Jeff
Bagwell followed with his team-leading sixth home run. Bill Spiers
put the Astros on top with a solo homer in the fourth, and Paul
Bako's sixth-inning sacrifice fly gave the Astros a 5-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Spiers' home run marked the fourth time the Astros have hit
three homers in a game this season. The Astros have not gone
consecutive games without a home run since April 7-8. They have
homered in 13 of their last 17 games, with multiple home runs in
eight games this season.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Wednesday's home-run derby couldn't have been
possible without the Diamondbacks, who have allowed 31
round-trippers _ the second-highest total in the National League.
Benes, who served up all three of Wednesday's homers, has
surrendered an NL-high nine home runs. He allowed only two other
hits against the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who extended his hitting streak to 14 games, tied the
score in the seventh with a two-run, one-out double off Elarton,
and the score remained locked until Williams' hit off Wagner in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw me a slider, and I snuck it through,'' Williams said.
``I was just trying to make contact. He was running it up there
pretty good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
