<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN NOT ONE TO HIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAEKNSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Only minutes after Tuesday's 10-1 loss to the
Blue Jays, many of the Anaheim Angels players were dressed and out
the door. By the time reporters were let into the clubhouse, it was
quiet and nearly empty.
</P>
<P>
   However, one Angel stayed around late.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn stayed and talked. And talked. With coaches and
teammates. At one point, he went into manager Terry Collins' office
and held court with Collins, general manager Bill Bavasi, assistant
GM Ken Forsch and communications director Tim Mead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came in, sat down and we talked about the game,'' Collins
said. ``He's a baseball player. It's easy to sit around and talk
about the game when you win. It's different when you lose. Most
guys get out of here as fast as they can after a game like that.
Not Mo. That's why he's so great.''
</P>
<P>
   No screaming: Collins said Tuesday's game was the worst a team
he has managed in the big leagues has ever played. That includes
three seasons with the Houston Astros and two with the Angels
before this season.
</P>
<P>
   But Collins didn't yell and scream at his team after the game,
which saw the Angels make numerous mental errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``To sit down and have me lecture after a game like that is
pointless,'' he said. ``Because we don't have those often.... I got
that one over with, put that baby away. About two hours ago. It
stuck in my craw for a while. But I wrote (Wednesday's) lineup,
talked to my friendly coaching staff and got ready for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Wednesday's game, Vaughn met with third baseman Troy
Glaus, who botched a rundown play in Tuesday's game. Collins,
though, said he found no reason to ask Glaus what went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy's 22 years old,'' Collins said. ``He made a mistake.
He'll be fine. Those things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: Shortstop Gary DiSarcina, recovering from surgery
on his broken left forearm, is doing exercises to increase mobility
and flexibility in his arm, which include light weights and therapy
in the pool.
</P>
<P>
   But Collins doesn't keep up with DiSarcina's progress. It takes
too much out of him, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Gary and the doctor and the trainer come in my office and
say he's ready to play, the next day he'll be in the lineup,'' he
said. ``Who knows when that will be? It might not be until
!ital!next!off! June. I'm done building up my hopes.''
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina is expected back around the All-Star break.
</P>
</TEXT>
