<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-BLUEJAYS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN LIFTS ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Mo Vaughn sauntered up to Anaheim Angels
manager Terry Collins during batting practice late Wednesday
afternoon and told him the time has come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be good to go for the Chicago series,'' Vaughn said.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who has been the DH since returning from the disabled
list April 22, has determined his sprained left ankle is healthy
enough to allow him to return to first base by Friday when the
Angels begin a four-game series against the White Sox. Collins
urged Vaughn to wait and see how it feels then, preferring Vaughn
not rush to conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Vaughn showed again Wednesday that his batting stroke
is healthy, hitting his second and third home runs of the year _
the second in the eighth inning giving the Angels a 12-10 victory
over the Toronto Blue Jays after they had blown a 10-0 lead before
18,304 fans at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   His first homer sparked a five-run third inning.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn has hit safely in five of the six games. But it wasn't
Vaughn that caused concern for the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   A more pressing concern was how the club would respond to
Tuesday's 10-1 loss, a game in which the Angels played so poorly
Collins called it the worst game any of his big league teams has
ever played.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, though, Collins said he was confident his
players would put Tuesday behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you walk into the clubhouse after a game like (Tuesday)
night's and you see Mo Vaughn, Tim Salmon, Darin Erstad, Chuck
Finley, Tim Belcher, Troy Percival, you know that (Tuesday) was
just one bad night. It'll pass. We know we've got a good team. You
put that sucker out of your mind and move ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins was reassured early, as his club built a 10-0 lead
through four innings. But Belcher, who squandered a 7-2 lead to the
Blue Jays last week in Toronto, could not make it out of the fifth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, Belcher gave up six runs and seven hits, including
home runs by Shannon Stewart and Shawn Green, and had to be rescued
by reliever Al Levine, who recorded the final out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels offense beat up on Blue Jays starter David Wells,
knocking the ex-Yankee out of the game after just 21/3 innings.
Wells gave up seven runs (six earned) and seven hits.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got two in the second inning, one scoring on Garret
Anderson's RBI triple, and another coming home on Charlie O'Brien's
sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, Vaughn's two-run homer was the seventh of
his career off Wells, more than any other active player. Albert
Belle, Chili Davis and Ken Griffey Jr. have six apiece.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels added three more runs in the inning on four hits,
including an RBI single by Tim Unroe and a two-run single by Andy
Sheets.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth inning, Troy Glaus hit a towering, three-run homer
off reliever Tom Davey for a 10-0 Angels lead.
</P>
<P>
   All that time between innings, apparently, took a toll on
Belcher. Needing to finish the fifth to qualify for a victory, he
gave up four consecutive hits to begin the inning, including a
three-run homer by Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher struck out Jose Cruz but then yielded a homer to Green
to make it 10-5. Carlos Delgado walked and Tony Fernandez singled
before Willie Greene struck out for the second out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   But after Darrin Fletcher singled to drive in Delgado and make
it 10-6, Collins marched to the mound with the hook.
</P>
<P>
   Green hit his second homer of the game in the sixth inning off
Scott Schoeneweis to cut the Angels lead to 10-8.
</P>
</TEXT>
