<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS' ONCE-PROMISING SEASON HAS BECOME DISASTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ All those months of inactivity during the
NBA work stoppage sure made a couple of the Los Angeles Lakers
restless. That was to be expected, we guess. After all, you know
what happens when kids are cooped up for 191 days. It doesn't
matter if they're 66 years old or 7-feet tall, they're bound to get
fidgety.
</P>
<P>
   So it was with owner Jerry Buss and center Shaquille O'Neal.
They waited so long for the 1998-99 season to start. Then, when it
finally did they acted as though they were supposed to have hoisted
the NBA championship trophy yesterday, already.
</P>
<P>
   There was so much lost time to make up and so few games. Just
thinking about it made them crazy. In their impetuousness they
club-jacked the Lakers, the better to get to the NBA Finals in five
months flat.
</P>
<P>
   They have steered the club so recklessly that executive vice
president Jerry West eventually turned around his squad car. Good
cop, bad cop, what did it really matter? He clearly grew weary of
the chase after a few miles.
</P>
<P>
   And so the Lakers continue to hurtle along fecklessly while we
watch, at once mesmerized and mortified. They're running out of
road, sure as Buss and O'Neal, the team's standout center, did
patience months ago.
</P>
<P>
   As hopeless as it looks, the fact is there's just enough time
for someone to wrest control of the club before it spins out of
control and plunges into a ditch while Houston and San Antonio and
Portland and Utah zoom on by.
</P>
<P>
   That someone is Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   In Kobe we trust. We must. What other choice do we have?
</P>
<P>
   We feel for Bryant, who has had to grow up so abruptly it's a
wonder he hasn't been on the injured list with whiplash. And yet at
the tender age of 20, with no college seasoning to speak of, he
already is infinitely wiser in one respect than O'Neal, his senior
by nearly seven years.
</P>
<P>
   The supremely skilled guard is smart enough to see he isn't
perfect. He'll own up to his mistakes, which is the first step
toward not repeating them. When he talks, he puts the accent on
Superman squarely on the third syllable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take the heat,'' he said after practice Wednesday. ``It
doesn't bother me. It's part of the learning process.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week at Portland, Bryant launched a 3-point shot in the
final minute of a four-point game with two men in his face and
plenty of time on the shot clock.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, he readily acknowledged that he should have driven to
the basket and tried to draw a foul.
</P>
<P>
   And O'Neal? He readily acknowledged that certain teammates
shouldn't be shooting a three-pointer in the final minute with two
guys in their face and plenty of time on the shot clock.
</P>
<P>
   That's the Lakers' avowed leader. He is SUPERman, hear him roar.
He's as likely to deflect blame onto his teammates as deflect
opponents' shots. He'll be the first to tell you he's good for 26
points and 11 rebounds a night. But the next time he blames his
shoddy defense or lackluster shotblocking (he had zero in that
aforementioned Portland loss) or poor free-throw shooting for a
loss it'll be the first time.
</P>
<P>
   If only O'Neal could check his ego and his insecurities just a
little, he might be able to learn a lot from Bryant. He'd certainly
be able to better co-exist with him.
</P>
<P>
   Their first two years as teammates, O'Neal never publicly picked
Bryant apart the way he has this year. Maybe the fact that Bryant
signed a contract extension before the season and O'Neal holds the
option to walk away as a free agent at the end of this miserable
year is behind O'Neal's imperiousness and his impatience.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, in Buss he found a person willing to indulge his
whims. Thus the past three months have seen O'Neal barking
directions (who can forget his recent boast, ``I'm glad I'm the
general manager of this team. I've got this team just the way I
want it.'') and Buss at the wheel and a city of sports fans
watching, transfixed.
</P>
<P>
   We've already seen one coach get tossed as though he were an
empty aluminum can (we remain confident someone will come along and
recycle Del Harris).
</P>
<P>
   We've seen one itinerant hitchhiker climb aboard, ostensibly to
help the club safely navigate the shortened season. For a while it
looked like Dennis Rodman would steer the Lakers straight, as weird
as that sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Then Buss, again doing O'Neal's bidding, dumped two hostages,
center Elden Campbell and the defensive-minded Eddie Jones, and
brought aboard shooters Glen Rice and J.R. Reid. Shortly thereafter
Rodman was discarded like yesterday's sandwich wrapper and the
Lakers haven't been able to stop much of anything _ their
opponents, their sniveling, their course _ since.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have met the enemy all right. It isn't Pacific
Division-leading Portland, whom they'll face tonight at the Forum.
It's them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 0215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
