<SLUG> BC-CAR-CALNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFIELD CAMPERS CLAIM SPOTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LOUIS BREWSTER  
 Inland Valley Daily Bulletin  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ While team transporters waited on the outside,
infield campers claimed their spots Wednesday evening at the
California Speedway in preparation for Sunday's NASCAR Winston Cup
Series event.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 vehicles, ranging from expensive motor homes to
vans, were ushered into the infield at 5 p.m. Last year, the huge
response prompted speedway officials to open the backstretch gates
a night before the first event.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the charge was Tom Villa of West Covina, subbing for
brother Richard. It was Richard, a Dale Earnhardt fan, who left
work at 6 a.m. on Tuesday and made the trek to Fontana, arriving
more than 24 hours before anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's first-come, first-serve, so we wanted to get the choice
spot,'' said Tom. ``We're season ticket holders, so we want a spot
near the tunnel, close to the track and our seats. Also close to
the showers.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard and Tom will be joined by brother Eddie and two other
friends in the infield. Their Volkswagen van was crammed with food,
drink, a bike, generators, tents, chairs, a wagon, blankets and a
Monopoly game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll spend the whole weekend here, it's great,'' said Tom,
wearing a Bobby Labonte hat. ``Especially Saturday night in the
infield, it's just crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   The lure of infield life also prompted Vince Hanley of Encino to
leave the San Fernando Valley at 10:30 a.m. Wednesday to get in
line. He and wife Cathy have also camped out for NASCAR races at
Phoenix, Sears Point in Sonoma, Calif., and Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have general admission, so we really don't know where we'll
be,'' said Hanley, a NASCAR fan for 15 of his 37 years. ``It's hard
to get the popular spots.''
</P>
<P>
   All the Hanley family will be present and each rooting for a
different driver. Daughter Ashley, 12, is a fan of ``The
Intimidator,'' Dale Earnhardt; 7-year-old Trevor likes Jeff Gordon;
Mom cheers for rookie Tony Stewart and dad sticks with Bill
Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seats,'' said Hanley before moving into the infield.
``It's hard to see from the infield during a race, but it's pretty
good afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   According to speedway officials, more than 20,000 are expected
to live in the infield area this weekend. All reserved and general
admission spots have been sold, leaving only weekend infield
passes, which cost $40.
</P>
<P>
   WINSTON WEST QUALIFYING: All positions for Saturday's California
200, the 100-lap Winston West race, will be determined during this
afternoon's qualifying. The drivers will practice from 11 a.m. to 2
p.m. before making timed runs at 3:30. The fastest 31 cars will
qualify for the 36-car field, which also includes five
provisionals.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Schrader, who has won two of the three Winston West races at
the speedway, holds the qualifying mark of 40.084 seconds (179.623
mph). After three of 14 races, former champion Mike Chase leads the
points race. He's seven ahead of Brandon Ash. Austin Cameron, Sean
Woodside and rookie Sammy Potashnick round out the top five.
</P>
<P>
   Schrader and fellow Winston Cup regular Ricky Craven are entered
in the event along with Craftsman Truck Series drivers Ron
Hornaday, Mike Wallace and Jerry Glanville. Wallace won the West
season-opener last January in Phoenix. AUTOGRAPH SESSION: Several
Winston Cup drivers, including ex-champions Rusty Wallace and Terry
Labonte, will be among those signing autographs today from 5 to 7
p.m. as part of the first RaceFest. There is no admission charge to
the session, which will also include Ernie Irvan, Michael Waltrip,
Johnny Benson, Brett Bodine, Elliott Sadler, Jason Jarrett, Mike
Dillon, Larry Pearson and Butch Gilliland, the 1997 Winston West
titlist from Chino Hills.
</P>
<P>
   SOLID FUTURE: According to Randy LaJoie, the future of stock car
racing looks pretty good. LaJoie is referring to the youthful
competitors in the Busch Grand National series. The names range
from NASCAR royalty _ Dale Earnhardt Jr., Adam Petty, Jason Jarrett
_ to those getting experience before making the transition to
Winston Cup, drivers such as Mike Dillon, Matt Kenseth, Kevin and
Wayne Grubb and Dave Blaney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two thumbs up,'' said LaJoie, who has opted to race in the
Busch series so he can spend more time with his family. ``They're
very smart. And they are very talented.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing I've seen about these guys compared to some of
the ones in the past is they will ask questions,'' LaJoie said.
``The last couple of years, we've had guys coming through here who
thought they were smarter than the rest of us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
