<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7480 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEN-PREGNANCY-SFCHRO     04-29 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-PREGNANCY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TEEN PREGNANCY RATES DROP _ EDUCATION, ECONOMY CREDITED  &HT;     By RAMON G. MCLEOD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teenage pregnancy rates in California and the rest of the
country dropped in 1996, and it appears that sex education,
economics and more realistic attitudes by teenagers played a large
role in the downward trend.
</P>
<P>
   A new study by the New York-based Alan Guttmacher Institute
shows that pregnancies in females 19 and younger declined 4 percent
from 1995 to 1996. Teen pregnancy rates have dropped 17 percent
since peaking in 1990. Pregnancy rates include births, abortions
and miscarriages.
</P>
<P>
   And new information released by the U.S. government on
birthrates for 1997 shows that these have been falling since 1991
with the greatest improvements nationally among African American
females 19 or younger. Pregnancy rates are not available for 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty happy to see this,'' Beth Frederick, a
spokeswoman for the Guttmacher Institute, said of the new figures.
``The pregnancy declines are across the board, and that means kids
are getting the message that having a baby too young is something
they want to avoid.''
</P>
<P>
   California, which has the second highest teen birthrate in the
nation, has seen these figures drop much faster than the national
average.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, birthrates for white teens fell 13 percent from 1991
to 1996, but fell 24 percent in California. The African American
birthrate fell 21 percent nationally, but 23 percent in California.
The Latino birthrate went down 5 percent nationally, but 15 percent
in California.
</P>
<P>
   Comparative Asian American data has not been published, but
other data show that Asian American teen birthrates have followed a
similar downward path.
</P>
<P>
   Attitudes toward sex and sex education by both children and
their parents may be playing a significant role in the declining
teen birth and pregnancy rates, Frederick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to remember that these kids are the first generation
to have been exposed to sex education messages for a very long time
now,'' Frederick said. ``They have been hearing about AIDS,
condoms, abstinence and how it is bad to have a baby when you are
not ready, since grade school.''
</P>
<P>
   Parental attitudes about frankly talking to kids and attitudes
about school-based sex education are also likely playing a role,
said Gary Yates, executive director of the Wellness Foundation of
California, a Los Angeles health care organization that is
launching a major teen-pregnancy prevention campaign in May.
</P>
<P>
   A survey by the Field Institute in San Francisco that was
commissioned by the foundation and released this week found that 88
percent of California adults believe that sex education should be
taught in the schools. Most believe this should happen before the
eighth grade.
</P>
<P>
   Mark DiCamillo, director of the Field Poll, said Latino and
African American parents are the strongest supporters of quality
sex education and are the groups most likely to consider it a
serious problem for their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Birthrates are higher for these two groups than for other
groups, and this is definitely an issue of real importance to the
parents,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Field Poll shows that more than 90 percent of parents and
nonparents alike are highly supportive of education about AIDS, the
basics of human reproduction, and the use of condoms. Better than
83 percent of parents and 73 percent of nonparents also believe
that schools should discourage kids from having sex before
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Yates said the survey shows that ``parents believe that young
people should have sex education in schools and they want it to
begin at a fairly young age,'' he said. ``They may not show up at
school board meetings to announce their support of these programs,
but this poll shows how strong the sentiment is.''
</P>
<P>
   Sex education alone cannot account for the drop in teen birth
and pregnancy rates, however, said Yates and others familiar with
the statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the economy being sound, hope for the future increases,
and when that happens pregnancies tend to decline,'' Yates said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
