<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 02:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7489 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI &LR;      04-29 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYTON BLOWS TOP AFTER BLOWOUT LOSS TO TRAIL BLAZERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND _ Minutes after the Sonics suffered their worst loss
this season, Gary Payton unleashed an emotionally charged tirade as
soon as his agent entered the team's locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``You better do something about this,'' Payton hollered at Aaron
Goodwin Wednesday night after the Sonics were destroyed, 119-84, by
the Portland Trail Blazers at the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care about this (expletive) no more. I'm tired of
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin immediately tried to calm Payton, who yelled in front of
teammates and a room filled with print and television reporters.
After Goodwin's prodding, Payton eventually lowered his voice. The
pair continued their discussion near the showers, out of sight and
earshot of those in the room.
</P>
<P>
   However, as Payton walked away he could be heard saying ``I
don't care about Wally ... '' _ a reference to team president Wally
Walker.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time this season Payton has publicly griped
about the Sonics' losing ways. It was also a tangible indication of
Payton's displeasure with Walker and possibly first-year Sonics
coach Paul Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics again fell out of the Western Conference playoff
standings. They are in ninth place, one game out of the playoff
picture. Minnesota beat Phoenix Wedesday to pull even with the idle
Sacramento Kings for the seventh spot.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics have four regular-season games left with Westphal
standing firm by his claim that three wins will get the team into
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Payton, who for the second time in three games was held to
single digits (7), may not be so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just frustration,'' Goodwin said after Payton left the
locker room without speaking with the media. ``He wants to win. He
wants to be in the playoffs. That's why I pulled him aside. I told
him we don't need theatrics. I told him to relax. It's acceptable
and it's understandable. It's been a long season.''
</P>
<P>
   Said center Olden Polynice: ``Everybody would love to see us
unravel. But I'm not going to let that happen. We're going to stay
together for the next four games and get into the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   At 22-24, the Sonics are toying with not making the playoffs for
the first time in Payton's career. The Sonics have been in the
postseason in each of Payton's eight seasons since he was drafted
No. 2 overall in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Sonics began summer vacation early was
1989-90.
</P>
<P>
   There is growing speculation, heightened by a recent report in
ESPN The Magazine, that Payton will ask to be traded in the
offseason. Goodwin squelched that notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real truth is he doesn't want to leave here,'' Goodwin
said. ``The real truth is he doesn't want to lose. Wally's going to
do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Walker nor Westphal witnessed Payton's outburst. Walker
attended Wednesday's blowout, but there was little he could do
about the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Portland, owner of the best record in the NBA, pummeled the
Sonics with a third quarter that, in the words of Polynice, rivaled
a ``Mike Tyson uppercut.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They just straight cold-cocked us and we never recovered,''
Polynice said.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers, doing whatever they pleased, outscored the
Sonics 44-19 in the third. Point guard Damon Stoudamire, another
Goodwin superstar, punished the Sonics the most. He scored 17 of
his season-high 31 points in the decisive period.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle, which successfully stalled John Stockton in a win
against Utah Tuesday night, could not handle Stoudamire's
quickness.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was Hersey Hawkins, John Crotty or even Payton
defending, Stoudamire crossed them over, scooped layups or drilled
3-pointers in their faces.
</P>
<P>
   Portland multiplied an eight-point halftime lead into a 97-64
bulge at the end of the period. The Sonics' biggest deficit was 38
points in the fourth. They never found a way to match Portland's
energy, toughness or size.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is not going to make or break our season,'' said
Dale Ellis who, along with Detlef Schrempf, led the Sonics with 13
points. ``They play well here in Portland. And we haven't had a lot
of success here lately. Plus, they were just a little more physical
than we were.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' backcourt will affirm that. Both Crotty and Hawkins
were injured in the loss.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins jammed his right ring finger in the first quarter, and
had to leave the game in the third because of the injury. Crotty
suffered a mild concussion late the third. He took an elbow to the
head from Portland's Stacey Augmon while driving to the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Both incidents were painful reminders of how much the Trail
Blazers wore the Sonics down.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can look at the score and draw any conclusions they
want,'' Westphal said. ``But we're going to be ready for Denver
(Friday at KeyArena). We're not giving up. We're just going to
flush this one.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, Wednesday night revealed bigger problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
