with tears in his eyes and said: ``I have lost what I hold most
dear to me.''
</P>
<P>
   In a house just down the road, the same NATO bomb had blasted
his aunt Stanica Rasic to death and his cousin Dragan Manolov as
well.
</P>
<P>
   An old woman was dragged alive from the mud, just as Vojislav
Milic was pulled from the tomb of his family. ``When he was taken
out of the basement, `Voja' said he would hang himself,'' the
middle-aged woman remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing he said when they pulled him out was `Shoot
me,' `Kill me.' He had lost everything, you see _ his whole family,
his home... .''
</P>
<P>
   Surdulica was not the place Wednesday to discuss NATO's latest
explanations of a single erroneous bomb, or its expressions of
regret or the British Ministry of Defense's statement _ made four
hours after the Surdulica attack _ that NATO had had ``a good day''
over Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take some pictures of my house,'' a man shrieked at us from
the timbers of his smashed roof. ``(Screw) Clinton and his family
for this. I spent 30 years building my home. You're a bunch of
fascists.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (175-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 825) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even the woman who had watched ``Voja'' Milic tugged out of the
wreckage, believed these houses had been deliberately bombed.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO hit the barracks on April 6th,'' she said. ``So now they
came to attack us in our homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Half a mile away, the anger was just as intense, tempered only
by the fact that the NATO bomb which landed there had totally
destroyed the only empty house in the street.
</P>
<P>
   Radica Ristic, shouting away on the lip of the crater that was
her home, her grey cardigan splashed with mud, her string shoes
covered in earth, spoke only of a small life in a small town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had run into the cellar of our neighbor's house and our
home had turned into smoke,'' she wailed. ``When you look at this
hole _ this was my home. I've been building this house for 10
years. I work in the agricultural school and out of this I made a
living and made my home.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM; STORY CONCLUDES) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Surdulica will now be known as a town that lost its children.
And by terrible irony, their street of death _ Zmaj Jove Jovanovica
Street _ was named after a 19th-century doctor and poet whose
personal tragedy is known to every Serb. All of his seven children
died. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
