<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2538 - April 29, 1999  NEWS &AMP; FEATURES
SUMMARY N0 2538 - April 29,1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability in your
country. Karl Horwitz
                                                                 1.
MADELEINE ALBRIGHT: DRIVEN BY HER OWN BIOGRAPHY By A.O. Scott from
Slate - 1.900 words Madeleine Albright is a ``celebrity''. Of her
predecessors, only Henry Kissinger exercised a comparable hold over
the public imagination. Albright's celebrity is less a matter of
what she has done than of who she is.
--------------------------------------------------------2.PLAN TO
DE-BALKANIZE WHEN THE WAR ENDS By Flora Lewis There are no new
answers and the questions have scarcely changed. But it is
impossible to change the subject. War in Kosovo remains the
throbbing overwhelming issue that can't be stopped and can't keep
going on.
----------------------------------------------------------------3.
WAR WITHOUT DEATH By Corey S. Powell from Discover - 1.200 words
The image of the perfect nonlethal weapon - a Star Trek-style
phaser set on stun - is so powerful that no one has given up on the
idea. The Defence Advanced Research Projects Agency is
collaborating with the National Institute of Justice to develop a
more sophisticated laser weapon.
----------------------------------------------------------------4.
WHO SAYS WE CAN'T STOP EVERY GENOCIDE? By Lucy Russell from Slate -
1.200 words Critics say moral consistency requires us to do nothing
in Kosovo because we can't intervene every time a thug like
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic decides to start slaughtering
his own citizens. But is it true?
----------------------------------------------------------------5.
CLONING MAY CAUSE LONG-LASTING HEALTH PROBLEMS By Michael McCarthy
from The Lancet News Service French researchers report that a
cloned calf may have died because of a genetic malfunction caused
by the cloning. This is the first time anyone has reported that
cloning could cause long-lasting health problems in clones.
----------------------------------------------------------------6.
LIZ TILBERIS: A GALLANT STRUGGLE ENDS By Sharon Edelson from
Women's Wear Daily - 2.500 words She was the epitome of glamour,
escorting Princess Diana to the Costume Institute gala at the
Metropolitan Musueum of Art in 1996. But beneath the velvet and
satin, Liz Tilberis was fighting the battle of her life. On April
21, at Mount Sinai Hospital in Manhattan, the 51-year-old
editor-in-chief of Harper's Bazaar, lost her six-year struggle with
ovarian cancer. In this tribute, friends, designers and co-workers
remember this very extraordinary woman.
----------------------------------------------------------------7.
SHEDDING LIGHT ON JET LAG By Everett Potter - 1.000 words Forget
melatonin and faddish diets. When it comes to jet lag, that
traveler's hangover of digestive ailments, sleep deprivation and
moodiness, it is best to turn on the lights. External and internal
desynchronization are the major culprits.
----------------------------------------------------------------8.
EXCLUSIVE INTERVIEW WITH RUSSIAN PRIME MINISTER EVGUENI PRIMAKOV by
MAREK HALTER - text in French (not available in France and Italy.
----------------------------------------------------------------9.
ENVIRONMENTAL MYTHS from Discover - 600 words The editors of
Discover set the record straight on a spectrum of erroneous
environmental assumptions, from the primary source of U.S. energy
(70 % is derived from coal and other fossil fuels) to the primary
culprit responsible for oil pollution (autos and boats - not
tankers). Learn the direct cause of damaging environmental effects
as well as what, if anything, is being done to safeguard our
national forest and bottled water.
----------------------------------------------------------------10.
ISABELLE HUPPERT'S RISQUE BUSINESS By Daniel Perez - from Fairchild
Isabelle Huppert is stumped. She just can't figure out why she's
occasionally referred to in the press as ``the little French
mouse''. But if she had seen herself sitting in the front row of
January's Yves Saint Laurent couture show, just one seat down from
Catherine Deneuve, she might have some idea...Please fax to Paris : 33.1.47.42.80.44 or: 33.1.47.42.18.81
