<HEADER>
A7616 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN-COX     04-29 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Legal system fails to do justice to blacks
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a book us white folks need to read but black folks can
skip. Black folks already know why there's such a grotesque
disproportion of their young men in prison. And, no, it's not
because African Americans are natural-born crooks; that's
talk-radio tripe. It's in good part because the relentless
inequities of the criminal justice system are geared, however
unintentionally, to produce that disproportion.
</P>
<P>
   The book is ``No Equal Justice.'' It is by David Cole. He brings
a disturbing _ and what ought to be an urgent _ message.
</P>
<P>
   For every black man who is graduated from college, 100 are
arrested. The consequences for our national life are corrosive. The
current, unprecedented disproportions are devastating black family
formation and economic opportunity and creating an alienation that
is more, not less, likely to produce crime.
</P>
<P>
   The tilt against the poor, especially the black poor, starts at
the bottom of the criminal justice ladder, with kids, and compiles
with every rung up. A 1991 study found juvenile drug use about
50-50 black and white, but black juveniles were detained for drug
cases at twice the rate of white kids and were charged in adult
criminal courts at four times the white rate.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutorial decisions disfavor the black and poor. Georgia's
prosecutors, Cole reports, have invoked their state's
two-times-and-out life sentences against 1 percent of the whites
facing a second drug conviction, 16 percent of eligible blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors are drawn from pools that underrepresent the poor and
minorities and prosecutors misuse preemptory challenges to keep
minorities off trial juries.
</P>
<P>
   Drug, especially crack and powder cocaine laws, prosecutions and
sentences, are notoriously tilted. Some 65 percent of crack users
are white but in 1992, 92.6 percent of crack convictions were of
blacks, and black federal crack offenders serve an average 5 years
longer than white cocaine offenders.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Public Health Services finds that 76 percent of all
drug users are white, 14 percent black, 8 percent Hispanic. But
African Americans account for 35 percent of drug arrests, 55
percent of convictions and 74 percent of prison sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Black defendants are 50 percent more likely than whites to be
imprisoned for larceny; twice as likely to be imprisoned for
weapons offenses.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court gave indigent defendants a theoretical right
to counsel but undermines the practical right. The court has
accepted as ``competent'' indigents' attorneys who slept at the
trial, used heroin during a trial, were drunk in the court and were
suffering from Alzheimer's.
</P>
<P>
   Most states underfund public defenders and judges appoint
defense lawyers with little or no criminal trial experience. Few
states provide post-conviction counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The cumulative effect of all this is that while blacks are 12
percent of the population, prisons are 50 percent black. And citing
that as justification, beat cops, highway patrols and custom agents
then target black folks for frisks and searches _ powering a
self-fulfilling cycle.
</P>
<P>
   A nation intending justice would be offended by these
distortions. An artful one would right them.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
