   The breakdown ...
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BREAKTHROUGH BRIEFS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THREE COLOR SLIDES ARE AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (800 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By THE EDITORS OF DISCOVER &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The latest, greatest and strangest: A Spanish neurologist
ponders the origin of vampire legends (clue: rabies); NASA
engineers test a new spacecraft that travels twice the speed of
light while cutting takeoff weight in half; Stephen Hawking
discusses the theory of everything and proffers a one-word critique
of the recently published book, ``The End of Science.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DRUGS FROM THE SEA &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THREE COLOR SLIDES ARE AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By ROSIE MESTEL &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   With the glory days of antibiotics coming to a rapid end, the
marine-based quest of biologist William Fenical may be critical to
the future of medicine. Since the 1980s, Fenical has been plunging
into the ocean to find what could be the richest sources for all
manner of drugs. Will the next wave of killer drugs come from the
sea?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FIRST AMERICANS: ORIGINS OF MAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FOUR COLOR SLIDES ARE AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; 1,000 words &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Exciting new evidence suggests that the first humans in the New
World were not, as previously believed, mammoth hunters from
Siberia who crossed the Bering Strait at the end of the Ice Age.
Who, when, where and how the first North Americans came to the
continent is an evolving mystery with some new, compelling and
evolving answers. The surprising remains of Spirit Cave in a museum
laboratory outside Carson City, Nev., offer startling clues about
the origins of mankind.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Stories from last week, which are still available for purchase:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PARADISE AND OIL: A TALE OF ENVIRONMENTAL-FRIENDLY BUSINESSMEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FIVE COLOR SLIDES SHOWING CREATURES OF THE RAIN FOREST ARE
AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,100 words and one 200-word sidebar) &QL; 
 &UR; By JARED DIAMOND &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In New Guinea's rain forest, environmentalists and business
executives are learning that what's good for this pristine world is
also good for the bottom line. The author, a professor of
physiology and an avid bird-watcher, makes his 17th visit to New
Guinea and discovers an elusive bird _ a cassowary _ living near
the oil fields. What makes it possible for this big, shy,
ostrichlike bird _ rarely found anywhere near the disturbances
people create _ to survive alongside the country's largest
operating oil and natural gas field?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A CROOKED CHILD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ONE COLOR ILLUSTRATION SHOWING A CHILD IS AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By SHARRON SUSSMAN &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The author, an orthopedic surgeon in Berkeley, Calif., seeks to
cure a severe condition of developmental dysplasia found in a
3-year-old patient named Gabrielle. Can the child be saved from
what would become a life crippled by debilitating arthritis? After
two operations, body casts and leg braces, little Gabrielle finds
herself taking dance classes.
</P>
<P>
   All stories are also available in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
