<HEADER>
A7659 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENVIRONMENTAL-MYTHS-N     04-29 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENVIRONMENTAL-MYTHS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENVIRONMENTAL MYTHS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    THREE COLOR ILLUSTRATIONS are available FREE OF CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. The art can be sent by mail or
overnight delivery, using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number.
Please specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- This article is also available in Spanish.-----
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By THE EDITORS OF DISCOVER MAGAZINE  
 c.1999 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   &UR; MYTH: &LR;  Most energy in the United States comes from solar,
nuclear and hydroelectric generation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FACT: &LR;  Seventy percent of our electricity is produced by
burning coal and other fossil fuels _ sources linked to global
warming.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MYTH: &LR;  Plastic six-pack rings do not break down in the
environment and can trap marine animals.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FACT: &LR;  The rings are designed to disintegrate in sunlight, but
the process can take 10 years. Therefore, the rings should be
snipped, recycled or avoided altogether. Surveys have shown that
the rings can strangle birds and fish, but the worst culprit is
abandoned plastic fishing line responsible for 37 percent of marine
entanglements.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MYTH: &LR;  Destruction of tropical rain forests will cause Earth's
atmosphere to run out of oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FACT: &LR;  Oxygen makes up almost 21 percent of atmospheric gases.
Burning all the tropical forests in the world would decrease the
proportion of oxygen by four-hundredths of one percent. Destruction
of tropical rain forests, however, would significantly increase the
concentration of carbon dioxide _ the most important greenhouse gas
_ in the atmosphere by 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MYTH: &LR;  Household and industrial chemicals are routinely tested
and approved for safe use by the U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FACT: &LR;  Federal officials do not test pesticides or household
products for safety. They rely on producers to do so.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MYTH: &LR;  The solar-energy market has plateaued.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FACT: &LR;  Worldwide sales of solar cells increased 11 percent a
year from 1990 to 1996, then jumped by 43 percent in 1997 and by
another 28 percent in 1998. Sales of coal and oil have grown by
slightly more than one percent a year since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MYTH: &LR;  Spent fuel rods from nuclear power plants _ which will
remain radioactive for millions of years _ are safely stored in a
deep underground facility in the West.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FACT: &LR;  No such long-term storage facility exists. All fuel rods
are stored temporarily at the nation's 103 active nuclear plants.
Another 12 plants have been shut down, but the spent rods are still
stored at the plants.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MYTH: &LR;  Most oil pollution comes from tankers that run aground
or ships that wash out their holds at sea.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FACT: &LR;  More than twice as much oil gets into the environment
each year because of sloppy activities involving automobiles and
boats. At least 200 million gallons of oil are dumped each year in
the U.S. by people who change their own automobile engine oil.
Overfilling auto gas tanks also contributes to the mess, as do
spills when refilling outboard-motor tanks. However, tens of
thousands of leaky auto engines whizzing over already polluted
urban environments can't compare with the damage done to a pristine
environment by a single oil tanker such as the Exxon Valdez, which
spilled 10 million gallons of oil into Prince William Sound in
Alaska in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MYTH: &LR;  Aerosol spray cans are the leading source of
ozone-destroying chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FACT: &LR;  CFCs were banned from aerosol cans in 1978. They are
still found, however, in many air conditioners and refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MYTH: &LR;  Government agencies test bottled water for safety and
purity.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FACT &LR; : Bottled water is not tested by federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MYTH: &LR;  Our national forests are protected from logging, mining
and drilling for oil.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FACT: &LR;  Fifty-two percent of national forests are logged, mined
and crisscrossed by more than 373,000 miles of roads, enough to
circle Earth 14 times. Just 18 percent of national forest land is
permanently protected wilderness, and much of that is thin soil
over rock where trees rarely grow.
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (By the editors of Discover magazine.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
