<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7686 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-DATA-$ADV02-CO     04-29 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-DATA-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PUBLIC SUPPORT SHOWS NATO UNALIGNED OVER AIR STRIKES ON
YUGOSLAVIA
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-EUROPE-$ADV02.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., May 2 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATO's EUROPEAN MEMBERS
</P>
<P>
   While the governments of all NATO countries support the attack
on Yugoslavia, public support -- and perhaps ultimately political
support -- varies dramatically. following is a breakdown of where
each of the 18 European members of the alliance stands, separated
into four groups: solid supporters, supportive supporters and
reluctant supporters and publicly opposed.
</P>
<P>
   SOLID SUPPORTERS
</P>
<P>
   UNITED KINGDOM
</P>
<P>
   Public Support: 68 percent
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Prime Minister Tony Blair has been a leading hawk and
has strong public support. Second only to the United States in
providing troops and firepower. British
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Secretary Robin Cook has been at the forefront of the
public relations assault on Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosovic,
often invoking memories of Adolf Hitler. The aggressive British
stance is seen in Europe as a guidepost for the direction U.S.
President Bill Clinton is likely to move. A whopping 54 percent of
Britons favor launching a ground attack.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE
</P>
<P>
   Public support: 54 percent
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Not since the '60s have France's leaders worked so
closely and harmoniously with the United States despite deep
misgivings over the growth of U.S. power and influence.
Surprisingly, 55 percent of the French public favors a ground
attack and polls show a strong desire to remove Milosevic from
power.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY
</P>
<P>
   Public support: 57 percent
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Contributing 14 fighter-bomber jets and 3,000 German
troops are in Macedonia. While support for Germany's first armed
campaign in Europe since World War II is high, it is not
unequivocal. A full 63 percent oppose the use of ground troops,
deeply complicating the political challenge for Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder should there be a move toward a land invasion.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLAND
</P>
<P>
   Public support: 78 percent
</P>
<P>
   Comment: One of most enthusiastic fans of NATO air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   DENMARK
</P>
<P>
   Public Support: 74 percent
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Contributing eight jet fighters and ready to do more.
Support for a ground attack also seems high.
</P>
<P>
   BELGIUM
</P>
<P>
   Public support: 70 percent
</P>
<P>
   Comment: No substantial political opposition; contributing four
fighter jets and 1,000 personnel.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA
</P>
<P>
   Public support: 64 percent
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Has contributed 12 jet fighters and 650 military
personnel. Stance closely follows that of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   NORWAY
</P>
<P>
   Public Support: 64 percent
</P>
<P>
   Pro-NATO government has support from all political parties, and
support is growing for ground attack.
</P>
<P>
   POLAND
</P>
<P>
   Public Support: 54 percent
</P>
<P>
   Comments: The Polish government is the most enthusiastic of
NATO's new members from the former Soviet bloc. It has sent 120
soldiers to Macedonia and has expressed
</P>
<P>
   willingness to send more.
</P>
<P>
   LUXEMBOURG
</P>
<P>
   Public support: 60 percent
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Despite popular support, the government of this tiny
country is unenthusiastic about the air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ICELAND
</P>
<P>
   Public support: 60 percent
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Doesn't have a military but all for the air strikes
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   SUPPORTIVE SUPPORTERS
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN
</P>
<P>
   Public support: 55 percent
</P>
<P>
   Comment: The home country of NATO Secretary General Javier
Solana also has a
</P>
<P>
   large percentage of its people -- nearly 40 percent -- in
opposition. The government
</P>
<P>
   has contributed eight warplanes. Spain has no obvious strategic
interests in the
</P>
<P>
   Balkans but is supportive of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   PORTUGAL
</P>
<P>
   Public support: N/A
</P>
<P>
   Comment: The Balkans are a long way away and the Portuguese are
grateful. Offered to make fighter planes available.
</P>
<P>
   RELUCTANT SUPPORTERS
</P>
<P>
   HUNGARY
</P>
<P>
   Public support: 48 percent
</P>
<P>
   Comment: A ``new'' NATO member as of March 12. Because it
borders Yugoslavia, Hungary is a potential staging area for a
ground attack. This could be difficult politically because 41
percent of the population opposes the air strikes. Many fear the
Serbs, who will be neighbors long after the war is over, have long
memories.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY
</P>
<P>
   Public support: 47 percent
</P>
<P>
   Comments: Also 47 percent of the public opposes NATO's campaign.
Italy is clearly the most reluctant of NATO's major members, even
though it is home to 11 airbases
</P>
<P>
   used in the attack. There are growing fears that Italy, which is
a ferry ride across
</P>
<P>
   the Adriatic Sea from Albania, will have to take on large
numbers of refugees. Italy has sent military doctors and nurses,
tents, volunteers and aid but has been wary of joining several of
its NATO partners in offering temporary homes to the refugees. The
country reluctantly voted for European Union oil embargo against
Yugoslavia. Even so, 60 percent of Italians favor more diplomacy,
while 64 percent oppose a ground war.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICLY OPPOSED SUPPORTERS
</P>
<P>
   CZECH REPUBLIC
</P>
<P>
   Public Support: 35 percent
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Just six weeks after being admitted to the alliance,
the Czech Republic finds itself supporting an attack on a country
with which it has had strong links. President Havel supports the
air strikes even though 57 percent of Hungarians oppose them. The
Czech Republic has allowed the use of its air bases and territory
for NATO air tankers and the transport of war equipment for the
bombing of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   GREECE
</P>
<P>
   Public Support: less than 5 percent
</P>
<P>
   Comment: Athens and Belgrade are old friends. Since the war
began, Greeks have burned U.S. flags. Newspapers have described
NATO as ``criminal'' and TV coverage has
</P>
<P>
   focused on destroyed buildings and cowering residents in
Belgrade and Pristina. Thus
</P>
<P>
   far, the government has been able to position its support for
air strikes as an obligation to NATO. The country also supported
European Union oil embargo against Yugoslavia. Greeks fear NATO
bombing will trigger an influx of thousands of Albanians across
their borders, a civil war in neighboring Macedonia and even
demands for autonomy or separatism from their own Muslim minority
in Thrace, on the border with Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Polls by the Angus Reid Group and The Times of London.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
