<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7687 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PANAMA-BOX-$ADV01-COX     04-29 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-BOX-$ADV01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PANAMA, AND THE PRESIDENTIAL RACE: AT A GLANCE
 &HT;    With PANAMA-ELECTIONS-$ADV01.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., May 1 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA:
</P>
<P>
   Capital: Panama City.
</P>
<P>
   Area: 29,208 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 2.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Location: The Central American republic is located between Costa
Rica and Colombia. It is an S-shaped isthmus that joins the
Atlantic and Pacific oceans.
</P>
<P>
   President: Ernesto Perez Balladares.
</P>
<P>
   Language: Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Religion: Overwhelmingly Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   Economy: Service-oriented, with most of its income derived from
the Panama Canal.
</P>
<P>
   History: Christopher Columbus landed here in 1502. Panama was
joined to Colombia in 1821. The U.S. flag has flown in Panama since
1903, when President Theodore Roosevelt engineered Panama's
separation from Colombia so that the ``big ditch'' could be built.
The United States began building the 50-mile-long Panama Canal in
1904 and completed it in 1914. Under the Panama Canal treaties,
signed by Gen. Omar Torrijos and former U.S. President Jimmy Carter
in 1977, Panama is to take complete control of the canal and all
surrounding property by high noon on Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Politics: Presidential elections are scheduled May 2. They pit
the son of a ruling-party strongman against the widow of the man
his father overthrew. Martin Torrijos, son of Gen. Omar Torrijos,
who signed the Panama Canal treaties along with former U.S.
President Jimmy Carter, will go up against Mireya Moscoso, widow of
former President Arnulfo Arias. Omar Torrijos headed a coup in 1968
that deposed Arias 11 days after he took office.
</P>
<P>
   TWO MAIN CANDIDATES IN THE MAY 2 RACE:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Martin Torrijos, 35.
</P>
<P>
   Graduated from Texas A&AMP;M University with degrees in political
science and economics. He served as vice minister of the interior
under President Ernesto Perez Balladares. He is the son of the late
dictator, Gen. Omar Torrijos.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mireya Moscoso, 54.
</P>
<P>
   Widow of former President Arnulfo Arias, who was overthrown by
Gen. Omar Torrijos in 1968. She has no government experience, but
made a strong showing in 1994 when she ran against the current
president, Ernesto Perez Balladares. She's known as a left-leaning
populist who has opposed many of the government's market reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
