A7697 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN02-CO     04-29 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Chasing dictators, and stumbling
 &HT;    For release Sunday, May 2,1999.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We began the '90s in hot pursuit of one dictator, Iraq's Saddam
Hussein, but did not succeed in ridding the world of him. Already,
we had Panama's Manuel Noriega in a Miami jail, nabbed by U.S.
troops who actually invaded Panama by the thousands to get their
hands on him.
</P>
<P>
   But there are so many more despots to pursue. Libya's Moammar
Khadafy is one, Syria's Haffez Assad another and Yugoslavia's
Slobodan Milosevic another; Milosevic being the present focus of
attention.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has made it the business of its government and
budget to bring down dictators but, except, for the greasy grab of
Noriega, hasn't succeeded. Despite embargoes and occasional warlike
actions against them, the dictators remain intact, likely more
cherished by their subjects than before as a result of the
nationalism that usually embraces a nation when its leader is
targeted.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, we have Fidel Castro _ the longest running
dictatorship in the world. While the remainder of the planet flocks
to the shores of Cuba to either sun themselves or invest in a
future Cuba, the U.S. stands firm, its teeth clenched _ but that's
all. Nothing changes, the man is in charge.
</P>
<P>
   As American pilots fly sorties over Iraq in 1999, they (and we)
must be wondering why a more complete job wasn't done on Saddam
Hussein at the beginning of this decade, why we quit fighting just
when we were within reach of Saddam's throat. George Bush, Colin
Powell, Dick Cheney and Stormin' Norman Schwarzkopf need to explain
that, although I would surmise _ the truth be known _ that they
would not all be in agreement with having let Saddam off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the dictators I've referred to aren't simply dictators;
they are butchers _ killers of innocents, destroyers of families,
genocidal practitioners. You can include in that Chile's Augusto
Pinochet, who's got himself pinned down in London by legal actions
emanating from Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, one rarely hears the name of Idi Amin any
longer. He was the brutal dictator of Uganda from 1971 to 1979.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran of military service under British colonial rule, Amin
took power with force and kept it that way. His rule is described
as a ``reign of terror'' in which 300,000 Ugandans were reportedly
murdered.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of things have been said about Amin that have yet to be
proved, including the appalling claim that he ate the flesh of some
of his victims.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Milosevic and Hussein, however, Amin is not living under
the threat of bombs. This man, acknowledged as one of the world's
cruelest, lives a sedentary life in Saudi Arabia, now deeply
wrapped in an Islamic existence, and reportedly sustained by the
Saudi government.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper reports during the 20 years of Amin's exile have him
shopping for himself in supermarkets, living in a large marble
villa with his wife and about nine of the 43 children he fathered.
It's a pretty good life for a man who was responsible for the
murders of hundreds of thousands.
</P>
<P>
   As for the U.S. and its allies, as gentle people of the world
call for the apprehension and trial of vile human rights abusers,
it seems somewhat eerie that Amin has been allowed to slip into the
shadows.
</P>
<P>
   For many, his crimes took place so long ago that they are
forgotten. His marked attempt to erase the Asiatic population of
Uganda seems lost to the ages. He did precisely what Milosevic is
doing in Kosovo; he shoved 70,000 ethnic Asians from inside Uganda.
Today that's called ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, no one seems to be pressing Saudi Arabia to turn this man
over to a court. It seems to me that while we're chasing down the
world's dictators _ well, some of them _ we ought to be making
noise about the Saudis hosting and subsidizing Idi Amin; and with
our oil money, no doubt.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
