<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What if they held an election and nobody came?
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Low voter turnouts spook politicians like
thunder and lightning spook cattle. In either a low voter turnout
or a stampede, no one has any control, and anything can happen.
</P>
<P>
   After a candidate forum last week, Council Member Jackie Goodman
said she took her campaign to the airwaves to make sure her
supporters knew that there was an election Saturday and that she
was running.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a lesson from political history, Goodman observed,
``There's a reason that Attorney General John Hill wasn't Gov. John
Hill.'' In 1978, Hill was the Democratic nominee for governor and
by virtue of the dominant party's nomination was considered a
shoo-in. Despite purveyors of conventional wisdom saying and
believing that, Bill Clements, the Republican, won.
</P>
<P>
   So, Goodman isn't taking the election for granted. Nor should
she.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom is that Goodman and her incumbent colleagues
Daryl Slusher and Beverly Griffith should have little trouble
winning re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Low turnouts have a way of turning conventional wisdom on its
pointy little head. The political cemetery is full of graves of
those conventional wisdom held were immortal.
</P>
<P>
   These days, people who follow Austin politics aren't guessing
who is going to win what and by how much. What people who follow
Austin politics are guessing is how low the turnout will be.
</P>
<P>
   Incumbents are especially vulnerable to low-voter turnouts
because their friends aren't as motivated to go vote as their foes.
</P>
<P>
   With little attention paid to the races, neither friend nor foe
is likely to be aware that there is an election.
</P>
<P>
   So, in a low turnout, the candidate with a lot of cousins is
considered viable.
</P>
<P>
   If you think the situation is bad here, consider the single-race
ballots in Round Rock and San Marcos. Candidates in our neighboring
cities and with whom we share an environment, also are concerned
about the apathy greeting their races.
</P>
<P>
   Some say people don't care because times are good. Others say
people don't care because they're happy. Still others say people
don't care because nothing changes whoever wins.
</P>
<P>
   None of those suppositions is any basis for a form of
government, to borrow a line from Monty Python.
</P>
<P>
   Don't give in to apathy. Go vote.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
