r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN30-COX     04-29 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    House Calendars Committee: Where bills go to die
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The House Calendars Committee is the
Legislature's equivalent of the Bermuda Triangle. Many bills sail
into it, and particularly in the hectic closing weeks of the
140-day legislative session, some are never heard of again.
</P>
<P>
   After bills are passed out of other committees, Calendars
schedules them for floor debate by the Texas House of
Representatives _ or doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Members fight to get on Calendars because of its power over
bills and bargaining leverage for their own legislative package.
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely love it,'' said Rep. Debra Danburg (D-Houston),
who is a member this time. ``It gives you a chance to look at all
the bills in advance. It's the only committee through which all
bills must pass.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has no such committee. It requires a two-thirds vote
to put a bill on the floor; once there, a majority can pass it.
</P>
<P>
   But the Senate also allows its presiding officer _ the
lieutenant governor, currently Republican Rick Perry _ to decide
which senators to recognize to try for the two-thirds vote to bring
up their bills.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's one-man calendars committee ``would be a fiasco in
a body with 150 members,'' said Calendars member Brian McCall
(R-Plano). But one-third of the Senate _ any 11 senators _ can
block any bill.
</P>
<P>
   Calendars has 11 members. The chairman is Rep. Barry Telford
(D-Texarkana), a relative teddy bear compared to big, intimidating
past chairmen like Democrats Stan Schlueter of Killeen or Mark
Stiles of Beaumont, who chaired it the past three terms.
</P>
<P>
   Stiles was ``a resounding success. Somebody once described Mark
as a force of nature. He could be terribly brusque,'' Telford said.
``I have to find my own way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry is a real member's member,'' said McCall. ``He wants to
help freshmen get their bills set.''
</P>
<P>
   Telford admitted Calendars, on which he'd never served, was ``a
mystery'' to him before.
</P>
<P>
   Calendars meetings are open, which they haven't always been. But
there is little discussion while nonmembers are present.
</P>
<P>
   The committee usually convenes upon House adjournment, though
late in the session it may meet while the House is meeting. Most
members stand.
</P>
<P>
   One will read a list of bill numbers and move they be reported
to the floor. Members vote, then they adjourn.
</P>
<P>
   But the real meetings have taken place one on one, bill by bill.
Legislators and lobbyists talk to individual Calendars members, and
Calendars members to each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talk amongst themselves,'' said Cliff Johnson, a lobbyist
who was on Calendars in the 1980s, ``but they don't talk outside
the committee.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes six of the 11 members of the committee to set a bill.
But an unwritten tradition allows each committee member to ``tag''
a bill and hold it up for a week. Enough tags can kill a bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``People talk about it like there's something mystical about it,
but there's really nothing mystical,'' said Schlueter, now a
lobbyist. ``Somebody has to be the traffic cop, and the chairman
has to try to get all the bills to the floor he can without bogging
things down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously the chairman has a lot of power _ and discretion.
And there's always complaints. It's a tough job in that you can't
please everyone. That is the job of the Calendars Committee
chairman _ to take all the heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Do House speakers use the committee as their killing ground?
Schlueter, appointed by former House Speaker Gib Lewis, said ``I
got one call from Gib all session _ one.'' And that was to set a
bill, not kill it. Telford said House Speaker Pete Laney leaves him
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Far more common, Schlueter said, are committee chairmen trying
to kill a bill they had let out of their committee. ``So you catch
the blame for killing a bill that the chairman didn't want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes legislators _ including senators _ will ask Calendars
members to kill a bill of their own that they carried to please a
constituent or lobby group, but consider unneeded or bad
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done it to my own bills,'' Danburg laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Even busy chairmen of other committees, like Public Education
Committee chairman Paul Sadler (D-Henderson), like belonging to
Calendars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather be on it,'' Sadler observed dryly, ``than off it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
