<HEADER>
A7705 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIPOSUCTION30-COX     04-29 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPOSUCTION30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In quest for beauty, liposuction is operation of choice
 &HT;    By Sonja Isger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A taught tummy. Less-lumpy legs. A
chiseled chin.
</P>
<P>
   When Americans head to the doctor's office to retool what they
see in the mirror, liposuction is their procedure of choice.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, nearly 150,000 people had unwanted fat sucked from
their bodies. That's about 40,000 more than had the same procedure
in 1996 and three times the number who sought liposuction in 1992,
according to the American Society of Plastic and Reconstructive
Surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   Advances in technology accounts for part of the boom. Doctors
can now use ultrasonic equipment or inject fluid into the targeted
pockets and pull out more fat as a result.
</P>
<P>
   That leap means people can see more dramatic results, but it
also may expose them to more risk of serious medical complications.
Doctors and professional associations say liposuction is still
safe, but patients should be educated first.
</P>
<P>
   West Palm Beach plastic surgeon Dr. Fred Barr, and San Francisco
author on plastic surgery Dr. Alan Gaynor answered questions about
the procedure:
</P>
<P>
   Are liposuction and lipoplasty the same thing?
</P>
<P>
   Both: Yes. They refer to the removal, reduction of fat in
specific body areas.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have to have all areas done at once?
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor: No, but it saves a lot of time and money if you do. It
takes about $600 to set up an operating room. If you want to do
your stomach one day and the hips another, that's $600 each time.
It's certainly safer to do it once than than several times. But
beware of ``selling up.'' Some doctors, for example, will tell you,
if you do your stomach your hips will be out of balance, so you
should do them too. That should send up flags.
</P>
<P>
   Is this a reasonable alternative to dieting or other medical
procedures to take off weight?
</P>
<P>
   Barr: No. It is not. It will never be replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor: Unrelated. If someone is obese, liposuction is not an
answer. But liposuction is not forbidden on overweight people.
</P>
<P>
   What if I'm not overweight at all, but have saddle bags or a
stomach pooch that won't go away? How much fat has to be there to
qualify for the procedure?
</P>
<P>
   Barr: There really isn't a minimum. It becomes an issue of what
the patient is concerned about. We are ``hangup physicians.'' We
are here to help people with their hangups.
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor: Any that's disproportional. You can take out 2 ounces or
2 pounds on a large portion. You're going after part of their
figure they could never fix on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Can this procedure turn me into a bikini model?
</P>
<P>
   Barr: I think the issue of unrealistic expectations should be
addressed here. If somebody is already a model and spent a
significant amount of time working on their bodies to be what they
need for their career, and then they come in, fine. If you have
somebody who is not modeling, has a sedentary job ... to say you're
going to be spectacular is unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor: To get someone to look phenomenal with liposuction, they
have to had a good body. Each person can be taken a certain
distance.
</P>
<P>
   Can you be too old for liposuction _ too old for your skin to
snap back?
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor: In the stomach, yes. But there are 80-year-olds that you
can improve their saddle bags. And then again, you can't do all
25-year-olds either.
</P>
<P>
   How many incisions do you make? How big are they? And do they
scar afterwards?
</P>
<P>
   Barr: Usually the incisions are about 1/2 an inch or less. At
least one, sometimes two, sometimes three. Everybody has a scar.
Obviously, as plastic surgeons, we try to hide them. But they may
raise up, discolor, become numb.
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor: The ones that show a bit more are on the hips because
there's no natural place to hide them. So then I tell my patients
to bring a bikini so we can put it on the bikini lines.
</P>
<P>
   What type of anesthesia is used (am I awake for the operation?
Do I feel anything?)
</P>
<P>
   Barr: Everybody has their own method. I use spinal or general.
My patient would be asleep. People do them awake under conscious
sedation.
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor: For stomach-only or hips-only, you can use local, but
others might use IV medication. For the whole body, you can use
general, epidural where they're awake _ like Clinton had when he
hurt his knee _ or something in between.
</P>
<P>
   Can you take the fat out and put it somewhere else, such as my
lips, during the same operation?
</P>
<P>
   Barr: You can with traditional liposuction. Not with ultrasonic
(where the fat is emulsified before removal). The only thing of
controversy is putting fat in the breast areas.
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor: I'm the king of that. I took it out of Geraldo's buns
and put it in his face.
</P>
<P>
   How soon will I see the results?
</P>
<P>
   Barr: You'll see results in the first two weeks or so. But there
can be swelling, hardness and lumpiness in that time. They resolve
in three to six months. To improve results, we recommend our
patients massage the area four times a day with moisturizing cream
and spend time in whirlpools.
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor: I'd say 40 percent of change in six weeks, more up to
six months. After six months, what you see is what you get.
</P>
<P>
   Will this get rid of cellulite?
</P>
<P>
   Barr: No. And that's a problem because cellulite is a
disturbance of the surface attachment of muscle, skin and fat.
Sometimes liposuction can worsen those areas.
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor: Any doctor or any ad that tells you this can treat
cellulite is a medical fraud. Same thing for stretch marks. But
we're working on it.
</P>
<P>
   How many days off do I need to take from work?
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor: A liposuction on the stomach, you could go to work in
the next two or three days. A full body, five to six days.
</P>
<P>
   What will I feel like that day? That week?
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor: It hurts like crazy. It feels like you've won the
Marines situp contest. But we can give you medication, then you're
just uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Will the fat return?
</P>
<P>
   Barr: The liposuction will remove fat cells permanently, but the
existing cells will swell with weight gain. You may gain it first
in other areas, but you will eventually gain in those areas. Don't
gain, maintain.
</P>
<P>
   What are the risks?
</P>
<P>
   Barr: Bleeding, infection, scaring, irregularities of contour,
swelling of the extremities, asymmetries. With the ultrasonic
liposuction you've got to add in there burn wounds.
</P>
<P>
   How many mortgage payments will I have to skip to pay for this?
</P>
<P>
   Barr: It really depends on how you're doing the procedure _
office vs. in-patient. It's really variable. Fees are not in
general major expenses _ from $500 to several thousand dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
