<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRCONTROL30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Pushing Tin' takes flight of fancy
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Critics have generally liked ``Pushing Tin,''
the romantic comedy about two fiercely competitive air traffic
controllers, starring John Cusack and Billy Bob Thornton. The movie
opened last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It's safe to say most movie critics don't know diddly about
guiding planes from the heavens to terra firma. Viewers who do _
namely real air traffic controllers _ have a different spin on the
film, and they are not amused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most controllers didn't like it,'' says Austin air traffic
controller Ed Mears, who works at the Terminal Radar Approach
Control (TRACON) center at the new Austin-Bergstrom International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a medical guy watching 'ER' or 'MASH,''' he says. To
these guys, the film's inaccuracies about the job stick out in
high, irritating relief. ``They forget it's a movie,'' says Mears
of his naysaying colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   (For the record, Mears didn't hate the film. ``It had
entertaining moments, but I don't think we're going to see it at
the Oscars.'')
</P>
<P>
   Mears, who is the local president of the National Air Traffic
Controllers Association, is a 16-year veteran of ``pushing tin'' _
a term he knows but rarely hears.
</P>
<P>
   We asked Mears where the sometimes tech-heavy ``Pushing Tin''
hit the mark _ and where it lost altitude.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How accurately does the film depict your job?
</P>
<P>
   A: From a technical standpoint, parts of it were real accurate,
parts of it were not. A colleague said that at least now people
don't think we're the guys with the flashlights directing the
aircraft. Those guys work for the airlines. We call them ``ramp
rats.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does the film's TRACON look authentic?
</P>
<P>
   A: They built their own TRACON because the FAA wouldn't let them
in the building. It looks very accurate. The lights are up too
(bright), which you have to have for a movie. In ours you're kind
of feeling your way around the dark. The display on the radar
scopes is not color like they are in the movie, it's just green.
Their phraseology is pretty accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Q: For kicks, Thornton and Cusack's characters lay on a runway
as a 747 lands. They get whipped around like dolls in a twister. Is
this likely?
</P>
<P>
   A: It would throw a plane around, so I guess it would throw a
person around. That part is accurate. With a 747, planes have to be
five miles behind them. The wake turbulence from the lift of the
wings looks like horizontal tornadoes. It'll throw a jet and loop a
little plane.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the workplace as festive and frat housey as it is in the
movie?
</P>
<P>
   A: That was inaccurate. It seemed like the guys who were working
could get up at will and walk across the room and get into a
conversation. You can't do that. We can get slow enough here where
we could turn around and talk to a guy for a second. But not in New
York. Another inaccuracy is the constant crowd hanging out in
TRACON. If they're not plugged in working they're not going to hang
out in TRACON; they're going to be in the break room. It seemed
like a moving pack of groupies going from scope to scope. That
would be terribly distracting. You don't want someone behind you
distracting you, because you've got to hang on to that mental 3-D
picture you have.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What else was false?
</P>
<P>
   A: How they put aircraft in jeopardy for their personal
squabbles. When they got into a fist fight on the floor when they
had a lot of traffic, that was bizarre. Thornton's training was
interesting. He showed up and they sat down with him for what
looked like 15 minutes. It would take at least six months, I don't
care how good he is. And they wouldn't have cleared the building
during a bomb threat, either. They didn't when we had one!
</P>
<P>
   Q: What struck you as really accurate?
</P>
<P>
   A: The lack of empathy for weak controllers. Part of the whole
controller thing, unfortunately, is we tend to feed on our own. If
controllers smell blood, there are sharks in the water. You show
weakness, you're dead.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So the job is as competitive as it looks?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's very ego-driven and the guys are very self-confident
because you have to be very sure what you're saying. If it comes
across in your voice that you're not, the pilots won't listen to
you. That's what you do. You tell them to turn left, turn right, go
up, go down, stop, go fast, and you have to be sure of what you're
doing. Most controllers think they're the best one. I'm smarter
than that (laughs). I'm not the best one.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
