<SLUG> BC-SOC-SOCCER-ATLANTA30 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Silver-gilded soccer revival
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The latecomers kept piling onto the concrete seating
at DeKalb Memorial Stadium, many of them children in full uniforms.
Concession and beer and wine lines curled around the ends of the
concourses. The staff and management of the Atlanta Silverbacks,
who drew a local A-League record crowd of 8,416 for their season
opener April 17, clearly were surprised _ and happily so _ by the
deluge of spectators.
</P>
<P>
   It's a problem they're glad to have, as they revive a franchise
that was on the verge of collapse less than a year ago. When
co-owners John Latham and Bobby Glustrom took over the former
Ruckus last June, barely a hundred people were turning out for
games, the latest debacle in a series of flops for professional
soccer in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   After several months of trying to repair the damage caused by
their predecessors, Latham and Glustrom will get a true test of
their commitment over the next few days in what figures to be one
of the biggest soccer weekends in Atlanta in years. The Silverbacks
play the Jacksonville Cyclones Saturday night, then will serve as
hosts Sunday afternoon for a ``friendly'' match at DeKalb Memorial
between the U.S. women's national team and Japan. More than 9,000
tickets have been sold for that nationally televised match, part of
the American team's exhibition tour to promote the Women's World
Cup that begins in June.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Georgia State Soccer Association, in conjunction
with a number of business, political and soccer leaders from the
metro area, will announce plans for a soccer-only complex that
includes a 25,000-seat stadium and adjoining fields in the northern
Atlanta suburbs. For a city that has had a checkered history of
supporting soccer as a spectator sport, could these events be a
major turning point?
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have any idea we'd get the attendance we did, but
we're going to be anticipating good crowds from now on,'' said
Glustrom, the president of an international bank in midtown
Atlanta. ``The grass-roots involvement in soccer in Georgia is
finally starting to translate into a desire for high-quality
professional soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Atlanta Chiefs coach and North American Soccer League
commissioner Phil Woosnam has felt that way for nearly three
decades. He is a key figure in the secretive plan to create what is
being dubbed the ``Atlanta Soccer Village,'' which might be located
in north Fulton County or near Doraville.
</P>
<P>
   Woosnam's long-stated desire is to attract an MLS franchise to
the city. The league considered Atlanta in its start-up plans in
1996, but backed out because of the Olympics and the lack of a
suitable stadium, local investors and strong community support.
Nearly three years after the Atlanta games, those other factors
might be coming into shape. ``There's a lot of momentum now,'' said
Rick Skirvin, executive director of the GSSA, which began hashing
out Soccer Village options last fall. ``This has more real
potential than anything we've ever seen in this state. There's such
significant momentum that this is going to be a reality.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Silverbacks are making do with a 15,000-seat high
school football stadium and emphasizing outreach, particularly to
families with soccer-playing children and the metro area's
burgeoning Hispanic community.
</P>
<P>
   Latham and Glustrom require that players stay on the field after
games to sign autographs. A season ticket costs $55 for adults,
roughly the price of two field-level seats for a single Braves
game.
</P>
<P>
   Latham is a partner in the Atlanta law firm Alston and Bird and
a legal representative for Umbro, the A-League's main sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Glustrom, who has three soccer-playing sons, said, ``This is
what we want the Silverbacks to be about: an affordable,
people-friendly alternative to Turner Field and $40 tickets and the
big crowds that often make it tough for families to enjoy a night
out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The changes have been great,'' said Silverbacks defender Brian
Crane, who came to the Ruckus in 1996 and quit last season before
deciding to come back. ``From the top down, they're trying to do
everything right.''
</P>
<P>
   On another front, MLS is planning to expand by two more cities _
most likely Philadelphia and Houston _ either by next season or
2001. The next wave of expansion after that could come as early as
2003, and Atlanta is one of at least six cities being looked at,
along with San Diego, a second New York City team, Rochester, N.Y.,
Portland, Ore., and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see Atlanta as a sound market, one that has the
demographics we're looking for,'' said Christopher Pepe, an
assistant to MLS commissioner Doug Logan for expansion matters.
``Whether it can support soccer like Philadelphia or Houston, for
example, we can't say right now. But we're continuing to look into
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Woosnam and Atlanta public relations executive Amanda Brown
Olmstead have been the central players in persuading disparate
elements of the area's business, political and soccer communities
to get behind the Soccer Village plan. However, they have refused
to divulge essential details, including location, capacity,
financing, zoning and possible tenants.
</P>
<P>
   Woosnam _ whom Pepe called ``the heart and soul and driving
force of the effort to get MLS in Atlanta'' _ declined any comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Silverbacks' more immediate goals are to work with the
DeKalb Board of Education to ensure a long-term beer and wine
license, tear out the track surrounding the DeKalb Memorial field
for wider soccer configurations and overhaul a patchy, rocky
playing surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to DeKalb Memorial,'' said Latham, who served
on the GSSA's advisory board for the Soccer Village. ``Whether
something else becomes an alternative to what we already have, we
can't say for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, that's not a choice that confronts us. We need to
prove that we can crawl before we walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
