<HEADER>
A7728 &Cx1f; tab-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SACRAMENTO-SITES-ART-     04-29 1460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SACRAMENTO-SITES-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER 
 HISTORY COMES ALIVE IN SACRAMENTO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special one-shot feature culled from The New
York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate is
not prohibitive _ contact sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 By GENE AND ADELE MALOTT 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    The enthusiastic guide in the ornate Victorian house draws the
members of the tour group along just as a real estate salesman
might, urging them to think of themselves as residents, make
decorating decisions and choose their bedrooms.
 &HT;    Joe Wolfenden, a guide in the Old Governor's Mansion in
California's capital city of Sacramento, tells stories relating to
each room. When he points to gowns worn by women in former Gov.
Earl Warren's household, he muses that his mother-in-law, Florence
Muschetto, may have been the seamstress who made one of the
dresses.
 &HT;    As you leave the mansion, whistles shriek across the treetops _
some from steam trains, some from sternwheelers.
 &HT;    Sacramento is a city that offers mature travelers insights into
history, railroading, riverboats, traditional jazz, politics and
gold fever. And it constantly adds new items to its repertoire. For
inquisitive travelers, Sacramento can be an in-depth and leisurely
learning experience in an easy-to-take climate.
 &HT;    The spirit of modern Sacramento depends on the many ghosts of
Sacramento's past _ like John Sutter, whose fort was the
provisioning headquarters for the 49ers in search of their fortunes
150 years ago. Touches of the golden heritage are everywhere:
melted gold coins creating the crown on the State Capitol, the
burnished golden onion domes of the Russian Orthodox Church, broad
golden bands circling china plates in the governor's mansion.
 &HT;    Sacramento was the site of the genesis of the gold rush that
tilted our nation west; the jumping-off place for the
transcontinental railroad that tied this nation together
economically; and the launching pad for the political dreams of
several notable people.
 &HT;    Sitting in the midst of rich agricultural acreage and a
meandering river delta, Sacramento is often overlooked in favor of
bigger, brassier California cities with their film and high-tech
industries. But it is easy to be surprised while sampling
Sacramento and to come away with tidbits of the past that make
today easier to understand. For instance:
 &HT;    _ The music room in the Old Governor's Mansion (1526 H St.),
where guests sang show tunes while an aide to Gov. Ronald Reagan,
Michael Deaver, played the piano.
 &HT;    _ The State Capitol's assembly chambers (10th &AMP; L streets),
which simultaneously boast chairs for representatives of the
English crown and display computers on each of its 130-year-old
desks. Or the brightly colored modernistic portrait of Gov. Jerry
Brown in the halls of the Capitol hanging beside more somber,
formal portraits of his predecessors, including his father, Gov.
Pat Brown.
 &HT;    _ The living history scenes showcased regularly at Sutter's Fort
(27th &AMP; L streets). They tell stories about life when the fort
stood alone on the Sacramento plain in 1847 through the gold rush
frenzy of 1849 until 1857, when the rush was over and the frontier
gone.
 &HT;    _ The Sierra scene in the California State Railroad Museum (2nd
and I streets), which tips its hat in tribute to the lives and
deaths of thousands of Chinese workers who helped build the
transcontinental railroad, a great civil engineering feat. You can
even catch a ride on the Sacramento Southern Railroad steam train
on weekends from April through September.
 &HT;    _ The Huntington, Hopkins &AMP; Co. Hardware Store sign in Old
Sacramento (113 I St.), which tells you clearly that a quartet of
merchants who sold hardware, groceries and dry goods could become
the Big Four railroaders, who had great influence in the worlds of
politics and finance.
 &HT;    It had been some time since we lingered in Sacramento. So when
we had a chance to stay awhile and wander the vast and comfortable
neighborhoods studded with architecture of every era and bike the
tidy trails along the American River, we relished renewing our old
friendship. We enjoyed not only the attractions in the city itself,
but neighboring areas where we could prospect for gold, hunt for
antiques, go river rafting or walk around historic neighborhoods.
And this year, added attractions include celebrations of the
Sesquicentennial of the Gold Rush.
 &HT;    My, how Sacramento has grown! Not so much in size as in style.
 &HT;    Monolithic government buildings of every hue and style cozy up
to gingerbread Victorians, some commanding high banks that once
helped thwart river floods, others with elevated porches and
staircases leading past unusual first-floor delta basements.
 &HT;    Quiet, clean, light-rail trains slide beside horse-drawn
carriages and lines of cars and trucks. Nouveau restaurants have
moved into warehouse districts and car showrooms. Their tables
spill outside, where patrons lounge on even the warmest (100-plus
degrees) or coldest days (around 35 degrees).
 &HT;    Sidewalks deviate from their straight lines to meander around
the bases of big leafy trees, towering palms and dusty evergreens.
 &HT;    New museums have popped up, such as the McClellan Aviation
Museum (3204 Palm St., McClellan Air Force Base, 916/643-3192, free
admission), which now displays approximately 31 vintage aircraft.
 &HT;    Another is the innovative Golden State Museum (1020 O St.,
916/653-4255, $5 admission for seniors), showcasing the people and
politics of California through interactive exhibits. For example,
you can climb inside a bus to hear the voices of those who
immigrated to ``Golden Mountain,'' as the Chinese referred to
California.
 &HT;    More established museums offer mini-theatricals with docents
dressed in costumes of the era or stage elaborate multi-day
festivals. One upcoming festival offered by the California State
Railroad Museum is Railfair '99 (June 18-27, 1999), which will
feature locomotives and railroad cars as well as live entertainment
and living history demonstrations to highlight the ways railroads
have made a difference in our lives.
 &HT;    Railfair prices for those 62 and older are $1 off whatever
admission you buy, from a one-day to a 10-day pass. Those buying
tickets in advance _ before June 17 _ get an additional $4 off.
Call 916/445-6645 for information.
 &HT;    And this year, dozens of special events are planned to celebrate
the Gold Rush anniversary, including ``Gold Fever!'' (Aug. 1-Oct.
31), an interactive, multimedia exhibition that is one of the
anniversary centerpieces. It will be held in Sacramento's Memorial
Auditorium at 15th &AMP; J streets (916/264-7072). Admission for those
65 and older is $6.
 &HT;    Sacramento's Old Town will convert itself into a theme park with
sawdust-filled streets for The Second Great Gold Rush from Sept. 3
to 6, featuring reenactments of everything from a horse-drawn
funeral to the arrival of the Pony Express. Call 916/264-8141 for
ticket info.
 &HT;    Earlier in the year, on Memorial Day weekend (May 28-31), the
city will resound with the music of the Sacramento Jazz Jubilee
(916/372-5277). Jazz concerts in dozens of venues from one end of
the city to the other will showcase bands from around the world and
across the United States, while aficionados dress up in costume and
dance and swing whenever the beat moves them. Daily tickets range
from $16 for half-day admission to $80 for the weekend; admission
on Monday is half-price for seniors.
 &HT;    Trains and planes and boats and all that jazz _ these are the
grown-up toys that hold fascination for many mature travelers and
are so much a part of the Sacramento of today.
 &HT;    For your copy of the Sacramento Vacation Planner with details
about these and other attractions, call 916/264-5553 or visit the
website at www.sacramentocvb.org.
 &HT;    
 &HT;     ( The Malotts are the publishers of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.)  
