<HEADER>
A7733 &Cx1f; ttf-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OVERCOMING-JET-LAG-TR     04-29 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OVERCOMING-JET-LAG-TRAVEL-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEDDING LIGHT ON JET LAG 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special one-shot feature culled from The New
York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate is
not prohibitive _ contact sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 By EVERETT POTTER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Forget melatonin and faddish diets. When it comes to jet lag,
that traveler's hangover of digestive ailments, sleep deprivation
and moodiness, it's best to turn on the lights.
 &HT;    That's the contention of Dr. Martin Moore-Ede, a Harvard Medical
School professor for 25 years, who says that ``external and
internal desynchronization'' are the major culprits. Moore-Ede is
now president of Circadian Technologies in Cambridge, Mass., a
company that deals with issues of sleep and productivity for major
U.S. corporations, and the co-author of ``The Complete Idiot's
Guide to Getting a Good Night's Sleep'' (Macmillan, 1998; $16.95)
with Suzanne LeVert.
 &HT;    ``You're asking your body to cope with a sudden shift from day
to night,'' Moore-Ede points out. ``You're cramped in a plane with
low humidity, and you're dehydrated regardless of what you consume.
And when you get there, you're required to sleep at times that are
counter to your biology.''
 &HT;    Moore-Ede believes that once travelers determine whether they
are a ``morning lark'' or a ``night owl,'' they can counter the
effects of jet lag with massive doses of light at the proper time.
They must factor in which direction they're flying, how many time
zones they've skipped and how much sleep they've lost.
 &HT;    As for other methods of dealing with jet lag, Moore-Ede says,
``There's no data whatsoever'' to support jet lag diets and there
are clear dangers to using faddish drugs like melatonin. Instead,
he believes in using light and making some sensible travel
decisions.
 &HT;    ``First, your choice of flights and times is quite
significant,'' he says. ``Certain flights are better suited to
certain types of people.''
 &HT;    Moore-Ede says that morning people who can adapt well to going
to bed early and then rapidly adjust to a new time zone should take
advantage of daytime flights from the United States to Europe.
 &HT;    ``But if you're a morning person and there isn't a daytime
flight,'' Moore-Ede says, ``take an early evening flight that gets
you into Europe anywhere from 4:30 a.m. to 7 a.m. and then go to
bed immediately when you arrive.''
 &HT;    For night owls heading to Europe, ``you may do well by taking
the latest evening flight that you can find and then try to sleep
on the plane,'' he adds. ``You don't want a flight that gets you in
at 6 a.m. local time. You want to get in as close to noon as you
can.''
 &HT;    For today's business travelers who are making a relatively short
trip to Asia or Europe, Moore-Ede says that ``there's considerable
logic to not adjusting your biological clock at all but simply
adapting as best as you can, and staying on your home time zone.''
 &HT;    As for getting that precious sleep upon arrival, look for hotels
that cater to business travelers. Some Hiltons, for example, have
special rooms with blackout drapes and extra soundproofing and have
specially trained their housekeeping staff not to disturb guests.
 &HT;    But the two key components for dealing with jet lag are light
and dark, says Moore-Ede, who was a member of the Harvard team that
discovered in the human brain the cluster of nerve cells known as
the suprachiasmatic nuclei, or SCN.
 &HT;    ``The SCN regulates the 25-hour time clock that we are believed
to have and it enables early morning light to reset our clocks to a
24-hour day, every day,'' Moore-Ede says.
 &HT;    To reduce jet lag, Moore-Ede suggests using heavy doses of light
to both reset and advance time clocks based on individual sleep
personalities and the distance traveled.
 &HT;    His theory is that any light that a traveler receives before 5
a.m. home time shifts his or her time clock westbound. Light
received after 5 a.m. home time will shift it eastbound. The amount
of light needed to make a real adjustment is measured in lux, a
metric unit used to quantify the intensity of visible light.
Moore-Ede says that one needs about 2,500 lux to move one's body
clock one hour or more in a single dose.
 &HT;    Moore-Ede notes that a room lit with 100-watt lightbulbs will
produce only about 200 to 500 lux. With his corporate clients, he
uses a light visor called Bio-Brite to deliver the required number
of lux to them when they're sitting in a hotel room or on a plane.
 &HT;    His clients also use his software program, Midnight Sun, to
figure out how much light they'll need. This program can tell them
before they get on a flight to Japan this afternoon the exact time
of dawn in Tokyo tomorrow. It will inform them of how long a dose
of light they'll need in flight and how much they'll need upon
arrival.
 &HT;    But for those who don't have $300 to spend on a Bio-Brite light
visor, let alone the money for the software program, Moore-Ede says
to simply go outside. He maintains that a cloudy day yields about
10,000 lux while a sunny blue sky provides a whopping 50,000 lux.
 &HT;    The disappointing news is that even with concentrated doses of
light, jet lag won't be completely eliminated. But it should make
the transition from the United States to Paris or Tokyo or Tel Aviv
that much easier.
 &HT;     (Everett Potter is a New York-based free-lance writer.)  
 &HT;     c.1999 Everett Potter  
