<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, April 29, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Friday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   STOCKTON-SCHOOL (Stockton, Calif.) _ When Stockton dedicated its
Children's Museum to the victims of a 1989 schoolyard massacre,
speaker after speaker repeated the same hope: ``This will be the
last school shooting.'' But 10 years and many campus tragedies
later, Stockton has instead become a study in survivors and a
community that cannot put the deaths of five children in the past.
The reminders are everywhere, especially in the headlines and
newscasts following shootings like the one last week in Littleton,
Colo. By ERIC DRUDIS.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-MISSING (San Francisco) _ A 5-year-old Santa Rosa, Calif.,
girl was reunited with her mother after a resident of a small
Mexican town used his computer to sign onto a Web site of missing
children and recognized the faces of the child and her alleged
abductor, the girl's father. By KATHERINE SELIGMAN.
</P>
<P>
   GROUNDED-THUNDERBIRDS (San Antonio) _ The Air Force has
suspended all performances by the Thunderbirds, the service's
precision flight team, for only the second time since a fatal 1982
crash. The decision was made after the Air Force reviewed an
incident in which two F-16 jets made contact while taking off at an
air show Sunday at Patrick AFB, Fla. By SIG CHRISTENSON.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-LAWSUIT (Houston) _ Three people from Houston have filed a
federal lawsuit challenging the constitutionality of a Texas law
that prohibits the direct shipment of wine to a Texas residence
from out of state. The law also prohibits the transportation of
more than three gallons of wine across the state line. By ED ASHER.
</P>
<P>
   DENTISTS-TEXAS (Houston) _ When health officials decided that a
panel of experts should review fraud allegations involving the
Texas Medicaid dental program, they told an aggressive consultant
that his services were no longer needed. But when a top health
official sent out letters soliciting members of the new panel, one
of them went to the consultant. Dentist Donald Crow says the
mailing suggests a lack of serious commitment to fraud enforcement.
By MARK SMITH.
</P>
<P>
   LATINOS-WAR (San Francisco) _ Anti-war author Jorge Mariscal is
frustrated that the Latino community isn't asking harder questions
about war in Yugoslavia, especially since two of the three American
POW's taken in the Kosovo conflict are Latinos. By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS-PASSION (San Francisco) _ If you ever have a chance to
see ``Rent'' _ or if you ever had a chance to see Wayne Gretzky _
you might appreciate why passion is more than a career counseling
buzzword. The career counseling mantra is that you should find work
that you're passionate about, but keeping that passion is a lot
easier to philosophize about than to accomplish. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   GASOLINE-PRICES (Sacramento, Calif.) _ A week-long breakdown at
a Southern California Arco refinery, kept secret from the public
until now, was a major factor in the recent huge increase in gas
prices in California, state officials say. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-MELLENCAMP (Undated) _ John Mellencamp, 47, has learned to
enjoy his success, even as his kind of music _ rock 'n' roll _
seems to be taking a back seat to other sounds among younger
listeners. By RICK MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-SONG (Undated) _ Jan Karon has produced another
adventure with Father Tim Kavanagh, but this time he has left the
small town of Mitford, N.C. If some of the new characters in ``A
New Song'' don't have the same resonance as our old Mitford
friends, it's probably just because we don't have the same history
with them. That's a sure sign of more to come. By JOHN GRIFFIN.
</P>
<P>
   MP3 (San Francisco) _ From garage trios to headlining divas,
modern-day musicians have jumped onto the cyberspace bandwagon en
masse, using the popular digital compression format ``MP3'' to
record and market their music to a global audience via the
Internet. By GLENN RUBENSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   STAR-WARS (Pleasant Hill, Calif.) _ Dan Killoran came up with an
idea crazy enough to get most people locked away on one of the
moons of Jupiter. Killoran, 29, a musician when he's not delivering
packages for UPS, decided that he was going to write a song
celebrating ``Star Wars,'' and try to get it done in time for the
mega-grand premiere of the latest epoch from George Lucas on May
19. By CRAIG MARINE.
</P>
<P>
   TV-NICK (Undated) _ Next time you find little Johnny watching
too much TV and you're about to snatch the remote away and begin
your patented Parental Lecture About the Great Outdoors, think
again. That kid could be in training to run a TV network. By TIM
GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PATAKI-BALKANS (Washington) _ New York Gov. George Pataki has
blasted President Clinton's foreign policy and his handling of the
war in Kosovo, saying the administration's ``track record of
indecisiveness'' helped create the Balkan conflict. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-TEXAS (Jefferson, Texas) _ To wander the pine forests of
East Texas is to see what pioneers from long ago saw. The past is
very much alive here. But this region is also very much about the
here and now. East Texas has a little something for just about
everyone _ except big city stress. By RENEE KIENTZ (Photos
available on NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-MARHSALL (Marshall, Texas) _ Some travelers might see
Marshall as a blip on Interstate 20, a chance to gas up before
heading on to the bed-and-breakfasts of Jefferson or the casinos of
Shreveport/Bossier City, La. But something's afoot. This East Texas
city has the feel of a town on the cusp of becoming a destination
in its own right. By RENEE KIENTZ. (Photo available on NYT
database.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-EL-CAMINO (Nacogdoches, Texas) _ To some folks traveling
through the Piney Woods, Texas Highway 21 is just a pretty
east-west stretch of road. It'll get you where you're going, all
right. Or it can take you back in time. Back to the early days of
El Camino Real, the Royal Road. By RENEE KIENTZ. (Photo available
on NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CADDOAN-MOUNDS (Caddoan Mounds State Park, Texas) _
Standing in a clearing at Caddoan Mounds State Park, you wonder
what this place looked like 1,200 years ago when a group of Caddo
Indians decided it was the right spot for a village. By RENEE
KIENTZ. (Photo available on NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-LAKES (Undated) _ Many of us appreciate the beauty of
East Texas best with a fishing pole in hand, though often fish have
nothing to do with it. It's more about a state of grace, the
enormously complex simplicity of sun flashing off the water's
surface, the chance to just sit and relax and enjoy the open air.
By RENEE KIENTZ. (Photo available on NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ If anyone was watching the debate
over Serbia on C-SPAN, it probably came as a surprise that the
power to declare war is reserved for Congress. Don't presidents
have the right to bomb any country that displeases them? On
Wednesday, the House of Representatives stood up for itself. By ROB
MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ In the Littleton, Colo.,
shootings, the two teenage shooters _ who allegedly planned to kill
hundreds of people _ were not members of a racial or ethnic
minority, were not poor and did not come from broken homes.
Remember that the next time a politician or condemnatory clergyman
heaps the blame for society's woes atop welfare mothers, divorce,
violence-prone minorities and the decay of traditional family
values. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
