<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7791 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-MELLENCAMP-HNS &LR;      04-29 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MELLENCAMP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN IN MIDDLE AGE, MELLENCAMP REMAINS PASSIONATE ABOUT ROCK 'N'
ROLL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICK MITCHELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've probably seen the T-shirts. The message is aimed at
uptight grown-ups yelling at their kids to turn down that darn rock
'n' roll: ``If it's too loud, you're too old.''
</P>
<P>
   John Mellencamp, middle-aged rock star, isn't buying it anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at what young people buy, it is not rock 'n'
roll,'' he said. ``Hip-hop is very popular with young people, and
country music is very popular with young people, but I don't see
rock 'n' roll being that popular with young people. I don't see a
lot of young rock bands going out on tour and selling records the
way that I experienced it in my youth. It just doesn't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he notes that there are still some good modern-rock
bands such as the Offspring, Mellencamp predicts that the rock 'n'
roll era is coming to a close.
</P>
<P>
   ``All music has its cycle, and it goes away,'' he said. ``I
remember the fear in our parents' faces when the Rolling Stones
showed up and we had our hair just barely on top of our ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where it started, and I think this is where it ends.
It'll never go away, but I don't think you're going to find another
movement like the punk movement rejuvenating the music.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Mellencamp is ready to hang up his rock 'n' roll shoes
just yet. He's bringing his band to the Houston area May 5, the
third stop on the ``Rural Electrification'' tour supporting his
latest album, titled simply ``John Mellencamp.'' The album came out
six months ago and is no longer on the Billboard Top 200 sales
chart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there some rule that I don't know about, that your album
comes out and you have to go on tour five days later?'' Mellencamp
asked in mock indignation. ``I just sort of approached it in an
unconventional manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Mellencamp's whole career has proceeded in a somewhat
unconventional manner. His first album, ``Chestnut Street
Incident,'' was released in 1976 under the name Johnny Cougar.
Mellencamp first learned of his new stage name when he saw the
album cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody ever called me Johnny my whole life,'' he said. ``That
record sold 18,000 copies _ hated by everyone. Read the first
review they ever did of me in Cream magazine; the last line went
something like, `This record is not very good, but what a wonderful
find it will be in the cut-out bins in 1984.''
</P>
<P>
   Mellencamp went on to enjoy massive commercial success with
``American Fool'' _ the best-selling album of 1982 _ and finally
won over the critics with his mid-'80s masterpieces ``Scarecrow''
and ``The Lonesome Jubilee.'' But he's never been able to shake
completely that manufactured pop-idol moniker.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first cut is always the deepest,'' he said. ``People still
call me Johnny Cougar.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the circumstances, Mellencamp considers himself fortunate
to have had such a long and rewarding career.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking to the luckiest guy in the world,'' he said,
punctuating his speech with his favorite unprintable adjective. ``I
started out at 22 years old. I had no idea what I was doing _ none,
no vision at all about what I was supposed to do. All I wanted to
do initially was make a record.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then here it is in 1999, 20-some years later. I'm still
making records. I do exactly what I want to do. I hear my songs on
the radio all the time. It's amazing to me that people will be
dancing and making love to my songs in the next millennium. Now
isn't that astonishing for a guy who started out as Johnny
Cougar?''
</P>
<P>
   Mellencamp admits he went through a period when he was less
appreciative of his good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a young guy, I really never was in the moment,'' he
said. ``In the '80s, I was always like five years ahead of myself.
I didn't really have the opportunity or the brains to enjoy what I
was going through at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to a point in my life in the late '80s and early '90s
where I had to make a decision _ if I was going to be one of those
bitter, jaded guys in the music business or if I was going to turn
my life around and try to be a little bit more upbeat about
things.''
</P>
<P>
   His newfound peace of mind is reflected in some of the songs on
``John Mellencamp.'' In the bouncy ``I'm Not Running Anymore,'' he
comically describes his two young sons as ``the hoodlums of my
third wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Over sweeping violins in ``Your Life Is Now,'' he declares his
intention to learn to live in the present:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Your finest days are lost to you
</P>
<P>
   This is your time down here to do what you will do
</P>
<P>
   We could shake this world if you would only show us how
</P>
<P>
   Your life is now ...``
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mellencamp, 47, lives with his third wife, model Elaine Irwin,
and pint-sized hoodlums Hud and Speck in Belmont, Ind., the town
where he grew up. (Two teen-age daughters by a previous marriage
are frequent visitors from South Carolina.)
</P>
<P>
   George Green, Mellencamp's childhood friend and frequent
co-writer (``Hurts So Good,'' ``Rain On the Scarecrow,'' ``Human
Wheels''), lives just a few blocks away.
</P>
<P>
   Mellencamp's small-town upbringing led to his involvement with
Farm Aid, which he formed in 1985 with Willie Nelson and Neil
Young. Each year, Farm Aid holds an annual all-day fund-raising
concert in support of the American family farmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just did one last year in Chicago, and we're doing one this
year in either Kansas City or Los Angeles,'' he said. ``Farm Aid
was really the one `aid' that came out of the '80s that was a true
representation of what it's supposed to do. The rest were invented
by corporations, promoted by corporations and sold to America and
the world by corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me put it like this: Are people still starving in Africa?
Where's Live Aid?''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Mellencamp suffered a mild heart attack. He's since
started taking better care of himself. He works out regularly,
maintains a healthy diet and takes medicine to keep his coronary
disease under control. The one bad habit he hasn't been able to
kick is smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cigarettes got their mitts into me early. Hopefully, someday
I'll be strong enough to quit smoking 'em,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After 14 albums on the Mercury/Polygram label, Mellencamp jumped
to Columbia prior to the release of his latest album. He felt his
previous label had stopped promoting his albums. (Last year,
Mercury released a greatest-hits collection, ``The Best That I
Could Do, 1978-1988.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``When Polygram went public, their whole outlook on how to sell
records changed,'' Mellencamp said. ``I'm very fortunate to grow up
when I did, because that's back when record companies were
privately owned by individuals who cared about developing artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's important to a public company? The stock holder. Hanson
had three albums out in their first year. You can see that people
were just harvesting this act to make numbers. That's what the
focus has become in the late '90s _ numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My favorite record ever made was `Highway 61 Revisited' (by
Bob Dylan). I don't know how many records it sold then, and I don't
know how many records it has sold now. Because I'm interested in
what's on the record, not how many copies it sold.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Mellencamp's albums aren't selling the kind of numbers
they did in the '80s, he maintains his faith in the power of music
to change lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``At my best, I can write a song that's powerful enough to touch
somebody's emotions. For a moment, that person thinks about himself
and that song. When you are able to do that, you have made a friend
for life. I've been fortunate that I've been able to write two or
three that people felt that way about.''
</P>
<P>
   And remember: If it's too loud, you're too young.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
