<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7792 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY29-COX     04-29 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY29-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: A playground in the woods
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Susie Clifton
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   My mother died in 1942 when I was a year old. In 1944, Daddy and
my Cherokee stepmother and I _ red-haired and freckle-faced _ moved
from Texas to our 10-acre farm in Clay County, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   My four half-brothers were born during the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Our nearest neighbor lived a couple of miles away, so we
entertained ourselves. We had radio, but no TV until the late
1950s.
</P>
<P>
   A railroad track ran along our piney woods farm. We'd wave to
the train engineers, and they'd wave back.
</P>
<P>
   Mom said that whenever a train was late during the night, we
children would wake up because we had not heard the train whistle
in our sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Daddy walked with our dogs and us a couple of miles
down the tracks to the trestle over Black Creek. The tracks
followed beside the main road to town, about ten miles.
</P>
<P>
   One year, a hurricane washed out the bridge on the road to town.
People had to either park their car on one side and cross the creek
in a neighbor's boat or hike through the woods to the railroad and
walk across the trestle. Everybody was happy when the bridge was
rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   Once Daddy took two of my brothers and me to Jacksonville, Fla,
to see a movie. We drove to town and boarded the train, which then
chugged by our farm on the way to Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   Mom and the babies waved to us as we passed, and everyone on
that train knew it was our farm.
</P>
<P>
   Daddy built our house. The log part was two bedrooms and two
closets.
</P>
<P>
   A concrete slab formed the porch beside the bedrooms. On the
porch stood a wringer washing machine and two rinse tubs, which I
was well acquainted with on wash day.
</P>
<P>
   Daddy put a small trailer on another side of the porch, took the
wheels off and made it into a kitchen. Mom planted flowers around
the outside of it.
</P>
<P>
   On the third side of the porch he attached a huge wooden crate
that an airplane engine had come in. He worked at the Jacksonville
Naval Air Station, so he had access to discarded crates.
</P>
<P>
   Inside this crate he put down a concrete floor with plumbing, a
toilet and a smooth concrete bathtub.
</P>
<P>
   The water heater was outside, behind the crate bathroom. The
water pipes ran from a shower to the metal hot water tank which was
tilted on its side, one end higher than the other, and set on
concrete blocks at each end.
</P>
<P>
   When we needed hot water, we built a trash fire under the tank.
In a few minutes Mom said, ``OK! Everybody get your bath. But don't
use up all of the hot water!''
</P>
<P>
   We had a garden every spring and summer, and Daddy planted a
pear tree right in the middle of it. We had all the vegetables we
could eat and always more tomatoes than we needed.
</P>
<P>
   Daddy loved gladioluses and included them in the garden. Every
year when he plowed, he'd spread gladiolus bulbs all over the
place, so there were multi-colored flowers among the beans,
potatoes, corn and everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   I loved the woods. They were the playground for my brothers and
me, acres and acres of woods.
</P>
<P>
   Once I saw an old movie, ``Rose Marie.'' I wanted to be an
Indian like Rose Marie, and like my brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Once I secretly wrote, ``I want to be an Indian'' on a piece of
paper, wrapped it tightly in tinfoil and buried it near the water
tank under some rocks.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until many years later that I realized I already had a
Cherokee spirit by the time I was four years old. I still do.
</P>
<P>
   I still live in the woods, now back in the piney woods of East
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   I still like train whistles. I still have a garden and grow more
tomatoes than I need.
</P>
<P>
   Susie Clifton makes her home in Nacogdoches, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915. A photo of the writer is optional. If your
article is used, you will receive $25. For other Dreamsville
stories, visit htt://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
