<HEADER>
A7798 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DENTISTS-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      04-29 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENTISTS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS ARISE OVER HOW DENTAL FRAUD OVERSIGHT PANEL PICKED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK SMITH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   State health officials told an aggressive fraud consultant last
year that his services no longer were needed and that a panel of
experts would be assigned to watch for irregularities in the Texas
Medicaid dental program.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks later, when the state's top health official sent out form
letters soliciting members of the new panel, one of them went to
the ousted consultant, dentist Donald Crow.
</P>
<P>
   In the Nov. 24, 1998, letter seeking ``expert consultation,''
Health and Human Services Commissioner Don A. Gilbert also
solicited at least two prospects whose expert credentials likely
were out of date.
</P>
<P>
   Crow said one gave up dentistry almost 20 years ago and now owns
a beer distributorship, and another dropped his Texas dental
practice more than five years ago and lives in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The letter to Crow was mailed to a 5-year-old address.
</P>
<P>
   Crow, 54, said the apparent carelessness of the mail-out
suggests a lack of serious commitment to fraud enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Postal Service spent more time tracking me down than the
Health and Human Services Commission did in attempting to find
skilled and experienced dentists,'' Crow said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sent nothing more than boilerplate letters using a very
old mailing list.''
</P>
<P>
   Commission spokesman Charles Stuart insisted that the Houston
Chronicle submit any questions to him in writing about the Nov. 24
letter, the process of selecting its recipients and the status of
any panels that have been formed. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; He said Gilbert declined to be interviewed on the matter.
Stuart had not responded to the written questions by late
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between Crow and the Health Department have been
strained since 1993, when he sued the department over an earlier
reassignment. The case was tried this week in Austin before state
District Judge John Dietz, who told the parties that he would rule
within a week. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Crow said he believes the proposed expert panel was a
``transparent attempt'' by state health officials to make the
public believe they were doing something about Medicaid fraud.
</P>
<P>
   He said the panel of dentists, serving as part-time consultants,
ultimately may cost taxpayers more than dentists paid full time to
review cases in the $146 million dental program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better to have a full-time staff,'' Crow said. ``That's
better than having all these people stumbling around not knowing
what they are looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Crow served more than two years at the helm of a high-tech
anti-fraud effort. He had been assigned to the job at Health and
Human Services from other duties at a subordinate agency, the Texas
Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   Perusing data generated by a new supercomputer at the Health and
Human Services Commission and following his own instincts, Crow
decided which dentists warranted investigation for possible
overbilling or improper patient treatment.
</P>
<P>
   He said he routinely had several dentists review a case once he
developed it, to avoid concern that a single reviewer's biases
might affect enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   In late August, shortly after the president of the Texas Dental
Association and several pediatric dentists complained about him,
Crow was told that he would be returning to the Department of
Health.
</P>
<P>
   Just weeks after that, he was informed that he was being placed
on paid ``emergency leave'' and would be out of work, effective
Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert described Crow last year as ``aggressive'' and ``very
conscientious,'' and said that his return to the Health Department
had nothing to do with the dentists' complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timing of this, I understand, provokes a lot of questions,
but it was not connected,'' Gilbert said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision already had been made to replace Crow with a panel
of dentists from different specialties ``to ensure we have a broad
range of dental expertise to evaluate dental practices,'' Gilbert
said.
</P>
<P>
   The change in Medicaid review methods followed a scathing letter
from TDA President Stephen Schwartz to Gilbert. Schwartz complained
of intimidation by investigators, selective enforcement and lack of
due process.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the Chronicle earlier this year, Gilbert said the
computer system, called the Medicaid Fraud and Abuse Detection
System, or MFADS, had resulted in more than 50 fraud investigations
and at least two probable criminal prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of stories beginning in 1995, the Chronicle has
reported on allegations that state health agencies have deferred
too readily to dentists' complaints that fraud investigators were
aggressive and unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Some dentists have billed the tax-funded programs for procedures
that dental experts said were unnecessary or even dangerous, the
Chronicle's investigation found.
</P>
<P>
   Although Crow wouldn't discuss specifics, he said ``six to eight
major cases'' involving Medicaid fraud and abuse remain backlogged
in the Human Services Commission's Office of Investigations and
Enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Crow sued the Health Department in 1993 after being replaced as
dental bureau chief by Dr. Gloriana ``Nana'' Lopez, a friend of
then-Health Commissioner David Smith. Lopez and Smith have since
left the Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   In his lawsuit, Crow alleges that it was improper for the Health
Department to remove him from his position as dental bureau chief
without a hearing to show he had performed inadequately at his job.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Department contends that it did not have to show any
cause for his removal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
