<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 11:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7801 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-TEXAS-ART-HNS &LR;      04-29 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-TEXAS-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORICAL TOWNS, NATURAL WONDERS PART OF PINEY WOODS IN EAST
TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Also see: Travel-Marshall, Travel-Caddoan-Mounds,
Travel-El-Camino and Travel-Lakes) 
 
(Photo available on NYT database) 
 
(Eds.: Accent mark needed over second e in Renee) 
 
By RENEE KIENTZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON, Texas _ Just the words whispered out loud have
restorative powers: Piney Woods. ``Piney Woods.'' Feel that blood
pressure dropping, the pulse slow a little bit? Close your eyes.
See the sunlight filtering through trees, forest floor carpeted
with pine needles, a red-shouldered hawk soaring overhead, at one
with the sky, the earth, you even.
</P>
<P>
   To wander the pine forests of East Texas is to see what the
Anglo pioneers saw, and before them Spaniard explorers, and before
that Indian tribes such as the Caddo and the Coushatta. The past is
very much alive here, the history breathing, in the woods and in
the towns spacing them, places such as Nacogdoches and San
Augustine and Jefferson, places whose very names trace the state's
lineage.
</P>
<P>
   Not that you have to even care about history to enjoy an East
Texas getaway. This region is very much about the here and now.
Sitting here in a boat gently rocking, rocking on Red Hills Lake or
Toledo Bend or Caddo Lake. Shopping now in the gift and antiques
shops facing Jefferson's brick-lined streets.
</P>
<P>
   East Texas has a little something for just about everyone,
except Big City stress. Want that? Stay home. Otherwise, point that
hood ornament a little bit north, a little bit east, right on up
U.S. 59. There are myriad destinations in the Piney Woods, but this
story is taking you right past most of them (don't fret, we detour
in related stories) and aiming upward, toward Jefferson, just past
Interstate 20.
</P>
<P>
   East Texas tourism is defined by the triad of history, nature
and antiquing, and you'll find a confluence of all three in and
around the little town of Jefferson, about a 4 1/2-hour drive from
downtown Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Long a weekend getaway for Dallasites, Jefferson touts itself as
the bed-and-breakfast (there are 50-plus) capital of Texas, and the
town is also home to a couple of historical hotels. There are
museums to see, excursions to take, shops to explore, all within
walking distance of the historic downtown area. If nature calls _
the trees, the lakes, we mean _ it's a short drive to the shores of
Lake O' the Pines or the spooky (in a good way) Caddo.
</P>
<P>
   But first ...
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A LITTLE HISTORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These days, Jefferson's population hovers at around 2,500. Once
upon a time, when steamboats carried cargo all the way from New
Orleans and commerce boomed, some 30,000 souls lived there.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in the early 1840s, Jefferson was a major inland port
and home to iron smelting plants, slaughterhouse and lumber
industries as well as to some very wealthy Texans. From the 1850s
to the 1880s, they built large homes using the finest materials.
</P>
<P>
   Confident in the power of the steamboat, city decision-makers
spurned the proposal of railroad tycoon Jay Gould to lay tracks in
Jefferson and their fate was sealed. Angry, Gould predicted the end
of the town and took his railroad elsewhere. His prediction was
right in a way: The steamboat era waned and Jefferson as they knew
it waned with it. But Jefferson didn't die, it just shrank, and
with ``progress'' halted, time pretty much stood still.
</P>
<P>
   Plaques denoting historic interest dot the landscape in downtown
Jefferson: More than 100 Victorian homes and 19th-century buildings
still stand in and around the 20-block historic district. Many of
the homes are bed-and-breakfasts, some open for tours. Other
buildings house shops, galleries and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WALK THIS WAY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because Jefferson's historic downtown is compact, you can park
your car on arrival and not turn that ignition key again until it's
time to head back home. Strolling is big in Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   So are long weekends. Most visitors come in for Friday-Sunday
getaways, giving the town a slowed-down feel on weekdays. Most
shops are shuttered on Mondays; some close early on other days, but
there are two distinct advantages to midweek visits: no crowds and
lower rates at many of the inns.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever you visit, a Turning Basin Tours cruise down Big
Cypress Bayou is a good place to start. Back when Jefferson was the
second biggest town in Texas _ and Galveston was first _ Big
Cypress was its lifeline. Sitting in this day for Capt. John Nance,
local artist and occasional river pilot Mac Spruell tells
passengers of the town's heyday and colorfully explains the
waterway's role in it.
</P>
<P>
   The pristine passing scenery represents progress in reverse.
Serene and green, the bayou's pretty banks now are lined with
cypress trees and little else, unless you know what to look for.
Spruell points out subtle signs of a long-ago boom, a commercial
surge that, 140 years back, crowded the banks with meat processing
plants, iron ore smelters and loading docks.
</P>
<P>
   Spruell tells us that, if we were of a mind, we could take that
boat all the way down through Louisiana to the Gulf of Mexico. That
some 85 species of fish live in this bayou, which is 20 feet deep
in places. That the cypress trees we're passing look large, but
they're nothing compared to the centuries-old trees harvested to
build the fine houses of Jefferson. When Spruell cuts the engine,
the quiet is deep and lovely, intense enough to scare the kids and
startle the adults.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 1141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 11:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7804 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-TEXAS-ART-2NDT     04-29 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-TEXAS-ART-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
JEFFERSON, Texas: startle the adults.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back on land, you've got a very short walk to downtown. If
you're in the mood for shopping, there are a number of antiques
malls and shops, mostly concentrated along North Polk and Walnut
streets, and gift shops. Stop for an ice cream soda at the
Jefferson General Store, 113 E. Austin. Fudge, coffees and a
variety of fruit preserves, including some sugar-free items, tempt
at the Old Store, 123 Walnut. Pick up sweet souvenirs at
Blackburn's Factory Outlet, 108 E. Lafayette, where a prettified
quart jar of the Jefferson-made syrup will cost you just $2.
</P>
<P>
   Hungry for more history? Check out the 2-year-old Texas Heritage
Archives and Library, corner of Dallas and Market, to view hundreds
of rare maps _ some dating to the 1500s _ and books, old Texas
currency and other Texana. Not far away, the Jefferson Historical
Museum, 223 W. Austin, is home to all sorts of artifacts,
everything from cannonballs to pioneer doctors' instruments to some
of Sam Houston's papers. There are guns, farm tools, old Bibles,
dolls, and a 200-year-old loom.
</P>
<P>
   For an up-close look at antebellum Jefferson, take a short drive
west out Texas 49 and tour Freeman Plantation. The Greek Revival
house, built in 1850 by Williamson and Drucilla Freeman as a cotton
and sugar plantation, originally sat on 1,000 acres of land. Nicely
restored, the home is furnished with impressive antiques of the
period, largely Empire, including petticoat tables and
plantation-style tester beds, and worth a visit, despite the
somewhat reluctant tour guide (and lady of the house).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FOOD FOR THOUGHT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Let's get the bad news out of the way first.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson has no shortage of restaurants, but service can be
less than exemplary on weekdays (you know you're in trouble when
your waitress wears a sweatshirt proclaiming ``Whatever!''). At
least, most folks are friendly.
</P>
<P>
   The better news is that the town includes several good
restaurants, places you'll look forward to for return visits.
</P>
<P>
   Considered Jefferson's best by most, Stillwater Inn is a short
hop from downtown, serving what may be the finest grilled duck
breast in the state, maybe the world. The chocolate mousse on
chocolate meringue dessert isn't bad, either. Surroundings are
comfortably elegant, with the restaurant situated in an 1890s
Victorian house that doubles as a bed-and-breakfast operated by its
chef/owner. Also on the menu: pork tenderloin, Cornish game hen,
New York strip steak, scampi and veal chops.
</P>
<P>
   Also recommended by locals for dinner: the Black Swan, across
the street from the Excelsior Hotel, and Lamache's Italian
Restaurant, located in the Jefferson Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Riverport Bar-B-Que on North Polk is a favorite, too, especially
for lunch. And why not? Stephen Joseph's place serves up the real
thing, plus atmosphere to boot: tall, 19th-century ceilings, a bar
that goes on forever, and the feel of a place that's seen a lot of
good meals dished out. Customers order at the counter, swing by the
iced tea table, then pick up their squeeze bottle of warm barbecue
sauce. It's a sauce with body, a little sweet, a little spicy, with
real depth of flavor. Chopped or sliced beef sandwiches are $3;
potato salad (89 cents) is very good, creamy, with a little black
pepper, green onion and eggs. The restaurant makes its own fries,
onion rings and buttermilk pie, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Hamburger Store on Market Street is another good lunch spot,
with burgers, sandwiches, innertube-sized onion rings and
fresh-baked pies with meringue peaked like cavalry tents.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a club scene? There isn't one. Diamond Bessie's
Saloon and Dance Hall can get frisky, especially on weekends when
live entertainment is featured. But like most small towns,
Jefferson pretty much shuts down a few hours after dark.
</P>
<P>
   There's talk among some Jeffersonians that what the town needs
is more nightlife, something to draw a younger crowd than the
boomers and empty-nesters who partake of Jefferson's low-key
pleasures now.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, that might spoil the mood. Most of Jefferson's
visitors come from places that offer a vibrant nightlife. They're
here, in this pleasant little Piney Woods enclave, for something
else: a slower pace. And after a leisurely day of sightseeing and
shop walking, they just want a good dinner, maybe a good look at
the stars as they stroll back to their inn for the night. They want
a nice, soft bed. A chorus of crickets outside their window might
be nice, too.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that's nightlife.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
