<HEADLINE>
CADDOAN MOUNDS OFFERS INSIGHT TO PAST 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Also see: Travel-Texas, Travel-Marshall, Travel-El-Camino
and Travel-Lakes) 
 
(Photo available on NYT database) 
 
(Eds.: Accent mark needed over second e in Renee) 
 
By RENEE KIENTZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CADDOAN MOUNDS STATE PARK _ Standing there, in the clearing, you
wonder what this place looked like 1,200 years ago when a group of
Caddo Indians decided it was the right spot for a village.
</P>
<P>
   A natural prairie, the site lay a short distance north of the
Neches River. Offering lots of wildlife (food), plenty of water and
good soil, this must have seemed like prime real estate in those
days. It's pretty nice now, too, with a breeze whipping through
ankle-high grass and the sweet fragrance of clover in the air.
</P>
<P>
   The Caddo who lived here are long gone, but the mounds they
built remain, now part of a state park six miles southwest of the
town of Alto on Texas 21.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to Caddoan Mounds State Park begins at the interpretive
center, where a video gives historical perspective and talks about
the present-day Caddo. Though this village, believed to have
operated as a regional trade center for some 500 years, was
abandoned around A.D. 1300, Caddos from other sites were rounded up
in the 1850s and exiled to Oklahoma. This may have been the
westernmost site for the Caddo, who built their mounds across a
wide swath of the southern United States.
</P>
<P>
   Mounds were built for temple sites and burials. The largest at
the state park is a burial mound. Excavated by archaeologists in
the late 1970s, it yielded the remains of some 90 individuals
buried during a 400-year period beginning about A.D. 900. Visitors
now can climb to its top, which affords a wide view of the prairie
site, once a thriving village of farmers and traders. Artifacts at
the center give us an idea of what the inhabitants' lives were
like.
</P>
<P>
   An interpretive trail guide picked up at the center explains the
trail, about seven-tenths of a mile long, that winds visitors past
the burial mound, a low temple mound and a borrow pit, where
workers picked up the dirt used to construct the mounds.
</P>
<P>
   Texas 21 _ or El Camino Real _ bisects the one-time Indian
village, separating the park from the high temple mound. You can
check it out when you leave; just cross the road and park. Before
you go, however, visit the park's reconstruction of an early Caddo
house, a thatch and timber structure resembling a beehive.
</P>
<P>
   The Caddoan Mounds State Historical park is open 9 a.m.-4 p.m.
Thursdays through Mondays. Admission is $2. For more information,
phone 409-858-3218 or access the Texas Parks and Wildlife Web site
at www.tpwd.state.tx.us.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
