<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 11:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7825 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-MARSHALL-ART-H     04-29 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MARSHALL-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARSHALL IS UNDERGOING TOURISM TRANSFORMATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Also see: Travel-Texas, Travel-Caddoan-Mounds,
Travel-El-Camino and Travel-Lakes) 
 
(Photo available on NYT database) 
 
(Eds.: Accent mark needed over second e in Renee) 
 
By RENEE KIENTZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ Some travelers might see Marshall as a blip on
Interstate 20, a chance to gas up before heading on to the
bed-and-breakfasts of Jefferson or the casinos of
Shreveport/Bossier City, La.
</P>
<P>
   But something's afoot. This East Texas city has the feel of a
town on the cusp of becoming a destination in its own right.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Newlan senses it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marshall is a great little town,'' says the restoration
architect, who enjoyed a visit so much he decided to move here _
from Austin. ``Things are happening in Marshall,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Newlan is busy restoring Wisteria Garden, a bed-and-breakfast
owned and operated by Mary Lynn and John Vassar. The 1884 house at
215 E. Rusk is in Marshall's historic district, an area abuzz with
activity.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, restorations are under way at the county courthouse and
the city's lovely old Texas &AMP; Pacific depot, soon to be a railroad
museum. Just across the tracks, the Ginocchio Hotel, at the core of
the city's historic district, now is home to a budding antiques and
collectibles mall. Other shops, bed-and-breakfasts and restaurants
are within walking distance, as is the first-rate Michelson Museum
of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Some visitors are finding Marshall a good base camp for
exploration of this corner of East Texas. Jefferson's attractions
are only 20 minutes away, Louisiana's casinos about 45 minutes.
Caddo Lake is only a short drive.
</P>
<P>
   History is at home in Marshall, settled in 1839. Later a
manufacturing center (saddles, clothing, ammunition) for the
Confederacy, Marshall became the seat of civil authority west of
the Mississippi River after Vicksburg fell. Still later, railroads
brought growth and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   That prosperity is evidenced in some of the grand old homes
located in and around the historic district as well as the splendor
of the Ginocchio Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1896 by Charles A. Ginocchio (jen-ock-ee-o), the hotel
served railroad workers and other travelers. It boasted magnificent
curly pine woodwork and fine architectural details. The lobby looks
today much as it did decades ago, featuring the original check-in
counter and Edison archway, which brought the first electric lights
to this part of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The antiques and collectibles mall opened in the hotel in May
1998. Some 45 dealers have goods scattered about the two-story
hotel, worth a visit for anyone enamored of old buildings,
regardless of any interest in antiques.
</P>
<P>
   Between browsings, you can sit and relax over a cup of coffee or
head next door to Suzie's Soda Shop for a sandwich and soda.
</P>
<P>
   Just up the street are several historical old houses, including
the Allen House, built in 1877, at 610 N. Washington, and Three
Oaks Bed and Breakfast at 609 N. Washington. Three Oaks, a fully
restored 1895 Victorian home, is listed on the National Register of
Historic Places and features spacious, high-ceilinged rooms, many
with clawfoot tubs, sitting areas and antiques. Especially nice:
the Magnolia bedroom with its huge bathroom/sitting area, situated
in a former sunroom. The Victorian room in the back of the house is
really a suite, with a king-size iron bed in its own alcove, plus
wicker double bed, sofa, rolltop desk and clawfoot tub. For more
information or reservations, call owners Tony and Laurie Overhultz
at 800-710-9789. Prices range from $85 to $95 per night.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, Newlan is at work on the Wisteria Garden,
which he anticipates will remain open through the largely exterior
restoration. This bed and breakfast offers four rooms, including
the Sleigh Room, with antique sleigh bed (double), bay window and
antique rockers, and the Eastlake Room, with a queen-size iron bed,
rockers, chaise lounge and clawfoot tub. Rates range from $75 to
$85. For more information, phone 903-938-7611 or access
www.prysm.net/wisteria on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street and down the block is the Michelson Art
Museum, home to an extensive collection of paintings, watercolors,
sketches and drawings by internationally known post-impressionist
Leo Michelson.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, worthy of cities many times Marshall's size
(population 26,000), also schedules traveling exhibitions of other
artists. It is located at 216 Bolivar, and is open noon-5 p.m.
Tuesday-Friday and 1-4 p.m. Saturday-Sunday. For more information,
phone 903-935-9480.
</P>
<P>
   Ready for lunch? What probably is the best restaurant in
Marshall is only a short walk away. Housed in a quaint old home
built in 1875 by Lady Bird Johnson's uncle, the Taylor House, at
212 W. Bowie, seems to be every native's answer to the question,
Where is a good place to eat?
</P>
<P>
   And they're right. Linen tablecloths, fresh flowers, a glass of
spiced iced tea before you, sunlight pouring in through the
windows, you know you're in for a good meal. Maybe sauted catfish
or shrimp salad, flavored with bits of cucumber and dill or spinach
salad with sweet pecan vinaigrette. In the evening, from a menu lit
by candlelight, you might choose crab cakes with a macadamia nut
crust or veal Oscar or a salmon tapenade with garlic, black olives
and capers.
</P>
<P>
   Chef Steve Mylar and his wife, Ginger, opened Taylor House in
1997 and are very hands-on. So is Ginger's mom, who makes the
desserts. Reservations are required for dinner (903-938-8549). The
restaurant seats about 70 people total in its three main dining
rooms. A charming one-table room offers an especially intimate
dining experience. Entrees range from $6.50 to $8 for lunch; $14 to
$19 for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
OTHER ATTRACTIONS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Harrison County Historical Museum, on the square. Exhibits in
this remodeled former county courthouse depict the history of
Marshall and Harrison County, including exhibits on the Civil War
and Caddo Indians. Phone: 903-938-2680.
</P>
<P>
   _ Starr Family State Historic Site, 407 W. Travis. This house
was built in 1870 by James E. Starr, son of Dr. James Harper Starr,
who served the Republic of Texas as surgeon-general and secretary
of the Treasury. Phone: 903-935-3044.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marshall Pottery and Museum, 4901 Elysian Fields Road. Shop
for clay pots, glassware and souvenirs, or watch demonstrations at
this pottery founded more than a century ago. Open year-round; free
group tours. Phone: 903-938-9201.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
