<HEADER>
A7826 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-LAKES-ART-HNS &LR;      04-29 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LAKES-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST TEXAS BEAUTY FOUND OUT BY THE LAKES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Also see: Travel-Texas, Travel-Marshall, Travel-El-Camino
and Travel-Caddoan-Mounds) 
 
(Photo available on NYT database) 
 
(Eds.: Accent mark needed over second e in Renee) 
 
By RENEE KIENTZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many of us appreciate the beauty of East Texas best with a
fishing pole in our hand. Though often fish have nothing to do with
it. It's more about a state of grace, the enormously complex
simplicity of sun flashing off the water's surface, the chance to
just sit.
</P>
<P>
   In the lakes of the Piney Woods, visitors and area residents
find many opportunities to soak up cosmic oneness _ or just catch a
fish. What kind of experience are you looking for? Here are three
choices available:
</P>
<P>
   _ Vast expanse of water, wide open sky, powerboats.
</P>
<P>
   _ Small, serene lake, shoreline pines reflected in its surface,
canoes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Large, mysterious cypress-lined lake, kayak or bass boat or
steamboat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TOLEDO BEND &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vast expanse of water, wide open sky, powerboats. This huge,
manmade body of water (the South's largest) has 1,200 miles of
shoreline, an average depth of 24 feet and unlimited opportunities
to catch your dinner. Forming the boundary between Texas and
Louisiana, Toledo Bend seems to go on forever, stretching from
Logansport, north of Center, to well south of Hemphill. And along
the way there are put-in points, campsites, picnic areas, fishing
camps and inns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this place,'' says Wayne Johnson, who's brought his
bass boat over to Hemphill from his home in Austin. He and a friend
will spend three days and some evenings out on the water, cramming
in as much fishing as they can.
</P>
<P>
   They've got the lures lined up, lunch in the cooler, Chee-tos
for later. Their prey: striped bass (although any fish will do).
Texas Parks and Wildlife says the best fishing for striped bass is
February through June. Not only that, but specimen up to 25 pounds
have been caught in the lake and 15 pounders are common.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RED HILLS LAKE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Small, serene lake, shoreline pines reflected in its surface,
canoes. If Red Hills Lake were an apartment, it'd be called
intimate, as in petite. It's also quiet, with boating restricted to
motorless craft that glide rather than ptt-ptt-ptt. Surrounded by
rolling hills covered in pines, this place looks more like Arkansas
than Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors enter on the honor system, slipping the $2 fee into the
provided envelope and dropping it into a box. According to the map,
there are just a couple of ways to go. Both take you past campsites
and screened shelters and pretty views of the water.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the lake is sectioned off for swimming, making this a
family-oriented haven.
</P>
<P>
   Located about three miles north of Milam on Texas 87, Red Hills
Lake is part of the Sabine National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CADDO LAKE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Large, mysterious cypress-lined lake, kayak or bass boat or
steamboat. This is Texas' spookiest lake. Good spooky. Writers
always get around to using the word ``primeval'' to describe Caddo,
because it just is.
</P>
<P>
   Straddling the line between northeast Texas and Louisiana, Caddo
encompasses more than 25,000 fresh-water acres, a meandering maze
of bayous and inlets. It's easy to get lost. First-timers might
want to take a guide along or take a tour.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. David Applebaum, who grew up on this natural lake, says
his Mystique Tours visit all three parts of Caddo _ the swamps,
bayou and big lake areas. Narrated tours go out several times a day
on a regular basis from mid-May through mid-September, though the
boats go out year-round weather permitting, leaving from the dock
behind Bayou Landing Restaurant on Cypress Drive.
</P>
<P>
   For a different kind of excursion, consider the Graceful Ghost,
an authentic re-creation of an 1890s steamboat. Lexie Palmore and
her husband Jim McMillen take turns piloting the steam-driven craft
on 90-minute tours of Caddo. The Ghost goes out several times a day
in the spring and summer months, less frequently in the fall, and
not at all during the winter.
</P>
<P>
   A call ahead is a good idea. You'll need reservations and
directions for both tours, based in the little town of Uncertain.
For information on Mystique Tours, call 903-679-3690. For
information on the Graceful Ghost steamboat, call 888-325-5459.
</P>
<P>
   You can check out the lake from shore at Caddo Lake State Park
in nearby Karnack, or rent canoes there if the urge to paddle is
overwhelming. A pontoon boat tour runs Thursday-Tuesday from March
to November.
</P>
<P>
   The visitor center's exhibits and artifacts give perspective on
the area and the Indians the lake is named for. There are cabins
($40-60 a night), screened shelters ($16) and campsites ($8-15
night) at the park, plus nature trails and short hiking trails. For
more park information, call 800-792-1112; for reservations, call
512-389-8900.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of visitors come to the shores of Caddo to eat catfish,
not catch and clean 'em. Two favorites: Bayou Landing on Cypress
Drive in Uncertain and Dawn's Caddo Crossing in Karnack.
</P>
<P>
   Several bed-and-breakfasts and camps also are located along the
shores of the Caddo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 1148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7829 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-EL-CAMINO-ART-     04-29 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EL-CAMINO-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOURNEY BACK TO A SIMPLER TIME ALONG EL CAMINO REAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Also see: Travel-Texas, Travel-Marshall, Travel-Lakes and
Travel-Caddoan-Mounds) 
 
(Photo available on NYT database) 
 
(Eds.: Accent mark needed over second e in Renee) 
 
By RENEE KIENTZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ To some folks traveling the Piney Woods,
Texas 21 is just a pretty east-west stretch of road. It'll get you
where you're going, all right. Or it can take you back in time.
</P>
<P>
   If you start at the Rio Grande and follow Texas 21 across the
state, you'll pass through a string of towns with historic
significance: San Antonio, San Marcos, Crockett, Nacogdoches, San
Augustine and Milam. You'll also be following the approximate route
taken in 1691 by the Tran-Mazanet expedition, which crossed the Rio
Grande and trekked across Tejas to the Sabine River and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Spaniards got most of the credit for carving out El
Camino Real _ the Royal Road _ the route was already an existing
network of Indian trails and natural stream crossings, some dating
well before the 17th century.
</P>
<P>
   Nacogdoches is the largest of the East Texas towns on El Camino
Real, which runs through its very heart as Main Street. Named for
the Caddo family that lived in the area centuries before the first
Europeans arrived, Nacogdoches makes a good base camp from which to
explore other sites on the Royal Road, including the Caddoan Mounds
State Historic Park to the west and San Augustine and Milam to the
east.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
STAY AWHILE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But first, there is a lot to see in Nacogdoches, which has a
rich history coupled with the energy of a college town.
</P>
<P>
   More than one-third of the 33,500 inhabitants attend Stephen F.
Austin State University, and the collegiate influence on this old
town is huge. But the future coexists nicely with the past on and
off the pretty campus, located on another historic road. North
Street, once known as Calle del Norte, is believed to have begun as
an Indian trading trail and may be the oldest existing thoroughfare
in North America.
</P>
<P>
   The two ancient roads, El Camino Real and Calle del Norte,
converge in downtown Nacogdoches to form a pleasant quadrant of
shops, restaurants and historical buildings. One block east of
North Street, which also is Business U.S. 59, sits the town square,
or Plaza Principal. It was here that Nacogdoches, as an official
entity, was born, having received the designation from the Spanish
government in 1779.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Antonio Gil Y'Barbo, political chief of the area,
established his headquarters in a stone house erected on the north
side of the square, adjacent to El Camino Real. Though the home was
torn down in 1902, its stones were used to create a replica in
1936. The replica, built on the SFA campus, now is known as the
Stone Fort Museum and houses a number of important artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   The Nacogdoches Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau conducts walking
tours of the downtown area, but historical markers fill you in if
you cruise the red-bricked streets on your own.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown offers more than history, with a number of antiques,
gift and specialty shops as well as restaurants to explore.
</P>
<P>
   Among shops worth a visit are the Old Pineapple Post, 102 North
St., an antiques mall; Old Pilar Street Antiques, at 108 E. Pilar,
a large shop offering 18th- and 19th-century American furniture and
glassware; and the Colony Mall, 209 E. Main, various boutiques in
the three-story shell of an old building.
</P>
<P>
   The Oldtime String Shop and General Mercantile, at 206 E. Pilar,
is an odd and fascinating space, a general store for pickers, who
gather 'round on Saturday afternoons to jam, and for the kids, who
wander in and out to admire the tin toys and the old dog snoozing
in the middle of the floor. The shop sells an assortment of items
besides banjo strings and toys, including Marshall pottery and
Jefferson syrups.
</P>
<P>
   Though you'll find lots of old-timers in downtown Nacogdoches,
there is new blood, too. Young shopkeeper Kevyn Barnes opened her
used book store, Serendipity, in 1996 and offers incense and old
LPs along with a good selection of mysteries, biographies,
science-fiction and Texana. She's at &UR;  &LR; 203 E. Main.
</P>
<P>
   In the next block, at 119 E. Main, Laura McKinney has opened
McKinnon's Linens, an upscale linens store carrying lines such as
Peacock Alley, Peter Reed and Banana Fish. The shopkeeper, who's
still in college, is a Nacogdoches native and a fine judge of
restaurants. Asked to recommend a place or two to eat, she names
two local spots that turn out to be winners, a ``down-home'' place
named Aubrey's and Taqueria Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   It's Sunday noon at Aubrey's Cafe, 1523 E. Main, just a short
drive east of downtown. A diverse cross-section of Nacogdoches is
crowding in for lunch. SFA students in jeans and ponytails, ladies
fresh from church in big hats and young families all have come for
soulful standards that include chicken and dumplings, collard
greens and black-eyed peas. On this day, a child, maybe 8, maybe 9,
struggles with his order _ the Mile High Meat Loaf Sandwich.
Desserts such as banana nut cake and sweet potato pie are hard to
pass up. Aubrey's prices are reasonable and the food, fine.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true of Taqueria Garcia, an unpretentious family-run
spot at 2710 South St. The guacamole? Bueno. The busy kitchen also
turns out tasty gorditas, little cornmeal pockets stuffed with
fillings such as chorizo (Mexican sausage) and cheese or shredded
poblano peppers and cheese for $1.65 each. On weekends, offerings
include chicken mole ($5) and tamales ($6 a dozen). The Garcia
family is revamping the menu, adding more Mexican specialties and
promising good things.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Now that you've eaten, maybe you're ready for more sights. One
Nacogdoches landmark has a Houston connection. At Millard's
Crossing, visitors tour a number of 19th-century Texas homes
gathered at this reconstructed village under the direction of Lera
Thomas, nee Millard. A Nacogdoches native, she was the wife of the
congressman who served as representative from Harris County for 29
years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ON THE ROAD AGAIN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Short treks from Nacogdoches let you explore El Camino Real in
both directions. Head west and check out the Caddoan Mounds State
Historic Park. A pretty 40-minute ride from Nacogdoches, the park
and its visitors center interpret what is believed to be the site
of the country's westernmost Caddo village.
</P>
<P>
   Following Texas 21 to the east from Nacogdoches will bring you
to San Augustine, where the Mission Senora de los Dolores de los
Ais was founded in 1717. The mission is gone, but the Mission
Dolores Visitor Center and historical markers identify the site
four blocks south of the courthouse on Texas 147. A short distance
away, the Ezekiel W. Cullen home, built in 1839, is open for tours
by appointment. A ballroom occupies the entire upper floor of the
Greek Revival-style home at Congress and Market streets. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Continuing east, there is Milam with its settlers' park and old
cabin, and, a little farther still, Toledo Bend. Standing at the
edge of this big body of water, you won't be seeing what the Caddo
saw, nor the Spaniards, for this impoundment of the Sabine River is
a relatively new development as East Texas goes.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't history that draws visitors to Toledo Bend, but the
Piney Woods' other great attraction: natural beauty. Known
nationally for its bass fishing, the reservoir's shoreline is in
part the Sabine National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Densely wooded and lovely, you won't find a prettier spot to
contemplate the end of the road.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
