<SLUG> BC-LILYTOMLIN28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Three questions for . . . Lily Tomlin
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to know who is more famous, comedian/actress Lily
Tomlin or the quirky cast of characters born from her fertile
imagination. There's Trudy the bag lady; Crystal, the hang-gliding
quadriplegic; '60s flower child Glenna; nasal-voiced telephone
operator Ernestine; and, of course, the precocious 5 1/2-year-old
Edith Ann.
</P>
<P>
   Tomlin has used her multiple personalities to score success on
television (``Laugh-In''), in film (``Nashville,'' ``Nine to
Five'') and as a Tony Award-winning stage actress (the one-woman
show ``The Search for Signs of Intelligent Life in the Universe'').
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, she brings them all to the Fox Theatre as part of the
Unique Lives &AMP; Experiences Lecture Series, a warm and often
intimate evening in which women of achievement share their
memories, perspectives and insights about life. Expect Tomlin's
tale to come from her and her characters. Here's what she had to
say when we caught up with her at her Los Angeles office:
</P>
<P>
   Q:Next year is the 25th anniversary of your first film, Robert
Altman's ``Nashville,'' and he is thinking about rereleasing it.
What are your memories of that movie?
</P>
<P>
   A:Being in that film was a pretty unique experience. It was a
great summer. Everybody in town was in the movie. My family is
Southern, from Paducah, Ky., and I know how sensitive Southerners
are, so I said to Bob, ``I hope we get out of here before people
see this movie.'' And, yes, they were terribly offended.
</P>
<P>
   Q:What's the difference between the Lily who spent the summer of
'74 in Nashville and the one who spent the summer of '98 in Italy
shooting a movie with Franco Zefferelli?
</P>
<P>
   A:They were two summers to remember. In Italy, I probably was
just a whole lot older, so I was a more experienced actor. But I
don't think I was that radically different emotionally or
temperamentally. I remember a scene in ``Nashville'' where we were
all sitting in a cafe listening to Keith (Carradine) sing, and when
I saw the dailies, I felt like I failed this whole scene. I went
back to my condo and cried. But you know what? I did that all
summer in Italy, too. You still do it; you give it up a lot
quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: If you had it to do over again, would you choose to be
famous?
</P>
<P>
   A:I like being famous in the sense that you have a rather warm
place in the world, and people are very generous to you and mostly
affectionate. As my mother says, ``I always get an appointment at
the beauty parlor.'' Her name is Lily Tomlin, too. There's a
certain aspect to it that you love it when you're very young. You
love your whole art.
</P>
<P>
   I still get very excited working on something new or having a
great new idea. But I'm naturally more reflective at this point in
my life. Time suddenly becomes a true, finite reality. These are
the most common of epiphanies. You want to still have that
breathless passion. A lot of people tire out. I can't say that's
happened to me.
</P>
<P>
   Lily Tomlin
</P>
<P>
   7:30 tonight. Speaking as part of the Unique Lives &AMP; Experiences
lecture series. $22.50-$37.50. Fox Theatre, 660 Peachtree St. N.E.
404-817-8700.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
