<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-GLAMOUR02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Series looks behind scenes at glamour of Hollywood
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 2.
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're passionate for all things fashionable but missed last
week's premiere of the new ``Hollywood Fashion Machine'' series on
American Movie Classics (AMC), don't feel bad. The initial
30-minute telecast, which profiled legendary costume designer Edith
Head, was far less riveting than the episode that airs Monday (7:30
p.m.).
</P>
<P>
   Monday's episode, ``The Star Makers,'' turns the spotlight on
the ways in which movie idols' appearances were altered to win them
fame and adoration. Among other things, it reveals how Marilyn
Monroe and Judy Garland had dead-end film careers until they
changed their hair color, how Liz Taylor's violet eyes were framed
by eyebrows painted on one hair at a time, and how Rita Hayworth's
Latin features were cloaked by dyeing her hair red and having
electrolysis done on her natural hairline. Hayworth, incidentally,
had mismatched eyes; the larger one was camouflaged with oversized
false lashes.
</P>
<P>
   As ``The Star Makers'' points out, Hollywood glamour was, is and
will continue to be achieved by zealous manipulation of hair,
makeup and apparel. Fittingly, the show's host, actress Daryl
Hannah, looks nearly unrecognizable with her blond locks pressed
straight and her customary bohemian look tempered by a demure Dolce
&AMP; Gabbana gown.
</P>
<P>
   Actress Lauren Bacall is hosting a companion series called ``The
Hollywood Fashion Collection,'' which features movies such as ``How
to Marry a Millionaire'' and ``Pillow Talk,'' noted for their
costume design. That series airs Mondays at 8 p.m. on AMC.
</P>
<P>
   Upcoming episodes of the ``Fashion Machine'' series will focus
on Parisian designers' influence on Hollywood and on George
Hurrell's groundbreaking work in glamour photography. If they're
anything near the quality of the ``Star Makers'' episode, this
series will truly be running at full throttle.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
