<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEEMAY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sowing seeds of loving competition
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Everyone loses, everyone wins, so gardening is not a
competitive sport, I've always said _ despite the strange contests
that solicit growers of the biggest tomatoes, the biggest
watermelons, cucumbers and on and on. I said it even as I heard
people brag about having the prettiest azalea in the neighborhood
or the sweetest peaches in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes further challenge to my assertion: Competition is
running hot in LA (Lower Atlanta). A family battle _ between mother
and daughter, no less.
</P>
<P>
   Terri Smith of Coweta County (Ga.) and her mother, Karla
Seymour, who lives about 40 miles south, in Greenville, have taken
the gloves off, or put them on, in a digging and planting and
watering and pruning contest that will be decided next summer. The
other day, I joined the two women at Terri's garden to check on the
rivalry at midpoint.
</P>
<P>
   This war of spades began innocently enough. Last year, when they
visited relatives in Michigan, mother and daughter, neither of whom
gardened, made a crucial discovery, Terri recalls:
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got to Midland, my cousin, Cindy Ullery, had these
fabulous gardens, really beautiful. We realized that real, regular
people could have beautiful yards. She dug up all these little
bitty baby plants she had in her yard, saying, `You like this and
you like this?' and showing us what they'd look like. She'd say,
`Do you want it?' and we said yes.''
</P>
<P>
   And the plants got loaded: ``The front seat was full of
plants,'' says Terri. ``The back seat was full. Four of us in the
car and a hundred little plants.''
</P>
<P>
   They drove the thousand miles back to Georgia, back from the
land of rich, black loam, back to the land where hard red clay
loves to intimidate newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Karla notes, ``We came back with great enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, they had that certain superior confidence with which
Southerners are endowed, a confidence stemming from mild climates
and abundant moisture. Terri, scanning the ``Yankee plants'' in
Michigan, had a vision: ``We figured if they could grow up there,
they could really grow down here where we have some sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Stopping at Terri's home, they divided the plants, including
calla lily, iris, hosta. When they discovered the joy of success,
Karla recalls, they took their new-found passion to another level:
``We decided to have a contest.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will judge is still under debate. Meanwhile, a year before
the competition ends, clearly both these new gardeners have reaped
benefits _ in the same way that parents and children always find
common ground in the garden, unearthing lessons for life.
</P>
<P>
   Always close, the two have grown even closer, noting that their
relationship has taken on the added dimension that shared
experiences bring.
</P>
<P>
   Says Karla: ``We call a little bit more often to check on the
flowers and ask how is this one growing or what that one was.''
</P>
<P>
   Terri says, ``It's fun for us to learn new things together,''
acknowledging that, until recently, her familiarity with plants
didn't go much beyond azalea, hydrangea and dogwood.
</P>
<P>
   A walk through her garden shows how far she has come. How far
both have come (they share everything). Like veteran gardeners,
mother and daughter trade stories, traditions and jibes (``You've
got to rub the rosemary,'' says Terri. ``You don't have to bend
down to rub mine,'' retorts her mother), as we admire the pansies,
foxglove, aster, geranium, rose campion, ice plant, thistle, toad
lily, astilbe, yarrow, aucuba, mahonia, lenten rose, fern, Japanese
maple.
</P>
<P>
   Learning breeds thirst for more knowledge. So, constantly in
search of new information, Karla and Terri dig through gardening
books and magazines and horticulturists' minds. ``Now,'' says,
Karla, ``We know what the questions are.''
</P>
<P>
   Terri says her Michigan cousin consults via e-mail: ``I'll say,
`This pulmonaria you gave me has just started to bloom,' and she'll
say, `Now, as soon as it finishes, you've got to pinch off these
flowers.' She'll tell me exactly what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   I had come to Coweta County to chat about a good-natured contest
between mother and daughter. But I also found two people who have
discovered a refreshing new passion, always a treat to witness.
They have a fire in the belly, a light in the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the light and fire are being passed along to
Terri's 5-year-old son, Jake, who's taken a special liking to
marigolds and pansies. When Terri, talking about the
mother-daughter contest, asked Jake who had the prettier garden, he
answered: ``I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Another generation joins the beautiful battle.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
