<SLUG> BC-LOUNGEWEAR02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Latest in loungewear goes from dawn to dinner without skipping a
beat
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 2.
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This Mother's Day, consider giving the woman who does everything
a gift as versatile as her busy lifestyle: a comfortable lounge
outfit that she can wear at home, in the school car pool or to a
laid-back dinner without the kids.
</P>
<P>
   Loungewear has evolved from Victoria's Secret-style satin and
lace to uncomplicated pieces that make an easy transition from day
to night, public to private. Whether she's a stay-at-home mother, a
busy career woman or a retiree with limited activities, these
clothes won't collect dust in her closet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Loungewear seems to have gotten more popular,'' said Kaye
Davis, fashion director for AmericasMart. ``Comfort is what we're
all looking for these days. It can be an oversized T-shirt or
something silk that you can greet a guest in. It's gone into a more
trendy look and not necessarily a behind-the-bedroom-door look.''
</P>
<P>
   The hot new drawstring pant is one of those crossover styles
that offers form and function for women of all sizes. So do pants
with elastic waistbands. Top them with a large shirt or a fitted
tank for an outfit mom can relax in.
</P>
<P>
   Sleeveless unconstructed dresses, or short shifts, offer added
variety and elegance on hot summer days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women want to look pretty and feminine at home, whether their
own family sees them or nobody sees them,'' said Amy Doelling,
public relations manager at Neiman Marcus in Lenox Square. ``We
even sell to women who live in assisted-living homes who want to
look pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   Loungewear comes in a wide selection of fabrics, from knits and
silk to linen and cotton.
</P>
<P>
   To make color selection easy, consider the colors Mom wears most
often.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two most popular colors now in loungewear are the greens
and blues,'' Doelling said. ``I don't know why. That's just what's
selling.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
