A7840 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMERSTYLE-MEN02-COX     04-29 0348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMERSTYLE-MEN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Best of show: Menswear sleek, chic
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 2.
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The recent ``Rubbing Noses'' runway show staged by Neiman Marcus
was aptly named. The spring/summer styles it showcased offered men
in the audience _ especially those who've been behaving badly in
the sartorial department _ a not-so-subtle reminder of their need
for a wardrobe update.
</P>
<P>
   The season's most sharply dressed men are the ones wearing
clothes that are sleek, chic, sexy and colorful. Comfort is always
a consideration when the temperature rises and the days get longer,
but slouchy and carelessly casual aren't the ways to go. Instead,
be aware of the modernistic, body-conscious and dressier turns that
menswear is taking.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Rubbing Noses'' show featured clothes from some of the
priciest lines Neiman's carries: Gucci, Prada, Dolce &AMP; Gabbana, and
Missoni. But paying top dollar _ $600 for a shirt, say, or $350 for
a pair of linen pants _ isn't as essential to appearing stylish as
self-confidence, attention to detail and knowing what to look for.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pants: The most stylish slacks now have a trim fit to them.
They're tailored without cuffs or pleats and can even be worn
beltless. Neutrals and pastels look right for the season.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Shorts: Just as Capri pants revolutionized the way women
dressed last year, the trend in men's shorts has them hemmed at the
knee and somewhat snug through the thighs and seat. Cargo pockets
are equally trendy. Just make sure those shorts are pressed if you
want to impress.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Footwear: Sneakers and sandals are fine, so long as they're
kept tidy. Sandals, by the way, get sexier and strappier all the
time.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tops: Healthy skin is a trendier accessory than jewelry these
days, and this season's muscle-hugging tops (in eye-popping colors
and patterns) afford ample opportunity for skin displays.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
