<HEADER>
A7841 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-ECUADOR02-COX     04-29 1437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ECUADOR02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vibrant Indian culture, Spanish opulence meld in a colorful
capital perched in the Andes
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 2.
 &HT;    By William Schemmel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador _ Like most Latin American capitals, there are
two Quitos.
</P>
<P>
   There's the modern might-as-well-be-Nashville city of
1.5-million, with five-star hotels, international restaurants,
tourist shops, museums, foreign embassies, airline offices and
dusk-to-dawn nightlife.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there's the compelling reason for visiting: the Spanish
colonial Old City, a congested web of narrow cobblestone streets
and confection-colored buildings that open onto enormous plazas and
spectacular churches.
</P>
<P>
   After the Spanish conquered the Inca empire in the 16th century,
they shrewdly set about to win over the native Indians by replacing
their temples with Catholic churches, monasteries, convents and
palaces that in sheer blinding opulence eclipsed the Old Country's
cathedrals and holy shrines.
</P>
<P>
   There are so many, it's impossible to walk more than a block or
two without being drawn into one more freighted with gold leaf,
stained glass, statues and religious paintings than the last.
International volunteers are restoring several damaged by a 1987
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   The Monastery of San Francisco, on a raised terrace above the
huge plaza of the same name, is the epitome of bombastic baroque
extravagance. Franciscan priests began it in 1534, mere months
after Quito was founded on the ruins of the Inca empire's northern
capital. When it was finished 70 years later, its altars and
columns fairly dripped gold-leaf ornamentation, religious art and
intricately carved Moorish arches and roofs. (The Spanish, who'd
recently evicted the Moors from their homeland, kept their
architecture as a souvenir.) A bell ringer in a cubbyhole near the
main door sounds huge bells that beckon the faithful to Mass.
</P>
<P>
   To outshine the Franciscans, rival Jesuits began their La
Compania Church in 1605. When it was finally dedicated 163 years
later, it was the most opulent in Spanish America. Some visitors
claim they get dizzy looking at walls, ceilings and altars
shimmering with 7 tons of gold.
</P>
<P>
   But it may be just the effects of altitude. Fifteen miles from
the equator, in a valley 9,350 feet in the Andes, Quito is the
world's second-highest capital, after La Paz, Bolivia.
</P>
<P>
   San Agustin Monastery is Ecuador's Independence Hall.
Revolutionary heroes who signed the nation's declaration of
independence from Spain on Aug. 10, 1809, are buried in the
17th-century crypt. Part of the old church is now a school. As a
young nun shepherds her charges through a colonnaded passageway,
under the moldering ruins of ancient frescoes, an imp about 8
stretches his mouth and sticks out his tongue at us. With the
back-of-the-head eyes that come with the veil, the nun sees the
malefaction and zings him on the knuckles.
</P>
<P>
   Plaza de la Independencia, a scrupulously clean open space with
heroic statues, flowers and benches from which to observe the
passing human parade, is the Old City's hub. In colonial fashion,
the two traditional symbols of power, the presidential palace and
the cathedral, preside over the plaza.
</P>
<P>
   You can walk down the palace's colonnaded portico and photograph
the honor guards in their blue and white colonial uniforms. They
won't even blink at your flash.
</P>
<P>
   After traipsing through drafty old churches all morning, you'll
be happy to take a table in La Cueva del Oso (the Bear's Cave), a
cool, sophisticated art deco-style restaurant facing the plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers and well-dressed businesspeople come for Ecuadorean
and continental lunch and dinner. Fresh fish and shrimp are
prepared many creative ways.
</P>
<P>
   If you're watching your sucres (Ecuador's currency), and aren't
afraid of Montezuma's revenge, street vendors sell soup, meat pies,
fruit, fruit juice, soft drinks and bottled water. Many of the
usual U.S. fast food suspects hold forth in the new city's hotel
district.
</P>
<P>
   Highly skilled pickpockets are the Old City's unfortunate
downside. They frequently work in pairs and groups. We were
repeatedly warned not to wear jewelry and to keep money secured in
a neck or belt pouch _ not in a visible hip pack. Even if you
normally prefer to travel alone, a group tour or private guide is a
big advantage. Our Metropolitan Touring guides kept constant vigil,
and none of us had any problems.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy colorful tapestries, embroidered cotton shirts and
blouses, folk art paintings, beautiful woolen sweaters (including
alpaca), leather goods, ponchos, rope sandals, traditional dark
felt hats and Panama hats at endless street stalls in the Old City
and the new. However, it's much more fun to shop for these
handicrafts at Indian markets two or more hours from the city.
</P>
<P>
   Driving the Panamerican Highway south of Quito toward Latacunga
and other market towns, the highway's nickname, ``Avenue of
Volcanoes,'' is self-explanatory. Eight snow-capped volcanoes,
several still active, appear. Chimborazo, a dormant 20,702-foot
snow cone overlooking the city of Riobamba, is Ecuador's highest
peak and a popular climbing destination. Cotapaxi (19,347-feet) is
the world's tallest active volcano.
</P>
<P>
   Latacunga's Tuesday and Saturday market is a warm-up for the
most famous, the Saturday market at Otavalo, 2 1/2 hours north of
Quito. Handicraft hunters can have a field day in the town of
22,000 where hundreds of stalls cover the main plaza and spill into
side streets. Most items are temptingly inexpensive _ you'll rarely
pay more than $5 to $10 for anything. Even at that, some
good-natured bargaining is expected.
</P>
<P>
   I bought three embroidered cotton shirts, a woolen wall hanging
with a scene of Mount Chimborazo, three folk paintings, a felt
fedora and a wooden wolf's-head mask, all for about $50.
</P>
<P>
   When I ate lunch at the Plaza Cafe, my ears did a double take.
Waitress Cray Sheedy, a recent Western Carolina University
graduate, said she ``wanted to see a different part of the world,
and Ecuador definitely is different.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 stores in Cotacachi, 10 miles north of Otavalo,
sell beautifully made, full-length leather coats, jackets,
briefcases, belts and luggage at sharp discounts.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of your shopping day, you needn't drive back to
Quito. Hacienda Pinsaqui, a restored 1790s hacienda three miles
from Otavalo, has 16 suites furnished with antiques and modern
baths, a restaurant, gardens, horseback riding and mountain biking.
(Rates are $75-$100 a night.) In a twist on ``George Washington
Slept Here,'' northern South America's early-19th-century
liberator, Simon Bolivar, was a frequent guest.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: The least expensive way to get to Quito or
Guayaquil is to fly Saeta or Ecuadorian from Atlanta for $607 and
$614, respectively. In the same price range, you can fly Lacsa
round trip from Miami for $350; add round-trip airfare of $158 to
Miami on Delta, AirTran, American or United for a total of $608.
The catch: On Lacsa, it's a 7 1/2-hour flight from Miami through
San Jose, Costa Rica. If you prefer a U.S.-based airline, American
flies direct from Miami in four hours, but the fare is $527 through
June 14, $577 June 15-July 31. If you book on American from Atlanta
through Miami, the fare is $789 before June 14, $839 June 15-July
31, and the flight time is around 7 1/2 hours. Restrictions apply
on all these flights. Your best bet may be to ask your travel agent
to check consolidator fares from Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Once in Quito or Guayaquil, strike off on your own or join a
tour arranged by Metropolitan Touring, Ecuador's major tour
operator. You can join a group tour or customize a private tour. In
the United States, Metropolitan is represented by Adventure
Associates, 13150 Coit Road, Suite 110, Dallas, TX 75240,
1-800-527-2500.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Precautions: Visitors unaccustomed to high altitudes sometimes
experience dizziness and nausea in 9,350-foot Quito and the higher
Andes surrounding the city. Diamox, a prescription drug taken
before arrival, can ward it off. Some of our group experienced
minor difficulties the first two days but quickly adjusted and had
no more problems. We drank only bottled mineral water and took
other food precautions. The high altitude keeps the temperature
cool and springlike. Bring a sweater or light coat for nighttime
and the high places. Only a passport is required to visit Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Ecuadorean consulate's office: 323-658-6020.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
