<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7842 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-ECUADORBYTRAIN     04-29 1502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ECUADORBYTRAIN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Riding rails to adventure in the Andes
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 2.
 &HT;    By William Schemmel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIOBAMBA, Ecuador _ With no bells, whistles or audible
announcement, train men jump aboard, and the Trans-Andean Railroad
(Ferrocarril Transandino) pulls slowly out of the station, a few
minutes behind schedule. We pass the backs of churches, shops,
whitewashed houses with red tile roofs, then rural shanties where
children and adults stand and watch and dogs run crazily along the
tracks, pleased that, like yesterday and the day before, they've
chased the clattering iron monster out of town. Forewarned, we've
brought bottled water, fruit, crackers, cheese and bread and
cushions whose worth accelerates with every jostling mile.
</P>
<P>
   The slow, lolloping speed _ the train rarely travels more than
35 to 40 mph _ and sardined humanity prevents anyone from tumbling
off the nearly flat roof, whose only safety feature is an
ankle-high guardrail.
</P>
<P>
   The roof-riders are a mixed bag of ages and nationalities _ kids
traveling with their parents, groups of twentysomething backpackers
and senior citizens, Europeans, Americans, Canadians, Latins,
Aussies and a party of Japanese. Wrapped in layers of sweaters,
jackets and ponchos, we huddle together against the chilly mountain
air.
</P>
<P>
   Some will depart after the white-knuckle ride down the Devil's
Nose. Others will go all the way to Guayaquil _ a 10-hour journey _
and ride back the next day. A group of us plan to overnight in
Guayaquil, then fly out to the Galapagos Islands and walk awhile
among wild nature.
</P>
<P>
   Like our transcontinental railroad, the Transandino was a
monumental project that gripped Ecuador's imagination. Construction
of what Ecuadoreans proudly call ``the world's most difficult
railroad'' began at Guayaquil on the Pacific coast in 1899.
Sacrificing countless lives, many of them Jamaicans imported for
the cruel work, it cut through rain forests, rivers, desert and
perpendicular rock walls more than 10,000 feet above sea level. It
reached Quito, the nation's capital, 280 miles from the coast, in
1908. Since then, floods, landslides and earthquakes have taken
their toll on bridges and tracks. Some sections were washed away in
the 1982-83 El Nino floods, but because of the revenue it generates
from foreign tourists, the line between Riobamba and Guayaquil has
been kept open.
</P>
<P>
   Free of Riobamba, the diesel-powered train puts its show
onstage. Behind us, Mount Chimborazo _ Ecuador's highest peak,
20,702 feet of snowcapped volcanic splendor _ is the dramatic
scrim. On both sides of the tracks, steep mountainsides 8,000 to
10,000 feet high are terraced with cornfields, potatoes and furrows
of beans and squash.
</P>
<P>
   High up, Indians in brightly colored shawls look like patches of
strawberries and raspberries against the verdant foliage. At rural
crossings, others wait patiently with flocks of sheep and goats. We
wave, but they don't wave back. Dogs rush out and chase us around
wheat fields and past rivers and streams shaded by aromatic
eucalyptus trees and wild purple lupine. Waterfalls race down from
creases in the mountains. A Japanese photographer utters mortified
apologies when the lurching train tosses him onto a pile of
strangers.
</P>
<P>
   The train stops frequently in the center of small towns and
villages with streets so narrow we can reach out and shake hands
with people hanging out their windows. We spill off to stock up on
fruit and bottled water and line up for cafe banos.
</P>
<P>
   The German woman I met in Riobamba comes back to the roof with
cuy, a whole roasted guinea pig wrapped in a greasy newspaper.
``Delicious,'' she smacks her lips, grins and tears off chunks of
the meat _ a sort of Ecuadorean barbecue, handed down from the
Incas _ and offers it around. The taste is reputedly somewhere
between chicken and rabbit, but the critter's rat snout, little
rodent teeth, upturned paws and tightly shut eyes turn off all but
the most daring.
</P>
<P>
   When we pull onto a rural siding to wait for the Riobamba-bound
train to pass, we jump down to stretch our legs. A tipsy man whose
breath would buckle bamboo totters out of his lopsided wooden hut.
With flapping arms and slurred Indian-Spanish dialect, he tries to
explain the mysteries of the yellow and blue butterflies that swarm
around us. ``Para la nina'' _ ``for the child,'' he says. We drop
Ecuadorean sucres into his outstretched palm and hope without much
conviction that the waif watching expressionless from the window of
the hut will get some small share of our charity.
</P>
<P>
   At another stop in a rural village, some say goodbye to the
train and board the autoferra, a sort of Greyhound bus with iron
wheels that rides the tracks like the train. It lacks the
Transandino's camaraderie and on-the-edge excitement, but padded
seats, a bathroom and a rooftop railing high enough to keep you
from pitching overboard in the precipitous mountain passes make it
a good alternative for those who want a few comforts with their
ride.
</P>
<P>
   Jungly foliage segues into mountainous desert peppered with
pampas grass, mesquite bushes and cactus. At the town of Palmira,
the line climbs to 10,623 feet, its highest point. Then comes the
ride's hair-raising showpiece. The steep drop from 7,655 feet at
the village of Alausi to 5,996 feet at Sibambe takes the train down
El Nariz del Diablo (the Devil's Nose), an almost perpendicular
rock wall hanging precariously above a river gorge. The descent is
an engineering feat, accomplished by a painstaking seven-mile
series of zigzagging switchbacks down a ledge cut into the
mountainside. On the way to the small Sibambe station at the
bottom, it crosses rickety bridges over yawning ravines and rushing
streams. When I overcome acrophobia long enough for a quick look
over the edge of the roof, there's nothing between me and eternity
except a few thousand feet of clear mountain air.
</P>
<P>
   Macho guys stand up and scream and flap their arms, daring the
train to toss them into the Andean blue yonder. Anxious friends
yank them down as the train rushes through dark tunnels, where
clearance is barely more than a foot or two and the ceiling a
scythe of jagged rocks.
</P>
<P>
   The roof riders laugh and scream like roller coaster riders at
Six Flags. I scrunch down, white-knuckle the railing and grin like
a man possessed. Under the rusty tin roof of the Sibambe station,
the welcoming committee is a mute little boy sucking his thumb and
a scrawny pack of dogs looking for a handout.
</P>
<P>
   After Alausi, we shuck our early-morning layers down to shorts
and T-shirts and ramble through tropical rain forests. OSHA would
have a field day with this: Branches overhanging the tracks sting
faces and arms. We could reach out and pick mangoes and papayas
from the passing trees.
</P>
<P>
   Termite nests high in the trees are so large an NFL linebacker
would have difficulty getting both arms around them. Brilliant
clouds of butterflies lead us into Bucay. We slice through banana
plantations, cattle ranches and aquafarms, where the shrimp in your
neighborhood grocery are hatched.
</P>
<P>
   The equatorial sun is ferocious now, ignoring layers of 30- and
40-SPF sunscreen. Many retreat inside the car. A few of us swab on
more high-powered lotion and ride it out. Japanese photographers
keep on clicking.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the afternoon, we finally get to the end of the line,
the sweltering sea-level town of Duran. Drenched and dehydrated,
pumped up from derring-do, we swagger down from the train and
wobble around on rubbery legs.
</P>
<P>
   We slap hands with fellow rooftoppers and board a bus across the
wide and muddy Guayas River to Guayaquil, Ecuador's Pacific coast
port and largest city. Over there somewhere is a hotel with air
conditioning, a pool and maybe a ``Seinfeld'' rerun on satellite
TV.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Traveling on your own rachets up the train's
adventure factor. There's no central information number, and
tickets must be purchased at the station where you board. As noted,
departure times are not completely accurate and cancellations are
often without notice. But it's an incredible bargain _ a one-way
ticket from Riobamba to Guayaquil is $14. It goes on Sundays,
Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Fridays and returns from Guayaquil the
same day or the next day, depending on freight and the number of
passengers. You can come by train from Quito to Riobamba (140
miles) only on Saturdays. So most travelers take a bus from the
capital and overnight in Riobamba.
</P>
<P>
   The hacienda-style Hotel El Troje, three miles from town, has
modern air-conditioned rooms, a good restaurant, bar, pool, tennis
and folkloric entertainment for about $50 a night. You can avoid
the hassles and uncertainties by booking through a reputable tour
operator, such as omnipresent Metropolitan Touring (represented in
the United States by Adventure Associates, 1-800-527-2500).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
