<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 12:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7851 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAWYER-$ADV02-COX     04-29 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWYER-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    REBEL WITH A CAUSE TAKES ON COCA-COLA
 &HT;    For release Sunday, May 2.
 &HT;    Eds: Note biography box at end of story.
 &HT;    By DAVID McNAUGHTON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As a young boy, Cyrus Mehri marched with his
parents to protest the Vietnam war. Before he was a teenager, he
was spellbound by the Watergate hearings. As a young man, he became
a field organizer for Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   These things, former colleague Michael D. Hausfeld said, helped
shape a lawyer who is still taking on the establishment, still
trying to change the world.
</P>
<P>
   This time the establishment is Atlanta-based Coca-Cola, a
``cultural icon,'' in Mehri's words. Mehri is suing Coca-Cola on
behalf of one former and three current employees of the company.
The suit alleges Coca-Cola discriminates against African-Americans
in promotions, pay and evaluations. The company says the suit ``is
without merit.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be several years _ and the spending of ``a small
fortune'' by his law firm, Mehri, Malkin &AMP; Ross _ before the
Coca-Cola case is resolved, Mehri said.
</P>
<P>
   Mehri, who started the Washington firm last year after being
part of the winning team in a $176 million discrimination suit
settlement with Texaco, picks his fights carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to take a case unless not only is it a solid
case, a well-rounded case, a viable case, but also has a public
dimension to it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The public dimension in the Coca-Cola case, Mehri suggests, is
race relations in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, Mehri noted, has talked in abstract terms
about starting a national discussion of race relations. The
Coca-Cola case, Mehri predicted, ``is going to trigger a
conversation about race with concrete examples: What it really
means to have a glass ceiling. What it really means to have people
channeled off into certain areas. What it means to have the full
panoply of opportunities that there would be for white employees,
not to be there for the black employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehri has been described as ``cocky,'' but lest he be
underestimated, recall his training under one of the nation's most
prominent consumer advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working with Nader ... was a tremendous experience for me
because I learned so much about taking on very powerful
institutions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He has had some success, notably in the Texaco case, in which
inflammatory tapes of conversations by company executives were
dropped into his lap. ``Masterfully'' orchestrated publicly
generated by the lawyers who took on Texaco also helped, according
to an article in The American Lawyer in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Was Mehri good in the Texaco case? Or was he lucky?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good, lucky lawyer,'' responded Hausfeld, a partner in
the firm of Cohen, Milstein, Hausfeld &AMP; Toll, for whom Mehri worked
at the time. ``Every good lawyer, now and then, needs a little
luck.''
</P>
<P>
   And media savvy, according The American Lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say we use the media, but my vision of this kind of
work is that we are like a private attorney general, and just like
an attorney general, there is a constituency, there is the
public,'' Mehri said.
</P>
<P>
   However, he denied leaking information to The New York Times,
whose front-page stories about the Texaco tapes were followed
shortly by the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word leak is not an accurate term, because that suggests
that something that was not public was leaked,'' Mehri offered.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Mehri shared in a $20 million payday for the
plaintiffs' lawyers. He wouldn't disclose how much much he got.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just say I'm doing fine financially,'' he confessed.
</P>
<P>
   But money is not the only motivator, Mehri said. ``For me, this
practice has twin goals. One, you need to be successful from a
business point of view, to survive, to keep going so you can
litigate other cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some of my brethren in the bar miss the other side of
it, which is that you have to be in this for the justice, you have
to be in this to open the doors and give access to the legal system
that ordinary people don't have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say the most gratifying moment I've had as a
professional was the day we had the hearing approving the Texaco
settlement,'' Mehri said, with a hint of tears in his eyes as he
recalled the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a no-press-allowed event with over 100 of the
(plaintiffs) at a hotel down the street from the courthouse. One by
one, the people came up, the African-American employees, with
testimonials. Hearing how much those folks appreciated what we had
done, and what I myself had done personally, because my life was
that case, and I put my career on the line for that case, when I
heard those words, that really moved me. It was worth it for that
one moment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think this is a cause for Cyrus,'' said Stanley Weiner,
who represented Fina, a petroleum company, in a mediated settlement
last year involving discrimination complaints by clients of Mehri.
</P>
<P>
   The financial reward is probably part of the equation, too,
suggested Weiner, of Jones, Day, Reavis &AMP; Pogue in Dallas, But, he
added of Mehri: ``He's doing this because he believes in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehri said he credits his father for his business sense and his
mother for a sense of justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents are immigrants from Iran,'' he said. ``They came to
the United States because they wanted their kids to grow up in a
free society.''
</P>
<P>
   Appropriately enough, Mehri was born on Bastille Day.
</P>
<P>
   In the Coca-Cola case, he will need more than the coincidence of
a birthday marking the French revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The American Lawyer, in its exhaustive story on the Texaco case,
noted that ``class action employment discrimination suits are
notoriously hard for plaintiffs to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehri's personality is a plus in such cases, according to
Hausfeld.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has an amazing facility with people,'' he said. ``They
trust him. He creates a good attachment with them so they feel free
to talk with him about what is bothering them.''
</P>
<P>
   Specializing in employment opportunity has ``magnified the best
of his talents,'' Hausfeld adds.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but the Coca-Cola case is likely to be a longer haul
than the relatively short Texaco case.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did pretty well in a sprint,'' noted Weiner. ``But how well
he will do in a marathon? I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   CYRUS MEHRI AT A GLANCE
</P>
<P>
   Born: July 14, 1961, in New York City
</P>
<P>
   College: Hartwick College, Oneonta, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Law school: Cornell University
</P>
<P>
   Law firm: Mehri, Malkin &AMP; Ross, Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Family: Wife, Robin Anne Floyd, of Greenville, S.C., and two
children: Dylan, 3 1/2, and Lilah, one month.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
