<HEADER>
A7875 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-REVIEW-SONG-HNS &LR;      04-29 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-SONG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PLACE, NEW ADVENTURE FOR THE INIMITABLE FATHER TIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN GRIFFIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hallelujah! Father Tim's back.
</P>
<P>
   But in Jan Karon's ``A New Song'' (Viking, $24.95), he's left
the small town of Mitford, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   That might not seem like a big deal on the surface. Pastors
change parishes all the time. But to those of us who are fans of
Karon's Mitford series, such news is tantamount to heresy.
</P>
<P>
   Through four novels, we have followed the adventures of Father
Tim Kavanagh and have grown quite fond of this aging, though not
elderly, Episcopalian priest who has found love and family later
than he ever thought. There's a kinship not only with him but also
with his wonderfully eclectic and somewhat eccentric neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Father Tim's world is incomplete without the likes of
his adopted son, Dooley; the jokester Uncle Billy and his
schizophrenic wife, Miss Rose; the hymn-loving Louella; the
industrious, gossipy Emma; Puny and her twins.
</P>
<P>
   The list goes on. And all are dear old friends.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps too old, for after four novels, Karon probably felt she
had no place to take Father Tim in Mitford, so she removed him and
his wife, Cynthia, to the North Carolina coast and an interim
position with a church on Whitecap Island.
</P>
<P>
   Such a change would be hard for anyone, especially someone like
Father Tim, who's genuinely homesick and spends a great deal of
time on the phone with old friends. Too often, it seems, for he is
admonished for not tending to the needs of his new church and a
whole new set of challenging parishioners.
</P>
<P>
   As in the previous installments, the good Lord lays out much for
the priest to grapple with. Like Abraham, who became a father late
in life, Father Tim learns the joys of parenthood when he and
Cynthia take in a 3-year-old whose mother suffers from debilitating
bouts of depression. And like Abraham, Father Tim eventually deals
with having to sacrifice the child.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the novel succeeds this well. Too much of the
plotting, such as an awkwardly rendered ``Phantom of the Opera''
rip-off, descends into the predictable.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, predictability on a certain level has always been one
of Karon's strengths. Her readers love knowing that, by novel's
end, at least one lost soul will find salvation and that, despite
life's rocky path, universal truths about God's love will come
shining through.
</P>
<P>
   But Karon's writing in the earlier novels, especially in ``A
Home in Mitford'' and, my favorite, ``Out to Canaan,'' had an
effortlessness about it while the storytelling displayed a
disarming simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   In ``A New Song,'' though, the humor is sometimes forced and
there's a slight strain in a couple of the stories. But the
author's heart is, as always, in the right place.
</P>
<P>
   And if some of her new characters don't have the same resonance
as our old Mitford friends, it's probably just because we don't
have the same history with them. That's sure to come, too, for
Karon has wisely left many a string untied, a sure sign that Father
Tim's inspirational story is far from being at an end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 1235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
