A7879 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-ELECTION-TEX     04-29 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ELECTION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ELECTION' WINS WITH SUBTLE SATIRE AND GREAT ACTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been said that the new comedy ``Election'' puts former
``Ferris Bueller's Day Off'' star Matthew Broderick on the other
side, as a befuddled and malevolent teacher. It's a glib
description and an inaccurate one. He's Jim McAllister, a caring
teacher who loves his kids and loves what he does. And it's his
love for doing what's right that gets him into trouble. He goes
nose-to-nose against the perky and ambitious Tracy Flick (Reese
Witherspoon), who's determined to add the title of class president
to her already waist-deep pile of accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Director Alexander Payne, who co-wrote the script (with Jim
Taylor, who has a featured role), has gone deeper and less broad
than he did with his previous comedy, the rambunctious ``Citizen
Ruth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Election'' works much closer to the bone, taking place under
cool gray skies that cast a somber tone to this MTV Films-produced
social satire that is, of all things, subtle.
</P>
<P>
   A key exchange early in the movie sets things up, in a funny and
painful classroom scene in which McAllister asks students to define
the difference between morality and ethics. The students, caught in
the vortex between indifference and boredom, try to force an answer
when they're singled out. But they're wrong, and they don't exactly
care. Tracy throws her arm up as if it were a flare, and McAllister
refuses to acknowledge her until he has to.
</P>
<P>
   If this were ``Ferris Bueller,'' the soundtrack would point up
the student's triumph so mercilessly that you'd have to duck the
Dolby bombast. Payne and Taylor make the point elegantly. Tracy is
the future, oblivious to everything except her own determination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Election'' is built on the kind of delusion that makes the
best American comedy, in which all are convinced that they're doing
what has to be done _ the hilarious and ultimately self-destructive
impulse to hurl themselves into the breach.
</P>
<P>
   In McAllister's case, it's finding the right person to run
against Tracy. He finds just the guy, the hobbled football stud
Paul (Chris Klein), an amiable born winner who seems stoned on his
own charisma. Which fires up Tracy even more. And which really sets
a fire under Paul's adopted sister, Tammy (Jessica Campbell), whose
jealousy _ her girlfriend dumps her for Paul _ prompts Tammy to run
for the office on the apathy ticket. (A ticket that gets the
biggest audience response at a school assembly.)
</P>
<P>
   Payne is equally interested in all of his characters. And, as he
did in ``Citizen Ruth,'' he fashions an observant social comedy in
which a woman is at the center of the action. Provisionally,
``Election'' is McAllister's story. But it's deceptive, because
although McAllister does most of the narration, we get to hear what
is going on in almost everybody's head.
</P>
<P>
   Witherspoon's pinging enthusiasm is beveled to a nightmarish
point. And Campbell is a wonder; her anguish and resentment have
twisted her into an angry knot, and Campbell makes Tammy's
suffering real and funny.
</P>
<P>
   You wonder how well ``Election'' will do. This kind of brainy,
sourball comedy isn't a high-concept wonder that pulls kids into
the tent like ``10 Things I Hate About You'' (which features one of
the best performances of the year, from Julia Stiles) or ``She's
All That.''
</P>
<P>
   And the subject matter ain't the kind of thing that might
attract adults, who would definitely like it. (The title doesn't
help either, although it is taken from the novel.) It's undeniably
one of the best comedies of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, though, content and accomplishment aren't enough to
bring in viewers. Let's hope that's not the case here.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Election''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Alexander Payne
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Matthew Broderick, Reese Witherspoon
</P>
<P>
   Length: 104 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ adult language and sexuality
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
