A7894 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-29 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMBS FOR BELGRADE, BOMBAST FROM WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If I were watching the debate over Serbia on
C-SPAN, it probably came as a surprise that the power to declare
war is reserved for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Don't presidents have the right to bomb any country that
displeases them? Recently we've only seen Congress declare war on
the president. For decades, Congress has stood by while presidents
blew up things around the world.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the House of Representatives stood up for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, our courageous members of Congress stood up halfway,
stooping to please, kneeling to pray or crouching to keep their
heads low.
</P>
<P>
   They failed to pass a proposal to declare war. It was sponsored
by Rep. Tom Campbell, a California Republican whose constituents
declared war on him for voting to impeach President Clinton. He
probably wants to go out on a high-minded note.
</P>
<P>
   They voted to make the president seek their approval before
sending infantry into the mud of Kosovo. Members of Congress are
experts in mud. Flinging it.
</P>
<P>
   They tied, 213-213, on what was meant to be a symbolic vote
supporting Clinton's bombing campaign in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   What does it all mean? Congress seems to like its wars
undeclared, without ground troops and deadlocked in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be the way Clinton likes his wars, too, so what's
the fuss?
</P>
<P>
   The measure that passed, sponsored by Republicans with lots of
Democrats voting for it, would require Clinton to get congressional
approval to send ``ground elements'' to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   While Congress debated what ground elements means, the Pentagon
was ordering more air elements to the war in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   A tie goes to the runner, and Clinton is on the run. He
maintained his traditional power to declare air war.
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on movies or video games, but Americans act like air
wars aren't really wars. Maybe this is because we've never had an
air war waged against our cities.
</P>
<P>
   It was amazing to listen to the squawking of Democratic hawks
and Republican doves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bombing for peace is wrong and it's not working,'' said Rep.
Doug Bereuter, R-Neb.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the time to cut and run,'' said Rep. Tom Lantos of
California, echoing the words of his fellow Democrat Lyndon
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton asked Congress to ``speak with a single voice'' so he
can demonstrate unity in the face of atrocities by Serbian leader
Slobodan Milosevic. Congress didn't speak with a single voice, and
in a way represented the American people better than it usually
does.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the war in Serbia, America is a barnyard of
hawks, doves, chickens and those who merely want to duck.
</P>
<P>
   Those birds do not flock together along party lines. For a year
everyone has called for bipartisanship, and we finally got it _ a
bipartisan ship of fools.
</P>
<P>
   I'm starting to feel for Clinton. He underestimated Milosevic,
thinking a few cruise missiles would cow the guy. He didn't
anticipate Milosevic would swamp his neighbors with refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton thought bombing would be enough. And since bombing is a
de facto power of the presidency, he wouldn't have to go to
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, his war with Congress isn't over any more than his
war with Milosevic. We have a weakened president, and maybe that's
good in some ways.
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson had been weak in 1964, maybe he wouldn't have been
able to get Congress to go along with the Gulf of Tonkin
resolution, authorizing presidential power to launch military
actions in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, we have all those Albanian refugees and we
owe them something.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to speak with one voice. There are always a bunch
chattering inside our consciences and our hearts.
</P>
<P>
   We don't want to see refugees raped, killed and run out of their
homes into filthy camps. We also don't want to see American troops
trudge through the mud and die in Kosovo, a place most of us never
heard of a couple of months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us don't like the idea of shooting guided missiles at
the home of the president of a country we haven't declared war on.
</P>
<P>
   But if they'd have found him at home, we probably wouldn't have
minded.
</P>
<P>
   Our president declared air war, which many Americans believe is
within his powers. But winning wars with aircraft alone is not
within anyone's power.
</P>
<P>
   So here we are, stuck 10,000 feet over the quagmire with our
precision weapons that have a disturbing way of becoming imprecise
right into villages and refugee convoys. The results don't look
like the Pentagon video games seen at press briefings.
</P>
<P>
   Our elected representatives are hard at work, though. Congress
has urged Clinton to meet with entertainment industry leaders to
curb media violence.
</P>
<P>
   I have a feeling, though, that we'll be seeing videotapes
showing bombs hitting buildings in Belgrade for some time to come.
</P>
<P>
   Keep declaring it isn't a war, and hope for the best. That seems
to be what both Clinton and Congress are doing.
</P>
<P>
   It's easier to declare war on ``The Matrix'' and ``Doom.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
