A7910 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-29 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MELTDOWN OF THE NUCLEAR FAMILY MYTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ While the familiar orgy of finger-pointing and
cultural analysis continues in the wake of the Littleton massacre,
a few facts should be underscored before they're forgotten. Again.
</P>
<P>
   Complete answers died with Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold, so we
may never know exactly why they stockpiled weapons, then launched
themselves on a murderous rampage through Columbine High School.
But we do know that decidedly absent from the case are some of the
customary social dogs that people love to kick around.
</P>
<P>
   The two teen-agers _ who allegedly planned to kill hundreds of
people _ were not members of a racial or ethnic minority, were not
poor and did not come from broken homes.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that the next time a politician or condemnatory
clergyman heaps the blame for society's woes atop welfare mothers,
divorce, violence-prone minorities and the decay of traditional
family values.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Klebold nor Harris was scarred by the pain of divorce;
both boys came from that much-touted panacea for society's ills:
the intact nuclear family.
</P>
<P>
   The killing spree had nothing to do with years of harassment and
discrimination over skin color, ethnic origin or family religion.
While Harris and Klebold were ridiculed and ostracized, it seems it
was because of a highly counter-cultural lifestyle they voluntarily
adopted in their teens.
</P>
<P>
   Nor were the boys products of the much-maligned welfare system
or the lower working class.
</P>
<P>
   Harris' father, a retired Air Force pilot, is employed by a
flight safety company. Harris' mother works for a caterer. The
Klebolds live in a $400,000 home. Dylan Klebold's father was a
geophysicist but now runs his own mortgage management company. His
wife provides vocational training for disabled community college
students.
</P>
<P>
   One long-time neighbor of the Harrises called them ``dream
parents ... supportive, not critical. They didn't put undue
pressure on their son.'' A friend and neighbor of the Klebolds
said: ``This is a conscientious, normal family that's done
everything right.''
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, the rabid blame layers will no doubt find
something wrong with the Klebolds' and Harrises' parenting; the
couples are human after all, which means they make mistakes. But
will it be enough to explain the enormity of their boys' crimes?
</P>
<P>
   When all the facts are known, the why of the Columbine massacre
may not be so tidily laid at the parents' feet.
</P>
<P>
   Then what? To whom will the indictment _ ``Why did no one see?''
_ be handed down?
</P>
<P>
   Just after the Littleton shootings, people in that community
repeated the same myth that sprang up in Jonesboro, Ark.; West
Paducah, Ky.; Springfield, Ore.; and Pearl, Miss. _ sites of other
rampages by middle-class, white teen-age boys: ``Things like this
just don't happen here.''
</P>
<P>
   They repeated it because _ despite the growing body of contrary
evidence _ most Americans still believe that explosive violence and
senseless destruction arise primarily in big urban centers.
</P>
<P>
   They expect kids to kill each other in places where unhappy,
attitude-wielding minorities are the majority; where teens drop out
of school or don the colors of street gangs; where fathers are in
short supply, and welfare is the common legacy from one generation
to the next.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Klebolds' neighbors told the Associated Press:
``There are so many kids whose goal in life is to hide their plans.
Most of us are the last ones to see our kids in trouble. You're
just blinded by ... love.''
</P>
<P>
   Love. And perhaps the belief that violence and insane rage don't
live in places like Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter &LR; examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
