<SLUG> BC-PATAKI-BALKANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI ATTACKS CLINTON'S BALKAN POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ New York Gov. George Pataki blasted President
Clinton's foreign policy and his handling of the conflict over
Kosovo, saying the administration's ``track record of
indecisiveness'' helped create the Balkan conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slobodan Milosevic did not fear us, and he had no reason to
fear us ... which is one of the reasons we're in this crisis in the
first place,'' Pataki, referring to the leader of Yugoslavia, told
an audience of several hundred people at Georgetown University.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican governor said the Clinton administration's
pattern of repeatedly issuing threats against foreign dictators,
such as Iraqi President Saddam Hussein, and then backing down led
the Serbian leader to believe the United States would not act
forcefully to prevent attacks against ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clear in my mind that this administration's track
record of indecisiveness would endanger the very people we set out
to help,'' he said in the Wednesday night address.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's appearance here was part of a series of speeches
he has made around the country in recent months intended to bolster
his national stature.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has been flirting with the possibility of running for the
presidency, traveling to Illinois, Florida, Missouri and New
Hampshire, site of the first presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has not said whether he would seek another office,
and the only race he has ruled out is the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said the president's policy in dealing with Yugoslavia
have resulted in a complete failure to achieve the original goals
laid out by the administration when the NATO bombing campaign began
March 24, namely to protect the Kosovo Albanians and to weaken
Milosevic's hold on power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of deterring atrocities in Kosovo, the bombings are
intensifying the atrocities ... and instead of eroding support for
Milosevic, the bombings have rallied the Serbian people around
him,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo is a province of Serbia that once enjoyed relative
autonomy. Serbia, the dominant republic of Yugoslavia, sees Kosovo
as an invaluable part of its history.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki urged Clinton to follow President George Bush's example
in the Gulf War and define what the country's goals are in the
Balkans and how he intends to achieve them.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the president should stop escalating the war in a
``Vietnam-style'' gradualism and should instead be prepared to act
``boldly'' to achieve victory if military action is required.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parallels between President Clinton in Kosovo and
President (Lyndon) Johnson in Vietnam are frightening,'' Pataki
said.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has billed his various speeches as his attempt to
maneuver the Republican Party's agenda during the upcoming
elections. The governor has emphasized lower taxes and longer
prison sentences, a combination that Pataki aides said they believe
offers a Republican image with wider appeal than that offered by
social conservatives in the party.
</P>
<P>
   With its emphasis on Kosovo and America's role in the world,
Pataki's speech appeared to be aimed at showing Washington insiders
that the governor has the mastery of foreign policy issues to be
considered for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next century will be America's second century, but only if
we reclaim the bold American leadership the world has received in
the past and demands in the future,'' Pataki said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
