</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-NFL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS MAY GAIN FROM NFL RESOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- National Football League commissioner Paul Tagliabue
finally got tired of presiding over the downsizing of the NFL and
the state of Massachusetts may be the first beneficiary.
</P>
<P>
   The league's decision at the March owners' meetings to pass
Resolution G-2, the Stadium Construction Contribution Policy, was a
key impetus that led to the new stadium proposal agreed to late
Tuesday night between House Speaker Tom Finneran and Senate
President Tom Birmingham. It is hoped that deal will provide
Patriots owner Bob Kraft with a reason to reject Connecticut's
sweetheart proposal that would hand him a state-funded, $384
million stadium at no cost if he agrees to move his franchise to
Hartford by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   For the team to stay in Massachusetts, Kraft would have to turn
his back on the richest stadium deal in sports history, a
Connecticut proposal that would give him a state-of-the-art stadium
plus $120 million in maintenance funding and $1 billion in
guaranteed suite and club seat income over the life of the lease.
</P>
<P>
   In rejecting that cash-rich offer, Kraft would have to agree to
privately fund a 68,000-seat stadium in Foxborough that would cost
him an estimated $225 million while he receives $70 million in
state-funded infrastructure that he would partially repay at $1.4
million a year out of parking fees or a ticket surcharge.
</P>
<P>
   If Kraft formally rejects Connecticut's plan by Sunday's
deadline and accepts the Massachusetts offer (assuming it passes
through the Legislature as presently constructed), he would become
the first owner in sports history to agree to partially pay for
infrastructure improvements to state roads and utilities as part of
a stadium project.
</P>
<P>
   But Resolution G-2, which was approved by a 29-2 vote of NFL
owners six weeks ago, would make Kraft eligible for a low-interest
loan from the league that could account for up to 34 percent of the
building costs. That loan would be repaid by the league from
television revenue and visiting team shares of club seat tickets as
well as through a contribution from the players' union out of its
share of gross revenues.
</P>
<P>
   That resolution was passed in large part because of growing
concerns among league owners and television executives that stadium
problems in major cities were forcing teams to abandon the nation's
largest television markets for far smaller ones. That trend has led
in recent years to the Los Angeles Rams moving to St. Louis, the
Los Angeles Raiders moving to Oakland, the Cleveland Browns moving
to Baltimore, the Houston Oilers moving to Nashville, and expansion
teams going to Jacksonville, Fla., and Charlotte, N.C., while
cities like Houston and LA lay fallow.
</P>
<P>
   These shifts were not pleasing to television executives who have
paid billions to NFL owners for broadcast rights only to see the
league leave the nation's second and fourth largest cities and were
facing the possibility that the sixth largest TV market, Boston,
would be traded for Hartford because of stadium funding problems.
This new reality led the owners to approve Resolution G-2 and
stepped up Tagliabue's efforts to negotiate acceptable stadium
deals in cities such as Boston, Pittsburgh, Detroit, and Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been no formal talks between television executives
and the league on this but obviously you don't trade down from
Boston to Hartford unless you absolutely have to,'' a highly placed
NFL source said. ``This is a trend that has not been good for the
league or our television partners. We all recognize that.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Browne, the NFL's senior vice president of communications
and government affairs, admitted Wednesday that Tagliabue had
become ``more proactive. We have tried to keep franchise stability
in the past. We went to court in 1980-81 to try and stop the
Raiders from leaving Oakland, for example, but we are certainly
trying to learn from our experiences, some of which have not always
been good.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important we're in the major markets and it's important
we stay in our current markets. Franchise movement is not good and
our club owners sense that, especially if the moves are from larger
communities to smaller ones. The owners are reluctant to approve
such moves unless there is no alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue met with local politicians and Boston business leaders
several times over the past year to try to help resuscitate what
appeared to be a dead proposal to help Kraft fund a new stadium in
Massachusetts. But it was not until after Kraft signed his
record-setting stadium deal in Connecticut earlier this year that
those talks began to gain momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Had that happened sooner there would be no Hartford deal and
until the Massachusetts legislature passes its proposal, Kraft will
not agree to reject Hartford's offer. And even if the state's new
plan is approved as outlined, Kraft will be in a bind because sound
business principals would never allow someone to reject
Connecticut's deal for the Massachusetts offer on its merits alone.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean Kraft could not opt for his hometown over his
wallet, but to do so would involve serious financial sacrifices.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people have to realize is Mr. Kraft has a major decision
to make,'' Browne said. ``The Massachusetts proposal does not come
close to matching what Hartford has offered. If he decides to stay,
he's doing it at a great financial loss to the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important issue to the Kraft family is that the team
stay competitive. The best opportunity for that is to go to
Hartford. Does he go where his team will be better funded or stay
where his family was born and raised but where he's been taken for
granted by the city fathers until very recently?
</P>
<P>
   ``While we applaud the city leaders for the steps they've taken
recently, the Krafts are being asked to do what no other team has
ever done in sports _ to pay for infrastructure in addition to
their stadium. That is a question other owners will surely ask. Why
is he paying for infrastructure? It's an issue we'll have to
consider and address with the other owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Kraft has a major decision to make between now and May 2,
when he has to tell the state of Connecticut that he'll play there
in 2002 or reject their offer. He is both a businessman and a
sportsman. The businessman viewing the difference between
Hartford's proposal and Massachusetts's would go to Hartford. I
know there have been owners in our sport and in other sports who
have advised him that that is what he should do.''
</P>
<P>
   Although neither the league nor CBS, which owns broadcast rights
for the American Football Conference and therefore most Patriots
games, would be happy to see the Boston TV market replaced by
Hartford's, owners may not be terribly pleased if Kraft agrees to
become the first professional franchise owner in history to bear
the cost of stadium infrastructure that has traditionally been born
exclusively by cities and states.
</P>
<P>
   But, in the end, that issue may pale in comparison with the
downsizing of a league that today calls itself ``National'' yet has
no face in Los Angeles and Houston and, unless Kraft agrees to pay
to stay here, could lose one in Boston as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 1328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7925 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-LATINOS-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     04-29 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LATINOS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... self-esteem.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``All kids recognize that seeing people like themselves is
important,'' said Lois Salisbury, president of the child advocacy
group Children Now, based in Oakland, Calif. The group surveyed
1,200 children ages 10 to 17 about media and race last year. ``It
gave them a sense of being included and provided role models.''
</P>
<P>
   While there are Hayeks and Nely Galans (Telemundo's
entertainment president) out there, Martinez says many of the girls
she knows want to become hairdressers. That, she adds, is what
people in their neighorhood do.
</P>
<P>
   Smart and sassy Martinez has a different path in mind. She's
contemplating a career as a journalist/photographer or an FBI
agent. The latter goal is influenced by her love of ``The X-Files''
star David Duchovny (whose picture Martinez carries in a locket
around her neck) and her idol, Puerto Rican actress Jennifer Lopez,
who played an agent in the film ``Out of Sight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to become the stereotype of what Hispanic girls
are,'' said Gonzalez's 15-year-old daughter, Annabelle Guerra.
``There are positive (role models) out there and we have to look
for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Guerra's search usually ends on television that's in Spanish.
Her role models are Univision talk show superstar Cristina
Saralegui and two female anchors on Univision's news show ``Primer
Impacto.''
</P>
<P>
   But, like most young Latinos, Guerra prefers gluing her eyes to
MTV if she's not watching the WB shows or ``Boy Meets World.'' Why?
``There aren't that many great shows'' in Spanish, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Telemundo and Univision, with their daily supply of soap operas,
talk shows, and game shows, have the unofficial reputation of being
for immigrants and the elderly. There's a local television station
that broadcasts in Spanish called Cuencavision, but Guerra said,
``It's extremely boring and half the time it's not even on.''
</P>
<P>
   Guerra's love of American TV doesn't stop her from taking action
if she sees a Hispanic stereotype. She'll switch channels. It's a
response she shares with almost 60 percent of the Hispanics polled
in the Tomas Rivera reports.
</P>
<P>
   With TV viewership plummeting, talk of turning off the tube is
enough to make any advertiser or TV programmer jittery. Hispanics
spend $3.5 billion in goods and services annually in this country,
according to LULAC. If Latinos watch a lot of TV now, imagine what
might happen to sales and viewership if executives fed the audience
more palatable fare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any broadcaster or network cable programmer who gets ahead of
this curve is going to capture meaningful market share,'' said
Salisbury.
</P>
<P>
   So by next fall, Hispanics may see Puerto Rican Rosie Perez play
a New York City actress in a sitcom or catch a fast-cutting,
MTV-style documentary on saints produced by Salma Hayek.
</P>
<P>
   They may switch to CBS to catch the proposed one-hour drama,
``Sherman Oaks,'' which features Latino actor Esai Morales in an
ensemble cast. Or they'll watch Diego Serrano star alongside teen
queen Jennifer Love Hewitt in Fox's proposed ``Party of Five''
spinoff.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's SiTV, the proposed 24-hour cable channel. Its
creators, who run a two-year-old production company catering to the
Latino market, plan to offer culturally sensitive sitcoms for 18-
to 49-year-old Latinos and educational programs for preteens. The
twist is that all of the shows will be in English.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said, `You're nuts; you can't put English-language
programming on a Spanish network,' '' said Jeff Valdez, cochairman
of SiTV in Los Angeles, who conducted his interview the LA way: by
speaker phone from his car. ``I said, `You're wrong; Latinos speak
English.' It's like the dirty little secret we keep trying to
hide.''
</P>
<P>
   In reality, SiTV's future is about as certain as finding a
Latino doctor on a sitcom. To make it on the air by 2000, SiTV must
raise money for the project, battle other wannabes for a
cable-provider berth and develop enough shows to fill a 24-hour
block.
</P>
<P>
   But Valdez is confident. SiTV has a talk show and stand up
comedy show in syndication. Nickelodeon and Disney recently picked
up SiTV sitcom pilots about two boys growing up in San Antonio and
a former soccer star adjusting to life off the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our initial meetings with the money people have been
phenomenally positive,'' said Valdez, who counts Smits, Daisy
Fuentes, and Hector Elizondo as SiTV advisory board members.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the National Hispanic Foundation for the Arts,
a Washington, D.C.-based advocacy group Smits founded in 1997, is
trying to change things from within. The group mentors and gives
scholarships to Latino film students at New York University, Yale
University, Columbia University, University of Southern California
and University of California at Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The aid may help create the next Eric Tannenbaum (Columbia
TriStar TV's president) or Doug Herzog (20th Century-Fox
Television's president). And that level of success is sorely
needed. Today, according to LULAC, Hispanics hold less than
</P>
<P>
   1 percent of Hollywood's creative and business positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply haven't been able to penetrate the decision-making
slots in the business side of this industry,'' said Feliz Sanchez,
the foundation's president. ``Those are the real determiners of
what we are going to see next season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
