<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELPING KIDS TO LEARN TO FIT IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even as we put distance between us and the murderous rampage in
Littleton, Colo., no parent is free of anguish. If our child is
somehow different and therefore not part of the dominant school
culture, we worry, ``Is he on a trajectory that could prompt him to
violence?'' If he's a mainstream kid who is well accepted by peers,
we pray he is tolerant of differences and not causing pain to other
children.
</P>
<P>
   Our response to either child seems more important today than
ever before.
</P>
<P>
   Child and adolescent psychiatrist David Fassler of Burlington,
Vt., is quick to reassure us that the overwhelming majority of
children who feel targeted by peers do not evolve into teenagers
who commit violence, and those in the ``in'' crowd are not
automatically cruel. But marginalized children may be unhappy and
suffering, and popular children may be too easily swayed by peer
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The most powerful antidote in either case, say Fassler and
others, is a strong connection to parents who are able to
articulate values clearly and to support their children at all
times.
</P>
<P>
   From kindergarten on up, children go through developmental
stages when they are more preoccupied with peer friendships and
less able to let slights roll off their backs than at other, less
vulnerable times. Temperament has a lot to do with it, but even at
young ages, whether they come home crying (``Suzie wasn't nice to
me''), bragging (``Josh is weird and I told him so''), or having
been simply an observer (``Josh threw sand at Suzie''), how we
listen sets them up to consider or not consider their own feelings
as well as those of others.
</P>
<P>
   What we don't want to do is minimize or ignore their issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``At any age, a child needs to be validated and supported. To
tell him, `It will go away' or `It's not a big deal,' leaves him
confused about his own perception and discourages him from coming
to you in the future,'' says Fassler. He is author of `` `Help Me,
I'm Sad': Recognizing, Treating and Preventing Childhood and
Adolescent Depression'' (Viking).
</P>
<P>
   Being supportive can be tricky. For instance, when:
</P>
<P>
   -- Perception doesn't match reality. A sixth grader reports that
no one likes him, but when you talk to the teacher, she says he's
in the social thick of things, and you can see for yourself that he
gets calls and invitations from friends. Though it may be tempting
to dismiss his statements, don't, says psychologist and
psychoanalyst Steven Marans of Yale University Child Study Center.
``There's a reason he's telling you things are lousy when things
are in fact going well,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   It could be that he feels you're neglecting him, and he sees
this as a way to get your attention. It could also be that he feels
awful about himself but can't articulate why. If you let it go, the
problem festers.
</P>
<P>
   -- The whining wears you down. A third grader who constantly
complains about being picked on can begin to seem like a loser,
even in the eyes of a loving parent. ``Kids who are victimized can
become less appealing to us, and we let them down without realizing
it,'' says Rebecca Coffey, author of ``Unspeakable Truths and Happy
Endings: Human Cruelty and the New Trauma Therapy'' (Sidran).
</P>
<P>
   Even though it's inadvertent, our diminished attention feels
like desertion and can lead to greater helplessness, hopelessness,
and isolation. Coffey tells parents always to validate feelings _
``Wow, that must have felt awful!'' _ and to follow up by asking,
``How would you like me to help you?''
</P>
<P>
   The combination of support and a willingness not to give up may
be the two most important things we can do, says psychologist Joy
Osofsky of Louisiana State University. She studies and works with
children exposed to violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may not be able to prevent your child from being unhappy,
but when you hang in there with her, even if she's cranky and moody
and pushing you away, even if she's stone silent, that feels to her
that at least someone cares enough to try to understand,'' says
Osofsky. ``That's the bottom line all kids need. That alone can be
an antidote.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning at about 11, it can be hard to tell when cranky,
moody, pushing-you-away behavior is developmental and therefore
normal, and when it's not. Consider it a red flag when:
</P>
<P>
   -- He isolates himself not just in his room (or garage or
basement) but drops or doesn't show up for extracurricular
activities, shuns friends, or ignores long-standing areas of
interest;
</P>
<P>
   -- She hooks up with friends who don't pay attention to
academics or who glorify weapons or fascism or any other value that
is anathema to you. ``If a kid has gone through early school years
without a friendship group, that he has found kindred spirits in a
new school is a huge relief to parents,'' says Marans. ``Stay alert
for what it is that binds them,'' he warns. ``If it isn't healthy,
talk to him, get school input or professional advice.''
</P>
<P>
   -- He persists in his complaints over a period of months. When
it's transitory and developmental, a child tends to be able to move
on, says Marans. If it has a systemic impact _ not sleeping, not
concentrating _ and he's irritable and critical, it may be
something more.
</P>
<P>
   As important as all this is, there's still a piece missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Differences need to be celebrated and independent thinking
valued,'' says psychologist Susan Linn of the Judge Baker Center in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   This needs to start in the preschool years, when children notice
differences without necessarily passing judgment. ``Validate
them,'' says Linn: `` `Josh doesn't like to play soccer, does he?
But he sure is a great artist!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in the elementary years, when judgment is proffered
frequently and harshly, your values need to come through loud and
clear. If you overhear your 12-year-old daughter and friends
disparaging a peer, there's a range of comments to make:
</P>
<P>
   -- ``I don't think she's geeky; I think she's creative.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``I was just like her when I was that age.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``It disappoints me when I hear you talk like that.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``You're proud of the necklaces you make. How would you feel
if someone didn't like you because of that?''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``I admire someone who has different interests.''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``It's true, she has an annoying hair-twirling habit, but
remember what an incredible skater she is?''
</P>
<P>
   -- ``You have a right to choose your friends, but you don't have
a right to be mean or disrespectful.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if your daughter walks away, even if she's disdainful, at
least, says Linn, ``She will have heard you articulate your values.
That counts at any age.''
</P>
<P>
   Over time, the articulation of these values creates an
atmosphere in your home that helps children learn how to make good
decisions, including being able to say no to peer pressure.
Hopefully, there's reinforcement from school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools need to have mechanisms for supporting children with
minority interests and for articulating and reinforcing
respectfulness,'' Linn says.
</P>
<P>
   Osofsky urges parents to see the school as a partner and to
expect and demand appropriate intervention and social curricula.
``When the school allows humiliation to go unchecked, it's no
longer a safe place'' for a victim or a perpetrator, she says. In
middle school and high school, that can increase a sense of
isolation, of ``me versus them'' mentality, that leads to rage and
revenge including, perhaps, violence.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, says Osofsky, the child who finds a niche in school
and has a family that cares enough to pay attention and love her
will feel some intrinsic sense of connection and self-worth that
enables her to get though unhappy times.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi David Whiman of Temple Shalom in West Newton put it
another way in his sermon last Friday night. In trying to explain
how two young men could show such disregard for human life, he
turned to the cornerstone of Judeo-Christian morality, the Golden
Rule: Love thy neighbor as thyself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very dangerous thing to base a rationale for ethical
conduct solely on a person's perception of his or her own value and
self-worth,'' he said. ``What if you do not love yourself very
much? What if you do not love yourself at all?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -- The more isolated a child is, even if it's self-imposed, the
worse he'll feel about himself. Entice him out of his room with an
activity to do together; working or playing side by side is a good
way to begin a dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   -- Help a young child who is teased to develop a repertoire of
responses, from walking away to standing up for himself: ``I don't
like it when you call me names.''
</P>
<P>
   -- The child who is neither the leader of the pack nor the
victim of it needs tools to intervene safely; to stand by and watch
behavior that he knows is wrong can make him feel as impotent and
enraged as the victim. Talk about the value of a kind word and when
and how to involve a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   -- Children of all ages need a healthy outlet for fun and glory.
</P>
<P>
   -- A child who is unhappy with himself and feaful of being left
out, even if he's not left out at the moment, may be most likely to
target differences in another child as a way to displace his own
fears.
</P>
<P>
   -- At the first sign your child is having trouble, check in with
the teacher: ``How can we help him?''
</P>
<P>
   -- If your child is persistently victimized or victimizing
someone else, get a professional evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz is author of ``Put Yourself in Their Shoes:
Understanding How Your Children See the World'' (Dell). She
welcomes letters and comments and can be reached via e-mail at
meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
