<HEADLINE>
DRAGON RECOGNIZES DIFFICULTY WITH OFFERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a market that swoons over the latest hot technology stock,
this deal seemed like can't-miss material.
</P>
<P>
   Dragon Systems Inc. and its proposed initial public stock
offering had it all: a well-known name in a sexy software category,
pioneering founders, a reputation for cutting-edge innovation, and
a real financial track record.
</P>
<P>
   But the IPO that might have raised as much as $100 million for
Dragon and its voice-recognition software, already delayed over the
winter, was pulled indefinitely last week.
</P>
<P>
   It was a surprising setback for a company that had nearly
tripled sales and posted a solid profit in 1998. Voice-recognition
products, the software that allows you to talk to your personal
computer instead of typing material or commands, blossomed in the
last two years, and so had Dragon. More powerful computers and
software that could recognize continuous speech instead of a
staccato, word-by-word recitation began to make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Dragon Systems said in a statement that it had postponed the IPO
to instead pursue talks with ``several potential strategic
investors.'' Executives at the Newton, Mass. company could not be
reached for comment this week.
</P>
<P>
   Other people familiar with the offering said it was initially
delayed because Dragon's fourth-quarter financial performance fell
below expectations, and was later shelved when first-quarter
results did not generate growth that had been hoped for. Though the
IPO probably would have gotten off the ground, they said, the
pricing of Dragon shares could have been affected.
</P>
<P>
   Documents filed by Dragon in March showed that sales in the
fourth quarter, usually a strong growth period, had increased to
only $21.8 million from $20.7 million in the previous quarter.
Fourth-quarter income from continuing operations improved slightly
to $1.6 million from $1.5 million three months earlier. Dragon did
not report first-quarter results in its public documents.
</P>
<P>
   But the anemic growth of Dragon business in the final months of
1998 may say more about the short-term ups and downs of an
individual software category than the company's operations.
</P>
<P>
   Dragon's market share of the retail voice-recognition market, in
both dollars and units, slipped just slightly throughout the last
nine months, according to software sales tracker PC Data Inc. of
Reston, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Dragon's share of retail units sold ranged from 35.6 percent in
the third quarter of 1998 to a low of 33.7 percent in the first
quarter of this year. Its closest competitor, IBM Corp., claimed
30.6 percent of the retail market in the first quarter of 1999,
according to PC Data.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most small software companies trying to go public, Dragon
Systems has been around for years and has been run by seasoned
computer scientists in their 50s.
</P>
<P>
   Dragon was created in 1982 by biophysicist Janet Baker and her
husband, mathematician James Baker, and operated on a lean diet of
US Defense Department contracts and other small bits of business.
James Baker, who underwent back surgery last fall, resigned as an
employee of the company in December, but remains its chief science
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Dragon operated in the black for years selling early computer
dictation products, staying small and relatively conservative. But
the Bakers changed tactics and decided to gamble in the early
1990s, diverting money and energy in an attempt to develop
continuous-speech software.
</P>
<P>
   They raised money by selling 35 percent of Dragon to Seagate
Technology for $26.5 million (the Bakers still own 52 percent of
Dragon). By 1997, they introduced Naturally Speaking to wide
critical acclaim and quickly growing sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the PCs got to the point where they were powerful enough
to do reasonable continuous speech recognition, Dragon was first to
come out with a product and that really changed the market,'' said
Bill Meisel of MTA Associates in Tarzana, Calif., publisher of
Speech Recognition Update.
</P>
<P>
   But they were hardly the last. Competition from IBM and Lernout
&AMP; Hauspie Speech Products quickly followed and remains today.
</P>
<P>
   They all see a growing market for software that will help
computer hardware recognize continuous speech of users. Small
hand-held computers, for example, would be easier to use with voice
commands, and spoken interaction over the Internet would be
beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   Large corporate customers also see opportunities. Fidelity
Investments has already launched a voice-recognition system to
provide mutual fund information and stock quotes over the phone.
Later this summer, Fidelity expects its customers will be able to
make account inquiries and execute financial transactions by
speaking to a computer over the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Dragon software consistently wins high marks for performance,
but it must rely on retail sales more than any of its big
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   IBM can bundle its product with hardware or turn it into an
added feature of its expensive Lotus software. Lernout &AMP; Hauspie
gets most of its revenue from other sources such as customized
corporate products and language-translation software.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Microsoft Corp., which has its own huge
in-house team working on voice recognition and owns a stake in
Lernout &AMP; Hauspie.
</P>
<P>
   If Microsoft adds voice recognition as a feature to its
omnipresent Windows operating system, as the company has suggested
it will, competitors like Dragon that sell the same thing as add-on
software face an uphill battle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
