<HEADLINE>
CLEARED BY THE COURT, VALHOL IS READY FOR THE DERBY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ The thoroughbred racing industry strives to
protect its image, but the Valhol incident gave the sport a black
eye on the eve of its greatest day.
</P>
<P>
   It's bad enough there are suspicions jockey Bill Patin used an
electrical device on Valhol in the $500,000 Arkansas Derby at
Oaklawn April 10, but to have it happen in a prep for Saturday's
Kentucky Derby makes it even worse for the sport. The matter was
not adjudicated until Tuesday when a Little Rock district court
ruled Oaklawn must release the $300,000 purse Valhol won, thus
permitting him entry into the Derby, which is limited to 20
starters based on earnings in graded races.
</P>
<P>
   The Kentucky Derby is racing's showcase, but the Valhol
situation has been ugly. While Patin left Louisville Saturday and
remains in seclusion in his homestate of Louisiana, trainer Dallas
Keen, who is participating in his first Derby, has fielded
questions and been as diplomatic as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``This took a lot of fun out of the Derby, but we'll make up for
it between now and Saturday'' said Keen, 41, Wednesday. ``Valhol
doesn't know anything about all the controversy and he's been
training very professionally. From the first day he stepped on this
track, he's been calm and relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Valhol, a gelding, won the Arkansas Derby at 30-1 as a maiden in
only the third start of his career. Owned by Texas oil mogul James
Jackson, who purchased the horse privately as a 2-year-old for
$30,000, Valhol ran second in a maiden race at Fair Grounds, then
finished fourth at 107-1 in the Louisiana Derby before going to
Oaklawn.
</P>
<P>
   After the Arkansas Derby, an Oaklawn employee found a battery on
the track, and a tape of the race showed an object falling from the
shoulder area of Valhol as Patin was pulling him up following a
four and one-half legnth tally.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling of the court was the purse could not be withheld
unless any illegal drugs were found. Granted permission to race,
Jackson and Keen named local jockey Willie Martinez as Volhol's
Derby rider.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime a jockey is riding for you, you want him to think
positively,'' said Keen. ``Because of all the allegations against
Billy, we didn't think he could be at his best. I think Billy
understands. He hasn't ridden since the Arkansas Derby. I think it
was in the best interests of the horse to make a change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't help but feel for Billy. He was the one who got us
high on this horse. Billy worked him and came back and said: `He's
the best horse I've ever been on.' Billy rode this horse with
confidence, even though he was a maiden. He was instrumental on
Valhol's road to glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the controversy broke, Billy told me: `There's no way I
carried anything on the horse.' I know this horse. If a buzzer had
been used, I don't think he'd have had the good disposition he did
after the race. I don't think a buzzer is going to make a horse run
faster then he can run, anyway. If anything, it messes him up,
makes him mentally unsound. A big part of training is keeping your
horse fit mentally, as well as physically.''
</P>
<P>
   After two weeks of working under a cloud, the court's ruling
provided Keen with his first ray of relief. ``I feel real good
about it,'' he said. ``It was a big load off my mind. It's been a
pretty tough couple of weeks not knowing if the horse was going to
run, and he deserves the chance to run.''
</P>
<P>
   Keen's only bitterness was directed at Oaklawn Park officials.
``I didn't like the way it looked, it was not good for racing,'' he
said. ``I'm very disappointed in the way Oaklawn handled it. We
didn't know anything for 10 days. Everything we knew came out by
being leaked to the press. I think they were trying to make it look
worse than it really was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
