<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7936 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-COMMENT-BO     04-29 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT A STYLISH TIE, BUT IT'S A MATCH NONETHELESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- No one said it had to be pretty to be good. The Bruins
and Hurricanes have been at each other's tails and throats now for
four games, and it has not been what anyone _ purist, casual
observer, or mayhem lover _ would characterize as an artistic
triumph.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a 2-2 series now, and a pretty good one at that. What
it lacks in flow and playmaking _ dare we say lacks as a tour de
force? _ it more than makes up for in suspense, in elbows and face
mashing, in honest effort and some genuine, festering dislike
between two sides.
</P>
<P>
   So what if the delivery is quirky, awkward. The punch line
works. One only had to hear the noise generated at the sold out
Vault to verify that. The joint had some of that enchanting Garden
hum in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you love to see that wide-open stuff,'' said Bruins
coach Pat Burns, when asked if the series might open up in the next
game or two. ``I don't think you're going to see that here. You
might have to go to another town.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolina coach Paul Maurice had about the same view on the
subject, and it was centered on the back of the two clubs' benches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will it open up?'' he said. ``Not if the coaches have anything
to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it's all about control, the tight-fisted will
that both Burns and Maurice twist like a roped towel around the
collars of their charges.
</P>
<P>
   The 'Canes moved to a 1-0 lead at 4:21 of the first period
Wednesday with Ray Sheppard breaking over the blue line with a long
Martin Gelinas lead pass and nailing in a top-of-the-circle
slapper. In that one flash, there was more available open ice than
in the three other games combined.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this was going to be the night the two sides stopped
trying to slip inside one another's sweaters?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the tractor pull would give way to a night of NASCAR?
</P>
<P>
   Forget that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another thing to remember: We're at Game 4 now, not Game 1,''
said Maurice. ``By that I mean guys are starting to pick their
favorites. You're seeing more after-the-whistle stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that after-the-whistle stuff, the aggravated pushing and
hacking when play is blown dead, that could come to benefit the
Bruins. Maurice knows that. He'll remind his team not to get
carried away with the Three Stooges two-fingered eye-poking the
rest of the way. When the refs whistle off one player from each
side _ as happened four times Wednesday _ the result, of course, is
a couple of minutes of four-on-four play.
</P>
<P>
   In a series that has less room than a European outdoor market
(picture fruits and veggies flying, live chickens pecking and
cackling), a couple of minutes of four-on-four is an afternoon
siesta, especially for the club that has the higher skill level
among its forwards.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, we think, have the higher skill level up front. We
can't say for sure, because skill hasn't had much room to work the
stage in this series. This has been a muscle, stamina, steel-nose,
buckle-your-chin-strap series. The best chance of it to transform
from a dandelion into a rose would be for more four-on-four hockey
and for one side to do something with that open ice. The bet here:
We won't see more than a couple of minutes of that the rest of the
way.
</P>
<P>
   It just ain't pretty.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, and it's not going to be,'' said Sheppard, who has popped
in four goals thus far, which, in regular-season play, when there
is more room, would translate to something like a 351-goal season
(more or less, depending on the number of five-minute OTs). ``It's
going to be a tight-checking series. Guys are not going to be able
to freewheel.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins finally began to buy themselves some space when
Landon Wilson jumped up and nailed a charging Keith Primeau with a
heavy check late in the first period. Primeau went down like one of
those buildings you see get imploded on the network news _ a pile
of bricks, a cloud of dust, passersby applauding _ and three goals
followed in the third period. There had been plenty of hitting
before that, in all four games, but this one provided a turning
point. At least in one game.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice felt the Hurricanes were off their game before that. He
thought the Bruins had the edge all evening. What can we say?
Coaches have their unique views. The 'Canes held a 1-0 lead for 33
minutes 57 seconds, until Don Sweeney knocked in the equalizer with
1:42 left in the second. If the Bruins outplayed his team as
thoroughly as Maurice said, they did good job of camouflaging it
for more than half the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only exciting part of the game'' said Maurice, ``is that
we weren't good and it was 1-1 going into the third.''
</P>
<P>
   Back to Greensboro they go. Skate and shoot have given way to
blocking and tackling. No one is picking corners or feathering
passes, but they are muscling down the slot and chopping the puck
into pate.
</P>
<P>
   And when someone gets to within 5 or 6 feet of the net, the
suspense ignites, the crowd noise swells, and every move, as
refined as it might not be, means something.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both teams have assessed their talent and their speed,'' said
Maurice. ``It's not going to change much.''
</P>
<P>
   And the best part is, it doesn't have to change.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 1336EDT &QL; 
