<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CUBANS-PLAYERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT GENERATION? 
 MOST CUBAN  PLAYERS OFF-LIMITS TO U.S. BASEBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO Gomez  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reciting the merits of Cuban-born baseball players in the major
leagues is not very difficult. From Minnie Minoso to Luis Tiant to
Tony Oliva to Mike Cuellar to Tony Perez to Jose Canseco to ``El
Duque'' Hernandez, Cuban players have distinguished themselves.
</P>
<P>
   A new group of Cuban players, each of whom is considered taboo
for big-league clubs, will be on display at Baltimore's Camden
Yards on Monday. The Orioles will host a group of select Cuban
players in the second of a two-game goodwill exhibition series
between the two contentious nations.
</P>
<P>
   Scouting directors and general managers from all 30 major league
clubs will take a look at the mostly unknown players from the
island nation that rests a mere 90 miles from U.S. soil.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba has long been known as one of the best cradles of baseball,
where the game is treated more like a religion than a sport.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba's numerous championships in amateur competition over the
past three decades and the slow trickle of defectors who have
recently made their way to the big leagues and managed to stand out
is evidence enough to most baseball people of Cuba's exceptional
level of playing the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any doubt that they have some very
talented players,'' said Texas Rangers General Manager Doug Melvin.
``As an industry, baseball has done a good job of getting players
from places such as the Dominican Republic, Venezuela and other
Latin American countries. Cuba would obviously be another great
place for us to recruit and bring talent over here. It's somewhat
similar to those other countries in that there are a lot of quality
players there.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that most of Cuba's current stars remain
relatively unknown to major league scouts and organizations.
Because Cuba remains communist, scouting Cuban players has been
prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   It was the biggest reason all 30 clubs eagerly sent the allotted
one person to Cuba last month to watch the Orioles' historic game
in Havana. Most were left overwhelmed after Cuba's hard-throwing
right-hander, Jose Contreras, struck out 10 while pitching eight
scoreless innings in relief that sunny afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The well-built Contreras, 6 feet 3, impressed not only the
Orioles, but most everyone else who was at Estadio Latinoamerica as
well as big-league officials watching the game on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question they have a talented group of players,''
Florida Marlins General Manager Dave Dombrowski said.
``Particularly in pitching, which was apparent from what everybody
has seen and talked about. As for Contreras, anyone that can pitch
and has a power arm and shut down a club like the Orioles has to be
considered a top-level prospect.''
</P>
<P>
   The list, however, does not end with Contreras, who was 9-3 with
a 2.22 ERA in 109 innings in the recently concluded Cuban season.
Third baseman Omar Linares, Contreras' teammate on Pinar del Rio,
is probably the most talked-about Cuban player.
</P>
<P>
   It is now known that New York Yankees owner George Steinbrenner
offered a then-22-year-old Linares $1 million to defect and sign
with his club in 1989. Linares, a staunch member of the Communist
Party and one of Cuban President Fidel Castro's prized athletes,
never considered the offer.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that pitching is what most clubs seek, and Cuba has
them in pitchers such as Contreras, Pedro Luis Lazo (15-4, 2.34),
Jose Ibar (18-2, 2.28), Antonio Sanit (18 saves, 2.78) and Ciro
Silvino, whose 1.85 ERA was the best in the country last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban delegation has refused to announce the 25-man roster
that will be present in Baltimore, preferring to list a pool of 48
possible players. Shortstop German Mesa was among the players who
could make the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa, who is in his late 20s, was the player who kept current
New York Mets shortstop Rey Ordonez on the bench for several
seasons when the two were teammates for Havana's team. But Mesa
also got into trouble with the government when his name appeared
among those rumored to be thinking of defecting to the United
States to seek riches in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa, whose skills were once ranked ahead of Ordonez's, recently
concluded a two-year ban from Cuba's official league and the
chances of his being part of the club in Baltimore seem very small.
</P>
<P>
   Havana closer Antonio Sanit, who comes from the side much as
Dennis Eckersley did and led all of Cuba with 18 saves, did not
make the list of 48, possibly out of fear he might defect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'a apparent they are a talented group of players, and
several could play in the big leagues if they come,'' Dombrowski
said. ``You can see that by the ones who have come here and
excelled. But I don't think we know the depth of their talent
because don't see all their players.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
