<HEADER>
A7945 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORLD-ECONOMY-BOS &LR;      04-29 1423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD'S ECONOMY SHOWS SOME VITAL SIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the Dow Jones industrial average climbing to
new highs, US stocks have been a sure money-maker for millions of
investors. But at the same time, another class of stocks has made
the soaring Dow look like a laggard.
</P>
<P>
   Where are they? Try South Korea, Thailand and Brazil _ the very
nations that watched investors flee in terror during the last 22
months, setting off a downturn that swept through Asia, Brazil and
Eastern Europe and threatened industrialized nations as well.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil, once considered a tumbling domino that might cripple all
of Latin America, has watched stock values double since September.
So has South Korea. In recession-plagued Japan, stock values are up
30 percent this year. Thailand and Indonesia have seen improvement
as well.
</P>
<P>
   This and several other encouraging trends have prompted analysts
to say that the global financial crisis is ending, and along with
it the fear of a prolonged global recession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps it is just that spring is in the air,'' said Stanley
Fischer, the No. 2 official at the International Monetary Fund, in
a speech last week, but Asia ``seems to be recovering or about to
do so.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The global financial crisis is now officially over,'' George
Soros, the international financier, declared last week after
investors gobbled up $2 billion in new bonds issued by Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, say some other analysts. The most encouraging
developments are coming so far in the financial markets, and they
are due largely to the decisions of global investors chasing high
returns. None of it suggests that real improvements have been made
in the underlying economies of these nations -- in the factories,
the banks and retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   A booming stock market is not always a reliable sign that a
nation's economy is on the mend. Since 1990, Japanese stocks have
rallied five times but the economy has never followed suit, noted
Richard Katz, author of ``Japan, the System that Soured.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, business conditions seem only modestly improved in
Asia, say Boston-area companies that sell goods and services in the
region. Many expect recession to remain for another year.
</P>
<P>
   After the Asian crisis hit in July 1997, several customers told
Raytheon Co. that they could not obtain the financing that would
have enabled the Lexington, Mass. company to build oil refineries
or other types of processing plants for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we are seeing people starting to talk about doing study
work and talking about reinvesting in these projects,'' said
Vincent Barry, a senior vice president at the Raytheon Engineers &AMP;
Constructors unit.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's just talk. ``It's nothing dramatic by any means, but
we think the down part has come to an end,'' Barry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just in one of the largest malls in Korea, and the place
was buzzing,'' reported Bruce Nevins, Asia chief for Reebok-brand
sneakers, part of Reebok International Ltd. of Stoughton, Mass.
``There were bags in peoples' hands, rather than just being out
taking a look at the stores.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he predicted, the region would probably not
recover until the end of next year or even 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Thomas of Westborough, Mass. computer-maker Data General
Corp. said that business is up ``a little'' in Korea, Japan and
China. ``The problems probably bottomed out a year ago, but
business is still not what you'd call robust,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette Co. of Boston offered a bullish assessment, saying
Asian sales were up 11 percent in the first quarter of 1999,
compared to the same period last year. It predicted that sales in
Eastern Europe and Latin America would soon follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts also caution that the rising stock markets in Asia
and Brazil could blunt the drive for reforms that are needed to
prevent the next downturn.
</P>
<P>
   In their view, the Asian crisis was proof of the failure of
``crony capitalism,'' in which governments directed bank loans to
powerful conglomerates, which used the money to support inefficient
businesses or to overbuild ship and auto factories that are now
only half-used. Billions of dollars in debts still lie on the books
of Asian banks and corporations, and it is unclear whether
governments will follow through on promises to enforce new banking,
bankruptcy and financial disclosures laws.
</P>
<P>
   In Korea, the giant Daewoo chaebol, or conglomerate, has said it
will sell its shipbuilding operations, one step toward cutting its
manufacturing overcapacity and returning to health. But critics say
Daewoo must do more, as must the other chaebols.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, the government has pumped $60 billion into debt-ridden
banks, which has allowed the banks and some of their client
companies to improve their books. But it has not prompted the banks
to lend new money to customers, which would spur the economy, said
Katz.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the government has merely moved corporate debts onto
its own books, rather than forcing companies to go bankrupt and
banks to write off their bad loans, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The government has cut interest rates to close to zero, but
Japanese consumers still refuse to spend money. That leaves
government spending as the only fuel for the economy. Rather than
leading the rest of Asia out of recession, the Japanese economy
will shrink 1.4 percent this year after contracting 2.8 percent in
1998, the International Monetary Fund predicts.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say that Thailand has also failed to close
debt-ridden businesses, and the recent stock revival might blunt
any will to take tough political actions. They see a similar story
in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expected a big jump in inflation and damage to the
Brazilian economy this year when the country devalued its currency.
That never materialized. Instead, said Nariman Behravesh, senior
international economist for Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI in Lexington,
Mass., low worldwide inflation and a record Brazilian crop harvest
kept prices down, allowing the central bank to lower interest
rates. As the economy improved, Brazil's currency appreciated and
investors began putting money back in the country.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Behravesh said, policymakers may become ``too
complacent'' to enact cutbacks in the country's ``very, very
generous'' pension system. They may not have the will to cut
government bureaucracy that is sapping tax revenues, or to improve
the tax collection system _ reforms the country needs to improve
its financial health, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Russia remains a constant worry. The country is in danger of
defaulting anew on foreign debt, and while the International
Monetary Fund has signaled it will provide additional relief loans
to country, many observers fear that Russian lawmakers will refuse
to enact the reforms that the IMF is demanding.
</P>
<P>
   Most economists who see improvement in the global economy add
other caveats and cautions that plenty could still go wrong. The
fragile nature of Brazil's recovery, for example, was on display
only this week, when a single political event raised fears that
investors would flee once again. The arrest of a former central
banker and news of a probe into foreign-exchange insider trading
raised prospects that the current government would be tainted.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, no one knows how much the slow-growing or
recession-bound nations can rely on the world's economic leaders.
Growth in Europe is exepcted to slow this year, for example. On
Tuesday, several German economic institutes cut their forecasts for
Germany, which accounts for one-third of the economy of the nations
embracing the new Euro currency. They said the German economy would
grow 1.7 percent this year, lower than the 2.3 percent they
predicted last fall.
</P>
<P>
   US economic officials have adopted a sober view of the news from
Asia. With the United States the only nation showing strong growth,
``the risks around the world are still very much tilted toward lack
of growth, spare capacity, and slowdown,'' Larry Summers, the No. 2
US Treasury official, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the doomsday scenarios of a global financial meltdown
seem more remote these days. ``We're back from really walking on
the precipice, where we might have fallen and not been caught,''
said Douglas Paal, president of the nonprofit Asia Pacific Policy
Center and a former National Security Council staffer. But much of
the world ``still has a long climb back to full health.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
