<HEADLINE>
--AS BROAD WAISTLINES AGE, HEALTH RISKS FOUND TO FALL  
 --AIDS DRUGS MAY OBVIATE A NEED FOR ANTIBIOTICS  
 --FOR MARFAN SYNDROME, SURGICAL PREVENTION  
 --FROM HEALTH GRAPEVINE, ADVICE FOR WINE LOVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 As broad waistlines age, health risks found to fall
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The health hazards of obesity appear to lessen with age, an AMA
Journal study has suggested. That's not to say waistlines can
expand without worry.
</P>
<P>
   People who are obese still face an overall greater risk of death
than thinner folks, the study found, even though that risk declines
as people get older.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, while the most obese 18- to 29-year-olds in the
study were at four times the risk of dying compared with their
thinner counterparts, 50- to 74-year-olds with the same so-called
body mass index were at just under twice the risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The excess mortality associated with obesity declined
considerably with age for both sexes in all degrees of obesity,''
the researchers wrote for the the Journal of the American Medical
Association, which was published Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The study followed 6,000 patients who had been referred to a
German obesity clinic for an average of 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier studies have come to varying conclusions about age,
obesity and death. For instance, one report last year, involving
324,000 people, found much higher death rates, across almost all
age groups, for people who are substantially overweight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AIDS drugs may obviate a need for antibiotics
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989, the US Public Health Service has recommended that
some patients infected with the AIDS virus take antibiotics as long
as they live, to prevent a rare but potentially fatal pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   But now, with the advent of drugs known as protease inhibitors,
there may no longer be a need for such a lifelong antibiotic
regimen among some HIV-infected patients, according to a new study.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have shown that it is safe'' to stop the use of antibiotics
to prevent the pneumocystis carinii pneumonia among certain
patients who respond to the new AIDS drugs,'' a team of Swiss
researchers reported in the New England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   In an accompanying editorial, US health officials welcomed the
study as ``gratifying evidence'' of the new drugs' effectiveness in
boosting some patients' immune systems, but added that more
research is needed to identify which patients might still need
antibiotics to prevent the pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   The study also suggests that other recommendations for lifelong
therapies among HIV-infected patients may no longer be needed,
although more research must be done first, according to the
editorial.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For Marfan syndrome, surgical prevention
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For patients with a disorder known as Marfan syndrome, a rupture
of the aorta, the major artery leading from the heart, is a
life-threatening possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Surgery to replace the weakened aorta with a synthetic graft was
devised in 1968, but the question of whether to do the procedure
only after the aorta has ruptured, or as an elective, preventive
measure, has not been settled _ until now, according to a new
study.
</P>
<P>
   The study, by researchers from Johns Hopkins and elsewhere, and
published in the New England Journal of Medicine, finds that
patients have a much better survival rate if they undergo the
surgery early, rather than after the blood vessel has burst.
</P>
<P>
   Within 30 days of surgery, only 1.5 percent of those who had the
elective procedure died, while about 12 percent of those who
underwent emergency surgery did. The study, the largest on Marfan
patients, followed 675 patients for about 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The study ``underscores the need for people to be diagnosed
early with the Marfan syndrome'' so that those with a weakened
aorta can choose to undergo surgery before it ruptures, the
National Marfan Foundation said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Marfan syndrome, a genetic disorder that affects connective
tissue, can often go undiagnosed, since there are few outward
clues. People with Marfan are usually tall and lanky, with long
arms, hands and fingers, but not everyone with those features has
the syndrome. An estimated 200,000 Americans have Marfan and
related connective-tissue disorders.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; From health grapevine, advice for wine lovers
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Debating the merits of Cabernet Sauvignon versus another red
wine?
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking to protect against heart disease, a researcher
based in the Bordeaux region of France says that Cabernet is the
red to choose, because it has high levels of resveratrol, which
increases the so-called good cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jean-Paul Broustet argues his point in the British medical
journal Heart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
