<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7948 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-29 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSGRESSING A SOFTWARE SIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though I now attend a Baptist church, I was brought up
Catholic, and have never forgotten the nuns' stern lessons about
honesty and integrity.
</P>
<P>
   So what would Sister Amanda make of Monday's news from Boston
College and the University of Notre Dame? These two redoubtable
Catholic institutions were among the few places in the US to report
serious damage from the Chernobyl, or CIH, computer virus. And
considering how this virus spreads, it would appear that somebody
has been coveting thy neighbor's software.
</P>
<P>
   CIH makes viruses like the much-touted Melissa look downright
primitive. Much has rightly been made of the virus' ability to wipe
out a computer's hard drive. But I'm more impressed by its unusual
ability to destroy a computer's main circuit board, commonly known
as a motherboard.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, this trick would have been impossible. But the
effort to make computers cheaper has also given them a dismaying
new vulnerability, one I've experienced firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   Ever wonder how your computer knows enough to boot itself up?
When you first start it, the processor inside knows nothing. So how
does it figure out how to start up the operating system and get to
work?
</P>
<P>
   What's needed is a bit of software that's built into the
machine's hardware. This program is called BIOS, or basic
input-output system. It runs at startup, telling the computer how
to boot itself. The BIOS program is small enough to fit onto a
single chip called a ROM, for read-only memory.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that you needed special equipment to alter the
BIOS software on a computer's ROM chip. But these days, most PCs
store the BIOS program on a chip called a flash ROM, a cheaper kind
of chip which can be upgraded by running a program on the PC.
Indeed, advanced computer users often ``flash'' their ROM chips to
add new features to the BIOS, like enabling the computer to work
with larger hard drives.
</P>
<P>
   But flashing must be done exactly right. If you load the wrong
instructions onto the chip, it's toast. You must replace the chip,
or the entire motherboard. Lots of people &UR;  &LR; -- &UR;  &LR; me, for
instance &UR;  &LR; -- &UR;  &LR; have destroyed computers this way. Some manufacturers
guard against this by putting a ``jumper'' on the motherboard that
prevents careless ROM flashing. But many others don't.
</P>
<P>
   You begin to see the fiendish possibilities. A virus that
flashes the ROM would savage your computer so completely that you
wouldn't even be able to boot up with an emergency boot floppy or
CD-ROM. (You do have an emergency boot disk, right? Well, make
one!) Not all Chernobyl-affected computers lost their ROM
chips &UR;  &LR; -- &UR;  &LR; some had their anti-flash feature turned on. But others
wound up with a corrupted hard drive and a dead motherboard.
</P>
<P>
   George Smith, editor of the Crypt Newsletter and a respected
virus expert, could think of only one other virus that attacks ROM
chips, and he told me the other one doesn't work. That makes CIH a
fairly sophisticated menace. But then, unlike Melissa, CIH should
also be quite difficult to catch. That's because it works by hiding
itself inside another piece of software _ a computer game, say.
When you run the game, you also run Chernobyl. If you only run
clean programs, legally obtained, a CIH infection is very unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   This should give you a clue as to why so many college students
got the virus, and why it also swept across Asia. Smith doesn't
believe the claims of a half-million infected computers in China,
India and South Korea. Media hype, he says. I'm not so sure.
</P>
<P>
   During a 1995 visit to Hong Kong, I saw store shelves heaped
high with pirated software, sold by sales clerks who cheerfully
admitted the stuff was illegal. Since then, the Chinese are
supposed to have cracked down. Yet the Business Software Alliance
says that 96 percent of all business software used in China is
pirated. And we're not even talking about games.
</P>
<P>
   Like those who make pirated videos by bringing camcorders into
movie theaters, pirate software dealers are none too concerned with
product quality. If a virus slips into the product, that's just too
bad. But a good little Catholic lad would never fall into such a
trap. He'd only use safe, legal software. Which is why I'm so
saddened by the outbreaks at Boston College and Notre Dame. I'd
recommend two Our Fathers and two Hail Marys, but I figure a dead
computer is penance enough.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(You can send electronic mail to Hiawatha Bray at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
