<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINNER CAN DRY UP OIL IN WOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am refinishing a maple table I built myself, with an
oil-turpentine and Japan dryer finish and would like to varnish it
instead. I have sanded it, but some oil continues to come to the
surface after sanding. The oil comes up in clumps. How can I get it
all off before varnishing?
</P>
<P>
   MARINA THOMPSON, Nahant, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It may be an ongoing thing, because that oil will continue to
come up as long as it is there. There are several ways to keep
after the oil. Try using paint thinner to soften, then a plastic
scraper or steel wool to scrape it off. Then sand again and wait a
while to see if more oil comes up. If it does, repeat until no more
oil comes up. Or, use a paint stripper, preferably a nonmethylene
chloride stripper such as Citristrip, which might pull out the oil
better than paint thinner.
</P>
<P>
   Then apply two or three coats of a semigloss, oil-based
polyurethane varnish. You could use a high-gloss varnish if you
like that look. If the oil does not continue to come up in clumps,
any oil left will be compatible with the polyurethane.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I just moved into a house on Beacon Hill with very squeaky
stairs. How can I silence those squeaks?
</P>
<P>
   TERRY KING, Boston
</P>
<P>
   A. Ah yes, the squeaky-step syndrome. It has been said before, a
thousand times, and it will be said again: Once more into the
breach!
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it is relatively easy to fix. The steps squeak because
the wood has dried out and shrunk, and the tread has loosened from
the riser. The tread moves when stepped on, and the squeak is the
sound of wood rubbing against nails.
</P>
<P>
   The cure is to stop the tread from moving. Here is how: Have
someone stand on the tread, pressing it down on the riser. This
person must stay on the riser during the entire process. Drill a
pilot hole through the tread about 8 inches from one end and into
the riser, and a 45-degree angle. Drill a second hole 2 inches away
from the first, at the opposite angle. Drive a hot-zinc dipped
galvanized finish nail 2 1/2 inches long into each hole,
countersinking them. The pilot holes are smaller in diameter than
the nails. Do the same thing at the other end of the tread, 8
inches in from the end. OK, now, you can release the person who
held the tread down.
</P>
<P>
   The nails will form an ``X'' in the riser, greatly increasing
their holding power.
</P>
<P>
   Fill the countersunk holes and you are home free. You can also
do this through carpeting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I painted my ceramic tile bathroom floor with BIN, then a
latex floor paint, and added a design on some of the tiles. I was
going to finish with varnish as a protector, but it will yellow. Is
there a clear finish that will not yellow?
</P>
<P>
   SUE NOCERA, Westwood, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You could try several coats of a water-based polyurethane
varnish, which would yellow less than other varnishes. But good
luck; I suggest you wear slippers and bare feet in the bathroom;
this finish is likely to be very susceptible to scuffing and
scraping. A small rug would help protect against this.
</P>
<P>
   But, hope springs eternal, and the handyman asks you to write
with a progress report, to let him know how that finish is doing
under wear and tear. Maybe you discovered something the handyman
doesn't know.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have two fireplaces, one on each floor, that are served by
the same flue. The first-floor fireplace makes the darnedest sound
I ever heard, a low, slow, rising moan. It doesn't sound like an
animal, and it occurs on windy days as well as calm ones. Have you
any idea of what it might be?
</P>
<P>
   JOE LEWICKE, Foxborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Simple. It's a poltergeist. It doesn't sound like an animal;
I think it's the wind. On calm days there is still a downdraft of
air going from outside (high pressure) to the house (low pressure).
You could make a hot fire in the fireplace to drive out any
animals, but I doubt if any are there. Then, seal off the firebox
openings of both fireplaces to try to stop the downdraft. If the
moans stop, you have found the cause. If they reduce a bit but
don't stop, close off the top of the chimney temporarily to stop
the downdraft even more.
</P>
<P>
   I think the draft coming down the chimney makes a sound when it
hits where the flue splits. That split may be forming an opening
that causes a sound when the draft goes down. It's a little like
blowing across a Coke bottle to make a toot, or a jug to make a
moan.
</P>
<P>
   Fixing it is another matter. But you at least you've found out
what it is and can live with. Call it Harry James or Wynton
Marsalis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
