<HEADLINE>
WISE WORDS FOR MODERN TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few premillennial proverbs and superstitions:
</P>
<P>
   It's extremely unlucky if even one of your breast implants is
bigger than your head.
</P>
<P>
   ``She who talks about herself in the third person may find no
one is listening'' _ modern proverb.
</P>
<P>
   Caller ID can ward off the Evil Eye or at least cut down on
unwanted phone calls, which amounts to the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Your love life will not prosper if your magazines smell better
than you do.
</P>
<P>
   If you dream of love with Larry King it's a sign you should stop
eating cold pizza just before you go to bed.
</P>
<P>
   It's bad luck to invite 13 people for dinner without engaging a
caterer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hot flash at night, you'll never sleep tight;
</P>
<P>
   ``Hot flash in the morning, loved ones take warning'' _ modern
proverb.
</P>
<P>
   To ward off evil, look both ways before crossing a one-way
street, especially in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing clothing right-side-out usually brings good luck.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sign of future trouble if you need more body work than
your car.
</P>
<P>
   Counteract the malignant force of a ``cute'' answering machine
message by hanging up immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``No good ever came of calling Dr. Laura'' _ modern proverb.
</P>
<P>
   It's bad luck to try to guess a woman's age, especially if she
invites you to try.
</P>
<P>
   If you must speak well of the Red Sox, cross your fingers to
frustrate the Evil Eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carry no credit cards, carry no debt'' _ modern proverb.
</P>
<P>
   It is extremely unlucky to find yourself on a cruise ship with
Kathie Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who's courteous to a ``courtesy caller'' brings
misfortune upon himself.
</P>
<P>
   If you look into a mirror and see no reflection, it's a sign you
will soon be spending a lot of money on new glasses.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bad omen to suddenly find you have your own personal IRS
agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``A stitch in time saves a fortune at the dry cleaner'' _ modern
proverb.
</P>
<P>
   It's an excellent financial omen if your cat concentrates on
destroying only one piece of furniture.
</P>
<P>
   If the invitation reads ``Black Tie Optional,'' it's bad luck to
wear ``optional.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The man who leaves the toilet seat up will find himself in
deep water'' _ modern proverb.
</P>
<P>
   It's unlucky to patronize a restaurant with a sign advertising
``Views of Five States.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoes foretell the future. If you have a closet full of Manolo
Blahniks you're destined to remain deeply in debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``No woman is a heroine to her cat'' _ modern proverb.
</P>
<P>
   It's an extremely bad omen if your cholesterol level is higher
than your bank balance.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune will smile on the woman who dresses up on dress-down
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe everything you see and hear on ``Jerry Springer''
it's a sign you forgot to take your medication.
</P>
<P>
   The number 13 may prove unlucky in the ``12 Items or Fewer''
line.
</P>
<P>
   Don't tempt fate when driving by simultaneously picking your
nose and calling a radio talk show.
</P>
<P>
   It bodes ill for your romantic prospects if you look too much
like your pet.
</P>
<P>
   ``She who laughs last is Martha Stewart'' _ modern proverb.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
