<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7957 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-29 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAST COMPANY, ATLANTIC TAKE TOP HONORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two Boston outposts of Mort Zuckerman's media empire took top
honors Wednesday when the American Society of Magazine Editors
announced the winners of the 1999 National Magazine Awards in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year-old Fast Company _ a business publication for the
new economy, high-tech era _ took the General Excellence Award in
the 100,000 to 400,000 circulation category.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty jazzed,'' noted associate editor Heath Row.
``We're young, and most people say that it takes about five years
for magazines to come into their own.''
</P>
<P>
   The venerable Atlantic Monthly, which received three
nominations, carried home the award in the Essays &AMP; Criticism
category for ``Hymn,'' a July 1998 article by Cambridge writer
Emily Hiestand that describes her Sundays in a black Baptist
Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really thrilled,'' said staff editor Lucie Prinz, noting
that Hiestand's autobiographical essays have been published in a
book called ``Angela the Upside-Down Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   The prestigious magazine awards produced several other notable
winners including Newsweek in the reporting category for its
coverage of the Monical Lewinsky scandal. The top design prize went
to the oversized upstart, ESPN The Magazine, best known for its
hyperkinetic and flashy graphics and Gen-X appeal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For all of the scolding the media have taken for reckless
reporting during the Columbine High School massacre and for
painfully intrusive interviews with the mourners, one crucial issue
has gone unnoticed: racial and demographic stereotyping.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Globe library search of newsclips concerning the
Littleton, Colo., tragedy, there have been nearly 1,400 references
to the so-called ``Trenchcoat Mafia,'' and more than 900 references
to the perpetrators as members of a ``clique'' or ``group,'' but
only 74 references to the killers as members of a ``gang.'' This
raises the question whether the term gang _ with all its ominous
connotations _ would have appeared much more frequently in news
accounts had the high school marauders been poor and dark-skinned
instead of middle class and white.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we have a group of students who all wear the same color.
They all hang together,'' said Greg Freeman, a St. Louis
Post-Dispatch columnist, who often writes on race-related issues.
``I think without a doubt if they weren't middle-class white kids,
the news media would be calling them a gang. . . . There's a little
stereotyping going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Viewers of the Black Entertainment Television call-in show ``BET
Tonight'' recently expressed anger at the apparent double standard
used to describe violent, young criminals. Clearly, that point has
yet to permeate the mainstream media.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is the journalistic equivalent of a family values campaign.
In the most exhaustive analysis yet of the frantic and sloppy
``mixed media culture'' that reared its ugly head in the Monica
Lewinsky scandal, Harvard Nieman Foundation curator Bill Kovach and
Tom Rosenstiel, director of the Project for Excellence in
Journalism, call for deep soul-searching in their book, ``Warp
Speed,'' to be published by The Century Foundation next month. (In
the preface, David Halberstam calls 1998 ``the worst year for
American journalism since I entered the profession forty-four years
ago.'')
</P>
<P>
   While many of the Lewinsky media post-mortems have focused on
technical issues like proper sourcing, ``Warp Speed'' gets much
more basic in its proposed remedies. The first, the authors say,
holds that ``each news organization should do a great deal more to
decide in advance what its news values and policies are.'' The
second is for the organizations to ``make it clear to those who
work there that these are the values in place.'' And then news
outlets must ``make these values clear to the audience. . . . In
effect, a newsroom must make a covenant with the public about what
it stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Kovach and Rosenstiel recognize that the new media
universe will be inhabited by everyone from Interent gossip Matt
Drudge to the august New York Times, they're just trying to get
journalists to choose a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of news organizations beginning to identify
themselves as fish or foul,'' in regard to journalistic standards,
said Kovach. ``I think it really is a democratization of
information and news, and people have to identify which side
they're on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These days, media maven Steve Brill is getting it from both
sides. MSNBC talk host John Hockenberry blasts the Brill's Content
founder in the May/June issue of Mother Jones, calling his view
that ``the media is to operate under the same standard as the court
system in terms of proof beyond a reasonable doubt'' nothing less
than a ``Stalinist concept.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, Brill's Content is being lampooned for being too
squishy by Danny Schechter, the former WBCN-FM ``news dissector''
who is now an executive producer at Globalvision. Schechter's first
issue of the Brill parody ``disContent'' _ mailed to several
thousand media types _ attacks the magazine for ``slick personality
profiles and soft features,'' and complains the magazine is ``under
market pressure to water down its own content.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, I felt that Brill's Content was steering away
from harder-hitting media coverage,'' said Schechter, who claims
the magazine has failed to look at the vital issue of concentrated
ownership of media. ``We meant (disContent) as a friendly nudge to
him.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
