<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LATINOS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPOSURE ON TV SPARSE FOR LATINOS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VANESSA E. JONES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Juan De Los Santos channel surfs from ABC to MTV, but the
39-year-old Dominican rarely finds people who look like him. He
dumped ``NYPD Blue'' when Latino actor Jimmy Smits left the
program. Although there are several Hispanic news reporters in
Boston, the only one De Los Santos can name is Tim Estiloz, a
general assignment reporter for WLVI-Ch. 56. And when De Los Santos
finally catches Hispanics on the local news, the news is inevitably
bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time I see Latin Americans is if they're a gangster
or robbing a store,'' complained De Los Santos. ``The way they show
us is always negative. It's not a lawyer. It's not a judge.''
</P>
<P>
   De Los Santos isn't the only one getting that message.
English-language television often offers a skewed vision of
Latinos. You'll find them speaking heavily accented English on
``Jesse,'' ``Suddenly Susan,'' and the ubiquitous Taco Bell
commercials. Or they're playing detectives and cops on ``Law &AMP;
Order,'' ``Homicide,'' or ``Nash Bridges.''
</P>
<P>
   But often, they're simply invisible. Between 1994 and 1997,
Latino characters accounted for a meager 3 percent of the 7,000
characters shown on prime-time television, a Screen Actors Guild
report reveals.
</P>
<P>
   Television's poor track record hasn't made Latinos tune out and
turn off the tube, however. Recent studies by the Tomas Rivera
Policy Institute, a think tank based in Claremont, Calif., show
that Hispanics watch English and Spanish television more often than
Anglos do.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Latinos aren't the only people of color
underrepresented in TV land. This is a world in which
African-American shows tend to be relegated to the UPN ghetto and
Asian-Americans and Native Americans barely register a blip.
</P>
<P>
   The invisibility of Latinos is particularly noticeable given the
community's explosive growth. In 1995, Boston was home to 71,000
Latinos, or 12 percent of the population, a 15 percent increase
since 1990, according to the Massachusetts Institute for Social and
Economic Research. The Census Bureau expects Latinos to be the
largest minority in the country by 2025, making up 25 percent of
the population.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until very recently the (television) audience was not
disproportionately interested in Latin America or the Caribbean,''
said Louis DeSipio, a political science professor at the University
of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign who authored the two Tomas Rivera
studies, released in the fall and last month. ``What we're
capturing is that changing process.''
</P>
<P>
   And it is changing. Latina actresses Salma Hayek and Rosie Perez
scored televison development deals earlier this year. Two proposed
network programs slated for fall will feature Latino actors in
prominent roles. And just in time for the millennium, cable viewers
may get SiTV, a Latino-themed English version of venerable
Spanish-language cable channels Univision and Telemundo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
``I watch a lot of TV . . . There's nothing else I have to do. I'm
still looking for a job. '' &QL; 
REINA AVILLAN MARTINEZ &QL; 
15, Roslindale &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than 99 percent of Hispanics own televisions, according to
the Tomas Rivera reports, which surveyed 1,000 Latinos in
California, Florida, Texas, New York, and Illinois. Most viewers
gaze at those sets more than four hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a population that has a lower income,'' DeSipio said.
``They can't take advantage of as many recreational opportunities
outside the house so they take advantage of free . . .
entertainment within the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics who are bilingual keep their eyes on the small screen
longer, according to the report. Latinos not only catch their
favorite television shows in English, they look at their favorite
ones in Spanish as well.
</P>
<P>
   De Los Santos, whose three televisions serve his 9-year-old son,
11-year-old daughter, his wife and her father, mainly turns on the
tube on weekends. He'll catch Spanish-language specials about his
home country, the Dominican Republic. Then he may switch to shows
on the History and Sci-Fi channels.
</P>
<P>
   De Los Santos spends his weekday tube time flipping between
Spanish- and English-language news. That's not unusual. About 92
percent of Latinos in the Tomas Rivera study watched the news in
both languages.
</P>
<P>
   Local news provides information about the immediate community.
Spanish news fills in the gaps because ``American news does not
tell us what's going on in our countries,'' said De Los Santos.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Barrientos, 50, who is from Guatemala and now lives in
Lynn, Mass., agreed. ``When they have something about Latin
American countries it's because it's the coverage of the President.
Other than that they don't show us anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Boston Latinos also complain about how often local news
shows Hispanics in handcuffs. About 60 percent of the people
surveyed by Tomas Rivera thought American news depicted Hispanic
men as undocumented aliens or criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't hear that (complaint) uniquely from the Latino
community,'' said Paul La Camera, general manager at WCVB-Ch. 5,
the longtime home of Latino reporters Jorge Quiroga and Amalia
Barreda, addressing the latter charge. ``We ask that they look upon
us as a whole. Hopefully, we provide a balanced positive picture of
our entire community.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Tomas Rivera study respondents said community coverage
improved when a television news station hired a Hispanic anchor or
reporter, Boston Latinos disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have channels that have Latinos anchoring but they don't
care about the community,'' said Regla Gonzalez, 50, vice president
of the northeast region of the League of United Latin American
Citizens (LULAC), the Hispanic version of the NAACP. The Cuban, who
now lives in Boston, is so offended by the stereotypes on local
news that at times she switches to CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Barrientos, who has two televisions in the home she shares with
her son and boyfriend, tries to avoid the news altogether. ``The
only reason I watch (it) is to see whether the weather tomorrow is
going to be good or bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The disaffection filters down to American sitcoms. Reina Avillan
Martinez, 15, dedicates 25 hours a week to cartoons, ``The
X-Files,'' and teen shows on the WB.
</P>
<P>
   But Martinez knows that American television represents Latinos
about as authentically as the accent Luis sports on ``Suddenly
Susan.'' Most of the Latinos she spots on television play plumbers
or other minor characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they put a Hispanic on TV they're never Dominicans or
Puerto Ricans, they're mostly from Argentina, Chile,'' said
Martinez, a non-Spanish-speaking Puerto Rican who lives in
Roslindale with her mother and younger sister.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Even on Dawson's Creek, when do you see anyone except the
Caucasian race? I've never seen an African-American. I've never
seen Hispanics. I've never seen Chinese. Why? ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ANNABELLE GUERRA &QL; 
15, Boston &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than 36 percent of the people polled by Tomas Rivera said
that television in English shows Hispanics negatively. Americans
who learn about Latinos on TV often accept these stereotypes as the
truth, said Gonzalez, ``because they have no idea about our
culture, our upbringing, our ways of living.''
</P>
<P>
   But negative images and invisibility can also have a devastating
effect on young people's self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
