<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-WILD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILD CREATURES, AND A FEW TAME, POPULATE OUR SUBURBAN EDEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH S. FOSTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A fat, black bunny ran around my yard for the third day. When I
tapped the window, he came to it and looked at me and waited. He
was not wild because ordinary cottontails are gray and never come
to a human. He was someone's Easter bunny who was turned out into
the wild to die.
</P>
<P>
   House pets cannot survive when let loose in the wild because it
is a cold, cruel place, where everyone eventually eats everyone
else. Pets, unschooled in the law of the jungle, die of starvation.
Abandoned white bunnies and guinea pigs are buried in our animal
graveyard and we've had kittens turn up crying in our garage.
</P>
<P>
   Actually our yard is already filled with all kinds of wild
animals. Last year I caught a red fox in the trap set for the
rotten woodchuck next to her hole. We've watched a pair of foxes
jaunt through the yard off and on for several years, so, of course,
we let him go.
</P>
<P>
   The pheasants rarely visit now. They used to nest outside the
bedroom window in a large, impenetrable bramble patch. But, as the
forest has grown, blocking the sun, and the swamp has spread, the
brambles have receded and no safe nesting habitat exists for them
anymore. They also need lots of brush at the woodland's edge to
hide in as they constantly search for food.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, a coyote was caught in Boston's South End. No
surprise. They are all over. So are lots of other critters, though
you may not see them all. Raccoons, rats, mice, feral cats, skunks,
muskrats, Canada geese, woodchucks, moles and voles. A little
farther out of the city, add wild turkeys, foxes, deer and beaver.
(Beaver were hunted out of existence in Massachusetts by the time
of the American Revolution. A few came back in the 1920s, and, by
1998, there were thousands.
</P>
<P>
   There is a commonly accepted myth that there are so many animals
in city and suburbs because human beings are encroaching on their
forest habitat. This is absolutely wrong. What is happening is that
suburbia is a wild-animal Eden.
</P>
<P>
   Wild animals are not in the suburbs because we have taken away
their habitat. They are there because suburbia is safer and has
more food than the forest. We have succulent shrubs and tasty
pansies, vegetables, green lawns with fat grubs and, best of all,
lots of garbage.
</P>
<P>
   The simple scientific fact is that animal populations are
habitat-driven. Where there is food, they will follow. Where there
is a lot of food, their populations will multiply until they become
too numerous and outgrow their food supply. Then they begin to die
of disease and starvation.
</P>
<P>
   In city and suburb, animals have lots of food. They eat and
multiply. (Before the rabies epidemic, the population of raccoons
in cities was estimated at up to 500 per square mile.)
</P>
<P>
   Loving and humanizing our wild animals is in fashion these days.
It's called anthropomorphism. CNN almost always ends its newscasts
with an animal story because animals sell, and can sell anything,
particularly on TV.
</P>
<P>
   But back to my black bunny and my fox and the rotten woodchuck
who eats everything nice.
</P>
<P>
   The black bunny will probably be run over or eaten by the fox.
My battle with the woodchuck will go on forever. Meanwhile, the
skunks and raccoons are digging up the little bulbs of my white
flowered spring beauty (Claytonia), which the Indians loved to eat,
too.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the bottom line? Animal populations have grown
exponentially this century. Because they are humanized, as well as
protected by multiple wildlife laws, we have to learn to live with
them and their depredations.
</P>
<P>
   What can we do?
</P>
<P>
   1. Fence or trap problem animals. Fencing is more permanent.
</P>
<P>
   2. Frightening devices rarely work, so don't waste your money.
</P>
<P>
   3. Repellents may help for a short while. You can spray nibbled
tulips, pansies and perennials with Ropel, a bitter-tasting
fungicide. It may cause some browning on soft new leaves, and don't
breathe its mist.
</P>
<P>
   4. Put in poisonous plants that you hope the animals won't eat.
</P>
<P>
   5. And sometimes just throw your hands up and rail at the sky.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Ruth S. Foster has been a landscape consultant for many years.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
