<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7964 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-SENIORS-DRUGS-BOS &LR;      04-29 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-SENIORS-DRUGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVOCATES SAY ELDERLY DRUG PLAN INCOMPLETE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Dr. Mario Motta is seeing more patients these days
with worsening heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at their swollen legs and see them huffing and puffing
and I ask, `Are you taking your meds?' '' said the Salem
cardiologist. ``They say, `Well, I take my pills every other day.'
They don't volunteer that they can't afford their medicine, but
that's what is happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Motta's story is far from unusual. The Massachusetts Medical
Society reports dozens of recent calls from doctors worried about
patients who can't afford to fill their prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physicians are very concerned about patients who skip doses or
take a quarter-pill, or share their medications with a spouse or
friend,'' said Dr. Marylou Buyse, the Medical Society president.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile on Beacon Hill, a legislative push to address the
problem noticeably lost steam this week.
</P>
<P>
   House leaders unveiled a Senior Pharmacy proposal that
disappointed elders and their advocates for what it doesn't cover,
such as individuals with heavy drug needs. ``It's an inadequate
response to a grave problem,'' said Geoff Wilkinson of the
Massachusetts Senior Action Council.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis was precipitated in January, when 75,000
Massachusetts elderly and disabled people abruptly lost unlimited
drug coverage through their HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   If elders are disheartened, advocates for the disabled are near
despair. The House proposal does nothing at all for people with
disabilities _ in violation of a recent private pledge from some
House leaders to include them, according to advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic that legislators think more about the Patriots
than they do about elderly and disabled people,'' said Cynthia
Homer, a part-time radiology technician in North Andover whose
43-year-old husband Robert suffers from multiple disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Homer's annual prescription drug bill runs $8,216, but
his quarterly Fallon Plan coverage limit is $175.
</P>
<P>
   Homer discovered Wednesday that his blood pressure has shot up
to 158 over 110, compared to 130 over 80 a week ago, because he has
run out of some pills and is carefully rationing the rest. He'll
run out of insulin within a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in a pickle, to say the least,'' Homer said. ``I'm
probably within about three weeks of ending up in the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   House leaders, intent on avoiding any proposal that involves new
spending, defend their $30 million Senior Pharmacy proposal as a
good first step toward a more comprehensive solution in a year or
two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this does a very good job of giving relief for the
present,'' said Harriette L. Chandler, a Worcester Democrat who is
House cochairwoman of the Legislature's Joint Health Care
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal does not widen eligibility for the Senior Pharmacy
program to elders with incomes twice the federal poverty level
($16,488), as some had hoped, but leaves it at 150 percent of the
poverty standard ($12,360). It increases the annual drug benefit,
but only from $750 to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fundamentally inadequate response to the problem,''
said Becky Derby of Health Care for All, a consumer advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal does permit elders with limited drug coverage to
take advantage of the $1,000 benefit if their incomes are low
enough or their drug needs are hefty enough.
</P>
<P>
   The plan's primary innovation is to offer the $1,000 benefit to
elders with incomes up to $32,960 ($57,512 for couples) if they can
demonstrate that their prescription drug bills in the previous year
amounted to more than 5 percent of their gross income.
</P>
<P>
   This provision was designed to address the coverage vacuum left
when Massachusetts Senior Plan HMOs stopped offering unlimited
prescription drug coverage in January after a federal court
invalidated a state law requiring them to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler acknowledged that the new proposal does not cover all
elders' drug needs, but she asserted that it would help take care
of 78 percent of the 75,000 elders who lost unlimited HMO coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The HMOs tell us that 78 percent of seniors had drug costs
below $1,500 a year,'' Chandler said. ``If you take that as a
given, we should be able to reach approximately 78 percent, between
this program and the coverage that HMOs still offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics challenged that assumption, but said if it were true, it
would still leave 16,500 elders (22 percent) with higher drug bills
who formerly had unlimited HMO drug coverage. Among the entire
Massachusetts population over age 65, there may be 180,000 people
with drug needs greater than $1,500 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My 83-year-old dad would qualify for the new Senior Pharmacy
benefits, but $1,000 is nothing,'' said Alan Kirby of New Bedford.
``He has like $900 in out-of-pocket drug expenses a month. He has
emphysema. He'll die before anything comes to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking people with catastrophic drug needs and putting them
into the Senior Pharmacy program with a $1,000 benefit is kind of
like spitting into the ocean,'' added Stephen J. D'Amato, a
Cambridge attorney who has been trying to design short-term and
long-term solutions for the drug coverage problem.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato had crafted a proposal, put forward by consumer groups
but rejected by House leaders, to restore unlimited drug coverage.
He said the plan would require beneficiaries to pay a monthly
premium of $80 and about $25 million in state subsidy for the
remainder of this year.
</P>
<P>
   The short-term plan would be replaced by a scheme designed to
enroll healthy elders to offset the costs of sicker enrollees.
</P>
<P>
   House leaders acknowledge their proposal is only a first step.
``Our goal is to see this short-term remedy develop . . . into a
long-term solution that benefits all seniors who need assistance,''
House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran (D-Mattapan) said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
