<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-PATRIOTS-FINNERAN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH STAND BY FINNERAN MIGHT PAY OFF IF DEAL IS OK'D 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEG VAILLANCOURT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- A few days ago, many football fans viewed House
Speaker Thomas M. Finneran as the man who forced the New England
Patriots into Connecticut's arms, while opponents of using public
money to lure sports teams praised his prudency.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Finneran might be able to enjoy the best of both worlds:
a chance to bask in the glory of putting together a package many
hope will keep the team at home, but without looking as if he caved
on any of his tight fiscal principles.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt about it,'' said one business leader
involved in the talks that led to the stadium accord. ``Others may
not like to hear it, but Finneran was driving the bus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were risks,'' Finneran said of his demanding
negotiations with Senate President Thomas F. Birmingham, Governor
Paul Cellucci, business leaders, and National Football League
officials. ``And in the end, we got an agreement everyone could
live with, including, I hope, the team. But we did not pay tribute
or ransom, and I think that might be a lesson for other states.''
</P>
<P>
   Finneran noted that no state funds would be used to buy land for
the Patriots or to help build the stadium. He also noted that the
final package aimed at keeping the Patriots in Massachusetts
requires them to repay the state for some of the infrastructure
improvements for a new Foxborough stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It was a demand business leaders and NFL officials fought,
because infrastructure is considered the responsibility of
government. And during the talks, Finneran compromised and agreed
to lower the price of the demand, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end his principle stood: If the Patriots accept
Massachusetts' offer, they will pay the state up to $1 million a
year to help pay for infrastructure improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a recognition that for the league, economics are
paramount, and that means TV revenues in this market,'' Finneran
said. ``But there is no burden on any taxpayer in any jurisdiction,
especially in Massachusetts, to step to the plate when in fact
there are abundant revenues generated by this franchise and this
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always thought our role was appropriately limited to
infrastructure. And this agreement reflects that precisely,''
Finneran said.
</P>
<P>
   The final agreement increases the amount of state funding of
infrastructure by up to $20 million from proposals offered last
year in the House and the Senate. The additional funds would be
spent on roadwork, sewer, water, and utility lines that were not
anticipated under Finneran's previous proposal, which would have
renovated Foxboro Stadium rather than build a new one. Because the
original estimates were developed more than 18 months ago, and were
called conservative, lawmakers said inflation and additional
requirements helped raise the price tag for the state's investment.
</P>
<P>
   Some also credit Finneran's intransigence _ and willingness to
play brinksmanship and possibly lose the team _ with encouraging
the NFL to change its rules and allow low-interest loans to owners
building stadiums in the top six media markets. Although some NFL
officials deny it, others note that the restriction specifically
includes the Boston area, which is ranked the sixth largest media
market in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finneran's insistence that no public money go into the stadium
was clearly a force to be reckoned with,'' said advertising
executive Jack Connors, a leader of the drive to keep the Patriots
in Massachusetts. ``And from one perspective, it could be viewed
that Finneran brought the NFL to its knees. But in the end, working
with the governor and Senate president, I think we wound up with an
agreement that can keep the Patriots in Foxborough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
