<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7971 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-29 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOP'S LEADERSHIP GAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wednesday the Republican National Committee held a fund-raiser
in Washington that took in $14 million. It was the largest such
event (in dollar terms) in the nation's history. The money raised
will be used to help the GOP maintain control of Congress in the
year 2000 elections. The question is, for what purpose?
</P>
<P>
   What benefit, other than some special favors for special
interests, is derived from a Republican-controlled Congress?
</P>
<P>
   The answer Republicans offer is telling: A Democratic-controlled
Congress would be worse. That's almost certainly true, but it's
both beside the point and a dysfunctional electoral strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The point of being in charge, after all, is to do something. The
Republican congressional leadership is afraid of doing anything
that might cause its members to have to stand up and be counted on
tough issues.
</P>
<P>
   Having nearly lost control of Congress in the 1998 elections for
this very reason, the GOP leadership team is now adopting the same
stance in preparation for the 2000 elections. They're not just
fighting the last war. They're repeating it.
</P>
<P>
   Consider four issues of great importance to the electorate:
Medicare, Social Security, war in Yugoslavia, and cultural
violence. On all of them, the GOP congressional leadership has
either abjectly surrendered or maintained the political equivalent
of strict radio silence.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicare cop-out was appalling. In 1998, President Clinton
appointed Senator John Breaux, Democrat of Louisiana, to head up a
bipartisan commission on Medicare reform. Breaux took the work
seriously and developed a plan that was endorsed by every
Republican member of the commission, the Democratic Leadership
Conference, and Senator Bob Kerrey of Nebraska. Kerrey's previous
work on entitlement reform lent his endorsement special weight.
</P>
<P>
   There was general agreement that the Breaux Commission report
provided a good framework within which to negotiate actual,
passable legislation. President Clinton, though, had other ideas.
Panicked by the notion that his party might lose one of its most
reliable ``wedge'' issues to bipartisan consensus, he disowned the
commission's report even before it was released.
</P>
<P>
   This presented the GOP congressional leadership with a rare
opportunity to ride to Medicare's rescue. The commission report
offered strong political cover, and both Breaux and Kerrey were
ready to make a deal. Instead, the GOP congressional leaders
disowned the issue almost as quickly as Clinton did, saying
(pathetically) they feared it would be used against them in the
2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Bad as the Medicare cop-out was, it paled in comparison to the
Republican leadership's cave-in on Social Security Reform.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security is an issue that looms larger with each
election, as the baby boom nears retirement age. Everyone knows
that the system will go bust unless something is done to fix it.
The sooner reform is enacted into law, the less painful the
necessary adjustments will be. And real reform should and will
require some measure of privatization, which would allow people to
exercise greater control over their own retirement planning.
</P>
<P>
   If ever there was an issue that ``fit'' responsible Republican
leadership, this was it. Too bad. Sunday, Senate majority leader
Trent Lott announced that there would be no Social Security reform
package in 1999 or 2000. GOP polling had vetoed the idea as both
too risky and too difficult. For Republicans who have been critical
of Clinton's poll-driven presidency, this was a grim reminder that
their congressional leadership was hardly any different.
</P>
<P>
   Polling is also driving the GOP leadership's response to the war
in Yugoslavia. Last June, Lott was all over the White House,
demanding that something be done about the humanitarian crisis in
Kosovo. Since the onset of NATO's aerial attacks, however, both
Lott and House Speaker Dennis Hastert have been struck dumb. The
silence of the GOP leadership is based on polling that suggests
that if things go badly in Kosovo, Clinton (and Gore) will be
blamed. Thus it is the unstated hope of the GOP leadership that
Kosovo end in disaster. That's politics at its worst.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, everyone agrees that something must be done about
cultural violence. Here the Republican leadership is afraid of
angering the National Rifle Association, even though roughly
three-quarters of the country agrees with the proposition that gun
ownership should require registration and licensing.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't seem like much to concede, if Republicans have any
real interest in addressing the culture of media violence. But the
truth is that the GOP leadership would like Littleton to fade away
from public consciousness so business as usual can continue.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of GOP leadership on these four critical issues augurs
ill for the coming congressional campaigns. Lacking anything
serious or substantial to say, Republicans will be left to argue
that Democrats would only be worse. That message didn't work in
1998 and nearly cost the GOP its majority status. It won't work in
2000 either.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 1358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
