<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7972 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAR-WARS-HNS &LR;      04-29 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAR-WARS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOONLIGHTING MUSICIAN FLIRTS WITH DREAM IN `STAR WARS' NOISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CRAIG MARINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLEASANT HILL, Calif. _ A long time ago in a galaxy far, far
away lived a man with a dream. Actually, he lives in Pleasant Hill
on the east side of the San Francisco Bay and the man is real.
</P>
<P>
   But he's not any ordinary man, he's Dan Killoran, the United
Parcel Service guy.
</P>
<P>
   And more than a year ago, he came up with an idea crazy enough
to get most people locked away on one of the moons of Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   Killoran, 29, a musician when he's not donning the distinctive
brown suit and delivering packages, decided that he was going to
write a song celebrating ``Star Wars,'' and try to get it done in
time for the mega-grand premiere of the latest epoch from George
Lucas, ``Star Wars Episode One: The Phantom Menace,'' which already
has people camping out in Los Angeles for the May 19 release.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds simple enough, but Killoran's method has never been used
before _ according to Killoran.
</P>
<P>
   He got the first ``Star Wars'' movie _ even if the new one is a
prequel or whatever _ and ran it from a VCR into his keyboard and
then into his computer, breaking down every sound effect in the
film into a separate sound element, or sample.
</P>
<P>
   Literally thousands of hours and 314 samples later (one saber
duel that lasted 90 seconds on film took two days and 35 samples to
deconstruct) and Killoran has a finished product. No, he didn't use
any actual music from the film, that would have been cheating.
</P>
<P>
   He has one song, 4 1/2 minutes long. That's it. And if you're
thinking he wants to get it to a big record company and try to cash
in big on the ``Star Wars'' craze, you're wrong. He just wants to
get his only CD to George Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not nuts,'' Killoran insisted, sitting in his modest condo
cramped full of computer monitors, musical instruments and
keyboards. ``I'm not even a `Star Wars' nut _ not as much as a lot
of people, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Killoran has hair nearly down to his waist and a computer geek's
understanding of the Musical Instrument Digital Interface _ or MIDI
_ computer musical program that he used to construct his song. Once
he had the film broken down into sound bites, his work was only
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to listen to all of what I had and categorize them as
either percussion, tone or vocals,'' he explained with remarkable
patience, which probably isn't surprising. ``And then if something
was percussion, for instance, I had to decide if it sounded more
like a snare drum, or a tom-tom or a bass. Then I had to group the
sounds together, so I knew what I had to work with.''
</P>
<P>
   For a guy who claims not to be a ``Star Wars'' freak, Killoran
has a remarkable knowledge of this particular movie. He'll play one
of his samples, which sounds like nothing in particular to the
uninitiated ear except for maybe the sound of a spoon hitting a
soup pan, and declare that this is the part where C3PO fell over on
his back. Which to him sounds like a snare drum, which he can then
loop through the record and create part of an ongoing drum beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do admit that when I was just about finished, I went over to
my friend's house and they had one of those `Star Wars' Trivial
Pursuit Games,'' he said. ``And I thought I was just going to kick
a__. I mean, I was ready to play for big money, that's how
confident I was.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you know what? I don't think I got a single question I
could answer. Those people just ate me up,'' he laughed.
</P>
<P>
   But what motivated Killoran?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do something no one had ever done before,'' he
said. ``And as far as I know, no one had ever done this before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I chose `Star Wars' because I really liked it as a kid and
because when it came out it just totally blew everything else
away,'' Killoran continued. ``No one had ever seen anything like it
and I figured that would be a perfect movie to use to try this new
idea I had.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Killoran, a former disc jockey, has had friends in the radio
business who have begged him to let them play his song on the
radio. And truth be told, it has enough of a catchy beat and
interesting loops and movie dialogue to likely go toward the top of
the dance charts. But Killoran is nobody's fool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know how many lawyers George Lucas must have?,'' he
laughed, eyes agog. ``The copyright laws would just kill me, I'd
never own another computer or keyboard again. I'd be toast.''
</P>
<P>
   But Killoran does hope that somehow, somewhere, he'll be able to
present Lucas with his labor of love. and after that, who knows?
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong, I like my job at UPS, but imagine if I
could get a job doing songs like this for other movies? Imagine
getting paid for doing something I love.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
