 Thursday, April 29, 1999    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following
stories for Friday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call
Susie McBee or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag
appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ANTHRAX-VACCINE-SAFETY (Washington) _ The government's General
Accounting Office says it cannot determine the safety or
effectiveness of the controversial anthrax vaccine being
administered to U.S. armed forces. The GAO, Congress' main
investigative arm, says the vaccine hasn't been studied enough to
make such a determination. But the Food and Drug Administration,
which licenses the vaccine, and the Pentagon say the vaccine is
safe, effective and necessary to protect U.S. forces against the
deadly anthrax disease. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The deplorable state of our national
culture is getting most of the blame for the Littleton, Colo., high
school massacre, but the politicians don't agree on which culture
is at fault. President Clinton singles out the hunting and
sport-shooting culture for insisting on easy gun availability. But
Republican congressional leaders look elsewhere, to the
violence-prone video and movie industries. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ADOPTION-KOSOVO (Washington) _ The State Department and adoption
agencies nationwide have been inundated with calls from people
wanting to adopt refugee children from Kosovo. But Washington and
the agencies agree that with family reunification still possible
for the lost or abandoned children, adoption now is not feasible.
By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
</TEXT>
