<HEADER>
A7977 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALKANS-TEACH-IN-ART-     04-29 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALKANS-TEACH-IN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACH-IN EXAMINES BALKAN DILEMMA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The teach-in, that seething caldron of antiwar
sentiment during the Vietnam years, is back. Only this time it's
``agenda-free.''
</P>
<P>
   The University of Massachusetts at Boston Wednesday staged a
campuswide teach-in on the Kosovo war, echoing the Vietnam protests
of yore. During the '60s, teach-ins were full of venom and passion,
all-night rhetorical marathons crammed with students and faculty
honing their antiwar stances to knife edges.
</P>
<P>
   But judging by the responses of students Wednesday, the Kosovo
war is murkier and more abstract than Vietnam ever was, and US
involvement is far more difficult to condemn.
</P>
<P>
   The roughly 200 students and faculty members who filled the
Herbert Lipke Auditorium Wednesday were not, for the most part,
there to oppose US military action in Kosovo. Nor were they looking
for holes in the official version of events there. They were still
deciding on their positions, searching for guidance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Learn about Kosovo in an agenda-free atmosphere,'' proclaimed
the posters for the teach-in.
</P>
<P>
   According to organizers, there's a lot more tolerance and
empathy now than there was in the Age of Aquarius.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to be as objective as possible,'' said UMass
student Amy George, a member of the philosophy club who helped
organize the event.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the students weren't born until well after the last
soldier was drafted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The term `teach-in' might be a good draw for the professors,
but I don't know if it means anything to students these days,''
said senior Daniel Rausch. ``That's why we put the word
`informational' before it.''
</P>
<P>
   Philosophy professor Nelson Lande, who chaired the event, was at
a Vietnam teach-in at the University of Michigan during the '60s.
He described himself as a ``tentative hawk'' on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Though many observers have drawn comparisons between Kosovo and
Vietnam, arguing that a lack of clarity of US aims, its heavy
reliance on a bombing campaign, and the absence of a clear exit
strategy all mimic the early stages of Vietnam, Lande said the
parallels have been overstated.
</P>
<P>
   ``During Vietnam, it didn't matter which side you were on; you
were quite confident you knew who the good guys were and who the
bad guys were,'' he said. ``In Kosovo, it's not entirely clear in
which direction the moral compass is pointing.''
</P>
<P>
   There were few unconflicted doves among the students who
attended Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of weeks ago, I thought we should be in there
fighting, but now I'm not so sure,'' said George. ``What gives us
the right? Then again, it's not right to tear people from their
homeland because of religous discrepancies. That's wrong, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think NATO is doing enough,'' added Hassan Mohamud, a
sophomore. ``They're bombing cities and destroying infrastructure,
but they're not engaging with the army.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The US forces should be there in some capacity,'' said student
Louis Spagnola, 40. ``Slobodan Milosevic can't just do (whatever he
wants). Something has to be done. Bribe him, bomb him, do whatever
you've got to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite his certainty that Milosevic should be brought to
justice, Spagnola said he is convinced the official version of
events in Kosovo is not complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted a different perspective,'' he said. ``I wanted to
hear it from people who had nothing to hide. There's a lot of
spin-doctor propaganda on the television.''
</P>
<P>
   There were other echoes of the original teach-ins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I don't accept the stated premise that the purpose
of this war is to do something about the Kosovo refugees,'' said
Paul Atwood, 52, a professor in the American studies department,
and part of the William Joiner Center for the Study of War and
Social Consequences. ``That's just a smokescreen.''
</P>
<P>
   If the US were serious about aiding refugees, they would have
done more for the Kurds, or the East Timorese, Atwood argued.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood stood outside the auditorium, handing out fliers for a
talk on Kosovo next week by Noam Chomsky, the legendary leftist
cultural critic who made his name during the Vietnam era.
</P>
<P>
   He said he expected the students, so measured now, to grow
angrier and more cynical soon enough. They aren't yet radicalized
because, in the absence of US deaths, and the draft, the war in
Kosovo hasn't really touched them yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paying a price in Vietnam made people look with more open eyes
at what really was the root of the problem,'' he said. ``As long as
we're not paying a price right now, people can cling to their
delusions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
