<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7978 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEASONS-review-LADN     04-29 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEASONS-review-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUTIFUL `THREE SEASONS' A FIRST FOR DIRECTOR, VIETNAM 
OUR RATING: 3 STARS
</HEADLINE>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Three Seasons'' arrives with at least three
impressive pedigrees. It's the first film that's ever won both the
top jury prize and the audience prize at the Sundance Film
Festival. It's the first American production filmed in Vietnam (and
in, mostly, Vietnamese). And it's a lyrically beautiful, first
feature effort from its 26-year-old, Saigon-born, Sunnyvale-raised
writer-director, Tony Bui.
</P>
<P>
   All pretty impressive, as are Bui's unmistakable talents for
handling actors (both Vietnamese and American) and illuminating
telling cultural insights. The film is set in and around
contemporary Ho Chi Minh City (formerly Saigon), a place coming to
bustling commercial life after decades of war and communist
oppression but, even in revival, rapidly losing its traditions. Bui
has a good grasp of how those tensions affect the lives of those
who are not necessarily a part of them but caught up in them just
the same.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, little that's original in the film's
characterizations and story lines. Bui is going for the kind of
profound simplicity that has been the hallmark of great Asian
filmmakers, from Japan's Yasujiro Ozu to China's Zhang Yimou, but
his narrative skills have yet to mature to a point where he can get
very far beyond the merely obvious. ``Three Seasons'' unfolds with
a certain delicacy and conviction that prevents it from ever
seeming egregiously trite. But it never adds up to much that
resonates distinctively.
</P>
<P>
   Four story lines unfold here, intersecting tangentially as they
pad deliberately along. The most interesting one involves a young
woman from the provinces, Kien An (Nguyen Ngoc Hiep), who comes to
work at the lakeside estate of a mysterious, reclusive master,
Teacher Dao (Tran Manh Cuong). Her job is to pick lotus flowers
from the muddy water, then sell them in the nearby city. But she
soon learns the truth about her depressed boss and offers him an
indispensable service.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the former Saigon, Hai (Don Duong) barely ekes out
a living driving a cyclo, a kind of bicycle-powered rickshaw. He
becomes obsessed with the impudent prostitute Lan (Zoe Bui, no
relation to the director) he pedals to and from jobs in the fancy,
modern hotels that may as well be part of another dimension. In
order to afford a night with his beloved, Hai enters a cyclo race,
which may be one of the slowest races ever filmed but nevertheless
looks pretty grueling.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Keitel's ex-GI also wanders around the city, searching
for the daughter he left behind at the end of the war. Young Nguyen
Huu Duoc completes the picture as Woody, one of those plucky
urchins that seem to be a required commodity in every foreign film
these days. The orphan boy spends most of the movie searching,
``Bicycle Thief''-like, for a stolen briefcase of cheap trinkets
that represents his only hope of survival.
</P>
<P>
   All of these stories go in the sentimental directions you'd
expect. But there are occasional, fascinating side trips into
ethno-cultural territory. I have no idea what the seemingly painful
thing is that Hai does to Lan's back, but she likes it, and it
makes for one hypnotically sensual scene.
</P>
<P>
   Generally though, these are pretty elementary tales of rescue,
reconciliation and redemption. All done up, however, with a visual
gorgeousness that somehow meshes with a realistic depiction of
serious poverty. The director of photography is Lisa Rinzler, and
as she demonstrated with the American inner-city dramas ``Menace II
Society'' and ``Dead Presidents,'' she can effectively find formal
beauty anywhere, in a tumbledown railroad shack or an idyllic grove
of crimson-leafed trees.
</P>
<P>
   She often helps ``Three Seasons'' rise above the murk of
predictability and at least look like a flowering lotus ... like
something sublime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
