<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7986 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROS-HOWTHEYLIVE29-CO     04-29 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROS-HOWTHEYLIVE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Interior designer Bill Stewart assembles a shrine to postwar
design in his modernist Atlanta house
 &HT;    By Danny Flanders Photos by Jean Shifrin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bill Stewart is like a kid on Christmas morning,
darting about showing visitors his favorite toys.
</P>
<P>
   Clad in his trademark black high-top sneakers, the Atlanta
interior designer cranks up one of his 100 robots, and his eyes
twinkle with a nostalgic fascination for all things '50s. For
Stewart, the mechanized gadgets represent an innocent age, when
artists, designers and inventors threw convention to the wind and
experimented with ideas that foreshadowed the future.
</P>
<P>
   They were ideas ahead of their time, like the 1960s Pulsar
watches he collects. ``There's something quirky about having a
calculator on your wrist _ it's so James Bond,'' Stewart says,
pointing to one of his favorites timepieces. ``Things like this
force you to look back at how far we've come.''
</P>
<P>
   For Stewart, collecting furnishings designed in the middle of
the 20th century is more than a hobby; his passion for plucking the
best of the postwar period is a lifestyle _ one for which he's
found a perfect backdrop in his 1951 modernist house in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   There Stewart is free to experiment with a style that is a time
warp removed from the traditional homes he designs for clients. ``I
choose to live this lifestyle because none of my clients do,'' says
the 44-year-old designer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the house isn't an attempt to re-create the past. It's a
shrine for emphasizing its highlights at a time when, as a new
century nears, retro influences are stronger than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a reproduction of a home in the '50s. This is my
interpretation, a '90s fantasy, of another period,'' the designer
says of his Tuxedo Park home, believed to be the area's first
modern house. ``The diagnosis is the same; the treatment is what's
different.''
</P>
<P>
   But as serious as he is about his collection _ he spent years
researching modern design and talking to antiques dealers before
selecting pieces that were desirable and affordable _ Stewart knows
how to have fun with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tend to take design so seriously,'' he says, holding up
kitschy condiment jars with Smiley Fruit heads in his kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   A Florida native, Stewart first fell in love with design as a
teenager while attending boarding school in Rome (Ga.). ``We took
field indows cast light on this classic home considered avant-garde
in its day, the kind inspired by legendary architect Frank Lloyd
Wright, who designed homes to blend with their surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very Californian in that it was meant to be enjoyed
both inside and out. The pool was 10 feet from the house, it had a
landscaped garden lit at night and sliding glass doors with
screens,'' Stewart says. ``I suddenly realized this wasn't about
buying a house but buying a lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart made no exterior changes to the house, other than adding
crab orchard stone walkways to match the back yard's retaining
walls.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, his only renovations were to the kitchen and bathrooms,
where Stewart maintained the '50s look with multicolored tile
patterns he designed himself. The pastel shades of vintage china
from the '30s and '40s in green, salmon and yellow formed his
inspiration for wall colors.
</P>
<P>
   Then the fun began. The designer set out to create an interior
which, while not cozy with overstuffed sofas and chairs, is
comfortable for lounging.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart relishes the art of mixing old and new 20th century _
chairs by Frank Lloyd Wright, and Charles and Ray Eames, a
bookshelf and dining room furniture by Jean Prouve, china by
Russell Wright and lamps by Serge Mouille, with a 1992 chaise by
Ralph Lauren thrown in to keep things interesting.
</P>
<P>
   The pieces are used judiciously throughout the house. ``My
biggest fear is that I will want to fill the house with the
collection,'' says Stewart, who maintains a New York apartment for
shopping and gallery hopping. ``I want to keep some sense of
minimalism from the period.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the possibility of discovering a new passion
that would take him in a whole different direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot to go out on a limb, and I'm too immersed in
this to think about that,'' he says. ``This time I've kind of found
my bride and think I'll keep her.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Atlanta is home to one of the country's largest design
communities. To suggest an architect, builder or interior or
landscape designer for How the Pros Live, call 404-526-5969 or send
an e-mail to dflanders(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   D E S I G N E R S N A P S H O T
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Vitals: Age 43, grew up in West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Education: University of Florida
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Career: Designer for Design Continuum; started William Stewart
Designs in 1985
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Biggest design goof: Ordering an armoire too large to go up a
client's stairs. It had to be hoisted by crane up several stories
and through a window.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Biggest pet peeve: ``People who don't trust you. Yet I know
trust must be gained.''
</P>
<P>
   S T E WA R T ' S A D V I C E T O H O M E B U Y E R S
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Keep an open mind about resources. Shop flea markets for
vintage furniture.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Read all the decorating magazines you can and tear out photos
of ideas you like.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pace yourself and buy the best quality furnishings you can
afford (``A good interior, unlike instant coffee, takes time to
brew.'')
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you're on a tight budget, you're better off decorating one
room (the one most used) than the entire house right away.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Create your own sense of style in your home instead of
imitating your mother's.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Collections give a home personality because they speak to the
individual. Think about the things you like.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make collecting fun. Keep an eye out for pieces while
traveling on vacations or business.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For more impact, group collectibles in one display instead of
scattering them throughout the house.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't overdo a collection. Display your best or most prized
pieces and store the others. Then rotor the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
