<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NICK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABY BOOMER HEADS THE BOOM IN `CLASSIC' TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Next time you find little Johnny watching too
much television and you're about to snatch the remote away and
begin your patented Parental Lecture About the Great Outdoors,
think again.
</P>
<P>
   That kid could be in training to run a TV network.
</P>
<P>
   It worked for Larry Jones, 38, who spent a good deal of his
youth logging some serious TV time and now he's all grown up and is
the general manager of Nick At Nite and TV Land. That's akin to
liking soda pop and growing up to run Coca-Cola. Nick At Nite
redefined ``classic'' television and the popular TV Land spun off
from there, going on to become a 24-hour home to some of TV's
greatest shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched a lot of TV as a kid,'' Jones says. His parents
never discouraged him from his pursuit _ as long as he got his
homework done (you don't become a general manager by flunking). In
fact, his whole house was TV friendly. ``None of my friends had a
TV set in their rooms,'' Jones says.
</P>
<P>
   But he did _ at age 8. So did his siblings. And his parents.
There were five TV sets in the house then.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, all those years of watching TV paid off,'' Jones
says.
</P>
<P>
   He is the perfect man to be running a channel called TV Land,
which, in the spirit of Nick At Nite, bows to and cashes in on
nostalgia. Jones was born for this job. Even now, he says, his mom
has eight television sets in a four-bedroom house. ``You turn the
light on, and the TV goes on,'' Jones says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely, then, that Jones harbors the kind of
TV-is-the-enemy belief that some parents do. He has two kids. ``My
6-year-old watches a lot of TV,'' he says. ``Obviously they watch a
lot of Nickelodeon.''
</P>
<P>
   His son also supports the ever-increasing domination of the
3-year-old TV Land. ``My son's favorite show is `Emergency.' He
says, `Why can't you put `Emergency' on one hour later so I can see
it when I get off the bus?'''
</P>
<P>
   TV Land was spun off of Nick At Nite because the channel was
filled mostly with kids and teen fare _ all very popular _ and when
the channel transformed into Nick At Nite in the evening, there
were only about nine hours to program.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Nick At Nite only aired sitcoms. TV Land has everything
from Westerns to cop shows and comedies, dramas and specialty
shows. The titles are a testament to fond memories, fun times and a
good deal of quality: ``Dragnet,'' ``Family Affair,'' ``Leave It to
Beaver,'' ``Petticoat Junction,'' ``My Three Sons,'' ``Kojak,''
``Gunsmoke,'' ``Hill Street Blues,'' ``St. Elsewhere'' and a litany
of other chestnuts, some obvious classics, others that only aired a
season or two. TV Land has a vault of 23,000 hours of shows, and it
is growing. ``It gives us a lot more depth and more options for the
hardcore baby boomer.''
</P>
<P>
   While all kinds of people tune in _ some are seeing these shows
for the first time ever _ the target audience is 25-54, ``the first
generation that really grew up on TV,'' as Jones says. ``So many of
these shows define a generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Back when Nick At Nite began to take off, based largely on
people rediscovering ``classic'' TV, Jones and others at the
channel had a wish list they could barely tap into because of the
limited time. Now they've gone out and pursued nearly every
available favorite. ``There've been shows we've had on the list for
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently the channel got ``All in the Family,'' a particular
favorite of Jones. ``We're pretty selective about shows we pick
up,'' he says. ``We want shows that defined that generation. We're
superserving that audience.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea has taken off. Nick At Nite continues to increase even
with limited hours for nostalgia, but on its third birthday TV Land
is celebrating a recent upswing in prime-time ratings as well.
Jones says, ``We've clearly hit a chord with our audience.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
