<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, April 30:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 3 pages of stories, photos and graphics
on the continuing crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Berlin) _ A diplomatic roundup: Germany's
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder sees ``movement toward a political
solution'' after meeting Viktor Chernomyrdin, the special Russian
envoy; Strobe Talbott, the deputy secretary of state, talks tough
in Brussels. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ NATO missile hits a suburb of Sofia,
Bulgaria's capital, 30 miles from Yugoslavia. No one hurt. Allied
bombers pound Montenegro, to get Yugoslav planes, and hit Slobodan
Milosevic's home town for first time. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Dateline to kum) _ Five refugees, crossing
from Kosovo into Macedonia, are killed by a land mine. By Barry
Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Folo on Thursday's votes in the
House, and developments on the administration's budget request. By
Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   We are considering, among others, stories on Jesse Jackson's
trip to Belgrade, anxiousness among U.S. reservists, attitudes in
the Muslim world to the NATO campaign, a look at damage to the Serb
economy and the situation of refugees who remain near the border at
Kukes, in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLORADO SCHOOL SHOOTINGS &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The Times plans 2 pages of stories, photos and grahics on the
aftermath of the shootings at Columbine High School, including the
long takeout -VOICES, described below.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING (Littleton, Colo.) _ A ledeall: An arrest
is expected a man the TEC-9 pistol used by the shooters, Dylan
Klebold and Eric Harris; a funeral is held for the black student
killed in the attack. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-VOICES (Undated) _ A roundtable in which Columbine
students discuss the shooting and their relationships. By Dirk
Johnson. (3500-4000 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SAFETY (Undated) _ Around the country, schools are
contending with hundreds of bomb threats and alleged plots in an
atmosphere of panic over school safety. By Robert D. McFadden.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-GUNS (Undated) _ It appears that the two young
shooters in Littleton got guns the same way most criminals get
guns, not by stealing them but by someone legally buying them. By
Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-LUVOX (Undated) _ A short on the antidepressant
Luvox, the medication being taken by Eric Harris. By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FROG-WARNING (Undated) _ Frogs with multiple limbs and other
deformities have been reported more and more often in recent years,
feeding worries that the frogs are bellwethers of some looming
environmental apocalypse. Two new studies reported in the journal
Science tomorrow conclude that at least some of the frog
deformities are the result of natural parasites in the wild. By
Carol Kaesuk Yoon. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MARS-TECTONICS (Undated) _ The Mars Global Surveyor has
detected bar-codelike magnetic stripes on Mars, indicating that the
planet may have once maintained an active plate tectonics system.
On Earth such stripes are thought to be caused by the spreading of
new sea floor in which iron-bearing minerals ``freeze'' in the
direction of the prevailing magnetic field, which reverses from
North to South and back again every 10,000 years or so. The results
suggest that, like Earth, Mars has been shaped in the past by the
spreading and colliding of such tectonic plates, pieces of crust
floating on a hot mantle, and that the planet's magnetic field is
also subject to reversal. On Mars the stripes are wider however,
suggesting either that the sea floor spread more rapidly or the
that magnetic field switched directions less frequently than on
Earth. By John Noble Wilford. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS (Jerusalem) _ Palestinians, meeting in Gaza,
wrap up their meeting on statehood, formally delaying an
announcement. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   SEASIA-CAMBODIA (Bangkok, Thailand) _ The Association of
Southeast Asian Nations formally admits Cambodia to its ranks on
Friday. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   EMORY-GIFT (Atlanta) _ In what may be the largest individual
donation to a private university, Emory received a gift of close to
$400 million last year from an undisclosed source. The gift was
uncovered by the Emory student paper that went through the
university tax returns. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   GAMBLING-ASSESS (Undated) _ Folo on the reported recommendations
of the federal gambling commission, and a look at who are the
likely winners and losers under the plan. A news analysis by Brett
Pulley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Washington) _ The employment cost index, the
government's measure for tracking changes in compensation costs,
rose 0.4 percent in the first quarter, the smallest increase on
record. The small rise was about half of what economists had
expected and is the strongest sign yet that inflationary pressures
remain muted. The ECI rose 0.7% in the fourth quarter. Year to
year, the rate is 3 percent, the slowest since 1997. By Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:55 p.m., the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 67 points, while the Nasdaq composite was down 23.
Stocks in Europe were modestly lower; the sharpest decline was in
London, where the FTSE 100 lost 1.2 percent. Hong Kong stocks were
little changed, and the Tokyo market was closed for a national
holiday, Greenery Day. By Robert D. Hershey.
</P>
<P>
   CLUB-MED (Cancun, Mexico) _ Club Med, the Paris-based company
credited with originating the ``all-inclusive'' vacation, fell on
fell on hard financial times through much of this decade. But Club
Med is now combating its old reputation as a dated swingers'
paradise is by offering cultural and literary forums and by
renovating its villages. Attendance is rising, and analysts say
Club Med is finally heading in the right direction. By Edwin
McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-BROKERS (Undated) _ The Securities Industry Association
releases its report on simluated trading in preparation for the
year 2000. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   WTO-APPOINT (Geneva) _ Profiling the two candidates for
director-general of the World Trade Organization: Michael Moore of
New Zealand and Supachai Panitchpakdi of Thailand. A decision is
expected Friday on replacing Renatao Ruggeiro of Italy, the WTO's
first leader. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-INQUIRY (Sao Paulo) _ Brazil's former central bank
president could be re-arrested for further refusal to cooperate
with a congressional inquiry into government favoritism toward
banks during the January currency crisis. But the inquiry is no
longer seen as a possible threat to Brazil's economic rebound, as
interest rates were lowered again late Wednesday, and stocks and
the real continue to strengthen. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-FORD (Sao Paulo) _ Ford Motor cancels plans to build a $1
billion vehicle manufacturing plant in Brazil's southern state of
Rio Grande do Sul because a newly elected left-wing governor there
reneged on financial incentives. Ford says it plans to look at
other sites in Brazil. By Simon Romer.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   A.M. Rosenthal's ``On My Mind'' and Thomas L. Friedman's
``Foreign Affairs.''
</P>
