<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8000 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTOS-HISTORY-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     04-29 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-HISTORY-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 (l and f coding)  
 UNDATED: ... East Coast cognoscenti.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   53. Ralph Nader writes ``Unsafe at Any Speed,'' paying
particular attention to the Corvair, and accuses the auto industry
of ignoring passenger safety. Congress listens.
</P>
<P>
   54. Pony Cars hit the streets and their names are Cougar,
Mustang, Camaro, and Firebird.
</P>
<P>
   55. The government requires shoulder belts, in addition to seat
belts.
</P>
<P>
   56. The Dodge Charger is introduced in 1966. A fastback with a
426-cubic-inch wedgehead V-8, it is the rumblin' suis generis
muscle car. Slap a hemi on it and it would wail.
</P>
<P>
   57. George Maharis and Martin Milner cross America on the
television show ``Route 66.'' If Seinfeld had owned a 'Vette, this
would have been his show about aimless wandering.
</P>
<P>
   58. Chevrolet introduces the Blazer. In the future, it will be
more politically correct than its big stablemate, the Subdivision.
</P>
<P>
   59. Arlo Guthrie narrates in ``Alice's Restaurant'':
</P>
<P>
   So we took a half-ton of garbage and put it in the back of a
red, VW microbus. . . .
</P>
<P>
   And the counterculture, flowered up and riding in the ultimate
counterculture vehicle, went out to meet The Man, in the person of
Officer Obie.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
1970-79:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   60. ``American Graffiti,'' a fine car movie featuring a high
school Class of '62, lights American movie screens. Before Kennedy
is killed, before we know what is happening in Vietnam, a
generation cruises: Richard Dreyfuss, scholar-in-waiting, in his
VW; Paul LeMat in his yellow hot rod going head-to-head with
Harrison Ford in a black and evil machine; Suzanne Somers, blonde,
pale and ethereal in a white and innocent Thunderbird. All to the
intonations of Wolfman Jack. Perfect.
</P>
<P>
   61. The 1973 fuel crunch. Lower speed limits, minimum gas
mileage rules come next.
</P>
<P>
   62. Ford builds the Pinto, a rolling, explosive can of gas.
</P>
<P>
   63. The Toyota Land Cruiser, the short box, not today's long
Yuppiemobile, goes off road in America.
</P>
<P>
   64. There is great mystique about the Volvo among the
counterculture. But since most of its members don't have to be
anywhere on time, it's like, you know, OK, if it doesn't run very
often. Meanwhile, those who do want to get somewhere on time
discover that those Slant-6 Darts and Valiants won't ever let them
down.
</P>
<P>
   65. In 1976, ABC televises the closing laps of the Daytona 500.
Richard Petty and David Pearson tangle on the last lap. Pearson's
crumpled car limps to the finish line as Petty's smokes in the
background. America watches. Here comes NASCAR fever.
</P>
<P>
   66. Bruce Springsteen, in affirmation of the open road and
working-class freedom sings:
</P>
<P>
   Roll down the window and let the wind blow back your hair.
</P>
<P>
   The night's busted open, these two lanes will take us anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
1980-1989: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   67. Freedom gets passed by greed and ostentation. Saab and BMW
become the auto of the lucky monied. Singer Bill Morrissey would
reflect on this trend:
</P>
<P>
   I make a lot of money in my hi-tech job.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, sure, you bet, I drive a turbo Saab.
</P>
<P>
   And:
</P>
<P>
   My BMW draws applause.
</P>
<P>
   I am not bound by traffic laws.
</P>
<P>
   68. Subaru offers a small, 4WD station wagon. It rusts, it eats
tim-ing belts, but it hints of SUVs tocome.
</P>
<P>
   69. Toyota introduces the 4-Runner.
</P>
<P>
   70. Japan agrees to import limits.
</P>
<P>
   71. Honda opens a plant in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   72. The federal government steps in to save Chrysler.
</P>
<P>
   73. Chrysler thanks America by introducing the minivan.
</P>
<P>
   74. The convertible, once virtually extinct, makes a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   75. GM forms a new company called Saturn.
</P>
<P>
   76. Goodbye to the inflatable spare tire. Welcome the hard
little rubber doughnut.
</P>
<P>
   78. Mazda debuts the Miata _ sporty, convertible, and cheap. It
brings back the roadster.
</P>
<P>
   79. Ford launches the Taurus-Sable line.
</P>
<P>
   80. Weld-through, zinc-chromate priming is introduced. Boring?
Too technical? It's why cars don't rust like they used to.
</P>
<P>
   81. Freon is out for air conditioning; environmentally friendly
substances replace it.
</P>
<P>
   82. AMC gives us the Pacer _ ugliest car ever built, but what
would you expect from a company that once took over Harley-Davidson
and almost killed it?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
1990-1999: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   83. Saturn becomes the first new American make in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   84. VW brings back the Beetle; restored Beetles soar in value.
</P>
<P>
   85. Airbags become standard. Unfortunately, no one did the tests
that would have revealed their danger to infants, children, and
small adults.
</P>
<P>
   86. Thunderbird prototype is displayed. Plans to bring it back
are welcomed.
</P>
<P>
   87. Dodge Power Wagon prototype is displayed. Bring it back.
</P>
<P>
   88. The Dodge Charger is reborn. Bring on the Muscle Car.
</P>
<P>
   89. At a shopping mall inNewton, the owner of a Honda Ac-cord
parks beside a ChevroletSuburban whose owner is just stepping down
from the cab. Each driver feels morally superior to the other.
</P>
<P>
   90. Subaru offers the Outback and the Forester. Politically
correct SUVs.
</P>
<P>
   91. The sports roadster is hot. Honda, Porsche, Jaguar, and BMW
offer models. Thank you, Miata.
</P>
<P>
   92. Global Positioning Systems in cars mean that men can
continue to never ask for directions.
</P>
<P>
   93. Mergers sweep the industry. Is
FordJaguarLincolnVolvoDaimlerChryslerGMSaabNissanRenault et al the
auto company of thefuture?
</P>
<P>
   94. The sports coupe makes a comeback: BMW, Nissan, and Audi
offer the Z3, the new Z, and the TT.
</P>
<P>
   95. In 1998, sales of vans, pick-up trucks, and SUVs surpass
carsales.
</P>
<P>
   96. The minivan gets associated with the ``soccer mom.'' Many
soccer moms respond by moving on to pickup trucks and SUVs. Better
cache.
</P>
<P>
   97. Station wagons make a comeback. Saab introduces what may be
the best of the bunch.
</P>
<P>
   98. Motor Trend names the Lexus RX300 its Sports-Ute of the
Year, another SUV that may never see mud. Can it pull stumps?
</P>
<P>
   99. Ford announces it will build an SUV, the Excursion, that is
bigger than the Chevrolet Suburban. Chevrolet hints it will not be
left behind. What happens when cars get bigger than garages?
</P>
<P>
   100. A generation of kids knows how to navigate computer
screens, at high speed, using joysticks that are reminiscent of the
tillers that Packard swapped for the steering wheel nearly 100
years ago. Are we going full circle here?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Want to do your own list of 100? Do as I did and check through
thousands of auto industry specifics at www.motorcraft.com. and
scroll through the history section.)
</P>
</TEXT>
