<HEADLINE>
TALENTED COUNTRY DUO HANGS TOUGH WITH OFFBEAT MUSICAL STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Perhaps the oddest thing that the Warren Brothers have
ever heard is that some country stations are ``afraid'' to play
their music.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's music, not a nuclear weapon,'' says Brett, lead singer of
the Florida-based duo. ``What are they afraid of? That their
listeners will love it? If they had been afraid of playing Shania
Twain, think of how many million of records wouldn't have been
sold.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Twain, Brett and his older brother Brad are pushing
Nashville's musical boundaries. But while the poster girl for
washboard abs goes for glittery pop hooks, the Warrens rely on
muscular harmonies, a smattering of pedal steel guitar and a
throbbing backbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Brett describes their sound as ``the Everly Brothers meet Steve
Earle.'' That's not a bad little label: The best stuff on the
brothers' debut, ``Beautiful Day in the Cold Cruel World,''
showcases their gritty songwriting skills and an incandescent vocal
blend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just a sibling thing,'' Brett says modestly.
``It's in the genetics. With brothers, the voices are so similar,
but then you get the little differences. When you hear some
families sing together, it can give you goosebumps.''
</P>
<P>
   The sound of the Warrens can do that, although their success has
been limited so far, sadly. Critics write them love letters while
radio programmers seem oddly indifferent.
</P>
<P>
   The singles ``Guilty'' and ``A Better Man'' _ the latter
inspired by Jack Nicholson's ``You make me want to be a better
man'' speech in ``As Good As It Gets'' _ both did well without
cracking the national top 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the cities that play us, we're making waves,'' Brett says.
``We can go in and sell out a 1,500-seat club. But a lot of places
are saying we're not country enough. We're on Country Music
Television, we're signed to a country label (BNA Records) _ how is
that not country?''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the brothers' greatest exposure has been as Faith Hill's
opening act on her current tour. Her crossover sound works well
with the siblings' aggressive stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been great,'' Brett says. ``We play for sold-out
audiences, then get to stare at her for 90 minutes. We're the kind
of band that works opening for Faith Hill, and I think we would
work opening for Lynyrd Skynyrd. We're not trying to cross over,
but music is music. I mean, the king of rock and roll is in the
Country Music Hall of Fame and the father of country music is in
the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame. Explain that.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Warrens, they're hoping the third time is the charm.
``She Wants to Rock,'' their third single, will head to radio May
17. They're keeping their fingers crossed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the radio people that are resisting us?'' Brett asks.
``Well, that's just because we're different. But we'll keep
working, because it's the people that ultimately decide. At first
it's just 180 people at radio that decide. But in the end, it's up
to the people. And the people that hear the Warren Brothers, more
of them like us than don't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just keeping the faith, man.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Randy Cordova can be reached at randy.cordova(at)(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
