<HEADLINE>
A LOOK AT THE 100 MAJOR MOMENTS IN AUTO HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A car is far more than the sum of its mechanical parts. At the
base of any automobile purchase are utility and faith in its
reliability _ the basis of the lemon law. But that is boring. What
energizes our auto culture, a defined culture as much as are
sports, television, movies, dining or politics, are things far less
tangible.
</P>
<P>
   How does that new car sitting in the driveway make you feel? Did
you purchase daring? Recapture youth? Make a statement? Show the
neighbors how practical you are? Did you buy it for color? Speed?
Size? Manufacturer's aura? Did you first see it in an ad? A movie?
Someone else's driveway?
</P>
<P>
   These emotional responses comprise the culture of the
automobile. And they are what make it so much fun _ and treacherous
_ to attempt to list 100 great moments in the past century of the
auto. Making such a list is like poking a stick into a hornets'
nest, the hornets' nest in this case being the world of auto
aficionados. What about the development of the ball-joint? some
will ask. Or electronic fuel injection? The radial tire? The
buzzing begins. I pick up the stick and poke that nest: Here,
decade by decade but in no order of importance, are my top 100:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
1900-1909:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Packard gets rid of the tiller and gives us the steering
wheel.
</P>
<P>
   2. The Oldsmobile Curved Dash is the first mass-produced,
gas-powered car.
</P>
<P>
   3. Ford Motor Co. and General Motors are incorporated.
</P>
<P>
   4. The first car is stolen _ not in East Boston, but St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   5. Glencoe, Ill., installs the first speed bumps.
</P>
<P>
   1910-1919:
</P>
<P>
   6. Cadillac introduces the electric starter.
</P>
<P>
   7. The first gas station opens in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   8. Ford, maker of Models A and T, installs the moving auto
assembly line.
</P>
<P>
   9. Gulf offers free road maps.
</P>
<P>
   10. Oregon adopts the first gasoline tax.
</P>
<P>
   11. Cadillac produces a good American V-8 engine.
</P>
<P>
   12. In Germany, Ferdinand Porsche builds a powerful, 6-cylinder
auto.
</P>
<P>
   13. Mitsubishi Motor Co. builds Japan's first production car.
They call it the Model A _ early industrial theft.
</P>
<P>
   14. Detroit installs the first three-color stoplights. Ninety
years later, many drivers in Massachusetts do not know what each
color means.
</P>
<P>
   1920-29:
</P>
<P>
   15. The first drive-in restaurant opens in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   16. The first suburban shopping mall opens outside St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   17. Cadillac ends double-clutching with the synchromesh
transmission.
</P>
<P>
   18. Balloon tires appear.
</P>
<P>
   19. The first station wagon by a company called Star is
produced.
</P>
<P>
   20. Dual taillights first flash.
</P>
<P>
   1930-39:
</P>
<P>
   21. In Camden, N.J., the first drive-in theater opens.
</P>
<P>
   22. The Airstream trailer is introduced. The sleek aluminum
homes-on-wheels show us that when it comes to vacation, you can
take it with you.
</P>
<P>
   23. Delco offers the first in-dash car radio.
</P>
<P>
   24. The Ford V-8 wins high praise _ from John Dillinger and
Clyde Barrow.
</P>
<P>
   25. Chevrolet introduces the Suburban Carryall, a big box on
wheels that 65 years later, and much larger, will be mocked as the
Chevy Subdivision.
</P>
<P>
   26. In Wolfsburg, Germany, the Volkswagen factory is completed.
</P>
<P>
   27. In Japan, the Toyoda Loom Works opens an auto division,
Toyota.
</P>
<P>
   28. Buick introduces electric turn signals. Sixty-five years
later, in Massachusetts, many drivers still do not know what they
are for.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
1940-49:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   29. American industry converts to wartime mode, building trucks,
tanks, planes, and ships at a remarkable rate.
</P>
<P>
   30. Willys sends the Army its first Jeeps.
</P>
<P>
   31. In Sweden, Saab builds its first cars.
</P>
<P>
   32. Somewhere in the hills of North Carolina, Junior Johnson
powers a souped-up car, laden with illicit liquor, through the dark
hills and hollows, a Southern boy learning to race cars.
</P>
<P>
   33. On Dec. 14, 1947, Bill France Sr. tells the organizational
NASCAR meeting in Daytona Beach, Fla., ``Stock car racing has got
distinct possibilites for Sunday shows and we do not know how big
it can get if it's handled properly.''
</P>
<P>
   34. That same year, a biker gang takes over the town of
Hollister, Calif. It inspires the Marlon Brando movie ``The Wild
One,'' and is an early instance of horsepower giving identity to
the alienated.
</P>
<P>
   35. The first Volkswagen arrives in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
1950-59:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   36. Chevrolet and Ford introduce the Corvette and the
Thunderbird.
</P>
<P>
   37. Two brothers from Manchester, N.H., open the first
McDonald's in California.
</P>
<P>
   38. Hemmings Motor News, a bible in the industry, is first
published in Quincy, Ill., in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   39. The 1957 Chevrolet escapes the mammilate-chrome, soda
fountain school of auto design. It may be the best-looking American
car ever.
</P>
<P>
   40. The first Volvos and Toyotas arrive in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   41. 9/30/55: James Dean, driving a Porsche Spyder 550, is killed
at a California intersection in a collision with a car driven by
Donald Turnupspeed.
</P>
<P>
   42. President Eisenhower launches the $25-billion, 30-year
project known as the Interstate Highway System.
</P>
<P>
   43. Chuck Berry sings:
</P>
<P>
   As I was motivatin' over the hill
</P>
<P>
   I saw Maybellene in a Coupe de Ville
</P>
<P>
   A Cadillac a-rollin' on the open road
</P>
<P>
   Nothin' will outrun my V-8 Ford.
</P>
<P>
   He's chasing a woman lost. Heartache, betrayal, and love merge
in a 110-m.p.h. auto chase. America is on the road with speed and
horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
1960-69:
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   44. The Beach Boys _ just surfing music, right? Wrong. Their car
tunes of the '60s are among the best. I give you:
</P>
<P>
   She's a little deuce coupe with a flathead mill.
</P>
<P>
   But she'll walk a Thunderbird like it's standin' still.
</P>
<P>
   45. And Chuck Berry might have caught Maybellene long before
that hill with the Beach Boys':
</P>
<P>
   Four-speed, dual-quad, positraction 409.
</P>
<P>
   46. All that speed. All that power. The first emission controls
are introduced.
</P>
<P>
   47. Front seatbelts are standard in all American-made cars in
1964.
</P>
<P>
   48. Put those belts in the back seat as well, the government
orders.
</P>
<P>
   49. Ed ``Big Daddy'' Roth moves from sculptor of fine custom
cars to spokesman for a generation of pimple-faced, adolescent
misfits. His models, and the characters who drive them _ Rat Fink,
Drag Nut, Mother's Worry _ become the alter-egos of disaffected
youths who will later be called nerds.
</P>
<P>
   50. Beach Boys again. Fun, Fun, Fun:
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, she got her daddy's car and she cruised through the
hamburger stand now . . ..''
</P>
<P>
   But because she was cruisin' a burger joint and and was not at
the library, where she said she was going, daddy took that T-Bird
away.
</P>
<P>
   51. Porsche introduces the 911.
</P>
<P>
   52. Tom Wolfe writes ``The Kandy-Kolored Tangerine-Flake
Streamlined Baby'' and Kustom Kars are revealed to the East Coast
cognoscenti.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
