<SLUG> BC-GASOLINE-PRICES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA LAWMAKERS DEBATE SPIKE IN GAS PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ A week-long breakdown at a Southern
California Arco refinery, kept from the public for more than a
month, was a major factor in the recent huge increase in gas prices
in California, state officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The revelation came during a special legislative hearing
Wednesday to examine why gas prices rose sharply during March and
April, one of the sharpest price spikes on record. Prices are at a
statewide average of $1.57 per gallon of unleaded, self-serve
gasoline, compared to $1.10 per gallon in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they can increase much more without driving
people to electric vehicles,'' said Senate President pro tem John
Burton, D-San Francisco, who called the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Oil company executives admitted Wednesday they had reaped
profits during the price spike, caused, they said, by the equipment
breakdowns and refinery explosions. Their ``refinery margin'' went
from 28 cents to 70 cents per gallon, an increase far too large not
to include profits.
</P>
<P>
   The Arco refinery shutdown was one of many explanations for the
price spike, which has prompted widespread complaints from
consumers, an investigation by state Attorney General Bill Lockyer
into possible price gouging and antitrust violations, and a
gasoline boycott planned for Friday.
</P>
<P>
   During the legislative hearing, an oil industry analyst for the
California Energy Commission said that five factors caused the
increased prices, including a Feb. 23 flash fire at the Tosco Avon
refinery in Martinez that killed four workers, another fire a month
later at the Richmond Chevron plant, and production delays at an
Exxon refinery.
</P>
<P>
   The analyst, Tom Glaviano, said he couldn't reveal the other two
factors because of confidentiality agreements with the oil
companies. The secrecy policy is in place because some fear that
making the information public might cause a further panic in the
gasoline market.
</P>
<P>
   But an Arco executive at the hearing chose to reveal the March
18 breakdown in a ``cracking unit'' that crippled production at the
company's Carson refinery in Los Angeles County, forcing Arco to
import an extra 800,000 barrels of gasoline from the Gulf Coast. No
workers were injured during the breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can assure you, at the time I did not know if I was going to
meet my customer's needs,'' said Chris Noble, senior vice president
of retail marketing at Arco, adding: ``It's very expensive to buy
fuel that has come around from the Gulf Coast.''
</P>
<P>
   The fifth major factor for the price increase remained a mystery
at the hearing, although lawmakers speculated it would have been
further problems at Tosco or Exxon, or a breakdown in the
distribution or oil pipeline systems.
</P>
<P>
   Noble and other oil company executives said higher crude-oil
costs had also played a role in the price rise, but the main
factors appear to be the refinery breakdowns and fears of lower
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Fear must be one of the factors, lawmakers said, since the
California Energy Commission recently reported there were adequate
supplies of gasoline to meet demand during March and April. The
commission said the huge price increases weren't warranted based on
a limited supply alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds to me that somebody panicked, that there was a
shortfall perception, but we really had supplies available,'' said
Sen. Hilda Solis, D-El Monte.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
