<SLUG> BC-PAYNE-MUSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POP SINGER CANNOT LIVE BY BUBBLEGUM ALONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Freda Payne's been singing for as long as she
remembers, but there's one song that's forever identified with her:
The 1970 blockbuster ``Band of Gold,'' a classic slice of pop soul
with an urgent bass line and a silky, purring vocal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never realized how far-reaching it affected people, but it
did,'' says Payne, a striking woman who still performs about six
months out of the year. ``Sometimes I don't get it. People tell me
it's their favorite song of all time _ I mean, I like it, too, but
I'm kind of flattered and amused all at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   She's probably amused because ``Band of Gold'' doesn't exactly
boast the heaviest of lyrics. In fact, it's probably the bubbliest
song ever to deal with the subject of impotency.
</P>
<P>
   There were other hits for Payne, including ``Cherish What Is
Dear to You (While It's Near to You)'' and the poignant anti-war
song ``Bring the Boys Home.`` But she fills up her show with
jazz-oriented numbers and show tunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who don't know my repertoire are sometimes surprised,''
she says. ``But I love to sing jazz, to sing ballads, to sing the
standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Her profile hasn't been particularly high since the early '70s,
but she's stayed busy. She's done Broadway and even hosted her own
syndicated talk show. These days, it's corporate shows, symphony
gigs and club dates that fill her time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could say I've been there and done that, but I haven't
done enough,'' she says. ``There's so much more I haven't done. I
mean, I guess I could be a stockbroker, but this is what I do. (The
late) Joe Williams was singing up to the end _ that's how I see
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the end comes, she'll probably be singing ``Band of
Gold'' _ unless she's at home in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always sing around the house, but I (begin ital) never (end
ital) sing `Band of Gold,' '' she says emphatically. ``Nothing
against the song, but there's no reason to sing it when there's no
audience there.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Randy Cordova can be reached at randy.cordova(at)pni.com &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 1450EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8029 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUNTRY-LIFESTYLE-AZR     04-29 1516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNTRY-LIFESTYLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTRY CONVERTS LOVE THE BOOT-SCOOTIN' LIFESTYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - When Rhode Island native Jack Joyce moved to the
Valley in 1979, it not only meant a change of scene, in some ways
it meant a change of identity.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few months, he owned his first cowboy boots: a pair of
light brown Justins.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came out here, I just fell in love with Western wear,''
says Joyce, a landscaper who works in the East Valley. ``I fell in
love with country music. I even took some country-Western dance
lessons. It was like a whole change in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   An overwhelming change. It's rare to see Joyce without a pair of
boots these days. His feet haven't touched a pair of dress shoes
for more than two years, not since he had to go to a wedding in
England (``It's so cumbersome to fly with boots,'' he apologizes).
</P>
<P>
   For 15 years, Joyce was the principal of Mesa's Westwood High
School. He was known for his firm handshake, for being easily
approachable, and for his Western wear. He would pair a handsome
pair of black lizard wingtips with suits featuring delicate Western
touches.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put your boots on, and you're a couple of inches taller,''
says Joyce, in a voice that still retains its East Coast accent.
``When I'm dressed up in my boots and my Stetson, I feel good about
the way I carry myself. I have a little more jump to my step.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's part of the whole Western mystique. There's
something about the entire Western look and Western sound that
appeals to people who couldn't rope a calf if their lives depended
on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Arizona, after all,'' says Roger Saba, looking pretty
spiffy himself in a pair of black teju lizard boots. He oversees
marketing for Saba's Western Stores, a business his grandfather
started in 1927.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come here and they get into the lifestyle. It's more
acceptable than it is in the East. People may not be cowboys, but
they see something in the lifestyle they want to emulate.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyce would agree. When he looks at himself in the mirror, he
knows what he wants to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although I've never been a smoker and I don't have a mustache,
there's something about the look of the Marlboro man,'' he says.
``Kind of a romantic, swashbuckling look to that individual. Maybe
it's a little bit of the copycat syndrome. Maybe it's a little bit
of `when in Rome.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But even though we are in the West, there seems to be some
confusion about just how Western we are. There are people born and
bred in the Valley who would rather walk barefoot across hot July
asphalt than slip on a pair of Tony Lamas and a big belt buckle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've basically got different types of people here in
Arizona,'' Saba says. ``You've got people who always wear this
stuff, day in and day out. You've got people who would never wear
this stuff. But most people are somewhere in between _ they own a
couple of pairs of boots and break them out when it's
appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   And people can start out as one type of person and end up as
another. The late Herb Drinkwater is probably the ultimate example.
He was a native New Yorker, but the beloved mayor of Scottsdale
rarely was seen without a pair of ostrich hides and a Western
tailored suit. He embraced the lifestyle and embraced the look.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Lucy Peterson. When she was growing up in south
Phoenix, she never gave a second thought about the Western style of
living.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you kidding?'' the pretty brunette asks incredulously.
``(begin ital) No one (end ital) listened to country music. And
people just didn't dress like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But here it is, Saturday night at Tempe's Rockin Rodeo, and
Peterson looks perfectly at home in tight-fitting Wranglers and
black boots with their dagger-sharp toes.
</P>
<P>
   She was divorced 2{ years ago and wanted to meet new people and
try something different. The people she met at Western clubs,
people who liked country music and enjoyed country dancing, seemed
less threatening than people who populate most nightspots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good way to meet new people, people who were
interested in dancing and talking, not just the other stuff,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be another whole element of the appeal. Maybe it's
simply a myth, but there's something almost quaint and gentlemanly
about the social scene.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of that is due to the dancing. It's not overtly sexual;
instead it is regimented and romantic. The steps are defined and
precise. There's little opportunity for hands to roam to forbidden
places, to paraphrase Conway Twitty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, it's about dancing,'' says Robin DeWitt, who works as a
registered nurse. ``You meet people and they're nice and they want
to dance. It's not like one dance means you're going to wind up in
bed together. It's almost more . . . refined.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, in some ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, there's something about the way a man looks in tight,
pressed Wranglers,'' she says, devilish enthusiasm lighting up her
eyes. ``A nice pair of boots, a good hat _ it just looks (begin
ital) good. (end ital) ''
</P>
<P>
   She then takes a look at the loose-fitting Levi's a visitor is
wearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, your jeans really need to be tighter,'' she says,
pinching the denim material. ``This is too loose!''
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie DeBenedetta knows how jeans should fit _ his Wranglers
almost look like they're painted on. He is studying to be a lawyer,
but right now he makes money teaching people the intricacies of
dancing the two-step and the Cotton-Eyed Joe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started dancing like this three years ago to meet a girl,''
DeBenedetta says. ``Pretty soon, she was gone and I was still
Western dancing.''
</P>
<P>
   It took him awhile to get into the Western mood: ``I'm
Italian!'' he exclaims. ``We don't usually dress like this!''
</P>
<P>
   Now he owns five pairs of cowboy boots, a couple of hats and
more than a dozen Wranglers. And he knew he'd found his destiny the
first time he walked into a country bar wearing a dark Stetson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a chick magnet,'' he says with a grin, like he's
letting loose with trade secrets. ``I would go into a bar without a
hat and was just another guy. With the hat, the women took
notice.''
</P>
<P>
   So part of it has to do with the opposite sex. But more
important, it has to do with how you feel about yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Take Dave Munsey. The Channel 10 (KSAZ) weatherman doesn't know
a whole lot about country music. But he sure as heck knows his
boots.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in the Vietnam War, I had my folks send me a pair
of cowboy boots,'' recalls Munsey, getting ready for an evening
newscast. ``I would have on my uniform and my boots, and the other
guys would look at me like I was crazy. But that was me.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 51, Munsey may be the best example of the man who walks
the walk _ literally _ without walking the walk. For instance, you
won't find him line dancing on weekends or roping cattle in his
spare time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably have about 12 pairs of boots,'' he says. ``Every
color to match every suit I own. My tuxedo is cut for my boots. All
my suits are cut for my boots. Nothing looks better than a good
pair of cowboy boots.''
</P>
<P>
   He favors exotic leathers made by Lucchese, known as the
Cadillac of Western footwear. They're not cheap, with prices
sometimes running into the four-figure category. Munsey has no
children, but he sounds like a proud papa when he discusses a pair
of orange boots he owns made from kangaroo hide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to have a set on Channel 10 where you could see my
whole body,'' he recalls. ``I would wear these orange boots, and
finally the director told me to stop: `More people are watching
your boots than are watching your weather.' It just about broke my
heart. They were really handsome.''
</P>
<P>
   It's become his trademark. Munsey is known for pushing pool
safety and for his fancy footwear.
</P>
<P>
   ``People I don't know will call me out of the blue because
they're going to buy a pair of boots and they want my opinion,'' he
says humbly. ``I try to do the best I can.''
</P>
<P>
   There's really no better salesman for the darned roach killers
than Munsey, who originally hails from North Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I pull my boots on, I feel really good about myself,'' he
says. ``There are some boots I like better than others, but nothing
feels as good as a really well-made cowboy boot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have three pairs of dress shoes, the kind with the little
tassels on them. I try to wear them occasionally, but I feel really
funny in them, like I should be tap dancing. I just don't feel like
``me''.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Joyce understands. The first time he went to a Western-wear
store, he was a novice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of awkward,'' he admits. ``I didn't know how a hat
needs to be shaped. I didn't know how jeans were supposed to be
tailored. But I'm a good student _ I wasn't afraid to show my lack
of knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I put on my boots, and it's just me. This is who I am.
This is how I dress. I don't feel conspicuous at all _ I feel like
me.'' &QL; 
Randy Cordova can be reached at randy.cordova(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
