<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SLCPUNK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TOUGH BEING A PUNK IN SALT LAKE CITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The funky clatter of ``SLC Punk!'' caused a minor buzz at the
Sundance Film Festival, perhaps because of its title alone _ the
SLC of the title refers to Salt Lake City, a few miles away from
the Utah festival. Or perhaps because the lanky Matthew Lillard,
who stars as Stevo, finally has a hairdo to go along with the
crackle of his personality _ it's glowing electric blue.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director James Merendino's film is about Stevo's
ingratiatingly rebellious attempt to set himself apart from the
status quo. Apparently he doesn't feel like he's different enough
by not being a Mormon. Stevo decides to pursue an Anarchy in the UT
lifestyle by following the road paved by the punks.
</P>
<P>
   ``SLC Punk!'' is funny because Stevo and his crew decide to
become punks in 1985, just about five years or so before the retro
movement reclaimed punk. Lillard ambles into every scene legs
first, as if his upper torso and lower body were torn in two
opposing directions. Stevo gives Lillard a chance to use his
skittishness. It's as if he loses interest in his thoughts before
he even completes them.
</P>
<P>
   So it's evident that he couldn't be less interested in trailing
his dad (Christopher McDonald, who should also be bored with this
part because he's played so often; it's hard to tell if he's
recycling lines from ``Leave it to Beaver'' or the more recent
``The Faculty'').
</P>
<P>
   Lillard's a born attention-getter. He makes as much of this role
as he did with the table scraps he was given in ``She's All That,''
in which he played a gross-out Prince patterned on ``The Real
World's'' Puck. That movie never recovered from his turn; the cast
seemed to be looking over their shoulders, waiting for him to come
back. Like the young Robert Downey Jr., half of Lillard's
performances may come from an effort to keep from getting bored.
You may find him irritating, but he throws himself bodily into a
part.
</P>
<P>
   The movie has the sense to be slightly embarrassed about the
snarling arrogance of its leads and the world they inhabit, which
isn't nearly as scary as they think it is; they're basically
suburban outlaws. Nevertheless, Stevo's pals try to match him on
the drama queen pedestal.
</P>
<P>
   His best friend is the ironically named Heroin _ ironic because
he doesn't do drugs. Merendino shows a sense of a humor, even
though the picture sometimes has as scattered an attention span as
its protagonist. ``SLC Punk's!'' star and creator imbue the picture
with energy, though, and they manage to succeed despite some
self-conscious storytelling devices.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``SLC Punk!'
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: James Merendino
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Matthew Lillard, Christopher McDonald
</P>
<P>
   Length: 97 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ adult language and situations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
