<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-IDLEHANDS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOP `HANDS' WRITERS BEFORE THEY STEAL AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TODD CAMP 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would be a lot easier to like ``Idle Hands'' if it weren't
such a patent rip-off of every horror movie I grew up watching, as
well as one I made in college.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if director Sam Raimi happens to stumble into theaters
to catch this derivative horror yarn _ the latest in a long line of
post-''Scream'' teen terrors _ the only thing he's likely to scream
is, ``Lawsuit!'' Most of the premise of ``Hands'' is largely
reminiscent of a scene in Raimi's inarguably classic gore outing
``Evil Dead II,'' in which hero Bruce Campbell does battle with his
own possessed paw after it's bitten by one of the evil dead.
</P>
<P>
   Insert ``hero'' Devon Sawa (''Wild America'') as Anton, a
slothful stoner whose right hand becomes a tool of Satan thanks
largely to his lethargic lifestyle _ idle hands being the devil's
workshop ... get it?
</P>
<P>
   Once he has figured out what his devilish digits have been up
to, his parents as well as a whole lot of locals have already
bitten the dust. Add to the body count buddies Seth Green (''Buffy
the Vampire Slayer'') and Elden Henson, who are unlucky enough to
point the finger at Anton's ... fingers.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing the two return as zombies to provide comic
relief for the killing spree that ensues as Anton tries to keep his
murderous mitt from harming the hottie neighbor (Jessica Alba) who
has finally taken an interest in him.
</P>
<P>
   As in ``Evil Dead,'' Anton cuts to the source of the problem,
hacking off the killer claw with a meat cleaver, but that only sets
it free to kill without the hindrance of a bulky body in tow.
</P>
<P>
   Vivica A. Fox is on hand as the obligatory evil expert stalking
the violent spirit, and Jack Noseworthy shows off his biceps as a
heavy metal meathead.
</P>
<P>
   What's sad is that the film wastes some really clever spins on
horror movie cliches and mires them in with a bunch of horror movie
cliches. Sawa is fine, especially when doing battle with his
rebellious appendage, and Green and Henson have enough amusing
asides to make their appearance _ an idea ``borrowed'' from ``An
American Werewolf in London'' _ seem like an homage.
</P>
<P>
   But for a horror comedy, it's neither scary nor funny enough.
And a comedic story about teen-agers murdered by a classmate seems
awfully ill-timed.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Idle Hands''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Rodman Flender
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Devon Sawa, Seth Green, Vivica A. Fox
</P>
<P>
   Length: 92 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ graphic violence, profanity, adult subject matter and
nudity
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Todd Camp is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
