A8052 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAREERS-PASSION-HNS &LR;      04-29 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-PASSION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASSION IS KEY TO LIFE AND WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you ever have a chance to see ``Rent'' _ or
if you ever had a chance to see Wayne Gretzky _ you might
appreciate why passion is more than a career counseling buzzword.
</P>
<P>
   The career counseling mantra is that you should find work that
you're passionate about, but keeping that passion is a lot easier
to philosophize about than to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   Say you're passionate about romance. Would you still feel
passionate if you were obligated to focus on your spouse eight
hours a day, five days a week, 50 weeks a year, for 45 years?
Sounds like a lot of work, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   So instead of tilting at windmills, take a few minutes to
appreciate the hokey play and the hockey player. (All right.
``Rent'' isn't really hokey; I just have a passion for deranged
sentences.) They're both about real passions, not fantasies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rent'' spans a year in the life of several struggling artists
in New York, at a time when AZT was the main treatment for AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   With death around the corner for many of them, life carries a
special urgency and preciousness. One of the main lyrics is ``no
day but today.''
</P>
<P>
   But what makes ``Rent'' universal is their zest for life, their
belief that they have the answers, that they can change the world.
Their world is fresh, before all of life's distractions set in,
before money becomes a preoccupation, before ``homeless'' and
``numbness'' blend together.
</P>
<P>
   You need that stage in your life, those booster rockets of
ambition and arrogance. In your own opinion, at least, you're never
smarter than you are in your early 20s, a time when you still don't
know what you still don't know.
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard to find anyone more passionate about work than
Gretzky, the greatest hockey player who ever lived. But staying at
that level requires hard work, training throughout the year to be
in shape for the season. And he was long past the stage of youthful
exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky had been playing hockey for 35 years, since he was 3. It
was time to find another passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rent'' creator Jonathan Larson lived for only 35 years. He
died from an aneurysm just before ``Rent'' debuted off-Broadway.
But his passion is still alive.
</P>
<P>
   Larson's ``no day but today'' theme is mostly about
relationships, and how AIDS makes them even more tenuous than
usual. But unless you're threatened with death's urgency, life
tends to turn into more of a marathon race, and it's easy to forget
about passion when you're sucking air at the 15-mile mark.
</P>
<P>
   Have you lost your passion? Not your passion for work,
necessarily; lots of people lose that. What about your passion for
life? Does something _ anything _ matter to you? Sure, you're
passionate about family and friends, right? But are you so wiped
out at the end of the day that you can't give them the time, much
less the passion? If all you're doing is staggering toward that
finish line, ask yourself if work is partly to blame.
</P>
<P>
   If you're constantly overwhelmed, ask for a week off _ without
pay if you have to. If you're a good employee and your boss isn't a
complete idiot, you'll get it. In a market like today's, the
company would lose a lot more time and money struggling to hire
someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Think about what you need to get your passion back. In an ideal
world, the career counselors are right: You should be passionate
about work because it's still probably the most time-consuming
aspect of your life. If you've been passionate before but aren't
now, ask yourself what has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Has your employer become unreasonably demanding? Do you feel
unappreciated? Has the job changed so much that it is no longer
enjoyable? Those are all good reasons to speak up or move on,
either to another employer or another career.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you don't think you could feel passionate
about any job, ask yourself what you do (or would like to) feel
passionate about, and whether your job is stopping you.
</P>
<P>
   If the workload is overwhelming, analyze your habits. Can you
get in a couple of uninterrupted hours by ignoring the phone? Do
you constantly check e-mail when you could be doing it once or
twice a day? Are you too timid to tell your boss that your workload
has become unreasonable and you need help in setting priorities?
</P>
<P>
   Even if work demands 60 or 70 hours a week and you have a good
reason not to leave (such as mental illness), think about
restructuring the hours to fit your passion, like taking Wednesday
afternoons off to go to baseball games or making a point that
neither you nor your spouse will work on Thursday nights so you can
have an evening of romance.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling passionate about work is a luxury, but feeling
passionate about life is a necessity. If you've lost it, fight to
get it back. No day but today.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His e-mail
address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
