w a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVOR-CALISTA-FLOCKHAR     04-29 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-CALISTA-FLOCKHART-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALISTA FLOCKHART'S `MIDSUMMER' MIRTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Calista
Flockhart in ``Ally McBeal'' and with Dominic West in ``A Midsummer
Night's Dream.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It's neither the best of times nor the worst of times for
Calista Flockhart these days.
 &HT;    On the one hand, she's a certified hit as micro-miniskirted
television lawyer ``Ally McBeal.''
 &HT;    On the other, her success has triggered a barrage of media
stories, most fixating on her weight. It doesn't help that in
photographs Flockhart looks like a severely undernourished waif. It
doesn't matter that she's denied _ well, sort of _ that she is a
melting-away anorexic.
 &HT;    But on the whole the actress admits that, while she could live
without the stories on her weight, ``Ally'' has been good for her.
 &HT;    The toothpick-thin, 34-year-old actress, clad in a black jacket,
matching slacks and a black T-shirt, with her blonde hair falling
to her shoulders, is at the Four Seasons Hotel in Beverly Hills,
Calif., to talk up her latest big-screen role, as Helena in
``William Shakespeare's A Midsummer Night's Dream,'' which will
open nationwide on May 14.
 &HT;    Flockhart _ whose first name is Greek for ``most beautiful'' _
shares the spotlight with an all-star cast that includes Kevin
Kline, Michelle Pfeiffer, Rupert Everett, Stanley Tucci, Christian
Bale, David Strathairn and Sophie Marceau.
 &HT;    ```Ally' has given me the kind of power in Hollywood I could
only dream of,'' the actress admits. ``No one would have given me a
role in `Midsummer' without `Ally.' I suppose opportunities like
this are worth losing some of my anonymity for.''
 &HT;    On the other hand, she says, the anorexia stories definitely
hurt.
 &HT;    ``All that intense scrutiny made me want to retreat and hide,''
Flockhart says. ``I honestly thought it was the end of my career,
and I was frightened it would destroy everything I had worked for.
Some of the stuff published about me was hurtful and vicious. I
wasn't prepared for it. At one time there was even a story that my
dog was anorexic!''
 &HT;    She insists that she doesn't think she's unusually thin.
 &HT;    ``It's difficult for me to be analytical about how I look and
appear to people,'' she says. ``You can't have the same perception
of yourself as others have of you.''
 &HT;    Unfortunately, that's precisely the kind of not-quite-denial
that convinces many eating-disorder professionals that the actress
does indeed have a problem.
 &HT;    If so, it's of long standing, since Flockhart was rail-thin even
in her days on the New York stage.
 &HT;    The daughter of a businessman father and a schoolteacher mother,
Flockhart grew up in suburban Iowa, Minnesota and New York. Her
first taste of acting came at Rutgers University, and in l987 she
moved to New York to try it professionally.
 &HT;    It wasn't easy. She landed a few bit parts in television soaps,
got a cable-television movie and worked part-time teaching
aerobics.
 &HT;    Gradually, however, breaks came her way. She made her Broadway
debut with Julie Harris in ``The Glass Menagerie'' (1994), and had
a small film role in Robert Redford's ``Quiz Show'' (l994). Mike
Nichols hired her to play Gene Hackman and Dianne Wiest's daughter
in ``The Birdcage'' (l995), but hardly anyone noticed her amid the
buffoonery of Nathan Lane and Robin Williams.
 &HT;    Most of the time, Flockhart recalls, Hollywood wasn't
interested. Even when she got an audition, she didn't get the part.
She lost out to Courtney Love for the role of Althea Flynt in ``The
People Vs. Larry Flynt'' (l996), and was beaten out by Cameron Diaz
for ``My Best Friend's Wedding'' (l997).
 &HT;    But then ``Ally'' producer/creator David Kelley heard about a
Broadway actress who might be right for the lead in his latest
television opus, and the rest is history.
 &HT;    Flockhart comes to ``Midsummer'' no stranger to Shakespeare,
having played Juliet and Cordelia onstage. This time out she plays
the sex-hungry Helena, enamored of the callous Demetrius (Bale).
 &HT;    ``People call Helena obsessed, but I'd like to think of her as
hugely determined,'' the actress says. ``I think she knows that,
somewhere inside him, Demetrius loves her, and she just has to get
his attention. That's what gives her confidence.
 &HT;    ``Helena is fixated on Demetrius,'' she adds. ``The play for me
is about love ... and how far we are willing to go to get what we
love.''
 &HT;    It's actually fun to return to her acting roots, Flockhart says,
after the changes wrought in her life since ``Ally McBeal'' hit the
airwaves in 1997.
 &HT;    ``I've lost a lot of my privacy,'' Flockhart says, ``but I try
to maintain my sense of humor and don't take it personally. `Ally'
has afforded me so many opportunities that I'd never have had. It's
been fast and fun, and I have no regrets _ I'd do it all over again
in a heartbeat.''
 &HT;    But that doesn't mean she wants to wear those miniskirts
forever.
 &HT;    ``I hope that people in Hollywood know I'm an actress and that
I'm not Ally McBeal,'' she says.
 &HT;    To reinforce that message, later this year she plans to take a
huge salary cut to return to the Off-Broadway stage in a new
production of ``I Am a Camera,'' playing Christopher Isherwood's
amoral, reckless Englishwoman Sally Bowles in the story set in
1930s Germany.
 &HT;    As for the big screen, ``Midsummer'' director Michael Hoffman
believes Flockhart has a major movie career ahead of her, perhaps
following in the footsteps of another beautiful but thin actress.
 &HT;    ``One day while we were talking on the film set in Tuscany,'' he
recalls, ``Calista told me she would like to star in a remake of
`Breakfast at Tiffany's' (l961). She sees herself resembling Audrey
Hepburn, and I agree she should exploit that.''
 c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Ally McBeal'' or ``A Midsummer
Night's Dream,'' consult the Twentieth Century Fox Website at
www.foxworld.com. And don't forget to visit The New York Times
Syndicate Web site at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
