<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8057 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLASS-SIZE30-COX     04-29 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASS-SIZE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SMALLER CLASSES HELP STUDENTS FOR YEARS, STUDIES SHOW
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Students placed in smaller classes in the early
grades continue to do better academically all the way through high
school, new research showed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The findings may bolster the chances that a reluctant Congress
will continue to fund President Clinton's plan to hire 100,000
extra teachers over seven years.
</P>
<P>
   A variety of researchers looked at the long-term effects of
Project STAR, in which 11,600 Tennessee students and their teachers
were assigned randomly to either small or large classes in
kindergarten through third grade between 1985 and 1989. The small
classes had 13 to 17 students and the large classes had 22 to 25.
</P>
<P>
   Those in the smaller classes did better in tests administered at
the time. After that, all the students were in regular classes for
their rest of their elementary and high school years.
</P>
<P>
   The new studies show that the benefits from the small classes
lasted for years. The students from the small classes:
</P>
<P>
   _ Had higher test scores in math, reading and science in grades
4, 6 and 8.
</P>
<P>
   _ Were less likely to drop out of high school.
</P>
<P>
   _ Were more likely to graduate from high school on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   _ Were more likely to graduate in the top 25 percent of their
class.
</P>
<P>
   _ Were more likely to take college entrance exams.
</P>
<P>
   The results were hailed by Democrats, who earlier this year
blocked Republican attempts to dilute Clinton's $12 billion teacher
hiring initiative by letting schools shift some of this year's $1.2
billion into special education. Over seven years, Clinton's bill
would help local districts reach a national target of no more than
18 students per class in the first through third grades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents and teachers have known for a long time that children
learn better in smaller classes,'' said Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash.
She and Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., predicted that the new
findings will help their bill, which calls for a $1.4 billion
second installment on Clinton's plan for the next fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptical Republicans didn't challenge the findings, though they
said class-size reduction might not be as cost-effective as higher
federal investment in improving teacher quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I welcome a debate on class size,'' responded Chairman Bill
Goodling, R-Pa., of the House Committee on Education and the
Workforce. But, he added, ``While smaller classes are an important
element too, quality teaching is the paramount factor in
learning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those aren't contradictory goals,'' said Education Secretary
Richard Riley. ``Our initiative sets aside 15 percent of the
(class-reduction) funds for professional development.''
</P>
<P>
   Teacher Sandra Horner of Knoxville, Tenn., told a House
education subcommittee that smaller classes would help keep good
teachers from accepting higher-paying jobs in other fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in the classroom for 25 years, and I know for
certain it makes a difference in the teacher's life when you ask
that teacher to teach 30 students, instead of 15,'' Horner said.
``A lot of a teacher's work is done at home, and teachers with 30
students in a class have very little life of their own.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
