<HEADER>
A8077 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NINE-WORDS-DRASKOVIC-     04-29 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NINE-WORDS-DRASKOVIC-COMMENTARY-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VUK DRASKOVIC'S GUTSY APPEAL FOR TRUTH _ OR FEWER LIES, AT LEAST  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This perceptive 850-word ``separate buy'' article is from The
Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ ``So let's tell people the truth...we are alone.''
</P>
<P>
   With those nine words, Vuk Draskovic has written himself into
the history of NATO's war against Yugoslavia, a roaring, harsh
voice demanding reality and an end to propaganda, peace with honor
and an end to lies.
</P>
<P>
   NATO misquoted him, of course. The Serbian regime responded in
shocked silence. But Yugoslavia's now-sacked deputy prime minister
and leader of the Serbian Renewal Party had struck.
</P>
<P>
   NATO was not about to break apart, he told Serbs. It was growing
stronger. Russia was not about to send its squadrons of Sukhoi
bombers to rescue Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   International public opinion had turned against Serbia after
``horrible scenes of Albanian refugees and human suffering
overwhelmed the western world.'' Serbia must be ready to accept
them back _ and to accept a U.N.-led international ``presence'' in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Even for Yugoslav viewers, this was strong stuff. Was Vuk
Draskovic preparing himself to be the ``interlocuteur valable'' of
Yugoslavia? The next president, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, NATO took what it wanted from Draskovic's
extraordinary soliloquy on the small Belgrade Studio B television
channel, happy to quote his condemnation of government ``lies'' and
his assertion that NATO is growing stronger _ but equally content
to censor out all his references to NATO's ``aggression'' against
Yugoslavia and NATO's failure to obtain U.N. Security Council
backing for its bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people have been cheated by claims from the start that
it's only a question of time before NATO breaks apart _ that
divisions are growing between Europe and the United States,''
Draskovic said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its aggression against the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia has
enabled NATO to dominate Europe and to homogenize NATO itself. So
Nato is becoming stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rumania and Bulgaria will enter Nato...it may even become a
kind of world military organization. If Russia joins...then it will
be the greatest army in the world. So it is important that the U.N.
places this machinery under international control.''
</P>
<P>
   British Defense Secretary George Robertson selectively quoted
only the first and third sentences of this remarkable statement.
Nor did NATO leaders mention Draskovic's demand that Albanian
Kosovo refugees should return home with the help of world
humanitarian organizations after ``U.N. troops have come.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was clear the Yugoslav deputy prime minister was
responding to last weekend's NATO summit in Washington, warmly
reminding his supporters that Yugoslavia was a founder member of
the U.N. and that the U.N. covenant was little different to the
constitution of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The Rambouillet and Paris agreements had, in effect, provided
for an independent Kosovo. That no longer applied.
</P>
<P>
   But it was his implicit criticism of those around President
Slobodan Milosevic that will have stung nationalist Serbs. ``Many
people talk about `unity' and `endurance,''' he said. ``But I
believe the most important thing is to understand and get a grip on
reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leaders of this country must clearly tell the people where
we are and who we're with...Will NATO break apart? Some false
prophets claim that in a couple of days we will celebrate victory
over NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``They must tell us what is the world public opinion...Let's not
lie to the people anymore that we are getting the Russian Sukhoi
(bomber), or S-300s or S-400s or military aid or that Russia is
entering World War Three.''
</P>
<P>
   World public opinion supported Yugoslavia in the first week of
the NATO bombardment, Draskovic said, because of its historical
ties with the country in two world wars.
</P>
<P>
   But the sight of human suffering among the Albanian refugees had
turned the world ``almost entirely against us _ but this is
concealed here...''
</P>
<P>
   Western countries were ``mainly reasonable and moderate.'' Words
were being misused. Why did the state media refer to ``criminal
NATO aggression'' as if aggression could ever be anything but
criminal?
</P>
<P>
   ``The other night, someone said (on the television) that the
three NATO POWs should have been taken to `Branko's Bridge' (in
Belgrade) and roasted there on a spit. I protested about this in
the Federal Government - although I'm willing to defend the media's
freedom, I demanded that these people be taken off the television
because they shame Serbia and our tradition. Serbs do not roast
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, only loose-lipped dissenters, it seems. There can be
little doubt that several leading figures in the regime delighted
in seeing Draskovic roasted for his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Novelist and journalist and leader of the democratic movement a
couple of years ago _ he and his wife were beaten up after
condemning Milosevic's government _ the deputy prime minister is
nonetheless regarded as a turncoat by many intellectuals for
joining the Milosevic coalition.
</P>
<P>
   No, he didn't cry surrender Monday. He didn't call for the
overthrow of the regime. The ``cracks'' in the government to which
Robertson referred had been there all along.
</P>
<P>
   But Draskovic's words just might provide a political path out of
a war which neither side seems able to win. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 850-word article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to
reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
