<SLUG> BC-SEASONS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THREE SEASONS': A TOUCHING FABLE ABOUT THE SEARCH FOR ROOTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(rk) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Three Seasons'' is a wistful, rain-streaked elegy for a
Vietnamese culture that is being swept away on the flood tide of
globalization. Too tenderhearted and lyrical to deliver a political
indictment, this touching film, which was chosen best dramatic
feature at the Sundance Film Festival in January, is a dreamy
cinematic poem whose interwoven voices offer different variations
of the same sad story.
</P>
<P>
   In that story, the gentle, common folk of Saigon are being left
behind as an emerging, hard-edged international culture symbolized
by Coca-Cola signs, luxury hotels and the peddling of plastic lotus
blossoms on the streets takes over the city. One of many symbols of
bald commercialization is a popular hangout once frequented by
American servicemen that is now vulgarly named the Apocalypse Now
Bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three Seasons'' is the first feature film by Tony Bui, a
26-year-old director who escaped from Vietnam with his parents when
he was 2 years old and grew up in California.
</P>
<P>
   After returning to his native country for a visit when he was
19, he became fluent in Vietnamese and went back to make a short
film, ``Yellow Lotus.'' Filmed in Saigon with a cast of Vietnamese
actors, ``Three Seasons'' portrays the Vietnamese capital as a city
of dissolving pastel colors, and the diffused palette reinforces
the film's romanticized vision of a world melting away under warm
tropical rains.
</P>
<P>
   All four of the film's principal characters are viewed as
innocent, struggling victims of economic forces beyond their
control. The opening scenes introduce us to Kien An (Nguyen Ngoc
Hiep), the latest recruit in an all-female work force hired to pick
white lotus blossoms on the temple estate of a reclusive boss.
</P>
<P>
   After gathering their crop, the women are bused to Saigon, where
they sell baskets of flowers on the streets. Business is good until
one day Kien An suddenly finds herself competing with vendors of
plastic, artificially scented imitations of the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Summoned by her mysterious employer, who has heard her singing a
work song that transports him back to his childhood, Kien An
discovers an embittered poet dying of leprosy. This once handsome
man whose face is decomposing is the film's most jarring symbol of
a traditional culture being pushed into the shadows.
</P>
<P>
   Another strand of the story follows Hai (Don Duong), a cyclo
driver who falls in love with Lan (Zoe Bui), an imperious
Vietnamese prostitute. Hai assiduously courts her by offering her
free rides from the luxury hotels in which she plies her trade.
</P>
<P>
   Lan scornfully accepts his transportation until the day he reaps
a windfall from winning a taxi race and purchases her professional
time. Beneath her hard, high-fashion exterior, he discovers a
frightened, alienated woman awash in shame and confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is Woody (Nguyen Huu Duoc), a wide-eyed street
boy who sells trinkets out of a suitcase. At the Apocalypse Now
Bar, the boy meets James Hager (Harvey Keitel), an American soldier
who has returned to Vietnam to search for his grown-up daughter.
When Hager leaves for a moment, the boy nods off and has his
suitcase stolen. Woody spends most of the rest of the movie trying
to retrieve the source of his meager livelihood in a drenching
rainstorm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three Seasons'' doesn't pretend that its stories or characters
(who all cross paths before the movie is over) are realistic. Each
is a symbolic thread in a larger fable of people searching for
their roots. The movie is so languidly paced that it occasionally
turns vague and meandering.
</P>
<P>
   And its characters, especially the adorable, saucer-eyed Woody
and the sweet, self-abasing Hai, are sentimentalized to the brink
of saintliness. So much misty sadness and soft-focus guilt swirls
around that you almost wish for a purgative eruption of anger.
</P>
<P>
   But such an eruption would violate the movie's sweetly uplifting
agenda. Determined not to revisit the Vietnam War and to open up
old wounds, ``Three Seasons'' preaches reconciliation, forgiveness,
reverence for tradition and the salvaging of all that was best
about the past.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THREE SEASONS'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Tony Bui; written (in Vietnamese, with English
subtitles) by Bui, based on a story by Bui and Timothy Linh Bui;
director of photography, Lisa Rinzler; edited by Keith Reamer;
music by Richard Horowitz, with Vietnamese songs by Vy Nhat Tao;
production designer, Wing Lee; produced by Jason Kliot, Joana
Vicente and Bui; released by October Films.
</P>
<P>
   With: Don Duong (Hai), Nguyen Ngoc Hiep (Kien An), Tran Manh
Cuong (Teacher Dao), Harvey Keitel (James Hager), Zoe Bui (Lan) and
Nguyen Huu Duoc (Woody).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 110 minutes. This film is rated PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three Seasons'' is rated PG-13. (Parents strongly cautioned).
It includes sexual situations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
