<HEADER>
A8096 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONET-RETURN-NYT &LR;      04-29 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONET-RETURN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE RESTORES A LOOTED MONET TO OWNER'S HEIRS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Almost 60 years after the collection of a wealthy
French-Jewish art dealer and collector was plundered by German
occupation forces, the French government Thursday returned a Monet
painting to the man's heirs in a ceremony that suggested greater
French enthusiasm for settling claims to looted art than has so far
been apparent.
</P>
<P>
   The 1904 oil, ``Waterlilies,'' one of a series painted by Monet
in Giverny, was taken from Paul Rosenberg in 1940 and sent to
Germany. It was returned to France in 1949, but it was only
identified as forming part of the Rosenberg collection while on
loan to the ``Monet in the 20th Century'' show at the Museum of
Fine Arts in Boston last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting France's eagerness to show its good will in restoring
stolen art returned here after World War II, Culture Minister
Catherine Trautmann presided over the hand-over at the Jeu de
Paume. Rosenberg's daughter-in-law, Elaine, and granddaughter,
Elizabeth Clark, flew here from New York. His ailing daughter,
Micheline, however, was not present.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of the Jeu de Paume for the ceremony was, in Mrs.
Trautmann's words, ``highly symbolic.'' After Germany occupied
France in June 1940, the large gallery on the Place de la Concorde
was used to store art seized from Jewish dealers and collectors.
The Monet in question was also displayed there between 1950 and
1973 as part of a permanent Impressionist exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   After it was taken from Rosenberg's villa near Bordeaux, in
September 1940, however, this painting was not in fact brought to
the Jeu de Paume. It was appropriated by the German Embassy in
Paris and sent to German Foreign Minister Joachim von Ribbentrop,
who included it in his private collection. After the war, the
painting was among thousands of stolen works recovered in Germany
and returned to France. Most were restored to their owners or their
heirs, including 160 paintings recovered by Rosenberg, but the
owners of some 2,000 paintings were never identified by the French
government. The best works were distributed among French museums,
with Rosenberg's Monet on display at the Musee des Beaux Arts in
Caen, Normandy, since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, however, American journalist Hector Feliciano published
a book in France, ``Le Musee Disparu'' (``The Lost Museum''), that
accused the French government of making minimal efforts to trace
the rightful owners of stolen works of art in its possession. The
book also prompted the heirs of numerous prewar collectors to renew
their search for missing paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Elaine Rosenberg sent a photograph of the missing
``Waterlilies'' to a London-based registry that operates a database
of stolen art. The organization reported that the photograph
matched a Monet at the museum in Caen. But it was only in November
that the family found the painting in the Boston exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   The culture minister said Thursday that this Monet was the
seventh painting to be returned to its legal owner since 1996, but
she noted that ``it will be always be a mystery'' why the work was
not identified by either Rosenberg, who died in 1959, or by French
officials, since it was on permanent display in France and was
loaned to exhibitions abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Feliciano was not convinced. ``The big mystery is why the
government had pictures for 50 years that didn't belong to them,''
he said in a telephone interview from New York. ``It returns
pictures only when it is under pressure. But it still does not
actively look for the owners.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 1539EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8099 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     04-29 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANAGEMENT BOOK TELLS WHAT MAKES EMPLOYEES UNHAPPY AND WHY THEY
QUIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At last, a management book with a huge amount of statistical
evidence behind it that is set squarely in the real world of
business.
</P>
<P>
   Forget perks, parties, bonuses and parking spots, this book
suggests. The best and brightest employees say that what they want,
more than anything else, is to have a great boss.
</P>
<P>
   Not some jovial CEO at the top smiling down on the peons, but
rather an immediate supervisor who answers the most basic needs of
his or her direct employees, whether they are waiters or bond
sellers.
</P>
<P>
   And from the viewpoint of the other side, the boss, this book
throws out the management theories of hundreds of books as if they
were hogwash.
</P>
<P>
   After extensive surveying, here is one of the revolutionary
ideas of the good manager:
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't change that much. Don't waste time trying to put
in what was left out. Try to draw out what was left in. That is
hard enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Bits of unconventional managerial wisdom such as this are handed
down in the insightful book ``First, Break All The Rules: What the
World's Greatest Managers Do Differently'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, 271
pages, $25).
</P>
<P>
   The book is written clearly and concisely by Marcus Buckingham
and Curt Coffman. Both are employed by the well-known Gallup Poll.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of this book is based on two large studies conducted
by Gallup over a span of 25 years. The first asked 1 million
employees what they wanted most out of their company; the second
asked 80,000 managers, identified as talented by performance
measures in their companies, how they manage. Both questions sought
to pinpoint gray, nebulous areas of measuring that hundreds of
management books have tried to define.
</P>
<P>
   The results of this survey are eye-popping.
</P>
<P>
   What it found was not the Jacuzzi-in-every-bathroom mentality
brought out by such surveys as ``The Best Hundred Companies to Work
For.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, by comparing positive and negative responses to rating
their managers, the study found the first real link between
employee opinion and business unit performance, across many
different companies. If the employees answered Gallup's questions
positively, the unit was ahead of the curve in productivity, sales
or other rankings; if the response was negative, the unit's
performance was lacking.
</P>
<P>
   And the positive responses to 12 specific questions that
identified those happy, productive employees were formed mostly
through the performance of their immediate supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had discovered that the manager _ not pay, benefits, perks
or a charismatic corporate leader _ was the critical player in
building a strong workplace,'' the authors write. ``The manager was
the key. ... People leave managers, not companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the most powerful questions Gallup asked employees to
determine their happiness were:
</P>
<P>
   _Do I know what is expected of me at work?
</P>
<P>
   _Do I have the materials and equipment I need to do my work
right?
</P>
<P>
   _In the past seven days, have I received recognition or praise
for good work?
</P>
<P>
   Direct, defined questions. Much different from the Perk a Day
mentality of most companies who have come to realize that their
most valuable asset is their employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that these employee-focused initiatives are
unimportant. It's just that your immediate manager is more
important,'' Buckingham and Coffman write. ``If your relationship
with your manager is fractured, then no amount of in-chair
massaging or company-sponsored dog walking will persuade you to
stay and perform. It is better to work for a great manager in an
old-fashioned company than for a terrible manager in a company
offering an enlightened, employee-focused culture.''
</P>
<P>
   The study of managers' opinions on how to manage successfully in
today's climate is equally enlightening. Buckingham and Coffman
also create a practical guide to hiring, firing, defining roles,
focusing on strengths and managing around weaknesses, again based
on the survey of thousands of managers.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the best, most practical, books I've seen on
managing in the six years I've been reviewing books. It should not
be missed.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs
</P>
<P>
   ``Polish Your People Skills''
</P>
<P>
   By Bobbi Linkemer
</P>
<P>
   Amacom, $39.95
</P>
<P>
   Interpersonal skills are among the most important in surviving
and thriving in the work force. But where do you learn them? This
book, complete with interactive CD-ROM, focuses on working with
others. One section talks about creating positive relationships by
learning how to become a team player and learning to negotiate.
Other sections discuss dealing with difficult situations and
difficult people. The author is a communications consultant.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Smart Guide to Managing Your Time''
</P>
<P>
   By Lisa Rogak
</P>
<P>
   John Wiley &AMP; Sons, $10.95
</P>
<P>
   If you can manage the time to read this short volume, you might
get some worthwhile tips on managing your time. This book looks at
ways that you might be procrastinating, planning your schedule and
learning to say no when necessary. The average person spends 16
years working and 15 sleeping. What you do with those waking hours
can be analyzed in a logical sequence with this book.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``How You Play the Game: Lessons from Life from the
Billion-Dollar Business of Sports''
</P>
<P>
   By Jerry Colangelo
</P>
<P>
   Amacom, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   If you aren't sports-minded, you won't recognize the author's
name, but Jerry Colangelo brought the Chicago Bulls basketball team
to glory as he helped created it and is now owner of the Phoenix
Suns and the Arizona Diamondbacks. Now, in this autobiography, he
tells readers how all of his hard work, faith and good luck made
him so successful. If you think business lessons from an industry
that is largely subsidized by public tax dollars can teach you
anything, read on.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
