<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONET-RETURN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE RESTORES A LOOTED MONET TO OWNER'S HEIRS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to append art note)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Almost 60 years after the collection of a wealthy
French-Jewish art dealer and collector was plundered by German
occupation forces, the French government Thursday returned a Monet
painting to the man's heirs in a ceremony that suggested greater
French enthusiasm for settling claims to looted art than has so far
been apparent.
</P>
<P>
   The 1904 oil, ``Waterlilies,'' one of a series painted by Monet
in Giverny, was taken from Paul Rosenberg in 1940 and sent to
Germany. It was returned to France in 1949, but it was only
identified as forming part of the Rosenberg collection while on
loan to the ``Monet in the 20th Century'' show at the Museum of
Fine Arts in Boston last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting France's eagerness to show its good will in restoring
stolen art returned here after World War II, Culture Minister
Catherine Trautmann presided over the hand-over at the Jeu de
Paume. Rosenberg's daughter-in-law, Elaine, and granddaughter,
Elizabeth Clark, flew here from New York. His ailing daughter,
Micheline, however, was not present.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of the Jeu de Paume for the ceremony was, in Mrs.
Trautmann's words, ``highly symbolic.'' After Germany occupied
France in June 1940, the large gallery on the Place de la Concorde
was used to store art seized from Jewish dealers and collectors.
The Monet in question was also displayed there between 1950 and
1973 as part of a permanent Impressionist exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   After it was taken from Rosenberg's villa near Bordeaux, in
September 1940, however, this painting was not in fact brought to
the Jeu de Paume. It was appropriated by the German Embassy in
Paris and sent to German Foreign Minister Joachim von Ribbentrop,
who included it in his private collection. After the war, the
painting was among thousands of stolen works recovered in Germany
and returned to France. Most were restored to their owners or their
heirs, including 160 paintings recovered by Rosenberg, but the
owners of some 2,000 paintings were never identified by the French
government. The best works were distributed among French museums,
with Rosenberg's Monet on display at the Musee des Beaux Arts in
Caen, Normandy, since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, however, American journalist Hector Feliciano published
a book in France, ``Le Musee Disparu'' (``The Lost Museum''), that
accused the French government of making minimal efforts to trace
the rightful owners of stolen works of art in its possession. The
book also prompted the heirs of numerous prewar collectors to renew
their search for missing paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Elaine Rosenberg sent a photograph of the missing
``Waterlilies'' to a London-based registry that operates a database
of stolen art. The organization reported that the photograph
matched a Monet at the museum in Caen. But it was only in November
that the family found the painting in the Boston exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   The culture minister said Thursday that this Monet was the
seventh painting to be returned to its legal owner since 1996, but
she noted that ``it will be always be a mystery'' why the work was
not identified by either Rosenberg, who died in 1959, or by French
officials, since it was on permanent display in France and was
loaned to exhibitions abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Feliciano was not convinced. ``The big mystery is why the
government had pictures for 50 years that didn't belong to them,''
he said in a telephone interview from New York. ``It returns
pictures only when it is under pressure. But it still does not
actively look for the owners.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
