<HEADLINE>
`YOU'VE GOT MAIL' TOPS THE STACK OF NEW RELEASES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ To paraphrase a recent New York cartoon on
independent films: ``Too many videos _ too little time.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, like indie films, there is never a shortage of video and
DVD product _ a lot of it of dubious merit, though. But this week
and next, there's a wide array of interesting stuff _ whether
you're in the mood for the lightly romantic or wish to trip the
light ``Future Fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt the big event in next Tuesday's releases will be
``You've Got Mail'' from Warners, which comes out on VHS ($22.95)
and DVD ($24.98). ``Mail'' was a big hit last December as the
holiday feel-good movie, and why not? Its stars, Tom Hanks and Meg
Ryan, are just so gosh darn cute together.
</P>
<P>
   The film brings back the ``Sleepless in Seattle'' team,
including director Nora Ephron. As a remake of Ernst Lubitsch's
1940 film ``The Shop Around the Corner,'' Ephron's film never
achieves a ``counterpoint between sadness and gaiety that
represents the Lubitsch touch,'' as film critic Andrew Sarris
described it. Nevertheless, ``Mail'' didn't lack charm, taking the
story of two rival store clerks who are having an anonymous romance
through the post and updating it into the electronic age.
</P>
<P>
   So, e-mail and the Internet play a part in the film _ along with
a part of the DVD. If your computer plays DVD-ROM, you can link up
with other ``Mail'' fans, enter chat rooms, send ``Mail'' Web
greeting cards, build your own Web page and search for your own
online romance (success not guaranteed). Meanwhile, the DVD also
contains cast interviews, commentary from Ephron, and a comparison
between scenes in ``Mail'' and ``Shop'' and another film version of
the story, the 1949 musical-comedy ``In the Good Old Summertime,''
with Judy Garland and Van Johnson. Oh, yeah, you can also watch the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   FICTION AS POSSIBLE FACT: One of the most amazing things about
``Future Fantastic,'' a co-production of the BBC and The Learning
Channel that looks at science fiction as possible science fact, is
just how relaxed Gillian Anderson appears. As repressed FBI agent
Dana Scully on ``The X-Files,'' Anderson often has a look on her
face like her shoes are too tight, but as host of ``Future,'' she
seems to be having fun and not taking it all that seriously. And
that is the best way to approach ``Future,'' which manages to be
relatively entertaining as it speculates about scientific
developments, some of which sound loopy, but they probably said
that about the light bulb. The double cassette from BBC Video,
which is released this week, is priced at $29.95, and covers such
topics as cybernetics, longevity and, of course, the possibility of
alien visitations.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, BBC Video also put out ``Intimate Universe: The Human
Body,'' which tracks the development of the human body, from
conception to death, with _ you guessed it _ speculation about the
great beyond. The four volume set, which was also a co-production
with The Learning Channel, lists at $59.95.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVIS REVISITED: The phrase ``You talking to me?'' has almost
become a humorous cliche, but when Travis Bickle (Robert De Niro)
said it in Martin Scorsese's 1976 film ``Taxi Driver'' it was truly
frightening. On Tuesday, Columbia is releasing a VHS special
edition ($14.95) of the landmark film, which includes a 20-minute
documentary on the making of ``Taxi Driver.'' A wide-screen version
also is available at $19.95.
</P>
<P>
   But real fans of Scorsese's dark vision, which also starred a
young Jodie Foster as a teen prostitute, may want to wait until
June 1, when the DVD comes out. Digitally remastered for audio and
video, the DVD will include a 70-minute making-of documentary and
have a suggested price of $19.95. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 1556EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0187 </DOCNO>
