<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8123 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-POLITICALADS-0     04-29 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICALADS-0430-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITH PHONY ARAFATS AND TRANCE MUSIC, ISRAEL'S POLITICAL ADS GET
TOP RATINGS
 &HT;    500&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The casts feature heroic commandos, the plots are
rife with menacing conspiracies and the soundtrack includes a
psychedelic version of the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Israeli political advertising makes for a prime-time
smash.
</P>
<P>
   Television advertising began this week for the candidates and
parties in Israel's May 17 elections. Under the country's elections
law, all ads are shown nightly in a block of time provided by the
government on two national channels.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of a country famous for life-and-death issues and masses
of news addicts, the premier Monday night was the highest rated
event on television, with nearly a third of the country's six
million people tuning in.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to watch it because the day after, every one is
talking about it and you want to be with them,'' said Niva Bar-On,
a 47-year-old social worker.
</P>
<P>
   The ads appear after the evening news programs, which themselves
have always drawn high ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising time is doled out according to the size of the
political party and dozens of parties are vying for seats in
parliament. There are five candidates for prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   It makes for a 40-minute series of commercials that provide a
view of the changing, always tense and sometimes humorous Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the ads are becoming less focused on issues and more
on candidates, a sign that American styles for campaigning have
crept into Israel just as they have for cuisine and dress. In fact,
shows competing unsuccessfully with the ads on their first night
included the popular American sitcoms ``The Fresh Prince of
Bel-Air'' and ``Caroline In The City.''
</P>
<P>
   And, while the ads become more American, many also have Russian
subtitles, a nod to immigrants from the former Soviet Union who now
make up more than 15 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile there's some sizzle. A party advocating the
legalization of marijuana invokes psychedelic graphics and a trance
rock version of Israel's solemn national anthem. A religious party
shows its animated logo emerging from a note crammed between the
blocks in the sacred Western Wall. The logo bows repeatedly in the
way customary for Orthodox prayer.
</P>
<P>
   The featured prime-time battle, though, is between the left-wing
Labor and the right-wing Likud parties.
</P>
<P>
   From Labor, Israelis view old photographs of candidate Ehud
Barak receiving a medal from slain Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin and
disguised as an airplane technician while storming a hijacked jet.
</P>
<P>
   Pitted against this hero is the villainous Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu. Labor shows a video clip of Netanyahu winking
in slow motion to one of his cronies. ``The only plan he has,''
viewers are told, ``is to lie.''
</P>
<P>
   But Netanyahu's Likud has a show of its own, casting him as the
hero.
</P>
<P>
   The villain is now Barak and he has a secret ally portrayed in
one Likud ad as a trembling hand marking the days until the
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's somebody who wants Barak to win,'' says the narrator.
``Then the day will come when he gets everything he wants.'' As the
camera pans back, the hand leads to an actor in the famous head
scarf and fatigues of Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Experts say ads in previous years were more playful, but
American influences have made campaigns more serious and
professional. James Carville, a campaign adviser for U.S. President
Bill Clinton, is one of several American consultants on the Israeli
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Yoram Peri, professor of communications at Hebrew University in
Jerusalem said candidates are taking American advice to repeat
their themes and simplify their messages.
</P>
<P>
   He found more focus on the candidate and less on issues. Barak
is shown jogging with his wife and shaking hands with Clinton -- a
popular figure across most of the Israeli political spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   But all the ads face a tough audience. Polls show only about 10
percent of Israelis are undecided in the upcoming vote. As people
who serve compulsory stints in the army and face spells of
terrorism and turmoil, they are hard to impress.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does Barak have to say, that he was in the army?'' asks
22-year-old Golan Hermon, a Netanyahu supporter. ``So what? So was
I.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
