<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREK-VINCENT-DONOFRIO-IN-THE-THIRTEENTH-FLOOR-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTN: CALIFORNIA 
 VINCENT D'ONOFRIO GETS OFF AT `THE THIRTEENTH FLOOR' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Inside Trek
science-fiction column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Vincent
D'Onofrio in a scene from ``The Thirteenth Floor.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    For a guy who's a regular on the science-fiction screen, Vincent
D'Onofrio has surprisingly little good to say about science
fiction.
 &HT;    ``As an audience member I'm usually not interested in them,''
the actor says. ``I think a lot of sci-fi is done very poorly.
 &HT;    ``I wasn't into comic books as a kid, and I wasn't very big on
`Star Trek' or anything like that,'' he adds. ``As an actor,
though, I can sometimes get pulled away from my vision of me
fancying myself a dramatic actor if the sci-fi is interesting
enough.''
 &HT;    The sci-fi of Barry Sonnenfeld's ``Men in Black'' (1997)
stimulated D'Onofrio enough to take on the physically tricky role
of a farmer-turned-alien-cockroach in what turned out to be a
blockbuster hit. And ``The Thirteenth Floor,'' D'Onofrio's latest
cinematic journey into the otherworldly, captured his imagination
as well.
 &HT;    Based on Daniel F. Galouye's novel ``Simulacron-3'' and
co-produced by Roland Emmerich of ``StarGate'' (1994) and
``Independence Day'' (1996) fame, ``Thirteenth Floor'' centers on
an enigmatic tycoon (Armin Mueller-Stahl) whose death has
unexpected ramifications for his right-hand man (Craig Bierko), a
cop (Dennis Haysbert), a mystery woman (Gretchen Mol) and a
computer genius named Whitney, played by D'Onofrio.
 &HT;    The plot thickens when it's revealed that all of the characters
are leading parallel lives in 1937, and that none of them may be
who they believe they are.
 &HT;    The versatile D'Onofrio _ whose credits include Stanley
Kubrick's ``Full Metal Jacket'' (1987), the genre outing ``Strange
Days'' (1995) and ``The Newton Boys'' (1998) _ thus plays two roles
in the May 28 release: the mild-mannered, emotional Whitney and the
mean-spirited, dry Ashton, a bartender at a swanky Los Angeles
night club.
 &HT;    ``What I do first with any character is to work on posture, what
he wears, how he looks and talks, the exterior stuff,'' the
soft-spoken 39-year-old says by telephone from his New York home.
``Then I cover the interior _ how he feels and reacts, and what he
thinks.
 &HT;    ``In this particular case,'' he says, ``I had to do everything
twice and make sure that I wasn't giving anything away too soon or
too late. That was interesting _ that was my challenge. You don't
fall asleep on the set, let's put it that way.
 &HT;    ``I tried hard, but it's always a crap shoot,'' the actor
concludes, ``because once you leave the set and the film is done
shooting, it's up to the filmmakers to sort out whatever they've
got of you on film. So I hope what I tried to achieve is on the
screen.''
 &HT;    Beyond D'Onofrio's dual performances, moviegoers heading up to
``The Thirteenth Floor'' can count on dazzling special effects,
stylized imagery and a complex plot that blurs the lines between
life and death, present and past, reality and virtual reality.
 &HT;    ``I hope `The Thirteenth Floor' is thinking man's sci-fi,'' the
actor says. ``Basically, though, it's a technological thriller, a
film designed to thrill and to entertain.''
 &HT;    D'Onofrio himself could use a doppelganger, so busy has he been
of late. In the next few months he'll turn up in ``Abbie,'' a
biopic he produced and stars in as 1960s activist Abbie Hoffman, as
well as in the black comedy ``Successful People'' and ``The
Velocity of Gary,'' a drama about AIDS, death and love in which he
co-stars with Salma Hayek. He'll even keep his science-fiction hand
in with a segment of the anthology ``Alien Love Triangle.''
 &HT;    ``I don't want to give too much away about `Alien Love
Triangle,''' the actor says. ``My segment is called `The
Impostors.' It's with Gary Sinise, Tony Shalhoub and me, and it's
directed by Gary Fleder.
 &HT;    ``I've seen the segment and it's great,'' he says. ``There's
this one amazing, amazing scene with Gary that you've just got to
see. It's me interrogating Gary _ and no, I'm not an alien.''
 &HT;    But back to ``The Thirteenth Floor.'' By opening the film on May
28, Columbia Pictures is gambling big that it can find an audience
in the shadow of ``Star Wars: The Phantom Menace.''
 &HT;    Does D'Onofrio think the ``Floor'' plan will work?
 &HT;    ``I'm hoping we do well,'' he says. ``I'm a little skeptical,
though, because it is going to be the summer of `Star Wars.'
 &HT;    ``I understand the idea of counter-programming us and,
hopefully, `The Thirteenth Floor' will stand on its own. You can
only hope for the best.'' 
 -0- 
 NEXT WEEK  
 &HT;    Rick McCallum, producer of ``Star Wars: The Phantom Menace,''
talks about the year's hottest sci-fi film.
