<SLUG> BC-ADOPTION-KOSOVO-$ADV02-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADOPTION AGENCIES, GOVERNMENT ADVISE AGAINST KOSOVO ADOPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 2)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Heart-rending images of refugee children from
Kosovo have led to hundreds of adoption inquiries, but the
government and private agencies are advising prospective parents
that now is not the time to try to bring the children to this
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We applaud the concern people have for Kosovo, but adoption is
not feasible at this point,'' said Maureen Evans, executive
director of the Joint Council on International Children's Services
of Cheverly, Md., which represents licensed international adoption
agencies and parent and advocacy groups.
</P>
<P>
   Evans explained that with conditions so unsettled among the
estimated 500,000 Kosovars forced from their homes by Serbian
troops, children depicted as orphans in television and newspaper
accounts may actually have relatives who can care for them.
</P>
<P>
   Adoption is not a realistic possibility until relief workers
have sufficient time to sort out who is temporarily separated from
parents, who has relatives elsewhere and who is truly an orphan,
Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department is echoing this view. ``In a crisis
situation such as Kosovo is experiencing at the present time, it
can be extremely difficult to determine if children whose parents
are missing are truly orphans,'' says a statement on a department
page on the Internet. For those who are orphans, ``staying with
relatives in extended family units is generally a better solution
than uprooting the child completely.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokeswoman Nyda Budig said officials also put
the statement on its phone-options menu. The agency's Office of
Children's Issues _ which oversees international adoptions _ has
been ``inundated'' with hundreds of adoption inquiries since
U.S.-led NATO forces began the air war March 24 over Serbia, she
said. Serbia is Yugoslavia's dominant republic, and the rebellious
Kosovo is its southernmost province.
</P>
<P>
   Adoption agency officials say they are used to a surge of
interest any time an international crisis puts displaced children
on the nightly TV news and newspaper front pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever there's a lot of media attention, when you see the
heart-breaking images, that's when we get the calls,'' said Andrea
Stawitcke, executive director of Bay Area Adoption Services, based
in Mountain View, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Stawitcke said her agency has received about two dozen phone
calls and e-mail inquiries about Kosovo-related adoptions.
</P>
<P>
   The exact number of refugee children separated from their
parents is difficult to determine. About 800 Kosovar Albanian
parents have reported missing children that so far have not been
found on International Red Cross lists of children alone. The
actual number may be much higher.
</P>
<P>
   Another complicating factor is the uncertain legal status of
refugee children. Under U.S. immigration law, only children legally
classified as ``orphans'' can gain admittance to the United States.
To qualify, children must have parents who are be dead or who have
abandoned them. Such children typically reside in orphanages when
adopted.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatively, a child qualifies as an orphan if a surviving
parent has ``irrevocably released the child for emigration and
adoption,'' and says so in writing, according to a U.S. Immigration
and Naturalization Service advisory to prospective adopting
parents.
</P>
<P>
   The INS requires a mountain of paperwork to complete an
international adoption, including proof that the pertinent foreign
nation's laws for obtaining custody have been obeyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. must have diplomatic relations with the country and
an embassy through which the paperwork can be processed,'' said
Stawitcke. ``Otherwise, with few exceptions, the INS won't let them
in.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. diplomatic ties to Yugoslavia have been broken since the
start of the NATO air campaign. ``There is no relationship,'' said
Tomilee Harding, executive director of Christian World Adoption in
Hendersonville, N.C., which has fielded ``a couple dozen''
inquiries since the bombing began.
</P>
<P>
   Harding says her group also counsels parents not to pursue a
Kosovo-related adoption. ``You really want to help these children,
but you have to be cautious,'' Harding said. ``You have to remember
you're dealing with human lives forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Bouwma of Bethany Christian Services of Grand Rapids,
Mich., which runs an orphanage and group home for children in
Albania, said refugees are arriving at border crossings to
neighboring Albania and Macedonia with no paperwork of any kind,
let alone documents that might form the basis of an international
adoption.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he added, ``this is not a child-supply frenzy that we
should be jumping into.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, relief agencies must concentrate on ``trying to help
these kids put their lives back together where they are,'' Bouwma
said. Eventually, he added, some of the refugee children might be
eligible for adoption. But that stage is ``a long, long way down
the road, as we see it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The State Department's recorded message on Kosovo adoptions can
be reached by dialing 202-736-7000. The same statement is on the
Internet at http://travel.state.gov.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
