A8156 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-ENTRAPMENT-TEX     04-29 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ENTRAPMENT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OLDEST ACTION HERO: HEY, MR. CONNERY: IT'S TIME TO SAY NEVER
AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unlike ``The Matrix,'' which says that nothing is what it seems
in a virtual sense, ``Entrapment'' lays out a
nothing-is-as-it-seems story the old-fashioned way. It's stuffed
with plot turns and character revelations that hark back to stylish
caper movies such the Cary Grant/Audrey Hepburn picture
``Charade,'' and the Steve McQueen/Faye Dunaway film ``The Thomas
Crown Affair.''
</P>
<P>
   (A ``Crown'' remake with Pierce Brosnan is scheduled for release
later this year.)
</P>
<P>
   Like those movies, ``Entrapment'' depends mightily on the
presence of its stars, Sean Connery and the remarkable Catherine
Zeta-Jones, to do much of its work. The sheer charming sex appeal
of movie stars doing bad things, to the world and each other,
shouldn't be discounted.
</P>
<P>
   And it's paced a little slower, as well. In fact, the lolling
rhythm of director Jon Amiel is a contradiction to the 100 percent
crank that action directors add to movement sequences these days.
``Entrapment'' starts with a risky robbery of a masterpiece
painting from a skyscraper _ the kind of audacious burglary that
put an end to the phrase ``second-story man,'' and gives new
meaning to ``cat burglar.''
</P>
<P>
   But the low-key quality that Amiel gives the film seems almost
willfully benign. Zeta-Jones is the insurance investigator obsessed
with bringing in the master thief (Connery) who has eluded capture.
She stalks her prey, and goes undercover to apprehend him. Or does
she?
</P>
<P>
   When Connery shows up on the scene as the 60-year-old superthief
who has perplexed investigators forever, cinema's legendary
no-nonsense guy cuts a fine figure. But he looks his age. And as
Zeta-Jones circles him in the push-and-pull dance of opposites
attracting, we have a hard time looking at this screen romance
between a lush babe and a man who seems old enough to be her
grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   Even though we tend to cut Connery a lot of slack for his bluff,
bare-knuckled persona, it's embarrassing to witness this tableau.
We shake our heads in disbelief that this nearly 70-year-old man
can romp through these stunts, outrunning and outperforming a
twentysomething woman whose workout to prepare for their big theft
is like some strenuous, soft-core version of tae-bo. (He can't
blame being forced into this on ``Entrapment's'' producers, either;
Connery is one of the film's producers.)
</P>
<P>
   Connery gives one of his greatest performances here _ he does
all of this stuff with a straight face. When it comes to old-school
masculinity maintaining its hairy-chested cool in crisis, no one is
better than Connery. He still has the burly self-possession and
regal bearing of a tiger. His bemused gravitas and baritone purr
are what we go to the movies for, and they're almost enough to make
us forget that scene in ``The Avengers'' _ all nine of us who saw
it _ when we cringe because Ralph Fiennes hits him and Connery's
age registers more than it ever has.
</P>
<P>
   Zeta-Jones has the physical confidence of a movie star, not to
mention good looks bestowed by the gods. ``Entrapment,'' with its
high-tech devices and low-impact story, has a supporting cast that
helps enormously in keeping it going. Ving Rhames is Connery's tech
support, Will Patton plays Zeta-Jones' boss, and Maury Chaykin is
Zeta-Jones' bratty equipment supplier.
</P>
<P>
   By the last third of the movie, there's some jeopardy and
tension going. ``Entrapment'' begins to work up a sweat with its
gambit-switching, which is intent on leaving you unsure where the
characters stand with each other. But by then, you may no longer
care.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Entrapment''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Jon Amiel
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Sean Connery, Catherine Zeta-Jones
</P>
<P>
   Length: 113 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ violence, adult language and situations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
