<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOMATOES ASIDE, NAFTA IS A PEACHY DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Give some of the credit to La Nina. But give most of it to La
NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking tomatoes here.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on where you live in this party to the tripartite
(United States-Mexico-Canada) North American Free Trade Agreement,
you may, if you frequent the produce sections of supermarkets, have
detected a significant drop in the price of tomatoes during the
past month.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the mild, warm weather sent our way by the South
Pacific water nymph, most tomato growers have hauled in good
harvests, creating a welcome supply-over-demand ratio for U.S.
tomato consumers. NAFTA has made the deal even juicier for U.S.
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the free-trade agreement, Mexican tomato growers have
a decided advantage over Florida tomato growers. Because Mexican
tomatoes are cheaper, U.S. supermarket chains get 65 percent of
their tomatoes from Mexico and 35 percent from Florida. That's just
the reverse of the way that things stood tomato-wise before NAFTA
jumped from concept to reality in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Understandably, Florida tomato growers are not happy. Some of
them are going out of business. To all of them, the five-letter
acronym NAFTA is a four-letter word.
</P>
<P>
   California Brussels sprouts growers and Washington apple growers
also know the feeling.
</P>
<P>
   NAFTA obviously has its winners and losers. But overwhelmingly,
it is a winning proposition. Most farmers in all three countries
are benefiting from it.
</P>
<P>
   But we're talking more than fruits and vegetables here.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking about a mushrooming escalation of trade in all
kinds of goods among the three countries. That increase in trade
can be readily discerned from the interminable caravans of
tractor-trailers snaking their way northward and southward through
Texas to other parts of the United States, Canada and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The downside of that trade is traffic congestion on the
interstate highways. That vehicular coagulation has become so heavy
that a lobby called the North America's Superhighway Coalition has
been formed to press for increased federal funding to expand and
maintain Interstate 35 from Texas to North Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   Congestion spawned by trade, however, is a good problem to have.
And the need for highway construction that it causes has the effect
of creating more construction jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs, of course, are NAFTA's primary reason for being. It's
creating them in all three countries.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of NAFTA used to speak of a ``great sucking sound'' by
way of suggesting that U.S. jobs would be lost to Mexico because of
cheap labor in that country. But the United States is enjoying
historically low unemployment rates, and there is mounting evidence
of sucking in both directions. That trend was underscored
spectacularly a month ago when United Copper Industries opened a
manufacturing plant, corporate headquarters and national
distribution center in Denton.
</P>
<P>
   United Copper Industries is a wholly owned subsidiary of the
giant Mexican conglomerate Unida. Its $35 million,
373,000-square-foot complex in the North Central Texas university
town will employ 250 workers by this fall. Expansion plans indicate
that the plant eventually will hire more than 800 workers.
</P>
<P>
   The copper rod mill and wire and cable plant is believed to be
the first manufacturing plant built from scratch in this country by
a Mexican company. Some Mexican companies have acquired U.S.
factories or partnered with U.S. companies to build them. United
Copper's parent company is involved in joint ventures with General
Electric.
</P>
<P>
   But the real significance of the United Copper plant is that it
contradicts the sucking-sound predictions. Workers at the Denton
plant will average $37,000 to $38,000 a year. United Copper built
the U.S. plant because it needed a skilled labor force to operate
its high-tech, high-speed machines.
</P>
<P>
   It also needed the location along the NAFTA superhighway, I-35,
and near Dallas/Fort Worth Airport, Alliance Airport and the
railroad junctions in the area for shipping its products all over
the country.
</P>
<P>
   United Copper is not likely to remain unique for long. Other
Mexican companies will build plants here for the same reasons.
European and Canadian companies, of course, were doing so before
NAFTA, and their numbers have grown since its inception.
</P>
<P>
   So we really are talking more than the price of tomatoes here.
We're talking bunches of additional jobs growing throughout the
NAFTA area, and a lot of green in the pockets and bank accounts of
Americans, Canadians and Mexicans.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
