r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     04-29 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEALING WITH GUESTS WHO GO BUMP IN THE NIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Being awakened by Casper-the-not-so-friendly ghost at 2 in the
morning is on my list of most frightening experiences ever. There
we were, face to face, his high-pitched wails blending with my
soprano screams.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as I could control the shaking in my limbs, I ran out of
our bedroom so quickly that I left skid marks on the carpet.
</P>
<P>
   It all started with a run-of-the-mill sleepover one Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' I said to my son. ``Just don't invite that snoring
kid. He could wake the dead. You know I'm a light sleeper.''
</P>
<P>
   I picked the boys up after school, and they spent the afternoon
playing basketball in our driveway. After dinner, they played some
more until someone suggested telling ghost stories.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I did it. I made the suggestion, but I love to tell ghost
stories around a campfire. We didn't have a campfire, so we turned
out the lights and lit a candle. The stories got scarier and
scarier until my husband wrapped it up with his retelling of ``The
Headless Horseman.''
</P>
<P>
   When the boys bedded down, I suggested that we turn on the night
light.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' responded my son, who always uses a night light.
``Only babies use night lights.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, I'm not sure whether it was the spicy pizza or the tall
tales, but I soon found myself dreaming of ghosts and goblins. I
was running for my life in the twilight of my consciousness when I
felt a soft tap on my shoulder. My eyes flew open and there he was,
right at my bedside: the headless horseman himself!
</P>
<P>
   I screamed. He screamed. My husband sprang out of bed. All I
could see in the darkness was a pale, glowing mass waving its arms
like a Ninja windmill.
</P>
<P>
   Then the ghost spoke, ``Can I sleep in here?''
</P>
<P>
   After that, all you could hear was the pitter-patter of my feet
leaving the building.
</P>
<P>
   I was starting the car when I heard my husband's laughter.
``Honey, come back. It's only Dillon, our little guest.''
</P>
<P>
   I peeked through the door and sure enough, it was little Dillon
in a white T-whirt and white shorts. ``Can I sleep in here,'' he
asked again with tears on the rim of his blue eyes.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, I found my son's sleeping bag in the attic and slept
on the floor of his room so that Dillon and everyone else could get
some rest.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, after Dillon had gone home, my son said: ``Can I
have a friend over next weekend? We don't have school on Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just take a break next weekend. Maybe the following
weekend will be OK,'' I answered vaguely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great. Hmmm, now who should I invite?'' he pondered.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, son, did I ever tell you how much I like your little
snoring friend? He's such a nice boy.''
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
