<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8181 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEB-MISSING-HNS &LR;      04-29 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-MISSING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SITE PLAYS ROLE IN FINDING MISSING GIRL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATHERINE SELIGMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A 5-year-old California girl was reunited with
her mother after a resident of a small Mexican town recognized the
faces of the missing child and her alleged abductor, the girl's
father, on an Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time the Polly Klaas Foundation's 3-year-old Web
site can be directly credited with solving a case, said Jenny
Thompson, a spokeswoman for the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Sonoma County authorities said the person in Mexico, who
requested confidentiality, had contacted the Petaluma, Calif.-based
foundation with details on the whereabouts of the girl. Foundation
officials gave the information to the district attorney's office in
Sonoma County, which had been working on the case since the girl
disappeared Jan. 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``This person just happened to be on the Web, picked it up and
put two and two together,'' said Sonoma County Deputy District
Attorney Ray Donnelly. ``It was the tip that got (the suspect) back
to the States ... We want to give full credit to that site.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Garstecki, 34, the girl's father, was deported from
Mexico on April 23 and is being held in Ajo, Ariz., on charges of
child stealing. An extradition hearing that would send him back to
California is pending.
</P>
<P>
   The girl ran into her mother's arms last weekend and was
``pleased to be back,'' according to Kristin Allen, the district
attorney's investigator on the case. The girl appeared
undernourished and was extremely dirty, Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had clothing on that didn't fit her by a long shot,''
Allen said. ``She had toddler clothes on and a pair of shoes that
were two sizes too small, and it looked like she'd been wearing
them a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen said additional charges could be filed against Garstecki,
depending on how the girl had been treated.
</P>
<P>
   Garstecki had been sighted at a former home in Joshua Tree in
San Bernardino County, Calif., and in Las Vegas, Allen said. The
man reportedly been working in the computer field while a fugitive
and was living in a house with his daughter when he was
apprehended, Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   The girl's mother, who has sole custody, declined comment
Wednesday, but told foundation officials she was grateful for
public support and help during her ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said foundation workers were excited about the role the
Web site had played. ``It's rare that you know this is why'' the
case was solved, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation had passed out brochures about the girl when her
father allegedly failed to return the girl to her mother at the
Santa Rosa Police Department after a visit.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site posted several pictures of the smiling child, who
was among 20 other missing children from the western United States
listed there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
