<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO: DVD ABOUT `TAXI DRIVER'; SLAMDANCE FILM FEST; NEW
RELEASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking Under the Hood
</P>
<P>
   Documentaries about the making of movies are turning up
frequently on digital videodisc, but a good one will be available
next week on videocassette.
</P>
<P>
   The film is ``Taxi Driver'' (1976), Martin Scorsese's dark
classic about the disturbed Travis Bickle (Robert De Niro), who
goes berserk after life on the mean streets gets the better of him.
Viewers can watch the film, reissued by Columbia Tri-Star, and then
settle in for a few insights from Scorsese, screenwriter Paul
Schrader, De Niro, Jodie Foster and others.
</P>
<P>
   Schrader says he was between relationships at the time and
hadn't spoken to anyone for weeks. The taxi was a metaphor for
loneliness. He wrote the script, considered a masterpiece, in 10
days.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was in Rome working in Bernardo Bertolucci's ``1900,''
De Niro returned regularly to New York to practice his taxi
driving. He and Scorsese say they both identified with Bickle's
rage and craziness. ``I was 31 or 32, and I felt those feelings,''
Scorsese says.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Foster, who was barely a teen-ager, had worked for Scorsese
on ``Alice Doesn't Live Here Anymore.'' This time, she says, ``he
called up my mother and said he wanted me to play a street
prostitute in New York. My mother said, `I think she's totally
wrong for it, but if you want me to bring her in, OK.'''
</P>
<P>
   Declaring Independence  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy asked, `Should I Slamdance?,' and I had no idea what
he meant,'' said filmmaker Marina Zenovich. Shortly thereafter, she
took her camera to Park City, Utah, and roamed all the ``dances''
held there every January: the mainstream Sundance Film Festival,
its alternative spinoff, the Slamdance Film Festival, and the
alternative to the alternative, called Slumdance.
</P>
<P>
   Independent filmmaking is a much chewed-over topic these days,
but the observations take on some freshness in Ms. Zenovich's 1997
documentary ``Independent's Day,'' released this week by New Video.
</P>
<P>
   Slamdance, of course, is where some directors take their movies
after they have been turned down by Sundance. With everybody trying
to land a distribution deal, it gets frantic in Park City. ``Cheap,
mean, rude, pushy,'' says an exasperated local resident.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the festivalgoers, Robert Redford, Sundance's
founder, says he likes the sense of place and the collegiality.
Jeffrey Gilmore, the festival's artistic director, says it's not
the deal that's important but the learning and mixing with other
film makers.
</P>
<P>
   Fine, but ``it's not about art, it's about business,'' Redford
says later. Steven Soderbergh, Bryan Singer, Tom DiCillo, Neal
LaBute, Eric Schaeffer, Tony Vitale and other better-known young
directors, most of them Sundance veterans, tell why the deal's the
thing. The most heartening case study belongs to Greg Mottola,
whose first feature, ``The Daytrippers,'' shot in 16 days, was
turned down by Sundance but was shown at Slamdance and then at
Cannes. In New York, the film ran for five months.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring a rare double on the Park City festival circuit, Ms.
Zenovich's film got seed money from Slamdance and finishing money
from the Sundance Channel. The price is $19.95. Information: (800)
314-8822.
</P>
<P>
   NEW VIDEO RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   You've Got Mail
</P>
<P>
   Joe Fox (Tom Hanks) and Kathleen Kelly (Meg Ryan converse
intimately and anonymously on the Internet about things they
wouldn't have the slightest reason to discuss if they knew each
other in the flesh. Kathleen runs a cozy little children's book
shop about to be put out of business by Joe's very big bookstore on
the Upper West Side of Manhattan. That suggests a difference of
approach, and when the two actually meet, while remaining unaware
that they are chat room confidants, they keep their defenses high.
Still, there's enough of a spark between them to withstand all the
expectable misunderstandings in Nora Ephron's film, which, Janet
Maslin wrote in The New York Times, ``becomes a New York story
reminiscent of early Woody Allen romances.''
</P>
<P>
   1998. Warner. $22.96. 119 minutes. Closed captioned. PG. Release
date: May 4.
</P>
<P>
   Babe: Pig in the City
</P>
<P>
   That sweet little porker who saved the day for farmer Hoggett in
``Babe'' has to do it again under decidedly different circumstances
in the big, bad city. After Hoggett takes a spill down a well, Babe
and Mrs. Hoggett fly off to a menacing, strikingly depicted
metropolis to raise money to save the farm. Left alone after Mrs.
H. mistakenly gets caught in a drug sweep at the airport, Babe
lands in a very odd part of town modeled after Venice. There he
finds shelter at the Flealands Hotel, which houses warring armies
of cats and dogs, some world-weary chimps, an orangutan named
Thelonius and a pregnant floozy of a poodle. The real charmer,
though, is a pit bull who envisions Babe as an animal-rights leader
in a film whose ``occasional taste for dark moments and
unappetizing sights makes its G rating somewhat questionable for
very young children'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Universal. $22.98. 97 minutes. Closed captioned. G.
Release date: May 4.
</P>
<P>
   The Thief
</P>
<P>
   Traveling by train with her 6-year-old son, Sanya (Misha
Philipchuk), a dewily beautiful young mother named Katya
(Yekaterina Rednikova) meets and immediately falls for Toylan
(Vladimir Mashkov), a seductive army officer with a likeness of
Stalin tattooed on his chest. The year is 1952 in the Soviet Union,
and to secure space in an already crowded apartment, Katya agrees
to pretend Toylan is her husband. Jammed into a single room with
the lovers, Sanya can only look on. While they disapprove of the
situation, the proprietors become fond of the boy and soon are
disarmed by Toylan, as are other boarders who are taken in by his
air of camaraderie and his boozy toasts to Stalin. Only later does
Katya learn that she has fallen in with a thief and schemer,
inspiring a bitter blend of love and fury that helps give Pavel
Chukhrai's ``story of fatherly betrayal its insinuating power''
(Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1997. Columbia Tri-Star. $99.36. 97 minutes. Russian with
English subtitles. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time, appeared on television or been on
videocassette in earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   CROWS. In Dorota Kedzierzawska's small, exquisitely photographed
Polish allegory, a scrappy 9-year-old girl (Karolina Ostrozna)
fends for herself after being deserted by her mother, who brings
home a lover and locks the child out. Tossed into the street and
ostracized by everyone from hustlers to school teachers, the child
(who remains nameless) rebels by kidnapping a toddler and declaring
herself a mother. Though all of this is captured with great visual
appeal, the film, Stephen Holden wrote in The New York Times,
``yields little complexity and few surprises.'' 1996. New Yorker.
$89.95. 66 minutes. Polish with English subtitles. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   PAINTING THE WORLD. Four 30-minute programs from the National
Gallery in London illustrate styles and beliefs from the 15th
through the 19th centuries. Works discussed include Hans Memling's
``Donne Triptych,'' Paolo Veronese's ``Family of Darius Before
Alexander,'' Peter Paul Rubens' ``Autumn Landscape With a View of
the Het Steen'' and Joseph Wright's ``Experiment on a Bird in the
Air Pump.'' 1999. Home Vision. Two cassettes, $39.95. 120 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   REAR WINDOW. Broadcast on ABC, the film is less about remaking
the Hitchcock classic about a man with a broken leg who thinks he
has spotted a murderer than it is about reinventing Christopher
Reeve as an actor. ``Tasteful, engaging and extremely clever,''
Caryn James wrote in The New York Times. 1998. Artisan. $19.98. 89
minutes. Closed captioned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
