</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VISITING-DEECEE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WONDER OF INNOCENCE REVIVES WASHINGTON'S GRACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
Samuel G. Freedman, a professor of journalism at Columbia
University, is the author, most recently, of ``The Inheritance.''  
 (bl)  
 By SAMUEL G. FREEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``You see those trees, kids?'' I said to my
children, Aaron and Sarah, as our cab headed down Pennsylvania
Avenue toward the White House. ``Those are cherry trees.
Washington's famous for them. And it's a special time when the
blossoms are coming out, like now.''
</P>
<P>
   Poking my hand out the window into the balmy air, I indicated
the trees' long, tapered tongues of pink and cream. I was heady in
the hallowed role of father as tour guide, father as historian,
leading the family on its spring break tour of the capital,
inculcating the next generation in the glories of democracy, an
amalgam of ``Born Yesterday'' and ``Father Knows Best.'' Not even
the skeptical gaze of my wife, Cynthia, could shake me from my
reverie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me, mister,'' the taxi driver interrupted almost
timorously, as if calibrating the effect of veracity on gratuity.
``Those are dogwoods. The cherries are down by the Tidal Basin.
They won't blossom till next week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dogwoods, right,'' I mumbled, struck at just how long it had
been since I'd visited Washington for pleasure. Over the years I
had shuttled into the city scores of times as a journalist and
author: to sift through the National Archives, to interview the
star of a Broadway-bound show, to make the promotional rounds for
my latest book. Rarely did I allow myself any more leisure, though,
than paying homage at the Vietnam Veterans Memorial or taking a
daybreak run along Rock Creek Parkway.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 years had passed since my parents brought our
family here for a long weekend similar to the one I was now
leading. And for two antiwar liberals _ Eugene McCarthy supporters,
avid members of the disarmament group SANE _ they had given my
brother and sister and me an unapologetically patriotic trek from
the Capitol to Mount Vernon to John F. Kennedy's grave. Now, in
retrospect, I recognized my folks' wisdom: they wouldn't abdicate
Americanism to the Cold Warriors and Vietnam hawks.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia and I faced a similar challenge, albeit for tawdrier
reasons. We boarded the Amtrak from central New Jersey to
Washington on the first day of April with a goal of reclaiming the
capital from Bill Clinton and Monica Lewinsky and Ken Starr and
Linda Tripp. Aaron, 7, had packed his red plastic binoculars and
Mickey Mouse autograph book for the journey. With every stop, even
pitiful Trenton and Wilmington, Sarah, 4, wanted to know if we
could see the Washington Monument yet.
</P>
<P>
   On arriving, we went directly to our hotel, a Doubletree Guest
Suites in Foggy Bottom, which we had plucked sight-unseen out of a
guidebook. Sarah dove for the covers and her afternoon nap, and
Aaron begged, successfully, for a visit to the Lincoln Memorial.
Drizzly as it was at the monument, the marble and limestone slick,
we found a tableau of populist communion. There were Rollerbladers
and veterans in fatigues, monks in saffron and women in chadors,
high school classes scrambling out of buses, fraternity brothers
practicing their cadence call.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron and I picked our way to the base of the Lincoln statue.
``Wow!'' he gasped. Then we turned to the southern wall, and I read
aloud the words inscribed there, the Gettysburg Address. Finally we
faced outward through the pillars, beholding the Reflecting Pool
and the Mall, dotted with open umbrellas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what happened here, right?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where did he speak?'' Aaron asked. ``This side?''
</P>
<P>
   We were referring of course to the March on Washington and the
Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.'s ``I Have a Dream'' speech, which
Aaron had studied during Black History Month. We descended from the
portico to a small museum in the memorial's base to watch film of
King in majestic oratory as well as scenes of protesters for
legalized abortion and gay rights and Soviet Jewry and all the
other causes that plead their cases on this ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did Martin Luther King know Abraham Lincoln?'' Aaron asked me
as we walked toward the Metro. For a long moment, I could not
answer.
</P>
<P>
   With every block we went, with each edifice we passed, more
questions arose. What's the Organization of American States? Why's
there a red cross on that building? Who was L'Enfant? The only
query I ducked concerned the Office of Thrift Supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the hotel, we rejoined Cynthia and Sarah, and on the
desk clerk's recommendation, one confirmed in our guidebook, we
decided to try the Italian restaurant next door, Donatello's. Three
main courses, one of them split by the children, and a few glasses
of wine came to $93 without tip. At least, I told myself, all the
Smithsonian museums are free.
</P>
<P>
   Early the next morning, we set out for the Air and Space Museum,
the most popular attraction on this stretch of the Mall and, we
feared, the most crowded. Aaron and Sarah capered through the
Hirschhorn sculpture garden, just down the street from the museum,
as Cynthia and I surveyed the size of the crowd awaiting entrance.
We hurried in just after the 10 a.m. opening and made immediately
for the booth to buy tickets for both the Imax theater and the
planetarium.
</P>
<P>
   In between the shows _ the theater's history of manned flight,
the planetarium's introduction to astronomy _ we strolled through
an exhibit on the Apollo 11 moon landing and walked through a model
of Skylab, replete with exercise bike, collapsible shower and
``sleeping restraint,'' a sort of upright hammock.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you sleep like that?'' Aaron asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're tired enough,'' replied Cynthia, who had been roused
by Sarah at 5:30 every morning for the past week, ``you can sleep
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Here is information on visiting Washington:
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   DOUBLETREE GUEST SUITES, 2500 Pennsylvania Avenue, NW, (202)
333-8060. We had a large, comfortable suite, including a complete
kitchen, for $189 a night. Situated in Foggy Bottom, the hotel is a
short walk from Georgetown, the Metro, the Kennedy Center, and Rock
Creek Park.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   DONATELLO, 2514 L St., NW, (just off Pennsylvania Avenue), (202)
333-1485. We enjoyed lamb and chicken dishes and homemade pasta,
though the $93 bill qualified as a splurge for a family.
</P>
<P>
   MISS SAIGON, 3057 M St., NW, (202) 333-5545. We ordered, and
savored, caramel chicken with ginger in a clay pot and grilled
salmon chunks of skewers. Those dishes and a side order of papaya
salad with beef came to about $30. The restaurant does take-out at
both lunch and dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions
</P>
<P>
   THE CAPITOL, First and East Capitol Streets. We arranged a
family tour, free of charge, by getting in touch with Senator
Charles Schumer's office, and most senators and representatives
will also arrange small-group tours for constituents if given
enough advance notice. Guided large-group tours and self-guided
tours, also free, are available as well. Call (202) 225-6827 for
information. During the peak tourism season, March through August,
the Capitol is open every day from 9 a.m. until 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   LINCOLN MEMORIAL, west end of National Mall, between
Constitution and Independence Avenues. Open 24 hours a day, free of
charge and staffed from 8 a.m. until midnight. Call (202) 426-6895
or (202) 426-6841 for information.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL AIR AND SPACE MUSEUM, Independence Avenue and Sixth
Street SW, (202) 357-2700 for general information or (202) 357-1686
for movie information. Like all the Smithsonian museums, this one
is free of charge, although there is a fee for films in the Imax
theater and planetarium. (We paid $30 for a two-film package for
two adults and two children.) The museum is open from 10 a.m. until
5:30 p.m. daily.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL POSTAL MUSEUM, 2 Massachusetts Ave., NE, (202)
357-2991. Next to Union Station, the museum offers hourlong tours
several times daily. It is open 10 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. every day
except Christmas. Free admission.
</P>
<P>
   OLD POST OFFICE, 1100 Pennsylvania Ave., NW, (202) 289-4224. Its
315-foot clock tower offers a view second only to the Washington
Monument's, without the monument's immense lines. The tower is free
of charge and from Easter through Labor Day is open 8 a.m. to 11
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Getting There From The New York Area
</P>
<P>
   AMTRAK. We paid $418 for two adults and two children going
round-trip from Metropark in Iselin, N.J., to Union Station, at the
hub of East Capitol, North Capitol, Second and East Streets and New
Jersey and Massachusetts Avenues. The Metroliner is faster, but
more expensive than Northeast Direct service. We compromised by
taking Northeast Direct down and a Metroliner back. Information and
reservations: (800) 872-7245.
</P>
<P>
   There are also Greyhound buses leaving from Port Authority in
Manhattan and Penn Station in Newark, N.J., and arriving at the
Greyhound Terminal, 1005 First St., NE, at L Street, in Washington.
Round-trip fare, $60 ($30 for children). Information: (800)
231-2222. By air, round-trip fares on Delta, (800) 221-1212,
United, (800) 241-6522 and US Airways, (800) 428-4322, range from
$98 to $404.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
