<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8189 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-790&AMP;A     04-29 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-790&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES COLUMN: EAMES CHAIRS ARE BENDING THE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.J., N.Y., Ill.)  (js) 
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1928 Charles Eames, an architecture student, was kicked out
of Washington University. Then he went on to have one of the most
distinguished careers in design.
</P>
<P>
   Eames' legacy is being celebrated in an exhibition that has been
touring Europe and that opens at the Library of Congress in
Washington on May 20. It will remain there through Sept. 14; in
October it moves to the Cooper-Hewitt National Design Museum in
Manhattan. The show, ``The Work of Charles and Ray Eames: A Legacy
of Invention,'' also honors the contributions of Eames' wife, Ray,
who worked with him. The accompanying book, published by Harry N.
Abrams, costs $49.50.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition is part of a renewed interest among auction
houses, galleries and museums in Eames and in 20th-century design
in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twentieth-century design is stronger than ever,'' said Mark
McDonald, owner of the Gansevoort Gallery in Manhattan. ``As the
century comes to a close, mid-century things are now antiques.'' He
continued: ``Americans were at the forefront of design in the
postwar period. There was a concentration of talent _ people like
Florence Knoll, the Eameses, George Nelson, Noguchi _ and a market
fueled by all the GIs coming home from the war.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Wright, a Chicago dealer, said, ``Americans are finally
realizing Eames was one of the most important designers of the 20th
century.'' He added, ``It's sad that European museums were ahead of
us in collecting Eames furniture.'' He was referring to the Vitra
Design Museum in Germany, which has a large Eames collection and is
the co-sponsor of the traveling exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Wlodek Malowanczyk, who owns Collage 20th-Century Classics, a
Dallas gallery, said: ``Even Dallas is catching up. My customers
won't buy the expensive things yet, but they will buy collectibles
like Eames' 1945 DCM Chair, with metal legs and a plywood back and
seat.''
</P>
<P>
   After his dismissal from Washington University in St. Louis,
involving his advocacy of the ideas of Frank Lloyd Wright, Eames
(1907-78) traveled to Europe and designed a church in Arkansas that
caught the eye of the Finnish architect Eliel Saarinen, then
president of the Cranbrook Academy in Michigan. He offered Eames a
fellowship at the academy. At Cranbrook, Eames met other
groundbreaking modernists like the artist Harry Bertoia and fell in
love with Ray Kaiser, an art student from California who would
become his second wife.
</P>
<P>
   In 1939 Eames went to work in Saarinen's architectural office.
The following year, while Eames was working as a resident
instructor at Cranbrook with Saarinen's son, Eero, the two
collaborated on a prototype of a modern chair that won first prize
at the Museum of Modern Art's Organic Design in Home Furnishings
competition. Nicknamed the Conversation Armchair, it had a plywood
shell, foam rubber cushioning, custom upholstery and four tapering
angled wood dowel legs. It was the first time a molded plywood
shell was shaped into three-dimensional curves. And it made a lot
of news.
</P>
<P>
   In 1941 Eames married Kaiser, and they moved to Los Angeles ``to
try to mass produce molded plywood with complex curves,'' said
Eames Demetrios, Eames' grandson.
</P>
<P>
   He has created a Web site, www.eamesoffice.com, and opened the
Eames Office Gallery in Santa Monica, Calif., to educate people
about the Eames philosophy. ``It's not about chairs,'' he said.
``It's a way of looking at the world.''
</P>
<P>
   During World War II the U.S. Navy commissioned Eames to develop
plywood stretchers and leg splints for wounded American soldiers.
After the war the Eameses adapted their experience to the design of
furniture. In 1948 they designed the Eiffel Tower Chair, which had
a fiberglass shell with metal rod leg supports. It won the second
prize at the Museum of Modern Art's 1948 International Competition
for Low-Cost Furniture Design. The Eameses went on to create
chairs, storage units, tables and folding screens, most of which
were manufactured by Herman Miller in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next two months work by Eames is expected to show up at
several auctions and at a fair devoted to 20th-century decorative
arts, beginning Saturday with David Rago's 20th-century modern
auction in Lambertville, N.J. (Information: 609-397-9374.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, dealers from as far away as Italy are expected to
participate in the Los Angeles Modernism Show at the Santa Monica
Civic Auditorium on May 8 and 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``L.A. is driving the market right now,'' said John Meany, a San
Francisco dealer who will be there. ``Since the movie colony
embraced modernism and started buying and restoring modern houses,
mid-century modern has gotten very trendy. Five or six years ago it
was Tokyo that was driving the market.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Los Angeles Modern Auctions, or LAMA, which specializes in
Eames, will also be at the Los Angeles show, along with
Malowanczyk. In addition, LAMA is conducting its own auction on May
16 in Beverly Hills. Highlights include the Eames Conversation
Armchair and three rare pieces that the architect R.M. Schindler
designed in 1934 for the Van Patten residence in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   On May 23 the John Toomey Gallery in Oak Park, Ill., in
conjunction with Wright, the Chicago dealer, and the Treadway
Gallery of Cincinnati is having four separate 20th-century sales in
Oak Park. For one, Wright assembled 150 Eames pieces for an
all-Eames sale.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's 20th-century decorative arts sale in Manhattan is on
June 10; Christie's is on June 11, at its new home in Rockefeller
Center, another icon of modernism.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald of the Gansevoort normally sells to American architects
and designers like Lee Mindel, Michael Formica and Thad Hayes, but
on Sunday he was in the Netherlands at the first Amsterdam Arts and
Design Fair, which focused on design after 1880. He was one of
three American dealers selling American furniture. Peter Loughery
of LAMA sold some Eames leg splints at the fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``The icons go for very high prices,'' he added. ``In Europe
many can't afford to spend thousands on a side chair.''
</P>
<P>
   But the number of collectors is increasing everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when I recognized everyone who bid at my
sales in L.A.,'' Loughery said, ``Now it's maybe 20 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lambertville auction, also organized by John Sollo, will
offer several pieces by the craftsman George Nakashima, including
an end table with a beautifully figured Buckeye burlwood top, a
rare Makassar ebony console table with a trestle base, and a
spectacular walnut music stand.
</P>
<P>
   The market for mid-century modern pieces today ``is a lot like
the stock market,'' McDonald said. ``The business runs the way the
economy runs. People have money to spend, and they are optimistic
about the economy. Good things come out because people think they
will get good prices for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
