<SLUG> BC-REAL-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GET REAL': TEEN-AGE BOYS IN LOVE AND IN PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steven Carter (Ben Silverstone), the hero of Simon Shore's
likable British film ``Get Real,'' is a bright-eyed, principled
high school student who has known he was gay since the age of 11.
</P>
<P>
   Now in his late teens, he has taken to cruising the public
restroom in a local park. While waiting in a stall one day, he
exchanges notes through a hole in the partition with a stranger
who, to his shock, turns out to be John Dixon (Brad Gorton), a
popular fellow student.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting each other outdoors, the two overcome their
mortification enough for Steven to bring John home with him (his
parents are out), where they have an evasive, bumbling
conversation, after which John, backing out of a tentative first
kiss, flees in terror.
</P>
<P>
   John isn't just any student; he's an Oxford-bound star athlete
and major high school heartthrob with a girlfriend, Christina
(Louise J. Taylor), who is a model.
</P>
<P>
   But neither Steven nor John can get the encounter out of his
mind. After a school dance in which they gaze longingly at each
other over their dates' shoulders, John barges into Steven's home,
drunk and in tears, and begs for help. A passionate, desperately
furtive affair develops, in which John swears he loves Steven but
forbids him to tell anyone or even to acknowledge that they're more
than distant acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get Real'' isn't the first movie to tell the star-crossed love
story of a gay teen-age nerd and his high-school jock boyfriend.
The same territory was covered a bit more fancifully in the 1997
British film ``Beautiful Thing,'' which was set in a working-class
housing project. The forthcoming American film ``Edge of
Seventeen'' (opening May 14), set in the Midwest during the 1980s,
also deals with an isolated teen-ager nervously dealing with his
own homosexuality and the suspicions of his peers.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Get Real,'' adapted from a play by Patrick Wilde, has
its sudsy moments, it offers a far more realistic and compelling
vision of teen-age growing pains and peer pressure than any of the
recent high-school movies from Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Its finely tuned performances by Silverstone and Gorton have a
wrenching emotional veracity. The movie captures the excruciating
paranoia of a situation in which there's nowhere the lovers can be
alone except in each other's homes on the rare occasions their
parents are out.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton has the more difficult role of the star athlete whose
aloof, self-confident pose crumbles when he is alone with Steven.
In the movie's most agonizing moments, John humiliates his lover by
playing it straight and barely acknowledging him. At one point, he
even has to beat him up to prove he's not gay.
</P>
<P>
   But in some ways ``Get Real'' also feels like a formulaic
made-for-television drama. Steven's understanding mother (Jacquetta
May) and not-so-understanding father (David Lumsden) are familiar
types who never come into individual focus.
</P>
<P>
   Steven also has a best friend and confidante in Linda (Charlotte
Brittain), a next-door-neighbor who has her own little subplot
about an affair with a married man. Her character, an overweight
girl with a sassy mouth, is a cliched gay sidekick. The school's
ranking bully, Kevin (Tim Harris), is also a stock character.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Get Real'' and ``Beautiful Thing'' reveal how far movies
have come from the days of ``Tea and Sympathy,'' when a kindly
older woman intervened to ``make a man'' out of a persecuted
preppy, how far is that really?
</P>
<P>
   For these movies also sadly remind us that peer-group treatment
of those who are different (especially those who are perceived as
gay) is almost as brutal today as it was back in the dark ages of
the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Get Real'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent
or adult guardian). It has strong language, delicate sexual issues
and one passionate kiss between the lovers.
</P>
<P>
   GET REAL
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Simon Shore; written by Patrick Wilde, based on his
play ``What's Wrong With Angry?''; director of photography, Alan
Almond; edited by Barrie Vince; music by John Lunn; production
designer, Bernd Lepel; produced by Stephen Taylor; released by
Paramount Classics. Running time: 110 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Ben Silverstone (Steven Carter), Brad Gorton (John Dixon),
Charlotte Brittain (Linda), Stacy A. Hart (Jessica), Kate McEnery
(Wendy), Louise J. Taylor (Christina), Jacquetta May (Steven's
mother), David Lumsden (Steven's father) and Tim Harris (Kevin).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
