YOU KNOW IT'S mAY SWEEPS WHEN ... 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know it's May sweeps when ...
</P>
<P>
   _You flick on the tube and, lo and behold, there's Hilton Lucas
(Bill Cosby) of ``Cosby,'' Doug Hefferman (Kevin James) of ``The
King of Queens'' and Ray Barone (Ray Romano) of ``Everybody Loves
Raymond'' shooting the breeze in the waiting room on ``Becker''
(Ted Danson). (Monday, CBS)
</P>
<P>
   _When Jarod (Michael T. Weiss) of ``The Pretender'' poses as an
Atlanta detective to search for a 13-year-old genius with Dr.
Samantha Waters (Ally Walker) from ``The Profiler,'' the series
that follows his show. (May 8, NBC)
</P>
<P>
   _When the aging Diana Ross plays the ``mother'' of Brandy in
``Double Platinum,'' about a singing superstar forced to face the
daughter she left behind for fame, fortune and an ``Entertainment
Weekly'' cover. (May 16, ABC)
</P>
<P>
   _When Jane Seymour returns as the beloved ``Dr. Quinn, Medicine
Woman'' to hook up with Sully (Joe Lando) to seek their kidnapped
daughter, who has probably roamed over to the younger-skewing WB.
(May 22, CBS)
</P>
<P>
   _When guest stars come a-calling: Muhammad Ali on ``Touched by
an Angel'' (May 9, CBS); Jason Alexander as the voice of evil human
resources director Catbert on ``Dilbert'' (Monday, UPN); Coolio
warming up for his new series on ``Malcolm &AMP; Eddie'' (Tuesday,
UPN); Kathy Bates as an alien hunter on ``3rd Rock From the Sun''
(Tuesday, NBC); NFLer Rodney Peete with real-life wife Holly
Robinson Peete on ``For Your Love'' (May 13, WB); Billy Dee
Williams on ``Promised Land'' (May 20, CBS); William Shatner as
``The Big Giant Head'' on the one-hour season finale of ``3rd Rock
From the Sun'' (May 25, NBC).
</P>
<P>
   _When Julia Roberts lowers her billion-dollar payday
expectations to put the moves on Detective Rey Curtis (Benjamin
Bratt), her real-life squeeze of the moment, in an episode of ``Law
&AMP; Order.'' (Wednesday, NBC)
</P>
<P>
   _When a network goes out of its way to promote quantity (13,000
extras, 7,000 horses, $30 million-plus budget, blah, blah, blah)
rather than the quality of its bigger-is-better treatment of
``Cleopatra.'' (May 23, 24, ABC)
</P>
<P>
   _When ``Early Edition's'' nice guy Gary (Kyle Chandler), who has
never hit anyone, teams with ``Martial Law's'' kung-fu fighting
Sammo Law (Sammo Hung), who has hit practically everyone, to
investigate a case at a rodeo. (May 8, CBS)
</P>
<P>
   _When ``Moesha's'' loudmouth Niecy (Shar Jackson) and ditzy
Hakeem (Lamont Bentley) attend the senior prom with loudmouth Sean
(Sean Holland) and ditzy Dionne (Stacey Dash) of ``Clueless.'' (May
11, UPN)
</P>
<P>
   _When old friends say farewell for the last (and about) time:
``The Nanny'' (May 19, CBS); ``Mad About You'' (May 24, NBC);
``Melrose Place'' (May 24, Fox); ``Home Improvement'' (May 25,
ABC).
</P>
<P>
   _When Vanessa L. Williams puts the finishing touches on a
three-episode story line portraying a crusading patient-rights
advocate on ``LA Doctors'' (Tuesday, CBS).
</P>
<P>
   _When Rob Lowe spends an entire four-hour miniseries searching
for ``Sex and the City's'' Kristin Davis in a movie titled ``Atomic
Train,'' about what happens after a train packed with nuclear arms
careens out of control and smacks into Lowe's already fragile
career. (May 16, 17, NBC)
</P>
<P>
   _When Barbara Walters shows up _ this time in ``A Celebration:
One Hundred Years of Great Women,'' a 90-minute special featuring
both new interviews (Katharine Graham, Oprah Winfrey) and classic
chats with folks like Lucille Ball. (Friday night, ABC)
</P>
<P>
   _When a tale that warrants only a few pages in the Bible is
stretched into a four-hour epic starring Jon Voight as the ark
builder in ``Noah's Ark.'' Can you say, dramatic license? Can you
say, ludicrous? (Tuesday, Wednesday, NBC)
</P>
<P>
   _When shameless Fox gives us ``Busted Everywhere!'' _ yet
another reality series about ordinary folks caught on tape doing
``extra-embarrassing things.'' Not just embarrassing things, but
``extra-''embarrassing things. (May 25, Fox)
</P>
<P>
   _When bad things happen to good people: Walker (Chuck Norris)
and Alex's (Sheree J. Wilson) plane crashes on ``Walker, Texas
Ranger,'' leaving them trapped at the bottom of a lake until the
show returns next fall. (May 22, CBS). Buffy (Sarah Michelle
Gellar) risks her life again in ``Buffy The Vampire Slayer'' to
save Angel (David Boreanaz), who really is leaving this time _ for
his own series. (May 18, 25, WB)
</P>
<P>
   _When there are more questions than answers: Should space cadet
``Felicity'' (Keri Russell) tour Europe with Noel (Scott Foley) or
travel back to hometown Palo Alto with Ben (Scott Speedman?) Oh,
geez, girl, get a life. (May 25, WB). Is it really true love for
Finch (David Spade) and supermodel Adrienne (supermodel Rebecca
Romijn-Stamos) in the one-hour season finale of ``Just Shoot Me?''
(May 25, NBC). Will ``JAG's'' Harm (David James Elliott) return to
the pilot's seat after getting his night vision back or do the law
thing with curvy Maj. Sarah MacKenzie (Catherine Bell). (May 25,
CBS) Will pregnant Hathaway (Julianna Margulies) of ``ER'' deliver?
(May 20, NBC)
</P>
<P>
   _When a governor who used to be a wrestler is the subject of a
made-for-TV movie in which he is played by another ex-wrestler.
Nils Allen Stewart stars in ``The Jesse Ventura Story.'' (May 23,
NBC)
</P>
<P>
   _When young warrior ``Joan of Arc'' (16-year-old Leelee
Sobieski) is promoted as a kind of Britney Spears with a sword.
(May 16, CBS)
</P>
<P>
   Ah, sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
