<HEADLINE>
ELITE AIR FORCE TEAM GROUNDED AFTER ACCIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The Air Force has suspended all performances by
the Thunderbirds, the service's precision flight team, for only the
second time since a fatal 1982 crash.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was made after the Air Force reviewed an incident
in which two F-16 jets made contact while taking off at an air show
Sunday at Patrick Air Force Base south of Cocoa Beach, Fla. No one
was injured and both planes landed safely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Safety is our No. 1 concern,'' said Maj. Gen. Glen Moorhead,
commander of the Air Force Air Warfare Center at Nellis Air Force
Base in Nevada, which oversees the team. ``We have a responsibility
to both the public and the team after an incident like this to step
back and take a hard look at our practices and procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how long the Thunderbirds would be grounded was unknown as
team members flew home late Wednesday to Nellis, which is near Las
Vegas. An Air Force news release issued by the Air Combat Command
in Langley, Va., said the show schedule was suspended ``until
further notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Air Combat Command officials couldn't be reached for comment.
Master Sgt. Joe Kubistek, a Thunderbirds spokesman, couldn't say
how long the team would be grounded. The Thunderbirds are entering
the heart of their schedule, which calls for 66 shows at 43
locations this year.
</P>
<P>
   Moorhead's decision marks the first cancellation of
Thunderbirds' shows since 1993, when 14 appearances were scratched
because of a back injury suffered by the command pilot, Kubistek
said. The team's 1982 schedule was canceled after four pilots were
killed during a training exercise on Jan. 18, 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``This suspension's only going to last as long as necessary to
ensure the safety of the public and the team,'' Kubistek said. Six
shows were planned for May, the first this weekend in Fort
Lauderdale, Fla., followed by a stop at Nellis, the team's home
base.
</P>
<P>
   Mixing formation flying with solo routines, the Thunderbirds
typically perform about 30 maneuvers in a 75-minute demonstration.
The team is composed of eight pilots, four support officers, four
civilians and about 120 enlistees.
</P>
<P>
   Created on June 1, 1953, the Thunderbirds have made thousands of
appearances in the United States and around the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 1644EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
