<SLUG> BC-FILM-ENTRAPMENT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ENTRAPMENT' FALLS SHORT OF POTENTIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 68-year-old Sean Connery is such an incomparable movie star
that he's probably incapable of making a totally bad movie. When
he's 105, he'll still be carrying big movies on his shoulders with
an ease that puts his younger rivals to shame.
</P>
<P>
   This is especially true when it's a movie with exotic locations,
James Bondian production values and a co-star as a watchable as
Catherine Zeta-Jones, the young British actress who jumped out of
last summer's ``Mask of Zorro'' to something nearing major stardom.
</P>
<P>
   But their joint star vehicle, ``Entrapment,'' as enjoyable as it
is in a few scattered spots, could have been much better. It is
strangely paced (especially in the beginning), always confusing to
follow, and extremely awkward as a romance.
</P>
<P>
   Connery plays Robert ``Mac'' MacDougal, the world's greatest art
thief, an aging loner who lives in a Scottish castle, who has
become so wealthy from his life of crime he no longer needs to
steal, but can't resist the challenge of a lucrative caper.
</P>
<P>
   Zeta-Jones is Virginia ``Gin'' Baker, an insurance investigator
who long has been obsessed by MacDougal. She works for a company
that has just lost $24 million due to the theft of a Rembrandt
painting that has all the earmarks of a MacDougal cat burglary.
</P>
<P>
   As the film opens, Gin goes after Mac by pretending to recruit
him as her partner in a series of dangerous heists for which she
has inside information. But pretty soon it begins to look like Gin
may be a real thief herself, and right up until the fade-out we
don't know for sure who is what.
</P>
<P>
   To the film's credit, both stars hold the screen nicely, the
script provides some truly unexpected developments, the locations _
New York, Scotland, England, Malaysia _ are glamorous and
well-photographed, and there's a dandy climax outside Kuala
Lumpur's Petronas TwinTowers, the world's tallest buildings.
</P>
<P>
   But Jon Amiel's direction too often is ponderous and
disorienting when it should be light and smooth; and he makes the
twists and turns in Ron Bass's hyperactive script seem jerky and
annoying when they should be delicious and fun.
</P>
<P>
   Amiel also seems thrown by the problem of dealing with the
near-40-year age difference between his stars. There's a
self-conscious timidity to the romantic scenes that makes them
surprisingly uncomfortable to watch. Everyone, including Connery,
seems to be embarrassed by this relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Like all films that deal with modern high-tech crime, the
methodology is so complex and antidramatic that ``Entrapment'' is
never terribly engrossing as a thriller. The mechanics of bypassing
security codes or hacking a supercomputer are not visually
gripping. Too many of the film's robbery sequences seem like dead
screen time.
</P>
<P>
   Entrapment. Directed by Jon Amiel. Screenplay by Ron Bass and
William Broyles. Cast: Sean Connery, Catherine Zeta-Jones, Ving
Rhames, Will Patton. 20th Century Fox. 113 minutes. Rated R for no
obvious reason.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 1646EDT &QL; 
