<SLUG> BC-IDLE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`IDLE HANDS': ONLY FOR IDLE MINDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If timing is everything, then the recent carnage at Columbine
High School indicates that now could scarcely be less opportune for
the opening of ``Idle Hands,'' a cheap-thrills horror film built
around a teen-age murder rampage that reaches its climax among
panic-stricken students at a Halloween dance in a small-town high
school.
</P>
<P>
   Even pretensions toward the humorous and hip cannot save this
blood-drenched film from its innate tastelessness, calculated to
find its audience among those, like its hero and his friends, whose
vapid lives are a celebration of truancy, marijuana and junk food
in a virtually parentless habitat that stretches only from bed to
television set.
</P>
<P>
   Anton (Devon Sawa), the 17-year-old victim and hero of ``Idle
Hands,'' is so alienated from a connection to anyone but his two
pals, Mick (Seth Green) and Pnub (Elden Henson), that when he wakes
up in his attic bedroom on the day before Halloween, detaches
himself from his headphones and goes downstairs, he manages to make
his way through the house and eventually across the street without
noticing that his parents have been bloodily murdered during the
night.
</P>
<P>
   According to the slapdash script, written by Terri Hughes and
Ron Milbauer and directed by Rodman Flender, who served his
apprenticeship with Roger Corman, the town, and others like it, has
been the site of a series of murders.
</P>
<P>
   From time to time, the story of Anton, who is eventually
possessed by a homicidal hand, which leads him to plunge a broken
beer bottle into Mick's head and decapitate Pnub with a saw blade,
is interrupted to track the listless exploits of Debi (Vivica A.
Fox).
</P>
<P>
   Debi, it seems, is descended from a long line of druid
priestesses who are trying to put an end to an evil force that
takes over the the laziest soul around. Eventually she hooks up
with Randy (Jack Noseworthy), introduced in a scene that pokes fun
at high school students mourning at a flower-filled memorial to
teen-age twins who are among the more recent victims of the demonic
force.
</P>
<P>
   So the main question is whether the repentant Anton, separated
from his evil hand with the aid of a cleaver, and his good-natured
pals, in the form of ghouls, and Debi and Randy can get to the big
Halloween dance in time to save Anton's girlfriend, Molly (Jessica
Alba), before the hand whisks her off to to hell.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is not something that most moviegoers will want to
pay to learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Idle Hands'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying parent
or adult guardian). It involves bloody murder, resurrected corpses,
severed body parts, partial nudity during sexual foreplay, sexual
references and coarse language.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `DLE HANDS'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Rodman Flender; written by Terri Hughes and Ron
Milbauer; director of photography, Christopher Baffa; edited by
Stephen E. Rivkin; music by Graeme Revell; production designer,
Greg Melton; produced by Andrew Licht, Jeffrey A. Mueller, Suzanne
Todd and Jennifer Todd; released by Columbia Pictures. Running
time: 92 minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Devon Sawa (Anton), Seth Green (Mick), Elden Henson
(Pnub), Jessica Alba (Molly), Steve Van Wormer (Curtis), Fred
Willard (Dad), Jack Noseworthy (Randy) and Vivica A. Fox (Debi).
</P>
</TEXT>
