<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8206 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CITY-BALLET-EXHIBIT-2     04-29 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITY-BALLET-EXHIBIT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC BALLET EXHIBIT: DISTILLING THE DANCE OF TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is much to appreciate and to contest in ``Dance
for a City: 50 Years of the New York City Ballet,'' an exhibition
that the New-York Historical Society is presenting through Aug. 15
on the occasion of the City Ballet's golden anniversary season.
</P>
<P>
   Two magnificent portrait photographs by George Platt Lynes of
George Balanchine and Lincoln Kirstein, the company's founders,
introduce the story at its start.
</P>
<P>
   Although undated, the Balanchine portrait shows the
choreographer as he appeared in other photographs shortly after his
arrival in New York from Europe in 1933. Russian-born, Balanchine
looks like the half-Georgian he was. The still-black hair and sharp
features are pronounced. Nearby, a 1930s group photo of the
American Ballet, the City Ballet's first precursor, is still signed
Balanchivadze, the choreographer's original and Georgian surname.
</P>
<P>
   Kirstein, his American patron and advance man, wears a business
suit like Balanchine. But Lynes catches the temperamental
differences between the two men with telling artifice. Hardly over
30, Kirstein is depicted as a brooding intellectual, leaning to one
side as if he were about to fall off his chair. Balanchine twists
in his chair and, suit notwithstanding, is the self-assured artist
aware of his performance before the camera.
</P>
<P>
   How such disparate personalities came together, as well as the
City Ballet's evolution to the present time, is retold through an
intelligent chronological sequence and an imaginative installation.
Layman and specialist alike will find something of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Garafola, a dance historian who was curator of the show
with her husband, Eric Foner, professor of history at Columbia
University, has done an admirable job of assembling material, some
of it unfamiliar, from a vast variety of sources.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the exhibition, which is not a City Ballet project,
is not without quirks or errors. The strangest mistake comes
glaringly early in a description of Balanchine's choreography for
Serge Diaghilev's Ballets Russes in Europe. ``Le Bal'' is called
``the last work Balanchine choreographed for the Ballets Russes,''
when, as is well known, it was ``Prodigal Son.''
</P>
<P>
   A larger quirk may be tied to the New-York Historical Society's
own focus on the city. Does the show need to justify itself in this
museum by identifying the company as the embodiment of New York?
Certainly this is the line promoted in the captions and in ``Dance
for a City,'' a book of essays published in conjunction with the
exhibition (Columbia University Press).
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Garafola notes in the book that after the City Center of
Music and Drama invited Ballet Society, another Kirstein-Balanchine
troupe, to join the center by becoming the New York City Ballet in
1948, a popular-price policy facilitated ``a large working-class
and lower-middle-class audience.'' Poets and artists were also in
attendance. ``This diversity helps explain the extraordinary
richness of the New York City Ballet repertory during the City
Center years,'' Ms. Garafola writes.
</P>
<P>
   Not true. No amount of determinist concepts can obliterate the
fundamental cornerstone of the Balanchine-Kirstein collaboration.
They led the way, they did not follow.
</P>
<P>
   For the same reason, it strains credibility to read Sally Banes'
strong suggestion in the book that Merce Cunningham perhaps
``influenced the look of Balanchine's `Agon' (1957) and `Stravinsky
Violin Concerto' (1972),'' especially in the use of stillness and
``disconnectedness of dance phrases.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, the idea of influence is used to undermine the City
Ballet's basic premises. It is no secret that Balanchine's
springboard for choreography was music while Cunningham's works are
not only  &UR; not &LR;  choreographed to music but also are deliberately
dissociated from whatever sound score is heard in a theater on a
particular night.
</P>
<P>
   Stravinsky's musical structures account for the way ``Agon'' and
``Stravinsky Violin Concerto'' look, not Merce Cunningham's
esthetics. The entire exhibition cannot be understood if the role
of music as the springboard for Balanchine and his disciples is
relegated to irrelevancy.
</P>
<P>
   The point is that the City Ballet created its own universe; its
creators and members lived in New York, but the company is unlike
any other. It is only because the City Center established resident
companies like the New York City Opera and the New York City Ballet
that the ballet company bears the name it does today.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition's gallery texts, taken from Ms. Garafola's book,
recall Balanchine's professional antecedents in the Diaghilev era.
There are programs, designs, posters and a rare Italian dancing
manual, a gift from Diaghilev. How close Balanchine still remained
with his family in Soviet Georgia is revealed by a letter he
received in New York in 1935: his mother asks him to promote the
music of his composer-brother, Andrei Balanchivadze.
</P>
<P>
   The section devoted to the American Ballet, so named by Kirstein
in his 1930s nationalist phase, and two successor troupes, Ballet
Caravan (directed by Kirstein alone) and American Ballet Caravan,
is particularly good on rarely seen photographs of its dancers
(including Michael Kidd and Erick Hawkins) and colorful program
covers.
</P>
<P>
   The striking aspect here, as in rehearsal shots from Ballet
Society, the City Ballet's immediate predecessor (1946-48), is how
theatrical the productions were. Kirstein maintained a strong link
with visual artists (from whom Balanchine sought to liberate
himself onstage). Hence the number of portraits of both men and
dancers by Kirstein's painter-friends of the moment, including
Pavel Tchelitchev, Lucian Freud and Paul Cadmus, Kirstein's
brother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Unsurprisingly, photographs best render a sense of the company's
evolution. Some of the most magnificent portrait photographs of
Balanchine and his dancers in the early 1950s were taken by the
ballerina Tanaquil LeClercq, Balanchine's last wife. Irving Penn's
more theatrically posed images are also outstanding, and a
curiosity is a 1952 shot from the wings by Stanley Kubrick, who
later married the dancer Ruth Sobotka.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the core of the photographic display lies in the
performance shots over the decades. Generations of dancers in the
same roles are often seen on the walls of boxlike or curved
installations by Stephen Saitas. A costume and props from ``The
Nutcracker'' is, for instance, surrounded by images of dancers in
the ballet. Recordings from the scores are also heard and
videotapes can be seen on monitors.
</P>
<P>
   There is, rightly, a focus on Jerome Robbins' work in one
gallery as well as designs and photographs referring to other
choreographers who worked in the company, especially in the 1950s.
The company today is represented essentially by photographs of
dancers, and Ms. Garafalo's introduction to Peter Martins, the City
Ballet's current artistic director, wisely drops the misplaced
attack on him in her book and pays tribute to his leadership. The
virtue of the exhibition is its clear sense of continuity,
reflected in the City Ballet's own history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dance for a City: 50 Years of the New York City Ballet''
remains on view through Aug. 15 at the New-York Historical Society,
2 W. 77th St., Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Hours: Tuesdays through Sundays, 11 a.m. to 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Admission: $5; $3 for students and the elderly; children 12 and
under admitted free with an adult.
</P>
<P>
   The Historical Society is sponsoring several series of lectures,
film showings and symposiums in connection with the exhibition. A
free symposium on the history of the City Ballet will be held May 8
from 9:30 a.m. to 2:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Information on all programs: (212) 873-3400.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City Ballet is performing through June 27 at the
New York State Theater. Through May 9, the company is performing
Peter Martins' new full-length ``Swan Lake.'' Performances are
Tuesdays through Fridays at 8 p.m.; Saturdays at 2 and 8 p.m.;
Sundays at 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: $16 to $70.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (212) 870-5570.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 1650EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8210 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WEEKEND-2TAKES-NYT     04-29 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOUR OF CABLE COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the next month the network sweeps period will bring specials
based on a premise programmers cling to as if it were a life raft:
that viewers can never get enough of treacly inspirational dramas,
bloated historical pageants and exploding vehicles of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   But while Joan of Arc struggles to disarm a nuclear bomb on a
high-speed train while singing ``Baby Love'' with Diana Ross (or
something like that), the true signs of television life are
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Cable series haven't rejected stale television forms; instead
they are mocking them, turning them against themselves to wry comic
effect. The results are wildly refreshing if uneven, and offer rare
moments of iconoclasm.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend brings several tongue-in-cheek cable shows. As he
did in ``Roger and Me,'' Michael Moore brashly explodes the
documentary form in ``The Awful Truth'' on Bravo, confronting
corporate executives as he blends television with social activism
(and makes himself famous in the process). Comedy Central's
``Uncomfortably Close With Michael McKean'' sends up puffy
celebrity interviews even as the host conducts one with Jason
Alexander, sitting on his front lawn because his house is encased
in a brightly striped tent the exterminators put up.
</P>
<P>
   More startling and inventive, ``The Tom Green Show'' is a skewed
talk show with filmed comic stunts. The star, a 27-year-old
Canadian, has cross-bred David Letterman, performance art, ``South
Park'' and Howard Stern to become MTV's latest instant celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   His favorite victims are his parents, who have returned home
from work to find their house filled with llamas and goats, and
awakened to find naked women painted on the hood of their car.
</P>
<P>
   Since it began in January, ``Tom Green'' has quickly become
MTV's second highest rated series. No. 1 is ``Celebrity
Deathmatch,'' the sly, hilariously written claymation show that
mocks wrestling-mania and celebrity culture. In the ring this week:
Antonio Banderas versus Cheech Marin.
</P>
<P>
   The major networks would consider these shows subversive, though
in many respects they provide a better measure of social attitudes
than the cautious networks ever could. In their popularity, quirky
cable shows echo the public's weariness with network banalities,
yet their own vestiges of celebrity worship demonstrate how hard it
is to ignore the famous, even when your brain tells you to.
</P>
<P>
   And when they are willfully rude, as so many are, they reflect
the cultural grittiness that is given a cosmetic gloss by the
network entertainment machines.
</P>
<P>
   The theme song for ``The Tom Green Show'' sums up the host's
sensibility and deadpan spoof of the talk-show form. He sings the
kind of embarrassing ditty more likely to be heard in the privacy
of the shower. At its farthest reaches, the tune seems to extend to
four notes and the words are the essence of vapidity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Tom Green Show,'' it begins. ``It is my fa-vor-ite
show/Because it is my show.'' The song, like the show at its best,
is absurdly funny and catchy.
</P>
<P>
   The show's star has a goatee that makes him look demonic, and he
comes with two nonprofessional sidekicks. One of them, Phil, does
nothing but stand behind the fake window in back of the host's desk
(the set itself is a talk show cliche), sip coffee and give those
hearty sidekick laughs every few seconds.
</P>
<P>
   But the heart of ``The Tom Green Show'' are the mischievous
on-the-street stunts meant to shock an unsuspecting public.
</P>
<P>
   In one, he rides a cow into a grocery store. He also seems
obsessed with drinking milk straight from a cow's udder, which he
has already done twice. This is rougher than David Letterman
dropping watermelons from a window, but you can see the genealogy.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent show, Glenn, the sidekick who sits next to the desk
and actually speaks, said he wasn't able to get away from his job
at the phone company for the taping in New York. (Both sidekicks
came along from the Canadian version of the show.)
</P>
<P>
   So his head was shown on a monitor, as the 20-something audience
asked him questions perfectly in tune with their generation's
concerns and the show's bluntness. ``What kind of loser works at
the phone company?'' one asked. Another said, ``I dream of being on
television, so do you think you're better than me?''
</P>
<P>
   In a sillier mood, Tom Wopat from ``The Dukes of Hazzard'' was
interviewed while the host wore a giant string bean costume, and
his sidekick was dressed as a giant carrot. If you're going to
interview minor stars, you might as well dress like a vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom Green'' is the perfect companion to ``Celebrity
Deathmatch,'' which shares its sardonic, love-hate attitude toward
fame. Now in its second season, ``Deathmatch'' has maintained its
bright writing. Last week, Oliver Stone fought Martin Scorsese. As
the announcer said, ``The only thing these guys enjoy more than
crushing skulls is the art of cinema.''
</P>
<P>
   The match itself was complete with flashbacks, when seen from
Stone's point of view, and 360-degree camera swirls from
Scorsese's. This week's Banderas versus Marin fight is set in
Havana, with Fidel Castro as the guest referee. ``I want a good
fight; no hitting below the belt,'' he instructs the wrestlers.
``No seizing the means of production.''
</P>
<P>
   There are lots of decapitations and plenty of clay blood and
guts in ``Celebrity Deathmatch.'' But even shows that are not about
body-slamming sports come with reminders that viewers pay a price
for creativity on cable, where budgets are low and audiences young.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it helps to have the mental attitude of a 15-year-old
boy, addicted to gross-out humor. There's no delicate way to
describe the ``Tom Green Show'' stunt in which he put dog poo on
his microphone before sticking it under the noses of people on the
street, saying, ``Tell me about New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Scatological humor is centuries old, of course, but it has
rarely been used so often and with less sophistication than on
these cable shows. (The writers of ``Tom Green'' as well as Comedy
Central's ``South Park'' and its sketch comedy ``Upright Citizens
Brigade'' must have a lot to tell their therapists about their
potty training.)
</P>
<P>
   Compared to such adolescent humor, the unevenness of these shows
seems like a minor annoyance, a tradeoff for the freedom they have
to take risks. But it is tough to sustain satire; sometimes these
shows are best viewed in five-minute gulps (not the worst quality
to offer an audience prone to channel flipping).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   With some shows, five minutes is way too long. Comedy Central's
new ``Strangers With Candy'' is simply boring. The idea sounds
funny enough: Jerri Blank (played by the Off Broadway writer and
performer Amy Sedaris) is a 46-year-old former teen-age runaway, a
one-time drug addict and prostitute who returns home and picks up
her life right where she left off, as a high school freshman. Jerri
whips up a batch of drugs to get the other students to come to her
party; Jerri has a catatonic father who likes her half-brother
better than her.
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly mocking the Afterschool Specials, the show lands with
a thud, proving that irreverence is no guarantee of comic success.
Much of the problem is that Ms. Sedaris' Jerri is so abrasive and
obvious, with a perpetual frown and exaggerated overbite. The show
doesn't fail on the grounds of bad taste, but of bad comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Youth may be the main audience for cable, but it is obviously
not the only one; the studio audience gathered in Chicago for ``The
Awful Truth'' is filled with balding 30-somethings. And just as
accurately as the ``Tom Green'' theme song, the opening of ``The
Awful Truth'' positions the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the end of the millennium five men controlled the media,''
the announcer says, as we see Rupert Murdoch, Michael Eisner, Ted
Turner, Sumner Redstone and Bill Gates on top of a spinning globe.
Moore's guerrilla television means to challenge that stranglehold
on power.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing on ``The Awful Truth'' has been quite as funny or
satisfying as a segment from the first episode, in which people
dressed as Puritans chase after Ken Starr's car, waving copies of
the Starr Report and howling like extras in ``The Crucible.'' But
the show energetically reflects the lunacy of living in a corporate
culture. What celebrities are to ``Deathmatch,'' big-money
executives are to ``The Awful Truth.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, the show sends a thuggish-looking dock worker named
Sal Pirro to UPS, trying to get the company to make good on a
promise to add jobs; confronted on camera, public-relations
executives say the agreement holds only if their business
increases. Though the show's tactics got one laid-off UPS worker
his job back, Moore spends too much time being predictably
stonewalled by public-relations people.
</P>
<P>
   In two weeks Moore awards the title Year's Biggest Polluter to
the industrialist Ira Rennert and tries to deliver the award at
Rennert's Rockefeller Center office. The results are
disappointingly tame.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the show becomes lively when it documents the effects of a
temporary restraining order Rennert got, ordering Moore to stay 150
feet away. That meant Moore could not show up at NBC's ``Late Night
With Conan O'Brien,'' taped in Rockefeller Center in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien is seen doing the interview by yelling out the window at
Moore, who is standing on the sidewalk at a legally safe distance.
``The Awful Truth'' is best when it captures such absurdities.
</P>
<P>
   So is ``Uncomfortably Close With Michael McKean,'' which begins
by mocking the celebrity interview _ the supposedly surprise visit
by the interviewer, the star whose house has bugs _ and ends up
doing one anyway. Though it is closer to a genuine interview than
to the mockery of ``This Is Spinal Tap'' ( McKean's best role), it
is amiable and intelligent.
</P>
<P>
   Few shows would let its guest go on, as Alexander does, with a
dryly funny story about his abysmal audition for Twyla Tharp. (The
show is a series of occasional specials, with three more to appear
this year.)
</P>
<P>
   In a different vein, VH1's highest-rated show, ``Behind the
Music,'' calls for do-it-yourself irony. Charting the careers of
rock stars, it often focuses on stories of losers and comebacks.
Its straightforward documentary form and hyperbolic narrative are
so hokey the show becomes campy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alice embraced his strange destiny,'' the narrator says of
this week's subject, Alice Cooper, and the creation of his demonic
onstage persona. A sign of the show's impact is that ``Saturday
Night Live'' parodies it relentlessly, featuring actors as flabby,
delusional, aging rockers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the contemporary interviews with the subjects can be
remarkably candid. Alice Cooper talks about his recovery from
alcoholism, and last week's subject, Julian Lennon, about the way
he was neglected by his father, John. Perhaps the subjects open up
because they no longer have much of an image to protect, or because
the show never depicts them as less than musical geniuses.
</P>
<P>
   However seriously it takes itself, though, the series' best
episode may be the goofy classic that showed Milli Vanilli
performing onstage; when the music began repeating itself like a
broken record, they stopped lip-synching, froze for a second, then
dashed off stage.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a sardonic sensibility on the viewer's part to enter
cable's mocking world. Even then, it can take a while to get on any
show's wavelength. (Just as dipping into ``The X-Files'' for a few
minutes and expecting to get it would be futile.)
</P>
<P>
   The pithiest statement of the premise these shows are built on,
and the sharpest satire, may come from ``Upright Citizens Brigade''
(now in reruns and beginning its second season on June 15). Their
sketches include one in which people peer into a Bucket of Truth;
it seems to be an ordinary bucket but the contents, which we never
see, are evidently horrifying.
</P>
<P>
   As in ``The Awful Truth'' and other cable shows, here is a view
of the world more honest and often more entertaining than yet
another encounter with the networks' deadly Bucket of Glitz.
</P>
<P>
   Like most cable shows, these are replayed several times during
the week. Here is this weekend's schedule, along with weekly
premiere days for new episodes where they apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE TOM GREEN SHOW,'' MTV: Saturday night at 11:30. New
episodes Thursday nights at 10:30.
</P>
<P>
   ``CELEBRITY DEATHMATCH,'' MTV: Saturday night at 11. New
episodes Thursday nights at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE AWFUL TRUTH,'' Bravo: Friday night at 10. New episodes
Sunday nights at 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``UNCOMFORTABLY CLOSE WITH MICHAEL McKEAN,'' Comedy Central:
Friday night at 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``STRANGERS WITH CANDY,'' Comedy Central: Friday night at 11.
New episodes Wednesdays at 10:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``BEHIND THE MUSIC,'' VH1: Sunday morning at 11, and Sunday
night at 9 and 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``UPRIGHT CITIZENS BRIGADE,'' Comedy Central: Sunday night at
11:30 (now in repeats; new season begins June 15). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
