<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON STAGE AND OFF: NOTES AND NEWS OF THE NEW YORK THEATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Power Of a Tony Jolt
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Broadway season effectively ended Wednesday, the
deadline for Tony nominations, bringing to a close what most
theater veterans say has been an odd year, devoid of the spark of a
blockbuster new musical and witness to the continued invasion of
British and Irish plays and very few new American entries.
</P>
<P>
   The season's final days were bumpy for producers: of the five
shows that opened in the last week, four received mixed to poor
reviews. The one to receive uniformly good notices, ``It Ain't
Nothin' but the Blues,'' which opened at the Vivian Beaumont on
Monday, had lackluster sales, with only about $25,000 worth of
tickets sold on the day after the opening.
</P>
<P>
   But now begins Broadway's second season, Tony Time, the theater
world's equivalent of the postseason playoffs. While everybody
wants nominations, which will be announced on Monday, some shows
will  &UR; need &LR;  them as pegs for marketing campaigns and as morale
boosters. The next five weeks are likely to determine the fates of
several new shows that may suffer if they receive no nominations.
``Marlene,'' at the Cort Theater, has already announced its
closing.
</P>
<P>
   The most competitive Tony category will probably be best new
play, where half a dozen strong candidates must give way to four
nominees. For ``Side Man,'' Warren Leight's acclaimed jazz drama, a
Tony nomination for best play has been the goal for several months.
</P>
<P>
   The producers have stuck with the play despite consistently
shrinking audiences and many recent money-losing weeks. The play is
considered a good candidate by handicappers because it is the only
new Broadway play by a living American playwright. Another
sentimental favorite is Tennessee Williams' ``Not About
Nightingales,'' which has had slipping sales this month.
</P>
<P>
   Of David Hare's West End imports, ``The Blue Room,'' ``Amy's
View'' and ``Via Dolorosa,'' the latter two are stronger candidates
for best play. Of the other British and Irish productions, ``The
Weir'' and ``Closer'' are doing decent business and are also strong
contenders, but mixed reviews may spell trouble for ``The Lonesome
West.''
</P>
<P>
   An Advertising Assault
</P>
<P>
   A week after ``The Civil War,'' Frank Wildhorn's latest musical,
opened to a chorus of harsh reviews, the producers have rolled out
a marketing counterattack, hitting the airwaves and suburban
newspapers with a barrage of advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   The show's early financial numbers were not good. Scott Zeiger,
president of the Pace Theatrical Group, one of the production's
producers, said the daily box-office grosses since the opening have
been between $50,000 and $70,000. For the $7 million musical, the
gross for the week ending Sunday was $336,616, and Zeiger said the
weekly running costs were expected to be about $400,000, though
more is being spent on advertising now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be very cautious at this level,'' Zeiger said.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating dismissive reviews _ Wildhorn hasn't had many good
ones _ producers invested $500,000 in advertising last week, going
after suburban and tourist audiences with advertisements on
television, radio and commuter trains, as well as in regional
newspapers and airline magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is such a thing as Manhattan's theatergoing
intelligentsia,'' Zeiger said, ``it has been beaten over the head
with the message not to go to `The Civil War.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Zeiger said part of the challenge of marketing the show lay in
its title and subject, which sound ``bookish and tutorial.''
Advertisements emphasize its ``entertainment factor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The show has an advance of $2.1 million, small for a major
Broadway musical, but the thinking seems to be long-term, a
financial mindset that has sustained Wildhorn's other Broadway
musicals, ``The Scarlet Pimpernel'' and ``Jekyll and Hyde.'' Both
survived bad reviews, but neither has recouped its initial
investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's our threshold for pain?'' Zeiger asked, considering his
question for a moment. ``We believe in the show, and we're digging
deep. It's not like we need to turn it around; it didn't collapse.
We just need to do better.''
</P>
<P>
   Chasing the Blues
</P>
<P>
   Ron Taylor can't read music and says he plays spirited piano
with the style of an amateur typist. But he can sing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always had a good ear,'' Taylor said. ``I always knew what
sounded right.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment seems especially true for Taylor lately in his
role as creator, co-author, associate producer and performer in
``It Ain't Nothin' but the Blues,'' a musical survey of the history
of the blues at the Vivian Beaumont.
</P>
<P>
   ``This part is easy,'' Taylor said of performing.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, 47, is a native Texan, and appropriately large, who gave
up football for theater. His Broadway debut came in the mid-1970s
in ``The Wiz.'' He said the idea for ``Blues'' came in 1987 when he
was taking a break from playing the voice of Audrey II, the
carnivorous flower in ``Little Shop of Horrors.''
</P>
<P>
   While preparing for a role in a Hank Williams revue, he started
researching some of the century's great unknown bluesmen. ``I
thought, `When are we going to do a show on these guys?''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So Taylor wrote a outline set in a bus terminal populated by the
ghosts of bluesmen past. In fits and starts, Taylor has simplified
and developed the idea with his fellow cast members and with the
director, Randal Myler. For several years, they toured regional
theaters, eventually landing at the Crossroads Theater in New
Brunswick, N.J., and stages in New York. Gone were the bus terminal
and ghosts; only the blues remained.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a simple show with a big message,'' Taylor said. ``No
matter where you're from, no matter your culture, you can get the
blues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
