<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE KRESS FOUNDATION GIVES OLD MASTERS NEW FOCUS  
 GRAPHIC DIPLOMACY IN U.S. EMBASSIES  
 SPRING CLEANING ON THE WHITNEY ESTATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., N.Y.)  (js) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1961 the Samuel H. Kress Foundation gave more than $1 billion
worth of European art to American museums, universities and
colleges. Now, as this New York-based foundation is approaching its
75th anniversary, it is starting a program to encourage
institutions to explain the origins of European art in imaginative
ways.
</P>
<P>
   This week the foundation approved a $20 million, five-year
program, ``The Art of Europe in Context,'' to help finance projects
by museums and scholars intended to sharpen the public's awareness
of Old Master paintings: how and for whom they were made and how
they were originally viewed. Funds will also go toward the
preservation of European architecture as well as training
conservators and art historians.
</P>
<P>
   ``All works of European art in American collections are
orphans,'' said Marilyn Perry, president of the foundation. ``They
were made for a different time, place and audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Interpretative installations, historical research and
conservation projects are included in the program. ``It is from the
research of art historians and the work of art conservators that we
gain our understanding of the historical context and physical
condition,'' Dr. Perry said.
</P>
<P>
   The program also seeks to encourage cooperation between
institutions: for instance, a museum and a university. All grants
will be awarded competitively. Planning grants can be as large as
$10,000, and implementation grants can go up to $100,000. Some of
the kinds of projects the foundation is hoping to support are
special exhibitions and the creation of architectural models that
illustrate the original environment of a work of art, as well as
lectures, publications and film and video presentations.
</P>
<P>
   A series of six panels in the Denver Art Museum that were given
in 1961 to the institution by the Kress Foundation may be the
subject of one of the projects. The panels were created for a
proposed marriage between two great Italian dynasties of the 15th
century, the Gonazaga family and the Szforas, and are thought to
have been part of the sumptuous furnishings in the bedroom of an
Italian palazzo.
</P>
<P>
   When the announcement of the program was made this week, Timothy
J. Standring, the curator of paintings and sculpture at the Denver
museum, said he planned to apply for a grant that would help
recreate a bedroom using the panels along with furniture and
objects from the museum's collection to provide a historical
setting.
</P>
<P>
   Graphic Diplomacy
</P>
<P>
   In years to come U.S. embassies around the world will have an
unusual collection of American art. Besides paintings and
sculpture, they will display a selection of prints by artists like
Frank Stella, Roy Lichtenstein, Robert Rauschenberg and Ellsworth
Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   A nonprofit foundation called the Friends of Art and
Preservation in Embassies, established in 1986 to help raise the
awareness of American culture in U.S. embassies, has raised money
for art and has been given about 200 American paintings,
sculptures, works on paper, photographs, decorative objects and
pieces of folk art. On Friday, President and Mrs. Clinton are to
unveil a 10-color print by Jasper Johns that has been donated by
the artist to the foundation's print collection.
</P>
<P>
   Jo Carole Lauder, chairwoman of the Federation of Art and
Preservation in Embassies and the wife of Ronald Lauder, who was
ambassador to Austria in the mid-'80s, oversaw the print project,
which has become an annual event. Every year a committee picks an
artist who is invited to make a print, which will then be offered
to any embassy that wants it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we lived in Vienna, it was nice to show off something
American,'' Mrs. Lauder said. ``Everybody is very patriotic and
proud of what you see, especially in a building that represents our
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Johns' print recalls a combination of past and present and
includes an American flag, a photograph of Johns' father as a boy
sitting at his grandfather's knee and a version of his galaxy
image.
</P>
<P>
   Spring Cleaning
</P>
<P>
   That winning combination _ a perfect pedigree plus furniture and
decorative objects that reflect the ever-popular English-style
decor _ made for a runaway success. In three days and one night of
auctions that ended at Sotheby's in Manhattan on Sunday,
attractions included the contents of five homes owned by Betsey
Cushing Roosevelt Whitney, the New York socialite and
philanthropist who died last year. Mrs. Whitney, who was the wife
of John Hay Whitney, the financier, publisher and former ambassador
to Britain, who died in 1982, left more than $300 million worth of
art by van Gogh, Matisse, Picasso and other masters to four major
museums. Last week her two daughters, Kate Whitney and Sara
Wilford, sold the bulk of their mother's estate to help pay taxes.
</P>
<P>
   For five days Sotheby's transformed its York Avenue headquarters
into room vignettes that recreated Mrs. Whitney's many homes,
something it has successfully done for name-brand auctions like
that of Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the auction ended on Sunday, sales totaled $13.1
million, nearly twice the $7 million high estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights were a rare hand-printed copy of ``The
First Book of Urizen'' by William Blake, which set a record for the
artist when it fetched $2.5 million, and a watercolor by Sir Alfred
J. Munnings, ``Violet Munnings' Horse `Chips' at Chantilly,'' from
the late 1920s, which was sold to an unidentified collector for
another record price, $739,500. The J. Paul Getty Museum in Los
Angeles also paid a record price for a drawing by Aubrey Beardsley,
``The Dream,'' which sold for $173,000.
</P>
<P>
   There's more to come. The final installment of the Whitney
estate, a sale of fine art including works by Cezanne and Seurat,
takes place at Sotheby's on the evening of May 10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
