<SLUG> BC-OIL-RISINGPRICE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OIL, GAS PRICES RESPOND TO SIGNS THAT OPEC CUTS ARE WORKING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN PILLER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Convinced that a report of falling U.S. oil
supplies means OPEC production cuts might finally be working,
investors are pushing crude oil futures prices to their highest
levels in 16 months.
</P>
<P>
   Natural gas futures are also rising, and shares of energy
companies are surging.
</P>
<P>
   Oil prices reversed a slump this week that reflected continued
skepticism over whether OPEC producers could make good on
production cuts announced last week.
</P>
<P>
   Major oil-producing nations, led by Saudi Arabia, had tried
unsuccessfully for more than a year to impose production quotas and
stem a worldwide oil surplus. The economic recession in Asia
lowered demand, worsening the oil surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It finally looks like the big guys, Saudi Arabia and
Venezuela, are sticking to their quotas,'' a New York trader,
Chester Irvin, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Crude futures rose 64 cents on Wednesday to $18.41 on the New
York Mercantile Exchange. That price, for the June contract, was
the highest since Dec. 23, 1997. Futures prices had dipped below
$11 per barrel several times in the intervening period.
</P>
<P>
   Even better news for hard-pressed Texas producers were posted
wellhead prices _ prices that refineries and pipelines pay _ that
ranged from $15.25 per barrel to as high as $16.85. Those prices
had slumbered below $10 per barrel earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   To round out a happy day for the energy industry, natural gas
futures ended trading Wednesday at $2.34 per thousand cubic feet,
up 44 percent since February.
</P>
<P>
   The news that touched off the price and stock increases was a
report that the American Petroleum Institute released late Tuesday
showing a 4.7 million barrel decline in oil inventories in the
United States as of Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The API said U.S. oil inventories dropped from 341.1 million
barrels as of April 16 to 336.4 million barrels on April 23.
</P>
<P>
   The API report showed that imports were down 17 percent for the
week, the clearest indication that international producers were
sending less crude oil to U.S. refineries.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Kelly of API noted that the figures for last week also
were down by 6.6 million barrels from the same period a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things go into oil prices, but clearly the surplus is
being reduced,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptical energy analysts had predicted that the much-watched
weekly API report would show a reduction of about 1 million
barrels, barely a quarter of what was actually reported.
</P>
<P>
   Such a small reduction would have given credence to the widely
held notion that OPEC can no longer hold its members to any kind of
production discipline, and that new production from Iraq allowed by
the United Nations would continue to keep inventories at surplus
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Of particular interest has been Venezuela, a major exporter to
the United States. Its energy minister, Ali Rodriguez, said
Wednesday that production for the United States will fall below
targets for the remainder of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez told news services that the country's state oil
company, Petroleos de Venezuela SA, will fall short of its OPEC
quota of 2.72 million barrels per day ``due to technical reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts interpreted the report as a strong indication that new
Venezuelan president Hugo Chavez will follow OPEC guidelines and
discontinue the country's recent practice of using its energy
production as a way to generate cash.
</P>
<P>
   Natural gas prices also have strengthened on news of reduced
surpluses. The American Gas Association reported late yesterday
that supplies, while 15 percent greater than a year ago, are less
than the 20 percent increase reported last week.
</P>
<P>
   Gas prices have been strengthened by late winter and early
spring demand from utilities in regions hit by cold weather,
reduced production in the United States caused by company cutbacks
and the shutdowns of several nuclear reactors that caused their
utility owners to switch to natural gas for fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts predicted that if natural gas prices hit $2.50 per
thousand cubic feet, a buyer panic could well push the price to the
$3 range.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
