<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS-TOYS-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEW WORDS IN DEFENSE OF SWAG  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Ty Burr is a senior editor at Entertainment Weekly  
 By TY BURR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sitting on a shelf in my office are two snow-globe paperweights,
each depicting a scene from the 1996 Coen Brothers film ``Fargo.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of them, a teeny Marge Gunderson is squatting by an
overturned vehicle and a bloody dead body; in the other, she is
pointing a gun at the equally teeny figure of villain Gaear
Grimsrud as he stuffs what's left of Steve Buscemi's character into
the wood-chipper. The snowflakes in the latter globe are both white
and red. It's really cool.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, visitors to my office pick up the globes,
give them a shake, burst out laughing, and ask where they can buy
them. They can't; the ``Fargo'' tchotchkes were freebies given out
to critics like me for the film's home-video release.
</P>
<P>
   If they (italics)had(end italics) been made commercially
available, you can bet that somebody somewhere would have made a
tidy little bundle.
</P>
<P>
   As we head into the season of big movies and their little toys,
may I say a few kind words about tie-ins? The fact is, my ``Fargo''
snow globes actually enhance my appreciation of the Coens' deadpan
playfulness. At the same time, their plexiglass crassness doesn't
detract one iota from my experience of the film.
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary: whenever I glance at the wood-chipper diorama,
my mind drifts to the wonderful scene that follows, the one where
the Coens at last commit to moralism (maybe) as Marge quietly says
to Gaear: ``There is more to life than a little money. Don't you
(italics)know(end italics) that?''
</P>
<P>
   How different is that response from the emotions invoked by a
moveable Obi-Wan Kenobi action figure? Less than you think, I'd
hazard. At their worst, licensed movie tie-ins are junk. In the
case of, say, a ``Mulan'' Happy Meal at McDonald's, the toys are
intentionally disposable: miniature billboards designed solely to
make the film inescapable and, therefore, desirable.
</P>
<P>
   But at their best, the products that spin off from films serve
the same function in our pop cosmogony as religious relics did in
medieval times: They're little bits of the immaterial (too often
literally, alas) made material. That may sound specious: The
toe-joint of a saint is not the same as a Klingon-English
dictionary. On the other hand, have you ever been to a ``Star
Trek'' convention?.
</P>
<P>
   It's fitting that I write these words in the Shadow of the
Approach of ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace.'' ``Star
Wars,'' of course, is both cause and effect of the licensing
phenomonen: the property that has sold, by one estimate, $2 billion
worth of tie-ins over the years and whose success sold movie
studios on the concept that bric-a-brac profits could cover film
production losses (somehow, the idea of better scripts has yet to
occur to these people).
</P>
<P>
   I don't have to spell out the negative results: more films that
are conceived as ways to sell toys; more films that are toys
themselves. Variety recently quoted someone from Warner Brothers
describing the coming summer film ``Wild Wild West'' as ``very
toyetic.'' I know; my flesh crawled, too.
</P>
<P>
   The creeping tide of synergistic shakedowns has infected all
media, in fact, from the recent mini-series ``The Sixties,'' which
shilled its soundtrack, to ABC ``specials'' devoted to Disney
movies, to pop-music cottage industries like the Spice Girls.
</P>
<P>
   If it makes you feel any better, though, the licensing landscape
has its own sense of justice. Nothing sells worse than a toy tied
to a bad movie. Let us note, with pleasure, that when ``Godzilla''
tanked last summer, it took all those action figures and games and
sunglasses and bath accessories down the hole with it. In fact, the
secrecy-obsessed filmmakers proved to be their own worst enemy by
keeping all product off the shelves until ``Godzilla'' opened.
</P>
<P>
   A good film, on the other hand _ or, more precisely, a
successful one _ can make its merchandise mean many things. An
advertisement for the self, for one thing: Putting a ``Touch of
Evil'' re-issue poster on your wall, wearing a ``Wedding Singer''
nightshirt or toting the reproduction of the ``classic'' ``Lost in
Space'' lunchbox broadcasts your taste to the world (suffering the
consequences of that taste is, as always, your own business).
</P>
<P>
   Purchasing a $6,000 limited-edition bronze bust of Frankenstein
from Universal Studios, or a $7,500 replica of C-3PO from Party
Professionals, indicates that you have devoted your life to the
worship of one entertainment property, and also that you might be
better off with a skilled stockbroker.
</P>
<P>
   Some tie-ins even abet literacy: the glitzy paperback edition of
```Shakespeare in Love': The Love Poetry of William Shakespeare''
may make snobs cringe, but who cares if it gets people reading the
stuff?
</P>
<P>
   At their most unpretentious, tchotchkes simply extend the
inherent fun of fun movies. (Serious movies like ``Saving Private
Ryan'' get extended by way of dreadful modern-dance tributes at the
Oscars). The swag that came with the first ``Austin Powers'' comedy
_ talking keychains and the like _ was goofily enjoyable even as it
mocked the whole notion of licensed merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   The tie-ins that have been announced for this summer's ``Austin
Powers II: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' sound even better: a Mr.
Bigglesworth doll modeled after the villain's bald cat (``the
world's first hairless plush toy,'' a New Line executive has drily
noted), and a toy replica, made by Mattel's Matchbox division, of
the ``Shaguar'' that Austin Powers drives.
</P>
<P>
   For someone who still cherishes the Christmas morning memory of
unwrapping the Matchbox version of James Bond's Aston Martin (and
who mourns the disappearance of the little ejector-seat-guy under
the refrigerator 30 seconds later), this is the one that gooses my
tie-in lust.
</P>
<P>
   And, no, I won't trade you my ``Fargo'' snow globes for it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
