<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8264 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV06-     04-29 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV06-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUST IN GOD AND YOUR GIRLFRIENDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday April 6)  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Oprah was talking about her friend Maya. When
Oprah has a bad day _ she didn't tell us what gives her the blues _
she calls Maya who sometimes commiserates but mostly tells her this
crisis will pass.
</P>
<P>
   This is Oprah imitating Maya's clipped tones: ``Stop it ... Stop
it. Do you or don't you believe that your life is bigger than this
moment?''
</P>
<P>
   Oprah then advised the 6,000 women inside Moscone Center, ``Have
someone in your life who will tell you the truth about yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how many wildly successful men talk about needing
to unload on their friends. Does Bill Gates share and with whom? I
suspect that this is something that women acknowledge more, at
least publicly.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also Oprah's style. That she connects well with other
women is a $125-million-dollar-a-year fact, which is why she was
the plum draw at Mayor Willie Brown's conference on women. But she
wasn't the only one talking about subjects warmer and fuzzier than
the harsh reality of glass ceilings and disappearing affirmative
action usually discussed at women's power confabs.
</P>
<P>
   There were more than a dozen speakers for the day but two plus
Oprah stand out because they were funny, talked unabashedly of
faith and friendship and they are black, which says a lot for a
movement once chided for speaking only to middle-class white
issues, ignoring religion and having no sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   If you've never heard Dr. Lorraine Monroe speak, sign up for her
next talk. When she took over as principal of a public school in
New York City she worked with minority students to get test scores
up so that 96 percent of the graduates were accepted into college.
</P>
<P>
   This woman could unstick anyone. Not just because she herself
overcame personal odds _ parents who were high school dropouts,
violence in the home, being a latchkey kid _ but because when she
talks you start thinking you have no excuse not to go the distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of our lives is to make a difference,'' she says.
Figure out what it is and do it. For that, she advises being a
``crazy woman'' who doesn't accept precedent or rules or people who
say ``that won't work'' and ``you can't do it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be afraid of being scared,'' she said, and stay open to
all possibilities. ``Life turns in a direction and you have to be
receptive to the angels.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't hang out with people who fret about what might happen, zap
your energy and don't respect your dreams. ``The dream killers,''
she calls them.
</P>
<P>
   She also says spend time ``to get back to you,'' which sounds a
lot like meditating. If you have no other time, go into the
bathroom, lock the door and ``have a vision quest.''
</P>
<P>
   For her time out, Oprah spends 15 minutes every morning with her
eyes closed talking to God.
</P>
<P>
   Singer Bertice Berry asks for help gospel style instead of
praying.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, a comedian, talk-show host and author, had everyone in
the audience - bank managers, steelworkers, women in saris and
purple hair _ turn to their neighbor and say how much we loved and
believed in each other.
</P>
<P>
   It's because she worries that ``Women don't support each other
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter, she said, who's a CEO or a welfare recipient,
``You don't have to understand my purpose to be in support of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Switching to humor, Berry, who is a gorgeous, big woman, said
she was sick of Monica talk but had to wonder ``If the president of
the United States prefers a large woman, shouldn't everyone?''
</P>
<P>
   On the same subject Oprah patted one silk-covered hip and said
``size 14. Amen 14.'' The audience roared back, ``Amen 14.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a girlfriend thing.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartz(AT)pressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
