<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTING-TOUR-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL WINE EXPERTS TOUR WEST COAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PEG MELNIK   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ Robin Don said ``Hello,'' in a British
clip, tipped his beige hat and then struggled to keep it from
flapping away in the Carneros wind.
</P>
<P>
   Don and 35 of his colleagues are wine know-it-alls with a degree
to prove it. This week they were in the Carneros, the Appellation
at the southern base of Napa and Sonoma counties, visiting Acacia
Winery.
</P>
<P>
   These scholars, each with a Master of Wine degree (M.W.), are on
a mission, touring and tasting their way through California, Oregon
and Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   While people in the wine trade travel through California with
some regularity, this international group has cachet. Most hail
from the United Kingdom, where people with an M.W. are said to
control 60 to 65 percent of the wine buying power as retailers,
distributors and importers.
</P>
<P>
   Don is from Norfolk, England, and has a cellar planning business
called Hicks and Don. As an M.W., Don has traveled to every
continent in the world, to every major vineyard area. Don was in
California 18 years ago on an official trip to the United States,
and he says he has already witnessed a remarkable change in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those days my impression was that nearly every winery was
trying to grow every kind of vine to make both table wines and
fortified wines,'' Don says. ``It was very clear to me that some
areas were much more suitable to certain varieties over others.
From what I've seen so far, things are being sorted out.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Hall, a vineyard consultant for Acacia and several other
area wineries, stood on a knoll with Don and his colleagues, a
huddle of M.W.s, overlooking the San Francisco Bay. Hall pointed
out rows of chardonnay and pinot noir grapes, explaining that the
appellation's shallow clay soils and cool climate bode well for
these varietals. She added that Carneros, perhaps more than any
other appellation, has made a commitment to these varietals, with
most of its vines planted to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our small vines are not particularly vigorous, so we get less
crop and the intensity that winemakers are looking for,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After the vineyard tour, the M.W.s stepped inside the winery for
a tasting of Carneros wines, a flight of chardonnay and two flights
of pinot noir.
</P>
<P>
   Between the pinot noir flights, Arabella Woodrow, who lives
north of Edinburgh, Scotland, said that since her last visit in
1985 ``I've seen a great development in new grape varieties
throughout California. I'm seeing more Rhone varietals and more
Italian varietals. It's changed a lot in 20 years when cabernet
sauvignon and chardonnay were the usual suspects.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodrow is a wine buyer for Forth Wines Ltd., a firm which
imports wine and sells it wholesale. Woodrow says she already sells
a great deal of California wine but now she's inclined to sell
more.
</P>
<P>
   Dermot Noland, an educator and a free-lance consultant from
Dublin, Ireland, occasionally advises importers and retailers.
Dermot said he's reserving judgment until the end of the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``My experience with California wines isn't that great,'' he
said. ``I look forward to see how they fit in with the wines of the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   The economic might of these M.W.s is not lost on vintners intent
on showing their most impressive wines. While the M.W.s are paying
for their own flights and accommodations, a host of wineries are
eager to wine and dine them. The long list includes Gallo of
Sonoma, Kendall-Jackson Vineyards, Beaulieu Vineyards, Opus One and
Robert Mondavi Winery. The M.W.s have even been invited to a
private dinner at the home of Robert Mondavi, an honorary M.W.
</P>
<P>
   Vintners know that the United Kingdom is the United States'
biggest value importer. In 1998 the United States shipped $143
million of wine to the United Kingdom or 16,851,000 gallons of
wine. What's more, the United States is expected to double that
amount in the next three to five years, according to Joe Rollo,
director of the Wine Institute International .
</P>
<P>
   Rollo says the distinction with M.W. travelers is that they
perhaps have ``a keener set of eyes and can put our California wine
industry into perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   To earn an M.W., wine enthusiasts study for three to five years,
pass a four-day exam and write a dissertation. There are only 224
in the world and a total of 19 in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute of Masters of Wine, with its headquarters in
London, was established in 1955 to promote the highest level of
educational achievement for the wine industry. The Institute
organizes trips to wine growing regions every two years.
</P>
<P>
   (Peg Melnick writes for The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa,
Calif.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
