u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTHRAX-VACCINE-SAFET     04-29 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTHRAX-VACCINE-SAFETY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAO CAN'T DETERMINE IF ANTHRAX VACCINE IS SAFE OR EFFECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional investigators reported Thursday that
they cannot determine whether the controversial anthrax vaccine
being administered to U.S. military personnel is safe or effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``The long-term safety of this vaccine has not yet been studied
and therefore one cannot conclude that there are no long-term
effects,'' said Kwai-Cheung Chan, the director of the national
security and international affairs division of the General
Accounting Office, the investigative arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO also said there are not enough studies to determine
whether the vaccine would actually protect U.S. forces from
becoming infected by the deadly anthrax disease if they are exposed
to the bacteria that causes it.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO reported its findings Thursday at a House Government
subcommittee on veterans affairs committee hearing on anthrax. The
panel's chairman, Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., is investigating
the Defense Department's mandatory anthrax vaccine program after
several service members raised questions about the vaccine's
safety.
</P>
<P>
   The anthrax program ``seems a very broad undertaking built on a
very narrow foundation,'' Shays said. He said he believes the
program should be voluntary, but has no plans to introduce
legislation that would make such a change until additional hearings
are held on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 service members have either resigned or been
disciplined for refusing to take the anthrax vaccination, according
to the Pentagon. Service members who testified at a congressional
hearing last month said many more service members were afraid of
the unknown long-term health effects, but were pressured by
superiors to take the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is that we don't have that much experience with
human studies,'' said Rep. John Mica, R-Fla., ``I'm wondering if
this forced vaccination is that effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the federal Food and Drug Administration, which licensed
the vaccine, and Defense Department officials reiterated Thursday
their beliefs that the vaccine is safe, effective and necessary to
protect service members who are at high risk of being exposed to
anthrax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anthrax is a major military threat faced by our armed
forces,'' said Army Brig. Gen. Eddie Cain. ``Death is the usual
outcome...of exposure to anthrax.''
</P>
<P>
   Cain, who manages the Defense Department's program for
biological defense, said more than 10 countries, including Iraq,
either possess anthrax or are suspected of having it.
</P>
<P>
   Anthrax is easy to manufacture in large quantities and can
easily be distributed as dry spores. An individual becomes infected
by inhaling the spores. If infected, a person can develop flu-like
symptoms, rapidly deteriorate and die within a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Cain said he recently received the fourth of the six shots
necessary to be vaccinated against anthrax. The shots are given
over an 18-month period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you I have no reservations about taking the
vaccine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But other service members, including three technicians from the
110th Fighter Wing Air National Guard Base in Battle Creek, Mich.,
testified that they do have reservations about the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta K. Groll, a technical sergeant with the Air National
Guard, said she has become ``seriously ill'' since receiving her
fourth vaccination on March 14. She said she felt like she had a
bad case of the flu, but on March 19 experienced a ``severe tremor
in my right arm and shortness of breath.'' She said her physician
told her she was having a severe reaction to the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   David J. Churchill, another technical sergeant, said he had no
reservations about the vaccine until he began suffering from severe
fatigue and body aches after receiving his fourth shot last month.
He said at least 11 other people also became sick after receiving
the fourth shot and have missed several days of work.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such anecdotes, Pentagon officials maintain that most of
the 223,000 vaccinated soldiers, sailors, airmen and marines have
experienced few side-effects. The Defense Department aims to
vaccinate 2.4 million active-duty and reserve military members by
2005.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department has conducted on-going studies of the
effectiveness of the anthrax vaccine in animals. The GAO said while
the studies show that the vaccine is effective in animals it does
not mean it is effective in humans. The GAO noted, however, that
DOD has started studies aimed at determining whether the animal
studies can be translated to determine how humans would react to
the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine, approved by the FDA in 1970, has been used by
livestock workers, veterinarians and military lab technicians since
the mid-1970s. The vaccine was originally designed to protect
humans from anthrax transmissions from sheep or goats.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that for persons at high risk (of exposure to
anthrax), the vaccine is safe and effective,'' said Kathryn Zoon,
M.D. the director of the FDA's center for biologics evaluations and
research.
</P>
<P>
   She said human clinical trials on the vaccine were conducted in
the 1950s and additional research was conducted by the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention in the 1960s that formed the basis
for the FDA's decision to license the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO said that the 1950s study, however, focused on whether
the vaccine was effective in preventing anthrax from penetrating
the skin and could not determine whether the vaccine was effective
in stopping anthrax disease in individuals who inhaled
anthrax-causing spores.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO refused to take a position on whether it was safe for
the military's anthrax vaccination program to continue but said the
use of masks and antibiotics could also stop anthrax infection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
