<SLUG> BC-MCMANUS-OUTCASTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADULTS, KIDS SHOULD REACH OUT TO `OUTCASTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Religion Commentary)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Mike McManus is a syndicated columnist whose ``Ethics &AMP;
Religion'' appears in almost 100 newspapers)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By MIKE McMANUS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    How could so many adults around the Littleton killers ignore so
many red flags?
 &HT;    Eric Harris had a sawed-off barrel of a shotgun on his dresser
and bombmaking materials in plain sight. Why didn't his parents ask
hard questions that could have averted the tragedy?
 &HT;    Harris and Dylan Klebold had made a video for a government class
that portrayed them killing athletes. Why wasn't the teacher
alarmed?
 &HT;    The parents of a boy threatened by Harris contacted police eight
times to report the threats, such as a computer game Harris created
that revolved around destroying their house. On his Web site,
Harris included instructions on how to make pipe bombs. Though
Harris was on probation, no further investigation was made. Such
neglect seems criminal.
 &HT;    More alarming, a Washington Post poll reports that a fifth of
high school students know someone who has brought a gun to school;
a third have heard students threaten to kill others and 40 percent
can think of students in their schools who are troubled enough to
be potential killers.
 &HT;    Therefore, President Clinton has proposed several gun-control
laws that deserve support:
 &HT;    1. Raise the minimum age for possessing handguns and
semi-automatic assault rifles to 21. The 18-year-old girl friend of
Klebold bought an assault pistol and a rifle at a recent gun show
that were used in the Littleton massacre.
 &HT;    2. Require background checks on people buying weapons at gun
shows or explosives.
 &HT;    3. Limit the number of handguns that can be purchased to one per
month. When Virginia passed such a law, the number of Virginia guns
used in New York crimes fell by more than half.
 &HT;    4. Restore a waiting period before the purchase of a pistol, a
Brady law that expired.
 &HT;    5. A Child Access Prevention (CAP) law would hold a gun owner
responsible for any crimes committed with his gun by a child. Since
16 states passed CAP laws, accidental deaths dropped an average of
23 percent, says Handgun Control. Guns kill 13 children every day.
 &HT;    6. Require new guns to have a safety lock with a combination
known only to the owner. As a 9-year-old, I remember opening my
father's sock drawer, where he kept his pistol. He once showed me
how to take out the clip, which I did, thinking that removed its
bullets. I put the gun into my mouth, then took it out and pulled
the trigger. BLAM! I shot a bullet into the drawer.
 &HT;    These laws would reduce deaths of young people. But far more
profound changes are needed. Most important, parents need to spend
more time with their kids.
 &HT;    I know a young woman who dressed in Gothic black in high school
because it was how she felt about the neglect of her parents and
their consuming drive for material success. Though other kids
mocked her, she felt she had to express the pain that was inside.
And the clothes formed a bond with other outcasts who hung
together. They hated the athletes and the Christians. But she was
not violent, not promiscuous, not a Satan worshipper.
 &HT;    A question for Christian kids: Why not reach out and befriend
someone who dresses differently? Wouldn't that demonstrate the love
of the Lord that you feel?
 &HT;    A week before the Littleton tragedy, Virginia's Attorney General
Mark Earley gathered 300 religious leaders in a Faith Summit to
consider mentoring young children as an answer for school violence.
He noted that he visited every juvenile detention center and met
one-on-one with 35 kids imprisoned for violent crime. ''With the
exception of one person, all of them came from homes in which a
father was not meaningfully present.''
 &HT;    Though he is a father of six children, ages 2 to 16, Earley
decided to become a ''Lunch Buddy'' to a fourth-grade boy, who is
at risk. He eats with him only once a month. The first time they
met, the little guy said, ''I'm so glad I have a lunch buddy.''
 &HT;    Another speaker was Virgil Gulker, who has created a church
mentoring program called Kids Hope that has matched up volunteers
who pledge to meet with one child once a week for one year. He
noted that suicide among children aged 14 and under is up 75
percent. Why? ''Kids are giving up finding that person who will
value them.
 &HT;    ''Don't tell me Jesus loves these children,'' Gulker says. ``So
what? Jesus does not have arms to hug them. He can't say their
names. He can't read to them. He can't laugh with them. We can.''
 &HT;    To learn more, call Kids Hope 616 846-7490.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1999 Mike McManus
<TEXT>
