<HEADLINE>
`LIMBO' MEANS WHAT IT SAYS  
 CREATING EFFECTS 
A HIP `TARZAN'
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska)   (rk) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ It is a season of certainty in Hollywood, at least
as far as story lines in popular movies are concerned. There is
often a very pronounced difference between the good guys and the
bad guys, and movies tend to end on a note of clarity.
</P>
<P>
   There is a winner and a loser, a resolution. It is no accident
that many movies now are based on comic books, which tend to have a
clear conception of good and right.
</P>
<P>
   John Sayles attacks that approach in his latest movie,
``Limbo.'' In fact, few films have ever been as ambiguous as
``Limbo,'' Sayles' 12th movie, which will play at the Cannes Film
Festival in May and is to open in theaters in the United States on
June 4. Suffice it to say that the word ``cliffhanger'' hardly
captures the uncertain note on which the film abruptly ends, on a
lonely, wooded island off the Alaskan coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why it's called `Limbo,''' said Sayles, who wrote,
directed and edited the picture. ``One of the things about an
ending to a movie is it should send you back to the movie itself,
and it should make sense. This movie is about risks, emotional and
physical, and so I want it to end focused on that, not what happens
to them ultimately. People will fill in the end for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie is about a group of good-hearted misfits in Juneau,
Alaska, who slowly work their way into each other's lives. David
Strathairn plays a fisherman who no longer fishes because of an
accident years earlier in which two of his friends were killed;
Mary Elizabeth Mastrantino plays a lounge singer who stumbles into
one bad relationship after another before falling for him, and
Vanessa Martinez plays her daughter, who is afraid of drawing close
to anyone because of her mother's tempestuous love life.
</P>
<P>
   Little by little, they begin to pull together when they find
themselves at a physical risk that mirrors the emotional risks they
are taking in trying to build a family.
</P>
<P>
   Sayles said the movie's tone was a throwback to the 1960s and
'70s, when ambiguity was more usual. ``I don't think it's as common
now to end a movie on a question as it was in the '60s and 70s,''
he said. ``Those were the days of the counterculture and
challenging authority. Heroes were flawed.''
</P>
<P>
   At the least, Sayles added, films with open endings make
audiences think. ``What you're hoping for is you don't want someone
to consume your movie like a fast-food meal and then forget about
it,'' he said. ``You don't want them to walk away thinking about
other movies, but about their own lives. This may do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Creating Effects
</P>
<P>
   George Lucas' ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' is
expected to be a major hit when it is released in May in a business
sorely hurting for blockbuster-size profits. But the film also
marks a coming of age for computerized special effects.
</P>
<P>
   When Lucas produced his first three ``Star Wars'' pictures, he
all but invented the modern special-effects industry. He made
innovative uses of computers and models of space ships, aliens and
the like to create realistic images of faraway worlds and far-out
characters. He eventually organized this expertise into a company,
Industrial Light and Magic, which was a pioneer in the
special-effects world and which rode the crest of Hollywood's huge
special-effects boom.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``The Phantom Menace'' is perhaps the most
sophisticated and one of the most costly special-effects pictures
ever made, it comes as Hollywood's ardor for the computer has
cooled, said Jim Morris , president of Lucas Digital, the parent
company of Industrial Light and Magic. He said this was partly
because of the costs, and partly because audiences were no longer
thrilled by what had become run-of-the-mill effects, like brilliant
explosions. As a result, the industry has been in something of a
recession.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a real cooling at the studios in green-lighting
these pictures, and some of the infrastructure built up is
collapsing under its own weight because there's not enough work
going around,'' Morris said. He said his company had been kept on
an even keel because of its work on ``The Phantom Menace,'' as well
as ``The Mummy,'' ``Wild, Wild West'' and a large number of
television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said roughly half the new ``Star Wars'' movie's $120
million budget was used to produce special effects, an unusually
high figure. He added that the picture had more computerized
effects than almost any previous live-action film, with about 2,000
special-effects shots, compared with 200 or so in a regular
special-effects movie.
</P>
<P>
   In making ``The Phantom Menace,'' Industrial Light and Magic
geared up considerably, from about 650 employees a couple of years
ago to about 1,000 now. In addition, it had to make huge
investments in computers and software.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said that when the original ``Star Wars'' pictures were
made, about 90 percent of the costs of creating special effects was
labor, and 10 percent computers. Today, he said, the ratio is about
half and half because of the growing expense of computer stations
and software.
</P>
<P>
   Morris also said that in the old days, the Industrial Light
crews often had to put in grinding hours and seven-day weeks to
complete their work. Now, he said, the company has learned to pace
itself better.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing their best work ever because they're not coming
in in a haze of exhaustion,'' Morris said. ``We avoided the
last-minute crunch.'' And so now, he said, several weeks before the
movie opens, many of the staff members have already left for
well-deserved vacations.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
