<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8338 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-PUNK-SPI &LR;      04-29 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PUNK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SLC PUNK' MAKES YOUTHFUL ANARCHY BORING AND PREDICTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nicholas Ray achieved it in ``Rebel Without A Cause.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It'' is capturing that elusive thing called teenage angst.
It's tough enough to present angry, rebellious teenagers in a
movie. But it's another thing entirely to impossibly stack the deck
by making them irresponsible, vain, self-laudatory and hell-bent on
a sort-of revenge as well.
</P>
<P>
   If only first-time writer and director James Merendino had
learned this lesson early on. In ``SLC Punk,'' which pulls from
Ray's classic as well as Gus Van Sant's spare, lean and
non-judgmental ``My Own Private Idaho,'' the kids are the ones who
won't forgive the adults for the world in which they are born. They
won't allow anyone other than themselves to err, be foolish _ or
out of control. Consequently, they come off as more priggish than
the parents who are products of their own generational mess.
</P>
<P>
   ``SLC'' stands for Salt Lake City and Merendino claims he lived
in Mormon territory in 1985. Though he says this first film is a
work of fiction, it's more a cinematic exorcism. It's way too
personal, mad and whiny to be entirely a work of the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   The title's joke is supposed to ask ``who knew there were punks
in Salt Lake City?'' A more obvious question might be, ``Where
better than in a place known for its right-wing, conservative
values?''
</P>
<P>
   But in this unforgiving, cold glance at growing up with a chip
on the shoulder, rich-kid punk protagonist and narrator Stevo
(Matthew Lillard) is so smug he can't see beyond his own attitude.
His mohawk-shorn best friend, Heroin Bob (Michael Goorjian), is
less assured. His family is itinerant and he is struggling to make
his place in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Between the pair, we're given a tour of endless drinking
parties, clubs, music, fights, random sex and typical teenage
foolishness. But Merendino has made a mistake in handing the
narration to Stevo _ a bright bum of a guy who just happens to
throw away every chance he gets. We can't engage with him or feel
his angst because he won't let anyone in and he feels superior to
boot.
</P>
<P>
   The quiet Heroin Bob, on the other hand, is the best thing in
this ``complex world of fascism that is Utah.'' Goorjian has a
puppy dog face that conveys his every thought. His complex
performance fuels the film and compensates for Lillard's drooly
baby-faced wimpiness _ a trademark of the ``Scream'' actor that is
beginning to grow wearisome.
</P>
<P>
   Bob has fallen in love with the worldly Trish (Annabeth Gish)
and decides he wants to marry her. He's searching for a place in
the punk realm while enduring being the butt of a joke that reveals
``Heroin Bob'' is a sham name. It seems he hasn't taken a drug in
his life and refuses to have anything to do with mind-altering
substances.
</P>
<P>
   Bob and Stevo struggle to find answers. And just when a flash of
reason rains upon them, tragedy strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the film disintegrates too, becoming just another
indie movie about not taking responsibility for one's actions,
while making it seem glamorous and cool to stay on the fringe. It's
an unenlightening film that proves youthful anarchy is just as dull
as a midlife crisis, and sadly, as predictable, too.
</P>
<P>
   SLC Punk. Directed and written by James Merendino. Cast: Matthew
Lillard, Michael Goorjian, Annabeth Gish. Sony Pictures Classics.
97 minutes. Rated R for language, sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
