<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8339 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRY-FOOD-NYTR &LR;      04-29 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRY-FOOD-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY FEELS DEMANDS TO FEED MILLENNIAL HUNGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BOB NORBERG   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEBASTOPOL, Calif. _ Apple processor Vacu-dry is used to seeing
demand for its dried, vacuum-packed foods rise and fall with crises
such as wars and monetary turbulence.
</P>
<P>
   But it has never seen anything like the demand generated by the
Year 2000 computer glitch. The company's sales to soared 1,000
percent earlier this year, although they have been slowing
recently. The reason: People stockpiling dried foods because they
fear economic chaos when the year 2000 arrives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The products have always been bought by some church members
who believe they need to be prepared for emergencies, by
survivalists and by those concerned about world crises,'' said
Vacu-dry president Gary Hess. ``But the last nine months' sales
have been 10 times the annual average.''
</P>
<P>
   The Y2K computer glitch, or Millennium Bug, refers to the
problem some computers and computer programs have in recognizing
the date Jan. 1, 2000, which could lead to inaccuracies or computer
failures.
</P>
<P>
   Opinions on the impact of Y2K range from those who feel it will
be almost imperceptible to those who predict chaos, including
financial failures, blackouts and shortages of fuel, food and
water.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Vacu-dry comes in. In addition to processing
apples, Vacu-dry also owns Perma-Pak, a line of vacuum-packed food
products ranging from raspberries to imitation beef that have a
shelf life of 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Perma-Pak products are sold largely by retailers who specialize
in emergency supplies of food, water and survival equipment. The
foods are usually packaged as one-year supplies of food, broken
into daily meals of 2,000 calories, and sold for about $1,500 to
$1,700. Many of the sales are made using the Internet, toll-free
numbers and mail.
</P>
<P>
   The largest seller of Perma-Pak products is Preparedness
Resources Inc. of Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Trent Holland, who with his father, Vern Holland, owns Emergency
Food Storage in American Fork, Utah, also deals in Perma-Pak
products and said Vacu-dry is merely experiencing the impact of
people getting prepared for Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the increase has been the Y2K panic,'' said Holland,
who has seen his company's sales go from $5,000 a week to $30,000 a
day. ``They believe everything will shut down and they will need to
have a food source.''
</P>
<P>
   Holland said sales fluctuate, increasing during times of
international stress, such as Operation Desert Storm in Iraq in
1991. But Y2K has been the biggest boost yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sales kind of go up and down, but as soon as the Y2K panic
hit, sales hit the roof,'' Holland said.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Larsen, a Santa Rosa anesthesiologist, bought a year's
supply of Perma-Pak meals last year, when Y2K fear was at its
highest, and is glad he did, even as Y2K fears ease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel comfortable having a year's supply of food,'' Larsen
said. ``It just makes me feel calm and relaxed. I'm glad I have
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hess said that two years ago, guessing that the Y2K computer
glitch would lead people to stockpile food, Vacu-dry rebuilt and
updated its Sebastopol production line for Perma-Pak products, a
line that Vacu-dry purchased in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   The products include fruits, vegetables, meat substitutes, dairy
products, beverages, grains, legumes, soup and corn starch that are
put through a special process for packaging.
</P>
<P>
   In the packaging process, cans are put into a vacuum to suck out
the oxygen, then flushed with nitrogen and filled with food. It
leaves the can with less than 1 percent oxygen, assuring a long
shelf life, said Vacu-dry product manager Chip Ruble.
</P>
<P>
   Between November and March, the production line ran in three
shifts as employment at Vacu-dry went from 275 employees to 350.
Officials declined to give production figures, except to say
production went up tenfold. The product is stored in Sebastopol and
in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Hess said the first increase in sales was noticed in March 1998
and peaked between January and March of this year, when Vacu-dry
posted its record earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Led by the sales of Perma-Pak, Vacu-dry in the third quarter of
this fiscal year, which covers January through March, had earnings
of $1.2 million, 77 cents a share, compared to $134,000 for the
same quarter a year ago, or 9 cents a share, said Bill Hartman,
Vacu-dry controller.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock, which is traded on Nasdaq, also has
fluctuated, trading between $6 and $12 during the past year.
Recently it has traded at around $8.
</P>
<P>
   Since March, Perma-Pak sales have declined as the U.S.
government, utilities, hospitals, banks and businesses began
reporting on efforts to deal with the Y2K issue.
</P>
<P>
   Hess said he expects sales will get back to the recent high
levels as the new year approaches and people who may have put off
stockpiling food and water start to prepare again.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
