<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, April 30, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Between five and eight inches of snow fell in the Spring
Mountains of southern Nevada Wednesday night and early Thursday as
a cold, upper-level low pressure system drifted east across the
region.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the lofty cold low will continue to produce pockets
of mountain snows across the southern Rockies as its eastward
advance remains blocked by a massive high pressure system covering
the Middle West. Showers and a few rumbles of thunder will affect
the valleys. Thunder is possible. The combination of clouds and
showers will keep daytime temperatures 15 to 20 degrees below
average in some of the deserts of southern Nevada, including the
city of Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   With the pattern brought to a standstill by the unyielding high
over the midwest, a steady stream of moist air will continue to
ascend the sloping terrain of west Texas, eastern New Mexico and
southern Colorado, setting the stage for recurrent rains that could
lead to flash flooding in some areas. Severe thunderstorms are
possible in west Texas as moist Gulf air is further lifted by a jet
stream disturbance pinwheeling east around the stalled Nevada low.
</P>
<P>
   In the Southeast, interior showers and a few thunderstorms will
shift toward the coast as a weakening upper-level low pressure
system migrates seaward. Pockets of light rain may linger in the
southern Appalachians as moist winds from the Atlantic ascend the
terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a cool morning will be followed by a sunny, mild
afternoon, although cumulus clouds will build over parts of the
Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Welcome Rain
</P>
<P>
   Rain totaled 1.23 inches at Orlando, Florida, on Wednesday,
setting a record for the date. After a long dry spell, welcome
rains followed an increase in tropical moisture. The trigger for
rain came from the sea breeze, which developed in concert with
cooler air from the Atlantic spreading inland. At the sea-breeze
front, which marks the leading edge of the inbound ocean air, very
warm and moist air over the land was lifted, setting the stage for
showers and thunderstorms. Without the reliable sea breeze and its
front, Florida's summer rainy season would be, on average, much
less rainy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
