<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8363 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-LORDS-NYTSF     04-29 1644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-LORDS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 LORDS OF THE HORIZONS
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Jason Goodwin.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 352 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Henry Holt &AMP; Company. $32.50.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; THE GLORY DAYS OF THE GRAND TURK
</P>
<P>
   BY FOUAD AJAMI
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The clock towers gave the thing away: shortly before the end
came for the Ottoman state in the latter years of the 19th century,
the rulers and the would-be reformers began to erect these towers
in their cities and towns, outside mosques or on the town squares.
Built for the most part by the royal architects, the Armenian
Balian family, those towers, Jason Goodwin tells us in this
arresting evocation of the Ottoman centuries, caught the confusion
of the Ottoman Empire. In their years of valor and triumph, the
Ottomans had not bothered with time and had dealt with it in a
lordly way. Now their confidence had cracked, and those towers --
some of which resembled minarets, others made in the shape of
pagodas or campaniles -- were a desperate attempt to graft onto the
Ottoman world the punctual ways of the West. It didn't work. ``The
harder the empire tried to secularize time,'' Goodwin writes, ``the
more absolutely ordinary it became,'' and the people of this
sprawling state grew ``disputatious and querulous'' by the day.
</P>
<P>
   We were bound to come around to the Ottomans. The furies of
nationalism in former Ottoman dominions in the Balkans have made
urgent a retrospect of that world. The power of the Turks has
disappeared, Communist rule has now slipped away, and what has
risen from the grave to avenge ancient slights is a pitiless
nationalism, one that mocks all those who thought that after the
Ottomans would come a better, more enlightened age.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Goodwin, a gifted English travel writer and journalist,
has gone back over the material of the Ottoman Empire, and returned
with a work of dazzling beauty. ``Lords of the Horizons'' is a
hybrid book -- part travel chronicle, part popular history and a
meditation on a vanished world that hovers like an apparition over
today's grim headlines. Goodwin's is a gift akin to that of Jan
Morris, the rare coming together of historical scholarship and
curiosity about distant places with luminous writing. Goodwin has
read deeply around the Ottoman world, and he takes his readers
effortlessly from the empire's modest beginnings, in the scrub
lands of the Eurasian steppe, through its time of ascendancy in the
15th and 16th centuries, to its time of lumbering sloth and
weakness in the 19th and early 20th centuries. He does it in a
beguiling way, the pace of his narrative catching, at times, the
speed and swiftness of those Ottoman horsemen of the frontier in
their days of glory, and then the ponderous style of a decaying
empire that answered the calls for reform with pretense and show
and outright cruelty -- as well as with a frenzy of palace building
that could not lift the gloom, as the unhappy sultans ``dragged the
terrible burden of their line from one palace to the next.''
</P>
<P>
   The origins of that great Ottoman enterprise have the simplicity
and the obscurity of the frontier. The Turkmen had quit the steppe
in the ninth century; they had adopted Islam, and the faith, a
``stripped-down, low-slung, racing sort'' of Islam, had carried
them into a vast imperial possession. They moved relentlessly
westward. A bey (lord) by the name of Osman began the great
imperial venture in the early years of the 14th century. His domain
was small, but Byzantium, all around him, was doomed. The Byzantine
city of Bursa at the end of the Silk Road fell to the new
conquerors in 1327. The factionalism of the Byzantine world gave
Osman and his descendants the space they needed, and took them
across the Sea of Marmara into Thrace. There, and across the Balkan
valleys, they were to discover ``a shepherd's paradise of cooling
water, greenery and shade.'' Edirne (Adrianople to the Greeks), the
region's capital, fell to them in 1362.
</P>
<P>
   With a world there for the plucking, the Ottomans came into the
inheritance of Byzantium and beyond: Constantinople in 1453, Athens
in 1456. Serbia was folded into the empire in 1459, Bosnia in
1462-66, Albania in 1468, Herzegovina in 1481. ``So hypnotic was
the Turks' advance,'' Goodwin writes, ``so rascally, duplicitous
and divided were their enemies, so beguilingly gentle was the way
they tickled their vassals to the halter, so otherworldly did their
success appear, that two centuries later Luther himself . . .
wondered piously aloud whether they should be opposed at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In the nationalist histories -- 36 nations were, by one count,
incorporated into this Ottoman edifice -- it was a terrible tale of
conquest and subjugation. But the truth was different. The Turks
created what the great historian Fernand Braudel described as
``structures of collaboration.'' There had been no great missionary
impulse in the Turkish incursions, no urge to extirpate the old
ways, nothing here akin to the spirit Spain brought to the New
World. This empire was a polyglot world: ``It was, by common
consent, a Turkish empire, but most of its dignitaries and
officers, and its shock troops, too, were Balkan Slavs. Its
ceremonial was Byzantine, its dignity Persian, its wealth Egyptian,
its letters Arabic. . . . Its most brilliant sailors were all
Greek. Its canniest merchants were Armenian.'' The Greek world had
been overwhelmed by the Ottomans, to be sure. But Greeks had
``sniffed the wind,'' Goodwin observes, and had made their own
accommodation with the Ottoman order.
</P>
<P>
   It began early, that accommodation. No sooner had Sultan Mehmet
the Conqueror claimed Constantinople as his city and his imperial
capital than he offered the Orthodox Church his protection. He
styled himself as the inheritor of the Caesars, and in the Church
of the Holy Apostles, in January of 1454, he enthroned a learned
monk, George Scholarios, as Patriarch Gennadius II, handing him his
staff as Byzantine emperors in days past had done. The Serbs, too,
currently hacking away at all things Ottoman, at all the traces
Islam left behind, made their own peace with Turkish rule, finding
their way into the court and armies of the empire. (It was
hindsight, and 19th-century romantic nationalism, that made the
Battle of Kosovo in 1389, when the Serbs met the Turks on the Field
of Blackbirds, just outside the town of Pristina, a great divide in
Serbian history.)
</P>
<P>
   Such imperial luck was not destined to last; this pastoral
empire of the borderlands had grown too large, too complex, for its
rulers. There is no precise date, no fixed event, to attach to its
decline, which set in with the closing years of the 16th century.
In retrospect, inflation and a price revolution triggered by the
silver bullion of the new world had unsettled the realm. It had
devastated those living on rent and fixed incomes. No one quite
knew it, but the frontier had closed. A scramble had begun for
state employment. Between 1640 and 1656, the number of salaried
officials rose from 60,000 to 100,000. A great struggle was waged
for mastery over the Mediterranean between Spain and the Ottoman
state. Venice mediated that conflict, winked at the antagonists,
looked after its trading interests. Fate had its own cunning. In
Goodwin's summation: ``The three great Mediterranean powers,
Venice, Spain and the empire itself, all soon toppled into a
decline as protracted as it was profound, and a note of exhaustion
stole across the whole Mediterranean world.''
</P>
<P>
   Plunder and caprice now sought to squeeze from the realm the
booty and the wealth that once had been obtained in war. Then the
peoples of this diverse empire began ``to huddle together for
security.'' Nationalism came into this Ottoman world, the one force
that it couldn't withstand. The philologists and the poets, and the
winds of nationalism blowing in from Europe, and the Philhellenes
dreaming of a restored Greek world, unleashed on this multinational
edifice demands it could never accommodate. Russia was seized with
a new messianic impulse, a determination to restore Christian
worship to the Church of St. Sophia, and the Greek and Slavic
peoples within the ramshackle Ottoman domain lost their taste for
the Ottoman world and its limitations.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that the clock towers were built, and the palaces
with heavy chandeliers, and the promises of reform became a daily
occurrence, and the realm grew more repressive. It was then that an
insolvent empire took up its first foreign loans, in the 1850's,
only to succumb to bankruptcy and tutelage two decades later.
Official terror was not far behind, as this large ``prison of
nations'' was buffeted by the new claims of nationalism and the
upheaval of World War I. The terrible calamities and mass slaughter
let loose on the Armenian community were the last, defining act of
the Ottoman state, an indelible stain on its record and on the
record of the Young Turk regime that tried to rescue the empire
only to make it more brutal and intolerant than the old order. Then
the Turks themselves grew weary of the imperial world and pushed it
into its grave. Goodwin has not quite come to praise the dead. He
has, though, stripped that Ottoman past of its ``otherness,'' the
alienness that has been its lot in this age of unyielding
nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Fouad Ajami, the Majid Khadduri Professor of Middle East Studies
at the School of Advanced International Studies at Johns Hopkins
University, is the author of ``The Dream Palace of the Arabs.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
