<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8364 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-MAJORS-NYTSF     04-29 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-MAJORS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE MAJORS
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Pursuit of Golf's Holy Grail.
</P>
<P>
   By John Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   Little, Brown &AMP; Company. $25.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; NO TIME FOR THE YIPS
</P>
<P>
   BY DAVE ANDERSON
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In golf, the stature of the world's best players is based on
each year's four major tournaments: the Masters, the United States
Open, the British Open and the Professional Golfers' Association
Championship. No matter how many other tournaments or how much
prize money a golfer wins, he is considered flawed if he hasn't won
at least one major title, just as the superior players are measured
by how many majors they have won.
</P>
<P>
   If Jack Nicklaus deserves to be ranked as the best golfer in
history, it's because he has won a record 18 majors as a touring
pro: six Masters, four U.S. Opens, three British Opens, five P.G.A.
Championships. Nicklaus also won two United States Amateur titles,
which some historians still consider, along with the British
Amateur, to be a major out of deference to Bobby Jones's 1930 Grand
Slam. That year Jones, although an amateur, defeated the best pros
in the two Opens and also won both the United States Amateur and
the British Amateur. Over his career, he won four U.S. Opens, three
British Opens, five United States Amateurs and one British Amateur.
</P>
<P>
   Counting their United States and British Amateur titles,
Nicklaus has 20 majors, Jones 13. Next is Walter Hagen with 11,
followed by Ben Hogan and Gary Player, each with nine; Arnold
Palmer and Tom Watson with eight; Gene Sarazen, Sam Snead and Harry
Vardon, each with seven; Lee Trevino and Nick Faldo, each with six.
</P>
<P>
   If you were to rank history's 12 best golfers, you wouldn't go
very far wrong if you were limited to considering only those 12.
Although a surprise winner occurs occasionally in a major, the best
players often win the best titles on the best courses. And the
difficulty of winning any of the four is the driving premise of
John Feinstein's book ``The Majors.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1987, when Feinstein's ``Season on the Brink'' illuminated
the best and worst of Bobby Knight, the Indiana University
basketball coach, he has produced several sports books, the best of
which was ``A Good Walk Spoiled,'' an examination of the golfers on
the professional tour. Now he has returned to golf to concentrate
on 1998's four major championships through some of the game's most
prominent names, notably Mark O'Meara, Tiger Woods and David Duval.
</P>
<P>
   Watson, a five-time British Open champion and two-time Masters
winner, defines the majors, saying: ``It's almost like taking a
final exam. . . . This decides your grade.'' Last year O'Meara
finally made the grade, winning his first major at the Masters at
the age of 41 and also winning the British Open. Lee Janzen won the
U.S. Open, and Vijay Singh won the P.G.A.
</P>
<P>
   Most golf followers remember the results, so there's no suspense
as to the outcome of each of last year's majors. But Feinstein, a
relentless reporter, supplies the individual dramas involving the
winners: O'Meara's determination finally to win a major and then to
win another in a four-hole playoff; Janzen's golf ball that
appeared lost in a tree before it dropped out; Singh's advice
during the final round from his experienced caddie, Dave Renwick.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein develops the odd-couple relationship between O'Meara,
now 42, and Woods, now 23, who are neighbors in their
million-dollar homes near Orlando, Fla. They play friendly matches
there, and they sometimes travel together. And when O'Meara won the
Masters last year, Woods, as the previous champion, held the green
jacket that O'Meara put on.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara's two birdies that snatched the Masters from Duval also
provide Feinstein with a recurring theme that he abbreviates into
``B.P.N.T.H.W.A.M.'' -- best player never to have won a major. It's
a theme that haunted O'Meara and Singh until last year. As this
year's Masters came and went, it still hung over Duval and Phil
Mickelson, the gifted left-handed golfer.
</P>
<P>
   As is the case so often in sports, the real charm of ``The
Majors'' involves those who didn't win, sometimes those who didn't
even qualify. The most poignant story is that of the adoption of
Larry Mize, the 1987 Masters winner, by British fans at the British
Open qualifying site. They appreciated Mize's willingness to risk
not qualifying in wind and rain and having to return to America,
all at his own expense if he didn't qualify and earn prize money.
(He qualified.)
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein also chronicles the human dramas: the illnesses of
Fred Couples's father and future wife, John Daly's struggle with
alcoholism, the death of Stuart Appleby's wife in a freak
automobile accident in London, the fulfillment of the amateur Ken
Bakst's dream of playing in the Masters, the harassment of Colin
Montgomerie by U.S. Open fans, Justin Leonard's understandable
annoyance at Peter Kuchar's on-course antics while caddying for his
son Matt.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to know how touring pros think, on and off the
course but particularly on the courses that are the crucibles of
the majors, this is the book. It also tells how golf officials,
especially those at the Masters and at the United States Golf
Association, think in setting up their courses, notably the hole
location on the 18th green at the Olympic Club in San Francisco,
which created so many putting problems on the second day of the
U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   In trying to establish when the majors emerged as the majors,
Feinstein mistakenly parrots the prevalent theory that Ben Hogan,
who swept the Masters, the U.S. Open and the British Open in 1953,
didn't enter the P.G.A. that year because of ``the difficulty of
rushing back from Great Britain and then going through seven days
of match play at a time when he still hadn't completely recovered
from the 1949 automobile accident that almost killed him.'' In
recent decades the P.G.A. has been played soon after the British
Open, but in 1953 the P.G.A. was completed before the British Open.
Its 36-hole semifinal matches were scheduled for the same Monday,
July 6, that Hogan had to be in Scotland to qualify for the British
Open that began two days later at Carnoustie. Not that Hogan would
have entered the P.G.A. had he skipped the British Open; his
damaged legs couldn't endure a possible 180 holes in five days.
</P>
<P>
   But that stubbed putt hardly spoils ``The Majors,'' another
major triumph for John Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Dave Anderson, who won a Pulitzer Prize for commentary in 1981,
is a sports columnist for The Times.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
