<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-GOLFER-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 A GOLFER'S LIFE
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Arnold Palmer with James Dodson.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 420 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Ballantine Books. $26.95.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; ARNIE'S ARDOR
</P>
<P>
   BY MICHAEL BAMBERGER
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   For 10 or 15 years now, golfers have been looking for the next
Jack Nicklaus, the single person who could dominate the game for
years and even decades. For a while it looked to be Tom Watson, but
he failed to have Nicklaus's staying power. Briefly it appeared to
be Hal Sutton, but all he had in common with the Golden Bear was a
golden mane and splashy early success. More recently, golfers have
been talking about Tiger Woods and David Duval as being the next
Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   The curious thing is that nobody is trying to identify the next
Arnold Palmer. Golf buffs must know instinctively the underlying
message of Palmer's autobiography, ``A Golfer's Life'': there won't
be another Arnold Palmer. Palmer's rugged charm could be produced
only in a certain time and place, and that's where this enjoyable
book, every bit as unpretentious as its author, is rooted.
</P>
<P>
   It opens not on a golf course or in an office cluttered with
medals, but in Latrobe, Pa., at a class reunion sponsored by
Palmer, in this case the 50th-anniversary reunion of the class of
'47 from Latrobe High. Latrobe is the western Pennsylvania town
where Palmer has lived all his life, a town that was, in his youth,
both rural and industrial but definitely not suburban. (The modern
American touring pro, with rare exceptions, was raised deep in the
heart of suburbia.) Palmer's father, called Deke, was a course
superintendent, a drinker and a hard man. Palmer revered him and
spent his adult life trying to earn his father's praise. His
mother, Doris, was loving and vivacious and fun. Palmer spent his
adult life trying to bring her joy. If this sounds like a
Depression-era family out of central casting, maybe that's because
it is.
</P>
<P>
   But ``A Golfer's Life'' -- the writing, which is simple and
excellent, is by James Dodson, a contributing editor at Golf
magazine -- is not sanitized and predictable. There's a refreshing
level of candor, and it yields interesting and unexpected stories
about Palmer's mistakes, disappointments and personal failings. He
describes, again and again, how much he needed cigarettes on the
golf course to calm his nerves, and how he never won a major
tournament after quitting. He writes about his father's drinking
and how upsetting that was to him (``It troubled me that the man
who rode me so hard about knowing the difference between right and
wrong often did something -- after too many shots at the firehall
-- he knew was wrong''). He writes about some of his bad
investments and some of his poorly considered business partners,
describing in detail his litigious involvement with a residential
development near Orlando, Fla., called Isleworth. (The project has
thrived since Palmer left the deal. Tiger Woods lives at Isleworth
today.) Palmer writes, movingly and sadly, about the death of a
great friend and fellow golfer, Bud Worsham, during their college
days at Wake Forest.
</P>
<P>
   The book details several disappointments on the golf course,
too. The best known and oddest of these came in 1966 at the United
States Open, at the Olympic Club in San Francisco. With nine holes
to play, Palmer had a seven-shot lead over Billy Casper. With four
holes to play, Palmer still had a five-shot lead. In the end,
Casper defeated Palmer in a playoff, the third U.S. Open playoff
loss for Palmer. He discusses what went wrong. At some point during
the final round, Palmer stopped thinking about Casper and started
thinking about breaking Ben Hogan's record for lowest winning U.S.
Open score. Palmer must be the only person in the world who can
really know how Greg Norman felt after squandering a six-stroke
lead before losing the 1996 Masters to Nick Faldo.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan, a golfing icon by 1955, when Palmer first arrived on the
professional scene, figures prominently in the book, but not
altogether positively. It becomes clear that Palmer respects
Hogan's skill but was deeply offended by his brusqueness. He is
more fond of some other golfers. He clearly likes Jack Nicklaus and
appreciates how much their rivalry did to enrich them personally.
(Palmer is not a great materialist, except when it comes to
airplanes. He's an accomplished pilot and has been flying himself
around the country for 40 years now, always in the latest and
fastest planes he can buy, as is all well chronicled in the book.)
Palmer describes his warm friendship with Gary Player, the great
South African golfer, winner of all four major golf championships,
something Palmer himself failed to achieve. But Palmer's favorite
golfer gets most of a chapter, the title of which is taken from the
man's initials: D.D.E. Dwight D. Eisenhower and Palmer played
dozens of rounds together, often at Augusta National, where
Eisenhower was a member and Palmer an honorary member, having won
the Masters there four times (1958, 1960, 1962 and 1964). His
father-and-son relationship with Eisenhower is another byproduct of
Palmer's golf talent and warm personality. One of the things that
make the subject of ``A Golfer's Life'' so likable is his gratitude
for what golf has brought him.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, he has been managed brilliantly by Mark McCormack,
the founder of International Management Group, who had the
foresight never to link Palmer's business deals to his on-course
successes; this extended Palmer's earning power immeasurably. But
in the most significant ways, Palmer was not managed at all. On the
course and off it he was just himself -- simple, courteous, manly
-- and that was enough to endear him to millions of people, men and
women. Palmer probably wouldn't have such an impact in professional
golf were he coming up today. For one thing, greens have become
exceedingly fast, and he describes himself as a poor fast-green
putter. But more significant, a young golfer today with Palmer's
talents would become overprogrammed -- by his parents, by his swing
coach, by his psychologist, by the golf industry. Everybody would
impose his own ideas on him. Caddies would give him too much
information. Reporters would be too interested in the minutiae of
his life. Today in golf, it's hard for an emerging star to breathe.
That was less true in Palmer's day.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Palmer has led a rich and singular life and has captured
it in a wonderful book.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bamberger is a senior writer for Sports Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
