<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8367 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CRIME-NYTSF     04-29 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CRIME-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 BY MARILYN STASIO
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The intricate plot of Robert Goddard's CAUGHT IN THE LIGHT
(Holt, $26) begins on a snowy winter morning in Vienna, where an
English photographer falls madly in love with a mystery woman who
steps in front of his camera. Their affair is recounted with
breathless romanticism (``The imminence of passion -- of heat and
flesh and broken taboos -- hung almost tangibly in the air''), and
the photographer, Ian Jarrett, plays into the mood when he deserts
his wife and daughter to run off with the woman he knows as Marian
Esguard. The story shifts into dramatic suspense when Marian
disappears and Ian discovers her ``true'' identity, as well as her
belief that she is the incarnation of the ``real'' Marian Esguard,
a pioneer photographer who vanished in 1820, along with her
revolutionary inventions.
</P>
<P>
   Words like ``truth'' and ``reality'' lose their meaning in this
dense and dazzling work, as further plot manipulations force past,
present and paranoid fantasy to share the same time frame. Although
the baroque turns can be confusing, the mystery eventually
clarifies itself for Ian when he realizes that ``the only thing
separating us from the past, or the past from us, is time,'' and
that a photograph (``a snapshot of time as well as people and
places'') is the only way to capture it. For his insight, Ian pays
a staggering cost that almost seems worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike those paragons of virility who never age (or lose their
hair or forget where they put the car keys) in long-running
detective series, K. C. Constantine's working-stiff hero, Mario
Balzic, seems as real as the rest of us -- or at least as real as
his endearingly imperfect neighbors in the battered steel town of
Rocksburg, Pa. This retired police chief wears his humanity all too
uneasily in BLOOD MUD (Mysterious Press/
</P>
<P>
   Warner, $23) when he reacts to a heart attack (a ``coronary
event,'' his whippersnapper cardiologist calls it) by withdrawing
from life. ``All I know is, I'm scared of dyin','' he confesses to
his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that draws Balzic out of the house is the private
job he promised to do for a lawyer friend, investigating an
insurance claim in a gun shop burglary. The oddball characters
mixed up in this caper are enough to get anyone's heart pumping
again, and Balzic is soon exchanging meaningful words with lowlifes
like Fat Artie Chianese, that ``two-bit Mussolini'' who runs the
local Mafia out of his deli, and his no-luck nephew (``Put him in
charge of a two-car funeral, he'd send one of 'em to the wrong
cemetery''). A master of primitive forms of tribal communication,
Constantine excels at the casual obscenity, the morose barroom
lament, the windy phone conversation and those illiterate arias,
heard all over Rocksburg, of men who have lost everything but their
anger.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of Anne Perry's strong-minded Victorian heroines should
appreciate their passionate defense of an article of masculine
ideology -- the value of a man's good name -- in BEDFORD SQUARE
(Ballantine, $24.95). Through a campaign of ``whisper, suspicion
and innuendo,'' someone is slandering men of high position in 1891
London society, and it is up to Thomas Pitt, commander of the Bow
Street police station, to scotch these poisonous rumors of
dishonorable behavior before reputations are destroyed and lives
ruined. Through his discreet investigations, the sympathetic Pitt
exposes the subtle cruelty of the anonymous letters that bring
disgrace to one man and death to another. But it is his wife,
Charlotte, and her octogenarian aunt, the indomitable Lady
Vespasia, who extend compassion to the victims and provide the
moral indignation to make a political cause of their persecution.
</P>
<P>
   Perry is generous with colorful period details about daily life
as it was lived at the end of the century, when the comfortable
classes were talking on the telephone, wearing smaller bustles and
investing in African diamond mines. She is even more remarkable at
shaping historical events -- like the Tranby Croft gambling
scandal, which blackened reputations -- into a piece of fiction
that offers both a satisfactory mystery to solve and a grave social
injustice to get all worked up about.
</P>
<P>
   With her mixed-race parentage and California upbringing, Rei
Shimura brings a fresh perspective to the Japanese culture (and
occasional crimes) she encounters in Sujata Massey's lively
mysteries. In THE FLOWER MASTER (HarperCollins, $24), the young
antiques dealer is living in Tokyo and doing her best to soak up
her Asian heritage without compromising her Western values. In
deference to her aunt, Rei enrolls in a flower-arranging class at a
venerable ikebana school where the rivalries are fierce. After ``a
Wild West showdown'' over esthetics, a master teacher is stabbed to
death with gardening shears, and Rei's aunt comes under suspicion.
Massey doesn't hesitate to ply the conventions of the genre
(there's a romance for Rei, along with an unlikely attempt on her
life and more coincidences than you could shake a cherry blossom
branch at), but they adapt gracefully to the foreign setting. And
they never upstage the local customs, which Rei observes closely
and interprets with the quick wit of a dutiful but independent
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Johansen didn't have to pile it on so thick, trying to win
sympathy for the offbeat and immensely likable hero of his debut
mystery, THE ANSWER MAN (Bantam, $23.95). Barely employed and
crushed by debt (his disabled brother's medical bills are pure
overkill), an honest Atlanta polygraph examiner named Ken Parker
pockets $50,000 for teaching a white-collar embezzler how to beat
the machine. For all his cynicism about his profession (``The
polygraph works only if you believe it does''), he figures that ``a
few tricks, some special exercises and a lot of practice could do
the job.'' Parker makes such fascinating work of these lessons that
the punishment he has to take for his criminal indiscretion seems a
bit excessive. But the characters on his case are too well drawn to
behave predictably, and Parker is so interesting he can survive all
the sadistic turns of the hard-boiled plot.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
