</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8368 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-KINGS-NYTSF     04-29 1570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-KINGS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE BOOK OF KINGS
<TEXT>
<P>
   By James Thackara.
</P>
<P>
   773 pp. Woodstock, N.Y.:
</P>
<P>
   Overlook Press. $28.95.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; STRAIGHT TO MINI-SERIES
</P>
<P>
   BY RICHARD EDER
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Why should only the lit-crit people be entitled to transgress
Thoreau's injunction (I adapt): Mistrust all writing that requires
new words. Why should they have all the fun (lots less fun for the
reader)? Exclusive to the present purpose, then: ``Greatwriting''
-- a kind of writing ostensibly done to achieve a great book but
preponderantly done to be a great writer. As for the books,
intention generally swamps result. Literary triumphs are commonly
built along the line of Napoleon's battle advice: ``On s'engage et
puis on voit'' (``Jump in and then figure'').
</P>
<P>
   James Thackara's midcentury moral and historical melodrama,
``The Book of Kings,'' amounts to an advanced case of Greatwriting,
with swaths of very good writing and quite a bit that is dreadful.
It is the product of 20 years' labor, agonizingly reported last
December in a New Yorker article that records the travails of the
author and his serially exhausted editors and agents. In the manner
of Scott failing to win the South Pole race, the travails seem to
account for much of the buzz.
</P>
<P>
   Thackara has constructed an all-inclusive panorama of World War
II in Europe and the decade that led up to it. He uses four
outsized characters: two Germans, one French-Algerian and one
American. The American is scanted; conceivably this is one of the
reasons that the 1,100 manuscript pages of December have shrunk now
to 773.
</P>
<P>
   Among them, the four keep an exhausting number of the
appointments required by historical fiction. Such appointments,
with their obligatory stops and starts, tend to give the genre a
relation to fiction, plain, that military music has to music,
plain. There is nothing plain about ``Kings,'' and though some of
its most brilliant passages describe battles, it would be
constrictive to label it military. Unless one is thinking of an
army of the Lord.
</P>
<P>
   Thackara, an American living in London, intends an epic
incorporating spiritual and historical lessons into the grand sweep
of its multiple stories. The parallel with ``War and Peace'' is
inescapable (Thackara, too, writes 50 years after the events) and
awkward. Tolstoy's lesson was war's reality versus its illusion, in
history and in particular human lives. Thackara's is an apocalyptic
question posed near the end of the book, when Nazism is about to
crumble: ``When at last the crippled lion lay dead, would Europe
still be there . . . or was that lion Europe?''
</P>
<P>
   Grandiloquent and taken out of context; unfortunately the
context is equally grandiloquent. Tolstoy gets to the lofty
questions by means of his unfailingly human details; Thackara's
lofty and far less original questions manipulate the details. It is
not so much that his main characters are larger than life as that
life is so often eclipsed in the effort to get them to display
largeness. Think of the figures scrabbling under the inflatable
effigies at the Macy's Parade.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the 1930's, four young men share an
apartment on the Rue de Fleurus in Paris. Except for one pair,
there is no particular reason for the sharing other than grand
design: From a fixed center the ``Fleurusians'' will radiate to
four compass points of history. It is one of the author's
innumerable instances of assigning his characters rather than
letting them assign themselves. Essence bops freely about in
``Kings'' and existence manages on what it can. It is the property
of fable more than fiction. Albert Camus -- one Fleurusian is
closely based on him -- made his fable-novels (``The Stranger,''
``The Fall'') short. A 700-page fable is a 10-pound hummingbird.
</P>
<P>
   The four, all huge (Thackara deals in large denominations; the
reader hungers for exact change):
</P>
<P>
   David Von Sunda, a Prussian aristocrat from a family tracing its
lineage back to Arminius -- the Von Sundas own his belt buckle --
zigzags between patriotic honor and decent conscience. He flees to
Mexico to evade Nazi recruitment, returns via the trans-Siberian
express (where his wife gives birth assisted by an anti-Stalinist
Soviet doctor who is a close friend of Marshal Zhukov) and serves
under the tank genius Heinz Guderian on the soon-to-open Russian
front. Failing to recruit his commander for an anti-Hitler plot,
David deserts, is sent to a concentration camp, escapes and then,
dialectic drama collapsing into postwar aimlessness, finds nothing
better to do than amass a fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Johannes Godard, a German philosophy student, achieves unworldly
eminence (he is ``a famous young philosopher'' and nephew of ``one
of Europe's most renowned thinkers'') by parsing Hegel and ignoring
what is around him. Then, like Faust, he is tempted carnally and
spiritually: enslaved by a Cruella- like Nazi opera singer and
hired by Goebbels for intellectual polish. Johannes is sucked
hellishly down and dies -- a switch from Faust to Faust's inventor
-- calling for more light.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Lothaire (the Camus character) is the son of an
impoverished pied- noir mother and a vanished Algerian father. A
Sorbonne scholarship plucks him out of Algiers and places him under
the mentorship of Marcel Dore (``France's one living master'').
Justin founds a brilliantly combative journal, writes a thunderous
book, fights in the Resistance and wins the ``Hague'' (i.e., Nobel)
Prize. He's Godard's opposite, the intellectual engaged and
uncompromised, deploring his Parisian glory and cherishing his
links to Algeria and its freedom fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan Penn, the fourth room-mate, does very little in these
curtailed pages other than inherit a great American arms fortune
and get mashed by a German tank during the Ardennes breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   There are women, as well, and Thackara works to raise them to
the mythical heights of his Fleurusians. Helne, Justin's lifelong
love but David's wife, is fitted out to be a steadily evolving
moral force. Luz (``Europe's most famous actress''), destined for
David and married to Justin, is conceived as a rainbow of feminine
fire and weakness. Though they're treated at length, only
occasionally is either more than a blur of words swathed in yards
of fictional gauze.
</P>
<P>
   The literary qualities that Thackara seems to set most store by
-- large visions and the life of the emotions -- are just those
that he handles least well, and that attract his most confused and
ill-tuned prose. By contrast, what he manages best is what his male
characters do, and what they say while they're doing it.
</P>
<P>
   There are at least a dozen extended set scenes in ``Kings,'' all
elaborately worked and burnished. Some of the burnishing goes to
episodes that misfire or droop in their suggestion of other authors
who have done them better: an Algerian fisherman's fight with a
giant tuna (Hemingway), the concentration camp (Primo Levi, Art
Spiegelman and a dozen others), Justin's childhood (the anguished
radiance of Camus's Algerian memoirs).
</P>
<P>
   Other episodes show brilliantly. There is the simple poetry of a
schooner unfurling sail and setting out; and the force of young
energy joined to young ignorance when David discovers a wrecked
plane on the family estate and spends the summer rebuilding and
then flying it. There is his brutal trek through the Russian winter
after he deserts. There is the painfully hyperreal, absolutely
authentic scene in which Justin, then unknown, tries to get his
manuscript past the receptionist of a Paris publisher.
</P>
<P>
   There are two brilliantly contrasted episodes: General Guderian
launching his panzer attack across the French border and the French
Army falling back in disarray. History has pondered this event as
thoroughly as Napoleon's advance and retreat in Russia. Here
though, in his mastery and marshaling of detail and dynamics,
Thackara makes his closest approach to the surging wave -- though
not the reflective undertow -- of Tolstoy's war chapters. More
quietly, but perhaps with greater artistry, there is Justin and his
fellow Resistance fighters blowing up a train. Thackara sets it
from the point of view of an angler fishing in a nearby pond: a
haiku that captures a landslide.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Kings,'' it is mostly a landslide -- woolly thoughts,
shards of history and junky sentences -- that submerges haiku,
historical reflection, moral passion, struggling characters and
quite a bit of assorted good writing. It has been suggested that
Thackara, like Thomas Wolfe, simply needed a Maxwell Perkins to
bring a novel out of cartons of manuscript. It is not fair to
assume that there is no Perkins at Overlook Press just because
cartons have been turned into fewer cartons. What I don't believe
even a Perkins would find in Thackara is a central Wolfean passion
to bring a vision to light. It seems more a case of a protracted
struggle to assemble a vision as a way of moving into the light.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Richard Eder writes articles and book reviews for The Times.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
