<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8389 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-29 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S AT FAULT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the sad search for answers to explain the
Columbine High School massacre, we are already focusing on a
particular villain _ the dubious mental and moral values of our
national culture.
</P>
<P>
   Aha, but which culture? Whose?
</P>
<P>
   The politicians are free to pick competing scapegoats here.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton made an eloquent plea at a White House
gathering Tuesday for a change in the hunting and sport-shooting
culture, which he thinks has ``gotten confused about its
objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said the National Rifle Association has persuaded
people that ``every reasonable restriction is just the camel's nose
in the tent and pretty soon they'll come after my shotgun and I'll
miss the next duck hunting season.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that ``cultures are hard to change'' but added,
``It's not just a culture of violence that has to change; it's the
culture of hunting and sport shooting that has to stop financing
efforts to frighten their members ...''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott and House Speaker Dennis
Hastert had a very different take on the problem. They called for a
national conference on youth and culture that would examine ``video
games, drugs in school, Hollywood, prayer in schools, parental
involvement and local control of schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Obvious elements of the religious right's familiar political
agenda appear on that list although it is hard to see what local
control of the schools has to do with anything. And Lott and
Hastert conspicuously did not mention the ridiculously easy access
youngsters have to guns. Guns? What guns?
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I., however, agreed with the president.
``It isn't our American culture that is wrong,'' he said. ``What's
wrong is our nation's love affair with guns ... This is about the
distorted interpretation of the Constitution that convinces
otherwise rational citizens it is their inalienable right to be
armed to the teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., and John McCain, R-Ariz., came
at it from yet another angle. They proposed a White House summit to
pressure media executives to cut back violent depictions of what
Lieberman called ``the culture of carnage.'' The summit, they
insisted, would be long on gentle persuasion and short on
censorship threats. Mostly, however, it sounds like public
relations grandstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, this is shaping up as a political free-for-all.
</P>
<P>
   Too many guns. Not enough religion. Parental indifference. Lax
school standards. Immoral movie makers. Unrestricted television.
Missing family values. This is what we can expect to hear
repeatedly during next year's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But will anything actually change in our society, let alone
improve? We don't go for revolutions, as former House Speaker Newt
Gingrich discovered. But we can, and do, evolve.
</P>
<P>
   It is unrealistic to expect some new legislative surge for
religious conservatism. It is silly to argue that mandatory praying
every day in school would have prevented the murderous impulses of
the two crazed student killers in Littleton, Colo. And we are weary
of those exaggerated efforts to link abortion to every sign of bad
conduct in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is demanding punishment for parents who cannot control their
children likely to get very far. Such demands are too prone to
unfair family second-guessing and too difficult to enforce.
</P>
<P>
   Passing gun control legislation would be an obvious and logical
step. But Lott has given the NRA two weeks to gear up opposition
before President proposed restrictions will be debated in the
Senate. The emotional reaction now fueling calls for gun control
may well have expired by then.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's proposals would mandate background checks on people
who make purchases at gun shows, raise the legal age for handgun
possession from 18 to 21 years, ban the import of high-capacity
ammunition clips, require child safety locks and limit sales of
guns to one per person per month. All of this seems like common
sense.
</P>
<P>
   But the president conceded it might mean ``a hassle'' for some
people. He compared the inconvenience with that of airline metal
detector security checks. They are a nuisance but can also prevent
terrorist attacks. ``It's worth it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Judiciary Committee chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah,
however, reflected the view of many Republicans when he scoffed,
``We got this pious statement (from Clinton) ... that it's all the
fault of the parents and it's all the fault of people who
manufacture guns. Look, there's plenty of fault to go around
here.'' With too many targets, nothing may happen.
</P>
<P>
   It is a shame that Clinton's unscripted performance discussing
the Colorado killings got little public attention. It was brilliant
_ the president at his most persuasive.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is a measure of how badly the Monica Lewinsky business
has undercut his authority that in some news accounts a remark by
First Lady Hillary Clinton got prominent play. She said during her
brief talk on the cultural causes of gun violence that ``part of
growing up is learning how to control one's impulses.''
</P>
<P>
   If you are of the school that Clinton still behaves like a
juvenile, you couldn't resist a hoot at that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
