<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8371 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-BREATH-NYTSF     04-29 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-BREATH-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 BREATH AND SHADOWS
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Ella Leffland.
</P>
<P>
   311 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   William Morrow &AMP; Company. $24.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; MORE MELANCHOLY DANES
</P>
<P>
   By Brooks Hansen
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Near the beginning of Ella Leffland's new novel, ``Breath and
Shadows,'' Grethe Rosted is listening to her husband, Holger, read
a poem about spring when her mind wanders: ``How many hairs are
lost in a lifetime, falling to shoulder or lap and brushed to the
floor -- perhaps thousands, yet they are nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The question of what we lose in a lifetime, and what traces we
leave behind, lies at the heart of this exquisite and moving family
saga. Spanning two centuries, ``Breath and Shadows'' tells the
stories of three generations of a moneyed Danish clan, the Rosteds,
focusing in particular on three vividly drawn characters: Thorkild,
an ill-tempered dwarf ``of extraordinary dimensions in every
direction except upward,'' who is mourning the death of his son,
killed fighting for Napoleon in Germany; Grethe, Thorkild's
great-granddaughter, who some 70 years later is living in a grand
house on the Danish coast with a devoted husband and two healthy
sons; and finally Paula, Grethe's granddaughter, a native of
Illinois who in the 1970's has forsaken marriage, wealth and a
nagging daughter to lead a life of near seclusion in the Swiss
Jura, sculpturing in sandstone.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs are not the only points of view. By chapter, Leffland
leaps from generation to generation; by paragraph she hops from eye
to eye. We see from the perspective of Thorkild's pitiless sister,
Bodil; Paula's brother, Philip; and Grethe's infuriatingly spiteful
and envious maid. We even occasionally enter the mind of Olaf, a
battle-scarred cat who slips in and out of the Rosteds' kitchen
window every night and who shares a strange intimacy with Grethe,
``the biggest moving, breathing thing he had ever let near him.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Olaf, Leffland goes where she likes, licensed by indelible
characterization and descriptions that are both crisp and sensual.
Grethe's morning bed is a ``wildly tumbled map of ardor.'' Later,
lying on a carpet of moss with Olaf, she looks up into the ``high
green trees, lit in a thousand places by small sunbursts.''
Leffland does more than paint with words; she is a guide as well,
leading us at carefully paced interludes from one setting to the
next, prompting the questions: What has changed between here and
there? What has been brushed aside, and what remains?
</P>
<P>
   Her pace is more deliberate at the outset. Nearly half the book
is spent steeping us in the lives and histories of her three main
characters. Thorkild's existence is a ludicrous bustle of
endurance, ``waddling and wheezing and spluttering'' against the
lashing northern winds. He has known companionship only briefly --
his wife died in childbirth -- and requited love only once, from
his son, who is gone. The surviving world is to him the final
insult heaped on a life of scorn, discomfort and gawking stares.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Grethe's world appears as a kind of idyll. She and
her husband (who is also her cousin) are deeply, physically in
love, and well enough provided for that they can pursue their
creative impulses without a care. Grethe translates Zola; Holger is
a painter. They take the children bathing in the sea daily; at
night they hold bohemian soirees. But the sweeter their life seems,
the more chilling are the surreal fissures of terror that begin to
trouble Grethe's mind, images of blood gushing though the soil and
surrounding her in a dark red marshland; of the moon crumbling and
all beings everywhere vanishing ``like shot arrows from the face of
the earth.'' There is one figment in particular that has been
haunting her, an anguished cry that only she can hear, coming from
the framed silhouette that hangs on the drawing room wall. It is of
her grandfather, who died long ago fighting for Napoleon.
</P>
<P>
   Of Leffland's three principal characters, Paula is the farthest
removed from the world, and for that reason the least compelling.
Hers is a life of chosen solitude. Her days consist of soup and
bread, hiking in the hills, chiseling at her workbench and
otherwise fending off her grown-up daughter's attempts to make her
come home. (``Why do I have to write a letter that will take days
to get there, why can't you get a phone?'') Paula is not tempted,
and yet her work with the sandstone, which may sound the novel's
one blatant note, indicates a yearning for an ``innermost grain''
she cannot find.
</P>
<P>
   It is her brother Philip, surprisingly, who points the way. He
is a successful businessman in Chicago. He travels where and when
he likes, often in the company of an obligingly ``athletic'' young
woman from his office, but he is not happy. A brief visit to his
sister's grimy mountain garret makes plain a midlife crisis: he has
failed his adolescent ideals. At length he prevails on Paula to go
to Denmark with him to learn more about their natural father, whom
they never knew but who is familiar to us as Grethe's younger son.
</P>
<P>
   Thorkild, meanwhile, has undertaken a search of his own. Unable
to assuage his grief, he sets off for the battlefield near Leipzig
where his son was killed, clutching the boy's last letter the whole
way. Despite careful preparation, the journey does not go as
planned. He soon finds himself lost on the German back roads, and
endures a treatment it would be wrong to disclose, but which
represents one of the novel's most inspired, sad and comical peaks,
and which more than justifies his subsequent descent from rage into
madness.
</P>
<P>
   Grethe also has begun to lose her battle with the voices in her
head, and suffers a nervous breakdown, recounted with startling
lucidity. It is only to Olaf the cat, whom Grethe imagines visiting
the genteel sanitarium where she has been admitted, that she
confides the true nature of her despair, that she has failed to
``bring God's Kingdom to earth,'' and that if one ``cannot end all
suffering, then one must at least end one's own begetting.''
</P>
<P>
   As tragic as Grethe's story is, and Thorkild's as well, ``Breath
and Shadows'' attains a surprisingly peaceful quality in the end.
By braiding the stories as she has, Leffland gives the reader a
perspective her characters lack, to observe the strains that
survive the generations, and bind them: Money, madness, aimless
compassion. Not all are so obviously inherited -- there is the
golden color of the sun to which the Rosteds' pagan forebears once
prayed, which reappears in a simple bowl that catches Thorkild's
eye, which becomes a thimble on Grethe's thumb, is woven into the
leaves and roses of a small rug for her boys, which eventually
finds its way to the floor of Grethe's studio, to be covered in
sandstone dust, washed and covered again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Breath and Shadows'' is laced with such threads, twisting in
and out for our attention, and though none yields a fixed meaning,
together they seem to answer the concerns of the novel's three
solitary protagonists. Their lives may be but breath and shadows,
but not all their traces are lost.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Brooks Hansen's novel, ``Perlman's Ordeal,'' is due out in
August.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
