<HEADER>
A8372 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-GIRLFRIEND-NY     04-29 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-GIRLFRIEND-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 GIRLFRIEND
<TEXT>
<P>
   Men, Women, and Drag.
</P>
<P>
   By Holly Brubach.
</P>
<P>
   178 pp. New York: Random House. $39.95.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; TOOTSIES
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Kimmel
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   A colleague recently returned home to find his 10-year-old
daughter and 6-year-old son playing dress-up in front of their
mother's closet. ``It's all right, Dad,'' his son reassured him.
``I'm not a cross-dresser.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly drag is chic; masculinity and femininity are no longer
fixed by anatomy. They have become fashion accessories, which is
one reason to welcome Holly Brubach's ``Girlfriend.'' A former
style editor of The New York Times Magazine, Brubach is well
positioned to explore a world where, she says, ``art, performance
and fashion converge.'' Unlike academic theorists, for whom the
only Jean-Paul is Sartre, not Gaultier, Brubach revels in the
playful passion for glamour and style shared by female
impersonators.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by the photographer Michael James O'Brien, Brubach
takes the grand tour of the drag world, and from Rio de Janeiro and
Bangkok to Berlin and Paris she describes her growing love affair
with drag queens. O'Brien's soft-focus and occasionally slightly
blurry images conceal facial and bodily flaws; the men seem shy,
vulnerable, curious about the camera even as they flaunt themselves
before it. The result strives to be an affectionate coffee-table
book. But, as with drag itself, the content is more serious than
the form.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its overt playfulness, drag elicits strong, visceral
responses. And despite her breezy journalistic style, Brubach
deftly negotiates a middle path between two politicized poles. To
some feminists, drag is a kind of blackface of sexual roles, in
which the powerful (men) appropriate the idiom of the powerless
(women) in order to express a range of otherwise unacceptable
emotions. Why do drag queens exaggerate the most traditionally
feminine traits? Some forms of feminism may have repudiated
traditional femininity; drag seems to worship it.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, drag queens just as surely offer a
protofeminist critique of masculinity. To be a man means living in
an emotional straitjacket so tight that the only way to express
oneself, to let in a little glamour, may be to do it as a woman.
Remember Dustin Hoffman's admission in ``Tootsie'' that he just
needs to learn to do it without the dress? Is putting on a wig the
only way a man can let his hair down?
</P>
<P>
   All the female impersonators Brubach interviewed are homosexuals
who understand that traditional masculinity repudiates all things
feminine. Perhaps drag's power comes from the simultaneous
appropriation of the feminine and abdication of the masculine by
those who are, at least biologically, entitled to its privilege. In
one wonderfully rendered vignette, Brubach tags along as the drag
queens of Fire Island's Cherry Grove invade the hypermasculine but
equally gay muscle beach of the Pines. That moment reveals how both
femininity and masculinity can be caricatures.
</P>
<P>
   This theme is amplified in the book's most surprising chapter,
in which Brubach enrolls in a workshop for ``drag kings'' and
learns to dress and act like a man. The parallel, she finds, is
inexact. Femininity already is a form of drag, ``predicated on
artifice,'' able to be acquired by any and all. Brubach fondly
recalls Gloria Steinem's appreciation of drag: ``Women have been
female impersonators for some time.'' A man in drag ``may in fact
uphold the ideology of femininity,'' Brubach argues, but a woman in
drag will ``undermine the ideology of masculinity.''
</P>
<P>
   Brubach plays this tension for all it's worth, and it's worth
quite a bit. But she explores only this one, albeit fascinating,
group of men who dress like women. Absent are the frat party female
impersonators, heterosexual cross-dressers and transgendered people
who seek to make their appearance consistent with their
self-perception. This narrowed focus flattens the text. Brubach
maps diversity only by traveling to different countries, and plays
down the similarities she finds -- the world over, drag queens
imitate the same 1950's Hollywood movie stars, sashay to the same
disco songs and share the same secrets for tucking tummies and
removing unsightly body and facial hair.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Brubach seems to learn more from her own efforts at
crossing sexual boundaries than from all her drag queens put
together. Though she disavows feminist orthodoxies, her conclusion
restates one of feminism's core insights: ``Masculinity, no less
than femininity, is an undertaking, and those who are unsuccessful
in their efforts -- all the failed men -- are branded women.'' Or,
as the rock singer Patti Smith once put it, ``Being any gender is a
drag.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kimmel is a professor of sociology at the State
University of New York, Stony Brook, and the author of ``Manhood in
America: A Cultural History.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
