<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8374 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-HIDDEN-NYTSF     04-29 1972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-HIDDEN-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE HIDDEN WORDSWORTH
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poet, Lover, Rebel, Spy.
</P>
<P>
   By Kenneth R. Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   W. W. Norton &AMP; Company. $45.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; STRANGE FITS OF PASSION
</P>
<P>
   BY HERMIONE LEE
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Erotic, passionate, young, adventurous, turned on by city life,
politically active, a man of mystery -- wait, isn't this Byron? No,
this is the ``hidden'' younger Wordsworth, exhaustively decoded by
his dedicated biographer-sleuth-critic Kenneth R. Johnston. This is
a Wordsworth we have never quite seen before -- difficult,
conflicted, struggling to create the triumph of the writing self
out of the failures and confusions of the first half of his life.
It is a problematic Wordsworth for the 21st century, and a far cry
from the serene, nature-loving, celebratory -- and boring? -- sage
of Grasmere.
</P>
<P>
   I came to ``The Hidden Words worth'' prejudiced against its
subject, fresh from the second volume of Richard Holmes's biography
of Coleridge, in which Wordsworth appears as mean, cold and smug,
an ungenerous, pompous critic of his once dear friend. Faced with
more than 900 pages that only got him up to the age of 36 and the
publication in 1807 of his ``Poems in Two Volumes,'' I felt I would
need a great deal of convincing.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly this didn't strike me as a book for the general
reader, in spite of its strategic scatterings of cuddly relevant
phrases (Wordsworth's poem ``An Evening Walk'' is like an ``amateur
video,'' his walk through France toward the Alps is ``on-road
conditioning,'' the reassuring end of a fragment written at
Chepstow Castle is the equivalent of ``Don't worry, be happy'').
But Johnston's staggering industriousness did draw me in, though he
did not make me like Wordsworth any more than before: his egotism,
irritability, dislike of criticism and shortcomings in friendship
are not evaded.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston, chairman of the English department at Indiana
University, takes the Holmesian model of following in his subject's
footsteps as far as it can go. When you see him casting about at
the top of the Simplon Pass to work out exactly where and when
Wordsworth had lunch and lost his way on Aug. 17, 1790 (``a matter
of some critical importance'') or crossing military territory on
Salisbury Plain and finding a tank turret heart-stoppingly swiveled
toward him or trying, ``with great difficulty,'' to follow
Wordsworth's precise route to Tintern Abbey on what is now a busy
roadway, you have to be thankful for his sake that Wordsworth did
not fall off a mountain or drown in a lake.
</P>
<P>
   His perseverance is matched by his audaciousness. What
Wordsworth needs, he says, is not more facts but more speculation.
His ``rule of thumb'' has been ``when there's a choice of
possibilities, investigate the riskier one.'' (Compare an admirable
predecessor, Stephen Gill, who often argues in his 1989 biography
``William Wordsworth: A Life,'' ``Caution seems best when we know
so little.'') But Johnson's risk-taking is never careless; it is
the fruit of long-term concentration, answering to what Coleridge,
Wordsworth's best commentator, said of ``Descriptive Sketches'':
``It demanded a greater closeness of attention than poetry (at all
events, than descriptive poetry) has a right to claim.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston never lets us see Wordsworth in splendid isolation but
always in the thick of his times. So the childhood is shaped not
only by the early deaths of his parents but by the ``violations of
honor'' involved in his father's job as the agent who looked after
the Cumberland estate of the much-loathed Sir James Lowther. All
through the book, we are made keenly aware of Wordsworth's uneasy
financial situation, the pressure on him from disapproving
relatives to get a conventional job and his paradoxical need of
security and early resistance to it.
</P>
<P>
   His school days at Hawkshead are set in a working landscape of
slate quarrying and timbering, peopled by ``miners, loggers,
charcoal burners, saddlers, joiners, peddlers,'' discharged
veterans, vagrants and social outcasts -- the people who became the
subjects of Wordsworth's great poems of suffering humanity. Here
and in his accounts of the West Country and of Wordsworth's return
to Grasmere in 1799, Johnston admirably upends any idealizing
sentimental version of picturesque rural England.
</P>
<P>
   Wordsworth's much-debated failure to excel -- or to publish any
prize poems -- at Cambridge is embedded in all you could ever want
to know about the late 18th-century examination system there,
explaining why he rejected ``not the exams per se, but the
personally humiliating subservience to a course of social
advancement of which they were the prime instruments.'' He was not
going to become, as his relatives would have liked, a learned
parson.
</P>
<P>
   The great adventure of his youth, his love affair in France in
1792 with Annette Vallon, who bore his child, and his deep, brief
friendship with the revolutionary hero Michel Beaupuy -- the two
experiences that radicalized him in ``love and politics
simultaneously'' -- are vividly connected to the historical drama
of the French Revolution. And the account of his life in London in
the early 1790's, moving into the circle of radical intellectual
publishers and polemicists like William Godwin and Thomas Holcroft,
shows him as a fascinated and involved observer of London life,
actively engaged in political debate and a contributor to the
radical weekly The Philanthropist, in which Johnston finds many
parallels between essays on ``the wages of the poor'' or ``the
freedom of the press'' and Wordworth's ``known writings'' of the
time. This is a more politically active young Wordsworth than his
later cover-ups of his past have led other biographers to credit.
</P>
<P>
   The contradictions and obscurities in his youthful politics are
startlingly underlined by Johnston's later contention that in the
years of his political retrenchment -- the years of a general
disillusionment with republicanism for many former radicals,
following the Terror, the war with France, the rise of Napoleon and
the clampdown in England on ``treasonable'' speech aWordsworth
could have been recruited as a spy. On his travels to Germany in
1798 he may have been involved in the Foreign Office's clandestine
efforts to control the plots of ``desperate Royalists'' to
overthrow the French Government. This theory is based on a newly
discovered entry in the account book of the Duke of Portland, the
Home Secretary, in charge of domestic security and espionage, of a
payment of nearly
</P>
<P>
   100 to a ``Mr. Wordsworth'' in 1799; on a provable link between
Wordsworth and ``powerful persons in the Foreign and the Home
Office''; on an unexplained gap of two months in the record of
Wordsworth's German tour; on evidence of Wordsworth's eagerness to
get out from under his Jacobin associations; and on Johnston's
growing belief that for the freedom and empowerment of the poet, it
was permissible to draw on funds from the state. So, paradoxically,
we discover at once a Wordsworth more adventurous and more
compromised.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston's other audacious decoding of a ``hidden'' Wordsworth
concerns his sex life. Previous biographers have assumed, for lack
of evidence, that Wordsworth had no sexual encounters before
Annette (when he was 21) and none between leaving her pregnant in
1792 and marrying Mary Hutchinson in 1802. Johnston deduces an
altogether more erotically charged life story. The amount of
promiscuity in Cambridge, and ``a careful reading of scattered
evidence in 'The Prelude,' ``suggest that as a student Wordsworth
at least knew about ``dissolute'' women. There may have been a
``sexual initiation'' at Lake District dances in his first
vacation. And a night on Lake Como on his tour of 1790,
inexplicably spent apart from his traveling companion, may have
involved an encounter of some kind with a ``dark-eyed maid.''
Johnston's reading of the relationship with Annette as one of
``deep passion'' makes him believe that Wordsworth made a rash,
secret journey to France in search of her in September 1793, at the
height of the Terror. (Johnston loves to build a ``wild surmise''
on lack of evidence.) In the years after Wordsworth's abandonment
</P>
<P>
   of (or unwilling separation from?) Annette, his intimate
relationship with Dorothy is seen as hovering on the edge of incest
(initiated by her, resisted by him) mediated through a third
person: ``To the degree that they could -- or could not -- love
each other directly, they did so through their shared passion for
Coleridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Johnston is often scathing about oversimplistic
psychobiography, his treatment of Wordsworth and Dorothy does come
close to it, as when, remarking on their curious habit of lying
down next to each other outdoors, pretending to be in their graves,
he explains it as ``a form of therapy for subduing their strong
erotic attraction to each other.'' But most of his arguments come
from avid deconstructions of the poetry. Wordsworth, he argues, was
a poet who may have refashioned his past but drew very literally --
more than we realize'' -- on his own experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston looks very closely for his clues. So, making the case
for a sexual encounter at a Lake District dance, he notes that (in
the 1805 ``Prelude'') Wordsworth uses the word ``glossy'' for the
``badge of manliness and freedom'' he got from the dances and
sports of his youth. This word, ``suggestive of fresh, glowing,
postcoital skin,'' ``could certainly suggest sexual initiation,''
since he also uses the word ``gloss'' about actresses in London
playhouses -- and his description of the sunrise after the dance
echoes Milton's sensual account of Adam's first sight of Eve.
(Whenever Wordsworth echoes Milton, Johnston finds an erotic
reference.) Or the unprinted revisions to his accounts of dancing
girls in ``Descriptive Sketches'' (``dewy lips,'' ``soft amorous
wishes'') suggest a narrator filled with ``pulsating voyeuristic
lust'' and ``glowering desire so strong that it hurts,'' which
confirms the supposition about the lost night on Lake Como.
Sometimes these interpretations look like overinterpretations.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a great pity, though, if the book's sensational
claims to new readings of Wordsworth's secret life were to
overshadow its most thoughtful and impressive aspect. This is its
account of a young man's self-transformation into a poet. Johnston
calls Wordsworth's poetic career a ``triumph of failure.'' It is
littered with collaborations that went wrong, with lifelong
processes of uncompleted revisions, with unfinished fragments,
postponed publications, promised works never achieved. Yet these
failures, and the confusions and contradictions of Wordsworth's
young life, fed into the complex, subtle power of his great works.
The readings here of ``Tintern Abbey,'' ``Lyrical Ballads,'' ``The
Prelude,'' the sonnets and many lesser known works show
Wordsworth's search to understand the ``moral responsibility'' of
the poet, his lifelong argument between history and the individual
consciousness, political reformism and the celebration of nature,
and, crucially, his struggle between the poet's observation of the
``solitary anguish'' of humanity and his refusal to be merely
heartless, forlorn or egotistical. Rightly, Johnston applies
Wordsworth's lines on Burns to him: ``Deep in the general heart of
men
/
</P>
<P>
   His power survives.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Hermione Lee's most recent book is ``Virginia Woolf.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
