<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-COCKS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 WHY THE COCKS FIGHT
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dominicans, Haitians, and the Struggle for Hispaniola.
</P>
<P>
   By Michele Wucker.
</P>
<P>
   Hill &AMP; Wang. $27.50.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; HISTORY AS A COCKFIGHT
</P>
<P>
   By Patrick Mrkee
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   If magical realism can be said to have a birthplace, it is,
appropriately, the island of Hispaniola. In late 1943 the great
Cuban writer Alejo Carpentier visited Haiti and toured what had
once been the kingdom of Henri Christophe. (Christophe, a traitor
to the revolutionary hero Toussaint L'Ouverture, declared himself
King Henri I after Haitian independence in 1804.) Walking through
the remains of Christophe's brutal reign -- through ``the poetic
ruins of Sans-Souci and the massive citadel of La Ferrire,
impressively intact despite lightning bolts and earthquakes'' --
Carpentier realized what set the New World apart from the Old. With
every step, he wrote in the influential prologue to his novel of
Haiti, ``The Kingdom of This World,'' ``I found lo real
maravillo,'' the early concept for magical realism, and found that
``the Americas are far from having used up their wealth of
mythologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Barely six years earlier Carpentier might have encountered the
less magical side of reality in Hispaniola. In 1937 Gen. Rafael
Trujillo, the Dominican dictator, ordered the killing of thousands
of Haitian immigrants and laborers in the border region, along the
aptly named Massacre River. In what later was called El Corte, the
Harvest, Dominican soldiers used machetes and bayonets to slaughter
the Haitians, many of whom had lived all their lives in the
Dominican Republic. Trujillo blamed the Haitians for the massacre,
but agreed to pay restitution to the Haitian Government, an amount,
the journalist and historian Eduardo Galeano once noted, that came
to $29 for every officially recognized death.
</P>
<P>
   The 1937 massacre is a central moment in Hispaniola's history,
and is vividly recounted in Michele Wucker's ``Why the Cocks Fight:
Dominicans, Haitians, and the Struggle for Hispaniola,'' a complex
exploration of the cultural divide between Haiti and the Dominican
Republic. Wucker, a journalist who lived for years in the Dominican
Republic and reported on the 1991 coup in Haiti, weaves together
five centuries of tragic conflict with a subtle picture of the
island today.
</P>
<P>
   The history is impossibly rich, and all too often desperately
violent -- from the conquest of the Taino Indians to the colonial
skirmishes between the French and Spanish for possession of the
island; from the United States occupation of Haiti in 1915 to its
invasion of the Dominican Republic in 1965; from the island's sugar
cane fields to the streets of Washington Heights in New York City.
And throughout this panoramic history Wucker inserts lively
portraits of Haitians and Dominicans struggling in contemporary
Hispaniola and abroad: Haitian cane cutters on Dominican
plantations, displaced peasants on the outskirts of Santo Domingo
and immigrants and exiles in New York.
</P>
<P>
   A major theme is the role of racism throughout the island's
history. Haiti, whose independence was born of a slave rebellion
and inspired by Enlightenment notions of human rights, came to be
dominated by a light-skinned elite. A series of Dominican leaders,
especially Trujillo, who sympathized with Nazi race ideology and
wore face powder to lighten his skin, demonized Haitians and
dark-skinned Dominicans. As Wucker notes, Dominican strongmen like
Joaquin Balaguer resorted time and again to the scapegoating of
Haitians. Even in recent years they have used thinly disguised
coded language to accuse populist leaders in the Dominican Republic
of being Haitian.
</P>
<P>
   Migration is the other major theme of the book. Wucker describes
in sharp detail the reality of Haitian sugar cane cutters,
collectively called braceros in the Dominican Republic, working in
virtually slave-labor conditions. She interviews a cutter who has
lived on a plantation for almost his entire life, toiling 70-hour
weeks for pennies an hour. For nearly a century the Dominican
Government has literally purchased thousands of workers each year
from the Haitian Government through annual contracts. The workers
have few or no rights, and their children no legal status; they are
trapped in a sort of no man's land. At the same time, they are
subject to the vagaries of the world sugar market and United States
sugar policy. As Wucker writes, ``the braceros are caught in the
logic of a time long ago, of the days of slave merchants and
colonial plantations.''
</P>
<P>
   Migration also plays a decisive role beyond the island. The
million Haitian immigrants in Miami and New York were a major
influence in forcing a flip-flopping Clinton Administration to
restore Jean-Bertrand Aristide to power in 1994. And the one in
eight Dominicans who live in the United States, the vast majority
of them in New York City, feel nostalgia for their homeland as
their children become more identified with North American culture.
</P>
<P>
   Wucker finds in the cockfight a microcosm for the two sides of
Hispaniola: the strongman leaders, like the Duvaliers and Balaguer,
staging bloody fights in the arena, while the players on the
sidelines -- the armed forces, the bourgeoisie, the United States
-- wager on the outcome. But she moves beyond this simple metaphor
to explore the role of the traditional cockfight in both national
cultures, using as a basis for comparison Clifford Geertz's studies
of Balinese cockfights. Indeed, she even enlists St. Augustine, who
was entranced by a cockfight he happened upon, and wrote of the
deformity of a bloodied, defeated rooster that ``by that very
deformity was the more perfect beauty of the contest in evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The book's closing scene is, fittingly, during carnival on the
outskirts of the Dominican capital, Santo Domingo, where Haitian
immigrants and peasant migrants reside. In the neighborhood of
Palave, whose name derives from the French Palais Bel, or beautiful
palace, Haitians dance to the sounds of a bamboo trumpet called a
vaksin. Merengue mixed with hip-hop blasts from a car stereo, and a
Dominican youth from New York break dances.
</P>
<P>
   ``During carnival, the festival that flaunts limits and rules,''
Wucker writes, ``real conflicts disappear as Dominicans and
Haitians celebrate their differences and their common roots.'' It
is a glimpse of the future, a New World moment when magic and the
real intertwine and Hispaniola's history unfolds in a more hopeful
way.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Markee writes about Latin America for The Nation.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
