<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8376 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-DYING-NYTSF     04-29 1562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-DYING-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 A PRAYER FOR THE DYING
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Stewart O'Nan.
</P>
<P>
   195 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Henry Holt &AMP; Company. $22.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; A GOOD MAN MAD
</P>
<P>
   BY PATRICK MCGRATH
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Stewart O'Nan is a writer who likes to dig deep into the
quotidian soil where evil germinates, and who designs his
narratives so as to bring that evil to a full and ghastly
flowering. In other words, he earns his horror. He painstakingly
establishes the conditions in which ordinary individuals are tested
beyond their strength and then, trapped in webs of circumstance and
wrong thinking, turn their rage upon those they imagine to be the
authors of their misery -- or upon themselves.
</P>
<P>
   This design is most apparent in O'Nan's first novel, the solid,
measured ``Snow Angels,'' in which an inadequate and shaky man,
having embraced religion for the spiritual ballast he so
desperately needs, veers into madness after the death of his
daughter. In ``The Names of the Dead,'' O'Nan's impressive Vietnam
novel, it is the trauma of war that plants the destructive seed as
the author intercuts the vividly realized experiences of a young
medic in Vietnam with the same man's later attempts, back home in
upstate New York, to live with memories that threaten to overwhelm
him.
</P>
<P>
   The narrator of O'Nan's fifth novel, ``A Prayer for the Dying,''
is similarly haunted, this time by memories of the Civil War. His
name is Jacob Hansen, and he functions as sheriff, preacher and
undertaker in the small Wisconsin town of Friendship. Jacob is a
man who worries constantly at the terrible knowledge of his past,
of the desperate things he had to do to survive that most grisly of
conflicts. As the novel opens, he must also contend with what seem
to be the punitive gestures of an angry God: the twin evils of
plague (in the form of a diphtheria outbreak) and fire.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is this: The brush fires that threaten Friendship in
its long hot summer arouse in its residents the natural desire to
flee. Yet the quarantine imposed by Jacob to halt the spread of the
disease constrains them to stay right where they are. Jacob's
situation is an impossible one. Despite his deep religious beliefs
and his quiet grasp of the logistics of the crisis, he is not equal
to the stresses that are imposed on him.
</P>
<P>
   O'Nan has employed a surprising but ultimately successful
narrative technique for Jacob's story: it is told throughout in the
second-person singular and the present tense. Thus Jacob's
references to himself as ``you'' have a self-distancing effect; it
is as if he doesn't fully occupy his own being and observes himself
from some other place. He is both in his own experience and outside
of it. This is a fine perspective for a narrator who will be forced
to move from the orderly, predictable contentment of his life in a
placid 19th-century farm town to confront the appalling prospect of
chaos and destruction as the people around him sicken and die and
the brush fires advance ever closer.
</P>
<P>
   The character of this strange man -- loving father and husband,
conscientious sheriff and pastor, indefatigable builder of expertly
made coffins -- is established by means of oblique strokes. Jacob
communicates much by what he leaves unsaid, frequently brooding
about his idea of duty and his relationship with God and only
seldom letting us glimpse the darker images that skulk about in the
shadows of his mind.
</P>
<P>
   O'Nan is a writer who in his past work has sometimes told us too
much about his characters, so the brevity and allusiveness that he
employs in the creation of Jacob Hansen come as a bracing
development. Jacob is skewed at a deep level, and our understanding
of just how skewed he is emerges so gradually, and so elliptically,
that the full impact is felt not in the direct telling but in our
sudden lurching grasp of just what this man has done -- and what he
is capable of doing -- as his world turns upside down.
</P>
<P>
   The horror, then, flares to life in the reader's mind rather
than on the page, just as it does in the work of a writer like M.
R. James, whose Edwardian ghost stories create hugely creepy
effects from the most minute phenomena. In all his books, O'Nan has
displayed an interest in the horrific, but he indulged it with the
most zest in a fast, dark novel called ``The Speed Queen.'' That
book was fashioned as the death-row memoir of a young woman whose
involvement in a botched robbery spiraled into an
amphetamine-fueled killing spree. The narrator of ``The Speed
Queen'' has sold her story to Stephen King, and she talks to him by
means of a tape recorder while awaiting the verdict on her final
appeal for a stay of execution. It is not the most elegant of
framing devices, nor is the spectacle of drug-driven bloody mayhem
especially edifying. Of more interest is the tone of the narrator,
her blandness, her moral vacuity, her lately acquired religiosity,
all the cheery banality of her stunted consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   The sense of a mind out of sync with the moral implications of
its own experience similarly permeates ``A Prayer for the Dying,''
but with a nuanced complexity that is altogether absent from ``The
Speed Queen.'' As the crisis faced by the township ratchets to ever
higher degrees of peril, so Jacob, somehow spared the sickness that
is rapidly carrying off his friends and neighbors, finds himself
thrust into the center of events.
</P>
<P>
   As he wrestles with not one but two destructive forces of
nature, the novel seems at times to expand to grand allegorical
dimensions, and the reader glimpses in poor Jacob an Everyman
confronted by powers he cannot control, powers that will surely
destroy him. He is also an Everyman in his attempts, in the midst
of so much unwarranted suffering, to fall back on a few flimsy
precepts about the nature of God and his own guilt-riddled soul as
he tries to determine the meaning of the disaster. It is hardly
surprising, then, that Jacob should lose his sanity, for Everyman
cannot really cope with sheer, blind, random meaninglessness.
</P>
<P>
   The manifestations of its narrator's madness are what lend this
short novel its Gothic originality and power. Jacob is a
God-fearing preacher, a good family man and an upholder of the law,
but by the end of the book there seems to be no moral taboo he has
not violated. He has not, however, committed his transgressions
with some great Nietzschean howl of defiance or even with the dumb
amorality of the death-row narrator of ``The Speed Queen.'' Rather,
he has sinned with the worried, puzzled, impotent earnestness of a
good man to whom bad things are happening on an appallingly large
scale.
</P>
<P>
   But how do we know that Jacob is good? Because he loves his wife
and daughter and would do anything to protect them -- and, indeed,
all the townspeople -- from the encroaching evil. Once the
swiftness and deadliness of the diphtheria epidemic have been
established, it is enough for us to hear a woman cough to know that
she is doomed. When that woman is Jacob's beloved wife, Marta, and
their child is already mortally ill, we can almost hear the struts
of Jacob's being bend and crack. Although he himself does not
comment on that cough, we recognize his silence as the mark of his
denial. He will sustain that denial almost to the end, refusing to
believe that his wife has died and maintaining their domestic
routines as if she were still alive. It is in such situations, as
Edgar Allan Poe well knew, when the distinction between a living
woman and a dead one breaks down, that great sins may be committed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jacob goes about his work as conscientiously as he
knows how. He buries the dead and burns their houses. He preaches
to the survivors and maintains the quarantine. The flames of his
guilt about what he did in the war are fanned by what he can only
regard as biblical punishments imposed on the town by an irascible
Deity. At some level, he believes that the calamity is all his
fault.
</P>
<P>
   There is even a moment of grotesque surreality when a traveling
circus, complete with an elephant, attempts to pass through the
area and Jacob turns it back at the town line. At another point,
when the fires have almost reached Friendship, a flock of swallows
drops from the sky. ``They come down around you, their soft bodies
pelting your back. They cover the road, dead yet perfect. When you
bend to touch one, its feathers are hot, its eye boiled white.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Prayer for the Dying'' is that rare thing, a horror story
that achieves its effects by taking a narrowly circumscribed area
of human experience and expanding it to probe much larger
questions. By splicing together the themes of individual guilt,
belief in a merciful God and the destructive power of an apparently
malignant Nature, Stewart O'Nan has produced a fine, terse novel
about the circumstantial nature of evil and the terrible fragility
of man.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Patrick McGrath's most recent book is a novel, ``Asylum.'' He is
completing a novel about the American Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
</TEXT>
