<HEADER>
A8377 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-COWBOY-NYTSF     04-29 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-COWBOY-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 COWBOY
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Sara Davidson.
</P>
<P>
   270 pp. New York:
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Street Books/
</P>
<P>
   HarperCollins Publishers. $24.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; MR. NOT-QUITE-RIGHT
</P>
<P>
   By Lucinda Rosenfeld
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt like I was fetishizing his otherness,'' a friend
of mine sighed on breaking up with her boyfriend, a southern
California car detailer who specialized in lightning bolts. Alas,
it's not easy being a member of the cultural elite -- as Sara
Davidson makes all too clear in her fifth book, a fictionalized
memoir about her love affair with an uneducated cowboy artisan.
Whether a fictionalized memoir ought to be read as a memoir or as a
work of fiction invites a separate discussion. But the story goes
as follows: Davidson, a Berkeley-educated, Mercedes station
wagon-driving divorced mother of two, learns of a cowboy poetry
festival from a wrangler-consultant on the set of the television
western she writes for (``Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman''). On a whim
inspired in equal parts by journalism and libido, she and a writer
friend pack their bags for Elko, Nev., where -- among the aging
cowboys performing ``Tumbling Tumbleweed'' -- a hunk selling
handcrafted rawhide bridles uses Davidson's press badge as a point
of conversational departure (``New York Times. . . . What's
that?''). Davidson dismisses the guy as an ``insolent yokel'' --
until a love poem arrives in her mailbox a week later, leaving her
shuddering on several counts, not just the poem's raw emotionalism
but the poet's poor spelling skills. As Davidson's friend comments,
``The only thing standing between you and this man is spell
check!''
</P>
<P>
   But an unexpectedly intense relationship develops between
Davidson and the so-called ``Zack.'' On the positive side, he plays
into a lifetime of erotic fantasies having to do with chaps (``The
rough leather directs the eye up the legs to the place where the
leather stops, just below the groin''). On the negative side, the
new boyfriend's never heard of Anne Frank. If that wasn't bad
enough, on their weekends together, the well-compensated Davidson
is forced to foot the bill for everything from his airplane tickets
to their seaside hotel rooms. After he relocates to Los Angeles to
be with her, Davidson even agrees to pay the bulk of the rent on
Zack's Topanga Canyon cottage. Can love transcend educational and
economic disparity? This is the question Davidson poses and
attempts to answer in the affirmative. (At publication time, she
and the Marlboro man were still a match.)
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Davidson never seems entirely convinced. ``He's fed and
groomed me, laughed and played with me, taken me riding and to
states of ecstasy and I'm complaining that he uses wrong words?''
But she continues to complain -- albeit couching her harshest
criticisms in the mouths of her bratty children (he smells; he's a
hick) and her snobbish talent agent ex-husband (he shouldn't have
given their 11-year-old son butane and a lighter to play with).
Meanwhile, for all her feminist posturing about societal
intolerance of powerful women who take up with less powerful men,
Davidson is only too eager to prove that her and Zack's primary
bond has always been a physical one. Indeed, you can almost hear
the kids shrieking ``Eeeeewww'' -- never mind this reviewer --
every time Davidson launches into another description of the
apparently time-defying bouts of lovemaking. Is it any wonder the
never-not-in-the-mood Zack comes across as some kind of stud for
hire -- all the while uttering made-
</P>
<P>
   for-TV lines like ``All I want to do is ride horses, braid
things and make love to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Davidson has a supposedly revelatory moment during which
she realizes that the whole time she's been writing ``Dr. Quinn''
(in which Jane Seymour plays a doctor from Boston married to a
sexually potent mountain man), she's actually been writing her own
story. The news came as no surprise to this reader, who found
herself doing the casting (Meryl Streep and Robert Redford?) from
page 1.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Lucinda Rosenfeld's first novel will be published next year.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
