<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8378 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-JERUSALEM-NYT     04-29 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-JERUSALEM-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 ISRAEL AND EUROPE
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Appraisal in History.
</P>
<P>
   By Howard M. Sachar.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred A. Knopf. $30.
</P>
<P>
   ----
 &UR; BUILDING THE NEW JERUSALEM
</P>
<P>
   BY SERGE SCHMEMANN
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Howard M. Sachar plunges into ``Israel and Europe,'' the latest
of his many books about Israel and the Jews, with minimal fanfare.
A few acknowledgments, and we're smack in medias res: ``On Feb. 14,
1947, Foreign Secretary Ernest Bevin informed the House of Commons
that he was referring the fate of Britain's embroiled Palestine
mandate to the United Nations.'' The ensuing account of Britain's
decision after World War II to unburden itself of its expensive and
unruly Palestinian dependency clips along at the same bustling
pace, with events, facts, judgment and analysis flowing as from a
finely engineered assembly plant. There are few pauses as Sachar
guides us through the enormously complex and ambivalent
relationship between European nations and the Jewish state, an
association built on both shared culture and antagonism, on common
values and the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   That pace and that richness of material are the strength and the
weakness of this study. It comes as no surprise that Sachar is
thoroughly familiar with his subject. A professor of history at
George Washington University, he has written 13 earlier books on
Jewish and Middle Eastern history, including comprehensive works
like ``The Course of Modern Jewish History.'' Indeed, this latest
study -- which Sachar somewhat enigmatically subtitles ``An
Appraisal in History'' -- amounts to fitting a few more pieces into
the grand jigsaw puzzle to which he has dedicated his scholarly
career.
</P>
<P>
   And critical pieces they are. Today, when Israel's paramount
security ties are to the United States, it is possible to forget
how intimately the Jewish state's history is bound to Europe --
that its founding fathers and first leaders were Europeans, that
the first waves of settlers were refugees from the Holocaust, that
the newborn state was armed and supported in its vulnerable early
years not by the United States, which in those days sought to stem
the flow of arms to Israel, but by France. Zionism, Sachar notes in
his acknowledgments, ``from its inception was the Jews' ideological
response specifically to European romantic nationalism, their
political response to European anti-Semitism.''
</P>
<P>
   The complexity of that response is richly chronicled by Sachar.
Focusing largely on Britain, France, West Germany, the Vatican and
Russia, he explains the interplay of prejudices, guilt, domestic
politics and cold war rivalries that shaped ever-shifting relations
between the Europeans and the little state on the eastern
Mediterranean. There is Germany, which perceives support of Israel
as ``a moral obligation of the German people, a commitment that
transcended all issues of conventional statecraft.'' There is
Britain, torn between traditional sympathies for the Arabs and the
reality of a gutsy Jewish state. There is the Soviet Union, locked
in a permanent contest for influence and power with the United
States, trying to use weapons and its sizable Jewish minority as
levers. There is France, careering from all-out support of the
Israelis to imperious opposition as its own fortunes shift. There
are the many other Europeans -- the Spaniards, the Vatican, the
East Europeans -- all guided, to varying degrees, by public opinion
and political need. And of course there is Israel itself, torn
between distrust of the Europeans and an elemental pursuit of arms
and trade, attracting admiration and support through raw courage
and spectacular victories, then creating resentment through its
treatment of Palestinian Arabs and their occupied lands.
</P>
<P>
   In his finest passages, Sachar displays a true professor's
talent for the cogent explanation of a complicated concept. Here,
for example, is his analysis of the ambivalent reaction of the
Europeans to the assassinations of suspected terrorists by Israeli
agents operating on European soil in the 1970's: ``In the prewar
era, their rightist elements had stigmatized Jews as a retrograde
people, from whom nothing good could be expected. But with the
postwar revelations of the Holocaust, followed by the rise of
Israel, and the Jewish state's underdog military victories over the
Arab armies, Europe tended to embrace a maximalist view of the
Israelis as 'new' Jews, paragons of all that was gallant, decent,
honorable and moral in the human condition. Belatedly and
subliminally, Europe in effect was imposing on Israel a categorical
imperative that its own peoples earlier had forfeited.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Sachar makes no secret of his profound
admiration for Israel, and his pride in the renaissance of the
Jewish homeland. This is a book in which Israel is hero. It is the
``little nation'' bravely staving off its foes, and European
leaders are divided according to their attitudes toward it -- they
are either a ``friend of the Jews'' or subject to ``blatant
pro-Arab partisanship.'' In a few instances, Sachar allows himself
a brief burst of angry sarcasm at European hypocrisy, as when the
Europeans assail Israel over the invasion of Lebanon in 1982: ``It
was the Jews, perennial victims of European persecution and
claimants on the European conscience, who were inflicting havoc on
others.'' In internal Israeli politics, Sachar also leaves little
doubt as to his own liberal and secularist leanings, or to his
regret at the current impasse in the Israeli-Palestinian peace
process. Yet he places some of the highest blame for it not on
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu but on ``the irresolution of
Washington's Middle East diplomacy'' under President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sachar does not allow his love of Israel to cloud his
judgment. He offsets his feelings with ample objective evidence,
and is scrupulously fair in explaining the full range of factors
shaping European attitudes toward Israel. In fact, I would have
dearly preferred more argument, more passion, more drama. For too
many of its 398 pages, the text reads like a catalogue of
developments, events and diplomatic maneuvers, all presented in
roughly the same tone. To use Sachar's own subtitle, there is too
much history and not enough appraisal. There are ample dates and
facts, countless diplomatic confrontations, but too few
personalities, too little of the intellectual debate in Europe or
Israel about each other, too little of the inherent drama in the
interplay of peoples with so much baggage in their common
histories.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps one longs for more because there is so much. What Sachar
achieves in collating the history of European-Israeli relations and
in keeping it clear, compelling and accessible is a remarkable
feat. It is a critical background for any appreciation of the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Serge Schmemann, a senior writer for The Times, was the paper's
bureau chief in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
