<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8380 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-TALES-NYTSF     04-29 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-TALES-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 TELLER OF TALES
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Life of Arthur Conan Doyle.
</P>
<P>
   By Daniel Stashower.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Holt &AMP; Company. $32.50.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; SHERLOCK HOLMES'S MAKER
</P>
<P>
   By David Walton
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   NOT long before his death in 1930, at the age of 71, Sir Arthur
Conan Doyle -- a writer from a family of successful artists and
illustrators -- struggled to his desk and drew a sketch, a copy of
which today hangs in London's Sherlock Holmes pub. It shows a
moth-eaten workhorse pulling a baggage cart loaded with crates,
each labeled with an aspect of Doyle's life and work: ``Historical
Novels,'' ``Poems,'' ``Tales,'' ``Psychic Research,'' ``The Great
War,'' ``500 Lectures.'' Heaviest, of course, is the one marked
``Sherlock Holmes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Conan Doyle lived long enough to realize that Sherlock Holmes
would, in Watson's phrase, 'eclipse and predominate' the rest of
his work,'' Daniel Stashower writes in ``Teller of Tales,'' his
excellent biography of the man who created Sherlock Holmes -- and
who would like to have been remembered for a great deal more. The
millstone of Doyle's reputation is not any discrepancy between the
Holmes stories and Doyle's other writings, but a more glaring
discrepancy between the cold logic of Holmes and the beguiled
enthusiasms of his creator for what Stashower calls ``fairies,
ghosts and that.''
</P>
<P>
   Most biographers minimize the spiritualist crusade that consumed
the last 10 years of Doyle's life, attributing it to grief over the
death of his son and other close relatives in the war. Stashower,
by contrast, takes that issue, which Doyle considered his life's
great work, as his starting point. He begins in July 1930, with
6,000 people crowding into London's Royal Albert Hall to attend a
lecture by Sir Arthur Conan Doyle -- who has died five days
earlier. Only one chair is empty, the one with the author's name on
it. A medium rises claiming to see him in that chair, in evening
dress, and she carries a message to the waiting ear of Lady Doyle.
Stashower reports the reactions of crowd and reporters -- the
mixture of reverence, incredulity and ridicule that had become
associated in his final years with the writer whom many saw as
``the St. Paul of spiritualism'' and many more as ``a sad and
deluded old man who had squandered his greatness.''
</P>
<P>
   Next Stashower looks back to the University of Edinburgh Medical
School in the late 1870's, the lecture hall of Dr. Joseph Bell,
master of observation and deduction. Bell dips a finger into a foul
liquid and puts his finger into his mouth, and instructs his
students to do the same -- then points out that while he placed his
index finger into the awful brew, it was his middle finger that
found its way to his mouth. He meets a patient he has never seen
before, and correctly states that she has crossed from Burntisland,
walked up Inverleith Row, has a second child in addition to the one
with her, and works in a linoleum factory. In the third row, young
Doyle, not yet 20, listens and takes note.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had a life which, for variety and romance, could, I
think, hardly be exceeded,'' this most prototypical of Victorians
once wrote, and Stashower shows the truth of that claim in a packed
but unhurried narrative that covers Doyle's medical career; his
expeditions as ship's surgeon to the Arctic and West Africa; his
service in the Boer War (which helped usher in an era of military
reforms); his defenses of George Edalji and Oscar Slater, two men
wrongly imprisoned; his unpopular support of the Irish-born
diplomat Roger Casement, hanged for treason in 1916; his six-volume
history of World War I (which accepted uncritically the
headquarters version of every engagement); his early and growing
belief in spiritualism and the power of mediums. He was, Stashower
writes, ``a man of strong convictions, some of them absurd, all of
them deeply felt.'' He was an accomplished boxer, was one of the
first in Britain to receive a speeding ticket and, if you can
believe, made skiing popular in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the draw remains how Doyle conceived and developed
Sherlock Holmes, a story that Stashower, though he claims to be no
``Sherlockian,'' clearly revels in. (Stashower is the author of two
mysteries, ``The Adventure of the Ectoplasmic Man,'' which brings
together Holmes and Harry Houdini, and ``Elephants in the
Distance,'' based on the stage magician's trick of catching a
bullet with the teeth; he has himself been a performing magician.)
It may not be precisely true that Doyle was ``the man who hated
Sherlock Holmes.'' But it is interesting how persistently he tried
to shake Holmes from his back. At the end of 1891, less than six
months after the Holmes stories started running in The Strand,
Doyle's mother had to talk him out of killing Holmes (she came up
with a better, though temporary, plot solution). In 1893, two
English clergymen he met on vacation in Switzerland suggested he
drop Holmes down a crevasse -- after failing to persuade Doyle he
would be ``rather rough on an old friend'' to end Holmes's career.
At The Strand, which had grown wealthy publishing the Holmes
stories and whose editors had pleaded for the detective's life,
20,000 subscriptions were canceled when Holmes went over the
Reichenbach Falls in the December 1893 issue. In London mourning
bands were seen. Doyle went happily back to work on meticulously
researching historical romances like ``The White Company'' and
``Sir Nigel,'' which he considered his ``high-water mark in
literature'' and which one reviewer hailed as ``the year's best
boy's book.''
</P>
<P>
   An additional challenge awaits any biographer of Arthur Conan
Doyle, in that he is invariably the best teller of his own history,
even the best commentator on his own shortcomings. He would repeat
for the rest of his life an anecdote from his first American
lecture tour, in 1894. A cabby, dropping him off, asked for a
ticket to that night's lecture instead of a fare.
</P>
<P>
   ``How on earth did you recognize me?'' Doyle asked.
</P>
<P>
   The cabman replied: ``If you will excuse me, your coat lapels
are badly twisted downward, where they have been grasped by the
pertinacious New York reporters. Your hair has the Quakerish cut of
a Philadelphia barber, and your hat, battered at the brim in front,
shows where you have tightly grasped it, in the struggle to stand
your ground at a Chicago literary luncheon. Your right shoe has a
large block of Buffalo mud just under the instep; the odor of a
Utica cigar hangs about your clothing. . . . And, of course, the
labels on your case give a full account of your recent travels --
just below the brass plaque reading 'Conan Doyle.' ''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   David Walton is a short-story writer who lives in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
