<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-FRIEND-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 A DANGEROUS FRIEND
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Ward Just.
</P>
<P>
   A Peter Davison Book/Houghton Mifflin Company. $23.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; THE QUIET AMERICAN
</P>
<P>
   BY JAMES MCMANUS
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Why were we in Vietnam? Dwight Eisenhower argued that unless we
provided aid and military advisers to Saigon, one country after
another would topple like dominoes before the Communist juggernaut.
By assembling the best and brightest minds to bolster the South
Vietnamese, John Kennedy hoped to demonstrate the resolve of the
United States to stick by its allies. Lyndon Johnson escalated our
military presence, insisting it was necessary to offset support
from the North. And Richard Nixon eventually brought our troops
home, bombing Hanoi to gain leverage while negotiating to achieve
``peace with honor.''
</P>
<P>
   The assessments of artists and writers have tended to be
different from those of the politicians. And so, in Ward Just's
12th novel, Americans go to Vietnam for a host of paradoxical
reasons. Set in 1965, ``A Dangerous Friend'' focuses on the
civilians who volunteered to administer aid programs, distribute
medicine, build schools and hospitals -- to take Vietnam, as one of
them puts it, ``from the Middle Ages to the 20th century in five
years.'' Among them is Sydney Parade, who wants to participate in
the history of his time, or at least be ``someone who could be said
to have done more good than harm.'' But to do so he has to abandon
his wife, Karla, who equates the American effort in Southeast Asia
with Hitler's invasion of Czechoslovakia, her parents' homeland.
Since Karla also believes that ``anyone who had anything to do with
this war in any capacity was as guilty as if he had put the barrel
of a gun in a child's face and pulled the trigger,'' their marriage
essentially ends on the day Sydney accepts his new assignment.
</P>
<P>
   As his central character retraces the route his Western
predecessors took, stopping in Paris on the way to Saigon, Just
begins to establish a convincing allegorical dimension to the
novel. We learned from the French, he seems to suggest -- and, then
again, we didn't. To young political scientists like Sydney, the
success of the Vietcong defies military and political logic: ``We
had so much and they had so little; our 19-year-olds were supported
by an arsenal beyond the imagination of the guerrillas facing
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sydney and his colleagues at the Llewellyn Group (``a benevolent
arm of the Government wholly separate from the Pentagon'') believe
in ``the perfectibility of societies, even primitive societies with
scant experience of democratic government.'' Yet some of the
group's senior members approach their work with deep cynicism.
Worse, their director, Dicky Rostok, wants information on the enemy
for reasons that seem personal as well as strategic. More than
money or weaponry, information is power, and Rostok intends to
acquire it by any means necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Just's unnamed narrator insists that in describing Sydney
Parade's experiences he is not telling a war story, and indeed ``A
Dangerous Friend'' contains little violence. Menace is conveyed
through glimpses of Vietcong guerrillas moving at night on black
bicycles, of an American officer alone in a Vietnamese village, of
blood on the sleeve of a suit. Battle scenes are described
obliquely through rumors and field reports discussed around
conference tables, their effects hinted at on slips of paper passed
anonymously in exclusive Saigon restaurants. Just has a veteran war
reporter's eye for the telling detail -- light from phosphorus
flares ``so fierce you could see it with closed eyelids'' -- and a
reporter's skepticism about his Government's stated objectives.
Though his prose occasionally betrays a reporter's fact-laden
unwieldiness and a weakness for cliches, he succeeds in evoking the
dense, tactile weave of life in country circa 1965. When the
narrator salutes Joseph Conrad and Graham Greene as models, the
connection does not seem farfetched.
</P>
<P>
   THE plot turns on the fate of a captured American captain who is
also the nephew of a Congressman. The captain was last seen in the
Xuan Loc sector near Plantation Louvet, which is managed by a
Frenchman named Claude Armand and his American-born wife, Dede. The
Armands are living a premodern idyll in an ``ambiance reminiscent
of Winnetka, if Winnetka were tropical.'' They have little sympathy
for the Americans and want desperately to remain neutral, but the
Llewellyn Group has other plans. Having spent weeks failing to
locate the plantation, Sydney finally manages to meet Dede Armand
under circumstances of such gruesome serendipity that readers may
find this key passage difficult to swallow. Yet once Sydney gains
the Armands' wary cooperation, the novel becomes a kind of Faustian
negotiation in which a sincere but provisional friendship leads to
shattering acts of betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   As in his previous novels (the National Book Award finalist
``Echo House'' foremost among them), Just imposes a severe
metaphorical order on the world, and on Americans' increasingly
critical place in it. In ``A Dangerous Friend,'' the intricate
network of imagery allows the reader to see the tragedy of Vietnam
in ways that throw into high relief the conflicted array of
Vietnamese, French and American interests. The most graphic
metaphors include a torture victim and the stillborn Vietnamese
children of French and American parents. More subtle is the Panama
hat that comes to represent not only the country's climate but the
customs and dreams of the Vietnamese, as filtered through the lives
of a Vietnamese woman and her American husband, a member of the
Llewellyn Group who, in the view of his colleagues, ``had lived in
Vietnam for too long and had lost perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Dangerous Friend'' persuasively suggests that Americans like
Sydney Parade were in Vietnam for reasons both misguided and
honorable. As the novel's plot proceeds, Sydney can only watch
helplessly as his efforts to do ``more good than harm'' spin out of
his control. He fails not only because of his adversaries' tenacity
but because he has been trying to foster American values in a
country so different from his own. As Just's narrator remarks, with
no little irony, Sydney was ``searching in a dark room for a black
hat that wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   James McManus's most recent novel is ``Going to the Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
