<HEADER>
A8383 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-PARADISE-NYTS     04-29 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-PARADISE-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 SCARS OF SWEET PARADISE
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Life and Times of Janis Joplin.
</P>
<P>
   By Alice Echols.
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Books/Henry Holt &AMP; Company. $26.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; NOTHIN' LEFT TO LOSE
</P>
<P>
   BY KIM FRANCE
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   FROM the time she was a teen-ager until the accidental heroin
overdose that killed her in 1970 at the age of 27, Janis Joplin
delighted in flouting expectations of conventional female behavior.
As a high-school girl in Port Arthur, Tex., she routinely sneaked
over the Louisiana border with a group of male friends to drink and
dance in divey blues bars. During her brief tenure as a student at
the University of Texas, she differed so much from the rest of the
student body that the mere fact of her was enough to merit a
profile in the student newspaper. (``She Dares to Be Different!''
read the headline. ``She goes barefooted when she feels like it,
wears Levi's to class because they're more comfortable and carries
her Autoharp with her everywhere she goes so that in case she gets
the urge to break out into song it will be handy.'')
</P>
<P>
   Once she became famous, Joplin cursed like a truck driver, did
not believe in wearing undergarments, was rarely seen without her
bottle of Southern Comfort and delighted in playing the role of
sexual predator. On stage, as Alice Echols writes in ``Scars of
Sweet Paradise,'' she stood in sharp contrast to folksy peers like
Joan Baez and Judy Collins. By all accounts, Joplin behaved as no
white woman had ever before behaved on stage -- a sexed-up
powerhouse who stalked the stage as if she owned it, reducing male
rock critics to comically blubbering buffoons.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the sexual barrier Joplin remains most remembered for
breaking is that of rock-and-roll crash-and-burn: it was she who
proved that a female rocker could self-destruct as quickly and
decisively as any man. The more prurient details of Joplin's life
have already attracted a number of biographers, and in her
introduction, Echols, the author of ``Daring to Be Bad,'' a history
of radical feminism, lays claim to a more high-minded goal. ``Scars
of Sweet Paradise'' is not another steamy romp, but an attempt to
use Joplin's life to examine the 1960's -- an era, she writes, that
remains ``mired in myth, reduced to a set of cliches that seem to
function as a defense against true remembering.'' To this end,
Echols employs the details of Joplin's life as a sort of outline
with which to examine a number of larger phenomena.
</P>
<P>
   Janis Lyn Joplin was born in 1943 in Port Arthur, the kind of
Texas town that regards its xenophobia as an advantage. By
adolescence she was an ungainly girl with a bad case of acne. She
fell so short of the local ideal of the button-nosed cheerleader
that she seems to have defined herself in opposition to it. After
reading an article about beatniks in Time, she started dressing in
lots of black and became, Echols writes, ``a beatnik girl -- the
only one in all of Port Arthur.'' At school, she was considered
unladylike and opinionated, and received the reputation -- possibly
unearned -- of class slut. Echols does an interesting job of
reconstructing Joplin's quest to find like-minded friends, first in
Port Arthur and later in Austin, New York, San Francisco and Los
Angeles. One gets a sense of what a struggle it was, in the early
60's, to deviate from ``straight'' culture.
</P>
<P>
   As Echols follows Joplin's story, she gives corresponding
cultural background. Joplin's time in Austin, during which she
frequented the seminal blues bar Threadgill's and participated in
hootenannies, provides Echols with an opportunity to cover the rise
in popularity of American folk music; Joplin's early years in San
Francisco are used to explore Haight-Ashbury; the chapter on Joplin
and her band's career-making performance at the Monterey
International Pop Festival in 1967 delves into the growing business
of rock-and-roll. And so on. But while Echols casts an admirably
cold eye on places and events that have become hopelessly and
mistakenly romanticized, these digressions feel jumpy and never
fully integrate themselves into the book. Furthermore, the music
industry of the 60's is not a topic that wants for coverage. Echols
treads into territory covered far more definitively by books like
``The Mansion on the Hill'' (1997), by Fred Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   Echols conducted more than 150 interviews for the book, in many
cases talking to friends and associates who were at first reluctant
to tell the story again. No doubt Echols won them over by stressing
the book's sociological focus. But it is this very aspect that
limits ``Scars of Sweet Paradise.'' Well researched though it might
be, the book has about it the air of a topic handled one too many
times; the quotations feel picked over, and Joplin's life never
leaps off the page. In addition, Echols has a maddening habit of
using quotations when a simple paraphrase will do. For instance:
``Austin with its lush rolling hills 'seemed like Nirvana,' a
'little center of enlightenment' amid the 'vast primitive wasteland
of Texas.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Joplin's life was simply too sloppy and unwieldy for
such a methodically conceived project. Deeply convinced of her own
unattractiveness, frequently lonely and unimaginably needy, Joplin
was a person who lived all over the page. It is impossible to read
about her and not crave more anecdotes and personal details of such
a wanton, tragic life.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Kim France writes frequently about music and popular culture for
a variety of publications.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To subscribe, call a New York Times Syndicate
sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or Connie White,
at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796). To publish this article, call New
York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at (732)
390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
