<SLUG> BC-STOCKTON-SCHOOL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY REMAINS IN SHADOW OF '89 SCHOOL SHOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC DRUDIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. _ When Stockton dedicated its Children's Museum
to the victims of a 1989 schoolyard massacre, speaker after speaker
repeated the same hope: ``This will be the last school shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   But 10 years and several campus killings later, Stockton has
instead become a study in survivors and a community that cannot put
the deaths of five children in the past. The reminders are
everywhere, especially in the headlines and newscasts following
shootings like the one last week in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 17, 1989, a 26-year-old man dressed in army fatigues
sprayed 107 rounds of ammunition from an AK-47 over the playground
at Stockton's Cleveland Elementary School, killing five and
wounding 29. The man, Patrick Purdy, had once been a student there.
He killed himself before police officers could arrest him.
</P>
<P>
   After the shooting, Stockton successfully transformed the
community's anger and grief into improvements in school security
and a museum dedicated to the joy of children. Administrators and
faculty members spoke out against school violence, lobbying
politicians _ including the Senate regarding the Brady Bill _ for
stringent gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Busher, the school principal then and now, spoke at
length last year with members of the National Education Association
after a school shooting in Springfield, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Communities that weather a tragedy need to know there's a
light at the end of the tunnel,'' Busher said. ``One of the ways to
make sense of it is to make good out of evil, and that's what we
did.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Busher returned from Sacramento, where she met with
Gov. Gray Davis and lobbied the California Legislature for a ban on
assault weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Security has been a top concern as well. The district has since
pieced together an extensive safety and communications network at
its 43 schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took many years to heal, but each year we continue to
recognize what happened,'' said Deputy Superintendent George
Ridler. ``Since 1989, the emphasis has been on safety. It is our
top priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Schools have intercoms in each classroom. Visitors are required
to check in at the office to get an identification card.
</P>
<P>
   There are mandatory monthly emergency drills to prepare for
fires, earthquakes, campus trespassers or other scenarios. Police
officers are assigned to each of the district's middle schools.
</P>
<P>
   Former Cleveland second-grade teacher Janet Geng, who was shot
during the 1989 attack, said Littleton could learn lessons in
healing from Stockton. She found solace in completing the Stockton
Children's Museum, now one of the largest in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want children to smile again,'' Geng said. ``Their faces
were of anguish, and people tried to think of things that made them
smile again. This is what comes out of the hurt and the death.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum is not a memorial to the shootings, but a ``living
place that ensures laughter still can come from children,'' Geng
said. ``Their innocence was lost that day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Museum symbolizes how the community came together
after the shooting, Geng said. Businesses donated thousands of
dollars to help, and the city rented a building _ at the nominal
cost of $1 per year _ to house the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't just be a fleeting moment; it can't be just hugs and
then forgetting about it,`` Geng said. ``We thought Cleveland would
accomplish something, and hopefully, something will finally come
out of this. We need to have more people talking about it. A
tragedy like this needs a purpose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
