<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8397 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASCAR-PONTIAC-NYTR &LR;      04-29 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-PONTIAC-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAM PONTIAC ON THE MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jaw set and eyes flashing, John Andretti strode through the
Talladega Superspeedway garage last Sunday until he got to where
Tony Stewart had just parked his Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   He stopped and glared at Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does it say on the front of this car?'' Andretti asked
angrily.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart just looked at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You better remember that,'' Andretti said as he stalked off,
referring to the block letters across the car's nose that spelled
out Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti was upset because late in Talladega's DieHard 500,
after running a solid second to eventual winner Dale Earnhardt, he
fell back to ninth when Stewart got in line behind some Fords to
sweep into fifth place, leaving Andretti alone on the bottom of the
track.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Andretti's frustration was an indication of how far
``Team Pontiac,'' as some like to call it, has come in just a year.
</P>
<P>
   While Andretti might have argued the ``team'' concept with you
in Alabama on Sunday, no one can argue that while Chevy and Ford
continue to command the spotlight, Pontiac may be quietly stealing
the show.
</P>
<P>
   At the least, Pontiac made a huge leap forward in the early part
of the season when compared with 1998, and Andretti and Stewart are
two big reasons why.
</P>
<P>
   In the race before Talladega, at Martinsville, Va., Andretti
came from a lap down to win, taking the lead for good just three
laps from the finish.
</P>
<P>
   In the last seven races, Pontiacs have won once and finished in
the top 12 a whopping 24 times. That's only one less than GM rival
Chevy, which has 25 top 12s, and three times as many as Pontiac had
in the same seven races a year ago, when it recorded just eight
top-12 finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has put 35 cars in the top 12 during this time, but
Pontiac's improvement is especially noteworthy when you consider
that in any given race, Ford will regularly field around 20 cars
and Chevy about 15 while Pontiac maybe has eight.
</P>
<P>
   Unquestionably, Andretti and Stewart and their two teams have
pumped new life into Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti, who drives for Richard Petty, has one win and four top
10s so far, which compares with no wins and 10 top 10s last season.
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Kyle Petty, who had two top 10s during all of 1998,
already has three this year.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, a rookie, has joined Joe Gibbs, who has the top Pontiac
on the circuit with Bobby Labonte in it.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte is on a pace similar to last year, when he had two wins
and 18 top 10s. So far, he hasn't won, but he has six top 10s.
</P>
<P>
   And Stewart has already recorded three top-10 finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Leaning on his car, Stewart defended his moves late in Sunday's
race, when he left Andretti to fend for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were so many guys getting a run that I just wanted to
put myself in the best position I could,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that can change in five seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while near the end, Stewart and Labonte ran together, but
Stewart said the two teammates hadn't made a deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just going to go with whatever scenario was best for
each of us,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess Andretti's upset. He just asked what kind of car I
drive,'' Stewart added.
</P>
<P>
   But if Andretti, who quickly left the garage area, was
frustrated, Robbie Loomis, general manager of the two-car Petty
team and Andretti's crew chief, took it in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't complain,'' Loomis said Sunday. ``It's like I told
John, we had our week last week, and you can't have it your way
every week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony did what he thought he had to do to get the best finish
he could. I think John would have done the same thing,'' Loomis
commented.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is a big change for Pontiac. Last year, with the
exception of Labonte, they were struggling just to finish.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's going to get very hot when you're racing for 25th.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, they've got some cars that can actually compete,
and now they argue about why they didn't win.
</P>
<P>
   (Pat Zier writes for The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
