<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STUDY SAYS GOP PLAN WOULD ERASE SOCIAL SECURITY'S FINANCIAL WOES
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Social Security Administration said Thursday a
House Republican proposal to create individual investment accounts
would eventually eliminate the program's financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis by Stephen C. Ross, Social Security's deputy chief
actuary, also said that under the GOP plan, the 12.4 percent
payroll tax that finances the program could be reduced by 2.5
percentage points in 2050 and another percentage point in 2060.
</P>
<P>
   It predicted that the investment accounts would produce a 5.3
percent rate of return, compared to the roughly 2 percent rate
Social Security now receives on special Treasury bonds. The
Archer-Shaw plan would allow Social Security to remain solvent for
at least the 75-year period used to judge the program's financial
health, it said.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis is ``really good news,'' said House Ways and Means
Committee Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas, who is the chief architect
of the proposal along with Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Fla., chairman
of the Social Security subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today the actuaries gave us a Good Housekeeping seal of
approval,'' Archer told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The Archer-Shaw plan would use about $874 billion in projected
federal surpluses over the next 10 years to finance a 2 percent tax
credit for workers. The credit would be invested in privately
selected, government-approved mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   The investments would be transferred to the federal government
for distribution when a worker retired. Monthly annuity payments
would be made from the investment account. Retirees would receive
either the Social Security benefit set by law or the monthly
annuity, whichever was higher.
</P>
<P>
   Archer said that despite cautionary comments by GOP leaders in
the House and Senate, he is encouraged about prospects for
congressional action on Social Security reform after speaking this
week with President Clinton and Democratic committee members.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said Congress ``will take
a close look at this proposal,'' but warned that it would not pass
without bipartisan support.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, responding to criticism from some Democrats that the
proposal was unworkable and irresponsible, said that ``doing
nothing would end Social Security, and it would put millions of
Americans in poverty. We can't afford to do that. Doing nothing is
irresponsible and unworkable, and anybody in this Congress who
chooses to do nothing shouldn't be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Without reform, the program is expected to run out of reserves
by 2034. Clinton's reform plan is to reduce the publicly held
federal debt and credit that reduction to Social Security, which
would extend its ability to pay full benefits until 2055.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
