<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8408 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0430-     04-29 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0430-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KOSOVAR ALBANIANS DISGUISED AS SERB MILITARY MAY BE HUMAN
SHIELDS
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0430.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ Ethnic Albanian men detained in Kosovo are
being dressed in Serbian Yugoslav military uniforms for work
details and propaganda campaigns, making them candidates for use as
human shields against NATO bombing, refugees crossing into Albania
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   It the same time, humanitarian aid workers questioned whether
the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) here is manipulating the refugees
for its own purposes, pressing them to stay in this crowded border
area to serve as a source of recruits and possibly even as human
shields against Serbian shelling that has targeted KLA guerrilla
operations in northern Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the latest stream of refugees from the city of Prizren,
about 15 miles north of the Albanian border, said they left because
Serb forces came to their homes Wednesday night and threatened to
draft the men of their families into the army. The prospect that
these men would be armed and put in fighting units is marginal,
since Kosovar Albanians are enemies fighting for independence from
Serb-controlled Yugoslavia and now are targets of a fierce ethnic
cleansing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two weeks Serb police in Prizren increasingly have
grabbed ethnic Albanian men from their homes, the refugees said,
taking some for manual labor and putting others in anti-NATO
television propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I saw (Kosovar) Albanians digging trenches. There were
two on one side of the road and two more on the other,'' said
Milaim Kryeziu, 28. ``I know them. They were arrested 10 days
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the four young men from Prizren were wearing Yugoslav
army uniforms when he saw them at a town just north of the Albanian
border. Kryeziu was fleeing Kosovo with his family when he passed
them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are making them wear uniforms so NATO will think
they are Serb soldiers and will bomb them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other refugees said men taken into custody have appeared on
local Serbian television in Prizren. Some were shown in army
uniforms, saying they had volunteered for service. Others were
placed prominently at televised anti-NATO and anti-American
rallies.
</P>
<P>
   On this side of the border, questions also arose whether KLA
guerrilla fighters are manipulating the Kosovar Albanian refugees
in their own protection plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are rumors that the KLA doesn't want the people to move
from here,'' said Staffan DeMistura, a special envoy here for the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR). ``They want
to be defended and they want more recruits for their ranks.''
</P>
<P>
   DeMistura, who has been tasked with dispersing the more than
100,000 refugees clogging this northern border region, raised the
issue while meeting with refugee leaders whom he had taken to view
alternative living sites earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Relief officials had hoped the leadership group would report
favorably and recommend that the resistant refugees agree to leave
this area, which is considered dangerously close to military action
and also is bending to physical and social strains.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of the eight refugees at the meeting Thursday responded
to DeMistura, and he said he hadn't heard such rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, have said in interviews that the popular and
respected KLA has made it clear it has a stake in keeping the
refugees up here.
</P>
<P>
   They did not suggest the refugees are viewed as protection
against Serb assaults on KLA bases that litter the area --
including a large barracks located in the center of this city close
to refugee camps. But they did say the refugees are an important
pool for new recruits.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for us young men, when there is a general (KLA)
mobilization, we have to join them. That's why not only I but
others want to stay here closer to the border,'' said Reza Abozaj,
24, one of the refugee leaders.
</P>
<P>
   He said that KLA fighters he has talked with have urged him to
resist the plan to disperse refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Two others of the leaders also cited discussions with KLA
members as influencing their decisions not to recommend that the
refugees depart for new locations.
</P>
<P>
   All eight refugees at the Thursday meeting told DeMistura that
they have not been convinced the people living in their tent camps
should pick up their meager possessions and large families and head
out to the selected site of Peshkopi, about an eight-hour drive
south.
</P>
<P>
   Of the original group of 10, the only two members who expressed
positive views of relocating to Peshkopi both were absent from the
meeting. One was described as having left the camps, and the other
was said to be helping sick relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
