<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MP3-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPSTART BANDS SING PRAISES OF NEW INTERNET MUSIC FORMAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GLENN RUBENSTEIN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ From garage trios to headlining divas,
modern-day musicians have jumped onto the cyberspace bandwagon en
masse, using the popular digital compression format ``MP3'' to
record and market their music to a global audience via the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, bands have been capitalizing on the
technology. And not far behind are mainstream artists who are
attracted to the grass-roots method of disseminating their work as
well as the low overhead and high royalties available on-line.
</P>
<P>
   It was announced Tuesday that Alanis Morissette, the
multiplatinum Grammy award winner, would embark on a
five-and-a-half-week tour across the United States this August,
sponsored by the retail chain Best Buy and by an emerging
powerhouse in the Internet music world: MP3.com, a San Diego-based
Web site/music label that began offering free MP3 files for
download by a variety of unknown acts in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential here is enormous. We've got to seize the
opportunity,'' said Michael Robertson, chairman, chief executive
and founder of MP3.com.
</P>
<P>
   The recent success has not gone unnoticed by the increasingly
worried music establishment.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, the Recording Industry Association of
America has targeted the popular audio compression format MP3,
claiming the technology helps listeners pirate music, thus
depriving bands of the money they would make from album sales.
</P>
<P>
   Legal action has been brought against San Jose-based Diamond
Multimedia, manufacturer of the portable MP3 player The Rio, and
countless Internet Web sites that host MP3 files for download.
</P>
<P>
   Short for MPEG 1-Audio Layer 3, MP3 is a compression scheme that
allows CD-quality music to be compressed to a size small enough to
download on even the slowest modems while retaining superior sound
quality.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of MP3 files can fit on one hard drive. With the use of
MP3 player software, they can easily be cued up, played in order or
shuffled through _ turning even mid-level PCs into a high tech
jukebox.
</P>
<P>
   The format has gained enormous popularity on the Internet due to
its small size and high availability. It also has drawn both fans
and critics because of the number of illegal MP3 files that are out
there (illegal meaning that they are pirated MP3s compressed from
popular artists' CDs).
</P>
<P>
   While the casual music listener might not even know what MP3 is
yet, some bands in the San Francisco area, for example, are using
the format as a powerful marketing tool by creating MP3 files that
can be heard by a potential Internet audience of millions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to promote yourself,'' said Brett Holt, drummer and
manager for the San Jose-based punk band Boy Kicks Girl, ``and MP3
files are an excellent way to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-piece group, which has played more than 100 shows
since 1997, is one of the many bands on MP3.com.
</P>
<P>
   Since the site was launched in 1998, it has become a virtual
clearinghouse for bands looking to work outside the music industry
and use the Internet. It boasts more than 21 million song downloads
since the site began and more than 200,000 visitors a day. (It also
recently announced $11 million in funding from the New York venture
capital firm Silicon Alley).
</P>
<P>
   ``''Your mission is to reach as many potential fans as possible.
Once you have them, you have got to let them know what you're up
to,'' Holt said, citing the band's Web site at www.bkg.com and its
e-mail list, which he speculates has more than 1,200 names.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is our best resource. It gives us the ability to
extend our reach beyond the Bay area,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition to offering space for downloadable MP3 files,
MP3.com recently began offering bands the ability to sell CDs
on-line. Bands sign up for the program at no cost, select which
songs they want on their CD, and within 24 hours, it is available
for sale on the site.
</P>
<P>
   When a visitor clicks to buy the CD for a price set by the
artist _ $4.99 to $9.99 _ MP3.com decodes the MP3 files, burns them
to a disc, adds a label and mails the package to the buyer.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com gets 50 percent of the deal. The other 50 percent goes
straight to the artist, as opposed to most major or independent
label deals, where artists are lucky to take home 10 percent from
their CD sales.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there's not always a consumer stampede. Since the
program began, Boy Kicks Girl speculates it has sold about 30 discs
on-line, in contrast to the 100 a month it sells at live shows.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10,000 bands have songs on MP3.com, which says that it
is adding more every day.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, some artists have expressed frustration over the
sheer number of MP3 files on the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's probably a lot of great music on MP3.com that
no one has the time to find,'' said Owen Otto, guitar player for
Little Tin Frog, a Petaluma, Calif.-based alternative rock band.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beautiful thing about the Internet in general is that it
allows anyone the opportunity to publish their work for anyone else
in the world to experience,'' Otto said. ``The problem is that
there's tons of stuff out there that is total garbage, so it's a
lot more work to sort through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
