<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8418 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-NYT &LR;      04-29 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN PEACE INITIATIVE FOR KOSOVO MAKES LITTLE PROGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ A Russian-led peace initiative for Kosovo appeared to
make little headway Thursday, with Moscow and the West divided over
the composition of any international force in Kosovo and the
Yugoslav government in defiant mood.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Chernomyrdin, Russia's Balkan envoy, held talks in Bonn
with German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, and declared afterward,
``There's progress, but no breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the progress was hard to discern. Schroeder reiterated
NATO's position that any international force in Kosovo in the event
of a settlement would have to have NATO at its core, but
Chernomyrdin said Russia favored a force under a U.N. mandate that
would consist substantially of Russian troops.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of any international force in Kosovo has been highly
sensitive ever since peace negotiations on Kosovo intensified
earlier this year. Serbia has a visceral objection to the notion of
NATO troops on its most sacred soil, and its rejection of such a
deployment was a prime reason why peace talks failed and NATO's
bombing began.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared Thursday that, even after a five-week NATO
bombardment, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's position had
not shifted. His brother, Borislav Milosevic, who is Yugoslavia's
ambassador to Moscow, said that only ``a civilian mission under a
United Nations flag'' and ``a big role for Russia'' would be
acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Vojislav Seselj, an influential nationalist leader in Serbia,
also said that only a civilian force would be acceptable in Kosovo
_ a demand that NATO is certain to reject. It was Serbia's refusal
to allow Austro-Hungarian police onto its soil in 1914 to
investigate the murder of the Habsburg crown prince that
precipitated World War I.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Brussels, Belgium, after visits this week to Moscow
and Berlin, Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott said he had
explained to the Russians that NATO had to be central to any
international force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Of the force, he said, ``That means NATO _ it does not mean just
NATO _ but it certainly means NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   It therefore appears that Chernomyrdin will face great
difficulties in his planned visit to Belgrade later this week. In
essence, he will have to persuade Milosevic not only to begin
withdrawing the estimated 40,000 troops he has in Kosovo, but also
to accept that they will be replaced in part by the very forces
that have been bombarding his country.
</P>
<P>
   The only concession he might be able to offer the Serbian leader
is a Russian presence in that force and the passage of a U.N.
Security Council resolution authorizing its deployment.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has demanded that Milosevic withdraw his troops from
Kosovo, allow several hundred thousand ethnic Albanian refugees to
return to the homes from which they have been hounded, and permit
the deployment of a military force with NATO at its core. For now,
the future political status of Kosovo has been set aside as an
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott said these aims were ``unchanged, unchanging and will
not change.'' Until there is evidence they will be satisfied, the
bombing will continue and intensify.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has said that NATO might ``pause'' in its
bombardment if Serbia began a ``demonstrable and verifiable''
withdrawal of the forces that have been burning ethnic Albanian
homes and villages. But there was no sign Thursday that Milosevic
is ready to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Thursday how Russia would respond if Milosevic
proved completely unyielding. The Western allies are eager to
secure Russia's support for a Security Council resolution on Kosovo
that would back at least the bulk of NATO's objectives in the
Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
   Such a resolution would increase Milosevic's isolation _ another
Western aim. For if Milosevic will not yield, the only apparent
route to a NATO victory _ short of a full-scale land invasion _ is
through his overthrow by dissident Serbian forces convinced that he
is leading his country to ruin.
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, however, the opposition to Milosevic has appeared
scattered, ineffective or acutely vulnerable, despite large doses
of NATO rhetoric aimed at undermining the current Serbian
leadership.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
