<SLUG> BC-COVANCE-PAREXEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COVANCE TO BUY BAY STATE DRUG-DEVELOPMENT RIVAL PAREXEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Parexel International Corp., the nation's third-largest
drug-testing and development company, says it has agreed to be
acquired by rival Covance Inc. in New Jersey for $827 million in
stock.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will catapult Parexel and Covance into the No. 1 spot
in the burgeoning business of developing and testing experimental
drugs for the pharmaceutical and biotechnology industries. The new
company, to be named Covance Parexel Inc., will be based in
Princeton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than trim staff, as is the case with many corporate
mergers, Covance and Parexel said they will hire an additional
3,000 workers in the first 12 months after the deal is completed.
Parexel, of Waltham, Mass., employs about 4,300 full- and part-time
workers, about 900 of whom are in the Boston area. Covance, which
has 7,300 full-time employees, has minimal presence in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan is to grow, not cut back, in Boston,'' said Josef von
Rickenbach, Parexel's chief executive, who said he will remain in
the Boston area as the merged company's president and co-chairman
with Christopher Kuebler, chief executive of Covance and
CEO-designate of the merged company. ``Boston is a very important
location to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger, which is subject to regulatory approval, is expected
to be completed in September.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street punished Covance's stock on the New York Stock
Exchange Thursday, pushing it down 5 3/16 to 22 5/16, while Parexel
shares rose 3 15/16 to 23 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Rouse, research analyst with Lehman Brothers in New York,
said the Covance stock slide is due to worries that the deal would
depress the company's 1999 earnings. Rouse, however, believes the
stock will recover once Wall Street is reassured that Covance's
earnings will be minimally affected. Kuebler said the deal will
supress the combined company's profits by about 4 percent in 1999,
but will have no effect in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Rouse said the deal was borne out of market demand for larger,
more sophisticated companies that can handle the full spectrum of
drug development, from clinical trials to consulting to marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what their clients have been asking for,'' Rouse said.
``And that is giving rise to the consolidation.''
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1982, Parexel was a pioneer in the relatively young
drug-testing industry, which has grown by leaps and bounds as big
drug companies increasingly outsource their drug development
functions. Parexel revenue grew from $58.6 million in 1995 to
$285.4 million last year. Covance, the second-largest drug
development company which tested such drugs as Viagra and
Herceptin, has $732 million in annual sales. When combined, the
companies will overtake Quintiles Transnational Corp. as the
industry leader.
</P>
<P>
   Parexel's CEO, von Rickenbach, estimates that drug makers spend
more than $40 billion a year to develop drugs. Up to $7 billion of
that is outsourced to his and other companies. Parexel's industry
of outsourced drug development is growing at a rate of 20 percent a
year or more, according to Rouse of Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Parexel also announced quarterly financial results Thursday,
posting a net income of $5.7 million on $90 million in revenue in
its third fiscal quarter ended March 31. In 1998, Parexel lost $2.4
million on revenue of $73.1 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
