A8430 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CGARCIA-COLUMN30-COX     04-29 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CGARCIA-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Violent films are not guilty in blame gameBy Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service AUSTIN, Texas _ This just in: Movie
<TEXT>
violence sells.
<P>
   Millions upon millions of people across the nation have bought
tickets for the perversely peculiar adrenaline rush provided by gun
'n' blood fests like ``True Lies,'' ``Natural Born Killers,''
``Reservoir Dogs,'' ``Pulp Fiction'' and, for some inexplicable
reason, ``The Matrix.''
</P>
<P>
   Millions upon millions of people. Yet only a tiny handful of
these people have gone on to kill or cause mayhem, leading some
people to invoke the titles of violent movies that may have
inspired the carnage. One of the teens in the Columbine High School
massacre in Littleton, Colo., was rumored to be a fan of the recent
neo-Nazi skinhead drama ``American History X.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, of course he was. It appears he and his partner were
neo-Nazis who lionized Adolf Hitler. Did the movie, a late 1998
release, arouse their interest in Hitler? I doubt it. That would
transpose the equation of symptom and disease. The boys admired
``American History X'' because they were burgeoning neo-Nazis, not
the reverse.
</P>
<P>
   Do people randomly maim and murder because they think the
killing couple in Oliver Stone's ``Natural Born Killers'' are role
models to be aped, as has been alleged in two recent court cases?
No, they murder because they are murderers, predisposed
psychopaths. Of course they're going to be drawn to an exciting
movie about their ilk. To suggest that ``Natural Born Killers'' is
to blame is flatly irresponsible. Fortunately, both cases _ one in
Louisiana, one in Georgia _ were dismissed, although the Louisiana
case has been appealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're making the artist responsible for the violent criminal
actions of unknown, disturbed audience members,'' says James
Hemphill, a lawyer at the Austin law firm of George &AMP; Donaldson,
which represented the film's distributor, Warner Bros., in both
cases. The studio was accused of inciting violence by releasing
``Natural Born Killers.''
</P>
<P>
   I agree with Hemphill's assessment. And I think blaming the
artist is dead wrong.
</P>
<P>
   If films are so powerfully influential, as parents and pundits
claim, we should be happy these horrific incidents don't happen
more often. Even one murder is a heavy burden for society to bear,
but I just don't think we have an epidemic here. Movies may
glamorize violence (in my mind they do), but they don't kill;
idiots do.
</P>
<P>
   Calls for ``cleaning up'' pop art by somehow making it less
violent and more morally nourishing hark back to the defunct Hays
Code that, from 1930 to 1966, regulated content in Hollywood films.
One rule, for example, demanded that gangster movies punish their
criminal anti-heroes before the end credits. Now we have the
ratings system, G through NC-17, which parents may want to take
more seriously.
</P>
<P>
   To say that Hollywood should make more socially redemptive films
is not only an unreasonably subjective request, but an
anti-capitalist, semi-fascist one. It's like saying McDonald's
should sell tofu burgers on organic whole wheat buns. Nice idea
but...
</P>
<P>
   I submit that art _ and movies are art _ does not need morals.
Art by its very nature is amoral. It is beholden to no one but its
makers. Morals or spiritual uplift are not requisites to attain the
singular transcendence art can furnish. Art is exempt and
blameless. Its sole duty is to illuminate areas of life, including
those shadow areas we'd rather not confront. The moment it becomes
prescriptive, the line between art and propaganda blurs.
</P>
<P>
   Art is often coarse and uncomfortable, devoid of answers and
hopelessly entangled in ambiguity. Some of its best tools are its
most challenging and, to many, its most difficult to countenance:
satire, irony, detached realism, allegory. (Several critics hailed
``Natural Born Killers'' expressly for its wildly sophisticated use
of irony and satire.)
</P>
<P>
   So let's get the equation right. A film might indeed be the prod
that pushes a troubled individual off the precipice into
destruction. So might someone neglecting to use their turn signal
on Interstate 35. In fact, the latter is statistically more apt to
happen. Should we blame the cars?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
