<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8432 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-ENTRAPMENT30-C     04-29 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-ENTRAPMENT30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chemistry? Not in this formula
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In the press notes for the emaciated thriller
``Entrapment,'' co-star Catherine Zeta-Jones compares her on-screen
chemistry with Sean Connery to that of Hepburn and Tracy and Bogart
and Bacall. I'm pretty sure this is slander.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, Zeta-Jones is cursed by her beauty. Dark and
panther-sleek, she's so conventionally perfect, so preternaturally
unblemished, she's bland. She certainly cannot act. She likes to
purse her lips a lot and squint her eyes to make ``looks.'' In a
self-conscious, Calista Flockhart-y way, she thinks she's the
cutest thing since Smurfs.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Connery, the most famous actor who whistles when he
talks. When he chooses to, Connery has charisma to burn. Somewhere
along the way to ``Entrapment'' he must have started a small
inferno. He's interesting to look at, but so are X-rays. Connery is
a living cultural artifact, whose appeal lies in everything he's
done before what you're watching him in now.
</P>
<P>
   So ``Entrapment'' is a chemistry-free zone. It's also an
imagination-, humor- and passion-free zone. At its best, the
movie's a tiresome pastiche of innumerable action-romances. Usually
Jean-Claude Van Damme is drafted for routine dross like this. At
least he's fun to make fun of.
</P>
<P>
   Connery plays the ``world's greatest art thief,'' Mac, who has
just purloined a Rembrandt with incredible style. He's pursued by
Zeta-Jones' American insurance investigator, Gin, whose company
stands to lose $24 million if the painting is not recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Her plan when she finds Mac is to pose as a fellow art thief and
enlist the master ripper-offer to nab a priceless Chinese mask _ to
catch him red-handed. He bites, and just like that they are
partners in crime.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly if inadvertently, the movie depicts Gin as a rather
loathsome person. This is a problem when it comes to audience
empathy. Oh, let's just say it: She's a slut. As Mac coaches her in
the ways of high-tech larceny, Gin repeatedly offers herself to
him. Connery, ever the cool cucumber, declines. She's stung. She
pouts. I think it's this whisper of tension Zeta-Jones mistakes for
``chemistry.''
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, there's no pressing need for Gin to seduce Mac. He's
already in, he's accepted her proposition; they're a team. Sex,
apparently, is just a bonus prize.
</P>
<P>
   The twist is that Gin, staid insurance investigator, likes being
a criminal. She and Mac are smashing at it. With balletic grace and
arsenals of gizmos, they steal their quarry, which later includes
the brain-numbing figure of $8 billion from a Malaysian bank. In
the plot's single clever conceit, the money can only be accessed 30
seconds before the millennium _ at precisely 11:59:30 p.m. this New
Year's Eve _ right as the bank has shut down systems to test them
for the Y2K bug. By now the film has choked and passed out on its
royal implausibilities.
</P>
<P>
   The film was written by veteran scripter Ron Bass (``Rain Man,''
``My Best Friend's Wedding'') and Austinite William Broyles, who
co-wrote ``Apollo 13.'' It's amazing such talent cooked up such
rubbish. Beyond tired, the film is shoddy, riddled with dumb lapses
in logic, weak character development and witless banter. An absence
of subplots and any intriguing side characters (Ving Rhames is
wasted) makes this one thin package. Jon Amiel's visionless
direction helps nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Once again the charming scamp, Connery is OK here, though he
brings little to the role except that twinkle in his gimlet blues _
a twinkle that probably has its own agent. Like Harrison Ford,
Connery's often confused for a good actor. He's a marvelous
presence who can mold a faded Scottish burr into a musical purr. At
68, the actor's biggest feat here is that he plays a 60-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the lithe Zeta-Jones, who was admirable in last
summer's ``The Mask of Zorro,'' can't break out of her enamelled
pulchritude.
</P>
<P>
   Chemistry? Try the local pharmacy. Better yet, try a video shop
and rent ``Adam's Rib'' or ``The Big Sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Entrapment''
</P>
<P>
   1 star
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Sean Connery, Catherine Zeta-Jones, Ving Rhames
</P>
<P>
   Director: Jon Amiel
