<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8433 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-HANDS30-COX     04-29 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-HANDS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Idle Hands' can't hold savvy viewers
 &HT;    By Alison Macor
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The latest teen comedy ``Idle Hands'' includes
gory horror for extra spice, but uninspired writing, brain-dead
characters (this is before they get the ax) and agonizingly slow
pacing stop this movie dead in its tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Idle Hands'' opens promisingly. An eerily abstract credit
sequence plays out against a thumping soundtrack. Fade to a
suburban neighborhood, where the camera tracks through a sprawling,
Prairie-style house and comes to rest in an upstairs bedroom. A
woman (Connie Ray) and her husband (Fred Willard) are turning in
for the night. They turn out the lights, crawl under the covers and
get the shock of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The old-fashioned thrills are the best part of ``Idle Hands.''
The movie is spring-loaded with minor terrors that keep us
pleasantly off-balance. It's the filler, however, that turns ``Idle
Hands'' into another trendy, dumb teen movie. Characters like Anton
(Devon Sawa) and his friends Mick (Seth Green) and Pnub (Elden
Henson) stumble around spewing mind-numbing chatter at one another.
They're not dumb because they're stoked on pot (although in the
long run this doesn't help). They sound dumb because they're
written that way by screenwriters Terri Hughes and Ron Milbauer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Idle Hands'' centers on a neighborhood that's being stalked by
a killer. While the rest of the town is either grieving for
mutilated victims or watching over their shoulders, Anton is
blissfully unaware of the mayhem. We're not told much else, except
that a woman named Debbie (Vivica A. Fox) is tracking suspects in a
parallel story shoddily intercut with the main narrative. Debbie is
constructed as the Final Girl character, who in the slasher
tradition is the triumphant if traumatized survivor. This character
saves the genre for feminism, but in the case of ``Idle Hands,''
female empowerment requires a push-up bra.
</P>
<P>
   Anton's apathy supposedly is at the heart of his involvement in
the murders, but the explanation (uh, the moral?) is so poorly
delivered that it might as well have been left out of the script
entirely. His ``idle'' hands, which he's been using only to
manipulate the remote, roll his joints and so on, make him the
perfect host for a satanic force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Idle Hands'' uses its characters as pawns in a larger,
somewhat random game that involves winking at the conventions of
both the teen comedy and the horror film in all its contemporary
permutations (think Wes Craven, ``Tales From the Crypt,'' etc.).
Even the movie's stylish poster is reminiscent of the graphic
design made popular by German Expressionism. We're encouraged to
recognize these references and laugh at the stupidity of the
characters and their dilemmas, but the plot also demands that we
identify with Anton and his friends in order to care what happens
by the end of the story. But we don't, in part because they don't
deserve our interest.
</P>
<P>
   As movie audiences grow more sophisticated, they become more
difficult to impress. Contemporary horror movies like ``Scream''
are so successful because they combine the most basic chills (the
killer's in the house) with a reflexivity (a nod to the genre's
history) that acknowledges viewers' media savvy. ``Idle Hands''
adopts this equation and succeeds only part of the time because its
cast isn't balanced by a character worth rooting for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Idle Hands'' is for the 13-year-old boy in us. How in touch
you are with this part of your psyche determines how much you'll
enjoy this movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Idle Hands''
</P>
<P>
   2 stars
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Devon Sawa, Seth Green, Elden Henson, Vivica A. Fox
</P>
<P>
   Director: Rodman Flender
</P>
<P>
   Screenwriters: Terri Hughes, Ron Milbauer
</P>
<P>
   MPAA rating: R for language, drug references, nudity, violence
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 1 hour, 32 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
