<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-DEFECTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON SUIT DISCLOSES DEFECTS IN MAVERICK MISSILE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon Co. said it will spend several million dollars to fix
defects in Maverick air-to-ground missiles made for the Air Force
and other armed services.
</P>
<P>
   The Lexington, Mass. defense contractor made the disclosure in a
lawsuit against its supplier, Helix Technology Corp. of Mansfield,
Mass., alleging the company provided faulty parts for the missile's
guidance system.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Helix said the company rejects the charges and said
Raytheon's own inspectors had initially approved the parts in
question while they were being produced, from 1991 to 1994.
Military officials said the problems would not affect stocks of
missiles being used by NATO forces in airstrikes against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   According to Raytheon's suit, filed in Middlesex (Mass.)
Superior Court last summer, the faulty parts cause the missiles to
fail ``at an alarming rate.'' According to the suit, 44 percent of
Mavericks tested in 1997 were found to have problems in their
`cryoengine,'' a $2,100 part used to cool the missile's infrared
guidance system.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation found that defective seals within the parts
allowed helium within the cryoengines to leak and damage other
detectors nearby. The failures apparently were caused by cotton
fibers and metal slivers ``introduced into the cryoengines during
the manufacturing process,'' the lawsuit states.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon is seeking to recover costs of investigation and
repairs from Helix, and to have the award tripled. In a cover sheet
accompanying the suit, Raytheon states that it will spend ``several
million dollars investigating and repairing the defects.''
</P>
<P>
   Helix has moved to have the case dismissed because an applicable
statute of limitations has expired. Helix's lawyer in the case,
Craig Stewart, a partner in the law firm of Palmer &AMP; Dodge, said a
hearing in the case is scheduled for May 24.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon has not previously disclosed the suit in its SEC
filings. The suit was first reported by the Wall Street Journal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
