<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONFLICT IN THE BALKANS &LR;   &UR; (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA (Washington) _ Clinton administration, saddled with
the humiliation of the House refusing to support the US role in
Kosovo, endures the embarrassment of a wayward NATO missile
slamming into Bulgaria and the uncertain prospect of the Rev. Jesse
Jackson's arrival in Yugoslavia on an unauthorized peace mission.
By Bob Hohler. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   ERRANT-MISSILE (London) _ The NATO missile that plowed into the
suburbs of Sofia raising questions about the efficiency of the
weapons system. By Kevin Cullen. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   BALKANS-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ Viktor Chernomyrdin heads off to Bonn,
