<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8447 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN30-COX-re     04-29 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN30-COX-resend </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Examine adult males' exploitative role in teen pregnancy
 &HT;    EDS: Corrects grammatical errors in 5th, 9th and 10th grafs.
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ George W. Bush and Elizabeth Dole have stated that
rape would be one of few factors considered in granting an abortion
if they could amend the U.S. Constitution. Life-or-death medical
necessity would be another.
</P>
<P>
   How to write a constitutional amendment or statute to reflect
that: Medical necessity _ on one doctor's word? On decree of a
medical congress?
</P>
<P>
   Rape is even more problematic. The next time Bush or Dole
broaches the subject, someone ask, ``Does that include statutory
rape?''
</P>
<P>
   If the latter is the case, the candidates would allow a lot of
legal abortions and, presumably, be prosecuting more rape trials
than one can imagine. For by definition in most states, a vast
number of teen pregnancies, maybe the majority, are the result of
statutory rape.
</P>
<P>
   A nasty little matter too commonly downplayed: Most teen moms
are impregnated by adult males. Roughly half of the babies born to
mothers age 15 to 17 have fathers older than 20. Though the girls'
participation is consensual and irresponsible, they are the true
embodiment of girls getting swept off their feet.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Planned Parenthood seminar called ``Unequal Partners''
addressed this, focusing particularly on ways to get teen girls to
foresee the potential problems of being squired by older males.
</P>
<P>
   For those who want government to make tricky personal judgment
calls, this is one of the most compelling puzzles: Sometimes
there's a fine line between romance and rape.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 study by the National Campaign to Prevent Teen Pregnancy
found that more than 80 percent of teen girls engaging in
intercourse for the first time did so with older males, that 45
percent involved an age gap of two to four years, that 17 percent
had a gap of up to five years, and that 11.8 percent involved a
male five or more years older.
</P>
<P>
   This means that the phrase ``children having children'' is only
half right in so many cases. The fathers have left their childhood
behind. They've also left a teen's childhood in ruins.
</P>
<P>
   The starkest reality is what happen when the girl gets pregnant.
That special someone, so responsible and mature _ he's gone.
</P>
<P>
   The girls are far from blameless. But Lynn Phillips, whose study
for Planned Parenthood of Greater Northern New Jersey is used in
``Unequal Partners,'' points out the ominous impressions that draw
some girls into these straits.
</P>
<P>
   Older males are seen by teen girls not only as more wealthy and
mobile _ that car, that apartment _ but also as ``more likely than
teens to be monogamous.'' The girl presumes Mr. Dream-Boat's wild
oats have already been sown.
</P>
<P>
   However, reported Phillips, the adult men she studied in these
situations ``were no more likely to take responsibility for
pregnancy and child rearing than were adolescent partners.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips also found young girls taking less care to use birth
control with older males who looked more like the marrying type
than teens, or at least more like the type to stand by them if they
got pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   This dynamic must be front and center in the discussion of teen
sexuality, the fact that a young girl being romanced by a mature
candidate for the altar may only become a notch on his bedpost.
</P>
<P>
   Should these adults be prosecuted for rape? California has taken
a more aggressive stance in so doing. But the extent of the problem
is such that one exploitative seed-sower unto himself is but a
grain of sand on a long, long beach.
</P>
<P>
   The solution is laying out the facts and getting girls to think
about ways to spare themselves life-altering pregnancies or the
abortion dilemma. Meanwhile, candidates: Rape or romance? Are you
ready for government to make the call?
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday. E-mail:
jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
