<SLUG> BC-ERRANT-MISSILE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO EMBARRASSED BY ERRANT MISSILE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS _ On the same day Bulgaria's government tentatively
authorized NATO to use its airspace in its war against Yugoslavia,
NATO acknowledged Thursday that one of its missiles went awry and
hit a house in a suburb of the Bulgarian capital, Sofia.
</P>
<P>
   No one was hurt in the accident, but its timing could hardly
have been worse for NATO, coming days before a vote Monday by
Bulgaria's Parliament on whether to allow the use of its airspace.
</P>
<P>
   NATO considers the cooperation of Bulgaria against its fellow
Slavs in Serbia to be crucial in persuading Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic that he is becoming isolated in his war with the
West.
</P>
<P>
   The accident also continued an embarrassing pattern of NATO
missiles missing their targets. On Tuesday, a missile which NATO
said was aimed at a Yugoslav Army barracks went off course and hit
homes in the Serb town of Surdulica, killing 20 civilians,
including children.
</P>
<P>
   But while NATO said Tuesday's missile that killed civilians was
only off by a few hundred yards, the missile that hit the Gorna
Banja suburb of Sofia landed some 30 miles inside Bulgarian
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Bulgarian Interior Minister Bogomil Bonev told reporters in
Sofia that his country would sue NATO for compensation, but said
the accident would not shake the government's resolve to ask its
Parliament on Monday to give NATO a 70- to 90-mile air corridor
along Bulgaria's western border with Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   On three previous occasions, NATO missiles have strayed into
unpopulated border areas in Bulgaria, but caused no damage to
people or property. Bonev called Wednesday night's accident, in
which the roof and second floor of a house were destroyed, ``the
most drastic violation of our airspace so far.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking here, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said the accident
occurred when a NATO fighter's defense system indicated that it had
been ``locked on'' to by a Serb antiaircraft missile system. Shea
said the NATO pilot fired a HARM, or High-speed Anti-Radiation,
missile in self defense, but that the missile went astray when the
ground radar system which it had targeted suddenly was turned off.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Shea nor a senior NATO officer, Brigadier General
Giuseppe Marani, could explain why the ground radar system was shut
off, nor how future accidents could be avoided. But in an
interview, Shea rejected suggestions that the Serbs had purposely
used the radar system to draw fire from a NATO plane knowing that
once it turned off the radar, the NATO missile would continue into
Bulgaria. Shea said HARM missiles have a range of about 50 miles.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said that while accidents are regrettable, they
are unavoidable in combat situations. Without specifying how many
accidents there have been so far, Shea and other officials said
that only a fraction of 4,500 bomb and missile attacks launched in
the 37 days of Operation Allied Force have ended in mistakes, such
as the 70 to 80 refugees killed when mistaken for a Serb military
convoy three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   While the missile that landed in Bulgaria was a mistake, NATO
purposely bombed Montenegro. NATO officials said that almost 30
missile strikes hit Podgorica airfield in Montenegro because
Yugoslav warplanes there could attack NATO forces in neighboring
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro is the smaller of the two republics which with Serbia
forms what is left of Yugoslavia. Its pro-Western government has
blamed Milosevic for provoking the war, and it fears that Milosevic
may launch a coup against them.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulgarians, meanwhile, are torn between their desire to join
NATO and the European Union and their instinctive sympathy with
fellow Orthodox Christian Slavs in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Bulgarian President Petar Stoyanov visited the area where the
missile hit and demanded an explanation. However, the Bulgarians
want more than assurances from NATO that it will look into the
accident. Bulgarian Foreign Minister Nadezhda Mihailova said NATO
should give his government sophisticated radar equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Bulgarians are especially worried about NATO missiles hitting
the Kosloduy nuclear power plant, which sits on the Danube River in
the north of the country, less than 100 miles from the Serbian
border.
</P>
<P>
   Bulgarian officials say that the air corridor they want
Parliament to approve would exclude Sofia and the area around the
power plant.
</P>
</TEXT>
