u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-SOCIETY-BOS &LR;      04-29 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-SOCIETY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOOTINGS SYMPTOM OF AMERICAN `DISEASE,' CANADIANS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The news from Taber, Alberta was undeniably shocking:
a 14-year-old dropout, armed with a .22 caliber rifle, strode into
W. R. Myers High School and allegedly shot down two former
classmates, killing one and seriously wounding the other.
</P>
<P>
   To many Canadians, the Wednesday afternoon gunfire that
shattered the tranquility of the prairie town that bills itself
``Corn Capital of Canada'' seemed not just a horrific and
inexplicable crime, but a symptom of proximity to the United States
-- as if violence was a virus borne north by Americans.
</P>
<P>
   CBC newscaster Alison Smith, anchoring the national network's
late night news, personified that notion in the opening words of
her report: ``A uniquely American tragedy has visited Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   That has been the refrain ever since, not only from news
analysts but from the stunned townspeople at the center of a
tragedy still unfurling as Taber mourns the death of Jason Lang,
17. The other victim, Shane Christmas, also 17, remains in serious
condition with a stomach wound.
</P>
<P>
   Their alleged assailant, described as a ninth grader who'd
stopped attending classes at the school, was charged Thursday with
first-degree murder and attempted murder. But many seemed to
believe that the real culprit was the violence that pervades
American culture, from main streets to movie screens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting like America, where nowhere is safe,'' said Jim
Cannady, father of a student at the high school. ``That's the sad
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   For as long as there has been a United States, Canadians have
been appalled by it. There is nothing more constant in Canadian
history than fear that this country might slide into some sort of
American abyss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go back a hundred years, and you'll hear the same theme _
Canada is in danger of becoming more violent, more unruly, like the
Americans,'' said Anthony N. Doob, professor of criminology at the
University of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we live next door to this huge and powerful nation,
it's the obvious place to blame,'' he said. ``Of course, lighting
can strike anywhere. Every time there's a violent crime in Canada
doesn't mean were becoming `just like' the US. It means we have
crime, like any society. But making that US connection tends to be
the way Canadians try to make sense of the senseless.''
</P>
<P>
   The shootings in Taber appeared at least in part a copycat crime
of last week's massacre at Columbine High School in Littleton,
Colo. That rampage, which received huge media attention north of
the border, was seen by many anguished Canadians as a portent for
their own society.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the United States is, we are on the way to becoming,''
wrote columnist Anne Giardini in the National Post, a Toronto-based
newspaper. ``We watch their bullet-riddled television and their
blood-spattered movies.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, for all the fear and trepidation, Canada remains a far
more peaceful and civil society than the United States, with a
violent crime rate barely a quarter that of its neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   The slaying at W.R. Myers High School marked the first killing
at a Canadian high school in at least two decades, and _ unlike the
shootings in Colorado _ appeared the crazed act of an alienated
loner, not a sinister plot. The 14-year-old suspect earlier this
year stopped attending classes because of ``personality problems,''
according to townspeople.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian police are forbidden by law from releasing the names of
minors accused of crime. The boy was described as tempermental,
unpopular and the butt of teasing from classmates.
</P>
<P>
   Garbed in a blue three-quarter-length parka, possibly in
imitation of the ``black trenchcoat'' killers in Colorado, he
entered a classroom just after lunch hour, briefly pointed a rifle
at a female teacher while shouting ``this is no joke,'' then strode
out to a hallway and fired four bullets into Lang and Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether he chose the victims or shot them at
random. Lang and Christmas were described as best friends. Both
were 11th graders, athletic and popular with other students at the
school, which has an enrollment of 440.
</P>
<P>
   ``May God have mercy on this broken society and all the hurting
people in it,'' said Rev. Dale Lang, father of the dead boy and
pastor at St. Theodore's Anglican Church. ``We grieve for our son,
for this community, and for a 14-year-old boy who killed so
senselessly.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of Canada was in grief, as flags were flown at half-staff
and experts on everything from child psychology to gun control
sought to explain the tragedy. Time and again, US violence _ both
real violence and that portrayed in movies and on television _ was
cited as a threat to Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canadians know we're tied into the United States in a lot of
ways, and are convinced American social diseases could cross the
border,'' said Conrad Winn of the Toronto polling firm COMPAS Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's tradition of fairly stringent gun control dates to the
late 1800s, when the Mounties would confiscate the six-shooters of
American rowdies seeking to enter Western settlements. Last year, a
new law was passed that tightened regulations further, making
private possession of handguns illegal in nearly all cases, and
strictly licensing rifles and shotguns.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there 7 million guns in private hands in Canada, which
has a population of 30 million. That compares to more than 230
million firearms owned by Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gun ownership here is a privilege, not a right,'' said
Chantale Breton, a spokeswoman for the Coalition for Gun Control.
``We aren't the country next door, we haven't reached that point,
but Canadians can't be complacent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
