</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-DRUGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TRIALS SHOW CANCER-SHRINKING DRUGS' POWER, RESEARCHER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It is still only animal research, but four new
tumor-starving drugs _ including the highly touted endostatin and
angiostatin _ have shrunk harder-to-treat and more human-like
cancers than any they have been tested against to date.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another step closer to the situation'' for humans,
said Dr. Judah Folkman, the Harvard and Children's Hospital
scientist and a pioneer in the discovery of compounds called
angiogenesis inhibitors that can choke off tumors' critical blood
supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' he added, ``this is also the first demonstration that
these compounds may be valuable in cancer prevention'' as well as
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   A paper of which Folkman is an author in the current issue of
the journal Science reports that the drugs showed they could
prevent premalignant cells from escalating to cancer. They also
limited the growth of small but mature cancer cells, and shrank
large, terminal tumors by up to 71 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can probably do even better with different `cocktails' of
angiogenesis inhibitors,'' said Douglas Hanahan, a biochemist at
the University of California in San Francisco and lead author on
the paper. ``The major question is whether this translates into
human cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Angiogenesis inhibitors do not attack tumors directly. Instead,
they target the network of tiny blood vessels that tumors need to
grow and spread to other parts of the body. The inhibitors block or
destroy this vascular life-support system, starving the tumor of
oxygen and nutrients and halting the cancer's growth.
</P>
<P>
   A key advantage of angiogenesis-blocking drugs is their much
lower toxicity than conventional cancer drugs that attack tumor
cells but also unavoidably kill normal cells.
</P>
<P>
   The Science report describes experiments carried out by Hanahan,
Folkman, and others in which four angiogenesis inhibitors were
given to mice that had been made highly cancer-prone by adding a
cancer-causing oncogene to their genetic blueprints.
</P>
<P>
   The added oncogene goaded normal pancreatic cells into
uncontrolled growth, going through a number of stages leading to
tumors that grew until they eventually killed the mice.
</P>
<P>
   This is much more like the development of human cancer than the
mouse ``models'' of cancer usually used to test new drugs. In these
models, scientists inject cells from existing mouse tumors under
the skin of other mice. These transplanted cells form easy-to-see
lumps that become growing tumors.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't die of lumps injected under the skin,'' noted
Hanahan, a longtime collaborator with Folkman. The tumors caused by
the oncogene, he said, are ``a very tough model to treat, even
harder than a human cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   The experiments are the first in which researchers gave
angiogenesis inhibitors at three distinct stages in the development
of cancer, to find out whether they were equally effective in
early, middle and late stages of the disease. In past experiments
the drugs were given only after the animals had developed large,
mature tumors.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the drugs, endostatin and angiostatin, are awaiting their
first tests in human patients. The National Cancer Institute in
collaboration with EntreMed, Inc., a Maryland biotech company that
has licensed the drugs from Children's Hospital, is preparing for
initial safety tests of endostatin in humans later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Two centers have been selected for the initial tests. They are
the University of Wisconsin in Madison and the M.D. Anderson Cancer
Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The other two inhibitors tested in the mice were AGM-1470 and
BB-94, angiogenesis inhibitors less potent than endostatin and
angiostatin. They are already in early human testing.
</P>
<P>
   In the prevention part of the study, BB-94 and a combination of
angiostatin and endostatin prevented 50 to 60 percent of abnormal,
precancerous cells from going on to outright cancer. The inhibitors
did this, the scientists believe, by shutting down the ``angiogenic
switch'' _ the sending of signals by tumor cells to nearby blood
vessels that results in the formation of new, tiny vessels to
supply the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   All four inhibitors, when given to 10-week-old mice that had
small tumors, shut down angiogenesis and reduced tumor growth by 60
to 88 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And in a test of their ability to shrink advanced tumors,
AGM-1470 and a combination of angiostatin and endostatin reduced
the tumors by up to 71 percent and extended the animals' life by
two weeks or more.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the inhibitors worked differently at different
stages of the cancer. For instance, endostatin alone strongly
prevented precancers cells from becoming malignant, but was less
effective in the advanced tumors.
</P>
<P>
   This finding was a surprise. One result may be that various
angiogenesis inhibitors will be ``fine-tuned'' to attack cancer at
different stages in its development, Hanahan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
