<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8458 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARS-PLATES-BOS &LR;      04-29 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARS-PLATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHIFTS IN MARS' CRUST SIMILAR TO EARTH'S, RESEARCHERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In what is being hailed as potentially the most important
discovery in decades about Earth's sister planet Mars, scientists
have found that the red planet probably experienced a process
similar to ``plate tectonics'' on Earth, with large sections of the
planet's crust spreading apart over time.
</P>
<P>
   No other world besides Earth itself has shown evidence of this
process, which some scientists say may have been essential for the
development and evolution of life on this planet. Even on Earth,
the existence of this process involving the movement of huge
``plates'' of the planet's crust was only discovered about three
decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's spectacular,'' said planetary scientist Bruce
Jakosky of the University of Colorado, who was not involved in the
new discovery. ``I can't overstate how important a result this
is.''
</P>
<P>
   The discovery is important for several reasons, scientists said.
First, the environment around the ridges where tectonic plates form
on Earth are now thought to be one of the likeliest places for the
origins of life here, and thus the existence of such environments
on Mars raises the likelihood that life may have begun there as
well. In addition, the process could drastically revise scientists'
understanding of the whole evolution of the Martian surface, and in
the process provide new clues about what could happen to Earth in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   The new findings came from instruments aboard the Mars Global
Surveyor spacecraft, which has been orbiting Mars since Sept. 1997.
In an extraordinarily lucky break, the data that produced the new
findings might never have been obtained if not for changes in the
spacecraft's orbit that were made as a result of damage to one of
its solar panels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was mind-blowing, really,'' said Jack Connerney of the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration's Goddard Space
Flight Center, who led one of two teams publishing the new findings
in the current issue of the journal Science. ``We had no idea we'd
see anything of this magnitude.'' Another team led by Mario Acuna
published an accompanying paper on the new findings.
</P>
<P>
   What the spacecraft revealed was a series of parallel stripes of
strongly magnetized regions in the planet's crust, some of them
extending for more than 1,200 miles across the surface. The bands
alternated in their north and south magnetic orientation, just as
bands of new crust that form beneath Earth's oceans do.
</P>
<P>
   It was the discovery of just such a pattern of alternate
magnetic strips on Earth's seafloor that provided the first
convincing evidence for the theory of plate tectonics on Earth in
the 1960s, and led to a revolution in geologists' understanding of
this planet.
</P>
<P>
   The magnetic strips on Earth occur along mid-ocean ridges where
the molten rock deep below, called magma, welled up through cracks
in the thin crust. As it cooled and solidified, crystals within the
rock lined up with the Earth's magnetic field. Since Earth's
magnetic field reverses itself unpredictably a few times every
million years, as new crust forms it records the alternating
sequence of the planet's magnetism like strips on a magnetic tape.
</P>
<P>
   The magnetized strips on Mars are broader and more intense than
those on Earth, which may imply that Mars once had a stronger
magnetic field than Earth, though it appears to have none at all at
present, the scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists expressed caution about this interpretation of
the new Mars findings, saying that there are significant
differences from the signs of plate tectonics found on Earth. Vicki
Hansen, a geologist at Sountern Methodist University in Dallas,
said that it may be premature to describe this as a process of
plate tectonics, because the dynamics of the Martian surface may
prove to be very different from those on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   But she agreed that the findings provide exciting new evidence
about Martian geology, and imply that there is ``certainly
something in terms of recycling of the crust'' on Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Sleep, a planetary scientist at Stanford University, said
the new results fit in very well with a theory he published five
years ago, suggesting that Mars had indeed experienced a form of
plate tectonics. Sleep said in an interview Thursday that with more
detailed data from Mars, it should be possible to prove the
existence and extent of tectonics there conclusively.
</P>
<P>
   If confirmed, tectonics on Mars ``shows that early Mars was even
more Earth-like than we thought it was. All the biological
conditions that existed on Earth'' at the time when life originated
here ``would have existed on Mars,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If Mars once had life, he said, ``it raises the probability that
it's still inhabited, because once microorganisms get onto
something, they're very hard to get rid of.''
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of these strips on Mars is ``arguably the biggest
discovery about Mars in many, many years,'' said Stephen Maran, an
astronomer at the Goddard Space Flight Center and spokesman for the
American Astronomical Society.
</P>
<P>
   Because Mars is smaller and therefore evolves faster, seeing
what happened there may be like observing a scale model of Earth in
order to learn about our own future, Maran said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
