<SLUG> BC-FLAG-AMENDMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMENDMENT BANNING FLAG BURNING MOVES CLOSER TO VICTORY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Proponents of a constitutional amendment to ban
flag burning appear closer to victory this year because of changes
in the Senate where the measure has been buried in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Judiciary Committee approved the amendment 11-7
Thursday, paving the way for possible full Senate consideration
before Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional amendment, which requires a two-thirds vote
in both chambers, has easily passed the House in past years but
fell three votes short in the Senate the last time it was
considered in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But last November's elections have brought in several new
senators who may tip the balance in favor of the flag-burning
measure, proponents say.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year it looks like the amendment is on the fast track to
consideration and passage,'' said Steve Thomas, a spokesman for the
American Legion, which has lobbied for the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas noted that two Republican senators elected in November,
Peter Fitzgerald of Illinois and George Voinovich of Ohio, are
committed to voting for the amendment. They replaced two Democrats
who had opposed the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., has indicated that
he would like to have a vote on the measure before Memorial Day. If
it passes both chambers the amendment would still require
ratification by three-fourths of the states before being added to
the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers predict the Senate vote could be close and may be
determined by two Democrats from North Dakota, Kent Conrad and
Byron Dorgan who had voted against the amendment before but now are
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   As in the past, the debate over flag burning has aroused
considerable passion on both sides. Proponents have pointed to the
flag as symbol of the nation's dearest values.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents, meanwhile, say the amendment violates the right to
freedom of speech. They have argued that cases of flag burning have
been highly exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have appealed to patriotism and brought in American
heroes to make their case.
</P>
<P>
   This week, former Ohio Sen. John Glenn, the astronaut who last
year became the oldest American to go up in space, returned to the
Senate to argue against the flag-burning amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, a Democrat, told the Judiciary Committee that ``it would
be a hollow victory to protect the symbol of our country while
chipping away at the freedom it represents.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Sen. John McCain, a former prisoner of war in Vietnam,
argued for the flag-burning ban and cited the case of a fellow POW
to make his point.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, R-Ariz., related how the prisoner, Mike Christian, was
severely beaten for hiding an American flag, stitched in his shirt,
and pulling it out daily for a secret recitation of the Pledge of
Allegiance. After the beating and destruction of the flag,
Christian stitched another one, McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``American blood has been shed all over the world for the
American flag ... and I believe it deserves respect,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican senator, Chuck Hagel of Nebraska, said that ban
on flag burning could even stem the cultural ills that led to the
high school shootings in the Denver suburb of Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our cultural problems today, and yes, Littleton,
Colo., fits in that'' are the result of ``lack of respect for
things bigger than ourselves,'' said Hagel. The flag, he said ``is
a symbol in itself of our values.''
</P>
<P>
   But the ranking Democrat on the Judiciary Committee, Sen.
Patrick Leahy responded that flag burning is not a major problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republic is not in danger. There is no crisis of state,
much less a crisis that demands the first-ever cutback on American
civil liberties,'' said the Vermont lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Leahy said that the Congressional Research Service had uncovered
only 43 flag incidents in the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Far more people have testified about flag burning over the
last 10 years than have actually burned a flag,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-word amendment would authorize Congress to prohibit the
physical desecration of the flag, but does not spell out how the
states or federal government would carry out such a ban.
</P>
<P>
   The push to amend the Constitution was prompted by a 1989
Supreme Court decision striking down a flag-burning conviction in
Texas. In that case, Houston resident Gregory Lee Johnson, a member
of the Revolutionary Youth Brigade, was sentenced to year in jail
and fined $2,000 for burning a flag in downtown Dallas during the
1984 Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the majority in the 5-4 case, Justice William
Brennan wrote, ``we do not consecrate the flag by punishing its
desecration, for in doing so we dilute the freedom that this
cherished emblem represents.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
