<SLUG> BC-NH-TAX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.H. LAWMAKERS RELUCTANTLY OK EDUCATION TAX BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ Even as one supporter called it ``manure,'' New
Hampshire Thursday finally enacted a measure to fund its public
schools, almost a full month after a court-ordered deadline.
</P>
<P>
   After bringing the state to the brink of fiscal chaos, the New
Hampshire Legislature adopted an $825 million patchwork of taxes
Thursday, which Gov. Jeanne Shaheen immediately signed into law.
</P>
<P>
   The last-minute action averts a crisis at town halls throughout
the state, allowing local governments to collect taxes, keeping
schools open for business and preventing mass layoffs of teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, amid the relief in the capital, there was the strong
sense that the law, the product of many months of bitter debate in
a state where taxes are anathema, was at best a temporary fix.
Virtually every lawmaker found something to hate about it. The
taxes themselves will certainly bring public protest, especially in
the property rich towns that will be hardest hit.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most immediate threat, though, was the risk that
education advocates will challenge the bill in court. They argue
that $825 million in new money for schools is not enough to provide
an adequate education for all students, and that the money will not
be distributed fairly.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Connair, chairman of the Claremont Lawsuit Coalition, which
initiated the original suit against the state, said a new court
challenge is likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is lacking in Concord are things called spine and courage
and leadership - in the House, the Senate and the governor's
chair,'' said Connair.
</P>
<P>
   But Shaheen, who has alienated many Democrats with her refusal
to end the crisis by agreeing to an income tax, greeted the
House-Senate compromise with praise and a call for reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all came to this issue from different perspectives and with
different ideas about how best to solve the problem,'' she said.
``We have all been called upon to reach past our differences and
find common ground. With this school funding plan, we together
recognize our responsibility to ensure that every child in New
Hampshire has an excellent education.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Legislature must return to the school funding
issue because of a gaping hole in its plan. While lawmakers used
property taxes, business taxes and other revenue streams to fund
the plan, revenues still fell at least $42 million short. All
agreed that they would have to return to find another way to come
up with the rest of the money.
</P>
<P>
   This state's drama over schools and taxes began 10 years ago
when Connair and the people of Claremont, Allenstown, Franklin,
Lisbon, and Pittsfield went to court to demand relief and protest
what they said were oppressive property tax rates that barely
raised enough cash to properly educate their children.
</P>
<P>
   After years of legal and political wrangling, the state Supreme
Court finally issued an ultimatum: find a new way to fund schools
by April 1. After that date, it would be unconstitutional to
collect the local property taxes that keep the schools going. With
no solution, the schools would close at the end of this academic
year.
</P>
<P>
   For a state whose identity is built in part on the absence of a
broad-based state tax, the choice could not have been more
difficult. Lawmakers were faced with the possibility of breaking
with two centuries of tradition and instituting an income tax or
cobbling together the money some other way. How best to move past
the crisis, and what the solution will mean for the future, have
been the state's all-consuming questions this year.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, the pro-income tax forces were dealt a lethal blow as
Shaheen stood by her pledge to never approve an income tax. That
meant lawmakers had to duke it out over other methods of raising
money. Left on the cutting room floor after weeks of negotiations
were state-sponsored video gaming and an entertainment tax on movie
tickets, ski lift tickets and fitness club memberships.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, lawmakers held their noses Thursday and approved the
plan, even as they complained the compromise, with its statewide
property tax, business taxes and cigarette tax increase, was
fraught with problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bad bill, but I'm going to vote for it,'' said
Senator Mark D. Fernald, a Democrat from Sharon, in a comment
typical of the session.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Debora B. Pignatelli, the Nashua Democrat, compared the
conference report to manure, saying she has never seen sludge tied
up in such a pretty package.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to give my very reluctant support to this,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was willing to go along in order to get along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just not that desperate at this time,'' said Senator
Edward M. Gordon, a Republican from Bristol, after listening to his
colleagues complain and then promise to vote yes.
</P>
<P>
   And Senator Burton J. Cohen, the Newcastle Democrat, said he was
pleased that the measure would temporarily end the state's crisis.
But he said it is unfair to take away money from some towns in
order to help other towns, and he said the package would not
provide any property tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Portsmouth is not a wealthy town, yet it is becoming a donor
town,'' Cohen said. ``I don't like going down that path.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approved the conference report by 16 to 8, then sent
it to the House, which approved it 204 to 154.
</P>
<P>
   While lawmakers spent the day complaining, their action brought
relief to officials in the towns and cities around the state who
had been left hanging for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they had to go forward, they had no choice,'' said
Rhona Charbonneau, a Hillsborough County Commissioner and Hudson
Selectmen who came to the State House to watch the debate. ``It's
getting late.''
</P>
<P>
   Charbonneau said she had hoped the counties could have received
some of the national tobacco settlement money, which is instead
being used for funding the schools. But she said it was more
important to make sure that teachers don't receive pink lay-off
slips.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Charbonneau was not celebrating. ``Claremont may not be
happy,'' she said, ``and they could sue us once again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 1930EDT &QL; 
