u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAGES-SLOW-BOS &LR;      04-29 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAGES-SLOW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US WAGE INCREASES SLOW IN FIRST QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   American workers' wages during the first quarter rose at their
slowest pace since the US Labor Department began keeping track of
them 17 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The fresh evidence of low inflation means there is little
pressure on the Federal Reserve to boost interest rates in the near
future, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the new data may be an aberration, economists were
surprised by such weakness in the government's index of wage and
benefit costs for employers at a time when unemployment is at its
lowest since Richard M. Nixon was president. The jobless rate was
4.2 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, low unemployment puts workers' skills in greater
demand, giving employees more leverage to negotiate pay raises.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what is puzzling all of us,'' said Suzanne Rizzo, an
economist at Maria Fiorini Ramirez Inc. in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The employment-cost index _ a broad measure of wage, salary and
benefit costs for employers _ edged up 0.4 percent from January
through March. That is less than half the quarterly increases over
the past two years, which ranged from 0.7 to 1.0 percent each
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, during strong periods of economic growth, ``wage
pressures, particularly with the tight labor market, will tend to
increase,'' explained Walter Marshall, senior economist for the
department's Bureau of Labor Statistics. ``That has not actually
occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, economists said, there is good reason wages haven't
risen: workers' buying power has not been eroded by inflation, so
pressure to raise wages hasn't been as strong as might be expected.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer price index rose less than 2 percent over the past
year, as competition from low-cost, imported goods makes it
difficult for US producers to raise their prices.
</P>
<P>
   During the same period, the employment cost index rose 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Wages were among several pieces of new data released Thursday by
the federal government that indicate economic expansion, well into
its eighth year, is in fine form.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department reported new single-family home sales
rose 2.1 percent in March, reversing a 2 percent decline in April.
And initial claims for jobless benefits fell a larger-than-expected
20,000 last week, after declining by 5,000 in the prior week.
</P>
<P>
   A breakdown of the government's report on employment costs
showed wages and salaries increased 0.5 percent in the first
quarter. The cost of benefits rose 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wages and salaries have been doing well,'' said Ezra
Greenberg, a senior US economist for Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI of
Lexington, Mass. He said yearly wages and salaries, adjusted for
inflation, are at a record $29,570 average per worker and have been
setting records since mid-1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story about why compensation costs haven't increased,'' he
said, ``has a lot to do with benefit costs staying in line and also
a lot of competition that is not allowing'' companies to pass price
increases to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The wage index's low level was also driven by declines in three
industries: wholesale trade, financial services and transportation.
</P>
<P>
   But the benefit to consumers and workers of low inflation may be
running its course.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are ahead,'' said Rizzo. And with employers struggling
to fill many positions, getting a job is much easier these days.
``Workers are in a seller's market.''
</P>
<P>
   But she noted that inflation has crept up. After bottoming out
in 1998 at 1.4 percent annually, it is now running at about 1.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
   As rising prices for oil and gas work their way into the costs
of goods, inflation is expected to exceed 2 percent by the end of
this year, Rizzo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
