<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8475 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-0430-     04-29 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-0430-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE VOTES ON WAR LEAVE BOTH SIDES DISSATISFIED
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (i) international categories
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the day after the House of Representatives
deadlocked on the air war in the Balkans, all sides were attempting
to make the best of the muddled outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Clinton administration pledged Thursday that the
213-213 vote on the air war would not effect their determination in
conducting the bombing campaign, now in its fifth week.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders blamed Republicans for stirring up opposition
to the president and charged that the GOP with failing to support
U.S. forces making daily bombing runs over Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans pointed to the 26 Democrats who voted against the
air war. And in yet one more mixed signal, the Republican-led House
Appropriations Committee approved $12.9 billion in emergency
funding, twice as much as the president sought, for the air war
that the House on Wednesday had refused to support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this was a clear message in any way, shape, or
form,'' said White House press secretary Joe Lockhart, brushing off
the series of votes that included a requirement that President
Clinton obtain authorization from Congress before using ground
troops against Yugoslavia. In another vote, the House refused to
order him to bring U.S. forces home.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that the public supports the campaign -- although he
added he knew of no White House polls on the subject -- Lockhart
said, ``We're going to continue to persevere.''
</P>
<P>
   At the State Department, spokesman James Rubin poked fun at the
lawmakers to-ing and fro-ing. ``As far as I can tell, they chose
not to put themselves in first gear, not to put themselves in
second gear, nor would they agree on putting themselves in
reverse.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin added that with the House ``idling in neutral with such a
</P>
<P>
   muddled message'' that he was ``confident'' that Yugoslavian
President Slobodan Milosevic would take no comfort from it.
</P>
<P>
   Only Defense Secretary William Cohen expressed some concern,
calling the lack of full support from the House
``counterproductive'' as he was reaffirming that the war would
continue.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, the failure to back the air war surprised even
Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., who had voted to support it. He
blamed the president's failure to explain his position to Congress,
a theme the speaker has frequently voiced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it behooves the president to come to the Congress and
lay out what his plan is, why we are there, and what his plan is,
and what our end game on this thing is,'' he said Thursday,
pointing to doubts within both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders turned the blame on Republicans, charging
that some sought to embarrass the president for political reasons.
House Minority leader Richard Gephardt of Missouri blamed
``right-wing extremists.''
</P>
<P>
   That brought a sharp response from House Majority Whip Tom
Delay, R-Texas, a passionate foe of the air war. Delay denied he
had attempted to make partisan gains from the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Delay pointed to the Democrats who voted against the air war.
``I am disappointed that Mr. Gephardt, as a leader of his party,
would call into question the motives of any member of the House,
particularly in the face of such a serious international crisis,''
Delay said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may be able to influence Republican votes from time to time,
but
</P>
<P>
   unfortunately I do not have the power to produce 26 Democrat
'No' votes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among those voting ``No'' were some lawmakers who have been
staunch Clinton backers, but who are raising questions about the
military operations in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lloyd Doggett, D-Texas, explained his vote by saying he
wanted to send a message that ``no president should entangle us in
offensive, non-emergency military operations abroad without prior
approval by the Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. Cynthia McKinney, D-Ga., who also voted against the air
war, joined two Democratic colleagues in a ``teach-in'' for a
diplomatic solution. ``Our bombing campaign has only resulted in
the displacement of millions of Kosovars and the destruction of
some buildings, but no peace,'' she said Thursday on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats reacted bitterly to the upset votes in the
House. Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash., complained that the House was
abandoning the troops. But then, noting that Congress was planning
to pass funding for the Balkan air war that the House has just
repudiated, McDermott said he felt as if he were in Alice's
``Wonderland.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This place is getting curiouser and curiouser,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
