<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8476 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      04-29 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS COUNTING ON YOUNG LEGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Experience or young legs?
</P>
<P>
   Youthful exuberance or veteran wisdom?
</P>
<P>
   It has come down to three games between the Bruins and Carolina
Hurricanes. What will win out? The Hurricanes have players who have
been around _ Ray Sheppard, Kevin Dineen, Paul Coffey, Glen Wesley,
Gary Roberts, Martin Gelinas.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have the youngbloods of the NHL _ Joe Thornton,
Sergei Samsonov, Anson Carter, Jason Allison, Kyle McLaren.
</P>
<P>
   It appears young legs could be the difference in Game 7, and if
that's the case, Boston will have the edge.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Bruins noticed it midway through the third period of
Wednesday's Game 4 on Steve Heinze's goal that gave Boston a 3-1
lead. Thornton won his battle behind the net, Carter then outdueled
center Jeff O'Neill and fired the puck to Heinze, who skated
between two Hurricanes and made a perfect shot into the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't see it in the first two games but I think you're
seeing it now, the young legs are starting to come through,'' said
Carter, who sensed the Hurricanes were a little tired late in Game
4. ``When the third period comes around, we're catching our second
wind a little bit. We're trying to take advantage of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter and other Bruins believe that, with rare exception, they
have shined the most in the third period. That was certainly true
in the last game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because of the mental toughness in this room and also
the tough practices we have,'' said Carter. ``I think we're one of
the best-conditioned teams in the National Hockey League, if not
the best. That's why we play so well in the third period, because
our practices are so tough. Once the games come, it's a breeze, to
tell you the truth, because nothing is like getting skated by
(assistant coaches Jacques Laperriere and Bob Francis).''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are also doing a better job of winning the one-on-one
battles along the boards, an aspect they have lacked at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those parts have been missing sometimes in this series, the
little plays behind the net, the battles in the corners, but we are
starting to wear them down as the series goes on,'' said Carter.
``It showed in those plays behind the net. In Game 1, it was a
little bit tougher to generate scoring chances because they were
playing intense hockey. They were on top of their game and well
rested. As the series goes on, all the crashing and banging they're
doing and we're doing, I think it's taking its toll a little bit on
their hockey club.''
</P>
<P>
   As this series progresses, it's going to come down to which team
can best utilize its most substantial assets. In the case of
Carolina, it's the craftiness and opportunistic nature of players
such as Sheppard. For Boston, it's a matter of having more in the
tank at the end of the marathon.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd think it'd be the other way around, legs would win Game
1 and experience would win Game 7,'' said Carter. ``During last
year's playoffs, we learned that as the series wore on, the Caps
wore down. They got a couple of lucky breaks in the end and that's
what beat us. We're going to wear teams down. We're going to keep
coming at you, no matter who we're playing against or who's in the
lineup, whether it's Heinzey coming off the bench or Landon Wilson,
who came up from Providence and did a great job for us. Or Mattias
Timander. We're going to keep coming at you.''
</P>
<P>
   When Carter and Allison arrived in Boston, they went from a team
that was fighting for a playoff spot (Washington) to a team that
had long been eliminated from playoff contention. As tense and
difficult as that was, Carter said he learned just how badly he
didn't want to go through it again. Last season, he went through a
different experience when he played in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I'd heard talk about playoffs but you don't really
know until you live it and experience it,'' he said. ``Now we have
the experience to fall back on. I've been through this before, you
know what to expect and when game time comes around, it's time to
execute.''
</P>
<P>
   In the dressing room, there was a palpable difference between
the atmosphere after Game 3, when you could cut the tension and
uncertainty with a knife, and Game 4, where it was still very
business-like but much more lighthearted and confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never thought this series was going to be a short series,
by any stretch of the imagination,'' said Carter. ``You go down,
2-1, and people start panicking, asking what's wrong with the
Bruins? I think the guys in this locker room know that it was going
to be a long series. But psychologically we're in better spirits
than we were a couple of days ago being down in the series.
(Wednesday's) game breathed a lot of life into our organization and
our team as well. I think we came out and beat them pretty
convincingly. We knew we could score goals against these guys and
there are chinks in their armor. We think we might have put a few
questions in their mind also. We have a lot of character in this
room. We don't panic and it starts at the top (with coach Pat
Burns).''
</P>
<P>
   Game 5 is Friday night in Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Youth or experience? We'll soon know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 1934EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
