<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYOFFS ARE A WHOLE NEW HOCKEY GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- You want to know what's great about the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot to like, but one thing is that you never know
where the intrigue will come from. Suppose, for example, someone
had said to you _ and by you I mean Mr. Casual, not the sort of
person who irons his Neely jersey before heading to the game _ that
the burning question entering Game 5 of this Bruins-Hurricane
series would be, ``Will Landon Wilson be able to play?'' Your first
reaction, I am sure, would be, ``Who the (naughty word) is Landon
Wilson?''
</P>
<P>
   Landon Wilson is a 24-year-old 200-pound right winger whose time
may have come. Either that, or he is the winner of the 1999 Steve
Kuberski Award. Bear with me. Somewhat forgotten now, but very much
the topic du jour in a 1972 Celtics series with the Atlanta Hawks,
was a startling performance by the then-24-year-old, 6-foot-8 inch
forward, who picked that series to play the best basketball he had
ever played, or ever would play.
</P>
<P>
   No one on the Atlanta side spent much time worrying about Steve
Kuberski before that first-round series began. He had averaged 6
points a game during the regular season. So what was he doing
getting 15 points and 13 rebounds in 21 minutes in Game 1, or 19
points in Game 3, or 20 points and 10 rebounds in Game 5, or 22
points in 21 minutes of the series-clinching Game 6?
</P>
<P>
   It remains a mystery to this day.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as it was over, Steve Kuberski went right back to being
Steve Kuberski. He was no factor in the following series against
the Knicks and the most points he averaged during the remainder of
his eight-year NBA career was 5.4 in 1975-76.
</P>
<P>
   But for a little more than a week in 1972 he was Bailey Howell.
Now the question before the Bruins is this: Do we have, in Landon
Wilson, a bruising, effective, rock-'em, sock-'em winger we can
count on to neutralize the likes of Keith Primeau for, oh, the next
10 years, or do we have someone who has been hit with a classic
case of Playoff Mania, and who will go back to being a skating
Steve Kuberski as soon as this series with Carolina is over?
</P>
<P>
   The future is the future, however. For Landon Wilson did not get
out of Tuesday night's Game 4 of this very even confrontation with
the expatriate Hartford Whalers unscathed. Just when he was
developing a true cult following in the aftermath of both a
ferocious open-ice hit on the menacing Mr. Primeau and a key goal,
he was sent to the bench in great pain, having sustained a hit to
his left shoulder, coutesy of one Steven Halko, and will be
sidelined for at least the rest of the series. It is safe to say
that Landon Wilson will be missed, and isn't that interesting to
say about a guy who spent most of the season in Providence and who
didn't join the big club to stay until March 4? In a
tight-checking, close-cornered series he has given the Bruins their
most prominent physical presence. ``He's been matching their hits
with his size,'' says goalie Byron Dafoe. Wilson is playing the way
his backers have always thought he would, or, at least, could. If
the Bruins gone on to lose this series, his absence would be cited
as a determining factor. It's all so very playoffy.
</P>
<P>
   And let me assure you that it is the playoffs. There is even
life in the Fleet, and how about that?
</P>
<P>
   Pat Burns, a noted hard marker, has gone on record as being very
impressed with the crowd support of late, and the players certainly
agree. ``They were phenomenal tonight,'' Dafoe was saying after
Game 4. ``I'm glad we gave them a reason to be good. This was my
first win here in the playoffs. But it was really nice for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe was beaten by a nice Martin Gelinas-Ray Sheppard open- ice
collaboration less than five minutes into the game, but that was it
for the evening. ``I always like to think I'm intense when I'm out
there,'' he explained, ``but my intensity level went up a notch out
there. I was following the play at the other end very closely. I
just felt that after I let that one in, that would be it. When the
playoffs come, you just have to be physically and mentally prepared
for the whole 60.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is happier to be watching playoff hockey than Harry
Sinden. ``I love the playoffs because they're fair,'' he maintains.
``You don't have travel discrepancies. You don't have situations
where you're secure in a playoff spot and the other team is
fighting for its life. Everything is equal. So it often comes down
to superior coaching. Good coaching is very important in the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Filling in the parenthesis here, Harry was clearly trying to lay
a little praise on his coach, who has been dealt a hand that is
heavy on youth. Burns had 12 players 25 or younger among the 18
non-goalies he threw out there against the Hurricanes, and some of
his kids came up very big indeed. It was a nice blend, in fact,
with guys like Don Sweeney and Steve Heinze teaming up with the
likes of Jason Allison, Joe Thornton, and Anson Carter to produce
goals. Throw in the crowd-pleasing empty-netter by veteran Rob
DiMaio, and it turned out to be a very pleasant evening for the
Black and Gold.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, it's the playoffs, all right, which is why you can't avoid
hearing things like, ``It's a three-game series now,'' or ``it
doesn't matter where the games are played,'' and assorted hockey
chestnuts. There is talk about the Bruins now having the momentum
(which will disappear as soon as Carolina gets up, 1-0, Friday
night) and, of course, there will be talk about the need for the
goaltenders to come up big.
</P>
<P>
   In the playoffs it's not just about the stars, but about the
star-crossed. From a guy lucky to be in the lineup for Game 1,
Landon Wilson has gone to being a major factor whose absence will
be a key part of the dialogue. We shouldn't be surprised. The
playoffs always come with a new script.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
