u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-INQUIRY-NYT &LR;      04-29 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZILIAN LEGISLATORS PROBE CENTRAL BANK AND ITS FORMER PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Brazilian lawmakers pressed forward Thursday
with an inquiry into allegations of inside information leaks at the
country's central bank.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers called Francisco Lopes, a Harvard-educated economist
and former central bank president who is at the center of the
inquiry, to testify before a panel of senators for a third time.
</P>
<P>
   Lopes is accused of engineering, perhaps illegally, a bailout of
two banks caught off guard by the central bank's decision to
devalue the currency in January. He is also suspected of receiving
payment in an offshore account for services at a consulting firm he
once owned while employed as a central bank director in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   These accusations have not been substantiated. But Lopes has
refused twice before to testify and was detained by the police
briefly earlier this week for his defiance. It was not clear
Thursday whether he would agree to testify this time.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the uncertainty over Lopes, Brazil's financial markets
are beginning to shrug off the effects of the inquiry, a sign that
it is losing momentum. Less preoccupied with the potential for new
allegations to emerge, the country's currency, the real,
strengthened Thursday to a four-month high of 1.65 to the dollar,
before weakening slightly. Wednesday, the central bank made another
in a series of interest rate cuts because of growing confidence in
the economy. And in recent days Brazilian banks have successfully
sold bonds abroad to foreign investors for the first time since
Russia's economic meltdown last summer suppressed demand for
emerging-market debt securities.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us it appears this investigation is nearing the end,''
said Carlos Castanho, the managing director of Credit Suisse First
Boston Garantia, an investment bank that is one of the largest
traders of Brazilian bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation may still hurt the credibility of President
Fernando Henrique Cardoso's administration, and Finance Minister
Pedro Malan may be called to testify. Malan may be criticized for
his role in the affair because, in Brazil, the president of the
central bank is subordinate to the finance minister. Another
high-ranking official, Budget Minister Pedro Parente, could also be
called to testify since he was deputy finance minister in
mid-January when Lopes bailed out the two institutions, Banco Marka
and Banco Fonte Cindam.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unlikely that the scandal will spread to other members
of the government's elite bureaucracy. The current central bank
president, Arminio Fraga, whose work has been praised by investors,
is considered largely untouchable because at the time of the events
in question he was managing a hedge fund in New York for
multibillionaire investor George Soros.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
