</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP JUDGE IN TURKEY COMES OUT FOR FREE SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Turkey's highest-ranking judge, speaking in
terms rarely if ever used by a senior official here, has surprised
the country by sharply condemning restrictions on freedom of
speech.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Ahmet Necdet Sezer, urged Parliament to repeal a
series of laws and constitutional provisions. The judge also called
for lifting the ban on teaching the Kurdish language, which he said
violated international agreements. The authorities say the ban is
necessary to check the rise of Kurdish nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   Western governments and human rights groups have often urged
Turkey to ease its curbs on free expression, and many Turks appear
to support such changes. But powerful military commanders and
civilian politicians fear that allowing greater freedom of speech
would lead to the spread of separatism, fundamentalism and other
movements that they consider highly dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech this week, Sezer, who is president of the
Constitutional Court, the highest judicial body in Turkey, asserted
that ``people in democratic societies cannot live without human
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   He was speaking to an audience of lawyers and government
employees gathered to celebrate the court's 37th anniversary. Many
of them applauded vigorously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although everyone knows that freedom of thought is vital to
democracy, we have not been able to overcome obstacles that keep us
from establishing it,'' Sezer said. ``Allowing people to hold
opinions is not enough. They must be able to speak freely. The
freedom to express one's thoughts is the basis on which all other
freedoms are built.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turkey should change its constitution and laws to harmonize
itself with universal standards,'' he continued. ``Restrictions on
freedom of speech should be lifted, and our legal codes should be
cleansed. The territory of freedom should be enlarged.''
</P>
<P>
   Sezer, who was appointed to his post last year, called for
changes in laws that he said limited the freedom of political
parties, labor unions and the press. He also urged relaxation of
``anti-terror'' laws, which punish statements deemed to encourage
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is often difficult to tell what behavior is criminal and
what is not,'' he said. ``Laws are blurry and open to
interpretation. As a result, they are applied irregularly, and
justice is more difficult to achieve. We need to eliminate these
problems by legislative action and make our legal framework more
concrete.''
</P>
<P>
   Sezer's speech synthesized many of the complaints that Turkish
intellectuals have been making for years, and the fact that it came
from such a high place has provoked considerable, and sometimes
amazed, discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really a surprise,'' said Nadire Mater, a leading
campaigner for press freedom. ``I completely agree with what he
said. He spoke very clearly and directly. I wish everyone in the
establishment thought the same way, but I'm afraid that's not true.
Maybe now, other people who are responsible for these things will
try to understand and listen.''
</P>
<P>
   But one influential columnist, Oktay Eksi, said he doubted the
reforms Sezer called for would be approved, since in the recent
election campaign ``none of the political parties made any
substantial commitment to freedom of expression.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkey's Constitution, which was written during the period of
military rule in the early 1980s, forbids ``thoughts or opinions
that run counter to Turkish national interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Other laws ban books or articles that ``threaten the internal or
external security of the state,'' undermine ``the national and
spiritual values of society'' or question ``the historical and
moral values of Turkishness.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkish leaders have conceded from time to time that the
country's human rights record is unsatisfactory. At the beginning
of 1998, Mesut Yilmaz, who was then prime minister, pledged that
improving human rights conditions would be his highest priority for
the year. He proposed only modest reforms to Parliament, however,
and even they were not passed.
</P>
<P>
   This year Parliament considered repealing a law banning speech
that ``incites people to enmity and hatred by pointing to class,
racial, confessional or religious differences.'' The debate ended
when military commanders warned that repeal would hinder their
ability to fight religious fundamentalism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
