<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8514 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-KOSOVO-HNS &LR;      04-29 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP ACCUSED OF UNDERMINING CLINTON'S KOSOVO POLICY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Democratic leaders accused Republicans on
Thursday of trying to undermine President Clinton's Kosovo policy
as the Senate canceled consideration of a measure calling for the
use of ground troops if necessary to end the NATO bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee canceled a hearing on a
bipartisan measure offered by Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Joe
Biden, D-Del., that would give Clinton the authority to use
``whatever means necessary,'' including a ground invasion of
Kosovo, to end the campaign as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The measure had been scheduled for debate on the Senate floor as
early as Monday. But a vote on the McCain-Biden bill seemed less
certain after the House voted Wednesday to deny support for the
36-day-old allied air campaign and to require the president to seek
congressional approval before mounting a ground offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than hold a straight up or down vote on the McCain-Biden
measure, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., indicated he
wanted to bring up the measure requiring congressional approval for
ground forces as an alternative to the bipartisan bill.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said the McCain-Biden bill gives Clinton too much freedom
in deciding how to use U.S. forces.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Republican aides said Lott would likely allow a
vote on McCain-Biden next week if he is assured that the Democrats
will not try to block consideration of the House-passed measure.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo.,
accused the Republicans of ``playing politics'' with the lives of
U.S. personnel involved in the NATO operation by pressuring GOP
lawmakers to vote against a resolution of support for the allied
air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   That resolution, offered by the Democratic leadership, was
defeated Wednesday on a vote of 213-213 even though it had the
support of House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution was headed for passage, despite opposition from
26 Democrats, when Rep. Mary Bono, R-Calif., switched her vote at
the last minute from ``yes'' to ``no,'' according to the
Congressional Record.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt and his deputy leader, Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich.,
charged that House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, engaged in
political arm-twisting to get Bono and other Republicans to vote
against the resolution, even after Hastert assured Democrats
members would not be pressured.
</P>
<P>
   In a scathing condemnation of DeLay's tactics, Gephardt and
Bonior all but declared Hastert a pawn of DeLay.
</P>
<P>
   Describing Hastert as ``a nice, good man,'' they nonetheless
suggested that he is incapable of reining in DeLay and other GOP
members, even on important matters ``where the House needs to speak
with one united voice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday was a low point in American foreign policy and the
history of this institution,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the House vote sent ``at best a muddled message, and at
worst a negative message'' to the world about the U.S. commitment
to the NATO operation.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay's office issued a statement calling the claims of
arm-twisting ``absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay blamed the measure's failure on Democratic opposition and
``yet another in a series of Kosovo blunders.''
</P>
<P>
   Delay spokesman Michael Scanlon, however, acknowledged that his
boss did talk with Bono and other members while the vote was in
progress. ``He told her that he thought she ought to vote no,''
Scanlon said. But he added that DeLay ``didn't pressure her or
anyone else'' to change their votes.
</P>
<P>
   The partisan bickering between DeLay and the Democratic leaders
is just one example of the deep divisions in Congress over the
Kosovo conflict, which is threatening to upset the lawmakers' work
on other legislative matters.
</P>
<P>
   Relations have also been strained by Republican efforts to beef
up Clinton's $6.05 billion emergency spending request to finance
the U.S. portion of the NATO operation for the rest of the fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
   The House Appropriations Committee approved a $12.9 billion
spending package Thursday that more than doubled the president's
request and included items that the administration considers
``unrelated'' to the Kosovo conflict, such as a shooting range for
military personnel in Germany and various construction projects.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is marking up a separate bill of its own, but
Republicans may be increasingly sensitive to charges they are
trying to load it up with ``pork barrel'' projects and may produce
a smaller spending measure.
</P>
<P>
   One Senate aide said the final bill the Senate Appropriations
Committee produces ``will probably be more in the neighborhood of
$7 billion.'' Both House and Senate leaders hope to have the
emergency package wrapped up in a final bill by next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said he still believes that Congress can produce a bill
that meets the military's needs for the Kosovo operation without
turning it into a ``wish list'' for defense contractors.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to better assess the president's request and to see
first-hand how the NATO campaign is progressing, House Majority
Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, will lead a congressional delegation of
19 members to the Balkans over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to talk to some of our troops there,'' Armey told Texas
reporters Thursday, adding that the delegation will also have a
chance ``to talk to refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm prepared to have my heart broken in some of those
conversations, but I think it's the sort of thing we need to do,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Armey disputed Gephardt's claims that Republicans are playing
politics with the Kosovo crisis. He said the House votes Wednesday
were simply a matter of trying to make a larger point to the
president that he should consult with Congress before committing
U.S. forces to military action and not seek ``our validation or
repudiation'' later.
</P>
<P>
   Armey's delegation will travel to Ramstein Air Base in Germany,
and then to Albania and Macedonia before returning home late Sunday
through Aviano Air Base in Italy and NATO headquarters in Brussels,
Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, another 10-member congressional delegation
headed by Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., will be going to Vienna to meet
with members of the Russian Duma to discuss ways of resolving the
Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be engaging Russia on Kosovo,'' Weldon said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
