<SLUG> BC-AFC-EARNINGS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AFC reports mixed earnings
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ AFC Enterprises on Thursday reported a loss of
$592,000 in the first quarter, compared to net income of $73,000
for the year-ago quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta restaurant company blamed higher interest expenses,
depreciation and amortization related to its 1998 acquisitions of
Cinnabon International and Seattle Coffee Co.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the company bought 66 Hardee's restaurants last year and
converted them to Popeyes Chicken &AMP; Biscuits stores.
</P>
<P>
   Operating income rose 24 percent to $19.1 million for the
quarter, compared to $15.4 million for the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   AFC is not publicly held, but reports its earnings because it
has public debt.
</P>
<P>
   Systemwide sales at AFC's more than 3,200 restaurants, bakeries
and cafes grew by 24 percent to $478.2 million, up from $383.6
million for the same quarter in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic comparable store sales, a key barometer of a company's
financial health in the retail and restaurant industries, rose 7.5
percent for Churches and 1.8 percent for Popeyes.
</P>
<P>
   International comparable sales fell by 2.4 percent during the
first quarter for all of AFC's operations, primarily because of
continued weaknesses in Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
   Overall international sales _ which includes new stores _ grew
by 16.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think in the second quarter we will continue to see solid
same-store sales growth and strong double-digit sales growth,''
said Chief Financial Officer Gerald Wilkins.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company expects to open 90 new stores in the second
quarter, and has commitments signed for another 200.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
