A8530 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COKE30-COX     04-29 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke chief: Suit wrong but serious
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co. Chairman M. Douglas Ivester told all of
the company's U.S. employees that while the racial discrimination
suit against the beverage giant has ``significant errors of fact,''
he is taking it ``very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have spent time this week meeting with senior
African-American associates of the company to get their insights
and opinions on the circumstances that have led to this serious
litigation,'' Ivester said in an e-mail late Wednesday to nearly
10,000 U.S. employees. ``As has always been the case, their views
are critically important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   It is Ivester's second e-mail on the issue since last week, when
four current and former employees filed a federal suit in Atlanta,
alleging that Coca-Cola discriminates against black employees in
pay, promotions, performance evaluations and terminations. The suit
seeks class-action status so it can represent 1,500 other salaried
African-American employees in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, let me emphasize what I hope and believe is apparent to
everyone associated with Coca-Cola _ our company has always
endeavored to treat our customers, our consumers, our bottlers and,
perhaps most importantly, our employees with fairness, respect, and
dignity,'' Ivester wrote. ``It is because of that background that
the lawsuit is so troubling to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivester said the company does not systematically discriminate
against African-Americans, as te lawsuit alleges, and said the
complaint's factual errors will be addressed when the company files
its legal response.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company has put in place several programs over the
past few years to help identify, train and develop employees ``who
can lead this business forward in the years ahead. A key component
of these efforts is the development of African-American associates.
It is the responsibility of every manager of the company, beginning
with me, to assure that these initiatives take root in our
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   But the lawsuit alleges that contrary initiatives have taken
root through a ``companywide pattern and practice'' of
discrimination. It says that blacks at corporate headquarters are
concentrated in lower pay grades and management positions than
whites and make considerably less money with fewer opportunities
for advancement.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed by employees Motisola Malikha Abdallah,
Gregory Allen Clark and Linda Ingram, and former employee Kimberly
Gray Orton.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs' attorney, Cyrus Mehri, said he had no comment on
Ivester's e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola also had no comment except to say the e-mail speaks
for itself, spokesman Robert Baskin said.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester said he will continue to send out e-mails on the subject
to all U.S. employees as information warrants.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
