<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8531 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CTBMAIN30-COX     04-29 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CTBMAIN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Citizens Trust parent joins publicly traded elite
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole and Susan Harte
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Citizens Bancshares Corp., the parent company of
Citizens Trust Bank CTB Mortgage Services, has joined an exclusive
club of formerly black-owned financial institutions that have gone
public.
</P>
<P>
   The 78-year-old Atlanta-based bank said Thursday it began
trading its stock over the counter last Thursday at $7 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Shares closed Thursday at $7.62 1/2, up 62 1/2 cents. The ticker
symbol is CZBS.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new beginning for us,'' Willard ``Chuck'' Lewis,
chief operating officer, said Thursday. ``Now, we're ready to let
everybody know we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   As if no one knew before. Some of the most celebrated names in
Atlanta's minority business community have been connected to
Citizens Trust Co., which opened on ``Sweet Auburn'' Avenue in
1919.
</P>
<P>
   It was founded with $500,000 in stock by five businessmen led by
Herman E. Perry, owner of the Standard Life Insurance Co., and its
subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Although the bank was born on the eve of the most severe
depression in American history, it survived the 1920s and 1930s
when other financial institutions failed. During the presidency of
L.D. Milton, the company financed the Morris Brown subdivision and
built housing in Mozeley Park, Bankhead and on Hightower Road. It
completed its own 12-story office building.
</P>
<P>
   When Milton retired in 1971, Charles M. Reynolds became
president. He spearheaded the creation of a holding company,
Citizens Bancshares Corp., as parent of the bank. At that point,
the company had $32 million in assets. The year also saw the
purchase of a mortgage brokerage and servicing company.
</P>
<P>
   Owen Funderburg, another executive credited with making the bank
increasingly profitable, became president in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to revitalize neighborhoods and he oversaw the opening
of branches and the installation of automatic teller machines. As
he led the bank into the technological age, it was named 1985 Bank
of the Year by Black Enterprise Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   He retired at age 68 in 1993 and was succeeded by William Gibbs.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Gibbs abruptly resigned just as Citizens Trust
was about to become the fifth-largest black-owned bank in the
nation by merging with First Southern Bancshares of Lithonia.
</P>
<P>
   James E. Young moved from president of First Southern Bancshares
to head the merged company. He said at the time his goal was assets
of $1 billion within a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Assets are about $207 million. The company still calls its Sweet
Auburn location home.
</P>
<P>
   When it chose a market maker, it went to J.C. Bradford, the
market maker for more than 60 community banks in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said the bank went public to enhance the value of
shareholders' stock. He said the company has about 1,343
shareholders, most of whom owned stock before the company went
public.
</P>
<P>
   About 2.2 million shares are outstanding. About 32 percent of
the stock is held by board members and officers.
</P>
<P>
   Those include automobile dealer Gregory Baranco, former chairman
of the board of directors of First Southern and current vice
chairman of the merged companies; and Herman J. Russell, who is
chairman. Lewis said taking the company public ``was not intended
to raise any additional capital at this point'' but ``when there is
a business proposition or deal in the future, we will strongly
consider issuing additional shares.''
</P>
<P>
   The offering ``is microscopic, but it's a move in the right
direction and we're going to see more and more black banks going
public within the next two years,'' said William Cunningham, owner
of Creative Investment Research, a Washington, D.C.-based
investment research firm.
</P>
<P>
   While he praised the move, Cunningham said it raises some
interesting questions about ownership. ``It's not entirely a
minority if you're public, but that's not a big concern because for
the most part the management is still minority and most of the
stock _ 51 percent _ will stay in minority hands. That's a risk
worth taking.''
</P>
<P>
   Several black banks are publicly traded, including Carver
Bancorp Inc., the holding company for Carver Federal Savings Bank
in New York; Broadway Federal Bank in Los Angeles; and Independence
Federal Savings Bank of Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Carver, which began trading on the American Stock
Exchange in October 1994, had 1998 assets of $437.5 million and is
ranked as the top black bank by Black Enterprise Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unusual, particularly for a black bank,'' said William
D. Bradford, dean of the business school at the University of
Washington in Seattle and an expert on black banks. ``Black banks
have not grown in assets as fast as the rest of the banking
industry and there has been a lot of turnover, so the long-term
viability of black banks is still in question even though there
will be some _ like Citizens Trust _ which will survive and
prosper.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradford said a community bank could have several reasons to
enter the public market: it is one way to establish a value for its
stock and it enables shareholders to to buy and sell their stock
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, going public is a way for a company to raise
funds. ``If Citizens is ever bought out or merged, this would be a
means of identifying the value of the stock and make it easier to
negotiate with other institutions about what the price should be,''
Bradford said.
</P>
<P>
   Baunita Greer, an analyst with Cromwell, Miller &AMP; Greer in New
York, expects to see more black-owned banks and companies go
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're realizing that they will have to go to the capital
markets for expansion capital,'' she said. ``This is a very crucial
period.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
