<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERNCO30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    S&AMP;P sounds a warning, lowers Southern's outlook
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Standard &AMP; Poor's corporate credit rating service
sounded a warning Thursday about ``higher business risks'' inherent
in a move by Southern Co. into global power markets and unregulated
U.S. energy businesses.
</P>
<P>
   S&AMP;P affirmed A and A-1 credit ratings unchanged for the
Atlanta-based utility holding company and its Southeastern U.S.
subsidiaries, but revised its outlook to negative from stable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outlook revision reflects a recognition that Southern Co.
is increasingly challenged to maintain financial performance
measures commensurate with the higher business risk arising from
the company's continued expansion into competitive, asset-based
energy businesses,'' S&AMP;P said. The service also cited Southern's
plans to repurchase up to 50 million shares of common stock over
the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Southern spokeswoman Janni Benson said S&AMP;P is ``still very
comfortable with our financial position'' but that the company must
``demonstrate to them that the strategies we have in place will pay
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew S. Levi, utilities analyst with Credit Suisse First
Boston, said the revision was in keeping with trends in an industry
moving toward a more risky environment with deregulation and more
competition. Southern stock closed unchanged at $26.81 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission is currently reviewing
Southern's request for permission to expand its unregulated
holdings. The company is authorized to invest up to 100 percent of
its retained earnings and has $3.5 billion, or 89 percent of
retained earnings, invested.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign for a Prosperous Georgia, an Atlanta-based nonprofit
consumer group, has contested Southern's application for a waiver
that would raise the company's limit to 175 percent of retained
earnings, or $4 billion, on grounds of potential harm to consumers
or investors. Southern countered that the group's arguments are
based on ``baseless legal arguments and speculative allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
