<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8544 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-MARS-TECTONICS-AR     04-29 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MARS-TECTONICS-ART-980&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVIDENCE INDICATES GEOLOGY OF ANCIENT MARS RESEMBLED THAT OF
EARTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A telling magnetic pattern in the ancient surface of Mars
appears to show that the planet in an early epoch churned with
internal heat and other powerful forces, remarkably like the
geology of Earth today, scientists reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of magnetized bands in the oldest Martian crust,
detected by the Mars Global Surveyor spacecraft, was being hailed
by surprised planetary scientists as a major addition to the
growing body of evidence suggesting that Mars and Earth seemed to
start out much alike, then evolved fatefully into very different
worlds.
</P>
<P>
   If the observations are confirmed by further research,
scientists said, this would be one more indication that Mars,
though cold, arid and placid now, was a more active world in its
early history, also possibly a warmer place with liquid water on
the surface and even the beginnings of simple life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really excited about this totally unexpected and
serendipitous discovery,'' Dr. Mario H. Acuna, a leader of the
group reporting the magnetic findings, said on Thursday at a news
conference at the National Aeronautics and Space Administration in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The new findings, in particular, were considered the first
strong evidence that the geological phenomenon known as plate
tectonics has existed on another planet besides Earth. Powered by
heat from a planet's molten metal core, so-called tectonic plates
float about like bits of eggshell, colliding, merging and dividing,
causing volcanoes, earthquakes, the creation of new crust and the
shifting of continents.
</P>
<P>
   In reports on the research in Friday's issue of the journal
Science, the scientists said the magnetic stripes imprinted on
parts of Mars like a bar-code were ``reminiscent of similar
magnetic features associated with sea floor spreading and crustal
genesis on Earth.'' Thus, they concluded, the pattern ``may be a
relic of plate tectonics on Mars.''
</P>
<P>
   In the course of more than 1,000 orbits of Mars over the last
year, the Surveyor spacecraft's magnetometer first picked up traces
of magnetism imprinted in the planet's surface. They seemed random.
Then the striped pattern emerged. It was mainly confined to the
most ancient, heavily cratered highlands in the southern
hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   Here was direct evidence, the scientists said, that Mars once
had a molten core acting as a dynamo generating magnetic fields.
The stripes were created when molten material called magma bubbled
up to the surface and spread out as fresh crust. As the iron in the
magma cooled and magnetized, each new band of crust solidified in
the direction of the prevailing magnetic field, which flip-flops
several times every million years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a Martian tape recorder, the crust has preserved a fossil
record of the magnetic field directions that prevailed at different
times in the ancient past,'' said Dr. John E.P. Connerney of the
Goddard Space Flight Center in Greenbelt, Md., one of the
scientists on the discovery teams.
</P>
<P>
   On Earth, the field reverses from north to south and back,
leaving stripes of alternating magnetic orientations that are best
preserved on the sea floors. The stripes are symmetrical, running
north-south on either side of mid-ocean ridges where the upwelling
magma surfaces to form new crust. It was the detection of this
pattern on sea floors in the 1960s that established plate tectonics
as a unifying principle of geophysics and one of the century's
major scientific discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   On Mars, the stripes run east-west, are wider and more strongly
magnetized than on Earth and are longer, some extending 1,200
miles. Scientists have yet to find the center where magma reached
the surface. And if the stripes are symmetrical on either side of
such a center, the pattern no longer exists or has eluded
detection.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis of craters where meteorite impacts erased the
magnetic traces, scientists said, revealed that plate tectonics, or
whatever the process is, ceased to be an important factor on Mars 4
billion years ago, more than 500 million years after the planet's
formation. The planet was cooling, and its core presumably no
longer functioned as a dynamo. But plate tectonics is still
shaking, shaping and re-arranging Earth's surface.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the journal reports, a research team led by Connerney
wrote, ``The most straightforward interpretation of the magnetic
lineations in the Mars highland crust is that they formed early in
the planet's evolutionary history by plate tectonics and sea floor
spreading, analogous to terrestrial oceanic crust.''
</P>
<P>
   Connerney and other scientists said they were using terminology
developed for plate tectonics on Earth and did not mean to imply
that the findings were necessarily evidence for oceans on early
Mars. But they agreed that, based on what they know of terrestrial
plate tectonics, water seemed to be a necessary ingredient in the
processes.
</P>
<P>
   Observations by other spacecraft of the apparent effects of
water erosion on the Mars surface have already led most scientists
to conclude that liquid water played a role in the planet's early
history.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, scientists had assumed that the Martian surface was
like a single plate, not the several dozen crustal plates that
float on a hot mantle of Earth. Mercury and the Moon are presumably
too small to have such active geology, and Dr. James Head, a
specialist in Venus geology at Brown University, said there is ``no
definitive evidence for plate tectonics'' on Venus.
</P>
<P>
   The magnetic stripes of Mars might not have been discovered if
the Global Surveyor spacecraft's solar-power panel had not
malfunctioned. As a result, the craft had to spend a year slowly
adjusting its orbit around Mars, maneuvers that required it to dip
as low as 60 miles from the surface. At this altitude, the
magnetometer's repeated observations could pick up the surprising
magnetic stripes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the NASA news conference, Dr. Ronald Merrill, a geologist at
the University of Washington at Seattle, said, ``I'm convinced that
Mars had a magnetic field early in its history and it probably
reversed polarity,'' though he stopped short of endorsing the
plate-tectonic interpretation. Merrill said it was ``probably the
best explanation'' for the data, but he expressed concern over how
different the magnetic patterns on Mars are from the sea-floor
spreading seen on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   In another article in Science, Merrill was quoted as saying,
``If plate tectonics was operating on Mars, it worked differently
or it was recorded differently by the rocks.''
</P>
<P>
   In any event, planetary scientists agreed with Dr. Vicki L.
Hansen, a geologist at Southern Methodist University in Dallas, who
said, ``It makes us completely rethink Mars geology.''
</P>
<P>
   And it offers a vision of things to come on Earth. As Dr. Hansen
said, Earth will eventually exhaust its internal energy and shut
down its dynamo. With no protective magnetic field, intense
radiation from the Sun will strip away the Earth's atmosphere and
water.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Mars went through at a very young age is what will occur
on the Earth eventually,'' Dr. Hansen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
