<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AT&AMP;T buyout would affect many
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ AT&AMP;T is expected to announce today that it is making a
buyout offer to thousands of employees nationally.
</P>
<P>
   The package, intended to shrink the company payroll by
persuading many older workers to leave, was detailed by AT&AMP;T in
Washington, D.C., Thursday night to officials of the Communications
Workers of America, which represents AT&AMP;T's unionized work force.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, AT&AMP;T spokesman Bryant Steele would say only that,
despite rampant rumors, there was no layoff announcement planned
for today. ``We are aware that there has been some speculation
among employees that there would be a downsizing announcement.
There is not one planned. Downsizing is a forced reduction.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has already been through some serious cuts. In 1996, AT&AMP;T
announced plans to slash 40,000 of its roughly 140,000-employee
work force, much of that through divesting itself of units now
known as Lucent and NCR, and the rest through voluntary severance.
Since Michael Armstrong became chief executive in 1997, AT&AMP;T has
continued to shed some jobs while growing in other areas _
especially by acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   The spending spree, intended to extend AT&AMP;T's reach into many
forms of communications, has also intensified the need for further
cost-cutting elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T has a $70 billion deal to purchase Tele-Communications
Inc., the country's second-largest cable company. AT&AMP;T last week
bid $62.5 billion for MediaOne. Previously, AT&AMP;T paid $11 billion
for Teleport. This week, AT&AMP;T announced a $1.8 billion investment
in Japan Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   Before divesting itself of the regional phone companies like
BellSouth, AT&AMP;T had a payroll of more than 300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
