A8548 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-CENTURY30-COX     04-29 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-CENTURY30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Documentary best when it slows down
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One wonders, while reelin' in the years of CNN's new
overview of the century, whether the show was edited while R.E.M.'s
``It's the End of the World As We Know It (and I Feel Fine)''
played in the background: ``Leonard Bernstein, Leonid Brezhnev,
Lenny Bruce and Lester Bangs . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe Billy Joel's more coherent but every bit as whiplashed
``We Didn't Start the Fire'': ``Old Miss, John Glenn, Liston beats
Patterson, Pope Paul, Malcolm X, British politician sex.''
</P>
<P>
   That's about the speed at which the 10-part ``Celebrate the
Century'' clips along. The debut hour Sunday, for example, touches
on the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., Anne Frank, Gandhi, women's
suffrage, Rasputin, Nelson Mandela, the invention of the crossword
puzzle, the Titanic, the Indianapolis 500, Henry Ford, Picasso,
Freud, motion pictures, Sarajevo, Kitty Hawk and Einstein's theory
of relativity, which stated that the speed of light is a constant,
but not that someday TV shows would be pasted together at that
speed.
</P>
<P>
   Plus there's more.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are several ways to look back on a century, and
they've all been tried lately. ABC's ``The Century'' concentrated
on a handful of emblematic stories and told them with depth and in
detail. CNN's ``The Cold War'' (which was far better than
``Celebrate'') wrung every drop it could from the second half of
the century. The History Channel's ``America's Time,'' which just
concluded, focused on America's dominance, and PBS' ``The People
Century,'' which started last year and resumes in June, is more
thematic.
</P>
<P>
   That's probably more celebrating of any century than anyone
wants to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrate the Century'' doesn't have the razzle-dazzle of an
MTV video, just the pacing. The first hour, which covers the years
1900-1914, is best when it slows down, which it does twice. The
first time is to present Picasso, Freud and Einstein in context,
and to explain why what they did was both revolutionary and
important. The second time is to explain the hows and whys of the
beginning of World War I, a horribly complex topic presented here
with startling clarity (although history buffs naturally will want
more).
</P>
<P>
   David L. Wolper (``Roots'') produced ``Celebrate'' for CNN. He
uses actor Christopher Plummer to narrate, and hired noted jazz
trumpeter Wynton Marsalis to play thematically related songs in the
bumpers between segments (such as ``Nearer My God to Thee'' before
the Titanic).
</P>
<P>
   But there are choices that will bother documentary purists.
``Celebrate'' mixes Hollywood movie footage of historical events
with real footage. Not that anyone should be ``fooled,'' but it's
disconcerting to see a clip of Ben Kingsley playing Gandhi in the
movie, followed immediately by the real Gandhi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrate the Century''
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Sunday on CNN .
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
