<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8549 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLLYSPRINGS02-COX     04-29 1401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYSPRINGS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mississippi town finds favor in `Fortune'
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 2,
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLY SPRINGS, Miss. _ On Easter Sunday, the Rev. Milton Winter
of the First Presbyterian Church delivered some bad news and some
good news. Jewel Mae Orcutt was dead, but the Easter play would go
on as scheduled Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The congregation roared with laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Winter and his congregation are real, but Jewel Mae Orcutt and
the Easter play are a part of the fictional Holly Springs portrayed
in ``Cookie's Fortune,'' director Robert Altman's latest acclaimed
film playing in theaters.
</P>
<P>
   A drawling, tender story of friendship and family
eccentricities, the movie has a central character not listed in the
credits: The north Mississippi town of Holly Springs (population
7,200). Identified in the beginning of the film as the place where
the story unfolds, it is also where the entire film was shot. And
the depiction of the town is so flattering, residents are happy if
the world thinks the fictional Holly Springs is the real one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's loved it,'' said Vickie Carlton, news editor of
the South Reporter, the local newspaper. ``It was such a positive
portrayal of the town, while a lot of Southern films are not. You
couldn't find a travel book that could make the town look more
beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Many residents haven't seen ``Cookie's Fortune''; there's no
movie theater here and the closest place to see it is Memphis, 40
minutes away. But some 1,800 people went to three special
screenings Easter weekend at nearby Rust College. (The movie is
playing at metro Atlanta theaters.)
</P>
<P>
   Mary Hartwell, who works at the Center for the Study of Southern
Culture at the University of Mississippi, went to the premiere and
said it was a refreshing change to see a movie about Mississippi
where race was not the main focus. The movie's writer, Anne Rapp,
is a graduate of the university's Southern studies program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't `Mississippi Burning,''' Hartwell said. ``It makes
Mississippi look eccentric but nice, not eccentric and mean. It's
about race but not in a way that would hurt anybody's feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   Holly Springs, in celluloid and in reality, embodies many of the
South's best qualities. Set on a hill, its streets are lined with
restored antebellum mansions and Victorian cottages, its lawns drip
with wisteria and honeysuckle, its cemetery is crammed with Civil
War heroes and 13 Confederate generals. The downtown square is rare
in its authenticity. Most of the storefronts around the grand brick
courthouse still bustle with businesses that haven't yet succumbed
to the call of the strip mall. And people are proud of their town.
One man drew a map for a visitor to his favorite dogwood tree in a
neighbor's yard.
</P>
<P>
   Here, there is still time for lunch with friends at the City
Cafe. People take their time with their errands, lingering on
stools by shopkeepers' counters and telling long stories their
audience has probably heard a time or two before.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie made you feel that nobody gets in a hurry to worry
about things,'' said resident Bob Carrington. ``And that's how it
is here.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Greer, who was having lunch with Carrington at City Cafe,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't any deception in the way Holly Springs normally
conducts life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Except for that thing about the jail. In the movie, the good ol'
boy sheriff is so lax with security that he leaves the jail cell
unlocked with a murder suspect inside. How does he know the suspect
is innocent? Because he's fished with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wouldn't happen in this day and time,'' Carrington said
with a laugh. ``We aren't `Mayberry RFD' at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The county jail is locked up tight, with the receptionist
ensconced behind bulletproof glass. It's doubtful the murder
suspect, Willis, played by Charles S. Dutton, would have had access
to his beloved Wild Turkey in a jail that doesn't even allow
visitors to bring prisoners fruit.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike the sheriff played by Ned Beatty in the film,
Marshall County Sheriff Kenneth Dickerson doesn't play Scrabble
with inmates. He was unavailable to speak to a reporter on a recent
day because he was out chasing a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a little drier,'' said resident Charlie Shaw. ``But he's
the best sheriff we ever had. He enforces the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Exaggerated sleepiness is one of a few liberties Altman and Rapp
took in their portrayal of Holly Springs. The streets all look
deserted in the film, when in fact they are usually pretty busy.
And there's not just one attorney in town: There's about 10 on the
square alone.
</P>
<P>
   And Mississippi's demons, so far removed from ``Cookie's
Fortune,'' sometimes still haunt the real Holly Springs. The Ku
Klux Klan recently threw fliers in residents' yards suggesting
there should be a rally in town.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's eccentrics were not based on real residents, but
everyone agrees Altman could have had his pick if he was looking
for real-life models.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of weirdos here _ that's what I call 'em,''
said John Byrand, who was shooting the breeze inside a hardware
store on the square.
</P>
<P>
   There's Ju Ju, for example. He only comes out at night, and
carries pliers and copper wire and stops people on the street and
makes key chains for them.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a wonder how Altman could depict Holly Springs without
using its most famous eccentric _ Paul MacLeod. He's the creator of
Graceland Too, an antebellum home that MacLeod has spent 44 years
turning into a museum of Elvis Presley collectibles.
</P>
<P>
   MacLeod's obsession has driven him to keep anything and
everything with even the most fragile connection to the King.
Floors, walls and ceilings of the crumbling home are covered in
memorabilia ranging from priceless to worthless.
</P>
<P>
   MacLeod calls his home a shrine to ``the greatest entertainer
and humanitarian that has ever lived.'' His son is named Elvis
Aaron Presley MacLeod, and as a child bore a striking resemblance
to his namesake.
</P>
<P>
   After performing a leg-shaking Elvis dance and singing ``Kiss-uh
me once, kiss-uh me twice'' into a plastic echoing microphone some
college students gave him, MacLeod reflects on his absence from
``Cookie's Fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Doesn't bother me,'' he said, smoothing down his dyed black,
pomaded hair. ``I've had lots of people wanting to make a movie
about my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the cast of ``Cookie's Fortune'' dropped by Graceland
Too when they were in town, he said. He has a picture of actor
Chris O'Donnell when he visited, playing an inflatable Elvis
guitar.
</P>
<P>
   For six weeks last spring, the fictional and the real Holly
Springs mixed and mingled. More than 20 people moved out of their
homes to let the stars have a place to stay. And the cast went
about town doing normal things, blending into the community like
regular folks. People saw Glenn Close riding her bike, O'Donnell
playing golf, and Julianne Moore pumping gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nothing to see them in restaurants and in stores,''
said Gwen Henshaw, who works in the county courthouse. ``They were
just like anyone, and we'd just talk to them like they'd been here
all their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, residents are waiting to see if their newfound fame will
change anything. Some people hope it will attract visitors.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent editorial in the South Reporter, editor and
publisher Walter Webb summed up that hope:
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be just the time when Holly Springs is prepared to
take advantage of a good opportunity to become the tourist
destination that has been dreamed about for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cookie's Fortune''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Glenn Close, Charles S. Dutton, Liv Tyler and Julianne
Moore. Directed by Robert Altman.
</P>
<P>
   Rated PG-13 for sexually suggestive scenes. At metro theaters. 2
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Goes down smooth and easy. The laid-back,
affectionate tone is set early on by Dave Stewart's bluesy score
and by Altman's leisurely, let's-just-look-around approach to Anne
Rapp's script. Once the ostensible plot kicks in, you can sense
that Altman is still more interested in poking around among his
various characters than in getting on with the investigation of the
supposed murder.
</P>
<P>
   _ Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
