<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8556 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS30-     04-29 2638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of current movies
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie, Steve Murray, Drew Jubera, Bob
Longino, Jill Vejnoska and Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grades range from A to F.
</P>
<P>
   ``Analyze This''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Robert De Niro,
</P>
<P>
   Billy Crystal and Lisa Kudrow.
</P>
<P>
   R (profanity, sexuality, violence)
</P>
<P>
   This farce about a mobster (Robert De Niro) who takes his issues
to a psychiatrist (Billy Crystal) never becomes the laugh-riot it
could be. It's an offer you could refuse, but the stars (plus Lisa
Kudrow as Crystal's fiancee) make it worthwhile. (SM)1 hour, 46
minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby Geniuses''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kathleen Turner,
</P>
<P>
   Peter MacNicol, Christopher Lloyd.
</P>
<P>
   PG
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Turner and Peter MacNicol play rival researchers _ she
the breathy villainess, he the bland do-bee _ rushing to crack the
talk code emanating from five brilliant babes. Sly _ the toddler
leader _ has got a secret twin and you've got yourself 94 minutes
chock full of stupid pint-sized tricks from the brain of Bob Clark.
At first, ``Geniuses'' is dumb, and then it just gets dumber. (Bob
Longino) 94 minutes. D+
</P>
<P>
   ``Cookie's Fortune''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Glenn Close,
</P>
<P>
   Charles S. Dutton, Liv Tyler
</P>
<P>
   and Julianne Moore.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 (sexually suggestive scenes)
</P>
<P>
   This Southern gothic shaggy-dog story goes down as sweet and
smooth as a double shot of Jack Black. Glenn Close, Julianne Moore,
Charles S. Dutton, Liv Tyler, Chris O'Donnell, Ned Beatty and Lyle
Lovett are among those involved in the unexpected death of a gently
demented Mississippi widow (Patricia Neal.) A mellow Robert Altman
directs this magnolia-scented whimsy with affection and compassion.
(ERG) 2 hours. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Cruel Intentions''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Sarah Michelle Gellar,
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Phillippe and Selma Blair.
</P>
<P>
   R (profanity, sexual situations, drug use)
</P>
<P>
   Last decade's ``Dangerous Liaisons'' gets a makeover with Sarah
Michelle Gellar and Ryan Phillippe as a couple of desultorily rich
teens manipulating the romantic lives of everyone around them,
purely for their own amusement and without a whit of concern about
who may be hurt in the process. It's practically guaranteed to be a
runaway hit with the teen audience. (Jill Vejnoska) 1 hour, 37
minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancemaker''
</P>
<P>
   a documentary
</P>
<P>
   Unrated (contains a glimpse of rear nudity)
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancemaker'' is a documentary purporting to be a portrait of
Paul Taylor. It isn't. We don't learn much about Taylor, but we see
why some call him the country's best choreographer. The troupe's
dysfunctional, surrogate-family structure could be a fascinating
subject; but everyone interviewed (including Taylor and company
members) tiptoe around the man's rep as a loner and his personal
life. (SM) 1 hour, 38 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Doug's 1st Movie''
</P>
<P>
   Starring the voices of Thomas
</P>
<P>
   McHugh, Fred Newman,
</P>
<P>
   Constance Shulman.
</P>
<P>
   G
</P>
<P>
   Like the Nickelodeon series on which it's based, this movie's
appeal is centered in the carefully nurtured normalcy of its title
character, Doug Funnie, a nice kid coping with some typical preteen
passions. The gently anarchic, pro-environment plot is simply a
framework to dispense the quiet main-street morals and vivid
comic-book colors that make the wholesome Doug a superstar with
children. (Tom Sabulis) 1 hour, 17 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dreamlife of Angels''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Elodie Boucher
</P>
<P>
   and Natacha Regnier.
</P>
<P>
   R (strong sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   A good film noir _ even a tongue-in-cheek one, like this wants
to be _ has to ground its hairpin plot with real people. No such
luck here. The folks in this movie, about a sex-death-and-insurance
scam, are as slickly remote as the lavish set decor and
cinematography. (SM) 1 hour, 55 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``EDtv''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Matthew McConaughey
</P>
<P>
   and Jenna Elfman.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 (profanity, partial nudity,
</P>
<P>
   sex-related situations)
</P>
<P>
   Matthew McConaughey plays the subject of a 24-hour-a-day
documentary in Ron Howard's new comedy. Yeah, it's too much like
``Truman Show'' for its own good, but the slick packaging and
strong cast (including Jenna Elfman, Ellen DeGeneres and Martin
Landau) help it stand on its own. (SM) 2 hours, 3 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Entrapment''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Sean Connery
</P>
<P>
   and Catherine Zeta-Jones.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 (violence and mild profanity)
</P>
<P>
   A thriller with no thrills. A he/she sexual pas de deux with
little chemistry. Sean Connery plays Max, a dapper thief swiping
priceless works of art and computer chips. A shapely insurance
agent (Catherine Zeta-Jones) slinks into the picture and
``Entrapment'' becomes a cat-and-mouse game with lots of twists and
turns. Sadly, it's almost always a bore. (Bob Longino) 1 hour, 50
minutes. D+
</P>
<P>
   ``Everest''
</P>
<P>
   A documentary by David Breashears.
</P>
<P>
   Not rated
</P>
<P>
   Breathtaking. Even filmgoers accustomed to the five-story IMAX
format may gasp at the unearthly scale of ``Everest.'' David
Breashears'
</P>
<P>
   documentary was filmed at the same time as the 1996 storm that
killed eight mountain climbers, memorialized by Jon Krakauer's
best-selling book ``Into Thin Air.'' (SM) 44 minutes. A
</P>
<P>
   ``eXistenZ''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jennifer Jason Leigh
</P>
<P>
   and Jude Law.
</P>
<P>
   R (violence, sexual themes,
</P>
<P>
   general nastiness)
</P>
<P>
   n the near future, virtual-reality games have become so
mind-blowing that a counter-movement called realists has arisen.
One of their targets is celebrity game inventor Jennifer Jason
Leigh, a.k.a. the ``game-pod goddess.'' Fans of director David
Cronenberg know to expect mutilations, mutations and pitch-black
humor. But whether he's cracking you up or grossing you out, his is
a unique cinematic vision. (ERG) 1 hour, 37 minutes. A -
</P>
<P>
   ``Forces of Nature''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Sandra Bullock
</P>
<P>
   and Ben Affleck.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 (profanity, sexuality, drug use)
</P>
<P>
   Opposites attract as strait-laced Ben Affleck heads to his
wedding with free-spirit Sandra Bullock. Like ``My Best Friend's
Wedding,'' it's a savvy blend of romantic-comedy formula and wise
'90s updates. (SM)
</P>
<P>
   At metro theaters. 1 hour, 41 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Go''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Sarah Polley, Scott Wolf,
</P>
<P>
   Katie Holmes, Jay Mohr.
</P>
<P>
   R (drug content, sexuality, profanity,
</P>
<P>
   violence)
</P>
<P>
   A three-part comedy-drama unfolding on a single Christmas Eve,
it has the energetic, late-night delirium of a Chinese fire drill.
You could think of it as a movie built on ``X's.'' We get Xmas,
exhilaration, exhaustion, excitement and the drug called ecstasy,
better known as X. It's a bright, shining package. And though it
turns out to be pretty empty, you can't help admiring how cleverly
it's wrapped. (SM) 1 hour, 42 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``God Said `Ha!'''
</P>
<P>
   Featuring Julia Sweeney.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13
</P>
<P>
   A one-woman autobiographical show with ``Saturday Night Live''
alum Julia Sweeney talking about her brother's cancer, her parents
and her own illness. Lacking special effects or sex scenes _ and
with death as its undeniable subtext _ it's definitely a grown-up
film. And it proves laughter is indeed the best medicine. (Jill
Vejnoska) 1 hour, 27 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Hideous Kinky''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kate Winslet.
</P>
<P>
   R (brief nudity and sexual situations)
</P>
<P>
   Kate Winslet stars in this independent film about a single mom
who takes her daughters to 1972 Marrakesh in search of
enlightenment. Set in the waning days of flower power, the movie
portrays a generation whose idealism had its poisonous side.
Winslet gives a wondrously brave performance as a loving but
blinkered mother whose feckless romanticism makes her a benign
menace to her kids. (ERG) 1 hour, 39 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Life''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Eddie Murphy and Martin Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   R (language, sexual situations)
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Murphy and Martin Lawrence bicker for more than 60 years
in this sometimes hilarious and racially poignant prison comedy.
How they landed in a Mississippi correctional facility with life
sentences isn't nearly as important as the knack these talented
performers have for taking turns at generating laughs out of a
throwaway script. (Bob Longino). At metro theaters. 1 hour, 49
minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Nick Moran and Jason Flemyng.
</P>
<P>
   R (violence and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Smokin'. This whip-smart lark is an English caper comedy
glistening with confidence and a wicked sense of humor. Four
likable, conniving East End lads have a week to settle the debt
they owe a hood named Hatchet Harry. Rookie writer/director Guy
Ritchie piles on the characters, plot twists and violence, but one
thing is clear: everyone involved had a fine time making this
movie. You'll have fun watching it. (ERG) 1 hour, 45 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Lost &AMP; Found''
</P>
<P>
   Starring David Spade
</P>
<P>
   and Sophie Marceau.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 (profanity and gross-out scenes)
</P>
<P>
   There's something about David Spade's new movie ``Lost &AMP; Found''
that's way too much like last summer's over-the-top _ and better _
comedy ``There's Something About Mary.'' Like gross humor that'll
kick your gag reflex into gear. Still, Spade's flick has its
moments _ especially his knockout impersonation of Neil Diamond.
(Bob Longino) 1 hour, 50 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Matrix''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Keanu Reeves,
</P>
<P>
   Laurence Fishburne,
</P>
<P>
   Carrie-Anne Moss.
</P>
<P>
   R (sci-fi violence)
</P>
<P>
   A knockout sci-fi flick. Writer-directors Andy and Larry
Wachowski bring their sharp storytelling and visual showmanship to
an adventure starring Keanu Reeves that should please both comic
book fanatics and mainstream moviegoers. Balancing intelligence
with stunning special effects and action, it's a movie that earns
its explosions, high kicks and cascades of spent bullets. (SM) 2
hours, 15 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Metroland''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Christian Bale
</P>
<P>
   and Emily Watson.
</P>
<P>
   Not rated (but there is sex, profanity
</P>
<P>
   and drug use)
</P>
<P>
   This film wonders if settling down is the same as selling out.
In 1977, a 30-ish ad man (Christian Bale) with a wife (Emily
Watson), baby, mortgage, etc. is taunted by his free-wheeling '60s
youth when an old buddy shows up. The movie starts well but seems
to lose energy. Still, the theme is worthy and the performances
good, especially Watson, who does hard-headed sensible as well as
high-strung flaky. (ERG) 1 hour, 39 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``My Name Is Joe''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Peter Mullan.
</P>
<P>
   R (language, drug use,
</P>
<P>
   some discreet sex and mild violence)
</P>
<P>
   The titular Joe (Peter Mullan) is another of director Ken
Loach's sturdy working-class blokes. A recovering Glasgow
alcoholic, Joe begins a tentative and touching affair with a
good-hearted social worker. But his fragile peace with his past
becomes achingly clear, threatening their relationship. A slight
but affecting film anchored by Mullan's great performance (he won
best actor at Cannes) and Loach's evocative direction. (ERG) 1 hour
and 45 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Never Been Kissed''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Drew Barrymore
</P>
<P>
   and David Arquette.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 (profanity, drug use,
</P>
<P>
   sexual references)
</P>
<P>
   Drew Barrymore is Josie Geller, a mid-20s newspaper copy editor
and former high school dweeb (``Josie Grossie,'' they called her)
who goes back to teenville as an undercover reporter, promptly
relives high school hell and pretty much bumbles her way to
popularity. Everything about her career is implausible. The movie's
jokes are lame, its situations loopy. But Barrymore does make a go
of it. (Bob Longino) 1 hour, 47 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``October Sky''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jake Gyllenhaal,
</P>
<P>
   Chris Cooper and Laura Dern.
</P>
<P>
   PG (profanity, sensuality, alcohol use,
</P>
<P>
   some thematic elements)
</P>
<P>
   Deeply satisfying tale of West Virginia teenager Homer (Jake
Gyllenhaal) and three friends who, in the 1950s, began to build and
shoot off model rockets. Their goal: to win a science fair, which
could help them escape a future of working in the coal mine of
their small town. Based on Homer Hickam's autobiography ``Rocket
Boys,'' it makes the process of learning seem as exciting as a
special FX-driven action flick. (SM) 1 hour, 48 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Out-of-Towners''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Steve Martin,
</P>
<P>
   Goldie Hawn and John Cleese.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13
</P>
<P>
   It's a mess from the start. Henry (Steve Martin) and Nancy Clark
(Goldie Hawn) are a long-married couple from Ohio trying to
redefine their lives now that the children are grown. They land in
New York and high jinks ensue. The only time the film hints at the
madcap success it could be is when John Cleese appears as the
secretly cross-dressing hotel manager. (Drew Jubera) 1 hour, 31
minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Pushing Tin''
</P>
<P>
   Starring John Cusack,
</P>
<P>
   Billy Bob Thornton,
</P>
<P>
   Cate Blanchett, Angelina Jolie.
</P>
<P>
   R (profanity and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   A juiced-up ensemble comedy-drama that loses its bearings
halfway through its flight. John Cusak and Billy Bob Thornton play
rival air traffic controllers who keep 747s from colliding every
few seconds in the super-crowded sky above Manhattan. The talented
supporting cast includes Cate Blanchett (``Elizabeth'') and
Angelina Jolie. (SM)
</P>
<P>
   2 hours , 3 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare in Love''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Joseph Fiennes, Gwyneth
</P>
<P>
   Paltrow and Geoffrey Rush.
</P>
<P>
   R (sexuality, nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Seven Oscars, including best picture. Poor, overworked Will
Shakespeare (Joseph Fiennes) has to finish his play ``Romeo and
Ethel, the Pirate's Daughter'' and try to win the hand of
noblewoman Viola
</P>
<P>
   (Gwyneth Paltrow, who received an Oscar for best actress) in
this witty comedy that uses some of the Bard's more outrageous plot
devices. (SM) 2 hours, 2 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``SLC Punk!''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Matthew Lillard.
</P>
<P>
   R (profanity, drug use,
</P>
<P>
   violent anti-social behavior, sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   This energetic, amusing but scattered film introduces us to
Stevo's (Matthew Lillard) world of beer blasts, punk bands, acid
trips and run-ins with the rednecks of Salt Lake City, circa 1985.
A picaresque romp, it wants to be a ``Trainspotting''-Lite, an
Americanized howl against conformity that winds up, well,
conforming. (SM) 1 hour, 37 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``10 Things I Hate About You''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Julia Stiles and
</P>
<P>
   Heath Ledger.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 (sex-related dialogue,
</P>
<P>
   alcohol/drug-related scenes)
</P>
<P>
   What starts out as a terrible teen version of ``The Taming of
the Shrew'' unexpectedly starts to percolate with wit and charm,
thanks largely to its Kate-and-Petruchio stand-ins, Kat (Julia
Stiles) and Patrick (Heath Ledger). The script can't go too far
wrong with Shakespeare's plot. (It's worked for 400 years.)
References to the original verge on precious. But the film also has
a few nutty touches of its own. (SM) 1 hour, 34 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``T. rex: Back to the Cretaceous''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Liz Stauber
</P>
<P>
   and Peter Horton.
</P>
<P>
   Not rated
</P>
<P>
   The IMAX film has awesome special effects but, as a fictional
story, is too short. Ally Hayden (Liz Stauber) is a budding teenage
paleontologist who wants to go on a dig with her dino-hunting dad
(Peter Horton). When her dad brings what could be a dinosaur egg
into his lab, Ally accidentally cracks it and is thrust back in
time 65 million years, when the big beasts roamed the Earth. (ERG)
40 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Wolves''
</P>
<P>
   A documentary.
</P>
<P>
   Not rated
</P>
<P>
   Not as visually stunning as some IMAX films, this is a highly
instructive look at the once nearly vanquished gray wolf's gradual
reintroduction to Yellowstone National Park and other parts of the
American West. Covers a bit too much ground, historically and
geographically; the best parts show wolves ranging from adult pack
leaders to newborn cubs exploring and adjusting to the wild again.
(Phil Kloer)41 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie, Steve Murray, Drew Jubera, Bob
Longino, Jill Vejnoska and Phil Kloer write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
