<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8557 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-ANGLES30-COX     04-29 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-ANGLES30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Angels' gives meaning to everyday moments
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two women in their early 20s meet in a small French town and
decide to share an apartment. They scrounge for odd jobs; they
flirt with guys, joke and argue. They smoke cigarettes and drink
coffee and share late-night bar talk about getting money, getting
out.
</P>
<P>
   Not a lot happens in ``The Dreamlife of Angels,'' but a lot
happens. Finding the miraculous in the mundane, the feature debut
from director Erick Zonca is the kind of movie that finds grace in
small details, in a glance or the way someone smiles.
</P>
<P>
   We first meet Isa (Elodie Bouchez) trudging along a Lille street
under a mountainous backpack. Short-cropped and playful, she's a
curious imp who peddles handmade greeting cards to strangers,
pretending the money benefits immigrants. Bluffing her way through
a job at a sewing factory, she hooks up with languorous blonde
Marie (Natacha Regnier), who's caretaking the flat of a mother and
daughter; they're in the hospital, comatose after a car wreck.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately inseparable, Isa and Marie romp through town like
caffeinated teenagers, cruising men and cutting up. At night, they
tag-team a pair of bouncers, trying to sneak into a concert at
their club. They don't get in. But they become pals with the guys,
Fredo and Charly (Jo Prestia and Patrick Mercado).
</P>
<P>
   They also get to know the club's owner, a rich playboy named
Chriss (Gregoire Colin), who takes a proprietary interest in Marie.
She resists him at first. ``I don't get stuck on guys,'' she tells
Isa. ``They get on my nerves.'' But the line reveals itself as a
defensive posture. Marie becomes increasingly involved with the
hot-and-cold Chriss, the sort of guy who promises a weekend trip to
the family beach house, then never calls.
</P>
<P>
   Isa has her own obsession: the girl in the hospital, Sandrine,
whose diary she finds and reads with rapt interest. She even visits
Sandrine, sitting bedside as the girl's eyelids flutter from
endless dreaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're screwed up and you don't realize it,'' Marie tells Isa
when she hears about this. At times, we're liable to agree with
her. But our ideas about the women change the more we get to know
them. It seems that Marie, with her veiled insouciance and bottled
rage, is the more practical of the two. But perceptions change as
we study the ways the women engage (or don't) with the world, the
ways they shield themselves (or not) from emotion.
</P>
<P>
   And the emotions here are instantly recognizable as the women
try to make what they can of the few joys and possibilities their
daily grind offers. Zonca shoots his film with a documentarian
style that registers every nuance. (One shocking moment is all the
more powerful because of its casual presentation.) ``Dreamlife'' is
a remarkable case of empathy, a bittersweet love letter to the
everyday.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the credit goes to the actresses, who chart a symbiotic
friendship as deep and volatile as a love match. Isa and Marie grow
from girlish infatuation with each other to the sort of deep
familiarity that breeds contempt. During the filming, the two
shared an apartment; their close contact pays off onscreen in
performances that are luminously real. There's not a false, actory
moment in the whole movie. It's no wonder they shared the best
actress prize at last year's Cannes Film Festival. They deserve it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The
</P>
<P>
   Dreamlife
</P>
<P>
   of Angels''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Elodie Bouchez and Natacha Regnier. Rated R for strong
sexuality. In French, with subtitles. At Lefont Plaza. 1 hour, 52
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A beautiful character study of two young women
trying to make sense of life in a working-class town.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
