<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8558 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-GODSAIDHA30-CO     04-29 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-GODSAIDHA30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sweeney mines tragedy _ to comic effect
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Why would somebody make a movie about that?''
</P>
<P>
   Many people react that way upon hearing the story line of Julia
Sweeney's new autobiographical movie: Recently divorced and
thrilled to be living alone, she unexpectedly wound up taking in
her terminally ill brother (who had no health insurance) and their
parents (who came from out of town and just wanted to help). Throw
in a few more salient details _ it's a one-woman show filmed on a
stage and, oh yes, Sweeney herself comes down with cervical cancer
near the end _ and suddenly those same people may decide to rush
off and see ``The Matrix'' again.
</P>
<P>
   Which is unfortunate, because ``God Said `Ha!' '' is enjoyable
for a number of reasons, not the least of which is that it's very
funny. There's the family stuff: Her parents move in and soon it's
less Julia's home than it's theirs, a place where pasta is once
again known as ``noodles,'' smoking is verboten and the
thirtysomething divorcee has to sneak around to be with her
boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Even the medical stuff: A doctor trying to persuade Sweeney's
brother, Mike, to start taking his medicine via a shunt inserted
directly into his head assures him that all his patients ``love''
their shunts. Thereafter, Julia recalls, Mike regularly lightened
some of their gloomiest moments by shouting out with false
heartiness, ``I love my shunt!''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, ``God Says `Ha!' '' works because it feels
authentic. (If you haven't lost a beloved sibling way too young,
way too painfully, you'll just have to trust us on this one.) But
it never feels like too much: ``Saturday Night Live'' alumna
Sweeney may be a seasoned performer, but one never senses her
taking undue liberties simply for the sake of a good line. Or,
worse, already scheming to plumb her personal life some more for a
``God Said `Ha!' 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Lacking special effects or sex scenes _ and with death as its
undeniable subtext _ ``God Said `Ha!' '' is definitely a grown-up
film. See it, and grow up a little.
</P>
<P>
   ``God Said `Ha!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   A one-woman show starring Julia Sweeney. Rated PG-13. At
Cinefest. 1 hour, 27 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Laughter is the best medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
