r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-IDLEHANDS30-CO     04-29 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-IDLEHANDS30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quick Look at New Movies
 &HT;    By Steve Murray and Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ART FILM
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancemaker''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   A documentary involving the works of choreographer Paul Taylor.
Unrated, but contains a glimpse of rear nudity. At Toco Hills. 1
hour,
</P>
<P>
   38 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Works best as a celebration of dance, rather than a
study of the dancemaker.
</P>
<P>
   A superficial look at a dance genius
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancers'' might be a better title for ``Dancemaker,'' a
documentary purporting to be a portrait of Paul Taylor. It isn't.
We don't get to know much about Taylor _ but we amply see why some
call him the country's best choreographer.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Diamond's film kicks off with a fragment of the roiling
dance ``Esplanade.'' It's an exuberant braid of choreographed
couples spinning and tumbling across the floor _ then whirling into
the wings offstage, panting and pouring sweat. It's emblematic of
Taylor's style: sexy, inventive and astonishingly physical in ways
that can quickly turn a company member into an ex- company member.
Throughout the film, we hear the war stories: torn tendons,
strained back muscles.
</P>
<P>
   We also get news of Taylor's mercurial moods, including the time
he fired every single one of his dancers because they wanted to
take time off for the holidays. But how they won him back by
bringing him a Christmas tree. The troupe's dysfunctional,
surrogate-family structure could be a fascinating subject; but
everyone interviewed (including Taylor and current and former
company members) tiptoe around the man's rep as a moody loner and
his veiled personal life.
</P>
<P>
   It's not much of a documentary, but it's a knockout display of
dance.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   DRAMA
</P>
<P>
   ``Entrapment''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Sean Connery and Catherine Zeta-Jones. PG-13. At metro
theaters. 1 hour,
</P>
<P>
   50 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: It's you and Sean Connery, trapped in sheer
drudgery.
</P>
<P>
   Trapped _ with no thrills
</P>
<P>
   They don't really make movies like ``Entrapment'' anymore. There
are plenty of reasons for that, and all of them are evident to
anybody trapped in a theater showing this movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Entrapment'' is a thriller with no thrills. A he/she sexual
pas de deux with little chemistry. A star vehicle with a talented
star _ in this case, Sean Connery _ who, sadly, can no longer carry
a movie burdened with a weak script just by being in it.
</P>
<P>
   Connery plays Max, a dapper thief swiping priceless works of art
and computer chips. A shapely insurance agent (Catherine
Zeta-Jones) slinks into the picture and ``Entrapment'' becomes a
cat-and-mouse game with lots of twists and turns.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost always a bore _ lots of running to escape the
authorities, lots of implausible disappearing acts to illustrate
what a nifty cat burglar Max is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Entrapment'' does have some nice scenery, especially
Scotland's Isle of Mull. But anybody who's seen the movie's preview
has already witnessed it's most stunning visual _ Zeta-Jones'
Spandex-clad posterior rising and falling as she trains to elude a
treasure's protective laser beams. Yes, it's in the movie. Twice.
Once in Spandex and again later as Zeta-Jones performs a heist in a
black leather catsuit.
</P>
<P>
   It's the only part of ``Entrapment'' you'll ever remember.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bob Longino
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
