<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8560 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-CD02-COX     04-29 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-CD02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prequel launches its own, darker sound
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, May 2.
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe it's not the ``Star Wars'' you remember.
</P>
<P>
   John Williams' soundtrack for George Lucas' upcoming prequel
``Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace'' will be in record stores
Tuesday, and the music does indeed veer in new directions far, far
away from the celebratory strains of 1977's original film.
</P>
<P>
   Already playing on radio stations is ``Duel of the Fates,'' the
first single. It's dark, heavy, fast-paced and a definite
head-turner.
</P>
<P>
   But what the heck is it?
</P>
<P>
   Something maybe out of ``The Omen'' or Carl Orff's ``Carmina
Burana'' (used as the main theme for John Boorman's provocative
1981 King Arthur movie ``Excalibur'').
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Williams has introduced choral voices into a
main ``Star Wars'' theme in a pulsating, foreboding rhythm. It
evokes images of, say, medieval knights getting ready to wield
heavy weaponry and bash in somebody's brains.
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense. ``Phantom Menace'' is, after all, a dark
installment more akin to ``The Empire Strikes Back'' than ``The
Return of the Jedi.'' More importantly, it's a prequel. Williams'
task was not to move ``Star Wars'' music forward but to clearly
leap back to times long before the familiar Luke, Leia and Chewie
and even before the Clone Wars and other troubles we have inklings
about only through our heroes' whispers.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the choir sings Sanskrit for ``Fates.'' Other
tracks sometimes resemble trumpets blaring the entrance of Roman
legions or feature heavy use of a wooden xylophone _ the latter
apparently to underscore the metal bones of a skeletal droid army
(think ``Jason and the Argonauts'').
</P>
<P>
   As always, Williams' music often suggests other works: new
funnycreature Jar Jar has a tuba and oboe accompaniment that will
sound to some like ``Peter and the Wolf.'' The music involving
Naboo Temple and an audience with new character Boss Nass would fit
nicely into Holst's ``The Planets.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams ties it all together with frequent evocations of more
familiar ``Star Wars'' themes. You repeatedly recognize comforting
snippets of music that instantly recall the final Death Star battle
or Darth Vader's theme.
</P>
<P>
   The latter comes, of course, in the new ``Anakin's Theme.''
Here, Williams has composed a soft homage with strings to the young
Anakin Skywalker (a.k.a. Darth Vader) that at times echoes the
swelling majesty of ``E.T.'' But while the music slowly lifts, it
never reaches the sweet, joyous exultation from that earlier film.
Instead it faintly settles into the foretelling, menacing Vader
theme.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, it all not only works, it clearly rings ``Star
Wars.'' And once the film opens May 19, the music of ``Menace''
will more than likely become part of the ``Star Wars'' you'll
always remember.
</P>
<P>
   Movie soundtrack
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars: Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace''
</P>
<P>
   John Williams, the London Symphony Orchestra, London Voices and
the New London Children's Choir. Sony Classics. 17 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
