<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Friday, April 30. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
TVDRUGS (Washington) - An 11-year-old girl on ``Cosby'' returns
from a friend's birthday party bombed on spiked punch. A
12-year-old boy on ``Smart Guy'' downs a beer because he's worried
about embarrassing himself in front of his peers if he says no. A
``Wayans Bros.'' character blows an acting audition because he
shows up totally stoned. Something unusual is happening on
television's hottest teen and pre-teen shows. The characters are
getting drunk, they're getting stoned, and they're facing
consequences. If these programs seem different _ more pointed, more
frank _ than their predecessors, there's a good, if not surprising,
reason: the federal government. By JEFF BARKER. Story will move in
the ``A'' category.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
ALICECOOPER-MUSIC (Phoenix) - If you're going to do a box set, you
really couldn't do it any better than the guys at Rhino did for
Alice Cooper. This baby, which reached stores last week, has
everything a fan looks for in these things: There are 84 tracks,
licensed from 12 sources. There are 11 unreleased cuts, including
some intriguing demo versions. The liner notes are colorfully
informative, with Sex Pistol John Lydon chipping in a gracefully
written essay. Alice comments on every track, sometimes revealing,
sometimes funny. Even the packaging is pretty righteous. By RANDY
CORDOVA. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PAYNE-MUSIC (Phoenix) - Freda Payne's been singing for as long as
she remembers, but there's one song that's forever identified with
her: The 1970 blockbuster ``Band of Gold,'' a classic slice of pop
soul with an urgent bass line and a silky, purring vocal. ``I never
realized how far-reaching it affected people, but it did,'' says
Payne. ``Band of Gold'' doesn't exactly boast the heaviest of
lyrics. In fact, it's probably the bubbliest song ever to deal with
the subject of impotency. By RANDY CORDOVA. Story moved in the
``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
COUNTRY-LIFESTYLE (Phoenix) - When Rhode Island native Jack Joyce
moved to the Phoenix area in 1979, it not only meant a change of
scene, in some ways it meant a change of identity. Within a few
months, he owned his first cowboy boots: a pair of light brown
Justins. ``When I came out here, I just fell in love with Western
wear,'' says Joyce. There's something about the entire Western look
and Western sound that appeals to people who couldn't rope a calf
if their lives depended on it. By RANDY CORDOVA. Story moved in the
``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
WARREN-MUSIC (Phoenix) - Perhaps the oddest thing that the Warren
Brothers have ever heard is that some country stations are
``afraid'' to play their music. ``It's music, not a nuclear
weapon,'' says Brett, lead singer of the Florida-based duo. ``What
are they afraid of? That their listeners will love it? If they had
been afraid of playing Shania Twain, think of how many million of
records wouldn't have been sold.'' Like Twain, Brett and his older
brother Brad are pushing Nashville's musical boundaries. By RANDY
CORDOVA. Story moved
</P>
<P>
   in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
EDIT-VIOLENCE (Phoenix) - Blame guns... don't blame guns. Blame
parents... don't stigmatize embattled parents. Blame Hollywood's
anesthetizing sadism and cartoon violence... don't blame Hollywood.
Blame Howard Stern...don't blame the daft, grotesque deejay.
Scarcely a week has gone by since the Littleton, Colo., massacre,
and the raging first wave of media observation and analysis has
slapped down on the disaster like a tsunami. Story moved in the
`'K'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ARK-TV (Phoenix) - As a would-be biblical epic, ``Noah's Ark'' is
all wet. Which is not to say that it's completely vacant of
redeeming qualities. For example, it sent me on a rare trip to its
sacred source text. There, I scoured chapter and verse to find a
reference to pirates. Surprise. None there. But this NBC May sweeps
spectacular has pirates _ bawdy, brawling, eye patch-wearing,
ark-attacking pirates. Lordy. By DAVE WALKER. Story moved in the
``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
