<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0366 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8565 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-ARK-AZR &LR;      04-29 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ARK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV HATH WROUGHT ONE ALL-WET `ARK' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVE WALKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - As a would-be biblical epic, ``Noah's Ark'' is all
wet.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that it's completely vacant of redeeming
qualities.
</P>
<P>
   For example, it sent me _ a certified heathen _ on a rare trip
to its sacred source text. There, I scoured chapter and verse to
find a reference to pirates.
</P>
<P>
   Surprise. None there. Not in relation to Noah, at least. (But I
did learn something: Gomer is a biblical name! He was a son of a
son of the sailor, Noah. How cool is that?)
</P>
<P>
   But this NBC May sweeps spectacular has pirates _ bawdy,
brawling, eye patch-wearing, ark-attacking pirates. Lordy.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has also tweaked the Bible's time line, moving up God's
destruction of the wicked Sodom and Gomorrah to get some decent
special effects into Sunday's opening installment.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bible, those spectacular pyrotechnics follow the flood.
</P>
<P>
   The script also makes good buds of Noah and Lot, adds a crusty,
colorful traveling salesman to the tale, and offers dialogue that
wouldn't sound out of place on ``Melrose Place.'' Or in a Monty
Python sendup.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, you halfway expect to spot Eric Idle or John Cleese
silly-walking on all that water. ``Noah's Ark'' is frequently that
absurd. When Noah complains about having to build such a big boat,
God says, ``I think big.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, several lesser characters speak with English or
Australian accents. One guy torments Noah with what sounds like a
drunken pub ditty.
</P>
<P>
   Elements of action-adventure have also been added to the Noah
story. In fact, there's enough hand-to-hand combat to fill a month
of ``Xenas.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of synergy, Noah's dashing sons and their lovely
brides-to-be could populate a WB drama. (``Noah Limits?`` ``Ark
Shadows?'') Fortunately, Noah decrees a no-sex rule once the animal
houseboat is a afloat. This keeps the show family-friendly but also
foreshadows a lusty landfall of biblical proportions.
</P>
<P>
   One scene even answers every Sunday schooler's first ark
question. (Noah's sons do the shoveling.)
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, four Academy Award winners signed on to sail aboard
this ship of fools:
</P>
<P>
   Jon Voight (``Coming Home'') plays the title character, a
righteous soul hand-picked by God to headline his Genesis sequel.
</P>
<P>
   Noah walks softly and carries a big staff, and he spends a lot
of time gabbing with God, who remains unseen. (Imagined dialogue
from the NBC casting meeting: ``Get me George Burns! What? Oh.'')
</P>
<P>
   Although he's not one of the Bible's more vivid heroes, this
Noah can summon down God's wrath pretty much at will, much like a
baseball manager signals for a relief pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   With all the one-way dialogue and tricky special-effects shots,
Voight likely had to deliver most of his lines to a sound stage
``Exit'' sign. Given those constraints, he delivers a capable, if
slightly dazed-by-it-all, performance. I can't imagine anyone else
doing this ridiculous job any better.
</P>
<P>
   As Noah's patient wife, Mary Steenburgen (``Melvin and Howard'')
looks lovely and brings a tenderness to her role. Her performance
is tainted by an incredibly stupid, almost cruel scene near the
end, when Mrs. Noah goes nuts from spending too much time at sea.
It's the low point of a comparatively dignified career, although I
doubt many viewers will stick around to see it.
</P>
<P>
   F. Murray Abraham (``Amadeus'') portrays the chronologically
misplaced Lot as a lovable louse hen-pecked to distraction by his
wife, who is played so unsympathetically by Carol Kane that you'll
cheer the heaven-sent fireball that removes her from the plot. Lot
himself reacts to this horrific development with mild annoyance, as
if the missus had accidentally backed the family chariot over his
morning newspapyrus.
</P>
<P>
   James Coburn (``Affliction''), who obviously took this part long
before adding an Oscar to his bio, plays the traveling salesman.
Before the flood, Coburn's peddler provides mild comic relief.
Later, he actually peddles his floating showroom right up next to
the ark for a gala reunion with Noah's crew. This, too, is a slight
departure from the gospel truth. Or so I'm told.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Halmi Sr., who in recent seasons brought ``Gulliver's
Travels,'' ``The Odyssey'' and ``Merlin'' to the wee screen,
justifies his script's more outrageous liberties with a verbal
shrug.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, a lot of things are unsaid in the Bible,'' he said,
when questioned recently by TV critics. ``So it leaves a lot to
imagination, and you're pretty much free to do anything you want
with it if you don't steer the wrong way.''
</P>
<P>
   The script actually deals with its own imaginative revisionism,
by having Mrs. Noah comment that sloppy historians aren't likely to
place her family at Sodom's big meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   Although the special effects aren't as spectacular as expected,
the spliced-together story is perversely entertaining. The critters
are cute, the pirates are ugly, and wanton wickedness drives all
the action. It's sweeps, baby.
</P>
<P>
   Pious, this ``Noah'' is not. But it's not ponderous or
sanctimonious, either, and lots of viewers will likely enjoy it as
an oddball yarn.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers who believe that the Bible is more than mere sweeps
fodder likely won't be so forgiving. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Contact Dave Walker at dave.walker(at)pni.com &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
