<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8566 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VETS-SYNDROME-$ADV02-     04-29 1986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETS-SYNDROME-$ADV02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VA LOOKING AT HIGH RATE OF ALS AMONG GULF WAR VETERANS
 &HT;    630&AMP;adds. For release Sunday, May 2.
 &HT;    Eds: The 2nd optional add could run as a separate box.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Department of Veterans Affairs (VA) is trying
to determine why the fatal wasting disease, amyotrophic lateral
sclerosis, may have stricken more than 40 Persian Gulf war
veterans, a rate experts say is several times higher than the
disease's normal incidence.
</P>
<P>
   A University of Kentucky neurologist confirmed last week that he
had been asked to review more than 40 medical files of VA patients
to determine how many of them were correctly diagnosed as suffering
from ALS, as the disease is sometimes known.
</P>
<P>
   Also known as Lou Gehrig's disease, after the legendary baseball
player who died of it in 1941, ALS destroys motor neurons, the
specialized brain and spinal cord nerve cells that control muscles.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 30,000 Americans have it. Although Gehrig was only
37 when he died, it is almost unknown among people that young.
Experts say it typically appears between ages 50 and 70.
</P>
<P>
   Many spouses and other relatives of Gulf war veterans who have
the disease are convinced that exposure to chemicals, possibly
including low doses of the chemical weapon sarin gas, predisposed
the veterans to developing ALS a few years later.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that a drug that might arrest the disease is within
grasp, they watch their loved ones waste away while the government
continues to deny that sufficient evidence exists to link any of a
broad range of mysterious illnesses to service in the 1991 war.
</P>
<P>
   A number of nongovernment experts who have studied the matter
also have concluded that the evidence does not exist.
</P>
<P>
   The Kentucky neurologist who reviewed VA files, Dr. Edward J.
Kasarskis, declined in a telephone interview to say how many of the
patients whose case files he and other experts have reviewed appear
to have been correctly diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   He said some of the files appear to have been miscoded, and
therefore would not represent patients who have ALS.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he was applying to the Department of Defense for a
grant to make a wider study of the incidence of ALS among Persian
Gulf war veterans in an effort to ``find out whether or not there
are are more ALS cases that we would expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Fran Murphy, the VA official who asked Kasarskis to review
the files, was not available to answer questions about the
suspected cases.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to her office were referred to a VA spokesman, Terry
Jemison(cq), who would say only that the agency was ``not prepared
to release any information about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Denise Donnelly, who with her brother, former Air Force Major
Michael Donnelly, co-authored a book on his experiences in the Gulf
war and subsequent struggle with ALS, said she was told by
Kasarskis and VA officials that there were 49 names on the original
list.
</P>
<P>
   If as many as 40 of the roughly 700,000 U.S. troops to serve in
the 1991 war against Iraq have developed ALS, the rate would be
dramatically above normal, said Dr. Robert Haley, a University of
Texas Southwestern Medical Center at Dallas epidemiologist who has
argued that significant numbers of Gulf war veterans suffer from
unexplained brain and nerve damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be extremely elevated,'' Haley said. ``The incidence
of this disease among people this age is so low that it can't even
be reliably measured.''
</P>
<P>
   He said some estimates suggest that the normal risk that a
person in his or her 30s will get ALS is less that one in 1 million
per year. That would mean only around six cases would be expected
among the 695,000 veterans who served in the Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   But the numbers are so low that they defy statistical meaning,
he said. Haley spent 10 years as an epidemiologist at the Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta before joining the
Dallas medical center.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, scattered around the country, Gulf war veterans from
the Army, Air Force and Marines struggle to live with the disease
as the relentless destruction of nerve cells saps their muscles.
</P>
<P>
   They tap out computer messages with the few muscles that
continue to function, work out ways to communicate with members of
their families with eye blinks, and ask themselves what caused them
to change from vigorous, energetic individuals to helpless
paralytics.
</P>
<P>
   One was urged by the VA to get his physicians at Emory
University in Atlanta and the University of Alabama, Birmingham, to
change his diagnosis from ALS to ``undiagnosed illness,'' according
to his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``The VA doctor told us that if we got his diagnosis changed
from ALS, we would qualify for benefits,'' said Lynn Booker of
Monroeville, Ala. ``We didn't even ask. No doctor would do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Booker said her husband, Rob, was in the Alabama National
Guard and was called to active duty during the war against Iraq in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in perfect health when he went over there,'' she said.
``Now he is completely paralyzed from the neck down. He can no
longer talk, but he is still able to swallow soft food.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Rob, now 35, is participating in a drug trial at Emory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can still whisper to me, but I can see it is getting worse,
daily,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At Emerald Isle, N.C., former Marine Corps Major Randy L. Hebert
has a little motion left in his right knee. He uses it to control a
computer mouse and slowly spell out messages.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert was a combat engineer in the Gulf war, on the front
lines. Like most others, his ALS began insidiously, a weakness in
one hand, muscle twitches, weak legs, a rash and other symptoms. He
was diagnosed at the Naval Medical Center at Bethesda, Md., in
1995. He was retired from the Marines with full disability.
</P>
<P>
   But Rob Booker's symptoms did not appear until after he was no
longer on active duty and his condition is not deemed
``service-connected.''
</P>
<P>
   A special appropriation provides benefits for Gulf war veterans
who develop the ``undiagnosed illnesses'' that have come to be
known as Gulf War Syndrome. But as long as Booker is listed as an
ALS patient, he does not qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Because the benefits law provides compensation only to veterans
with undiagnosed illnesses, there is a disincentive for a veteran
to confirm a diagnosis of ALS. Thus, other cases might exist beyond
the 40 being reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, Lynn Booker said she was told by VA personnel that
her husband's name does not appear on the list, even though he has
been diagnosed with the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, ALS paralyzes all muscles, including those that
affect breathing. Many persons with ALS die in their sleep from
respiratory failure. Typically, it is fatal within three to five
years, although there have been notable exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   The English physicist and mathematician Stephen Hawking
developed ALS many years ago as a graduate student. He has lived to
propound many leading-edge theories about the origin of the
universe and the development of objects such as ``black holes.''
</P>
<P>
   In their book, ``Falcon's Cry: A Desert Storm Memoir,'' Michael
Donnelly and Denise Donnelly argue that Major Donnelly was exposed
to chemical warfare agents while flying his Air Force F-16 in the
Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, while jogging at Sheppard(cq) Air Force Base
at Wichita Falls, Texas, he ran through a fog of insecticide being
sprayed for mosquito control. Shortly thereafter, he developed ALS
and is now confined to a wheelchair, unable to talk or move below
his neck other than to punch the keys of a computerized voice
synthesizer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe with every fiber of my being that they know exactly
what happened to my brother, and there are individuals in the
Pentagon who are withholding the information for whatever reason
and are letting him die,'' Denise Donnelly said.
</P>
<P>
   One theory of ALS suggests that a low-dose exposure to
organophosphate chemicals _ such as Sarin gas, malathion pesticide
and others _ may damage nerve cells and predispose them to begin
dying following a second exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say this theory is unproven. There is more evidence to
support another theory, which suggests that exposures that occur in
rapid succession can cause the disease. The body has an enzyme that
neutralizes many organophosphates, said Haley, but the process
often depletes the enzyme supply. A second exposure, if it occurs
before the enzymes are replenished, may cause permanent nerve
damage.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Donnelly said experiments with monkeys showed that
repeated low-dose exposures to organophosphate chemicals will cause
ALS, even when the exposures are widely spaced.
</P>
<P>
   Former Marine Corps Capt. Montana Rickett of Albuquerque, N.M.,
jammed his thumb playing basketball two yeas ago. The sprain
refused to heal.
</P>
<P>
   While in Africa on a month-long church mission, Rickett met a
U.S. doctor who told him he should have the thumb checked. Little
by little, it developed that Rickett had ALS. He had been out of
the Marines for six years and did not qualify for VA benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Former Air Force Staff Sgt. Tom Oliver of Topsail Beach, N.C.,
had sprained an ankle playing softball. It would not heal. While he
was at Keesler Air Force Base in Mississippi in August 1997, his
ALS was diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   So far, his condition is not as bad as that of some other Gulf
war veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk and I can eat and my left arm is still pretty strong,''
he said in a telephone interview. ``My right hand is pretty much
gone. I have to be helped into my wheelchair.''
</P>
<P>
   (Eds: The following optional add could run as a sidebar.)
</P>
<P>
   At his home in North Carolina, Hebert used his knee-operated
computer mouse to respond last week to a reporter's questions about
his experiences in the Persian Gulf and the disease he later
developed. The task took most of a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I served as a combat engineer officer with 2nd Combat Engineer
Battalion, 2nd Marine Division,'' he wrote. ``During my time there
I was assistant operations officer, operations officer and, during
the ground combat operations, officer in charge of breaching the
Division's left flank. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my responsibility to create two emergency traffic lanes
through the two minefields to evacuate wounded. I believe my
service led to my current condition. During our breaching
operations a chemical mine exploded in our area. Readings confirmed
positive for nerve agents. I think I received low levels of agents
during my service there.
</P>
<P>
   ``During my battle with the medical board fighting for 100%
disability, two of three officers agreed with me and recommended my
illness was in fact, combat related. All agreed on 100% disability.
After more exposure in October '94 to commercial pesticides; I
believe put me over the limit of what my body could handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``On our government: too little, too late. Hopefully the truth
will rise above the chaos, deceit, and lies that continue to
prevail in our government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had some problems sleeping that started shortly after the
ground war ended, and lasted about 5 months. Also, I was ill with
flu-like symptoms for several days, as were many others in my
battalion during the month of March '91. Had bad headaches that
finally ended in the spring of '94. Other weird problems included
rashes, lumps under the skin, and difficulties with my throat
muscles. October of '94, noticed atrophy in right hand and arm.
Progressed from there. Final diagnosis, October 95. Completely
wheelchair dependent.
</P>
<P>
   ``On future: plan on living to at least 80. Believe a cure will
be found in the next 5 years. God could heal me any time He wants.
I could be running marathons again next month!
</P>
<P>
   ``Semper fi, Randy Hebert''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
