<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: JAPAN'S NUTCRACKER SUITE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the past decade whenever anyone told me Japan was
finally opening its economy and lowering its trade barriers, I
always thought of that story of the prisoners who were in jail
together for so many years that they didn't need to actually tell
each other their jokes anymore.
</P>
<P>
   They would just say ``Joke number 3,'' and everyone would laugh.
In my case, the simple phrase ``Japan is really opening up its
economy this time'' always had a similar laugh-inducing effect.
</P>
<P>
   Well, laugh no more. After visiting Tokyo a few weeks ago, I
left convinced that Japan has indeed begun its third great
modernization _ something Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi will be
touting on his visit to the U.S. beginning Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The first modern opening of Japan began when Commodore Perry
broke down the doors and arrived in 1853, triggering the Meiji
restoration. The second was Douglas MacArthur's imposition of
democracy on Japan after World War II, and the third is being
driven now by the invisible hands of globalization: the Internet
and global capital flows are breaking the shell around Japan like a
nutcracker.
</P>
<P>
   Let's be honest: For the past 50 years Japan was just the most
successful Communist country in history. It was only a matter of
time before the forces that brought down the Berlin wall and the
Soviet Union felled the wall around Japan as well.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to talk to anyone in Tokyo these days without hearing
the ``Nutcracker'' suite in the background. A friend at the
Japanese Foreign Ministry began a conversation like this: ``My son
informed us the other day that he wants to be a fund manager, but
he doesn't want to work for a Japanese bank. He wants to be with an
international bank. The Japanese institutions that young people of
my generation would automatically like to join, like the major
banks, are crumbling. That is new. My wife couldn't understand my
son. So he said to her, ``If you want to understand what I want to
do, watch this film.'' He gave her a video of the movie ``Other
People's Money,'' about a New York financier who takes over a dying
company in New England. ... My wife is still worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Japanese friend who works in executive recruiting
informed me that she always had a hard time recruiting Japanese to
work for U.S. companies because these companies, unlike those in
Japan, practiced ``the three Ks _ Kitsui, the Japanese word for
`very demanding'; Kaiko, Japanese for `firing people' when they did
not perform, and Kyoso, Japanese for `competition.'''
</P>
<P>
   This friend now tells her clients: ``Even if you think you are
signing up for life with a Japanese company today, you could wake
up in the morning and find yourself working for a foreign-owned
company very soon, so you might as well join one now and learn to
adapt to it.''
</P>
<P>
   So I've got good news and bad news and good news. The good news
is that Japan is really changing. The bad news is that the Japanese
government is still using its savings to prop up inefficient
companies. ``The good news, though,'' said a foreign banker in
Tokyo, ``is that the state is now running out of money, and that
guarantees that the free market is going to increasingly decide
where capital and labor should go, and that will bring about the
new Japan. But it will take 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many Japanese companies, strapped for cash, are now
seeking foreign partners, and those partners are bringing foreign
business practices. French auto maker Renault just came in and took
a chunk of Nissan, while GE Capital, AIG, Merrill Lynch and
Goldman, Sachs are all buying up cash-starved Japanese businesses
and restructuring them.
</P>
<P>
   While the transformation taking place in Japan today is going to
make it a formidable competitor over time, it will be a wrenching
transition. Sure, Japan's economy was a rigged game in many ways,
but it provided enormous social stability and cohesion. There is
much to admire in Japanese society, and it is not clear what is
going to go and what is going to stay in this transition.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Strom, a Tokyo reporter for The Times, wrote a moving
article the other day about a Japanese manufacturer who stabbed his
brother _ who was also his business partner _ to death after their
once-high-flying welding company went bust. It went bust after the
walls around Japan started to fall and the company had to deal with
more open, global competition. Ironically, their bankrupt company
had specialized in making metal doors.
</P>
</TEXT>
