<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-VIOLENCE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMBINE HIGH RAMPAGE: THE BLAME GAME BEGINS  
 (ADV: THIS ARTICLE APPEARS IN FRIDAY'S ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   blame guns. Blame parents... don't stigmatize embattled parents.
Blame Hollywood's anesthetizing sadism and cartoon violence...
don't blame Hollywood. Blame Howard Stern...don't blame the daft,
grotesque deejay.
</P>
<P>
   Scarcely a week has gone by since (begin ital ) it (end ital)
happened, and the raging first wave of media observation and
analysis has slapped down on the Columbine High School disaster
like a tsunami. In this newspaper alone, more than 150 news
articles, opinion columns, letters and editorials have appeared -
reporting, wailing, bemoaning, micro-analyzing, fulminating and
renting our communal vestments over the murderous Littleton, Colo.,
rampage. And what more do we know about what to do? Not much, if
anything.
</P>
<P>
   Succumbing to absolute helplessness, however, is not an option.
If any modern-age horror has provided indisputable evidence that
complacency invites more of the same, it is America's plague of
school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   You can, in fact, blame guns.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, then U.S. Sen. Dennis DeConcini of Arizona introduced
the Anti-Drug Assault Weapons Limitation Act, which banned the
sale, manufacture and importation of nine types of semiautomatic
assault weapons. One of the weapons that DeConcini's ill-fated
legislation sought to ban was a version of the TEC-9, a major part
of the Littleton killers' arsenal. There is no place in a civil
society for those kinds of guns.
</P>
<P>
   But the problem is not only guns. The problem, too, is
de-stigmatizing bad behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In February, 1998, Phoenix police raided a teenager's bedroom in
upscale Ahwatukee, thus crippling ``the most active`` drug ring at
Mountain Pointe High School. Amid the drug paraphernalia and
killer-rock posters, they found The ``Anarchist's Cookbook,'' a
guide to making explosives and drugs. Citing the fact that he kept
his bedroom door locked, the boy's parents pleaded helplessness.
</P>
<P>
   Hugs are nice. Talk is important. But assertive responsibility
has its place in the parental mix, too. Parents - and their
surrogates in schools - have come to condone behavior that simply
cannot be tolerated. The phrase ``authority figure'' needs to make
a comeback. With a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not just parents.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Second Lady Tipper Gore initiated a social campaign
against the sense-deadening, profane and violent music so favored
by teens. She nearly was laughed out of Washington, D.C., by a
cynical media, and second-guessed by her own husband, Vice
President Al Gore, who assured Hollywood enterntainment moguls that
they need not fear her campaign of ``censorship.``
</P>
<P>
   There are measures a society can take to impose standards of
decency and civility on itself short of censorship. Complaining
about and refusing to spend money on violent music and movies is a
decent first step.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not just Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   It's about Howard Stern. It truly is all about Howard Stern.
Stern's disgusting, profane ``jokes`` about events at Columbine
High ought to earn him a one-way ticket off the air.
</P>
<P>
   There is action you can take. It may be inappropriate to cast
blame on one ``cause`` of these horrific murders, but it is just as
wrong to shrug your shoulders and not cast blame at all. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
