<HEADER>
A8572 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      04-29 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US DEPLOYS MORE BOMBERS TO THE BALKANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER GLOBE STAF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration, humiliated by the
House's refusal to give official support to the US role in Kosovo,
Thursday also endured the embarrassment of a wayward NATO missile
slamming into Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Pentagon officials said there is no end in
sight to the Kosovo conflict, as Serb forces continued their
campaign of ``ethnic cleansing'' and the refugee crisis worsened in
the fifth week of NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, thrust on the defensive Wednesday night by the
House action, vowed Thursday to forge ahead with the air raids and
deployed 10 additional B-52 bombers to the Balkans. ``If Solobodan
Milosevic or anyone in Belgrade takes this as some sort of
comfort,'' Joe Lockhart, the White House spokesman, said of the
House vote, ``they'll be sorely mistaken. ``The president is
determined to see this through.''
</P>
<P>
   But other administration officials expressed concern about the
aftershocks of the House dissent, particularly in NATO countries
and Yugoslavia. The divisions over US policy emerged as officials
consulted with Russia and other nations in a search for a
diplomatic resolution to the military showdown in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William S. Cohen denounced the House's
repudiation of the air campaign as a ``counterproductive'' act that
``conflicts with the strong solidarity expressed by all of the NATO
leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   There were these other developments as the NATO campaign entered
its sixth week:
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX) Bombing continued around the clock, as NATO warplanes
engaged in the largest number of attack flights in one day since
the campaign started: 296. An additional 374 NATO sorties were
classified as support or reconnaissance missions.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, a top Air Force general said the Pentagon is
trying to rush supplies of air-launched cruise missiles and special
bombs dropped by B-2 bombers to avoid crucial shortages of both
munitions.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX) Russia's envoy to the Balkans, Viktor S. Chernomyrdin,
met with leaders in Germany and Italy and claimed to have achieved
some progress in his quest for a peace plan.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin also spoke by phone with Vice President Al Gore.
And Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright conferred with Russian
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov. But US officials cited no significant
progress in the talks.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX) Yugoslavia sued the United States and 10 NATO allies in
the International Court of Justice, calling the airstrikes a breach
of international law. State Department spokesman James Rubin
characterized the court filing as ``frivolous and absurd.'' The
court said it will begin hearing the case May 10.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX) Nearly 5,200 ethnic Albanians fled from Serb forces in
Kosovo and poured into neighboring Macedonia, where refugees camps
have grown so overcrowded that a spokeswoman for the United Nations
High Commission on Refugees declared: ``We are on the brink of a
catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 155,000 Kosvars have fled to Macedonia, while
448,000 have found refuge in neighboring countries, primarily
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, NATO officials were busy explaining how a NATO
missile veered 30 miles east of Yugoslavia and struck a suburb of
the Bulgarian capital of Sofia. The missile ripped the roof off a
private residence but caused no injuries.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said a jet fired the missile ``in
self-defense in response to the threat from a surface-to-air
missile'' in Yugoslavia. He said the NATO missile ``strayed from
its target and unintentionally landed in Bulgaria.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Reverend Jackson arrived in Belgrade to the sound
of air sirens and distant explosions. Accompanied by a delegation
of US religious leaders, Jackson drove to Yugoslavia from
neighboring Croatia, despite White House warnings that his safety
could not be guaranteed and his mission could be used by Milosevic
for anti-NATO propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson hoped to meet Friday with three American captive
soldiers and Saturday with Milosevic. He will ask Milosevic to
release the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My experience has been whenever captured soldiers are
released, it at least creates a window for dialogue,'' said
Jackson, who in 1984 secured the release of a Navy jet pilot from
Syria.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, Wednesday's House action Thursday inspired the
hottest rhetoric since Clinton's impeachment trial. In a deadlocked
vote, 213-213, the House refused to support the NATO air campaign.
A second measure, which would bar Clinton from sending ground
troops into Kosovo without congressional approval, passed, 249-180.
</P>
<P>
   The House Democratic leader, Richard A. Gephardt, denounced the
opposition to airstrikes as ``a low moment in American foreign
policy and the history of this institution.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Democrat, Representative Sheila Jackson Lee of Texas,
cited the vote as evidence that Republicans are consumed by hurting
Clinton. ``I saw a repeat of the impeachment vote,'' she said.
``The undermining of a president.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, who supported the White House
in the two votes, said the outcome indicated that Clinton has
failed to adequately ``explain the goals, the costs and the
long-term strategy of why we are there.''
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup poll released Thursday showed that 38 percent believe
Clinton has a clear policy in Kosovo, while 54 percent believe he
is simply reacting to events.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the fallout from the House votes, the Appropriations
Committee Thursday approved a $12.9 billion emergency package to
pay for the US role in Kosovo, more than double the amount Clinton
requested.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Democrats tried to reduce the figure by $1 billion,
arguing it was hypocritical for Republicans to double Clinton's
request the day after rebuking his policy. But they were defeated,
35-20.
</P>
<P>
   The spending package covers Clinton's request for $6 billion to
fund the US role in the NATO campaign through September. It also
would pay for other Pentagon needs and provide $1.7 billion for US
farmers and victims of recent natural disasters in Central America.
</P>
<P>
   The full House is expected to debate the measure next week.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, several Republicans pushed for a vote on the
House measure that would require Clinton to obtain congressional
approval before he deploys ground troops in Kosovo. Majority Leader
Trent Lott expressed interest in forcing a vote on the measure, but
he had to make a final decision.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
