<HEADLINE>
THERE ARE SPIRITS AMONG US
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Findhorn Press, which describes itself as ``devoted to the
pursuit of truth and wholeness,'' has published ``The Celestial
Voice of Diana'' ($19.95), in which  &UR; Rita Eide &LR; , a Norwegian
psychic, reports on her conversations with the late princess.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Commodore International Hotel in San Francisco is offering
a $105 a night Teletubby Turndown package that includes the
placement of a Tinky Winky on the bed at night. The package has
been available for three weeks, and the hotel says it has been
requested for both children and adults.
</P>
<P>
   _ AllHerb.com offers seekers the chance to discuss their medical
problems online with  &UR; Don Antonio Montero Pisco &LR; , a shaman who
lives in the Peruvian rain forest. ``Having Don Antonio on our site
is equivalent to having  &UR; Thomas Edison &LR;  talk about inventions over
the Internet,'' said Ken Hakuta of AllHerb.
</P>
<P>
   Because the shaman doesn't speak English and lives in the heart
of the rain forest, e-mailed questions are ferried to him by
translators, who carry his answers back over land and water.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ A major concert is planned on June 27 at London's Palladium to
celebrate the 40th anniversary of  &UR; Judy Garland &LR; 's debut there, but
 &UR; Liza Minnelli &LR;  has not responded to invitations to take part. The
New York Post says  &UR; Lorna Luft &LR;  is the headliner at the Palladium
concert, and Minnelli hasn't spoken to her in years.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Arne Naess &LR;  revealed in an interview on Norwegian TV that he
and  &UR; Diana Ross &LR; , married 13 years ago, have separated. The BBC
reports that Naess lives mainly in London and Ross lives in
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   _ The National Rifle Association spent a million more dollars on
lobbying in 1998 than it had in 1997 ($2.25 million to $1.27
million), reports the Washington newsletter the Hill. The extra
cash was deemed necessary to combat the Child Safety Lock Act and
the Brady Waiting Period Extension Act. Meanwhile, the Wall Street
Journal asked ad pros how they would handle the NRA as a client:
Drop the kids in ad campaigns, said sensible  &UR; Allen &LR; 
 &UR; Adamson &LR; , of the New York office of Landor Associates. The use of
ads showing kids learning about guns ``is going to get them into
trouble. They're just going to get slammed.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Hit the deck: A frightened traveler has forwarded a brochure
from a Holiday Inn in Herndon, Va., that promises ``Happy, cordial
team members who satisfy guests and demonstrate aggressive
friendliness.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Walking in the Lower Haight,  &UR; Alex Behr &LR;  came upon a piece of
crumpled notebook paper with the following message written on it:
``Thanks Love. You're great! I hope you work naked today.'' The
name of the signer will be omitted in case you know him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A MESSAGE FROM THE TOBACCO COMPANY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A full-page ad for Carlton cigarettes in Tuesday's paper asked
consumers, ``Isn't it time you starting thinking about number one?
Think Carlton. With 1 mg. tar, it's the ultra ultra light.''
</P>
<P>
   The small print advising smokers that ``actual tar and nicotine
deliveries will vary based on how you hold and smoke a cigarette''
sent Personals scurrying to the Brown &AMP; Williamson Web site _ given
in the ad _ to research what the heck it was talking about.
</P>
<P>
   The company says a smoker's intake of smoke (and tar) varies
``depending on the size of the puffs, the number of puffs per
cigarette, how long the smoke is held before exhaling, how far the
cigarette is smoked down to the filter overwrap, and possibly the
extent to which the ventilation holes in the filter may be blocked
by the fingers in holding the cigarette or by the lips.''
</P>
<P>
   The company says it certainly doesn't mean ``to suggest to
consumers that the cigarette will deliver any particular amount of
tar under all smoking conditions.'' Furthermore, as though the ad
had been placed by someone else, the company insists that ``it is
also not B&AMP;W's intention to suggest that any individual brand,
regardless of the category descriptor terminology used or tar
yield, is safer than any other.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I love riding through the garden. It's an efficient way to
inspect the crops, and being up high gives a sense of dominion that
is undeniably satisfying, something of what the Sun King must have
felt when he walked around the raised walkways that surround the
Potager du Roi.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Carolyne Roehm in Traditional Home magazine, harvested by
gardener Angela Weber.
</P>
