<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0375 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8578 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-POLITICS-ART-71     04-29 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-POLITICS-ART-710(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA'S ANGRY POOR: A POLITICAL QUESTION MARK
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By   CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAKRA, India _ The farmer rode his shiny blue bicycle to the
village blacksmith's hut Tuesday to get his wheat thresher
repaired. But as the two men sat on a string cot in the withering
110-degree heat, with a haze of flies periodically rising from a
pile of sugar-cane fodder to engulf them, the talk turned to
politics.
</P>
<P>
   The farmer, a Brahmin named Brij Nandan Tyagi who owns six acres
of land, was upset that the government led by the Hindu nationalist
Atal Behari Vajpayee _ also a Brahmin _ had been toppled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a blind supporter of Atal Behari,'' said Tyagi, 52, who
was dressed in a dingy white dhoti. ``Even if he is bad, I'll close
my eyes and stamp his name.''
</P>
<P>
   The blacksmith, Shamshuddin, a poor Muslim who owns little more
than the two water buffalo who live in his hut with him, heartily
disagreed. Prime Minister Vajpayee and his Bharatiya Janata Party
got exactly what they deserved, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shamshuddin, who would give only his first name, supports a
family of six on $80 a month, and he has not forgiven the
government for the sharp rise in the prices of cooking oil and
vegetables late last year, which forced him to go into debt to the
grocer. Not long before, he had voted for Vajpayee's party on the
advice of a local doctor he counts as a friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time we'll vote for Congress,'' he said. ``All the poor
people will vote for Congress this time.''
</P>
<P>
   While pundits and politicians in the capital try to calculate
who will be blamed for the collapse of one government and the
failure to form another, the people in this village of 4,000 just
an hour's drive away ask fundamental questions as they ponder whom
to support in the balloting, the third general election in India in
three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these are political games,'' said Amrish Tyagi, who like
most Brahmins in this village in Uttar Pradesh uses the Tyagi caste
name as his surname. ``You never know who's playing what.''
</P>
<P>
   Voters here are less concerned with convoluted attempts to parse
who double-crossed whom in the whitewashed colonial bungalows of
New Delhi's political elite, and more interested in who can
deliver, among other things, stability, lower prices and programs
to help the poor.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions that the people of Uttar Pradesh make could shape
who governs India. In the Parliament that was dissolved after the
collapse of Vajpayee's government, the two largest parties _
Bharatiya Janata, with about a third of the members, and Congress,
with a quarter _ are vying for primacy. The forces of power in New
Delhi are so precariously balanced that the former government lost
a confidence vote by one vote, 270 to 269.
</P>
<P>
   The Hindu nationalists now draw about a third of their members
of Parliament from this one state _ the most populous in India,
with 140 million people and a sixth of all the seats in Parliament.
If it were a nation, Uttar Pradesh would be the seventh or eighth
most populous in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Congress Party has made Uttar Pradesh and neighboring Bihar
its top election year priorities. ``Unless we revive there, we have
no future,'' said Sharad Pawar, a veteran politician from Bombay
who leads the Congress Party in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the first four decades after India gained
independence in 1947, Uttar Pradesh was the bulwark of the Congress
Party. It was home to three Congress Party prime ministers from the
Nehru-Gandhi dynasty (Jawaharlal Nehru; his daughter, Indira, and
her son Rajiv). It may yet produce a fourth _ Rajiv's widow, Sonia
Gandhi.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past decade, Uttar Pradesh has seen the near
elimination of Congress as a political force, mirroring and
magnifying its fall from power at the national level. Congress,
which once routinely won most of the parliamentary seats in the
state, came up with zero in the 1998 election.
</P>
<P>
   The party disappeared in Uttar Pradesh because its traditional
coalition was decimated. Upper-caste Brahmins moved to Bharatiya
Janata, drawn by its vision of a resurgent, politicized Hinduism.
Dalits, from the castes formerly called untouchable, shifted to
their own caste-based political party. And Muslims, alienated by
the national Congress government's failure to protect the mosque at
Ayodhya from destruction in 1992 at the hands of Hindu fanatics,
deserted Congress in droves.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In a place as populous, complex and varied as Uttar Pradesh, no
single village can predict the broader trends. But the thoughts of
the people in Kakra do suggest that the Congress Party has a chance
to make some gains.
</P>
<P>
   The single most pressing issue on the minds of many voters here
is one that many analysts in Delhi thought had faded: inflation.
Though the prices of onions, cauliflowers, potatoes and other
staples have fallen back to normal levels, people have not
forgotten the hardships they endured when prices were sky high in
the fall and early winter.
</P>
<P>
   Rakesh Kumar and Raj Kumar, factory workers from a caste of
leather workers that was once treated as untouchable, chatted at a
snack shop in the Dalit neighborhood of Kakra. The two men, who are
not related, bemoaned the high prices. Rakesh Kumar earns $80 a
month and Raj Kumar makes $60 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are poor and the poor are hurt most by the price rises,''
said Rakesh Kumar, 30. ``This government did nothing for us.''
</P>
<P>
   In past years, both men have supported the leader of the Bahujan
Samaj Party, Mayawati, herself a Dalit, whose power is drawn from
the fifth of Uttar Pradesh's population that is Dalit. But they are
reconsidering. Mayawati, who like many lower-caste women goes by
one name, has not been able to win enough power at the national
level to protect them from high prices or to materially improve
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tested all the parties and the period under Congress was
better for the poor people,'' said Raj Kumar, sweat streaming down
his cheeks. ``Nobody came to your house with food on a plate, but
at least they talked about the welfare of the poor and prices were
held in check.''
</P>
<P>
   But broad national issues like management of the economy and the
desire for political stability are only one layer of the voters'
political decision making. In Uttar Pradesh, where the middle and
upper castes have risen to positions of power in the past decade,
caste and patronage, often yoked together, are a potent force at
all levels of society.
</P>
<P>
   Like most men in this village, somnolent in the searing midday
heat, Kalu Ram Tyagi, 50, lazed in the shade on a cot in his
undershirt.
</P>
<P>
   A Brahmin and a wealthy farmer by local standards, Tyagi talked
about his admiration for Vajpayee. But Tyagi will not vote for him.
</P>
<P>
   Instead he will support the Samajwadi (Socialist) Party, because
the local state assemblyman, a fellow Brahmin, was elected under
that party's banner. And it is this local politician and caste
leader whom Tyagi credits with bringing brick lanes, a post office
and a health dispensary to Karka.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are with our caste leader,'' he said. ``Where ever he goes,
we will follow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
