<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8582 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-BOS &LR;      04-29 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK VICTIM OF SCHOOL GUNMEN LAID TO REST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ In a thoroughly modern tribute to a young man
named for a Biblical prophet, Isaiah Shoels was buried Thursday
amid hymns from popular recording artist and calls for racial
unity.
</P>
<P>
   Singled out by his killers because he was black, Shoels was
recalled as a Columbine High School senior whose determination on
the football field made up for his five-foot, five-inch frame.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Duane Williams urged Thursday's crowd of several thousand
mourners to put aside religious and racial differences. But the
minister seemed to be addressing his remarks as much to the
audience as to troubled youths like Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold,
who chronicled a yearlong plan to kill athletes and minorities _
classmates who looked and acted nothing like them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way you look, the clothes you wear, the color of your
skin,'' Williams shouted, elicting thousands of ``Amens.'' ``That
wall must come down! It's time to see Jesus!''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's three-hour service at the Heritage Christian Center,
with a Baptist choir and the popular black singing group Silk,
contrasted with Sunday's outdoor vigil that was attended by Vice
President Al Gore and criticized by some religious leaders for
having been as white as the snow that falls on the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   The Greater Metro Denver Ministerial Alliance, a largely black
group, has publicly complained that Sunday's event represented a
narrow view of Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   Shoels, the only black victim of the April 20 shooting rampage,
was hailed as a victim of a ``new-age'' hate crime, a millennium
martyr, the face of the phenomenon of schoolyard killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He left us a message,'' said Vicki Buckley, ``He left us a
message about new-age hate crimes that are no different from a man
being dragged to his death behind the back of a pickup truck in
Jasper'' _ a reference to the killing of James Byrd last year in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   More simply, Shoels's grandfather reminded people that the color
of blood is always red no matter how dark the color of the skin
that shields it.
</P>
<P>
   While Shoels's burial was the last for the 12 students and one
teacher killed by Harris and Klebold, the mourning in Littleton was
unabated Thursday. Searching for something they cannot fully
explain, thousands keep returning to Columbine High School at all
hours of the day and night.
</P>
<P>
   The shrine to the shooting victims now resembles a tiny village,
with canvas tents originally set up to protect mourners from snow
and rain now serving as meeting spots for people who want to strum
guitars, pray, or sit for hours.
</P>
<P>
   While makeshift memorials have sprouted up across the country,
marking tradegies at roadsides or city parks, the one that keeps
growing in Littleton will be preserved by historians who say it can
provide valuable lessons.
</P>
<P>
   The Clement Park memorial site next to the school inspires
silence, with visitors hushing their voices as they tour nearly
four acres of artwork, passages from the Scriptures, and photo
collages showing smiling children taking their first steps or
waving goodbye as they leave for their first class trip abroad.
Now, historians say the same process that followed the Oklahoma
City bombing, an effort to preserve the momentos left by mourners,
will begin here.
</P>
<P>
   Truckloads of flowers will eventually be discarded, but many are
already being crushed into potpourri for mourning families.
Beginning May 10, the Bibles, stuffed animals, baseball hats,
candles, and varsity letter jackets will be taken from the site and
stored at a large warehouse, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 100 years, someone is going to look this tragedy, and they
are going to look at our mourning process,'' said Edith Hylton,
manager of community services.
</P>
<P>
   The written words and artwork, ranging from the sophisticated
sketchings of local artists to the simple thoughts of Colordo
kindergarden students, are among the priorities for the team of
local historians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pieces that got to me were the posterboards filled with
pictures of Dave Sanders' players,'' said Hylton, referring to the
girls' softball team coached by the slain teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``My chest just tightens up every time I look at those team
pictures,'' Hylton said. ``We're leaving a legacy that shows this
community cared.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they are focusing on how Harris and Klebold
assembled a small arsenal of weapons, and Thursday confirmed that
the semiautomatic handgun used in the killing was sold within the
last 18 months at a Denver area gun shop.
</P>
<P>
   A man who worked at a pizza shop with Harris and Klebold may
have acted as a broker, putting the boys in touch with the seller,
investigators said. They say the co-worker has hired an attorney
and has agreed to speak with them.
</P>
<P>
   The seller of the handgun is also represented by an attorney,
and authorities said the dealer had stepped forward to negotitate
the terms of an arrest and possible plea arrangement. In Colorado,
it is illegal for a licensed gun dealer to sell a handgun to anyone
under age 21.
</P>
<P>
   The three long guns used in the attack were purchased by
Klebold's 18-year-old girlfriend, Robyn Anderson, police have said.
It is not illegal for an 18-year-old like Harris to possess a
hunting rifle or shotgun in the state, and police have said
Anderson is not a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson County officials Thursday said arrests do not appear
imminent, but they remain convinced that the pair had help placing
explosives around the school and carrying the heavy weaponry used
in the rampage.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also said a special toxicology test would be needed to
confirm reports that Harris had been taking the antidepressant drug
Luvox. Earlier this week, the coroner's office said no drugs or
alcohol were found in the bodies of any of the 15 who died. But a
special test is needed to detect a prescription drug like Luvox.
</P>
<P>
   Harris's use of the drug played a role in his rejection by the
Marine Corps just five days before the shooting. His parents had
told the Marines about their son's medical history, which Harris
had repeatedly denied to recruiters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
