<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8587 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  {{{{un~sh~~lMfUf'o~?u!~h     04-29 0005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
{{{{un~sh ~~lMfUf'o~?u!~hdH5 Kx2
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 2022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8588 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-YUGO-ARMY-2NDT     04-29 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-YUGO-ARMY-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: they collapse.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A key to the army's success so far is that its commanders knew
they would have to absorb punishment and, the experts said, they
prepared well for it.
</P>
<P>
   When NATO's air war began on March 24, the Yugoslav army had
already built up its forces in and around Kosovo. It relied on a
large number of reservists and conscripts to fill out a force of
about 40,000, including 24,000 army and 16,000 military police.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's initial barrages focused almost exclusively on
Yugoslavia's air defenses. By the time NATO turned to army targets,
including barracks, staging areas and headquarters, they had been
emptied. NATO and the Pentagon now believe that five weeks of
bombing have caused total casualties that number only ``in the
hundreds,'' as one official put it.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Clark asked for and received approval to intensify
the strikes at the end of March, the army and police units had
routed the Albanians from most of Kosovo's villages and towns. Then
they hunkered down. Some have dug into defensive positions along
Kosovo's borders with Albania and Macedonia, but most have
dispersed, moving in relatively small units that are much harder
for NATO's high-flying warplanes to strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're hiding their vehicles whenever they can, staying under
cover, staying relatively immobile _ number one to cover themselves
from air strikes and number two to conserve fuel,'' a senior
defense official said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Pentagon estimated that NATO attacks had
destroyed 10 percent to 20 percent of the 300 tanks the Yugoslav
army has in Kosovo. To put it another way, that leaves 80 percent
to 90 percent still intact in the province, by the Pentagon's own
count.
</P>
<P>
   While officials say the attacks have limited Yugoslavia's
ability to mount effective military operations, the army does not
have to mount offenses at this point, having having completed its
campaign in Kosovo. It simply has to hold on to the defensive
positions it has on the ground. It could do that indefinitely,
officials said, as long as its soldiers remain motivated despite
the destruction of fixed targets like headquarters and barracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a while before you have any wear and tear on the
foot soldier,'' said one senior U.S. military officer. ``It's hard
to do that with air power alone. That's the lesson of Vietnam. We
pounded Vietnam and we never did stop the supplies along the Ho Chi
Minh trail.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's armed forces, while badly overmatched, have
effectively used churches, schools and hospitals to shield troops
and equipment against strikes by pilots under orders to avoid
killing civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've taken their strengths and applied them against our
weaknesses,'' said a former western military attache to Belgrade.
``They know our loathing to lose pilots, and they've used their air
defenses in a way that exploits that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Intelligence reports indicate that the army is still able to get
fuel to its forces, although there are widespread shortages and
rationing for civilians. While the destruction of railways and
bridges has made transport of fuel much more difficult, two senior
defense officials said the army was still shipping gasoline in
small convoys of six-axle trucks, bypassing destroyed routes or
building makeshift river crossings.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to improvise and endure underscores how NATO's war
has revitalized the army's officer corps.
</P>
<P>
   Many officers have long grumbled about and, in some cases,
flatly opposed the wars that Milosevic pursued in Croatia and in
Bosnia. In the course of those conflicts in the early 1990s, he
shifted resources from the army, which historically has seen its
mission as one of protecting the nation from outside aggression, to
the more loyal and more pliable Serbian police.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers are now significantly better paid and have
better housing than army officers. These changes caused enormous
morale problems among an officer corps that plucked its recruits
from villages, trained them in guerrilla warfare and largely
insulated them from the country's chronic economic problems.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic also purged scores of senior army officers to find
generals willing to command troops that work with police in savage
attacks on civilians. Mid-level officers in the army have long
questioned the professionalism of these Milosevic loyalists, while
quietly voicing doubts to Western military officers about the
future of the army itself.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. government experts on the region said this week that
the bombing of Yugoslavia has silenced the grumbling and erased the
doubts, at least for now, while handing the army a mission that
officers perceive as both legal and just.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either by dumb luck or a stroke of genius, Milosevic has given
the army a direction,'' said the U.S. military official who spent
time in the region. ``Militaries respond well to crises. When you
talk to senior Yugoslav army officers, they always speak of the
constitution. They will talk about defending their borders against
external threats and defending the country against internal
enemies. It is not much of a stretch for the army to take the
situation on the ground in Kosovo and feel they are doing the right
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Partly as result of this, the army appears to have moved to the
dominant command position in the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NATO campaign has put the Yugoslav army in first place in
the institutional command for the first time this decade,'' said
James Gow, a specialist on the Yugoslav army who teaches war
studies at Kings College, London.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt among military analysts, both inside and
outside the U.S. government, that a large NATO ground force could
make short work of the out-of-date tanks and artillery pieces that
would be the pillars of the Yugoslav army defense.
</P>
<P>
   But a successful NATO ground attack that cut through Yugoslav
army lines would probably not quickly destroy its ability to
inflict casualties on Western troops, U.S. government officials and
other military analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   They said that the Yugoslav army has planned since World War II
to fight a hit-and-run war against an overwhelming force that could
not be kept from invading the country, but could be punished by
months of guerrilla attacks. In mountain bunkers and underground
depots across Yugoslavia, the army has massive stockpiles of fuel,
food and ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't think they can beat NATO,'' said a U.S. official.
``But their objective is to try to inflict as much pain as
possible. Morale and terrain, they hope, will off-set NATO's
advantages.''
</P>
<P>
   The Greek ambassador to the United States, Alexandre Philon,
said that the Yugoslav military has long planned to sustain a war
not by repelling an attack but by absorbing it with several layers
of defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very good and would withdraw from open warfare,''
said Philon. ``They train for that, plan for that. They are people
who can last much longer than a traditional army. If NATO ground
forces went in, there'd be a lot of fighting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
