<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8598 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-NYT &LR;      04-29 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNDS FOR NATO'S AIR WAR, BUT LITTLE MORAL SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans moved on Thursday to add billions
of dollars to the bill for NATO's air war against Yugoslavia, the
day after denying President Clinton political support to fight it.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert of Illinois said ``the Congress is
deeply divided'' over the fighting in the Balkans. That appeared to
be a rare understatement on Capitol Hill on Thursday, as
skirmishing and sniping over the political and economic costs of
the war erupted all over Congress.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, the House Appropriations Committee approved
nearly $13 billion in emergency spending, $7 billion more than the
White House sought. The committee's chairman said the money was
intended to fix pressing military needs and to ``let the troops
know we really support them.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure was labeled as ``relating to the conflict in
Kosovo.'' But Clinton's budget director said it included extra
billions for military projects with ``no relation to Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans pushing for the added spending, some of whom now
speak of the conflict as ``Clinton's war,'' said they saw no
contradiction in voting to reject a measure supporting the fighting
while voting for money to finance it.
</P>
<P>
   They called the extra billions in the spending bill a small
downpayment toward beefing up the post-Cold War Pentagon. Some
angrily accused President Clinton and the Democrats of bleeding the
American arsenal and leading the nation into a military morass.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the same chicken hawks who vote against defense all
the time,'' Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the House majority whip, said
in an interview. ``Not only is their president getting us in a
mess, but he's undermining our military.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats bitterly charged Republicans with sabotaging American
foreign policy after Wednesday night's unexpected 213-213 House
vote withholding support for the bombing of Serbian targets. Their
leaders said the vote could encourage the Yugoslav president,
Slobodan Milosevic, to think the United States and NATO might be
weakening in their war aims.
</P>
<P>
   In a show of unity on Thursday, Secretary of Defense William
Cohen and Gen. Hugh Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
appeared unannounced at the regular Pentagon briefing to criticize
the House vote and emphasize NATO's ``solidarity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a vote signaling less support on the air campaign is
counterproductive,'' said Cohen. ``But we will continue to wage
this effort and we will continue to take this case to the American
people, and we will continue to go after Milosevic until such time
as we achieve our goals.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats had been confident the measure would pass. DeLay
called that ``a monumental miscalculation.''
</P>
<P>
   The House minority leader, Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri,
said the vote marked ``a low moment in American foreign policy and
in the history of this institution'' and ``a betrayal of everything
America stands for.'' To follow that vote with a move to add
billions of dollars of unrequested Pentagon spending to the
emergency bill was ``hypocrisy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is mindboggling that some of the same members that voted
against the operation will today vote to double the spending for
the operation,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   In the House Appropriations Committee, Republicans and a handful
of Democrats who usually support military spending increases
approved a $12.9 billion emergency bill. It more than doubled the
$5.1 billion Clinton sought to pay for military operations in the
Balkans through Sept. 30. The request included money to pay for
military operations in Iraq dating back to December.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Jack Lew, Clinton's budget director, said House
Republicans were ``going too far.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're exaggerating the costs of the Kosovo operation and
they're funding things that meet no one's definition of an
emergency,'' he said. ``It matters that we level with the American
people as to what is and is not an emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   The House spending bill added nearly half a billion dollars for
bombs and missiles the Pentagon did not request. It would also
finance more than $1 billion in military construction projects,
most of them at bases in Europe. It also includes $1.8 billion in
pay increases for military personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The law says emergency spending must be restricted to
``unanticipated'' and ``immediate'' needs. The chairman of the
Appropriations Committee, Rep. C.W. Bill Young of Florida, said
that the bill met some pressing military demands, would cover
hidden costs of the Kosovo conflict, and would show that Congress
``stands behind our troops.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration's record in anticipating the costs of
military deployments is pretty sad,'' Young said. ``We were
supposed to be in the Balkans for a year, at a cost of $1.5
billion. Five years later, it's nine billion.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill could be voted on by the full House next week, he said.
A Senate vote on an emergency bill would come the following week,
following a House-Senate conference.
</P>
<P>
   If such a bill arrives on the president's desk, he does not have
to take it or leave it, Young said. He can decide that any given
item within the bill is not an emergency and withhold his approval
for that project. The money would go unspent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all depends on what your definition of 'emergency' is,''
Young said. ``That's a phrase that should be familiar to the White
House.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is also struggling over two bills that would finance
the conflict and urge the President to achieve victory over Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Appropriations Committee has drafted a $12 billion
spending bill for the war. But at least six senators, all fiscal
conservatives, say they are loath to vote for a bill far in excess
of the president's request, especially since the money will come
from excess Social Security revenues, which they have sworn to
protect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
