<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROUND-TROOPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US TROOPS READY TO DO THEIR DUTY FOR KOSOVARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RINAS, Albania _ Knee-deep in Balkan spring mud and surrounded
by heavy, offensive weaponry, the US soldiers at the airport base
here are in the same boat as the Albanian refugees they are
defending and the Yugoslav enemy they are trained to defeat:
waiting for someone in NATO to make the decision to go to a ground
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see the actual people it happens to, the indigenous
people'' who hang around the air base looking for temporary work,
said Army Lt. Timothy Wolfe, 26, as he stood by a Bradley Fighting
Vehicle. ``It gives you a sense of why you are here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are always looking forward to the opportunity to do what we
are trained to do,'' Wolfe said, when asked about the possibility
of a ground war. ``So I would say, yeah, it's always exciting to
think about the possibility of doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the thousands of US soldiers holed up about 16 miles
from the capital of Tirana will actually get around to doing it _
waging a ground war against the Yugoslav Army _ is still an open
question here.
</P>
<P>
   Many local Albanians, anxious to destroy the regime of Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic and to return the Kosovar refugees who
are clogging private homes and public spaces here, are hoping US
and other NATO troops will head over the border and finish the job
against Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But for the moment, the troops, planes, missiles and tanks
stationed at the headquarters for Task Force Hawk are simply
waiting for the word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pilots are always chomping at the bit,'' said spokesman Capt.
Martin Downie. ``They're ready to go at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the two airmen who survived this week's explosion of the
Apache attack helicopter are ready to go back on the job, their
colleagues say.
</P>
<P>
   The two unnamed pilots ``brushed themselves off'' after the
Monday night crash which destroyed the aircraft, and are ready to
take off again, said Capt. Mark Arden.
</P>
<P>
   The infantry forces stationed at Rinas are less enthusiastic
than their flying colleagues, but ready to go if ordered.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some anxiety here,'' said Sgt. Darnell McKinney, 25.
``But we're trained for this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart goes out to the refugees,'' he added. ``I read an
article about a little girl being molested, and my heart was full
of rage and anger. I can't believe this is actually happening,''
McKinney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always anxious to do your job, but given what our job
is, you don't want to rush into anything,'' Wolfe said. The
infantry would prefer that the air campaign be completed _
``destroying as much as possible'' of Milosevic's artillery _
before the troops go in, Wolfe said.
</P>
<P>
   US military officials won't say how many troops are at the base,
and how many have moved to other posts, such as the
Albanian-Kosovar border. A total of 5,350 troops have been okayed
for the mission, and ``they continue to flow in,'' Downie said.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the reason the troops and Bradley Fighting Vehicles
are here is to provide protection for the Apache helicopters and
their crews. But the vast array of weaponry viewed by a small group
of reporters at the base seems like overkill for the guarding of a
couple of dozen helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers have spotted some weaponry up north, where some
shelling has been reported from the Serbian side of the border.
Downie refused to confirm the sightings, but said the munitions
``need to go where they need to go. It's not all going to be at the
airport.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the troops are left to conduct dress rehearsals
for a show that may never arrive.
</P>
<P>
   They fly helicopters, and take the Bradleys out for spins in the
mud. They maintain planes and other vehicles. About 500 are
involved in getting humanitarian supplies to refugees elsewhere in
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is to basically wait it out'' until NATO makes the big
move, McKinney said. ``We're good at waiting it out.''
</P>
<P>
   A bomb scare Thursday held up civilian and military air traffic
for awhile, but so far, no explosive has been found.
</P>
<P>
   A bomb-sniffing dog noted ``something suspicious'' in a civilian
truck filled with gravel that was driven onto the base, said Maj.
Tom Dolney, a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   A second dog was sent in, and the animal also found something
wrong, so the military sent in a special robot to detect explosives
in the gravel, he said. Air Force and Navy personnel were moved
from the area as a precautionary measure.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials wouldn't speculate on the nature or source of
the threat.
</P>
<P>
   But ``there are a lot of lawless groups in Albania who aren't
too thrilled about NATO being here,'' Downie said. ``This is an
offensive operation. It's as close to combat as we've gotten.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
