<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-FUNERAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FINAL FUNERAL FOR A BROKEN-HEARTED COMMUNITY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ It was the last one, and from the look of it, everyone
on earth showed up Thursday. The mourners poured in and poured in,
filling the mall-sized parking lot, lining the streets around the
church for three blocks each way, and jamming the Heritage
Christian Center sanctuary to the doors, so that late-comers had to
watch the ceremony on television monitors in the church gym.
</P>
<P>
   This last funeral, in the longest week of funerals ever seen in
the broken-hearted community surrounding Columbine High School, was
for Isaiah Shoels, the 4-foot 11-inch football player who was to
graduate in two weeks. The one singled out because he was black.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 5,000 mourners _ students, faculty and parents
connected to Columbine High in Littleton and people from here in
Denver who never knew Isaiah Shoels _ came to celebrate a youth
remembered as preternaturally happy and exceedingly polite. But it
became clear, through the many eulogies, the presence of state
dignitaries and the outpouring of grief, that the ceremony Thursday
was for all 13 victims of the shooting and bombing rampage
perpetrated on Columbine High by two students who no one,
apparently, really knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the last piece,'' said the Rev. Larry Russell,
executive pastor of the Heritage Christian Center, after his church
choir sang a rousing medley of gospel tunes. ``Now the healing
begins.''
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony, though tinged with humor, was a sorrowful
occasion, with sobs heard throughout it. Many of the hundreds of
Columbine students in attendance sat together, forming a solemn
assembly of young faces that have shed more than their share of
tears since the massacre that ravaged their lives nine days ago. At
times, groups of students left the sanctuary in twos and threes to
cry in the lobby. One young woman wracked with grief fell on her
knees and stayed that way, until after several moments she was
helped to her feet by a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the young woman was close with Shoels, her friend shook
his head.
</P>
<P>
   Among the speakers, one of Isaiah Shoels' teachers, Tim Capra,
remembered him as the student who all the other students wanted to
be around, who eagerly helped his teachers, who always made his
class laugh. Frank DeAngelis, the principal, brought laughter when
he remembered that Isaiah always addressed him when they met in the
halls with a nod and a ``Hey, Mr. D.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the other 12 students killed April 20, Isaiah Shoels had
plans. The second of five children, he planned to attend an arts
college and become a music producer. His father, Michael, said he
had no doubts his son would succeed. He had, after all, survived
two heart surgeries, the first when he was 6 months old. Built like
a fireplug, he could bench press twice his weight and became a star
varsity football player.
</P>
<P>
   He was buried in his cap and gown.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Luther King III, recalling his father's assassination 31
years ago, used the occasion to announce that the Southern
Christian Leadership Conference planned to mount a renew a campaign
of collecting guns. ``A lot of people in America were saddened by
what happened in Columbine but we should not be shocked,'' he said.
``For we knew that America had sown the seeds of violence and our
children are still reaping the fruits of that violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bill Owens state joined dozens of other local political and
religious leaders who did not speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have the privilege of knowing Isaiah,'' Owens said.
``And I didn't know the boy that we buried yesterday or the child
that we buried on Tuesday, and Monday, or Sunday or Saturday. But I
do know these were good children. If there's any good that can come
from this, it's that it's bringing Colorado and the nation
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, although Isaiah was singled out by his killers because
he was black, the Heritage Christian Center was filled with black
and white mourners, many who came together. And the tearful
ceremony broadcast live on CNN took a different turn once the
cameras were gone, half the mourners had left, and Isaiah's powder
blue coffin was closed.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Dennis Leonard, a pastor at the church, asked everyone
in the pews to come down to the altar. Everyone did. The
dignitaries on the stage and the people from the balcony joined
those from the pews who surrounded the coffin decorated with blue
and white carnations. The pastor asked everyone to raise their
right hands and say ``Isaiah's life was not in vain.'' Everyone
said it. Then they applauded and cheered.
</P>
<P>
   The awesome church choir began signing ``It'll be all right,''
and people began dancing in the aisles. One woman literally danced
a jig. ``It'll be all right, `` It'll be all right,'' the choir
kept repeating as people filed out, many of them smiling, as though
they believed it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
