<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-SUMMER-FILMS-2TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCOVERING THE ALLURE OF A EUROPEAN SUMMER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Kristin Hohenadel's most recent article for Arts and Leisure was
about Wayne Wang's ``Chinese Box.''  
 By KRISTIN HOHENADEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The wedding lasted from late one August afternoon
through daybreak. At a long table beneath the shady trees in
Normandy, three generations toasted the newlyweds with homemade
Calvados and unlabeled champagne from the in-laws' vineyards.
</P>
<P>
   The table was artfully strewn with fruit and flowers. Chickens
plucked the meadow grass; children feasted on peaches nearly burst
with sweetness. I danced with a queue of expectant boy cousins
under the 3 a.m. stars.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in the midst of all that, I stole away inside myself
and thought: I feel like I'm in a movie. For in my New England
childhood, long before it was possible to make such romantic
pilgrimages in person, European cinema had taught me how to dream
of a European summer.
</P>
<P>
   While we barbecued in our sterile backyards, those celluloid
Europeans cast their yachts onto the Mediterranean, picnicked among
sunflowers in the Van Gogh fields of Provence, sipped wine in
outdoor cafes. They swam in tranquil Tuscan pools, rowed on
picturesque lakes, took endless strolls and bicycle rides down
leafy country lanes. Their summers were made of small, civilized
pleasures acted out on what seemed the most exquisite stage in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Europe was a feast, summer its most luscious course; and
Europeans knew how to savor every morsel. If those Tuesday nights
at the art house with my mother had taught me anything, it was that
there was a charmed life waiting elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, the train to Normandy was swamped with Germans
and college students. Venice was a hot, mobbed, rude shock in July.
But that Europe of my imagination has never failed to be a metaphor
for all of life's romantic possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Renoir's ``A Day in the Country,'' made in 1936,
demonstrated that pleasure often revolves around the achievement of
a very simple desire _ in this case, finding the perfect spot for
lunch. In black-and-white scenes framed like anemic versions of the
Impressionist paintings of the director's father, an uptight
Parisian family chooses a spot beneath the cherry trees in which to
unwind, has long discussions about the tomatoes and the wine.
</P>
<P>
   In between, girls in flowered hats push one another on tree
swings and marvel over caterpillars. Local young men twirl their
handlebar mustaches and row the ladies down the river. And there
is, in the bushes by the river, a stolen kiss that will ignite a
lifetime of desire.
</P>
<P>
   The cinematic summer in Europe often involves what happens when
all the relatives are thrown together in the country house. In
Louis Malle's ``May Fools'' (1990), it's a death that reunites the
family in the midst of the 1968 Paris riots.
</P>
<P>
   They spend so much time discussing the menu, it's easy to wonder
if they're gathered for a wedding banquet or a funeral. They picnic
in the grass, exchange partners and sexual orientations. No matter
what happens, the whole family takes a walk in the woods after
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   We know that Europeans devote whole months to pleasure in the
summertime. Perhaps this helps explain the pace of such films as
Eric Rohmer's ``La Collectioneuse'' (1971), in which beautiful
young people lie about in a villa on the shores of the
Mediterranean. Walk countless times down a rocky hillside to the
sea. Sleep in the sand. Live and relive the sensual particulars of
their sun-baked flirtations.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Claire's Knee'' (1971), Rohmer's camera lingers on the
serene mountains and lakes near Annecy, in the French Alps. The
film is emblematic of all the desire conjured up by the season in
its signature image of Claire's bronzed knee, glimmering in the sun
while she stands on a ladder picking cherries from a tree. And in
Andre Techine's ``Wild Reeds'' (1990), the passionate cauldron of a
southern French summer is the setting for an adolescent love
triangle that captures the wistfulness of lost innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the moments that can be singled out, there are surely
dozens of others that have been assimilated directly into the
imagination. If we know the meaning of the words Rome in the
summertime, it is because Anita Ekberg and Marcello Mastroianni
tiptoed barefoot in the Trevi Fountain at midnight in Fellini's
1960 ``La Dolce Vita.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   If we grasp the meaning of summer on the Riviera, it's thanks to
the naked derriere of Brigitte Bardot in the opening scene of ``And
God Created Woman'' (1956), sunning herself in a port town near St.
Tropez.
</P>
<P>
   If we have memorized the quiet poetry of an Italian island, it's
because we have watched Mario Ruoppolo on his daily route up the
winding road toward the house of the exiled Pablo Neruda in ``Il
Postino,'' the bay spreading out before him. If we understand that
the piazza is the beating heart of every village, it is from the
main square in Giuseppe Tornatore's ``Cinema Paradiso'' (1990), in
which men linger in the silky night air, church bells ring out at
every hour, girls wash their hair in the fountain in the noon sun.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise forgettable movies can imprint a montage of resonant
images. Claude Chabrol's psychological thriller ``L'Enfer'' is less
compelling for its story than for its evocative scenes of life at
an inn in the Pyrenees. In the end, Bertrand Tavernier's ``Sunday
in the Country'' can be remembered as a series of sharply etched
paintings: Little girls in lace dresses jumping rope; a civilized
Sunday walk; drinks under the rose arbor on the sprawling lawn of
the many-roomed house covered in overgrown vines.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, our most vivid images of summer on the Continent are
provided by outsiders. Take Kenneth Branagh's scenic 1993
adaptation of ``Much Ado About Nothing,'' filmed on the grounds of
a Tuscan villa, or movie versions of novels by Henry James such as
``Portrait of a Lady,'' in which Isabel Archer follows her
wanderlust to Italy.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the country outside of Florence, after all, that Lucy
Honeychurch kissed George Benson in the barley field in the 1985
Merchant and Ivory adaptation of E.M. Forster's ``Room with a
View.'' And while it wasn't quite summer when the ladies escaped
dreary London in search of wisteria and sunshine in an Italian
villa by the sea in Mike Newell's ``Enchanted April'' (1991), it
might as well have been.
</P>
<P>
   Bertolucci's ``Stealing Beauty'' was a visually seductive ode to
the Tuscan expatriate fantasy; Richard Linklater's ``Before
Sunrise'' blatantly exploited the stranger-on-a-train fantasy, as
its protagonists get off to wander Vienna in a 24-hour love affair.
</P>
<P>
   These films offer glimpses of what awaits such romantic
pioneers. We can observe from a safe distance as our innocents
abroad search for what has eluded them so far _ beauty, truth,
love, escape, enlightenment.
</P>
<P>
   David Lean's ``Summertime'' (1955) is a timeless postcard from
Venice, the city Gore Vidal once called ``the most beautiful cliche
in the world.'' But it's also a story about awakening and
transformation, as the spinster played by Katharine Hepburn dances
with her married Italian lover under a full Venice moon, walks
through the Piazza San Marco at midnight, floats down the Grand
Canal on a gondola at dawn.
</P>
<P>
   It was that summer in Normandy that did me in. The next time I
set foot on French soil, it was with the intention of staying as
long as the dream lasted. Katharine Hepburn leaves him in the end,
takes her indelible memories of that Venice summer and boards the
train toward home.
</P>
<P>
   It's been five summers since that August wedding, and there are
still days when I gaze upon my life as if upon a movie screen,
wondering when that sensation will end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
