<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAFFERT KEEPS THEM GUESSING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Bob Baffert kept bettors _ and owner John
Mabee _ guessing Thursday about his plans for Santa Anita Oaks
winner Excellent Meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The trainer said he'll announce this morning whether Excellent
Meeting will run in this afternoon's 1[-mile Kentucky Oaks against
seven fillies or in Saturday's 1\-mile Kentucky Derby against one
filly and 18 colts and geldings.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert promised Churchill Downs he'll make the call before
wagering begins on the track's unique Oaks-Derby double. Baffert
would prefer the Derby; he already has Silverbulletday in the Oaks.
Mabee would prefer the Oaks; he already has General Challenge in
the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Mabee, the San Diego insurance man, apparently was persuaded to
enter Excellent Meeting in the Derby as well as the Oaks as
insurance against a prerace injury to General Challenge. It cost
$15,000 to enter the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   The two men will discuss it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to keep your options open,'' Baffert said,
``because you never know what's going to happen to these horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a feeling where she's going to go,'' he added _ but he
wouldn't say more.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert was asked if the decision was up to him or to Mabee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell him,'' he replied. Mabee indicated he's comfortable
with that.
</P>
<P>
   This indicates one of two things: the respect owners have for
Baffert, who trained Derby winners Silver Charm and Real Quiet and
will go for a record third straight victory Saturday with General
Challenge and Prime Timber and perhaps the filly as well; or the
mellowing of Mabee, who has been known to resolve disagreements
with trainers by firing them.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert could be the first trainer to win both the Oaks and the
Derby since Ben Jones did it in 1952 with Hill Gail and Real
Delight.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Pegram-owned Silverbulletday, ridden by Gary Stevens, is
3-5 on the Oaks morning line. Excellent Meeting, with Kent
Desormeaux, is 2-1. Excellent Meeting handed Silverbulletday her
only defeat in 10 starts _ at Del Mar in August.
</P>
<P>
   Next to the Derby itself, the Oaks draws the largest U.S. racing
crowd each year, more than 94,000 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Musical stirrups?: Daragh O'Donahue was named to ride
Dubai-based Aljabr, but Sheikh Mohammed indicated another jockey
might be aboard in the Derby. Presumably he has Desormeaux in mind.
</P>
<P>
   If Excellent Meeting scratches and he doesn't ride Aljabr,
Desormeaux will be without a Derby mount a year after he won the
race with Real Quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders: Baffert made the 12th and 13th picks in Wednesday's
post-position ``draft,'' and chose posts 14 and 15 for Prime Timber
and General Challenge even though less remote slots were available,
and his explanation sounded like spin control.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert said he'd have taken post 15 even if he'd had the No. 1
pick.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, General Challenge jockey Gary Stevens backed
Baffert's story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob and I and (owner) Mabee had talked earlier and decided we
wanted the 14 or 15 hole. There's quite a gap between the main gate
and the auxiliary gate,'' Stevens said, referring to stalls 15 and
up. ``This horse has gotten away a little slow in every one of his
races.''
</P>
<P>
   Having space on his left might prevent General Challenge from
getting cut off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes him a stride or two to get his balance,'' Stevens
said.
</P>
<P>
   C notes: Trainer Nick Zito said he'll bet $100 on each of his
Derby horses, 12-1 Stephen Got Even and 30-1 Adonis.
</P>
<P>
   But before you take that as a whole-hearted endorsement,
remember those are modest-size bets for Zito, who won the 1991
Derby with Strike the Gold.
</P>
<P>
   Car talk: Churchill Downs wouldn't let ABC-TV drive a
camera-toting car on the turf course during the Derby in part
because it feared damage to the grass. But the track let NASCAR's
Jeremy Mayfield drive a stock car, painted in a thoroughbred motif,
around the main track between races Thursday as a promotion.
</P>
<P>
   This must be what they meant when they said the NTRA would try
to create NASCAR-like popularity for the horse racing industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
