<HEADLINE>
HOLLANDSWORTH DELIVERS BIG HITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Dodgers outfielder Todd Hollandsworth was activated
from the disabled list last week, but pinch-hitting in blowouts and
playing a half-inning in a game doesn't count for much.
</P>
<P>
   So while it was game 22 for the Dodgers, Thursday was like
opening day for Hollandsworth. In his first start of the season, he
had two hits and three RBI as the Dodgers beat Milwaukee 10-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can sit and take batting practice and do drills and even
pinch hit, but until you can get back out and get the flow back,
it's not the same,'' said Hollandsworth, 0 for 2 before Thursday.
``It's just good to get back in there and contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth's first three at-bats produced an RBI groundout, a
run-scoring triple and an RBI double. How often Hollandsworth gets
an opportunity to play could hinge on how he produces.
</P>
<P>
   With an outfield of Gary Sheffield, Devon White and Raul
Mondesi, there isn't any room for Hollandsworth. What can
Hollandsworth do to gain more playing time? There isn't an answer.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said he would use Hollandsworth to
rest an outfield starter, which he did in this case. With White
getting the day off, Hollandsworth started in center field.
</P>
<P>
   During the next six days, the Dodgers play at Philadelphia and
Montreal. All six games are on artificial turf.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth began the season on the disabled list (pulled
hamstring), but after being activated last Friday, he appeared in
only two games and was hitless in two at-bats. Johnson said he was
taking it slow with Hollandsworth because of the injury and cold
weather.
</P>
<P>
   Defining roles: The phone in the Dodgers' bullpen rang in the
seventh inning Monday and lefty Pedro Borbon was the only one to
get up. When it rang the same time Tuesday, lefty Onan Masaoka was
up. When it rang in the eighth, Alan Mills got ready. In the ninth,
Jeff Shaw took his jacket off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in the year, guys didn't know when to take their jackets
off, but now when the phone rings, you know who's jacket it's going
to be,'' Shaw said. ``Guys are understanding their roles.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' bullpen is 2-3 with a 3.93 ERA. The starters,
considered the strength of the staff, are 10-7 with a 4.52 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Noticing a trend? Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone remained
in Los Angeles for the Milwaukee series and will join the team in
Philadelphia. With the sweep, the Dodgers are 4-0 without Malone in
attendance and 1-5 with him on the road. And you know about
baseball superstitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the big discussion, on figuring how to keep the head
honcho out of here,'' Johnson said jokingly.
</P>
<P>
   In conclusion: Third baseman Adrian Beltre went 4 for 5 to raise
his batting average to a team-high .347.... Rehabbing right-hander
Antonio Osuna is slated to pitch two or three innings with Single-A
San Bernardino today.... The three-game sweep of the Brewers is the
first for the Dodgers against a Milwaukee club since their days in
Brooklyn. The Brooklyn Dodgers swept the Milwaukee Braves in June
1953.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
