<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8624 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-FROG-WARNINGS-620     04-29 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FROG-WARNINGS-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARASITES, NOT TOXINS, MAY BE BEHIND FROG DEFORMITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CAROL KAESUK YOON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trailing tangles of a dozen limbs or missing legs altogether,
the deformed frogs found in rising numbers around the country have
become a powerful symbol of what many fear is an ever more poisoned
environment. But at least in some areas, scientists report on
Thursday, evidence shows the frog deformities are being caused not
by toxins but by parasitic worms.
</P>
<P>
   In two new studies focusing on Pacific tree frogs in California,
separate teams of researchers report in the journal Science that
when parasitic worms known as trematodes burrow into a frog's
developing limb, the infestation can cause exactly the kinds of
deformities seen in frogs in the wild. Scientists say the studies
provide the first solid evidence pointing to a culprit behind the
long mysterious deformities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've finally solved one piece of the puzzle,'' said Dr.
Stanley K. Sessions, the lead author of one of the new papers and a
herpetologist at Hartwick College in Oneonta, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Andrew Blaustein, an ecologist at Oregon State University
who was not involved with the new studies, said: ``This is the best
experimental evidence so far showing a particular agent causing the
limb deformities we see in nature. I think parasites will explain a
lot of the deformities.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers interviewed, including Sessions and Pieter T.J.
Johnson, lead author of the other new paper, all emphasized that
the new findings do not rule out the possibility that chemical
pollutants or increasing ultraviolet light caused by a thinning
ozone layer could be causes of deformities elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the people next to the ponds they studied can breathe a
sigh of relief,'' said Dr. Judy Helgen, a research scientist at the
Minnesota Pollution Control Agency in St. Paul, ``but everywhere
else we have to be vigilant. It would be irresponsible to sit back
now and say, `Oh no, it's not a chemical cause.'''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers said most of the scientific community had ignored or
even ridiculed the idea that parasites could create deformities.
The big labs and big money were focused on studying chemicals and,
to some degree, ultraviolet radiation. So far though, researchers
say, while there is much evidence that chemicals can cause some
kinds of limb deformities in the lab, there has been little to show
that chemicals are actually deforming frogs in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will cause a lot of soul-searching,'' Dr. David Wake, a
herpetologist at University of California at Berkeley, said of the
new studies. ``A lot of people will have to re-evaluate what
they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Working without any high-powered competition, two teams composed
mostly of undergraduates were able to uncover the importance of
parasites.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was an undergraduate at Stanford University when he
carried out his experiments on Pacific tree frogs, or Hyla regilla,
with two undergraduates and one post-doctoral colleague. His team
showed that frogs exposed to higher concentrations of the trematode
known as Ribeiroia had greater numbers of deformities and died at a
higher rate.
</P>
<P>
   In the other paper, Sessions and two undergraduates provided
corroborating evidence from five species of frogs from twelve sites
in California, Oregon, Arizona and New York. All their deformed
frogs were infected with the trematodes around the bases of their
limbs.
</P>
<P>
   In Minnesota, where there have been the greatest concerns about
frog deformities and water quality, Dr. Helgen said there remains
no clear-cut cause. In spite of the new study, she said, ``For us
chemicals are the leading hypothesis.''
</P>
<P>
   She said her collaborators have found no sign of Ribeiroia in
the Minnesota frogs, nor of any connection at their study sites
between parasites and deformities.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Researchers said that while the deformed amphibians, which
typically die before reaching sexual maturity, add pressure on
amphibian populations, there does not seem to be any direct
connection between deformities and world-wide amphibian declines.
Hot spots for die-offs, researchers agreed, do not correlate well
with hot spots for deformities.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the discovery of the role played by parasites,
biologists, including those behind the new studies, say both
deformities and population declines should still be viewed as
signals that something may be amiss. Researchers said human-induced
changes, including pollution, could well have led to increases in
parasite-induced deformities, causing parasites to increase in
number or frogs to become more susceptible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our study does not eliminate water quality from being an issue
on the national level,'' said Johnson. ``We're not signaling the
all-clear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
