<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALTIMORE-MAYORAL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MFUME, COURTED BY BALTIMORE TO RUN FOR MAYOR, LEAVES CITY GUESSING
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ State lawmakers shortened a city residency
requirement to allow him to run. Prominent civic, business and
church leaders formed a draft committee to encourage him to run.
Three former mayors have implored him to run.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Kweisi Mfume are so convinced he is the only
choice to succeed Kurt L. Schmoke, who is stepping down after three
terms as mayor of Baltimore, that they predict dire consequences
for the city if anyone else from what they view as a lackluster
field prevails in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as they want a candidate of Mfume's stature _ a
five-term Democratic congressman from west Baltimore who left the
House in 1995 to become president and chief executive of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People _ they
can only cross their fingers and hold their breath.
</P>
<P>
   As the city approaches its first mayoral election campaign
without an incumbent in 28 years, Mfume says he has not decided
whether to run for mayor or remain at the NAACP, which is based
here.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty has kept the city's political forces on edge,
would-be candidates on the sidelines and officials of the civil
rights organization in the dark. Even Julian Bond, the
association's chairman, says he has no idea what Mfume will do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants this on their timetable,'' Mfume said in an
interview on Monday, during which he expressed ambivalence over a
decision that he is promising by mid-May. ``But at the end of the
day, it's my call, it's what I'm comfortable with. In my heart of
hearts, I have to choose the best thing I can do to help the
greatest number of people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' he added, ``I go back and forth between my head
and heart, back and forth, day and night. What I ought to do. What
I should do. People think I have made up my mind about this. That's
not the case at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore is one of those places that have always strained to
maintain big-league stature among American cities. Schmoke, a
former Rhodes scholar and assistant U.S.attorney, has helped. So
has a vast urban redevelopment effort over the last 20 years,
creating a vibrant downtown, stabilizing neighborhoods and stemming
a slow but steady migration to the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Chronic problems remain, though, including a large number of
homicides (aout 300 a year), underachieving public schools and an
abundance of crumbling low-income housing.
</P>
<P>
   Schmoke, a Democrat in an overwhelmingly Democratic city, has
endured much of the recent criticism for the problems' persistence.
The complaints only heightened interest in Mfume as a problem
solver once the mayor announced in December that he would not seek
a fourth term.
</P>
<P>
   While other Democrats, including Mfume's second cousin, Lawrence
Bell, the City Council president, say they are running for mayor no
matter what he decides, none can match Mfume's credentials.
</P>
<P>
   A former member of the City Council, Mfume, now 50, went on to
gain national prominence as a congressman and chairman of the
Congressional Black Caucus before being chosen to lead the nation's
oldest civil rights organization.
</P>
<P>
   At the outset, Mfume played down any interest in becoming mayor.
He had two years remaining on a five-year contract at the NAACP,
where he had inherited an organization facing discord, debt and a
struggle to make a case for its own relevance.
</P>
<P>
   He has since restored financial stability, brought in new
leaders and expanded membership, especially among those of college
age. But he contends that the association needs more time to
re-establish its once-weighty role in the nation's social
conscience.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the dichotomy I face,'' he said. ``I don't feel that
what I've started here is finished. The foundation is stable, but
now it's up to the association to put up the superstructure.''
</P>
<P>
   Only recently has Mfume begun sounding more like a prospective
candidate. As members of the City Council discussed increasing the
mayor's salary of $95,000 as an added inducement _ Mfume earns
about $220,000 with the NAACP _ he said in a speech last week that
if anything ultimately persuaded him to run, it would be his love
for the city and public service, not money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need to be enticed to be mayor of this city,'' he told
his audience, in what was regarded as the strongest indication yet
that he was giving serious consideration to a run.
</P>
<P>
   The speech came shortly after Gov. Parris Glendening signed a
measure that reduces the city's residency requirement for political
candidates to six months prior to election, from one year.
</P>
<P>
   The state initiative allows the Baltimore City Council to
restore the one-year requirement, and on Monday night Councilman
Norman Handy, with strong support from Bell, introduced a measure
that would do so. But that bill is not expected to gather enough
votes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although Mfume moved last month from a suburban home into the
city, he said in the interview that his change of residence had
nothing to do with the new law or the mayoral race. And to those
trying to read him for signals, he urged caution for now, saying,
``I have been trying to run away from this for four months in a
dignified, respectful fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I appreciate people expressing support,'' he added. ``But
I am not a messiah.''
</P>
<P>
   With Mfume on the sidelines, the campaign leading to the
September primary sputters on. Bell is regarded by many as the
front-runner in an Mfumeless Democratic field, whose winner is all
but assured of victory in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   While Bell has announced plans to run, he has not yet filed with
the city's election board, as candidates must by July 6. Five other
Democrats have filed, including former Councilman Carl Stokes. But
none of the campaigns have taken off, largely because Mfume's
decision will have such a strong bearing on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Schmoke, among others, predicted in an interview that if Mfume
decided to stay out, other candidates might emerge, perhaps even
William Donald Schaefer, who served a record four terms as mayor
before serving two as governor and, last year, winning a four-year
term as state comptroller at the age of 77.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer, who has been joined by former mayors Clarence H. Burns
and Thomas D'Alesandro 3rd in urging Mfume to run, has offered no
public sign that he is seriously interested in returning to City
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   As for Mfume, he said he began to consider the race in earnest
last Friday, sounding out his five sons, ages 25 to 30. In a
perfect reflection of his own ambivalence, two urged caution, he
said, while two encouraged him to run and one expressed
uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks ahead, Mfume said, he intends to ``pray on the
issue'' and discuss it further with his family before meeting with
the NAACP board next month in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   After that, he said, he will announce his decision.
</P>
<P>
   Bond, the association's chairman, who lives in Washington, says
he has been following developments only through published reports.
Those developments include a draft movement that he called
``certainly impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 250 city leaders, including 11 City Council members
and a handful of state lawmakers, endorsed Mfume's candidacy in
full-page newspaper advertisements last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would hate to lose him,'' said Bond, who expects to meet
privately with Mfume next week. ``But the institution is bigger
than any individual chairman or CEO. It would take a search, but we
would find a replacement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
