<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTOHN-GIULIANI-ART-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POTENTIAL SENATE RIVALS ARE SCHOOL PRINCIPALS FOR A DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(js) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was just another quiet day in the New York City
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   While Hillary Rodham Clinton answered a question about the NATO
bombing of Kosovo from an eighth-grade student at a junior high
school in Queens, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani was asked about his
political future by a fifth-grade student in Brooklyn, nicknamed
``the mayor,'' who pointedly said to laughter from her classmates
that she wanted to remain as mayor _ and not become a senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard you want to be a senator,'' said the student, Amy
Diaz, 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is, I can't be mayor after two more years,''
Giuliani responded. ``That doesn't mean I don't want to be. You
see, unlike you, I have a term limit.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday both Mrs. Clinton and Giuliani, potential rivals for
the U.S. Senate seat to be vacated in 2001 by Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, were ``principals for a day'' as part of a program that
puts role models into the city's schools. Aides to both Mrs.
Clinton and Giuliani insisted that politics had nothing to do with
their participation, and pointed out that both are frequently in
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unclear if both were ever in the New York City public
schools on the same day at exactly the same time, as they were on
Thursday. And whether the pairing of the noncandidates was mere
coincidence or plain politics, neither took any note of the other.
Asked if it mattered to him that Mrs. Clinton was in his school
system, Giuliani said, flatly: ``No. That isn't the message that
I'm sending.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet later, in one of the more striking sights of the day, Mrs.
Clinton sat cozily next to schools Chancellor Rudy Crew, who has
been in an escalating battle with the mayor in recent weeks over
vouchers and control of the public schools. At one point during the
meeting of other ``principals for a day'' at the New York Public
Library, Mrs. Clinton put her hand on Crew's shoulder and whispered
in his ear. Crew said afterward that the two did not discuss
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a political event,'' he said, repeating a theme
sounded by education officials all day long. ``We had a very good
time.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a seeming reference to Giuliani's comments last week that
the New York City school system ``should be blown up,'' Mrs.
Clinton told the library crowd, to applause, that ``we have to see
the public schools as they are, and we should be worrying about
building them up.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani was invited but did not attend the meeting for some of
the 1,000 ``principals'' at the library, which was organized by the
group called Public Education Needs Civil Involvement in Learning,
or Pencil.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the day seemed a preview of what a
Clinton-Giuliani Senate race might look like, although played out
for an audience of astute New York City school children. At Virgil
I. Grissom Junior High School 226 in Queens, Mrs. Clinton was asked
twice by students whether she would run for the Senate. ``She said,
`There's some people talking to me about that, but I haven't made
that decision,' '' recounted Rhia Warren, the principal of JHS 226.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton was at the school, which has students from almost
30 countries, from 9:15 a.m. to around 2 p.m. In a sign that she
may be less nervous about a press corps that is usually shooed away
at Mrs. Clinton's New York school appearances after the pictures
are taken, on Thursday her staff allowed newspaper and wire service
reporters to remain in the school library for the hour that Mrs.
Clinton talked with students in an eighth-grade social studies
class about the problems in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   When one student said that parents don't always realize how many
problems their children have, Mrs. Clinton agreed with the student
but said that ``most parents are doing the best they know how to
do.'' She added: ``We try. We're going to mess up. There's no
escape from it. It's part of living, and parenting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
