<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT PLANS ANTI-VIOLENCE MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton said Thursday that he planned to summon
high-ranking leaders of the entertainment industry and other
experts to the White House ``in the near future'' to discuss how
violent incidents like the school shootings in Littleton, Colo.,
might be prevented.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview to be broadcast Friday morning on the NBC
program ``Today,'' Clinton said questions to be addressed included
these: ``What should we do about guns? What should we do about
culture? What should we do about the schools? How can we help
parents? And what is government's responsibility?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments were broadcast Thursday night on the NBC
``Nightly News.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, network representatives in Washington said
White House officials had notified them of the planned gathering,
and that it had been tentatively scheduled for May 13. A White
House spokesman said Thursday night that no firm date had been set.
</P>
</TEXT>
