<HEADLINE>
WAGE GROWTH FAILS TO MEET EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Pa., Ohio, Ill.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite declining unemployment and a shortage of
workers in some industries, wage and benefit increases slowed
markedly in the first three months of the year, the government
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The government's broadest gauge of compensation, the employment
cost index, rose just 0.4 percent in the first quarter, the Labor
Department said. The quarterly increase _ the smallest since the
index was created in 1982 _ was half what economists had been
predicting, and showed that compensation growth had now slowed for
two consecutive quarters even as joblessness had declined to a
29-year low of 4.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The slowing was driven to some degree by a steep decline in
bonuses paid to Wall Street executives following last fall's
financial market turmoil and a decline in commissions earned by
real estate agents as the housing market cooled.
</P>
<P>
   A number of industries, including construction and retailing,
showed accelerating wage gains, indicating that tight labor markets
were benefiting some workers. And as they have since 1996, workers
are still enjoying wage gains after accounting for inflation, a
turnabout from long stretches in both the 1980s and 1990s when
wages were stagnant or falling in inflation-adjusted terms.
</P>
<P>
   But the overall slowing trend in compensation costs was
pronounced in the first quarter, analysts said, and was in line
with a slowdown in another key wage indicator, hourly earnings.
With inflation dormant, the trend highlighted a conundrum that has
economists and policy makers at the Federal Reserve scratching
their heads: Why has the combination of steady growth and low
unemployment not forced a run-up in wages and then prices as
history and traditional economic models suggest it should?
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not appear to be a fluke,'' said Stuart Hoffman, an
economist at the PNC Corporation in Pittsburgh. ``No matter how you
slice it or dice it, the story is the same, that total compensation
and wages in particular have actually been rising more slowly in
the face of a declining unemployment rate over the last several
quarters.''
</P>
<P>
   The report suggested that there were no inflationary pressures
building in the economy and that compensation costs were unlikely
to squeeze corporate profits. Bond prices and blue-chip stocks
rallied, pushing the Dow Jones industrial average up 32.93 points,
to 10,878.38, its third consecutive record close.
</P>
<P>
   The 0.4 percent increase in the employment cost index in the
first quarter followed a 0.7 percent rise in the fourth quarter of
last year and a 0.9 percent jump in each of the two previous
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The figures showed a 3 percent increase in wage and benefit
costs for private industry in this year's first quarter compared
with the same period last year. That was down from a 3.5 percent
year-to-year comparison in last year's fourth quarter and a 3.8
percent increase in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Wage growth in private industry was up 3.3 percent in the first
quarter compared with the same period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Overall compensation costs were also held down by a decline in
the growth of benefit costs. Benefit costs were up just 0.3 percent
in the first quarter, half the rate of the previous quarter,
belying predictions that resurgent medical costs would lead to
increased health care expenses for businesses.
</P>
<P>
   To a large extent, economists said, the explanation for the
slowdown in compensation appears to rest with the realization among
employees that inflation is no longer eating away at the purchasing
power of their paychecks. Consumer prices last year rose only 1.5
percent, meaning that even a 3 percent wage increase still put them
ahead of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing nominal wages being pulled back down by lower
inflation expectations,'' said James O'Sullivan, an economist at
the Morgan Guaranty Trust Co. ``Both workers and companies were
surprised by how low inflation was last year, due in part to lower
oil prices.''
</P>
<P>
   With wages in private industry having grown 3.9 percent last
year and inflation at 1.5 percent, workers enjoyed a real wage
increase of 2.4 percent last year, the best in two decades,
O'Sullivan said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, companies are making extra efforts to hold
down their costs because intense global competition has left them
with little ability to raise prices to maintain their profit
margins. When they do agree to wage increases, they often demand
flexibility from workers in helping the company be more efficient
and productive.
</P>
<P>
   Increases in the last several years in the rate of productivity
growth have helped companies to absorb higher compensation costs
without putting undue pressure on either prices or profits.
Economists are debating whether the absence of inflation results
from temporary factors like low oil prices, cheap imports and weak
economies in much of the rest of the world, or some fundamental
improvement in the economy's capacity to grow and create new jobs
without igniting inflation.
</P>
<P>
   At the Wisconsin Central Transportation Corp., a small rail line
serving the upper Midwest, 300 locomotive engineers recently
approved a union contract that gives them a 3 percent pay increase
this year and 2 percent next year. The pay increase was coupled
with an agreement to formalize flexible staffing rules that allow
the rail line, which is trying to build a business on tracks
abandoned as unprofitable by bigger carriers, to respond to the
needs of its customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wage increases we're talking about here are above the rate
of inflation,'' said Ann Thoma, a spokeswoman for the railroad. The
local union representative, Ken Davis, said he was ``very pleased
with the result.''
</P>
<P>
   When the United Steelworkers of America agreed to a deal with
the RMI Titanium Co. in Niles, Ohio, this month, it concentrated on
winning improvements in its pension package and in job security.
The pay increase was 50 cents an hour for five years, or a little
over 3 percent a year for a worker earning $14.50 an hour. RMI is a
unit of USX.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a modest wage increase that keeps us up with inflation,''
said Ray Raschilla, the unit chairman of the union's local 2155-7.
``We had a lot of issues that needed to be addressed quickly, and
to be honest it would have been too expensive to hit every area.''
</P>
<P>
   Wage increases are being held down, especially in manufacturing,
by a persistent fear among workers about losing their jobs despite
the strong economy, said Calvin Campbell Jr., chairman and chief
executive of Goodman Equipment, a maker of mining machinery in
Bedford Park, Ill. Unemployment may be low but the pace of layoffs
in many industries is high, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously sometimes you have to find someone with a particular
talent, and you may see some wage pressure there,'' said Campbell,
who is chairman of the National Association of Manufacturers. ``But
that's in the minority. Growth is slowing and a lot of companies
will be cutting back or not expanding. Fewer workers will have a
tendency or desire to jump jobs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
