<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8636 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0430-1     04-29 1406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0430-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: adds grafs on Russian diplomacy; Monday's errant NATO
missile
 &HT;    NATO AIR STRIKES AND BUILD-UP CONTINUES, AS DIPLOMACYBUILDS
MOMENTUM
 &HT;    With 1100&AMP;ADD.
 &HT;    Moving (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. and allied pilots took advantage of clearing
weather Thursday night to conduct some of the heaviest strikes yet
in NATO's air war against Yugoslavia, as the Pentagon said it would
send 10 additional B-52 heavy bombers to join the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have some time to go yet,'' on the air strikes,
U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen told reporters at the
Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   As the bombing escalated, so did diplomacy, with U.S., Russian
and European officials all citing measured progress in difficult
negotiations aimed at formulating a plan for bringing peace -- and
armed peacekeepers -- to the embattled Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now getting down to the footnotes,'' in talks among
NATO members and Russia, said British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook.
``The issues of principle are beginning to be resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in another reminder of the perils of prolonged conflict, a
NATO aircraft flung the combat equivalent of a wild pitch, firing
off an anti-radar missile that missed its mark not by a mile but by
many, tearing through the rooftop of a home in an upscale suburb of
the Bulgarian capital of Sofia, 30 miles east of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The missile, which did not explode, caused no injuries but came
at a delicate moment: NATO has been awaiting permission from
Bulgaria's parliament to fly strike missions through Bulgarian
airspace. The errant missile prompted a formal apology from NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bulgaria knows full well that this is a mishap,'' said NATO
spokesman Jamie Shea. ``I'm confident that we can put this behind
us.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second errant NATO munition this week. During attacks
late Tuesday, a NATO bomb fell some 200 yards short of its intended
target -- a military barracks -- and exploded in a residential
neighborhood in the Yugoslav state of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The state-run Tanjug news service reported that between 16 and
20 people were killed and others injured.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting 28 targets late Wednesday and early Thursday, NATO
pilots geared up to fly some 670 sorties -- nearly half of which
were potential strike missions -- Thursday night and early Friday,
as heavy cloud cover lifted to give Balkan bombers their first
clear view of the targets below them in more than a week.
</P>
<P>
   To add to NATO's ability to strike around the clock at a
widening array of targets, Cohen said the additional B-52 heavy
bombers would be accompanied by two fresh E-3 AWACS -- jumbo jets
stuffed with equipment that allows them to monitor aircraft over a
wide area -- and an EC-130 airborne combat command center. The
planes will be used to help coordinate NATO attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The additions are part of some 300 additional warplanes and
support craft requested by the NATO commander, U.S. Army Gen.
Wesley Clark. The Pentagon announced on Monday that it would send
30 refueling tankers as part of that package, and Cohen said
Thursday that additional portions of Clark's request would be
processed soon.
</P>
<P>
   The additional tankers and B-52s will bring to roughly 620 the
number of U.S. aircraft in the NATO armada. There are roughly 200
aircraft from other NATO countries.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said he spoke with Clark on Thursday and, among other
things, received an update on the readiness of 22 Apache attack
helicopters that arrived earlier this week in Albania. One crashed
on Monday during training exercises.
</P>
<P>
   ``He indicated they've got some more training to do,'' before
the Apaches can fly missions inside Kosovo, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   During the same briefing, Gen. Henry Hugh Shelton, Chairman of
the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said NATO commanders were nowhere near
finished reassessing the requirements of sending a ground force
into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will probably take another week or two at least,'' Shelton
said.
</P>
<P>
   If those plans were developed and approved, Shelton said, ``I
would not take any of the options off the table in terms of the
troops that would be available as a U.S. contribution to a NATO-led
force.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO estimated last fall that it would take a heavily armed
force of some 75,000 troops to successfully invade Kosovo -- an
option the alliance rejected. Last week, NATO leaders decided to
update that assessment to reflect changing conditions on the
ground. The alliance has made clear that it intends to carry on
with the air campaign, and not try to fight its way into Kosovo,
for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO military power is a great hammer,'' Shelton said, ``but
it is not the only tool in our foreign-policy toolbox.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to apply diplomatic leverage, Deputy Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott wound up two days of meetings with Russian officials
Thursday and flew to London to confer with his British counterpart,
Cook.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan met on
the conflict with Russian President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   And Yeltsin's special envoy to the Balkans, former prime
minister Victor Chernomyrdin, conferred on the matter with
officials in Germany and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early to speak about a breakthrough in the Yugoslav
settlement,'' Chernomyrdin told reporters after a meeting with
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, ``but there is a certain
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia, a close partner to Yugoslavia, has opposed NATO air
strikes since they began on March 24 to try to coerce Serb leader
Slobodan Milosevic, the president of Yugoslavia, into accepting a
NATO-backed plan for political autonomy for the majority ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has rejected that plan -- which calls for a NATO-led
peacekeeping force of some 28,000 troops to, in effect, occupy
Kosovo for an indefinite period of time. Milosevic has said that,
instead, he would accept unarmed U.N. monitors, an option the
United States and its allies contend is insufficient to protect
Kosovo's ethnic Albanian population.
</P>
<P>
   NATO contends that Serb troops and police have executed more
than 4,000 Kosovar Albanians and run an estimated 1.5 million more
from their homes in a province-wide rampage over the past six
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Milosevic regime appeared to reject a NATO-led peacekeeping
force in public comments on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``An international presence in Serbia's Kosovo province is not a
problem,'' the spokesman of Milosevic's Socialist Party, Ivica
Dacic, told reporters in Belgrade. ``But only a civilian and
unarmed mission under U.N. auspices, with Russia's participation,
would be acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Dacic, ``Those who are bombing Yugoslavia today cannot be a
part of any peace mission.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, though, State Department spokesman James Rubin
said ``there is increasing understanding on the Russian part,'' of
the U.S. insistence on an armed peacekeeping force with NATO at its
core.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't say they agreed with it yet,'' said Rubin. ``But the
idea of the composition of a force is now being discussed more
intensively than it was before.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States and its allies have said for some time that
Russian participation in a peacekeeping force would be welcomed.
Russian troops are part of the NATO-led peacekeeping force in
Bosnia, which shares a border with Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin cautioned, however, that agreement with Russia was not yet
at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not fully agreed with Russia on the points
necessary,'' Rubin said, ``nor does even agreement with Russia
necessarily signal that Belgrade will agree.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia has exercised limited, and apparently declining,
influence over Milosevic in recent months. It is, however, the only
one of the five permanent members of the U.N. Security Council to
currently enjoy close ties to Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``And as far as we're concerned, we still don't have concrete
indicators from Belgrade that they are prepared to do what the
whole world is demanding they do,'' said Rubin, ``which is to stop
the offensive, pull their troops out, allow the refugees back, and
allow the necessary international security force to be deployed.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
