<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8638 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS--LADN     04-29 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS--LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS POUND BREWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ The Dodgers limped into County Stadium amid myriad
questions, and they leave as the team everyone thought they should
be.
</P>
<P>
   Three days of sound baseball accompanied by three wins has that
effect.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers used pitching and a timely hit in the first two
games, and slammed down the exclamation point in the series with
nine runs in the first four innings of Thursday's 10-4 beating of
the Milwaukee Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   It was a season-high for runs scored and gives the Dodgers
(12-10) a 3-0 start to their nine-game road trip. It's the first
time the Dodgers have scored more than five runs since April 17.
</P>
<P>
   It also gave the Dodgers their first series sweep since they
opened the season with three straight wins against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time. It took us how many games to have an easy
win?'' Dodgers shortstop and Milwaukee native Mark Grudzielanek
said. ``They were playing well coming into the series so it's good
to come in here and sweep.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers (9-12) won four straight before meeting the Dodgers,
but in the first two games fell victim to strong pitching and
opportune hits from Raul Mondesi and Chan Ho Park. The Dodgers won
both games 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   This one was much easier.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers third baseman Adrian Beltre led a 13-hit attack with a
career-high four hits and two RBI. Grudzielanek had three hits and
an RBI and outfielder Todd Hollandsworth had a double, triple and
three RBI in his first start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Brewers right-hander Cal Eldred (0-1) was knocked out after
allowing six runs in three innings and the Dodgers built a 9-1 lead
in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice three wins, a big three wins, especially
considering the first two,'' Dodgers first baseman Eric Karros
said. ``It's a good way to start a road trip.''
</P>
<P>
   The road trip could still crash and burn, but it seems less
likely considering the Dodgers showed signs of breaking out of a
two-week funk. When the Dodgers were losing nine of 13 before the
sweep, they weren't getting hits with runners in scoring position
and the starting pitching was suspect. In turn, the bullpen was
overworked and ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was the Brewers' deficiencies showing up or the
Dodgers' ability kicking in, all that changed. Starters Kevin Brown
and Park each allowed two runs in 62/3 innings in the first two
games and Ismael Valdes (3-0) capped the series with seven innings.
He gave up four runs on eight hits.
</P>
<P>
   In the series, the bullpen allowed three hits in 62/3 innings,
but their importance was diminished Thursday by the Dodgers offense
finally getting hits with runners on second and third. That offense
toiled under .200 earlier, but went 6 for 16 against a quartet of
Brewers pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to get out of that drought,'' said Dodgers left fielder
Gary Sheffield, who walked three times and scored twice. ``We
showed we can play a 3-2 game and win or a 10-4 game and win. The
offense has to pick up and contribute more.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a monumental feat for the Dodgers to score 10 runs
without hitting a homer. Of the 95 runs the Dodgers had scored
heading into the game, 42 had come via a home run.
</P>
<P>
   That trend disappeared in the third inning when Karros, 0 for 10
since moving to the cleanup spot before the series, had a two-run
double. Hollandsworth followed with an RBI triple and Beltre added
an RBI single as the Dodgers took a 6-1 lead. It was the first time
this season the Dodgers scored more than three runs in an inning
without hitting a homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference in hitting fourth compared to somewhere else is
you're going to have more chances to drive in runs,'' Karros said.
``I had three opportunities today. When you're hitting fifth or
sixth you may only have one chance in a game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
