<HEADLINE>
REV. JESSE JACKSON DELEGATION IS WELCOMED BY YUGOSLAV OFFICIALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Yugoslav government officials welcomed
the Rev. Jesse Jackson and a group of American Christian, Jewish
and Muslim leaders Thursday at a border crossing with Croatia,
providing them with an escort to the capital and a promise that
they would meet President Slobodan Milosevic and three captive
American soldiers during their three days here.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-member delegation, whose trip has irritated the Clinton
administration, was openly relieved at the reception. The Rev. Joan
Brown Campbell, general-secretary of the National Council of
Churches, described the scheduled meetings on Friday with the
soldiers and on Saturday with Milosevic as ``a serious program.''
</P>
<P>
   The clerics have said they hope to persuade Milosevic to release
the soldiers as an act of good will that could lead to a diplomatic
solution in Kosovo. They are also to meet with religious leaders in
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``They represent civil society and they must be heard,'' said
Jackson, referring to the Serbian Orthodox patriarch and others who
have expressed anger at the NATO bombing and support for
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The group flew on commercial airlines from Washington to Zagreb,
Croatia, and then traveled in a rented bus, crammed with television
crew members and journalists, to the border. There they took a bus
provided by the government to Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The group traveled under a full moon shining down from a
cloudless sky. It seemed to be perfect weather for bombing, a
situation that evoked nervousness from many on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are definitely in a war zone,'' Jackson said as the bus
pulled up at the Hyatt Hotel in central Belgrade, not far from a
bombed-out building and near a billboard that said, in English:
``We believe in God. They believe in bombs.''
</P>
<P>
   The bus trip began on a religious note. The clerics _ Serbian
Orthodox, Roman Catholic, Methodist, Russian Orthodox and Jewish,
with an official of the American Muslim Council _ held hands across
their seats and bowed their heads as Jackson offered a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bond us as brothers and sisters and as instruments of thy
peace,'' he said. ``We hope you will be the wind beneath our
wings.''
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Washington, the group met with Sandy Berger, the
national security adviser, who told them of the administration's
concerns that the trip would become a propaganda tool for
Yugoslavia. He also warned them that their mission would prolong
the war.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have said they neither approve nor
disapprove of the visit, but do not view the three soldiers,
captured by Yugoslav forces last month near the border with
Macedonia, as bargaining chips.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the group, non-clerics, have their own agendas.
One, Obrad Kesic, a Serbian-American businessman, said he had used
his contacts in the Serb military and government to arrange the
trip and hopes to bring about an end to the allied attacks by
creating disunity in Belgrade or in NATO.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
