<HEADER>
A8641 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPERSE-DANCE-2TAKES     04-29 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPERSE-DANCE-2TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBSESSED WITH A VISION OF EXISTENTIAL DESPAIR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wis., N.C., Md.)   (af)  
 William Harris writes on dance, art and theater in Manhattan.  
 By WILLIAM HARRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Albert Camus had made dances instead of writing fiction, they
might have looked like the work of the choreographer John Jasperse.
The final image of Jasperse's ``Waving to You From Here,'' which
was performed at Dance Theater Workshop in Manhattan two years ago,
still haunts with its depiction of despair.
</P>
<P>
   A false ceiling, which had slowly lowered over the dancers'
heads during the hourlong concert, finally collapsed on them. A
metaphor, in part, for the shrinking dance world, devastated by
AIDS and a declining audience, it was also a literal image of the
experimental artist being crushed by the world he has created.
</P>
<P>
   Out of that destruction has come the inspiration for Jasperse's
new work, ``Madison as I Imagine It.'' The 55-minute abstract dance
for four people _ Miguel Guitierrez, Parker Lutz, Juliette Mapp
(who is from Madison, Wis.) and Jasperse _ with music by Hahn Rowe,
received its world premiere two weeks ago at the Spring Dance
Festival in Utrecht, the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Thursday, the John Jasperse Company will present it in
eight performances at Dance Theater Workshop, through May 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the work I have made up to now had this consistency of
looking at the world and saying, here is my statement about the
problem,'' said Jasperse. ``It didn't really propose any kind of
solution. If that world in `Waving' has collapsed, now what? What
do you do now? The new piece is about how imagination deals with a
circumstance and reinvents it. It's difficult making dance, and
it's especially difficult making dance in New York. I felt I wanted
to be proactive about creating an alternative way of thinking about
dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Jasperse, a very skinny, 6-foot-2-inch man of 35, looks more
like a gangly teen-ager than someone who has been dancing
professionally since 1985. Yet he is one of the hottest _ and
brainiest _ choreographers on the downtown scene and is
increasingly asked to choreograph for other companies.
</P>
<P>
   His dances are fragmented, gesture-based explorations aboutidentity, intimacy and anxiety. He has little use for traditional
dance vocabulary. ``What people think of as beautiful dance has
always left me frustrated and alienated,'' said Jasperse, who
prefers jagged lines and entangled limbs.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his movements are absurdly task-oriented, like the
repeated stacking and restacking of piles of books in ``Waving to
You From Here.'' Others are less about the body and more about the
flow of energy in the room.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in ``Madison as I Imagine It,'' the dancers wave
their arms in a synchronized fury, like a squadron of hyperactive
airport ground personnel. Still others can be disarming.
</P>
<P>
   In Jasperse's 1995 ``Excessories,'' a dance about sexuality and
the fetishization of the body, five dancers stood downstage staring
blankly while tugging and jiggling each other's exposed breasts and
penises. But the cumulative effect is always the same: Jasperse's
work is hypnotic and unsettling.
</P>
<P>
   Within the dances are also formalist concerns about spatial
relationships and perception _ for instance, how a viewer can be
manipulated to see the whole body in motion, or just the fingers
executing some indecipherable sign language, to recapture what
mesmerized him about dance in the first place. ``Dance has a power
to somehow express something that is inexpressible,'' Jasperse
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``John is incredibly inventive and intelligent,'' says Stephanie
Reinhart, who is the director, with her husband, Charles, of the
American Dance Festival in Durham, N.C. ``He takes rituals of
everyday life and transforms them poetically, triggering memories
of your own.'' The Reinharts have commissioned a new piece to be
presented at the festival in July _ the choreographer's first
appearance there.
</P>
<P>
   Jasperse is one of the few experimental choreographers who works
with sets. ``I am really sick of seeing an empty black-void box,''
he said. Upon entering the theater for ``Madison as I Imagine It,''
the audience will see a three-sided white drop hanging from the
ceiling to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the sides will be tilted, forming a parallelogram, and the
back will be sliced off on the diagonal with the black wall behind
it visible, creating a weird floating room. Meanwhile, upstage
right, will be a table, precariously balanced on legs of different
heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sense of something being a bit off,'' explained
Jasperse, who designed the set as well as the unisex costumes,
which he also constructed. ``It's not about nice, pristine
symmetry, but about asymmetry. I'm definitely mining territory
about unsureness or lack of security, a sense of fragility and
awkwardness. The architecture of the set and the movement are a
reflection of the psychodynamics of the piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't necessarily a real place, it's a place as I
imagined it. Not the place that you know or have actually been to,
but maybe a place that you've heard about, one you may want to go
to or are afraid to go to.''
</P>
<P>
   Jasperse grew up in a Maryland suburb of Washington, the
youngest of three children. His mother is a former nun. His father
was an electrical engineer who worked for the Navy designing radar
systems. (The father, Roger Jasperse, also built the low-tech
apparatus that allowed the ceiling to fall in ``Waving to You From
Here.'')
</P>
<P>
   Jasperse started taking dance classes at 14 and dreamed of a
career in the musical theater. But while in high school, he
discovered a love for post-modern dance and went to Sarah Lawrence
College to pursue that interest. Shortly after graduating in 1985,
he began showing solo pieces as well as dancing in the works of
other choreographers like Anne Teresa De Keersmaeker. He started
making his own group works in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excessories'' was the dance that put Jasperse on the
international dance-festival-circuit map. That piece won the Prix
d'Auteur at Les Rencontres Internationales Chorographiques de
Bagnolet in 1996, a prestigious prize for contemporary
choreography, and has subsequently been performed throughout
Europe, South America and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   It also led to a commission by Batsheva Dance Company, the
modern troupe based in Tel Aviv, which will be presented in
February, 2000. In addition, a piece by Jasperse has been
commissioned by the Baryshnikov Dance Foundation for the White Oak
Project.
</P>
<P>
   Choreographic commissions will help keep the John Jasperse
Company, with its modest $130,000 annual budget, barely solvent.
Obviously, no one relying on an income from Jasperse is renting in
the Hamptons this summer. Although it bothers him that the money he
has earned is hardly commensurate with the critical acclaim he has
received, Jasperse is not giving up.
</P>
<P>
   ``With `Waving,' I was feeling totally beaten down,'' he said,
``and filled with so many questions about whether I wanted to keep
making dances. Here I was being a successful choreographer, this is
what I had always wanted, and it felt kind of empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of my work has been about power, about people defining
themselves in terms of others. I feel the energy we're trying to
address now is much more adult. This dance is kind of like you're
sitting on a street corner and a day passes. There's continuity of
events you experience through that block of time, even if they
don't necessarily make sense immediately.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
