</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDEPENDENT-FILMS-3TAKES-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIE FILM IS LOSING ITS VIGOR AS IT AGES 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Graham Fuller is executive editor of Interview Magazine and editor
of ``Loach on Loach,'' about the director Ken Loach.  
 By GRAHAM FULLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In one of the most memorable scenes in ``Hype!,'' a playfully
ironic documentary that was introduced at the 1996 Sundance Film
Festival, a young fan laments the commercialization of the Seattle
music scene that had spawned the grunge-rock movement of the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   A miserable expression clouds the youth's face as he recalls how
he supported a particular group at the beginning of its career when
it had a small following, only to watch its growing popularity ruin
it as something meaningful to him.
</P>
<P>
   His disillusion will be familiar to anyone who has attended the
birth of a grass-roots cultural revolution, then witnessed it being
co-opted by bigger, stronger forces that rob it of its original
spark.
</P>
<P>
   The same kind of disillusion is beginning to surround another
artistic movement that flourished in the early 90s but has turned
into a hyperbolized growth industry: American independent cinema.
</P>
<P>
   Production of independent films in the United States is at an
all-time high (about 1,000 starts a year), and there is an
expanding market for them on television, with the success of cable
networks like the Independent Film Channel, and on the
ever-burgeoning festival circuit. But within the entertainment
business, the consensus suddenly seems to be that, documentaries
aside, powerful, innovative independent films are thin, and that it
has been a while since anything has measured up to the likes of
``Stranger Than Paradise,'' ``She's Gotta Have It,'' ``Blood
Simple,'' ``Sex, Lies and Videotape,'' ``Reservoir Dogs'' or
``Safe,'' to name some of the high points of the movement.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-directors like Todd Solondz (``Welcome to the
Dollhouse,'' ``Happiness'') and Neil LaBute (``In the Company of
Men,'' ``Your Friends and Neighbors'') are, perhaps, the only
unique voices to have emerged in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality of American independent film is weak,'' said Tom
Bernard, a co-president of Sony Pictures Classics, which is
stirring several home-grown indies into the mix of films it is
distributing this year. These include the August release ``Twin
Falls Idaho,'' a tale of conjoined twins that will need glowing
reviews to attract audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Cary Woods, the producer of such diverse independent films as
Larry Clark's ``Kids'' and Wes Craven's ``Scream,'' was just as
blunt. ``The independent scene has fallen into a formulaic rut,''
he said. ``There's a dearth of fresh and original filmmaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Some might accuse ``Scream'' itself of bringing an unwelcome and
hugely influential streak of exploitation to indie cinema. To give
Woods his due, though, his new company, Independent Pictures, has
just produced ``The Julian Chronicles,'' the second film directed
by Harmony Korine, whose first, ``Gummo,'' was one of the most
audacious, least seen experimental films of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   As despised in some quarters as it was praised in others,
Korine's debut was undeniably the work of an obsessive maker of
images, a director who isn't a slave to narrative conventions but
an artist _ a difficult one to be sure _ intent on plowing his own
intentionally wayward furrow.
</P>
<P>
   Ideologically speaking, he is a true independent. He is also
that rarity, a young filmmaker with a vast knowledge of cinema.
</P>
<P>
   The crucial problem that seems to beset the current independent
scene is that a spirit of careerism has replaced the sense of
vocation that originally fueled it and resulted in the most
invigorated personal films. Whereas Korine will rave about a Werner
Herzog film from the early '70s with the same zeal with which you
hear Martin Scorsese enthusing about Michael Powell's ``Red Shoes''
or Steven Spielberg about David Lean's ``Lawrence of Arabia,'' many
of his peers tend to discuss who the hot agents are.
</P>
<P>
   One indication that accomplished American indies are few and far
between right now is the low level of industry buzz on those films
set for release this summer or fall. Among the films generating
excitement are ``The Blair Witch Project,'' a creepy
mock-documentary written and directed by Dan Myrick and Eduardo
Sanchez that is opening in July, and ... nothing else whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twin Falls Idaho,'' made by the identical twins Michael and
Mark Polish, and other forthcoming films like Eric Mendelsohn's
suburban drama ``Judy Berlin,'' Jim Fall's gay romantic comedy
``Trick,'' the producer-turned-director Scott King's World War
II-era drama ``Treasure Island'' and Mark Illsley's gender-bending
comedy ``Happy, Texas,'' all have a track record at Sundance and
other festivals, but no one is claiming they are truly special.
</P>
<P>
   For distributors and consumers looking for a small gem, like
Whit Stillman's ``Metropolitan'' or David O. Russell's ``Spanking
the Monkey,'' pickings are slim.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989, when ``Sex, Lies and Videotape'' took Sundance by
storm, the most accurate barometer for American independent film
has been the reception accorded to selections at the festival,
which takes place in Utah in January. And it's virtually impossible
to find a distributor or producer who is enthusiastic about the
fictional movies that were shown at Sundance '99.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking at the dramatic competition, I saw a lack of passion
comparable to what that festival usually programs, and I think that
is a general reflection of what is being made,'' said Mary
Glucksman, programming director for First Look, a film organization
that provides a distribution and marketing platform for 9 or 10
independent features a year.
</P>
<P>
   Equally glum was Mark Urman, co-president of Lion's Gate
Releasing. ``I must say I came out of Sundance a bit distressed
because there was nothing to buy, although the dust is still
settling,'' said Urman, whose company in 1998 picked up six
Sundance titles, including two, ``Gods and Monsters'' and
``Affliction,'' that went on to significant critical success.
</P>
<P>
   Even Jeff Gilmore, director of programming at Sundance since
1990, was cautious. ``There was work at the festival this year that
I thought was extremely interesting and in some sense
iconoclastic,'' he said. ``Perhaps not entirely successful in every
case, but usually involving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty pleased when I see films like `Pi' or `Slam' or
`Three Seasons' or `Judy Berlin,' which don't fit into the hyped
and preordained categories of what people expect independent films
to be,'' he said, referring to two 1998 selections and two from
this year. ``It wasn't just critics that were saying they were
tired of looking at twenty-something angst films. We were getting
pretty tired of them, too. But of the 800 films that we looked at
for the dramatic competition this year, I have to say many of them
were very formulaic.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry insiders aren't blaming Sundance for the apparent drop
in quality; most recognize that a festival is only as good as the
films available. They're pointing instead to a mood of opportunism
that has steadily engulfed the indie movement since it became a
conduit to directorial stardom in 1992, the year Quentin
Tarantino's ``Reservoir Dogs'' became the benchmark for neophyte
filmmakers.
</P>
<P>
   One result of the inordinate attention given to the indie
explosion of the mid-90s is that most first-time directors in this
country now seem driven less by the need to make an artistic
statement than by the desire to expedite their Hollywood careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It created some false expectations on the part of people who
felt they wanted to become directors,'' said Emily Russo,
co-president of the boutique distributor Zeitgeist Films.
``Filmmaking is a talent. Just as not everyone can write a good
book, not everyone can make a good film. But these days anyone with
enough initiative and drive can make a film. But that's not the
same thing as having a true filmmaker's sensibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Gill Holland, the producer of ``Desert Blue,'' which will be
released this summer, put it in even stronger terms. ``There's a
lot of rich kids out there who can come up with $500,000 to make a
movie with talented people,'' he said. ``The problem is they don't
know how to direct actors, they don't know how to handle crews,
they've never even made a short film. A lot of them think they have
talent, but they don't, and some of them are siphoning off funds
from more deserving cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Urman blames the hype, but also believes that much of the
downturn is an inevitable part of an aging process. ``American
independent film as a classification has matured to the extent that
it's actually become self-aware and a little decadent,'' he said.
``Because a machinery has been put into place _ the festival
circuit and a whole generation of distributors geared to bringing
these films to market _ it's less about the individual struggle of
the filmmaker and more about the bandwagon. As soon as that
happens, you get a different kind of movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is now a cottage industry that is so watched and written
about, it's simply impossible for independent films to
spontaneously erupt anymore,'' Urman added. ``Independent
filmmakers are going into production knowing that they can have a
cassette to show or a print to screen by the submission deadline
for Sundance or some other notable festival or market. They attach
themselves from day one to agents, sales agents, publicists and
other representatives who will advance them. When people set out to
become an overnight sensation, it's very different from setting out
to make a good movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernard notes the absence among new directors of genuine auteurs
like John Sayles, Jim Jarmusch and Hal Hartley, who have mostly
opted to work outside the Hollywood system because they are
unwilling to accept the artistic compromises inherent in making
studio films. ``The motivation for most kids to make independent
movies is not to have a means of independent expression, to say
something you can't say within the system, but to get into the
system, become a major director, and get rich,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Allison Anders, the writer-director of such personal,
story-driven films as ``Gas Food Lodging'' and ``Mi Vida Loca,'' is
so disenchanted with the United States indie business that she is
thinking of moving to Britain, where she raised the money for her
latest movie, ``Sugar Town,'' a Sundance entry scheduled to open in
the fall.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still some good American directors scrounging to
make independent films,'' she said, ``but I think the movement is
basically over. The trend that has really bothered me is the white
middle-class boy movie. I'm so tired of hearing that voice. In
general, I don't think the guys who make those kinds of films
really know what they want to be _ they could be a filmmaker, a
rock star, whatever _ but they're very good at usurping what's
going on in the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Anders also blames the post-``Scream'' influx of stars into
indie films for foisting a level of mainstream blandness onto them.
``As a director, you should really be passionate about the stories
you want to tell and making sure you have the actors you want to
tell them with, and you shouldn't compromise too much.''
</P>
<P>
   John Pierson, who presents the Independent Film Channel program
``Split Screen,'' and who has shepherded many vibrant
micro-budgeted films to completion, suggests that frequently young
filmmakers, having not studied pre-'90s cinema, do not have the
faintest grasp of film narrative. ``Many of the trendsetting
independent films, including some I've been involved in myself,
have championed the idea of the character-driven movie,'' he said.
``But many of them have fallen into the trap of thinking that
creating an interesting character is enough, meaning there often
isn't much of a story when you add it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore put it this way: ``The fundamental knowledge of
storytelling isn't as imbued in many young filmmakers as it should
be, but they know all about grosses. A lot of them simply can't
talk to you about films and filmmakers. They can't sit there and
say, `This is the Nicholas Ray film that inspired me,' because they
won't have seen any of his films. We've got to get back to film
literacy in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not just the naked ambition or artistic callowness of
today's young wannabe directors that is taking the gleam off the
golden era of American independent film. Independently produced
movies have traditionally required several weeks to ``build'' in
theaters. The glut of mediocre pictures _ from Hollywood studios or
not _ has created a situation in which low-grossing films are being
pushed out of theaters more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rise in independent productions has led to a rise in the
number of releases,'' Pierson said, ``and nobody can deny that has
caused good films to cannibalize each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the art houses that showed independent films in the
'60s,'70s and '80s have been swallowed by theater chains, which are
more likely to show ``Shakespeare in Love'' _ that $41 million,
Oscar-grabbing faux indie produced by the Disney-owned Miramax _
than rawer films like ``Slam'' or ``Buffalo 66.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With a few exceptions, theater owners are so greedy that
they're not making room for the really edgy product,'' Bernard
said. And this makes it even more unlikely that a first-time
director will make a risky film with limited commercial prospects.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a moral to this story, it is that more means less.
</P>
<P>
   But ``even more'' is what is about to happen to the American
independent film scene with the advent of digital video, a format
that will enable anyone who can raise around $50,000 to make a film
with high production values.
</P>
<P>
   This format has been used to great effect by the Danish
directors Lars von Trier (the forthcoming ``The Idiots'') and
Thomas Vinterberg (``The Celebration''), whose Dogma 95 manifesto
calls for shooting in natural light with hand-held cameras. It's a
good bet that digital video will become pandemic in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no let-up in production, that's for sure,'' said
Pierson, figuratively throwing his hands up in the air. ``There
will always be first-timers who, come hell or high water, are going
to make a feature film. You'd think a lot of people who make a
feature that disappears without a trace would lick their wounds and
go away, but most of them come back and make another. There should
be some kind of 12-step program to break people of this habit _
maybe I should start it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
