<HEADLINE>
AT THE SCENE OF A CRIME?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By MICHELLE COTTLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I recently discovered that the corporate division in which I
am a manager has been engaging in practices that are at least
questionable and possibly illegal. With a few discreet questions, I
have learned that the vice president in charge of the division
sanctions the activities and that my peers don't share my qualms.
Without disclosing my reason, I have lined up a transfer out of the
division, but it won't take effect for several months. In the
meantime, how can I protect myself if things blow up? Should I talk
to a lawyer?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. ``Possibly illegal'' is not the same as illegal _ or even
unethical. At this stage, you need more facts about the issues
involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Try to determine whether you're calling the line too close''
advised James Schrager, a business ethicist and professor of
strategy at the University of Chicago's Graduate School of
Business. Because you seem to be the only person who questions
these activities, you may be overreacting.
</P>
<P>
   To understand your company's actions _ and how or why it may be
bending the rules _ talk to your peers, Schrager said. Someone may
be able to explain the situation to your satisfaction. ``But if
you're hearing things like, `everybody does it,' or `they've never
stopped us before,' or `the law is poorly written,' there may be a
real problem,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, there is good news: In most cases, you don't have
much to worry about from a legal standpoint. ``If an individual
employee is not engaging in wrongful or criminal activity, then
there isn't much likelihood of individual liability,'' said Philip
M. Berkowitz, a management employment lawyer with Salans Hertzfeld
Heilbronn Christy &AMP; Viener of New York.
</P>
<P>
   But if you think you should distance yourself from your
division's practices, get your objections on record, Schrager said.
</P>
<P>
   Talk to your boss, but be sure to keep the conversation private
and nonconfrontational. ``If you make it a personal dispute between
you and the boss, that doesn't do anybody any good,'' Berkowitz
said.
</P>
<P>
   As a last resort, consider talking to in-house counsel. The
lawyer could not only clarify the law, but the conversation could
also document your concerns. Be aware, though, that the lawyer will
almost certainly tell your boss about the discussion.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid the appearance of going over your boss's head, you may
want to ask him or her for clearance first. (Of course, even if
nothing shady is going on, your boss may take offense, refuse your
request or even blow up at you.)
</P>
<P>
   Think twice about approaching an outside lawyer. Not only will
it cost you serious money, but the lawyer also won't have a
complete picture of your organization, Schrager said. And should
anyone find out, your loyalty could be questioned.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, if the behavior you've uncovered is serious enough to
merit your own legal representation, you may want to think less
about protecting yourself until your transfer, and more about
finding another employer altogether. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she responds
to readers' questions about career and workplace issues. Send them
by e-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by mail to Working, Money &AMP;
Business, The New York Times, 229 West 43d Street, New York, N.Y.
10036.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
