<SLUG> BC-BIZ-SENIORITY-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATCHING UP, FOR TRAVEL AND MORE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Pa., Mich.)   (af)  
 By FRED BROCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For seven years after her husband died in 1977, Margaret Hayward
didn't go out much. Then, in 1985, when she was 67, she went as a
single traveler on a group tour of Europe. ``I found that rather
lonely,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   So in 1988, she joined Travel Companion Exchange of Amityville,
N.Y. It manages a registry of single, divorced or widowed people
who are looking for travel companions and, in some cases, romance
or marriage.
</P>
<P>
   In the decade since she found the organization, Mrs. Hayward,
now 81, a retired church organist who lives in Centerport, N.Y.,
has taken trips several times a year, to scores of countries. Her
traveling companions, all arranged through Travel Companion
Exchange, have always been men, and she has never traveled with the
same one twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had heard from some women friends that other women didn't
make good traveling companions,'' Mrs. Hayward said. ``So I started
out with that in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Any problems sharing a room with a man? ``Not with me,'' she
said. ``I'm a normal female. None of them were suitable to marry
after my husband, but that's my problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Hayward usually meets potential travel companions for a
``day or so'' in advance of a trip in an attempt to make sure they
are compatible. But she concedes that on at least one occasion, the
initial meeting amounted only to a lunch.
</P>
<P>
   When Jans Jurgen started Travel Companion Exchange in 1982, his
goal was to provide a service that would help travelers save money
by sharing expenses and avoiding single-supplement charges. He had
little inkling he would end up as a matchmaker. ``I was really
surprised at the number of ladies who wanted men as travel
companions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he tries to appeal to all age groups, in recent years
the majority of his clients have been over 50. The group has 2,500
active members who pay $159 to $298 a year for access to extensive
profiles of possible companions as well as a travel newsletter
published every other month.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jurgen, more than 70 percent of his clients either
request companions of the opposite sex or are willing to accept
them; fewer than 15 percent want private rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Another 500 people subscribe only to the newsletter, for $48 a
year. For either service, the address is Travel Companion Exchange,
Box 833, Amityville, N.Y. 11701 (phone 800 392-1256).
</P>
<P>
   Jurgen, 63, who now operates the service with the help of his
wife, Eul Lee, estimates that his match-up service has led to as
many as 800 marriages _ including his own. He met Ms. Lee, who is
43, five years ago when she signed up as a client; they married in
1997. It was his second marriage and her first.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, things don't always work out so swimmingly, which is
why Jurgen requires profiles of all members and advises prospective
travel companions to meet before they take off together. Mrs.
Hayward, for instance, turned down travel with a man who wanted to
rough it for a month in an Asian beach house that had no running
water or toilet facilities.
</P>
<P>
   But for Maralynne Flehner and Larry Spielvogel of King of
Prussia, Pa., joining up as travel companions in 1990 for a trip to
Africa turned into love at first flight. They were married the next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Flehner, now 52, was a Wall Street lawyer when she met
Spielvogel, a consulting engineer based in King of Prussia. She had
been divorced once and then widowed. Spielvogel, 60, said he had
been a ``confimed bachelor'' all his life. Ms. Flehner quit her job
and moved to Pennsylvania when they married.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never, ever expected to find anybody who was so much like
me,'' Ms. Flehner said. ``It was a stroke of luck. When I found
myself widowed in my early 40s, I was not someone who felt
comfortable going into a bar to meet people. What do you do? There
are so few resources available for middle-aged and older people to
meet each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Spielvogel echoed a complaint of many single people who turn to
services like Jurgen's: They may have friends, but the friends
often don't have the time, inclination or money to travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a bachelor, I dated many women, but when I decided
it was time for a vacation, the majority of them either weren't
interested in going to places where I wanted to go or couldn't take
the time to go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   James Flannigan, 71, and Marilyn Laughlin, 66, of Williamston,
Mich., also found each other, in 1997, through travel. They now
live together but have opted not to marry. Flannigan is a retired
criminal investigator for the United States Justice Department, and
Ms. Laughlin is a retired teacher and a former Roman Catholic nun.
</P>
<P>
   Flannigan joined Jurgen's travel service a year or so after his
wife of 38 years died in 1987. He always chose female travel
companions and praised them recently in a letter to the Travel
Companion Exchange newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   They included, he said, the ``nudist that visited the Palm
Springs Nudist Resort with me and the marvelous (ex-nun) companion
with whom I (an atheist) now reside.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
