<HEADLINE>
IN SEARCH OF THE PERFECT SECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of mutual fund newsletters that pursue sector
rotation strategies is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2)  
 (af)  
 By MARK HULBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most popular strategies for mutual fund investors is
sector rotation. More than 20 of the 66 fund newsletters tracked by
The Hulbert Financial Digest pursue such a strategy at least in
part, three times the total a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   There are many variations, but in general, sector rotation means
switching among sector funds _ those that specialize in particular
industries _ in the hope of always being in the best-performing
sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors pursue the strategy through Fidelity Investments,
which offers 38 sector funds, designated by the word ``Select'' in
their names, as in Fidelity Select Regional Banks.
</P>
<P>
   The allure of sector rotation is easy to understand. If you were
lucky enough to have been invested in the best-performing Select
fund in each of the last 10 calendar years, you would have made
64.4 percent a year, on average, versus 19.2 percent for the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   Few investors, of course, are lucky enough to be in the
top-performing sector fund in any given year, let alone for 10
consecutive years. Yet to hear some newsletters trumpet their
returns, you'd think investors could come awfully close to such
good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Funny things can happen on the way to the bank. The real-world
returns of newsletters' sector-rotation portfolios don't come
anywhere close to 64.4 percent a year. In fact, few portfolios even
match the market. And those that do are inordinately risky.
</P>
<P>
   Among the newsletters I track, the one that has made the most
money over the last decade investing in Select funds is Fidelity
Monitor of Rocklin, Calif., edited by Jack Bowers. His sector
rotation portfolio made 21.5 percent a year, on average, for the 10
years ended March 31, according to The Hulbert Financial Digest,
versus 18.7 percent for the S&AMP;P 500 (And Bowers makes no claims of
anything more.)
</P>
<P>
   That 21.6 percent return is impressive _ until you consider the
portfolio's risk, which was 21 percent greater than the market's.
To put that risk and return into perspective, imagine that 10 years
ago, you decided to buy an S&AMP;P 500 index fund on 21 percent margin
_ that is, for each $100 in your portfolio, you borrowed $21 and
invested $121 in the fund. Your risk would have been the same as
that of Bowers' portfolio, yet you would have made slightly more _
an average of 21.8 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Only one sector-rotation portfolio I track has beaten the stock
market on a risk-adjusted basis over its life _ though not over
just the last 10 years. It is maintained by Investors Intelligence,
edited by Michael Burke.
</P>
<P>
   Since I began following it at the beginning of 1987, it has had
an average annual return of 14.5 percent, versus 17.8 percent for
the S&AMP;P 500, but with 29 percent less risk. If your portfolio had
contained an index fund and T-bills in the proper combination to be
29 percent less risky than the market, it would have made 14.4
percent annualized, slightly less than Burke's portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Burke's portfolio is the exception that proves the
rule: Its beating the market on a risk-adjusted basis has nothing
to do with sector rotation. Instead, it is a result of timing the
market. Before some market declines, he reduced his exposure to the
Select funds and increased his cash position.
</P>
<P>
   I calculate that if he hadn't used market timing and had focused
instead on sector rotation, his portfolio would have lagged behind
the S&AMP;P.
</P>
<P>
   Consider what would have happened if, every time Burke directed
you to buy a Fidelity Select fund, you bought an index fund
instead. Over the last 12\ years, you would have picked up an extra
1.3 percentage points of annual return. Better yet, you would have
incurred only three-fourths the risk that Burke's portfolio did.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Burke reduced returns and increased risk by
investing in sector funds.
</P>
<P>
   Keep that in mind the next time you're ready to pursue a
sector-rotation strategy. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hulbert is editor of the Hulbert Financial Digest, a
newsletter based in Alexandria, Va. His column on investment
strategies appears every other week. E-mail:
strategy(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
