<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8656 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KID-INSURANCE-HNS &LR;      04-29 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KID-INSURANCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LHOUSE OKS INSURANCE PLAN FOR CHILDREN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Eager to tap $423 million a year in federal
matching funds, Texas lawmakers on Thursday moved a step closer to
establishing a state-supported children's health insurance program
to help low-income residents under age 19.
</P>
<P>
   The House unanimously approved the plan after a fiery three-hour
debate, during which repeated attempts by conservatives to limit
eligibility were turned back.
</P>
<P>
   The bill still must be returned to the Senate because it was
changed by House members in several major ways. It was expanded to
include 55,000 children more than the Senate version and was
amended to say that if federal funding ceases, the state program
would, too.
</P>
<P>
   The measure was described as ``conservative, compassionate and
good for Texas'' by sponsoring Rep. Patricia Gray, D-Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   As tentatively approved, Senate Bill 445 by Sen. Mike Moncrief,
D-Fort Worth, would cover about 445,000 uninsured children whose
family income falls above the Medicaid eligibility limit but below
200 percent of the poverty level. For fiscal 1999, the poverty
level for a family of four is $16,800, so the bill would apply to
families earning up to twice that, or $33,600.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 1.4 million Texas children may be uninsured,
officials estimate.
</P>
<P>
   About $180 million has been set aside for the next two years for
the Children's Health Insurance Program, which would attract about
three times that amount from the federal government. A 1997 federal
law stated that Texas was eligible to receive an average of $423
million a year for the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   During a protracted committee review process, several lawmakers
sought to tinker with the income limits and other factors to either
increase or decrease the number of children who would be covered.
One proposed amendment on Thursday would have limited the program
to children under the age of 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make sure the youngest kids, the most vulnerable
kids, are covered first,'' said Rep. Kyle Janek, R-Houston, who
proposed the change, which was defeated.
</P>
<P>
   But the most stirring debate centered on a proposal to ax a
separately funded program to provide health insurance for legal
immigrant children. Rep. Arlene Wohlgemuth, R-Burleson, withdrew
her suggestion after complaining that her motives were mistakenly
construed as racist.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is being characterized as being a race-based, prejudicial
amendment, and it is not, was not to begin with, was never intended
to be. This was about a program that had been put into this bill
that I did not feel belonged in this bill,'' Wohlgemuth said.
</P>
<P>
   Several members had implied that Wohlgemuth was unfairly
slighting immigrant children. They argued that the impacted
children are too young to apply for citizenship and are already
endangered by inadequate health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the state of Texas to make a statement today that those
families that are coming here are welcome and those children are
going to be covered under this program,'' said Rep. Leticia Van de
Putte, D-San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about fellow Texans,'' thundered Rep. Rene
Oliveira, D-Brownsville. He said the move to strike the immigrants'
eligibility was akin to California's efforts to deny services to
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's House sponsor said lawmakers have been wrangling over
the proposal since August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have here today an enormous opportunity. We have secure
funding that will insure our kids, and I can think of no better use
for that funding than to fully invest in the health of our
community,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the primary reason for taking advantage of the
so-called ``CHIP`` program is that Texas is home to one in 10
uninsured children in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through broad-based, consensus decision-making, the cosponsors
of this legislation bring to you today a bill that we believe is
conservative, compassionate and good for Texas,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill faces a final House vote Friday before being returned
to the Senate. In the unlikely event that the Senate accepts the
House amendments, it would go to Gov. George W. Bush. But members
in both chambers have indicated that a House-Senate negotiating
committee will have to be appointed to resolve dozens of major and
minor differences.
</P>
<P>
   If finally approved, the program would come into existence on
Sept. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
