</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REALESTATE-MARKETPLACE-ART-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS SHOW MORE INTEREST IN REIT STOCKS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Colo., Ill., Mass., N.J., Pa.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until now, Warren Buffett's best-known real estate gamble was on
a bank.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, his Berkshire Hathaway bought a big stake in Wells
Fargo amid a California real estate slump. The bank did not break
out of the real estate quagmire for two years, and Buffett later
acknowledged that he had not foreseen the severity of the problem
even though his investment ultimately paid off handsomely.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Omaha billionaire is betting on real estate again. And
investors are left to wonder if he has correctly spotted the bottom
_ this time in real estate stocks _ or if he is early again.
</P>
<P>
   Buffett has spent more than $50 million, much of it in personal
funds, on shares of four REITs, with three purchases disclosed this
month. REITs, the publicly traded companies that own shopping
centers, apartment complexes, office buildings and other
properties, have been in the doldrums even as rents and real estate
values strengthen across much of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But they are coming to life. News of Buffett's purchases, and a
broad rebound in cyclical stocks that tend to soar with the
economy, has pushed REIT indexes about 10 percent higher in the
last month, the first good news for real estate shareholders since
the sector peaked in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the sudden shift, real estate stocks look cheap by some
measures. For example, the stocks in the Standard &AMP; Poor's big
company index are trading at about 34 times their earnings.
</P>
<P>
   For the last dozen years or so, that multiple has been about 1.5
times the average REIT's funds from operations, an industry measure
similar to cash flow. The stock multiple is now more than three
times the real estate average.
</P>
<P>
   Investors pulled money out of real estate mutual funds every
week for four months, but reversed course in the week ended April
21, pouring about $80 million into these funds, according to AMG
Data Services, an Arcata, Calif., mutual fund researcher.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the attraction is the relatively high yields _ on
average, at least 2 percentage points more than on Treasury notes.
Wall Street analysts anticipate double-digit profit growth at many
real estate trusts this year. This means yields will remain strong,
since REITs pay out 95 percent of their taxable income to
shareholders every year to avoid taxes.
</P>
<P>
   REITs could still get hurt if the economy stumbles. But few
analysts expect problems anytime soon. Corporate earnings continue
to be surprisingly strong, and many economists have pronounced the
fallout from the financial crises in Asia, Russia and Brazil to
have passed. Meanwhile, commodity prices have stabilized _ a
bullish sign for real estate and other assets that perform well
with higher inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The current environment is similar to that at the bottoms of the
last six REIT cycles, says Bob Steers, co-manager of the Cohen &AMP;
Steers Realty Shares fund. Over the last three decades, he says,
the average bear market for real estate stocks lasted 14 months and
share prices declined by about one-quarter. Before the April rally,
the stocks had been in a slump for a little longer and had declined
a bit more.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the group is ready to move, it's ready to move because it
has been oversold,'' Steers said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Among the big real estate funds without high minimum investment
requirements, top performers for the three years ended in March
include Longleaf Partners Realty, with a 10.7 percent annualized
return; Cohen &AMP; Steers Realty Shares, 9.3 percent; Fidelity Real
Estate Investment Portfolio, 8.4 percent, and CGM Realty, 8.3
percent. All figures are from Morningstar Inc., the fund tracking
company in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the recent rally, analysts say shares in REITs are
mostly trading for less than the total that their properties would
sell for piecemeal. As a result, some real estate trusts are
diverting cash that would normally be used to buy properties to
buying back their stock.
</P>
<P>
   A few have even sold assets and used the proceeds for stock
buybacks. Archstone Communities, a REIT in Englewood, Colo., which
owns apartment buildings, sold property and repurchased $84.4
million in stock in February and March.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of last year, REITs have announced that they
will buy back $2.9 billion of their stock, compared with just $861
million in announced buybacks during the previous eight years
combined, according to Thomson Financial Securities Data in Newark,
N.J. CRA Real Estate Securities, a money manager in Radnor, Pa.,
counts 36 REITs that have announced buybacks since last summer, and
those have so far repurchased, on average, about 44 percent of the
shares authorized.
</P>
<P>
   Some managers are doing more than partial buybacks. An investor
group led by the company's chairman recently won a battle to
acquire Berkshire Realty outright for $12.25 a share, or a 26
percent premium to the stock's price before the buyout offer.
</P>
<P>
   And a group including the chief executive of Sunstone Hotel
Investors, a hotel operator based in San Clemente, Calif., has
offered to acquire the company for $9.50 to $10 a share, about 35
percent more than what the stock sold for earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Buffett recently disclosed that he had increased his
stake in MGI Properties, a Boston real estate trust, to 10.3
percent, as the company nears liquidation. MGI's management decided
last year that it should sell everything and distribute the cash to
shareholders because of its low stock market valuation.
</P>
<P>
   The sale is now expected to generate $29 to $30 a share, almost
one-third more than MGI shares fetched last summer, when the plan
was disclosed. Shares closed Thursday unchanged at $27.5625.
</P>
</TEXT>
