<HEADER>
A8671 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-SMART-VAN-RANKING     04-29 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-VAN-RANKINGS-ART-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S THEIR EXTRAS THAT ADD UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2)  
 (af)  
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Virtually every manufacturer has minivan ergonomics down pat.
After all, functionality, comfort and convenience are the reasons
people drive these mobile dens. So other factors now count: Four
doors have become essential for convenience (and for children's
safety on one-way streets). Power-operated sliding doors win extra
credit. I also appreciate extra horsepower and nimble handling.
Innovative features, like folding seats, are a big plus.
</P>
<P>
   Given all these demands, one van was a clear winner. Second
place was easy, too. After that, it was pretty much a tossup. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. HONDA ODYSSEY Having grown to equal a long-wheelbase Chrysler
van, the new Odyssey is the right size. Its standard four doors
include two rear sliders (electric on the EX model). The second-row
seats move sideways on tracks to create a bench or separate into
captain's chairs (leaving a DMZ between squabbling children).
</P>
<P>
   The Odyssey shares a five-star crash rating with the Windstar;
its only shortcoming is a lack of side air bags. Outfitted in fine
materials, it is packed with nice touches like a folding table
between the front seats. This van is very nimble and gets smooth,
quiet power from its 210-horsepower V6.
</P>
<P>
   But what really sets the Odyssey apart is the third-row seat
that folds into the floor _ as a single mother, I've found it
impossible to remove most vans' third-row seats by myself. Finally,
since this is a Honda, you know the Odyssey's quality is
top-notch. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. FORD WINDSTAR Ford has fixed nearly everything that was wrong
with the original Windstar _ particularly the lack of a second
sliding door. Two sliders are now standard; both can be had with
power operation. The second-row seat slides sideways and there are
rear headphone jacks.
</P>
<P>
   With its optional 3.8-liter V6, the Windstar is powerful, and
its handling is good. Safety is also a strength; in addition to its
five-star safety rating, it has optional side air bags that protect
heads and chests and sonar sensors that detect objects at the rear.
</P>
<P>
   I had two complaints that kept the Windstar out of first place:
its engine is very noisy, and its parking brake lever is awkwardly
situated to the right of the driver.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. TOYOTA SIENNA I was disappointed with the Sienna when it made
its debut. Although it is a perfectly fine vehicle, it was just a
base hit _ I had expected Toyota to hit a home run. Still, the
Sienna's nearly bullet-proof quality gives it an edge, in my view,
over the Plymouth and the Chevy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Smaller than the other tested vans, the Sienna has all the right
ergonomic pieces in place. And there are some nice touches, like
cargo nets on the side of the front seats for storing sunglasses
and wallets. Power is adequate, handling is agile and the ride is
quiet and smooth. The Sienna lacks side air bags and is available
with only one power door. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. PLYMOUTH GRAND VOYAGER I have always been a fan of Chrysler's
minivans _I used to own one _ and I've always recommended them
above all others. Chrysler still offers the most variety, with an
array of models and special packages, short wheelbase or long,
front drive or all-wheel drive, and three V6 engines.
</P>
<P>
   But the competition has moved ahead. Chrysler doesn't offer
power doors or side air bags. Its seats are awkward to remove. Its
brakes feel soft and its 3- and 3.3-liter engines are relatively
wimpy. Chrysler and Dodge (but not Plymouth) offer a more potent
3.8-liter engine; equipped that way, I'd raise my rating a notch. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. CHEVROLET VENTURE The Toyota, Plymouth and Chevy are all
close enough _ and all good enough _ that it seems a shame to rank
any van last. That said, I put the Venture at the bottom by a
narrow margin, although I consider it (and its GM stablemates from
Olds and Pontiac) a perfectly capable, acceptable alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Its side air bags are a big plus. Its acceleration and handling,
especially with the sport suspension, are solid. The cargo net
between the front seats is clever.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is narrower, it does have slightly less interior room
than the others. Only one door can be power-operated. But my
biggest complaint is about the seats, a crucial matter for
long-trip vehicles. The raised, theater-style rear seats are ideal
for small passengers who want to see out, but they are miserable
for adults. In them, I felt as if my chin were resting on my knees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 2130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
