r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WELLS-SFCHRON &LR;      04-29 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELLS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Glitch Hits Wells Customers
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Sam Zuckerman &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Wells Fargo Bank said yesterday its fast-growing online bill
payment service has repeatedly crashed since Monday in a systems
breakdown that is similar to the woes that recently have plagued
the electronic brokerage industry.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Wells Fargo, the nation's largest online bank,
said as many as 150,000 customers who use Intuit's Quicken or
Microsoft's Money software to pay bills from their bank accounts
haven't been able to get through. The bank said it did not know
when it could restore service.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Wells Fargo's 860,000 online customers pay bills
directly through the bank's Internet site and haven't been
affected.
</P>
<P>
   The bank blamed the breakdown on a software glitch at CheckFree,
the Georgia company that processes bill payments made through
Quicken and Money.
</P>
<P>
   CheckFree described the breakdown as ``intermittent'' and said
it affected customers of as many as 21 banks nationwide which use
Genesis, the company's most-advanced transaction processing system.
</P>
<P>
   The company traced the problem to a software bug that created a
bottleneck at the point that consumers enter Genesis from Quicken
or Money, spokeswoman Laurinda Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   The company is testing new software code to fix the problem but
it doesn't know when the system will be operating again, Wilson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten our customers to rely on the availability of
these systems,'' said Catherine Graeber, Wells Fargo's marketing
manager for online financial services. ``This isn't acceptable to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The bank said it is waiving April Internet banking fees, which
are as high as $8 a month, for Quicken and Money bill-payment
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Leading online brokerages, including Charles Schwab and E-Trade,
have suffered repeated failures of their electronic stock trading
systems as surges in demand have swamped their computer capacity.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, online banking has grown at at a slower, more
manageable pace, and service breakdowns have been less common. Bank
customers go online to monitor their accounts, pay bills, transfer
funds and apply for loans.
</P>
<P>
   Quicken and Money customers click on a button in their money
management software that automatically connects with CheckFree
computers to pay bills from their accounts at any of more than a
dozen banks nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Since Monday, Quicken customers who bank at Wells Fargo said
they repeatedly got messages saying Intuit was unable to complete
the connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a hard time understanding how a computer network could
be down for so long,'' said David Schnapf, a San Francisco
attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Schnapf said Wells Fargo representatives couldn't explain the
breakdown or estimate when service would be restored. ``I'm
frustrated by the lack of information,'' he complained.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the episode shows how banks and other companies
that deal directly with customers are vulnerable to errors made by
third-party vendors, such as CheckFree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problems are out of the bank's control,'' said Chris
Musto, an Internet banking analyst at Gomez Advisors in
Massachusetts. ``But to the customer, whether or not the bank
outsources is irrelevant.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 2132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0437 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8675 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON &LR;      04-29 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Preventing Violence In the Workplace
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Ilana DeBare &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  Some of the recent news stories about mass shootings
have gotten me thinking about workplace violence. I'd like to get
some training for my company in how to prevent and handle workplace
violence. Where could I find such resources?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Workplace violence is a serious problem: The federal
government estimates that 20 people are murdered and 18,000
assaulted at work  &LR; every week. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   But the most common media image of workplace violence _ the
crazed employee who goes on a shooting spree in his office _ is
quite uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   Most workplace violence involves less dramatic scenarios such as
robberies at convenience stores, gas stations and restaurants, or
one-on-one altercations between employees.
</P>
<P>
   The single highest homicide rate is found among taxi drivers,
who run the risk of robbery daily but get little media coverage
when they're victimized.
</P>
<P>
   How to forestall workplace violence? Rebecca Speer, a San
Francisco employment lawyer who specializes in workplace violence
prevention, suggests the following steps:
</P>
<P>
   _Adopt clear personnel policies prohibiting violence and threats
of violence, and requiring employees to report such incidents to
company officials.
</P>
<P>
   _Choose certain managers to receive and resolve complaints about
violence. This could be an interdisciplinary team including people
from human resources, the legal department and operations.
</P>
<P>
   _Provide employee training so people understand these policies.
</P>
<P>
   _Establish security practices that are appropriate for your type
of business.
</P>
<P>
   The California Occupational Safety &AMP; Health Administration
offers a useful guide to preventing workplace violence at
 &LR; www.dir.ca.gov/dir/OS&AMP;H/DOSH &LR; 
 &LR; /dosh(UNDERSCORE)publications/worksecurity.html.  &LR; Federal
officials offer similar materials at &LR;  www.osha-slc.gov &LR; 
 &LR; /SLTC/workplaceviolence &LR;   &LR; /index.html &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   And the Santa Clara County Committee on Workplace Violence
offers a helpful guide at  &LR; www.growing.com/nonviolent &LR; 
 &LR; /protocol/wv(UNDERSCORE)pgce.htm. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Also check out a free workshop in San Francisco on May 11 called
``Preventing Violence in the Workplace: A Workshop om the Needs of
Small and Mid-sized Employers.'' The workshop will be at the Main
Public Library from 9 to 11 a.m. For more information, call (415)
433-2062.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of consultants now offer workplace violence
prevention help. You could call your local chapter of the Society
for Human Resource Management for names of some in your area. In
the Bay Area, contact the Northern California Human Resource
Association at (415) 291-1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be a challenge to find professionals who can address
all the different aspects of the problem _ the legal, security and
human resource aspects,'' Speer said. ``You might need to shop
around a bit to find someone who is sensitive to the fact this
requires an interdisciplinary approach.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  Union Dues
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a new part-time job and just discovered that the
company deducted money from my first paycheck for union dues. The
employment ad in the newspaper never said that union membership was
required as a condition of employment, and the company never said
anything about that in my job interview either. I fully recognize
the value of unions, but is forced membership like this legal? What
can I do?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Some states, known as ``right-to-work'' states, say it's
illegal to make union membership a condition of employment. But
California isn't one of them.
</P>
<P>
   In California, it is legal to have what is called a ``union
shop,'' in which you must be a union member or pay a fee to the
union to be employed. And there's no law requiring companies to
disclose information about union representation to job applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what private-sector companies and unions are required to
do, according to Rob Remar, a labor lawyer with Leonard Carder
Nathan Zuckerman Ross Chin &AMP; Remar in San Francisco:
</P>
<P>
   _Unions must inform new employees of their obligation to pay
membership dues or _ if they don't want to become a member _ their
obligation to pay the portion of dues that is used to negotiate or
implement their contract. That portion is often called the ``Beck
amount,'' after a landmark court case on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   _Companies must get written consent from individual employees
before union dues are automatically withheld from their paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that both your employer and the union did these
things, but you didn't notice because you were so busy wading
through all the other new-hire paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   It's also possible that they didn't notify you _ a mess-up that
would violate the National Labor Relations Act.
</P>
<P>
   What should you do? First, decide whether you want to be a
full-fledged union member or a nonmember who pays the Beck amount.
Being a nonmember won't save you much money. That's because most of
your dues goes to things like negotiating contracts and handling
grievances _ things you'd have to pay for even as a nonmember. Only
a small portion _ 5 to 25 percent, depending on the particular
union _ goes to noncontract-related purposes like political
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't want to be a member, write a letter to the union
saying you only want to pay the Beck amount.
</P>
<P>
   If you do want to be a member, you don't have to do anything:
You apparently are signed up already.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't want union dues withheld from your paycheck, let
the company know. But be aware that you'll still be required to pay
dues or a Beck fee _ you'll just have to do it yourself by check
rather than by withholding.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San
Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or send
e-mail to workways(at sign)sfgate.com. &LR;   &LR; Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query, but we will answer as many in print as
we can. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
