<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8678 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      04-29 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Toy Sellers' Internet Battle May Be Bloody
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Mark Veverka &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The quest for toy-selling supremacy on the Internet is going to be
a battle royal.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Amazon.com's one-sided massacre of bookseller
Barnesandnoble.com, the fight between fledgling eToys and
traditional category-killer Toys R Us is going to be a bloody war.
</P>
<P>
   Etoys may possibly rise to victory over time, but by no means is
it going to be a cakewalk.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the Santa Monica e-tailer _ which managed to rack up
sales of only $578,000 for fiscal year 1998 _ has many fans, who
liken its impressive business model and crisp execution to that of
Amazon during its startup years.
</P>
<P>
   But Toys R Us, which is the wounded brick-and-mortar heavyweight
of toy retailing with about 1,500 stores and $11 billion in 1998
sales, still boasts many traditional strengths that should give
eToys fits.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, earlier this week, Toys R Us revealed its revamped
strategy for the Internet, which included the acquisition of a $30
million Memphis distribution warehouse. That was a smart first
step, given that overnight shipper Federal Express makes its hub
there. Williams-Sonoma, for example, and other direct-merchandisers
have located their distribution operations in Elvis-town for that
precise reason.
</P>
<P>
   But the bigger, and more important, news was that Benchmark
Capital reportedly invested $10 million in the online unit.
Benchmark is a Menlo Park venture capital firm that slugged a grand
slam with its backing of Internet superstar eBay, the San Jose
online auctioneer.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, according to First Albany Internet analyst Ullas Naik,
Benchmark's money and expertise gives the Toys R Us online unit
immediate credibility. ``That's one of the things that makes them
more of a threat than Barnes and Noble was to Amazon,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Benchmark ``is going to make sure that the whole Toys R Us
Internet initiative will run on Internet time, while Barnes and
Noble (launched its Net operations) on brick-and-mortar time.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, one of the biggest disadvantages that Barnes and
Noble faces is Amazon's huge head start. The bookselling giant
dragged its feet, and it has cost them dearly. ``Amazon has left
Barnes and Noble in the dust,'' Naik says.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Toys R Us is certainly behind eToys in Net brand and
site development _ it has been operating for less than two years _
but the traditional retailer hasn't spotted its online nemesis an
insurmountable lead, Naik says.
</P>
<P>
   It seems reasonable to assume that Benchmark would not be
betting on the New Jersey toy retailer if the venture capital
firm's partners thought that Toys R Us could not catch up to eToys,
Naik says. Calls to Benchmark were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Benchmark) has its act together,'' Naik says
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Toys R Us has been given a bit of reprieve because
eToys' much-anticipated initial public offering has been delayed by
its acquisition of San Francisco's BabyCenter.
</P>
<P>
   IPOs are critical branding opportunities that introduce
little-known e-tailers to the masses. EBay's notoriety exploded
after its stock started to skyrocket.
</P>
<P>
   So, for now at least, Toys R Us is still the dominant brand name
in toys and it has a chance of remaining so if its new online
venture proves to be a worthy adversary of eToys, says Neil Stern,
a retail consultant with McMillan/Doolittle, a retail consultancy
in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The huge edge they have over eToys is in name recognition and
vendor relationships. They are  &LR; the  &LR; category-killer toy store,''
Stern reminds. And those long-standing relationships with
toy-makers should still give Toys R Us the inside track for getting
``hot'' new toys first.
</P>
<P>
   By setting up a stand-alone subsidiary in Silicon Valley, Toys R
Us has taken an ``interesting and different path'' to avoid
conflict with its core brick-and-mortar stores, Stern says.
</P>
<P>
   It's better to let the ``virtual guys'' start from scratch as
opposed to having the ``brick-and-mortar guys'' try to figure out
the Web. But creating a separate operation also presents some
sticky issues, such as how you make sure that pricing and return
policies between both operations mesh and don't create confusion
for customers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, even if Toys R Us' online venture is a success, how
much of those sales will come out of the hide of its own
traditional business, Stern questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Still), I assume many of these challenges are manageable,''
he adds.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a big fan of traditional retailers. And in my mind, many of
them are brilliant and are capable of integrating their businesses
with the Web (If they act quickly enough).
</P>
<P>
   At one time, Toys R Us would qualify. It was a top-notch
mass-retailer. But the mighty has fallen. And if they can't excel
anymore at what they do best, how are they going to figure out the
Net?
</P>
<P>
   ``Toys R Us is an extremely screwed up retailer,'' Stern says.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have, over the past six to seven years, just taken their
eye off of the ball and let their store execution really suffer,
their customer service suffer and have gotten sloppy on pricing,''
Stern says.
</P>
<P>
   His criticism doesn't end there. Stern also chastises Toys R Us
for not keeping pace with customer demands for computer-oriented
and educational toys.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went from being the absolute dominant market share
player'' in toys to second place behind Wal-Mart, Stern says.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every way possible, they've been asleep at the switch,'' he
adds.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, how did you like the play Mrs. Lincoln?
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Stern thinks that Toys R Us has let its once laudable
franchise go to pot. But he doesn't dismiss its chances with
Benchmark's involvement. ``They still have a lot going for them,''
Stern concedes.
</P>
<P>
   But eToys may still have too much high-tech weaponry for the
old-line toy seller. ``Etoys has a very classy, very well done Web
site,'' Stern says. ``It's going to be an interesting battle.''
</P>
<P>
   One that has the makings of a 15 rounder.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; STREET SMART CLASSIC: &LR;  In light of McKesson blowing up this week,
Street Smarts goes back into the archives to resurrect a prescient
nugget from a November 17 column:
</P>
<P>
   ``HBO's immediate future is about as clear as summer in the
Sunset District. The Atlanta software-maker is slated to be
acquired by McKesson, but the ill-timed departure of HBO's chief
financial officer and co-president, Jay Gilbertson, casts a dark
cloud over a deal that investors already didn't like, says a New
York hedge fund manager. ... `Wall Street has been skeptical of
this deal for sometime, and now it has even more reason to be
leery.'''
</P>
<P>
   Boy did it ever. McKesson restated its quarterly earnings on
Wednesday, admitting that $26 million in health care software
bookings for the quarter weren't final. Now, I guess we know why
HBO's chief bean counter wasn't asked to join McKesson.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
