<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8680 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL-750&AMP;A     04-29 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIBUNAL CHIEF PLANS TO QUIT, ALARMING U.S. OFFICIALS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chief prosecutor of the international war
crimes tribunal is planning to leave her post, a move that
officials worry will weaken the tribunal at a time when the Clinton
administration is looking to the court to prosecute atrocities
committed to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the prosecutor, Louise Arbour, discussed her
possible departure during meetings with senior administration
officials, where the major item on the agenda was the possibility
of an indictment against the Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic,
officials said. Mrs. Arbour is seeking more information about
potential war crimes from the Americans, while administration
officials say she has enough evidence to indict the Serb leader.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they have criticized Mrs. Arbour for not
aggressively pursuing Milosevic, the Clinton administration and
human rights organizations are now alarmed that she may leave. She
is the top candidate for a seat on the Canadian Supreme Court,
which becomes open this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to create disruption in the tribunal,'' said
Michael Posner, director of the Lawyers Committee for Human Rights,
a private organization in New York. ``It's going to slow down the
indictments, and it's going to send exactly the wrong message to
Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Arbour's four-year term does not expire until next year,
and her departure now would leave the tribunal leaderless, and set
off a polarizing fight over her successor. The chief prosecutor
must be approved by the U.N. Security Council, which means that
Russia and China _ the two council nations with the strongest
objections to the NATO bombing of Serbia _ can veto anyone they
consider unfavorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like what she's done, but I don't think we'll do
better,'' said an administration official.
</P>
<P>
   Russia would almost certainly not approve of someone from a NATO
country, or anyone who would be overly aggressive in pursuing
Serbian military officers, above all Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Arbour's predecessor, and the tribunal's first prosecutor,
Richard Goldstone, a South African jurist, won the support of
Russia after he was endorsed by President Nelson Mandela. When he
stepped down, Goldstone recommended Mrs. Arbour as his successor,
and her nomination was approved at a time when the court had not
been thrust into the middle of a war involving NATO.
</P>
<P>
   In Canada, an intense internal battle has erupted over the
naming of Mrs. Arbour, 52, to the Supreme Court. She is considered
to be eminently qualified, and the fact that she is a
French-speaking woman from Ontario makes her an attractive
candidate for Prime Minister Jean Chretien to appoint. But the
Foreign Ministry has been urging Chretien to keep Mrs. Arbour in
her tribunal post, because of the high visibility it gives to
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has so far stayed out of the fray,
out of concerns for Canada's sensitivities to interference from its
neighbor, American officials said.
</P>
<P>
   At a luncheon Thursday, some American officials tried to
persuade Mrs. Arbour to remain as the tribunal's chief prosecutor,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The officials trying to influence Mrs. Arbour's decision are a
bit ambivalent, however, the officials said, because they think
that Mrs. Arbour has not done as much as she could and above all,
has not indicted Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   A cautious jurist by nature, Mrs. Arbour has been reluctant to
indict anyone without an air-tight case. A more aggressive
prosecutor _ in the mold of New York Mayor and former prosecutor
Rudolph Giuliani, for example, several human rights lawyers
suggested _ would have long ago brought a case against Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Her cautious nature has been reinforced by her chief adviser on
international humanitarian law, William Fenrick. He is a Canadian
military officer, and is very hard to convince on so-called command
and control cases, several former tribunal officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Milosevic did not carry out any of the atrocities himself,
he can be convicted of a war crime only if it is established that
he exercised ``command and control'' over the units that did commit
them.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Arbour wants the United States government to provide more
information about Milosevic's role in the campaign in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   American officials respond that there is enough in the public
record to indict Milosevic, and that that has been supplemented by
information from the United States government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've given her more than enough information to indict him,''
an American official said Thursday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But an outside analyst, experienced in gathering evidence of war
crimes, said that the officials in the U.S. government who are
combing through the files for evidence of Milosevic's culpability
did not have the expertise needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do not need the most sophisticated intelligence
gathering,'' said Jon Western, who was a Bosnia war-crime's analyst
in the State Department in 1992 and 1993, and is now a scholar at
the U.S. Institute of Peace. What is needed, he said, is an
understanding of the Balkans and especially knowledge about the
structure of the Yugoslav Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are good, smart, dedicated people,'' Western said about
the war-crimes analysts now gathering information on Milosevic and
other Serb commanders. ``But they don't have any military
intelligence background.''
</P>
<P>
   Above all what is needed, Western said, is the ``commitment from
the president himself, and that has not been forthcoming.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the administration, there are strong advocates for
indicting Milosevic, while others argue that an indictment would
not be a good idea, because it might be necessary to negotiate with
him to end the war. For that reason, some NATO allies are also
opposed to seeing him indicted, a NATO official said Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
