<HEADLINE>
WHAT HAS SPRING SPRUNG AT USC?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The defense lost Chris Claiborne. The offense has
the quarterback of the future entrenched for as long as he wants to
play college football.
</P>
<P>
   Those were givens of USC spring football practice, which
concluded last week. The real question on everyone's mind, though,
is whether the Trojans will be any better than last year's 8-5
team.
</P>
<P>
   Even after a full month of spring practices, it's too soon to
tell exactly where USC will end up during coach Paul Hackett's
second season. Just ask the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's really hard to say,'' strong safety David
Gibson said. ``In the spring, there's so many injuries. The
attitude around the locker room is, ``Hey, it's time do something.'
We've done a lot of talking, but it's time.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at how USC emerged from spring drills
position-by-position:
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback: Carson Palmer enjoyed his first spring as the No.1
quarterback. Junior Mike Van Raaphorst was very smooth, although
some teammates still wonder whether nerves contributed to his
nausea before and during games last season. The only problem will
occur if both were somehow injured, and John Fox would be pressed
into emergency duty.
</P>
<P>
   Running back: Chad Morton remains the Trojans' top tailback, but
there should be a lot more depth this season. Malaefou MacKenzie is
returning from a knee injury and will play tailback, probably in
split-back formations.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise was freshman Sultan McCullough, who had 99 yards in
a scrimmage before being ruled academically ineligible. He has the
best breakaway speed of any of the backs.
</P>
<P>
   A potential worry is fullback, where unproven Brennan Ochs, Chad
Pierson and Charlie Landrigan are the only candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Receivers: R. Jay Soward finally showed up and was his usual
self. Senior Windrell Hayes emerged with a strong spring, but after
that, there isn't much experienced help.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exciting thing is that we have four young people coming
in, Marcell Allmond, Steve Stevenson, Kareem Kelly and Craig
Mitchell. They are going to be the wide receiver corps,'' Hackett
said. ``Seeing us in four wides early will be a real shock. I can't
imagine us playing a lot of receivers until we get some time for
the young guys to develop.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line: The big news was the amount of shuffling that
took place during practices. Right guard Travis Claridge, who will
be an Athlon preseason All-American, spent a considerable amount of
time at right tackle.
</P>
<P>
   That gave freshman Zach Wilson time at right guard. Whether this
will continue in the fall remains to be seen. The other change was
senior Donta Kendrick moving ahead of Jason Grain at left guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem here is depth,'' Hackett said. ``We're not where
we need to be or expect to be in the offensive line, but I think
the spring has shown clear-cut improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive line: This position has undergone the greatest change
in the spring. Sultan Abdul-Malik moved to linebacker, and tight
end Lonnie Ford is now a defensive end. The Trojans also have
worked Kansas State transfer Matt Childers into the rotation. Ennis
Davis missed spring practice with a knee injury, but is another
Athlon preseason All-American and is expected to be ready in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when you talk about rebuilding (the defense), you
start with the defensive line,'' Hackett said. ``We've got
competition there and that will be a strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Linebackers: Mike Pollard's knee injury and Abdul-Malik's switch
to the line make depth a question here. There is much anticipation
about Markus Steele, but it's probably asking a lot for a JC
transfer to make a major impact his first year.
</P>
<P>
   Zeke Moreno will anchor the middle, with Abdul-Malik appearing
to make a nice transition to outside linebacker. Darryl Knight was
starting in the spot Steele will supposedly play, although
converted fullback Henry Wallace was another surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive backs: Another area of flux as Gibson moved to strong
safety and the Trojans searched for a replacement for Daylon
McCutcheon. Kris Richard won the job in spring, but there's
expected to be battle in the fall with incoming freshman Darrell
Rideaux.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darrell, goodness gracious,'' Hackett said. ``You bring in a
guy that's going to compete right away. He's not a big guy and they
played him at cornerback and safety (at Long Beach Poly). The
ground he can cover at safety and the way he can cover the field is
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Specialists: Kicker Adam Abrams is gone, which isn't necessarily
a bad thing, except USC has no experience at the position. David
Bell was the only kicker in spring, but JC transfer David Newbury
is expected to win the job in training camp. Mike MacGillivray
returns at punter.
</P>
<P>
   Soward and Morton will return kickoffs and punts, so this will
be considered a strength next season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
