<SLUG> BC-SEASIA-CAMBODIA-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMBODIA GAINS FULL STATUS IN SOUTHEAST ASIAN GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ Starting Friday, Cambodian Prime Minister
Hun Sen will finally have a chance to show off his golf game. He
will be invited to sing karaoke, too.
</P>
<P>
   With these badges of club membership, he will confirm his
nation's coming of age as the final member of the pre-eminent
political and economic group in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The group, the Association of Southeast Asian Nations, or ASEAN,
will achieve a decades-old dream Friday with the induction of the
10th regional nation, Cambodia, at a ceremony in Hanoi. The event
will cap the emergence of Cambodia over the last year from three
decades of warfare and international exile, with the collapse of
the communist Khmer Rouge insurgency and the resolution of
long-running civil-war rivalries.
</P>
<P>
   But the occasion will also highlight an identity crisis in the
group, which has been accused of irrelevance as the region
struggles with political, economic and environmental crises that
the association was unable to deal with as a body.
</P>
<P>
   The ASEAN expansion in recent years from six to 10 members has
led to re-examinations of its character and culture, with fears of
new divisions between the older haves and the newer have-nots and
between the more democratic and the more autocratic governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is cause for concern in ASEAN, because it is virtually
dead,'' said Alex Magno, a professor of political science at the
University of the Philippines. ``It is still operating like a tea
party, keeping to the safe points and waiting for a consensus based
on the least common denominator.''
</P>
<P>
   An ASEAN expert at the Institute of Southeast Asian Studies in
Singapore, Daljit Singh, disagreed, saying the economic crisis,
with its mix of internal and external causes, was not one that the
association could properly address. Singh said that the crisis had
worsened frictions among neighbors, but that after the crisis had
passed the group could return to its basic focus of free trade,
regional cooperation and the building of a relationship with
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The autocrats who shaped the organization in recent years and
gave it its character are gone or weakened. They include Suharto of
Indonesia, Lee Kuan Yew of Singapore, Ferdinand Marcos of the
Philippines and Mahathir Mohamad of Malaysia. ``The old world has
crumbled, and the new one has not yet been born,'' Magno said.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion from the original five members will strain the
ASEAN culture of consensus decision making, said Hadi Soesastro, a
political scientist at the Center for Strategic and International
Studies in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the ASEAN leaders try to force everything to be agreed upon
by all 10 members, that could be a problem,'' Soesastro said.
``They should be willing to accept that you can have a two-tier
ASEAN in different areas of cooperation.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The possibility of such a division demonstrates the degree to
which ASEAN has shifted its focus. Throughout much of its life, the
group has achieved its cohesion as a bulwark against communism,
principally Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Now Vietnam, which joined in 1995, could emerge as the leader of
the newer second-tier grouping, which would include not only
Cambodia, but also communist Laos and authoritarian Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
   The older ASEAN members are Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore,
Thailand, the Philippines and Brunei.
</P>
<P>
   The admission of Myanmar, formerly Burma, in 1997 was a turning
point. The stubbornness of its military junta in resisting
democratic reforms displayed the weakness of ASEAN's belief in
behind-the-scenes diplomacy. And the problem badly damaged the
group's relations with the European Union, which refused to include
Myanmar in joint meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Cambodia was barred from admission then because of a coup by Hun
Sen. Now Cambodia's voice will carry equal weight with those of its
fellow members, a giant step up from its position as international
pariah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe there is going to be influence going both ways,'' said
Kao Kim Hourn, who heads the Cambodian Institute for Cooperation
and Peace, a private policy institute. ``The old members will
influence us on how to socialize, to engage with each other and to
build consensus. But the new members will influence them, as
well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
