<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASDAQ AND S&AMP;P SLIDE; DOW NOTCHES ANOTHER HIGH
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq stocks slumped for the third straight session as
investors took profits in high-technology shares, casting a further
pall over the market in general.
</P>
<P>
   Some money was redeployed into issues sensitive to the business
cycle, helping push the Dow Jones industrial average up 32.93
points, or three-tenths of a percent, to 10,878.38, its fifth
record in seven sessions. The Nasdaq composite index fell 21.93
points, or nine-tenths of a percent, to 2,528.44, while the
Standard and Poor's 500-stock index fell 8.08 points, or six-tenths
of a percent, to 1,342.83.
</P>
<P>
   DIRECT TALK FROM WOULD-BE WITNESS
</P>
<P>
   Michael L. Dertouzos, the director of the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology's laboratory for computer science, was
asked to be a witness in the Microsoft antitrust trial by William
H. Gates, but he was quickly dropped from the company's witness
list after he was questioned by a government lawyer last fall. Yet
judging from his deposition testimony released this week, Dertouzos
had a lot to say and would have been a most unusual witness, blunt
and direct, with views not tailored to either side.
</P>
<P>
   A FRENZY FOR GOLDMAN'S OFFERING
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, Sachs could increase the size of its planned initial
public offering eightfold and still leave some investors
disappointed, so great is the interest in the shares.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. SEES FEW HURDLES IN AETNA DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and consumer advocates contend that Aetna's plan to buy
Prudential Health Care, creating the nation's biggest managed-care
company, would harm competition among insurers. But antitrust
officials say they have found potential problems in only a few
states.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE SHELVES YEAR 2000 MEASURE
</P>
<P>
   Legislation to limit lawsuits arising from year 2000 computer
breakdowns was shelved by the Senate because of partisan politics
and the running battle between lobbyists for business interests and
those for trial lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street firms and exchanges completed extensive mock trading
of securities simulating the start of next year with almost no
interruptions from year 2000 problems.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG MAKERS POST QUARTERLY PROFITS
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn, the pharmaceutical giant, said that its
first-quarter profit rose 17 percent, while Hoechst and
Rhone-Poulenc, which plan to merge later this year and form the
world's largest drug maker, posted lower-than-expected quarterly
earnings because of the slumping chemicals business. Shares of
Pharmacia fell $1.8125, to $55.50.
</P>
<P>
   `DOLPHIN-SAFE' RULES ARE RELAXED
</P>
<P>
   In a decision that has outraged many environmental groups, the
Commerce Department announced it was broadening the definition of
``dolphin-safe'' tuna to include fish caught by a method that was
banned by law in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   AUTHOR OF CHERNOBYL VIRUS IDENTIFIED
</P>
<P>
   A former computer engineering student was identified by his
college as the author of the Chernobyl virus _ the menace that
caused hundreds of thousands of computer meltdowns around the world
this week.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WORLDCOM NET TOPS FORECASTS
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom posted a better-than-expected rise in first-quarter
net income, but its stock fell because investors feared it might be
planning to acquire Nextel Communications.
</P>
<P>
   FORD ENDS PLANS FOR FACTORY IN BRAZIL
</P>
<P>
   Ford has abandoned plans to build an innovative $1 billion
factory in a southern Brazilian state, which refused to honor a
pledge to provide the company with incentives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
