<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLPHINS-TUNA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT LOOSENS STANDARDS ON TUNA DEEMED `DOLPHIN-SAFE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a decision that has outraged many environmental groups, the
Commerce Department on Thursday announced that it was broadening
the definition of ``dolphin-safe'' tuna to include fish caught by a
method that was banned under a 1990 law.
</P>
<P>
   The method is used by fishermen from Mexico and Venezuela, among
other countries, and uses nets a mile wide to capture tuna in the
tropical waters of the eastern Pacific Ocean. Fishing boats using
the nets chase schools of dolphin and encircle them, since tuna
often swim just below the dolphins. The practice has been condemned
by animal-protection groups because they say that chasing the
dolphins separates mothers from infants and causes stress and
injuries. Proponents say dolphins usually wriggle free on their own
or with fishermen's help.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a cruel, inhuman method, and to call it dolphin-safe is
just a government-sanctioned consumer fraud,'' said Nancy Blaney,
director of federal government affairs for the American Society for
the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals, which has joined with 85
environmental groups to protest the decision. Ms. Blaney and others
said pressure from Mexico, whose tuna has been banned since the law
went into effect, had influenced the change.
</P>
<P>
   Terry D. Garcia, the assistant secretary of commerce for oceans
and atmosphere, said the change was ``an interim finding'' and was
based on research that found little evidence that encirclement
fishing was harming three dolphin species that are considered
depleted _ the Northeastern offshore spotted dolphin, the coastal
spotted dolphin and the Eastern spinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this change in the definition, consumers can still be
confident they are purchasing dolphin-safe tuna,'' Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   As for international pressure, he said, ``Certainly, the
Mexicans were anxious to see it lifted, but there was pressure from
all sides.''
</P>
<P>
   A provision in the International Dolphin Conservation Program
Act, which went into effect in 1997, requires the Commerce
Department to research the effects of encirclement fishing on
depleted species.
</P>
<P>
   Dolphin deaths have decreased from 133,000 in 1986 to 2,000 last
year, Garcia said. Using the Commerce Department's most recent
studies, he said, ``We cannot conclude that encirclement as a
method of fishing for tuna causes significant adverse impact on
these depleted stocks of dolphins.''
</P>
<P>
   A final ruling will be made in 2002, after further research,
Garcia said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 2153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
