<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-CARLIN-EXCLUSIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARLIN TO STEP DOWN AS STATE SCHOOL BOARD CHIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- James F. Carlin, the feisty businessman who chafed
with professors' unions in his drive for higher standards and
tighter budgets at the state's public colleges and universities,
said Thursday that he plans to resign as the state's top higher
education official.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Paul Cellucci is trying to replace Carlin as chairman
of the Board of Higher Education with Charles D. Baker Jr., who was
the top financial officer in the Weld-Cellucci cabinet before
leaving the administration last fall to head one of the region's
largest medical practices.
</P>
<P>
   Carlin, who turns 59 Friday, suffered several small heart
attacks last summer. The attacks occurred in the midst of
responding to the stunning failure of the majority of state teacher
college graduates on a certification exam. But he said Thursday
that health was a small factor in his decision to leave his post.
</P>
<P>
   Carlin, a self-made millionaire, still oversees his insurance
and real estate companies from an office in Natick, serves on
several boards, and spends much of the year in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that three or four years is as long as people ought to
stay in state government,'' he said. ``When they are in longer,
they start to like it for reasons other than why they get started.
I got done pretty much of what I thought could get done. We put
together a list of 25 things when I started three and a half years
ago, 17 of them are done, four or five are almost done, and four or
five will never get done.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlin, a former transportation secretary who also oversaw the
receivership of scandal-plagued Chelsea in the early '90s, was one
of the ``Three Amigos,'' the hard-charging Democrats who Governor
William F. Weld brought in four years ago to shake up public
education in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Although John R. Silber, as head of the state board of
education, attracted the most headlines, Carlin and William M.
Bulger, the longtime state Senate president who became president of
the University of Massachusetts, have been credited with more
significant results.
</P>
<P>
   Carlin took over the state's public higher education system in
late 1995, on the heels of dramatic budget cuts and increases in
tuition. His board has cut tuition and student fees four years in a
row at the state colleges and UMass, giving Massachusetts the most
dramatic cuts in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Another Carlin proposal has made community college almost free
for most low-income and middle-class students. The board also
eliminated remedial education at the state colleges and UMass,
increased admissions standards across the board, and established
the Commonwealth College, an honors program to attract higher
caliber students to the Amherst UMass campus.
</P>
<P>
   With the Legislature, Carlin has worked to require state schools
to stick to tight accounting as a condition of receiving state aid,
and won significant increases in that aid. The board, under his
direction, has also eliminated 50 programs that were
undersubscribed or duplicated on state campuses.
</P>
<P>
   While Silber's board was mired in petty and often personal
disputes, Carlin's board meetings by comparison were run like a
well-oiled corporation. He insisted on efficiency from
institutions, as well. A letter demanding action from colleges
after 59 percent of prospective teachers failed a state
certification exam was classic Carlin: ``I do not want to get
involved in a six-month intellectual debate over `defining the
problem' or preparing `a thoughtful, deliberate process of
establishing a dialogue pointing toward a solution,' '' he wrote,
`` . . . or whether `education school graduates are poorly prepared
because their mothers didn't love them or they weren't chosen to be
a cheerleader in junior high school.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But his businesslike approach earned him the ire of professors,
especially at the state colleges, who blasted what they saw as his
lack of understanding of the academy and its traditions. They
worried that his plans to reduce tenure would destabilize their
institutions, and that raising standards would cut off access to
disadvantaged students.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the Chronicle of Higher Education after a glowing
1997 profile of Carlin, Northeastern history professor Harvey Green
called Carlin ``a skilled demagogue,'' who was encouraging strains
of anti-intellectualism in the United States. ``Clothing himself in
the garb of Everyman, he is, in fact, an enemy of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlin had taken a hands-on approach in the early years of his
post, acting as lead negotiator with the professors unions. But in
the past nine months, he had scaled back his involvement.
</P>
<P>
   He said he considered leaving his post last fall, but stayed on
to deal with the crisis over teacher training, and to shepherd
another reduction in tuition and increase in admissions standards
this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said Thursday only that he was ``considering'' the job. He
has yet to talk to the board of his employer, Harvard Vanguard
Medical Associates, about taking on another responsibility.
Cellucci recently appointed him to the state board of education,
and Baker would probably have to give up that post to take on
higher education. Baker, 42, also serves on the Massachusetts
Convention Center Authority board.
</P>
<P>
   As a replacement, Baker is not likely to comfort any of Carlin's
critics. The two cut a similar profile. In state office, Baker
earned a reputation as a blunt-spoken cost-conscious manager,
closing several state hospitals, and overseeing the Department of
Social Services amid one of its worst foster child scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Of Baker, Carlin said, ``Charlie will be spectacular.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
