<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8693 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCKESSON-SFCHRON &LR;      04-29 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCKESSON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Pressured McKesson Circles the Wagons
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Tom Abate &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With its stock sinking and shareholder lawsuits growing,
McKesson HBOC Inc. remained tight-lipped yesterday about where to
place the blame for the accounting screwup that has cost the
company half its market value.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in the San Francisco drug wholesaler and hospital
software vendor slipped an additional $1.25 to close at $33.25
yesterday on the heels of Wednesday's precipitous $31.25 decline.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day drop was triggered by McKessonHBOC's announcement on
Wednesday that it had prematurely booked $42.2 million in sales
made by its newly acquired HBOC software division.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a 15-minute conference call with financial analysts
Wednesday _ during which questions were not allowed _ neither chief
executive Mark Pulido nor Chairman Charles McCall has dealt with
the key question in this accounting debacle: Did anyone know HBOC
might have an earnings skeleton in its closet before McKesson paid
$14 billion to acquire the software division in January?
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have all the answers yet and in the interim there
have been several lawsuits filed,'' McKessonHBOC spokesman Larry
Kurtz said yesterday in explaining the executive silence. ``When we
do have the answers I fully expect Charlie and Mark will be out
there answering questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who followed Atlanta's HBOC before the merger said
that, although there was never any hint of impropriety at HBOC,
there were plenty of warning signs that the high-flying software
firm might not be a good match for the 166-year-old drug
wholesaler.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Clulow, an analyst with CIBC Oppenheimer in New York, said
the first warning bell rang last July, when a merger between
McKesson and HBOC was called off after news of the deal was
inadvertently leaked by Salomon Smith Barney, the investment bank
that first tried to marry HBOC, headed by McCall, to McKesson, run
by Pulido.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCall had taken this little software company and made it into
one of the 10-top performers in the S&AMP;P,'' said Clulow, averaging
roughly 50 percent a year in average growth in sales and earnings.
``Investors were asking why HBOC would sell off to low-growth
McKesson.''
</P>
<P>
   As HBOC's stock sank about 20 percent on the leak, Clulow said
McCall assured investors the talks were just that, and there
wouldn't be a deal. McCall also sued Salomon for the lost
shareholder value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three months later, the deal happens,'' Clulow said. ``The
combined entity lost a lot of credibility'' for the about-face.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Brodsky, a financial analyst with Vector Securities in
Deerfield, Ill., said the second trip by HBOC and McKesson to the
altar in October sounded another alarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``When HBOC accepted McKesson's bid for a nominal (11 percent)
premium over the market, it led a lot of investors and analysts to
wonder what Charley knew,'' Brodsky said.
</P>
<P>
   By then, she said, HBOC's smaller competitors in the hospital
software market had already been hammered because their clients _
forced to spend up to 50 percent of their budgets on Year 2000
fixes _ had less to spend on other hospital software. HBOC, with a
huge installed base and a revenue stream from annual software
license fees, had forestalled _ but could not indefinitely dodge _
that reckoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``McKesson's shareholders didn't understand what they were
buying,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the deal closed in January _ after a second
lawsuit was filed, this one by Salomon, arguing that it had come up
with the idea for marrying HBOC, the leader in health care
software, to McKesson, the leader in drug distribution, and
therefore deserved a matchmaking fee.
</P>
<P>
   All this time, McKesson's shares were trailing down, from a high
of $96.25 in September, before the merger was announced, to the mid
60s in early February, when the now-merged company acted to bolster
its price.
</P>
<P>
   On February 8, McKessonHBOC said its top executives would buy
1.2 million shares at the previous Friday's closing price of
$63.33, for a total investment of $76 million. The two biggest
buyers that day were Pulido and McCall, who bought 150,000 shares
each. But they didn't pay exactly the same amount for this
good-faith stake in McKessonHBOC.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Elliott, who tracks insider trades for First Call/Thomson
Financial in Rockville Maryland, said Pulido, the former McKesson
chief and current CEO of the merged entity, paid the full price for
his stake or $9.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   McCall, the former HBOC CEO, who as chairman of the merged firm,
exercised options that reduced his outlay for the same amount of
shares to only $5.9 million, Elliott said. Today, the value of the
shares purchased by both executives is $5 million, but Pulido, who
paid the full price, lost substantially more.
</P>
<P>
   Since February's executive buying spree, McKessonHBOC has traded
in the mid 60s _ until the plunge precipitated by Wednesday's news
that McCall's division had overstated some revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Despite what seems like a situation ripe for recrimination,
company spokesman Kurtz said no one on the McKesson side of the
deal felt misled, and there had been no finger pointing at the
board meeting earlier this week where the bad news was disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some 20 shareholder lawsuits have been filed,
alleging, in essence, that somebody knew _ or should have known _
the earnings were about to hit the fan.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the controversy swirling around McKessonHBOC led CIBC
analyst Clulow to say, ``This stock is certainly going to be in the
penalty box for a while.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 2159EDT &QL; 
