<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8694 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-VICAR-DERBY30-COX     04-29 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-VICAR-DERBY30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vicar team keeping low profile
 &HT;    By John Crittenden
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ After he won the Kentucky Derby in 1990 with
Unbridled, Carl Nafzger wrote a book on how he trains
thoroughbreds. Now that Nafzger is back on the doorstep of the 1999
Derby with Vicar, one of the Saturday race's favorites, the book,
``Traits of a Winner,'' is in a second printing.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Tafel, owner of Vicar, with homes in Kentucky and Illinois
but a resident of Delray Beach, Fla., for most of the year, is a
retired executive from a publishing company that prints technical
books.
</P>
<P>
   As skilled and experienced as they are in the ways of the media
(after all, they're in the profession), Nafzger and Tafel both have
limitedtheir exposure during Derby Week, the high-profile period of
the racing year.
</P>
<P>
   The press is not a problem for either the trainer or Vicar's
owner. A one-time rodeo bullrider with a dry Texas sense of humor,
Nafzger is a quote machine. Tafel is right at home in the press
box, where he visited often for post-race interviews as Vicar won
Gulfstream's top 3-year-old stakes in February and March.
</P>
<P>
   But they are determined that Derby Fever is not going to wreck
their week or damage Vicar's chances to win racing's biggest prize.
</P>
<P>
   Nafzger's wife, Wanda, who functions as the stable operation's
business manager, is responsible for keeping newspaper stories away
from the trainer. ``You read something you don't like and it
irritates you,'' said Nafzger. ``I don't want to get caught up in
that. I don't have time to waste this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Tafel's concern is slightly different.
</P>
<P>
   Nafzger is best-remembered outside of racing for his call of the
1990 Derby finish at the side of Frances Genter, the 92-year-old
owner of Unbridled, who was losing her sight and her hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's taking the lead ... he's going to win ... you've won the
Kentucky Derby,'' Nafzger shouted in what was obviously an outburst
of genuine emotion. ``Oh, Mrs. Genter, I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   Jokes Tafel, ``I'll be so nervous that Carl is going to have to
call the race for me like he did for Mrs. Genter.''
</P>
<P>
   So Tafel, 75, is determined not to be around much when the
swarms of journalists make their morning charge through the
Churchill Downs stables. His ego does not demand that he be present
for daily interviews at the barns. He skipped the big Derby
dinner-dance this week. One of his horses ran at Churchill Downs on
Thursday, but Tafel saw the race on the simulcast at Keeneland.
</P>
<P>
   Under normal circumstances, when Tafel and his wife, Ida May,
are at their Lexington home, he might be seen on the golf course,
where he spends a lot of time in Palm Beach County, Fla. Not this
week. ``I'm so keyed up for the race I'm playing terrible,
especially around the greens,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With about 30 horses in racing, he sends a division to Calder,
where Luis Olivares is his trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Tafel's stable produced its biggest success in 1998, when
Banshee Breeze, trained by Nafzger, earned the Eclipse Award as
3-year-old filly of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Her success makes it clear to Tafel just how much better known
the Kentucky Derby is than any other race. He did not hear from
them in 1998, but this year some of his Air Force comrades have
contacted him from the days in the 1940s when he flew as a
navigator on B-24s over Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, Banshee Breeze became the first filly ever to
be invited to the Dubai Cup. Tafel skipped the trip to allow
Nafzger to concentrate on the 4-year-old's primary
end-of-the-season objective, the Breeders' Cup at Gulfstream. It's
too long-range to be realistic, but if Banshee Breeze stays healthy
and Vicar continues to run well, perhaps Tafel will get two
invitations from the Persian Gulf for the Dubai Cup in the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
