u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOTUS-PAPOWS-BOS &LR;      04-29 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTUS-PAPOWS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTUS SAYS IT WILL BACK PAPOWS VS. JOURNAL REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY AND ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lotus Development Corp. says it will stand by Jeffrey Papows,
its chief executive and president, in the face of a published
report suggesting that he may have fabricated details of his
military service record and educational background.
</P>
<P>
   ``You shouldn't expect to see him leaving the company,'' said
Lotus spokesman Bryan Simmons, responding to a front-page story in
Thursday's Wall Street Journal that cast doubt on stories that
Papows is said to have told friends and colleagues about his
accomplishments. The Journal quoted a number of Papows' former
colleagues and customers.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal said that, among other things, Papows claimed to
have been a back-seat radar-intercept officer in fighter jets
during his stint in the US Marine Corps from 1976 to 1979. He also
claimed that he served in the Marine Corps Reserve in the 1980s,
and was forced to bail out of a crippled plane, according to the
story.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal article said that Papows served as an air-traffic
controller and did not serve in the active Marine Reserves. Papows
used stories of his fighter plane exploits to win military
contracts for Lotus, the story suggested.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Journal, Papows stated on his resume that he
held the rank of captain when he left the Marines, but actually was
a first lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   The paper also said that Papows claimed to hold a black belt in
tae kwan do and a PhD from Pepperdine University. In fact, he holds
a master's from Pepperdine and a PhD from a correspondence school.
He practices tae kwan do, but has not achieved a black belt in that
discipline, the article said.
</P>
<P>
   The 45-year-old Papows also told business associates that he was
an orphan, the paper said, when in fact his parents live in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   In an electronic mail message sent to Lotus employees Thursday,
Papows charged that the Journal story ``includes false allegations
about my career and military experience. ``. . . It is extremely
unfortunate that the Wall Street Journal chose to focus on my
distant personal background rather than our collective business
accomplishments.'' However, Papows did not dispute any specifics of
the Journal story.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons, the Lotus spokesman, said the Cambridge, Mass. company
also will not comment on the specifics of the article. He said
Papows would not give any interviews about the article and would
not elaborate on his remarks in the e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen at Lotus' parent company, IBM Corp., referred
questions about Papows to Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, one former Marine Corps Reserve general who is quoted
in the Journal story came to Papows' defense.
</P>
<P>
   Major General Thomas L. Wilkerson, former commander of the US
Marine Corps Reserve, said he did not increase purchases of Lotus
software after meeting with Papows and hearing about his military
background. The Journal suggested that Papows' claims about being a
military aviator helped win the business.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkerson, currently president of MBIA Muni Service Co. in
Armonk, N.Y., said the decision to buy the software was made
further down the chain of command.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Journal said Wilkerson had been accurately
quoted.
</P>
<P>
   At Lotus Thursday, where Papows is viewed by many as an
ambitious manager with a large ego, one employee who spoke on the
condition of anonymity said there was much talk about the Journal
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff does fashion himself as a cool machismo dude, and I have
a funny feeling he just took it too far,'' the employee said. Some
employees speculated Papows might be forced to resign, but others
said he should remain because of his successful track record, the
employee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough call,'' the employee said.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy comes at a time when Lotus has been prospering
on the popularity of its Notes software for collaborative
computing. IBM generally does not break out details of Lotus'
financial performance, but in his e-mail to employees, Papows said:
</P>
<P>
   ``We have just closed out our best Q1 ever, with our largest
revenue growth in 6 quarters and a 40 percent year-to-year growth
in Notes'' sales.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Levitt, who tracks Lotus for International Data Corp., a
computer industry research firm in Framingham, said he doubted the
controversy will hurt Lotus sales.
</P>
<P>
   The company's key products, Notes and Domino, are used in large
businesses and organizations to share information and coordinate
group activities. Lotus installations often cost hundreds of
thousands of dollars, and Levitt said that companies making such
decisions aren't impressed by tales of the Marine Corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it comes down to the product,'' Levitt said. ``Can the
product deliver what it claims to be able to deliver?''
</P>
<P>
   Levitt also said that Papows' success at Lotus may enable him to
ride out the controversy. ``Any shortcomings in his actual resume
notwithstanding, he has proven to be an energetic and reliable
leader for Lotus Notes. He has proven himself on the job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
