r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CMP-SFCHRON &LR;      04-29 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CMP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CMP Media, Miller Freeman Join Forces
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Dan Fost &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco publishing firm Miller Freeman Inc. and computer
magazine publisher CMP Media are joining forces in a $920 million
deal to create a high-tech publishing and trade show powerhouse
employing 1,300 people in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Miller Freeman's parent company, United News &AMP; Media PLC of
London, bought CMP and will fold it into Miller Freeman's
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Miller Freeman, which employs 1,000 people at its San Francisco
headquarters and a San Mateo office, publishes more than 270
business magazines and newsletters in areas as diverse as farming,
jewelry, and pulp and paper. Geeky computer publications are its
mainstay, however, accounting for 43 percent of its revenue last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Miller Freeman claims to be the largest trade show producer in
the world. It runs PC Expo in New York and 370 other trade shows
and conferences.
</P>
<P>
   CMP, based in Manhasset, N.Y., employs 1,800 people in the
United States, including &LR;   &LR; roughly 300 employees at offices in San
Francisco and San Mateo. Founded 28 years ago by the Leeds family,
which has maintained ownership, it publishes 11 computer-oriented
magazines such as Information Week and Computer Reseller News.
</P>
<P>
   CMP's 1998 earnings of $10 million dropped 67 percent from 1997,
reflecting hard times in the computer magazine business. The
company announced in February that it had hired the investment bank
Lazard Freres and Co. to ``explore strategic changes'' including a
possible sale or merger. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Regina Ridley, group president of Miller Freeman's high-tech
division, said CMP has ``a very impressive group of products.'' She
doesn't anticipate large layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Miller Freeman hopes CMP will give it the muscle it needs to
compete with Ziff-Davis of New York and International Data Group of
Massachusetts. Both firms have a significant West Coast presence,
Ziff-Davis with 900 employees in the Bay Area and IDG with 1,400 in
the Bay Area, Southern California and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Miller Freeman even plans to follow Ziff-Davis' footsteps and
sell stock in its online arm, perhaps later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Even though CMP runs 40 Web sites and Miller Freeman runs 140,
the two make most of their money from their print businesses, and
they aren't yet a formidable presence online.
</P>
<P>
   CMP's online arm badly lags Ziff-Davis' in the competition for
Web traffic. ZDNet was the 13th most visited Web site last month,
while CMPNet ranked 650th, according to PC Data.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Tchong, editor of Iconocast, an Internet marketing
newsletter, said the print wars are ancient history because paper
publications are going away.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're fighting a battle of print that belongs in the
dinosaur age,'' he said. ``The battle is not in print. The battle
is online.''
</P>
<P>
   Tchong said many prospective buyers were turned off by CMP's
high asking price.
</P>
<P>
   United News, which bought Miller Freeman in 1985, is Britain's
fourth-largest media company, with revenues of $3 billion last
year. It has a well-known line of Fleet Street publications,
including the Express and the Daily Star.
</P>
<P>
   British analysts applauded the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very nice strategic move,'' said Louise Barton, an
analyst at Investec Henderson Crosthwaite, who rates United News a
``buy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going all the way from magazines to these electronic
portals.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Mark Hawkes at CCF Charterhouse hailed the notion of
selling stock in CMPNet, and said, ``It looks a sensible deal at a
good price.''
</P>
<P>
   United News paid CMP a cash price of $39 per share _ a 15
percent premium over Wednesday's closing price. CMP shares rose
$4.56 to $38.44 yesterday. On the Nasdaq market, United News &AMP;
Media shares rose $1.50 to $23.75. In London, United News shares
rose 7 percent to close at $11.60.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst, who asked not to be identified, said it was unusual
for United News to pay cash in an era when most mergers involve at
least some swapping of stock. He speculated that stock, with its
inherent risks, could have driven the price higher.
</P>
<P>
   The companies hope to close the deal within 25 business days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
