<SLUG> BC-HEDGE-FUNDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEDGE FUND REPORT RAISES FEW HACKLES ON WALL STREET 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hedge fund managers, who six months ago were beside
themselves that regulators might clamp down on their freewheeling
partnerships in the wake of Long-Term Capital Management's
near-collapse, are breathing easier.
</P>
<P>
   A long-awaited government report released Thursday did not
propose _ at least for now _ any direct regulation of hedge funds,
recommending instead heightened disclosure and perhaps greater
reviews of trading practices and capital requirements for brokerage
firms and banks that deal in derivatives and make loans to hedge
funds.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the President's Working Group on Financial Markets
followed the failure last fall of Long-Term Capital, a hedge fund
in Greenwich, Conn., that suffered huge losses when its debt-laden
portfolio crumbled, helping to roil financial markets worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Congress will ultimately decide what to do with many of the
recommendations. But the report has already ruled out requiring the
funds to make explicit disclosures of specific investment positions
and strategies. And it even contained a victory of sorts for hedge
funds by noting that many large Wall Street firms _ and not just
hedge funds _ routinely use almost as much debt in their day-to-day
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``This report contains ideas that are constructive and
healthy,'' said Leon Metzger, president of Paloma Partners Co. LLC,
a large hedge fund, who testified before Congress on the matter. It
recognizes, he said, that ``other financial institutions are
generally more highly leveraged than private investment funds.''
</P>
<P>
   E. Lee Hennessee, chief executive of Hennessee Group, a New York
hedge-fund advisory service, said, ``Ninety percent of them are not
affected by any of this.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not going to be something that overwhelms everybody,''
she added, though ``it is going to affect people who use excessive
leverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Other managers of large hedge funds said the recommendations
would create more difficulties for banks and brokerage firms than
for them. A top official of one of the nation's largest hedge
funds, who asked not to be identified, said the recommendations
were not likely to cause major changes for the industry,
``depending on how this plays out'' in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   A chief industry concern was that the report would include the
recommendation that fund managers disclose specific information on
trading positions and strategies. That would allow smaller traders
to profit by anticipating a fund's next move.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, ``what they've tried to recommend are disclosures that
are more top-down, how much leverage you have, what are the
liquidity and concentrations,'' the hedge-fund manager said.
``Those are the types of things we are very happy to provide to our
lenders, though we're not necessarily eager to make them public.''
</P>
<P>
   Had regulators recommended requiring new disclosures about
specific strategies and positions, ``every hedge fund would leave
the United States,'' a manager of another large hedge fund said.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual-fund companies had been among the loudest critics of
hedge funds following LTC's plunge, attributing the stock market
drop and other fallout that ensued to a lack of regulation that had
allowed the hedge fund to borrow about $30 for every $1 of its
investors' money _ leverage that accelerated the fund's plummet.
</P>
<P>
   While the report could have called for much tougher oversight
and regulation of the industry, it is ``great news,'' said John
Brennan, chief executive of Vanguard Group, the nation's
second-largest mutual fund company. ``I didn't think the
recommendations would be as concrete.''
</P>
<P>
   Brennan, who is also chairman of the Investment Company
Institute, the mutual fund industry's trade group, said the
proposals, if carried out, would give federal regulators ``better
access to information about these unregulated vehicles that will
help avoid the kind of overreaching that occurred last year. There
will be less extreme risk as a result of these in the
marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, David Runkel, a House Banking Committee
spokesman, said the panel's chairman, Rep. James Leach, R-Iowa,
``was disappointed it didn't say right off the bat that the first
government policy should be we are not going to bail out these
suckers.'' Federal regulators had organized a consortium of banks
to rescue LTC in September.
</P>
<P>
   But Runkel added that ``generally, on first blink, it is a very
well-reasoned, common-sense approach that's not intrusive but does
provide a few additional safeguards.''
</P>
<P>
   For lenders to hedge funds, the recommendations seek far greater
disclosure of the loans. If further recommendations are needed,
regulators could propose much greater supervision of investment
houses.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wall Street had little to say Thursday about the report.
A spokesman for Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. said, ``We are reviewing
details of the report and look forward to working constructively
with the regulators and Congress to address the issues raised.''
</P>
<P>
   And Citigroup and Chase Manhattan Corp., two of the largest
banks that had each been involved with Long-Term Capital, both
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   But one industry official said: ``I dont think it's a big
problem. We are still looking through it. We now know what the gist
is. There was a problem last fall and we want to work with them.
It's no fun seeing the global financial system brought to its
knees.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
