<SLUG> BC-INVEST-MULTINATIONALS-ART-$ADV02-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING MULTINATIONALS AN INDEX OF THEIR OWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2)  
 (af)  
 By DYLAN LOEB McCLAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Diversification is one of the cardinal rules of investing, and
it is on many people's minds as they put their money into various
single-country index funds to spread risks among financial markets.
But such a strategy may overlook the burgeoning influence of
multinational companies on the national indexes.
</P>
<P>
   Because country indexes usually weight the stocks within them
according to market capitalization, multinationals, which are
typically large, can have an undue influence on them, some analysts
say. Moreover, a big economic event that affects a multinational's
business abroad can unduly influence the index of the nation where
its stock is based. That can make otherwise independent markets
move in unison, undermining diversity.
</P>
<P>
   A fund manager who wants to track the British market will find
that ``the biggest UK stocks aren't really UK companies anymore,''
said Matthew Annable, a managing director of Barclays Global
Investors, a fund management company. ``It just happens to be that
they have an office in the UK.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, multinationals account for more than half of the market
capitalization of indexes for countries like Sweden and
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   To address the issue, Barclays Global Investors; Bacon &AMP;
Woodrow, a large European consulting company, and FTSE
International, which develops indexes, are proposing an index that
will treat multinationals as a separate asset class and at the same
time keep them out of some new single-country indexes.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary study of how the new index might work, using data
from 1988 to 1998, turned up mixed results. Companies in the Morgan
Stanley Capital International World index that were in the top
quartile based on market capitalization and had at least half their
sales outside their home markets were classified as multinationals.
Then the performances of local indexes with and without these
stocks were compared over a 10-year period.
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected, the indexes with the highest
concentrations of multinationals saw the biggest declines in their
correlation to other countries' market indexes once the
multinationals were removed.
</P>
<P>
   But many European market indexes tracked one another more
closely once the multinationals were removed. The report explained
the anomaly by suggesting that some European companies that do
business primarily in Europe really shouldn't have been classified
as multinationals because Europe is increasingly becoming one
market.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees that multinationals should be removed from
local indexes. Brian Mattes, a principal at Vanguard Group, the
index fund giant, said the matter was ``not a concern at present.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Crosby, director of global marketing at Morgan Stanley
Capital International, acknowledged the disproportionate impact
that big multinationals can have on indexes but argued it was not
necessarily time to treat them as a separate asset class.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are witnessing now is sort of a new phenomenon from
these huge cross-border mergers,'' she said, adding that many older
multinationals continue to reflect the performance of local
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Annable said the companies proposing the multinational index
plan to refine it and introduce it by this fall, along with new
local indexes revised to remove large-cap multinationals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
