<HEADLINE>
TWO TEXAS CHILDREN BURIED AS MOM CHARGED WITH ABANDONMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMIE STOCKWELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGETOWN, Texas _ While two children found dead in a creekbed
last week were buried Thursday afternoon, their 22-year-old mother
was charged with two counts of child abandonment, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson County District Attorney Ken Anderson announced the
charges against Tina Marie Cornelius, a topless dancer from Austin,
who was found Wednesday evening at a Corpus Christi apartment after
a weeklong search.
</P>
<P>
   Cornelius' children, 3-year-old Amanda Lee Miller and 2-year-old
Dominick Logan Cornelius, were found April 19 in 6 inches of water
in Brushy Creek, just south of Hutto. Autopsy reports show that
Amanda died of suffocation and her brother died from a cracked
skull.
</P>
<P>
   According to the probable cause statement, Cornelius told
authorities she was present and ``observed Amanda and Dominick when
they were injured and lying in the creekbed or ditch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defendant told affiant that she left the children in the
creekbed or ditch and thought they were alive when she left. She
indicated she did not go back to help them,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   A Williamson County grand jury will hear the evidence May 18,
Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been an extremely hectic and extremely involved last 24
hours,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the homicide investigation will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will make absolutely positively sure of the facts before
any other charges are filed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The children were buried Thursday in a service attended by about
70 relatives, day-care teachers and friends. Cornelius was in
custody and did not attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are reminded of the incongruity of this moment by the
presence of these two small coffins,'' the Rev. Phil Ware said of
the identical white coffins decked with pale roses and sprigs of
baby's breath. ``We are angered at the loss of all that these lives
were intended to be, but which will never be realized.''
</P>
<P>
   In the foyer of the funeral home, a photo collage showed the
youngsters unwrapping Christmas presents and splashing in a baby
pool. Drawings made by the boy and girl also were displayed. Some
mourners wore pink and blue ribbons above their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   The children were last seen April 14 when Cornelius picked them
up from day care, according to police. Their bodies were found five
days later, but police do not think that they had been in the creek
long.
</P>
<P>
   Cornelius is in county jail on a $200,000 bond, $100,000 for
each second-degree felony charge. Both are punishable by two to 20
years in state prison.
</P>
<P>
   Cornelius was interviewed at the Corpus apartment for six hours
before being flown to Austin for further interrogation, authorities
said. It was not known whether she voluntarily returned to Austin,
or who she was staying with in Corpus.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Cornelius did not resist the officers and agreed
to answer their questions. Before tracking her down, police had
expressed concern that she might be in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Police have been investigating the claims of a 25-year-old man
who says he spent the weekend with Cornelius. He told authorities
that she told him the children's father had taken them and they had
died by falling off a cliff. The children have different fathers.
</P>
<P>
   The man told the Austin American-Statesman that he had a brief
relationship with Cornelius that began on Saturday, April 17, at an
Austin musical festival and continued through the morning of April
19, about half a day before the children's bodies were found.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
