<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NUKE-360&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA SPY SUSPECT REPORTEDLY TRIED TO HIDE EVIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JAMES RISEN and JEFF GERTH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A scientist suspected of spying for China tried to
hide evidence that he had transferred nuclear secrets out of a
computer system at a government nuclear weapons laboratory two days
after he failed an FBI polygraph examination in February, according
to U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
   The scientist, Wen Ho Lee, deleted more than 1,000 files
containing millions of lines of classified computer codes related
to nuclear weapons from the computer system at Los Alamos National
Laboratory after the lie detector test in February. U.S. officials
say one of the questions on the test, on which he was shown to be
deceptive, related to his computer use at Los Alamos, where he
worked since 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Lee had not deleted the enormous files earlier, but had moved
them out of the lab's classified computer, renamed them and stored
them in an unsecure system years earlier, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI discovered the deleted files in March, after Lee gave
the bureau permission to search his office computer. The
administrator of the computer systems at Los Alamos then helped the
bureau to recreate the deleted files. Officials say that after the
polygraph test, Lee, apparently aware that investigators were
suspicious of his computer use, deleted between 1,000 and 2,000
files.
</P>
<P>
   Lee was fired from his job at Los Alamos on March 8 for security
violations, but has not been charged with any crime.
</P>
<P>
   Lee has denied wrongdoing. His lawyer could not be reached on
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Experts from the FBI and Los Alamos said they were horrified
when they began to sift through the files that they say Lee
transferred and then deleted. He had downloaded what amount to the
keys to the American nuclear arsenal, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The computer codes and data were, in effect, the distillation of
more than a half-century of research on how to perfect nuclear
weapons, they said. They included the so-called legacy codes that
enable scientists to generate computer simulations of nuclear
explosions. When coupled with data on the performance of specific
warheads, they create a virtual blueprint of the nuclear explosive
parts of a nuclear weapon.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   American officials contend that Lee transferred files out of the
classified computer and into an unclassified computer network at
Los Alamos between 1983 and 1995. Most of the reported transfers
took place in 1994 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have not determined whether China obtained the
computer data. But there is evidence that someone accessed the
files after they moved to the unclassified system.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say Lee came under suspicion in 1996. Yet he
retained his access to nuclear secrets at Los Alamos for nearly
three more years, and no one checked his computer. The FBI and the
Energy Department, which owns the government's nuclear weapons
laboratories, are now facing sharp criticism from Congress for
their failure to control his access to secrets or to monitor his
computer use.
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials say that in 1997 the Justice Department rejected
their request to seek court approval to wiretap Lee's telephone and
covertly monitor his computer use.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau has been seeking to re-interview Lee and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the FBI, Louis Freeh, was questioned about the
bureau's handling of the case in a closed briefing for the Senate
Select Committee on Intelligence Thursday. After the hearing, Sen.
Richard C. Shelby, Republican of Alabama and chairman of the panel,
said he was not satisfied with the way the case had been handled.
But he said Freeh had pledged that it was now one of the bureau's
highest priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby said the briefing confirmed ``some of our worst fears.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 2207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0457 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8718 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-PIPPEN-HNS &LR;      04-29 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PIPPEN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIPPEN MUM AS DWI CASE IS RESCHEDULED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE BREWER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Scottie Pippen ran a fast break through a Houston
courtroom Thursday, quickly securing a reset of his drunken-driving
case and then giving reporters the slip.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen, who is in his first season with the Houston Rockets,
must appear in Harris County Criminal Court-at-Law Judge Sherman A.
Ross' court again May 26.
</P>
<P>
   The brief court appearance marked Pippen's first to answer to
the driving-while-intoxicated charge he was arrested on last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real comfortable, after investigating it, with the
conclusion that he was not intoxicated that night,'' said his
attorney Rusty Hardin. ``We're confident that will be the system's
ultimate conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardin wouldn't say what had brought him to that conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows and believes he wasn't intoxicated, and he didn't do
anything wrong,'' Hardin said. ``He's willing to let the system
take its course, and he's comfortable that's the conclusion
everyone else will reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen's appearance in court seemed to be a welcome diversion
for onlookers in the hall and in Ross' court. But he said nothing
to reporters and repeatedly declined to comment by shaking his
head.
</P>
<P>
   With news cameras and reporters trying to keep up with his quick
pace, Pippen eluded most of them afterward on a courthouse
staircase. He went to a tunnel below the courthouse and waited to
be picked up.
</P>
<P>
   Found there by a reporter and asked again for comment, he again
shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   Police stopped Pippen's Mercedes at 1:20 a.m. April 22 after he
allegedly passed traffic stopped for a red light at Prairie by
driving south in the northbound lanes of Main in downtown.
</P>
<P>
   After talking with Pippen, an officer thought he was
intoxicated, and called a member of the DWI Task Force. Police say
Pippen failed a field sobriety test and was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say he was later videotaped and refused to take a
Breathalyzer test.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen, 33, was charged with misdemeanor DWI. He was released
after posting a $500 bail.
</P>
<P>
   Patrons of the Jones Bar in Houston said Pippen was there after
an April 21 game, with teammates Charles Barkley and Matt Maloney.
The Rockets had lost 109-95 to the Dallas Mavericks in Compaq
Center, with Pippen scoring only four points.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen was arrested in Chicago in January 1994 after a police
officer checking on his illegally parked car noticed a loaded
.380-caliber semiautomatic handgun inside. The charge was dismissed
when a judge ruled the officer had no probable cause to look in the
car.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen was charged with misdemeanor domestic battery in May
1995, after being accused of grabbing his fiancee, Yvette Deleone,
and shoving her. The case was dismissed when Deleone declined to
testify.
</P>
<P>
   After an 11-year career with the Chicago Bulls, which earned him
six NBA Championship rings and the status as one of the league's
most talented players, Pippen was traded to the Rockets in January.
The team signed him to a five-year, $67 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
