u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS &LR;      04-29 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT APPEARS TO DIM CONNECTICUT STADIUM HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEG VAILLANCOURT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Connecticut's bid to lure the New England Patriots
suffered a potentially fatal setback Thursday as consultants to
team owner Robert Kraft told him it was unlikely a new Hartford
stadium could be completed on time or within budget, people
familiar with the situation said.
</P>
<P>
   The consultants concluded that ``there is a low probability that
the stadium can be ready for a 2002 opening date,'' the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
   That bleak assessment dramatically bolsters the counteroffer
made this week by Massachusetts to keep the team.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the local effort said they were increasingly
confident the Patriots would reject Connecticut's record-breaking
deal, and instead accept Beacon Hill's offer to provide $70 million
in infrastructure funds if Kraft builds a privately financed
stadium in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft met privately Thursday evening in Hartford with Governor
John G. Rowland to discuss the status of Connecticut's work to
prepare the site on which it would build a 68,000-seat stadium with
$374 million in taxpayer money.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft would not comment on the report. Under the terms of his
agreement with Connecticut, Kraft is legally bound not to discuss
any plan other than the Hartford stadium deal.
</P>
<P>
   But before he flew to Connecticut Kraft received a ``very
critical'' status report from the team of consultants he hired to
help him determine whether the Hartford stadium proposal is
realistic.
</P>
<P>
   Based on all the data Connecticut provided to the Patriots, the
consultants concluded that ``there is a high degree of risk
associated with planning for the stadium to be open for the 2002
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the problems plaguing Connecticut's bid for the Patriots:
</P>
<P>
   --Soil tests were delayed and results are not expected for
several weeks. Without that information it is unclear whether the
state can prepare the site on time and within the budget allocated
by the Legislature. Further delays are likley if the project
requires additional funding authorization.
</P>
<P>
   --The state has not come up with a fully detailed plan to move
the steam plant on the Hartford site, which could cause the state's
2002 timetable to slip further behind.
</P>
<P>
   --Current designs call for part of the stadium to be built over
a highway, and construction experts have already questioned whether
the work can be done within the $55 million allocated by the state.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the team's consultants believe it's unlikely
Connecticut can meet its promised deadline could kill the Nutmeg
State's bid for the Patriots, sources in both Massachusetts and
Connecticut said.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft can terminate his contract with Connecticut at no cost if
he decides by Sunday that the state cannot deliver on its promise
of opening the stadium by 2002 or within the budget constraints
outlined in the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The consultants' findings, sources said, hands Kraft the
opportunity to exercise the escape clause.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very, very critical assessment,'' said another source
familiar with the discussions.``The agreement says the stadium will
open 2002. And that was already a year later than originally
planned.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When Connecticut had trouble, the team accepted the state's
request to push back the deadline to 2002,'' the source said.
``Going to 2003 isn't an option under the contract.''
</P>
<P>
   The consultants also pointed out that the construction timetable
envisioned by Connecticut ``is based on every detail going
perfectly, which is rare in projects of this size and scope,'' one
source said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The project is very complicated and is impacted by a number of
difficult logistical requirements, including building parts of the
stadium over the Whitehead Highway.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Connecticut Attorney General Richard
Blumenthal said he was preparing to sue the National Football
League for actively promoting Massachusetts' bid to keep the
Patriots, despite an agreement Kraft had signed to come to
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit would charge the NFL with interfering with the
agreement between Connecticut and Kraft, and with restraining
competition, by trying to block a move by the Patriots to Hartford,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL is proactively intervening to lure the team away from
an agreement the team has with Connecticut,'' Blumenthal said. ``We
could sue for hundreds of millions of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue is scheduled to meet Tuesday
with Rowland at the governor's request. Connecticut may be talking
tough, but there is a clear record of delays and problems at the
Hartford site. In the end, the NFL does not expect the state will
sue, industry sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL prefers that the Patriots remain in the Boston
television market because games can generate higher broadcast
revenues here than in Hartford's much smaller media market. The
league, along with Boston civic leaders, urged state lawmakers to
come up with a stadium plan that could persuade Kraft from leaving.
House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran, Senate President Thomas F.
Finneran, and Governor Paul Cellucci struck a compromise on
proposed legislation Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Boston business and political leaders continued to
express confidence that the Patriots will remain in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, a drive by the business community to gain
commitments for $15 million in luxury box seats is in full swing.
``We will make it,'' declared advertising executive Jack Connors.
``I am not worried at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday is a crucial deadline for Kraft because he can walk away
from the deal at ``his sole and absolute discretion'' if he feels
an interim report from Connecticut, which formed the basis for his
consultants' evaluation, does not provide enough assurances that
the 2002 deadline can be met. But there are also other escape
hatches for the team in the artfully negotiated contract. The later
exits put Kraft more at risk, however, since they carry possible
fines that would be decided in a Connecticut court.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft can also cancel the Connecticut deal if other team owners
refuse to approve his proposed move to Hartford. Kraft has formally
petitioned the league to make the move, but many expect the owners
will vote against it since it will mean the loss of valuable
broadcast dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
