<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIZZERIA CO-WORKER IS TIED TO GUN IN SCHOOL SHOOTINGS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ill.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold got the
high-powered, semiautomatic pistol used in last week's high school
massacre with the help of a man who worked with them at a pizza
delivery store, law-enforcement officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did have a role in it,'' Sgt. Jim Parr, a spokesman for the
Jefferson County Sheriff's Department, said Thursday, noting that
the man they were interviewing had hired a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   If the co-worker acted as a middleman, linking two minors with
the owner of an automatic weapon, he could face charges as an
accessory to the crime of selling a handgun to someone under 18.
</P>
<P>
   If he had knowledge of the two young men's plans for mayhem,
charges could be stiffer. Klebold was 17 when he and Harris killed
themselves after slaying 12 students and a teacher. Harris turned
18 two weeks before the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of the pizza parlor, Blackjack Pizza, did not return
calls for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Post reported Thursday that the pistol, a Tec-DC9,
went from its Miami manufacturer to Zander Sporting Goods, a
firearms wholesaler in Illinois, then to Just Guns, a suburban gun
store five miles north of Denver. The gun store closed about a year
ago, and the owner, Royce Spain, told The Post that a former
employee had sold the pistol for him at a gun show.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the pistol, officials said three long guns, provided by
Robyn Anderson, who went to the prom with Klebold three days before
the shooting, were used in the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Anderson, 18, bought one or more of the long guns late last
year at the Tanner Gun Show, according to the Jefferson County
sheriff, John P. Stone. The sheriff said Ms. Anderson was a
witness, not a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   A friend, Tiffany Burk, has said that Ms. Anderson did not know
anything about Klebold's massacre plans and that during the
shootout she was caught in a school parking lot, where she cowered
under the seat of her car for three hours.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to trace the guns comes as new details emerge about
the devastation wrought by the two gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers who have toured the cordoned-off high school
said the killers walked from room to room, bombing the cafeteria,
blasting out computer screens in classrooms, heavily shooting up
administration offices and exploding a bomb that blew a hole in a
wall of the library.
</P>
<P>
   The young men had affixed abrasive strips to their trench coats
so they could strike matches to light their bombs. As fire alarms
blared and sprinklers sprayed, they strode through the chaos,
shooting with one hand and throwing pipe bombs with the other.
</P>
<P>
   The news that one or more of the guns was bought at a Denver
area gun show has put a spotlight on a corner of the gun trade.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of the news, a recorded telephone message by the
organizer of a show that was to be held on Saturday, only 10 miles
from Littleton, said the show had been canceled ``due to the
politics in Denver at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Gun shows are held in the Denver area almost every weekend, and
buyers flock to them because they can buy guns anonymously from
vendors. Appealing largely to white, middle-aged men, vendors
advertise with signs that say, ``Cash and Carry'' and ``No
Paperwork, No Questions Asked.''
</P>
<P>
   Last November, about the time Ms. Anderson apparently bought one
or more ``long guns'' at the Tanner Gun Show, area gun shows
experienced a surge in rifle and shotgun sales as buyers sought to
beat a Nov. 30 deadline. On that day, federally licensed firearms
dealers were required to expand mandatory background checks from
buyers of handguns to buyers of ``long guns,'' or rifles and
shotguns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cash and a handshake,'' Bob Glass, owner of Paladin Arms
in Boulder, said of sales by unlicensed dealers at gun shows. ``An
underage buyer has a good chance.'' Defenders of the shows say they
give blue-collar gun owners an alternative to ``high end'' firearms
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the federal government estimates, roughly five
million people attended 5,000 gun shows, typically held in
convention centers, hotel meeting rooms or at country fair grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how many come out to the Tanner Gun Show,'' said
Darrell Hare, president of the Denver Merchandise Mart, which has a
maximum occupancy of 2,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, after Denver experienced a rash of drive-by shootings,
Denver's City Council banned the sale of 33 assault weapons _
rifles, shotguns and pistols, including the Intratec Tec-DC9.
Because of the ban, gun shows are generally held in halls near the
first interstate highway exit outside of Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Merchandise Mart, which hosts the Tanner Show nine
times a year, is six blocks north of the city. Most of the region's
gun shops, like ``Just Guns,'' the one linked to the Intratec sale,
are outside the city limits.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Last June, an aide to Rep. Diana DeGette, D-Denver, went to a
Tanner show at the Mart and bought a Chinese-made version of an
AK-47 semiautomatic assault rifle for $450 in cash. According to a
transcript of the conversation released by the congresswoman, the
only question the seller asked the buyer, aside from dickering over
a price, was, ``Are you interested?''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, President Clinton included in his package of gun
control legislation a bill that DeGette has sponsored requiring
background checks at private-transaction gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association, which is to hold its annual
meeting in Denver on Saturday, has long opposed such legislation.
Last fall, it pressured Denver to relax its assault weapon ban.
</P>
<P>
   After Denver officials refused, the association threw its
support in the state Legislature behind a bill that would have
pre-empted local gun control ordinances. The bill, which was
expected to be passed, was withdrawn last week after the shootings
in Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   While investigators are trying to unravel the gun trail, more
details are emerging about the killers, and investigators said they
were setting up interviews with the parents.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, a Juvenile Court magistrate admitted that the pair
fooled him in March of last year when they appeared before him on
charges of breaking into a car and stealing electronic equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was, `yes, your honor, no, your honor,''' John A. DeVita
said. ``They were appropriately dressed, nothing in their demeanor
that I can recall that was inappropriate. They didn't come all in
black.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on their demeanor and because they were first offenders,
the magistrate allowed the two to enter a juvenile diversion
program. They were to attend anger management classes, perform
community service, and promise not to own firearms.
</P>
<P>
   But within weeks of this court appearance, Stone said, Harris
started a diary that became a blueprint for a plot to blow up the
school. Late last year, about two months before the pair graduated
from the program, Ms. Anderson apparently bought one or more guns,
the sheriff has said.
</P>
<P>
   In a tape of the magistrate's interview with the boys and their
fathers last year, DeVita can be heard praising Wayne Harris,
Eric's father, for ``ratcheting back his curfew.'' Addressing the
retired Air Force officer, he said, ``Good for you, dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Eric can be heard meekly listing his household chores:
``Laundry, pick up the trash, vacuum, sweep the floors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you do that without being told?'' the magistrate asked
Eric.
</P>
<P>
   Eric replied, ``Yes, your honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on the lack of red flags in the Harris-Klebold case,
DeVita said of the five-minute encounter: ``Both dads were there,
and that's pretty rare. Most of the time, it's moms only.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
