<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8726 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLUB-MED-ART-900(2TAK     04-29 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLUB-MED-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLUB MED IS GETTING A BIT SERIOUS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Colo., Utah, Mexico, Singapore, Belgium)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANCUN, Mexico _ The 85-acre Club Med resort here, like many of
its counterparts around the globe, has lured millions of
vacationers to the tropics by offering them a simple choice: work
on their tans or keep active from sunup until exhaustion playing
tennis, hiking, snorkeling or wind surfing.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing it never offered was cultural or literary
enrichment _ until now. In early April, some 20 novelists,
essayists, poets and book editors gathered for a weeklong literary
forum, to discuss weighty topics like diversity and the
globalization of literature. The discussions were open to any of
Club Med's 400 or more guests.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that Club Med _ formally Club Mediterranee S.A. _ the
Paris-based company credited with originating the ``all-inclusive''
vacation with one price that covers transportation, meals,
accommodations and recreation.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the same company that fell on hard financial times
through much of this decade, a casualty of rundown properties, a
reputation for mediocre food and amenities, the aging of the baby
boomers, a backlash against the sexual revolution and an
inconsistent message that was filtered through eight advertising
agencies in different countries.
</P>
<P>
   But now Club Med is making a comeback. Attendance is rising, the
company turned a modest profit last year and 74 of its 116 villages
are undergoing a $350 million facelift. While hurdles remain,
analysts say Club Med is finally heading in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting that perception, the stock of Club Med, which fell to
a 12-month low of 59.91 euros ($63.67) on Oct. 2, 1998, has
recovered sharply in recent months. Thursday, it closed at 86.95
euros.
</P>
<P>
   Current management is well aware that the name Club Med is far
more synonymous with the pursuit of pleasure than with the life of
the mind. But that has not deterred Philippe Bourguignon, Club
Med's chairman since 1997, from trying to change those perceptions
with offerings like the forum here, the first in North America.
Others are expected to follow.
</P>
<P>
   One purpose of the forums, clearly, is to help quash the
perception of Club Med as a swingers' paradise. For even if it
wanted to, Club Med, a public company operating in 36 countries,
would find it virtually impossible to compete with resorts that
have sprung up in Europe, Asia and the Caribbean in recent years
catering exclusively to hedonistic lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   So Club Med is pretty much stuck with a strategy that has been
evolving for more than a decade: a mix of villages, some with
special programs for children (there are now 56) some that welcome
children but have no special programs or amenities for them (22).
The other 38 are for anyone 18 or over, featuring disco nights,
Broadway entertainment and chug-a-lug contests, where the mating
dance _ for straights and, increasingly at some sites, gays _
remains intact.
</P>
<P>
   But even that strategy is not risk-free, given the spurt of
all-inclusive resorts, including dozens of them here in Cancun. So
one way to lift attendance is through niche markets, whether of
cultural mavens or golfers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have 76,000 beds in their villages, and these forums can
help them by building a bigger customer base, especially with
people they are not yet reaching,'' said Armel Coville, an analyst
with ABN AMRO in Paris. ``It's a good strategy, because it can help
increase their overall occupancy rate. And each one-point gain in
the occupancy rate equals about 60 million francs,'' or about $10
million.
</P>
<P>
   Under Bourguignon, 51, who took over Club Med in April 1997,
occupancy rose to 72.3 percent last year, up from 69.1 percent in
fiscal 1997 and 66.9 percent in fiscal 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Other results have also improved under Bourguignon, who was
recruited after the Agnelli family of Italy, the biggest
stockholder in Club Med, despaired of the losses and dwindling
attendance under the leadership of Serge Trigano, the son of
Gilbert Trigano, the company visionary and longtime chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   In the fiscal year ended Oct. 31, attendance at Club Med rose 5
percent, to almost 1.6 million, although it is still well below the
record 1.8 million set in 1989. Equally important, after huge
losses in both 1997 ($215 million) and 1996 ($130 million), the
company earned $30 million on revenue of $1.5 billion. Now,
Bourguignon predicts profits of about 5.5 percent in each of the
next two years, despite the loss of up to 10 percent of its rooms
during the renovation.
</P>
<P>
   But Club Med has not just been renovating properties. It has
been making other changes and fashioning plans both big and small.
</P>
<P>
   A big change is the decision to concentrate its sales and
marketing efforts on France, the United States, Canada, Belgium,
Japan, Italy, Germany and Switzerland, countries that account for
74 percent of visitors.
</P>
<P>
   With Japan in an economic slump and American attendance lagging
for a half-dozen years, Club Med's financial turnaround last year
came largely from European vacationers. But with its millions of
people with abundant disposable incomes, the United States is Club
Med's No. 1 target these days. Combined United States and Canadian
visitors totaled 189,000 last year, trailing by a large margin the
598,200 from France. And that was the lowest total in at least six
years _ and 11,500 fewer than in 1995. Still, Bourguignon said he
expected customers from the United States to equal those from
France in five years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, Club Med is considering building another
village in Florida, to complement its family village at Port St.
Lucie and plans to build its second U.S. ski resort in Colorado or
Utah _ resorts that unlike its 28 ski resorts in Europe can double
as summer vacation spots.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Club Med is pouring millions into advertising to
rejuvenate what is still a strong brand name but one that, it
acknowledges, ``has remained fuzzy and poorly understood'' chiefly
because each of its eight advertising agencies interpreted the ad
campaign's message in a different way. Each village is now ranked
with two, three or four tridents, based on amenities and comfort
level, with the result that the 13 budget Club Aquarius villages
are being folded into the two-trident category.
</P>
<P>
   And by 2003, Club Med will open minicenters in as many as 15
cities, including Paris, Singapore, Montreal, Brussels, Belgium,
and Barcelona, Spain, to give local residents a daylong sample of
the Club Med experience and to reacquaint former customers with
that experience.
</P>
<P>
   Another change involves pricing. This includes a more
sophisticated application of yield management to determine when to
lower prices during slack seasons and raise them (or at least guard
against lowering them) when demand is high. At the same time, Club
Med has already lowered prices at many villages as much as 30
percent to compete with other all-inclusive options, especially
cruise ships, which offer amenities in addition to visits to
foreign ports.
</P>
<P>
   Bourguignon acknowledges that cruise lines pose a serious
challenge, adding that Club Med is ``doing a lot of work about
whether we should match it or fight it.'' It should decide in about
six months, he said, what strategy to pursue.
</P>
<P>
   He also acknowledges that Club Med's relatively small size in an
industry that is steadily consolidating puts it at a disadvantage.
But he no longer favors Club Med's acquisition by Euro Disney,
which he championed while he was chief executive of Euro Disney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then there were synergies,'' he said, ``because both
companies had problems with their reservation systems and both of
us recruited the same types of people each year, so we could have
formed a training program. But now it's too late because both of us
have our own reservations systems and our own training programs.''
</P>
<P>
   So he is trying to set Club Med apart with innovations like the
literary forum. As an early announcement about the forum put it,
``Most Americans don't immediately think of culture in terms of
Club Med.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the writers in attendance were Rick Bass, Bharti
Mukherjee, John Edgar Weidman, Gish Jen, Susan Minot and Jay
McInerney.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks kicking off the forum, Bourguignon spoke of his
appreciation for the culture of America, where he had lived 10
years, and of his regard for Hemingway, Twain and Steinbeck, whose
books he had read as a schoolboy.
</P>
<P>
   But in interviews, Bourguignon, who is widely credited with
turning Euro Disney, an early money loser, into a financial
success, made it clear that he had no intention of trying to turn
Club Meds into latter-day Chautauquas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is not necessarily to attract a lot of people who
would come because of the forums,'' Bourguignon said, ``because
that would change the personality of Club Med.''
</P>
<P>
   The main purpose, he added, is to give Club Med vacationers
still another option, the opportunity to hear and mingle with
writers as at some Club Meds they mingle with sports figures, and
for the wider community ``to better understand what Club Med is all
about, beyond the cliches.''
</P>
<P>
   His idea of soft-pedaling the forums has already found favor
with some Club Med customers here. ``If I came especially for the
forum and found out it was only an hour or two a night, I'd be
disappointed,'' said Helga Lemke, the director of a nonprofit
community action program in Santa Rosa, Calif. But she had not
heard about it, and after attending the first two sessions, she
pronounced herself well satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Georgina Hinrichsen, a 28-year-old New Yorker who
came here to relax, was surprised to learn of the forums. ``But
it's a great idea,'' she said, ``and I can see where some people
would want to schedule vacations around them.'' As it was,
attendance at the sessions averaged a respectable 100 or so people
a night.
</P>
<P>
   What Club Med villages do not have, except in a few villages
outside of North America, are gambling casinos, and despite
overtures from several Las Vegas companies, it has no immediate
plans to jump aboard that bandwagon. ``We don't have the competence
for that,'' Bourguignon said, ``so for now, we'll stick to what we
know best.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
