<HEADLINE>
BIDDERS WITHOUT FACES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 2) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DANIEL AKST   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The auction, it seems, is the emblematic transaction of our
time, as characteristic of fin-de-siecle America as the potlatch in
some tribal societies, or imperial land grants in colonial days. As
a means of exchange, it encapsulates a good deal about us, with our
emphasis on individual freedom, fair markets and, lately,
technology.
</P>
<P>
   For while many of us still imagine a fast-talking,
gavel-wielding auctioneer, or perhaps the desperate shouting of
traders in the commodities pits, the rise of the auction is now
fueled by computers.
</P>
<P>
   We are not far removed _ a couple of hundred years perhaps _
from a time when ordinary people had no practical way to sell
things to anyone but their neighbors, or perhaps to a few strangers
at a market fair. Now, because of the Internet, we can auction
almost anything among millions of potential buyers at minimal
transaction costs. Culturally, this phenomenon has implications.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, it means the death of the bargain. After all,
bargains depend on such market imperfections as inadequate
information, barriers of time and distance, and so on. Buy
something in an Internet auction and you can be sure you are paying
the highest possible price.
</P>
<P>
   Economists refer to the ``winner's curse,'' which comes free
with whatever you happen to acquire at an auction. (The curse is
winning.)
</P>
<P>
   Prowl Ebay for a while and you'll sometimes see people bidding
as much for second-hand stuff as the same items would cost new.
Sometimes, bidders even drive the price above retail.
</P>
<P>
   The tendency to overpay at auction, of course, is not limited to
the Internet. Auctions have changed the nature of book publishing,
for example: Manuscripts or even fragments of manuscripts by top
authors attract frenzied bidding from publishers chasing the next
blockbuster, while piles of work by the rest of us poor hacks are
left to languish unloved in mid-list hell.
</P>
<P>
   The same dynamic is at work in the movie business, where studio
heads desperately bid huge sums to land the few hot scripts, and in
pro sports, where stars with expiring contracts can weigh multiple
proffered fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   In retail transactions, auctions take consumers another step
away from the face-to-face dealings once so central to village
life. On-line auctions are efficient, but how do you get one to
sponsor a Little League team, or lower an awning over Main Street
when it rains?
</P>
<P>
   To the extent that business becomes more virtual, so do
communities. The growth of auctions suggests we're becoming a
nation of solitary consumers, trading electronic balances for
overpriced tchotchkes without ever leaving home. Talk about home
shopping networks!
</P>
<P>
   While auctions do a good job of setting prices for copper and
pork bellies, the Everyman sort of auction fostered by the Internet
depends heavily on cultural ``commodities'' whose value is more
subjective.
</P>
<P>
   To help us arrive at a bid for pork bellies, we have information
about bacon consumption, population trends, herds on hog farms and
so forth. But who really knows how to value a lamp by Poul
Henningsen or a painting by Irving Lehman?
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon is also at work in the astonishing run-up of
Internet stocks, whose value, to the denizens of chat rooms and the
world of on-line trading, is just as subjective in the absence of
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   We may long for a world in which we buy staples across the
counter from a kindly old fellow in an apron, yet we like auctions
almost as much as we like the ``category killer'' superstores that
have wiped out the mom-and-pop retailers of memory.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, though, Internet auctions may have more in common with
market day in a medieval village than with ordering from the
operator at the toll-free number in Omaha. Ebay offers the
opportunity to inquire about items for sale via e-mail, and, after
the transaction, you can rate the person you bought from.
</P>
<P>
   These ratings are recorded, and anyone can look up anyone else's
record before entering a transaction. In other words, J.P. Morgan
has been proved right again: Character counts.
</P>
<P>
   And so far, when you buy something in an on-line auction, you're
not dealing with Wal-Mart or Home Depot, but rather with Joe
Cyberspace in Columbus, Ohio, who happens to be parting with a pair
of arts and crafts bookends you just can't live without. In this
day of a shrinking globe and vanishing community, that's something.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Akst is a novelist and financial journalist. His column
on the cultural dimensions of money and business appears the first
Sunday of each month. E-mail: culmoney(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
