u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-DERBY-ARCHDEACON3     04-29 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-ARCHDEACON30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sheik looks to expand crown of victory at Kentucky Derby
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Everyone on the Churchill Downs backside
stopped to watch the royal parade as it headed to the track
Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Five tiny blue-capped riders atop five well-muscled horses
wearing blue-trimmed saddle cloths were followed by a throng of
stablehands, trainers, gawkers, television crews, photographers and
one small, bearded man with a blue shirt, blue jeans, boots with
spurs and a pair of binoculars in one one hand.
</P>
<P>
   The last time there was this much fascination over a bunch of
blue uniforms in this state, Tubby Smith was guiding the University
of Kentucky Wildcats to the national crown.
</P>
<P>
   This is a crown affair, as well.
</P>
<P>
   The bearded man is Sheik Mohammed bin Rashid al-Maktoum, the
Crown Prince of Dubai, the single, most powerful person in the
entire world of thoroughbred racing and the man who has turned the
125th running of the Kentucky Derby into a much-debated Middle East
mystery, with his nontraditional thinking, secret training methods
and hidden-from-view horses.
</P>
<P>
   That's why all eyes were on the Sheik as he accompanied his two
Derby horses _ the big bay colt Worldly Manner and the smaller
Aljabr _ to the track for some unconventional 5 furlong work just
two days before the race.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, everything about this Derby effort is against the
grain. Although Worldly Manner was considered possibly the best
2-year-old in American racing last September, neither of the colts
has raced as a 3-year-old _ a practice that hasn't produced a Derby
winner since Morvich in 1922.
</P>
<P>
   Instead the Sheik and his three brothers _ who together own
Godolphin Racing _ have kept their horses on the other side of the
world, training in a plush, but strictly private compound in Dubai.
</P>
<P>
   And that raises plenty of questions. Can you train a Derby horse
in the middle of the desert? Can you skip the traditional prep
races in Florida, California and Kentucky? Can you ship a horse
over nine time zones, take him straight out of quarantine and six
days later send him into a grueling 1 mile cavalry call like the
Kentucky Derby? And can a horse that has prepped in solitude handle
the mob scene of 140,000 raucous, cheering fans and a track jammed
with 19 other horses?
</P>
<P>
   ``We will see if this works for us,'' the Sheik said. ``I love
the Kentucky Derby. It's a great challenge and we love challenges.
I'm not saying we are absolutely right here. It's our first time,
so we will learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Many here _ especially after the two colts had plodding workouts
their first time on the track last Sunday _ are skeptical. Hall of
Fame trainer D. Wayne Lukas, who has three Derby wins, said: ``This
is not the junior prom. This is war. This race is usually won by
the horse whose feet have been held to the fire to get tested.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet Lukas, like everyone else, doesn't totally write off the
Sheik because of what he has done. The Sheik has long shown he's
driven by dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday he told of coming to England as a young man to study.
And when he showed a fascination with racing and went to buy his
first three thoroughbreds, he was ridiculed by one racing insider
who said ``Why don't you just stay in your tent and race camels?''
</P>
<P>
   From that dig, he has built a dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   He is from the royal family of Dubai, which is one of seven
emirates making up the United Arab Emirates. Along with serving as
the defense minister of his oil-rich nation, he has put together
the most competitive racing consortium ever assembled.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, he showed up at race sales in Kentucky and spent $41
million on 29 yearlings. Back home, he and his brothers built Al
Quoz Racing Stables, a facility with a private track, a 250 foot
swimming pool for horses and some 140 thoroughbreds, most said by
racing experts to be worth over $1 million each. Along with top
trainers from around the world, he employs 40 jockeys from Ireland,
England and the United States and 70 grooms from Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   He owns another facility and track outside Paris that serve as
something of a minor-league farm system. He keeps 120 2-year-olds
there and the best 50 each year are brought to Dubai. In Kentucky,
he owns 5,000 acres of horse farm land worth $70 million in
Fayette, Bourbon and Woodford counties. He has 500 horses here and
employs 300 people.
</P>
<P>
   From such a stockpile, he has won most of the world's most
prestigious horse races. Everything, but the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Then last fall he sent an agent to California to tender an offer
for Worldly Manner, a Bob Baffert trained colt, owned by John and
Betty Mabee, who have General Challenge and Excellent Meeting in
Saturday's Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Worldly Manner had just won the Del Mar Futurity, his third win
in four starts and everyone was raving about him. The agent asked a
price and Mabee _ who said he didn't really want to sell _ tossed
out an exorbitant figure of $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Within two weeks, the money was wired to his account and he said
it was another three weeks until he found out who the buyer was. By
then, Worldly Manner was in Dubai, where he joined Aljabr, who was
bred in Kentucky and won all three of his 2-year-old starts in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the two colts' only competitive race was something
akin to a pair of inhouse scrimmages. The Sheik _ called ``The
Boss'' by his workers _ staged two prep races, using all his own
horses and jockeys like Jerry Bailey, who were flown in. No
spectators or media were allowed to watch and afterward it was
announced each colt had had impressive wins.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the Sheik should know better. He was a part owner of
the French wonderhorse Arazi, who was lightly raced when he came to
the 1992 Derby. Billed as the next Secretariat, he finished a
dismal eighth.
</P>
<P>
   To counter, the Sheik offers Lammtarra, who raced just once as a
2-year-old, wintered in Dubai and then won the demanding 1 mile
Epsom Derby. Since then he has sold the horse for a reported $30
million.
</P>
<P>
   There is method to the Sheik's money madness. With oil reserves
diminishing in Dubai, he's try to build the country's trade and
tourism industries and he's using sports as a rich marketing tool.
</P>
<P>
   He and his brothers already bankroll the $5 million Dubai Cup,
the world's riches horse race, and now they are proposing a $15
million event over three years involving nine races in eight
different countries.
</P>
<P>
   Some see the sheik as a guy who simply tries to buy everything _
including a Derby win. Others, like Derby trainers Nick Zito and
Bob Baffert, say he is great for racing. ``Look at him out here
today,'' Baffert said. ``He wants to be a regular guy and he hangs
out with the trainers. He's like a kid. He's got the fever.''
</P>
<P>
   The sheik didn't argue: ``I love the Derby and this atmosphere.
We are learning how its done here and if we don't win this one, we
will be back again. That I promise.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, as he finished the day's training, he was met by an
assistant carrying in a bag full of food from McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   A Big Mac for The Big Boss?
</P>
<P>
   The guy is learning how it's done here.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
