<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8740 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-ASTROS-HNS     04-29 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The weather outside the Astrodome was pleasant and delightful, much
too nice to be indoors.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Hampton wasn't about to let a little roof get in his way.
He strolled through the Arizona Diamondbacks on Thursday afternoon
as if he were taking a leisurely walk in the park, veering from his
path on only a couple of occasions en route to a 5-2 Astros
victory.
</P>
<P>
   If pitching were as easy as Hampton made it look, Major League
Baseball would have to double the number of teams to accommodate
the wave of job applicants. Hampton spaced four hits over eight
innings and allowed two runs (one earned) in his strongest outing
of the season. He did not walk a man.
</P>
<P>
   And if that weren't enough, he drove in a pair of runs with a
two-out, two-strike double in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm mentally drained,'' Hampton said after the game. ``I left
everything on the field, and that's a good feeling. Over the last
few games, I've been concentrating on getting more into every
pitch. Today I got into a rhythm, mixed up all of my pitches and
kept them guessing.''
</P>
<P>
   At times this season, Hampton has kept himself guessing, not to
mention his coaches and teammates. But if he can consistently pitch
anywhere near the level he exhibited Thursday, Hampton will be the
least of manager Larry Dierker's worries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say enough about Hampton,'' Dierker said. ``No one
said anything to him about it, but he knew that some of our main
setup guys weren't available to pitch a lot of innings, so he just
pitched right on through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton turned a three-run lead over to Billy Wagner, who had
allowed a career-high five runs the previous night. And in typical
Wagner fashion, he struck out the side for his seventh save.
</P>
<P>
   Billy the Kid seldom shows emotion on the mound, but he clearly
wore his feelings on his sleeve Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always good to jump right back out there after a bad
outing,'' said Wagner, who struck out the heart of the
Diamondbacks' order _ Jay Bell, Travis Lee and Matt Williams.
``When you give up five runs the previous night, you kind of get
(attitude) about letting people beat on you. Last night, they just
beat my brains in. I wanted to let them know that was a fluke.
That's why I was pumping my fist about getting a save.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros won three of four games from the Diamondbacks before
departing on a six-game road trip to Florida and New York that
begins tonight against the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of reasons for the Astros to be encouraged by
their performance against the Diamondbacks, who had won 10 of 13
games before running into trouble in Houston. The Astros hit .293
in the four-game series and outscored their guests 27-14.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bats woke up,'' said Derek Bell, who had one of the
Astros' 12 hits. ``We knew it was just a matter of time. The
Diamondbacks came in at the wrong time. We're starting to jell, and
we're starting to get our confidence back again. With the offense
we have, we know we can come and get you if we fall behind.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the few mistakes Hampton made put the Astros behind early
when Williams crushed the first pitch of the second inning for a
homer. But Hampton regrouped, facing the minimum number of hitters
in innings three through seven and allowing just three hits after
the home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to limit my mistakes and go after the
hitters,'' said Hampton, who rang up a season-high seven
strikeouts. ``I was able to throw my sinker to both sides of the
plate, and it had good bite on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the best command I've had all season; even the balls
that missed didn't miss by much.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton (2-1) barely missed hitting the first home run of his
career but gladly settled for a two-run double off the
left-center-field fence in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks starter Omar Daal created a mess for himself by
issuing back-to-back two-out walks to Tony Eusebio and Tim Bogar.
Daal worked Hampton to a two-strike count but couldn't finish the
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made me look silly on strike two,'' said Hampton, who
pushed the RBI total for the pitching staff to 10. ``I was just
lucky enough to get a hit. All of us pitchers take pride in our
hitting. We take a lot of extra batting practice, and we want to do
whatever we can to help ourselves out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton also was in the middle of the Astros' three-run rally in
the sixth. After Bogar singled home Carl Everett, Daal (2-2) hit
Hampton to load the bases for Craig Biggio with two out.
</P>
<P>
   It's safe to assume many among the 21,506 spectators expected
Diamondbacks manager Buck Showalter to make a pitching change,
since Vladimir Nunez was warming up. But Showalter decided to let
Daal take his chances with Biggio, a career .429 hitter against the
young lefthander.
</P>
<P>
   Big mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Biggio rapped a two-run double to left-center, pushing the
Astros' lead to four runs. Arizona scored an unearned run in the
eighth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
