<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smoltz vs. Avery to be `awkward'
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Former teammates, who are also golfing partners and
friends, take the mound tonight _ John Smoltz for the Braves and
Steve Avery for the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be kind of awkward,'' said Smoltz, whose parents live 25
minutes from Avery in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Avery, the 1991 NLCS MVP for the Braves, has faced his former
team once since he left after the 1996 season. Tom Glavine was
pitching. Avery gave up five earned runs in 3.1 innings in a 7-3
Braves win on Aug. 31, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get a chance very often to go through that what we
went through with the core of guys we did _ David Justice, Marquis
Grissom, Avery, (Jeff) Blauser, (Mark) Lemke, (Kent) Mercker,''
Smoltz said. ``With them playing for other teams, you want them to
do well, apart from tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine relief
</P>
<P>
   Glavine is hoping that the win he got Wednesday night, his first
of the season to prevent his first ever 0-4 start, is a sign of
things to come. ``I rely a lot on feel of my pitches,'' Glavine
said. ``The last three games I've felt pretty good about it. Now
it's a matter of going out and doing it consistently.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Braves strength and conditioning coach Frank Fultz has invented
the ``forearm builder,'' a weight machine that some of the Braves'
big boppers like Brian Jordan, Javy Lopez and Ryan Klesko are using
to build up their forearm muscles.
</P>
<P>
   The machine has players stand on a platform and turn a bar to
lift weight up and back down a pulley system. Fultz said he got the
idea talking to hitters like Hank Aaron, who stressed the
importance of having strong forearms.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
