<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PIRATES30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commanding Maddux is 4-0
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Greg Maddux isn't just about good pitching anymore.
</P>
<P>
   His presence on the mound has come to evoke offensive onslaughts
by the Braves. Or so it has so far this season, and Thursday night
was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   Using a three-hit, three-RBI night by Bret Boone and a three-run
homer by Andruw Jones, Maddux again got healthy run support and
another win, beating the Pirates 8-1.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux is 4-0 for the first time in his four-Cy Young inclusive
career. And he's gotten there with help from 11, 3, 20, 8 and now 8
Brave runs. Unlike his past two outings, Maddux didn't give up much
on the other side, scattering 10 hits and one run over eight
innings. He had a season-high seven strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux got a big hit from Bret Boone, who drove in a pair of
runs in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves had runners at second and third with one out when
Boone lined a 3-2 pitch from Pirates starter Jose Silva into right
field to score both runners for a 3-1 lead. Boone had had four hits
in his previous eight at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux was getting hit, like he's been doing in all four of his
previous starts (opponents were hitting .306 against him coming
in). Pirates shortstop Pat Meares had two hits off Maddux in the
first three innings and drove in the first run for the Pirates in
the third inning. He was down 0-2 in the count with two outs after
he swung through a pitch as Jason Kendall stole second base. On the
next pitch he golfed a low ball into center field to score Kendall,
the rare catcher with good speed.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux got his own rally started when he led off the next
half-inning with a liner to right, his fourth hit of the season in
his first 10 at-bats. After Otis Nixon reached on a fielder's
choice, Boone kept the rally alive with a grounder past Ed Sprague,
and Chipper Jones made it count by driving in the 1-1 tying run.
</P>
<P>
   Jones grounded to Meares, but he bobbled the ball at short,
which slowed the potential double play down just enough to where
Jones could reach first base safely and Nixon could score with two
outs.
</P>
<P>
   Silva was making his first start of the season, fresh off the
disabled list after getting hit in the face by a batted ball during
spring training. It's just the latest in a steady stream of
injuries that have stunted an otherwise very promising young
pitching career.
</P>
<P>
   When he's healthy, he's been good. National League rookie of the
year kind of good last year. He started 1998, his first full season
in the majors, 6-3 with a 3.44 ERA in his first 14 starts before he
broke his wrist trying to bunt. He missed almost three months.
</P>
<P>
   Mixing a mid-90s fastball and a good curveball, Silva kept the
Braves quiet outside of one run over the first four innings with
four strikeouts in that time, three of them looking.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
