<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN'S TIMING IS SPECIAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Mo Vaughn loves pressure. Just ask him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be in those situations,'' he said Thursday after
helping the Angels break a 10-10 tie late Wednesday with the
Toronto Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's two-run blast in the eighth inning spurred the team to
a 12-10 win and marked the fourth time this season the Angels won
in their last at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   So far this season, Vaughn has picked up RBI in game-tying or
game-winning situations four times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's special, there's no doubt about it,'' Angels manager
Terry Collins said. ``That's why he's great. He sees the ball and
drives through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn had two homers in Wednesday's win, and Collins was quick
to note that both came off left-handers David Wells and Graeme
Lloyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are outstanding pitchers,'' Collins said. `But when
(Vaughn) gets in that box, he's got the ability to go against
anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Holy cow:So what was going on in the Angels' dugout as the team
watched a 10-0 lead go down the drain?
</P>
<P>
   No much, according to Collins. When asked if he had much to say
to players and coaches during the course of Wednesday's game, he
replied: ``What did I say? `Holy cow. The lead's slipping away.'''
</P>
<P>
   Couch potatoes:Proof that professional wrestling has a wide
audience could be found in the Blue Jays' clubhouse before
Thursday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Several players crowded around a big screen watching an ESPN
special on wrestling, shouting out the names of big-time wrestlers
when they appeared onscreen.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, a small portable TV showed the Kansas City-Baltimore
game. No one was watching.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's Jose Cruz admits to being a huge wrestling fan.
Beneath his batting practice jersey, he always wears a T-shirt
proclaiming his allegiance to wrestling's New World Order, also
known as the Wolfpack.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right baby, the Wolfpack is in the house,'' Cruz
proclaimed before grabbing a bat and heading to the field.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's spot: Angels fans can expect to see Garret Anderson
in center field for the remainder of this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made some great catches out there,'' Collins said. `He's
playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past three seasons, Anderson has played left, right and
center, filling in for injured players.
</P>
</TEXT>
