<HEADLINE>
BREWERS SIGN NOMO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ The pitching-poor Milwaukee Brewers signed former
New York Mets and Dodgers right-hander Hideo Nomo to a minor-league
contract Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Brewers general manager Sal Bando said Nomo will start Sunday
for Double-A Huntsville and join Milwaukee in Florida on Monday.
Nomo could be activated and start next Friday in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's trying to catch lightning in a bottle,'' Bando said. ``If
it doesn't work out, there's no financial risk. There's no money we
have to pay. If it looks like he can be competitive and keep us in
games, he'll be with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee is Nomo's third organization in less than two months.
During spring training, he was released by the Mets. He signed a
minor-league contract with the Chicago Cubs on April 2, going 1-1
with a 3.71 ERA in three minor- league starts but was released when
he declined to make another minor-league start.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo, 30, is 49-41 with a 3.66 ERA in 123 games. He was 45-36 in
three-plus seasons with the Dodgers, including 13-6 with a 2.54 ERA
en route to being named the National League Rookie of the Year in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee's pitching staff entered Thursday 12th in the National
League with a 5.01 ERA. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
