<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVDRUGS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV EPISODES GIVE TRUE-TO-LIVE MESSAGES ABOUT DRUGS
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - An 11-year-old girl on ``Cosby'' returns from a
friend's birthday party bombed on spiked punch, and is confronted
by angry adults.
</P>
<P>
   A 12-year-old boy on ``Smart Guy'' wonders if it was wrong to
down a beer because he was worried about embarrassing himself in
front of his peers if he said no.
</P>
<P>
   A ``Wayans Bros.'' character blows an acting audition because he
shows up totally stoned.
</P>
<P>
   Something unusual is happening on television's hottest teen and
pre-teen shows.
</P>
<P>
   The characters are getting drunk, they're getting stoned, and
they're facing consequences.
</P>
<P>
   If these programs seem different - more pointed, more frank -
than their predecessors, there's a good, if not surprising, reason:
the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   In an unexpected marriage, television network executives have
united with the federal Office of National Drug Control Policy to
deliver true-to-life messages intended to steer kids away from
drugs, booze and tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   The collaboration has influenced several dozens TV scripts since
last year, including the ``Cosby'' episode on CBS that aired for
the first time on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership began after former Arizona state Sen. Chuck
Blanchard and other staff members of the so-called ``drug czar''
flew to Los Angeles last August to talk to network executives about
potential anti-drug strategies.
</P>
<P>
   The strait-laced visitors from Washington told the network
managers, some of whom were initially reluctant to even take the
meeting, that television could make a huge difference in kids'
perceptions of liquor, marijuana and other controlled substances.
</P>
<P>
   And then something most unexpected happened. The networks, at
least in part, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Eight months later, Blanchard can only marvel at the result: a
succession of drug and alcohol cautionary tales folded into the
story lines of teen shows such as ``Smart Guy'' and ``Wayans
Bros.'' on The WB network, as well as in mainstream programs such
as ``Cosby'' and ``Home Improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, The WB has tapped its teen talent - James Van Der
Beek, Alyssa Milano, Dylan Neal and others - to star in a series of
public service announcements airing on ``Dawson's Creek'' and other
shows.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-drug episodes, some of which, like ``Cosby'' and the
``Smart Guy,'' are airing for the first time this April and May,
are seldom preachy and don't employ scare tactics like the
hilariously overstated ``Reefer Madness'' that their viewers'
parents may remember. It helps that some of the shows are quite
funny and not, like ``Reefer Madness,'' unintentionally so.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there is a scene in a ``Wayans Bros.'' episode
broadcast in November in which main character, Marlon, is being
urged by his brother not to even pretend to smoke pot: ``That's how
it starts, just pretending . . . Next thing you know, you're
directing traffic butt-naked with just a pair of flip-flops.''
</P>
<P>
   Humor was also a key to the April 26 ``Cosby'' in which alcohol
and marijuana show up at 11-year-old Jurnee's birthday party. ``Was
there even a cake at this party?'' asks Bill Cosby's character, a
disbelieving adult.
</P>
<P>
   If you look closely, you may spot the ``Office of National Drug
Control Policy'' listed among the credits on an increasing number
of shows.
</P>
<P>
   The drug czar's office, as it is commonly referred to, is best
known for trying to keep drugs out of the country. But the office,
created by Congress in 1988, has been steadily shifting its focus
from curbing the supply of drugs to slowing its demand, especially
among youths.
</P>
<P>
   Drug czar Barry McCaffrey, a retired four-star general, had been
disturbed by a federal study last August showing most teens don't
view any ``great risk'' in smoking marijuana once a month.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly alarming to Blanchard, a former chairman of the
Arizona Senate Judiciary Committee, were the study's implications
for his home state. The study found that one out of six Arizona
youths had used illegal drugs in the past month - especially
marijuana - a rate that was one-third higher than the national
average. Blanchard, 40, left Arizona in 1997 to become McCaffrey's
chief counsel.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey thought it would be worth it to send Blanchard and
another staff member, Alan Levitt, to meet with TV executives.
</P>
<P>
   But they didn't expect too much. After all, many in Hollywood
have been suspicious of Washington ever since Wisconsin Sen. Joseph
McCarthy began blacklisting actors, writers and entertainment
executives as part of the ``Red Scare'' of the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Blanchard recalls sitting with WB executives last August in a
nondescript, one-story building at the Warner Bros. studios in
Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what they expected, but it was a pretty cool
reception, quite frankly,'' said John Litvack, WB's senior vice
president for curent programming.
</P>
<P>
   But, slowly, the atmosphere warmed.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Blanchard believes, the drug czar's staff hit a nerve
with programming executives and writers, some of whom have seen
their pals stumble into drugs. Everyone agreed, Blanchard said,
that it was a problem when kids, especially young ones, did drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Blanchard and Levitt were careful not to dictate how the network
should proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play the role of the flaming bureaucrat saying,
`Don't do this!' Levitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the pair offered its own research-based strategies for
how television studios might confront the drug problem if they were
so inclined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're human beings, ocasionally,'' Litvack said. ``And
occasionally we get affected by things. There were some executives,
including myself, who got fascinated with certain parts of the
(drug) problem.''
</P>
<P>
   In Litvack's case, his experience as a parent got him excited
about an upcoming ``Smart Guy,'' in which the principal character,
T.J., is a boy genius who has skipped to high school ahead of his
peers. In the May 16 episode, T.J. succumbs to pressure from boys
his own age and gets drunk; his father refuses to believe the boy
is guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``My passion for that part of it came out of the fact that when
one of my children (his son) was in grade school, there was a
meeting on drugs, and 11 parents out of 250 attended,'' Litvack
said. ``I said to the headmaster, `What the hell is going on?' And
he said this was par for the course. Everybody is in denial.''
</P>
<P>
   By the middle of March, the drug czar's office had counted 32
episodes of network entertainment programs that included an
anti-drug message consistent with the office's goals.
</P>
<P>
   But the networks' motives are not merely altrustic. In some
cases, they have a financial incentive as well.
</P>
<P>
   The drug czar's media campaign, of which Hollywood outreach is
just a part, has a $185 million budget for this fiscal year. The
office has been spending most of that money buying expensive
television ads - which makes it in the networks' interest to
cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   Blanchard says he doesn't care what the networks' reasoning is,
so long as the message gets out.
</P>
<P>
   Blanchard tells a personal story to illustrate that at least one
of the shows hit its mark.
</P>
<P>
   His secretary, Tammye Johnson, has a teenage daughter, and the
two watched the Wayans Bros. show not knowing of the office's
involvement. The next day, she wrote a moving e-mail to the staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black kids, to me, do not seem to get it unless it comes from
someone who they look up to,'' Johnson's e-mail said. ``Thank you,
Lord.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
