<HEADLINE>
FORMER EXECUTIVE SUES ALLIEDSIGNAL OVER FIRING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A former officer of AlliedSignal Electronic &AMP; Avionics Systems
in Olathe, Kan., has sued the company, alleging he was fired for
exposing improper accounting practices that led to big executive
bonuses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Douglas J. Boe filed the lawsuit this week in U.S. District
Court in Kansas City, Kan., against AlliedSignal's Olathe
subsidiary and the parent company in Morris Township, N.J. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the allegations of improper bookkeeping, Boe
contends the company violated the Americans With Disabilities Act
by firing him in part because of a mental disability. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boe is seeking actual damages in excess of $75,000 and punitive
damages in excess of $10 million. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AlliedSignal is aware of the lawsuit but does not comment on
litigation as a matter of policy, said John Bernaden, a spokesman
for AlliedSignal EAS in Olathe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for Boe also declined to comment Thursday beyond the
lawsuit's contents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boe's lawsuit follows a recent companywide restructuring at
AlliedSignal that included the layoff of 150 midlevel managers at
the Olathe facility. The facility, which has 1,500 employees and is
the headquarters of AlliedSignal's electronic and avionics
division, also brought in a new president earlier this year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to Boe's lawsuit, AlliedSignal hired Boe in May 1995
as division controller and director of finance. He was transferred
to AlliedSignal EAS in July 1996, which at the time was in Lenexa. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In late 1996, the suit says, Boe became concerned about some of
AlliedSignal's financial practices, including the violation of some
generally accepted accounting principles. Violating those
principles would put the company in violation of Securities and
Exchange Commission regulations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of Boe's concerns dealt with restructuring reserves after
AlliedSignal's 1994 acquisition of Sundstrand Data Control Inc.
Sundstrand was a competitor whose operations were consolidated into
AlliedSignal's electronics and avionics division. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boe ``believes that these accounting practices were employed so
that Allied could `make the numbers' for the purpose of satisfying
Wall Street's expectations and triggering massive executive
bonuses,'' the lawsuit says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AlliedSignal's most senior executives would not have been
eligible for millions of dollars in personal bonuses if generally
accepted accounting principles had been followed, according to
Boe's allegations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boe refused to sign documents attesting to the propriety of
AlliedSignal's financial practices for 1996 and the first quarter
of 1997, the lawsuit says. In April 1997, AlliedSignal informed Boe
that he was being investigated for the allegedly improper financial
practices that he had brought to his supervisor's attention. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About that time, Boe began seeing a psychiatrist as a result of
mental anguish he was suffering because of his employment
situation, according to the lawsuit. After taking a medical leave
of absence in July 1997, Boe was diagnosed with a permanent mental
disability known as bipolar affective disorder, a manic-depressive
condition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boe was assessed by his doctor as well as company doctors as
being fit to return to work in January 1998. However, despite
saying he was willing to transfer to another facility or
department, Boe was never brought back to work by AlliedSignal and
was fired in June 1998, the suit says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boe's lawsuit alleges a wrongful discharge, contending the
company fired him because he was a whistle-blower and because of
his mental condition. The latter allegation, if proved true, would
be in violation of the Americans With Disabilities Act, according
to the lawsuit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AlliedSignal moved into its $40 million Olathe facility in
September, celebrating with a ribbon-cutting attended by the
company's chairman and chief executive officer, Lawrence A.
Bossidy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert Johnson, who at the time headed AlliedSignal EAS, was
replaced earlier this year by Frank Daly, who came from
AlliedSignal's plant in Redmond, Wash. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
