<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHRA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERBERT MAKING HIS RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   How important is the crew chief in National Hot Rod Association
drag racing?
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Doug Herbert, who never had finished in the top 10 in
points prior to being associated with veteran tuner Dick LaHaie.
</P>
<P>
   Now with help from LaHaie and assistant crew chief Larry
Frazier, Herbert appears ready to make a run at the Top Fuel
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Herbert credits LaHaie, who won the Top Fuel championship as a
driver in 1987 before tuning Scott Kalitta to back-to-back titles
in 1994-95.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick's made a tremendous difference,'' said Herbert, who comes
into this weekend's Penzoil Nationals at Richmond, Va. a surprising
third in points. ``He likes to take it one step at a time and pick
at it a little bit. We just try to get the car to make consistent
runs and let the competition take chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Herbert advanced to the finals at the Gatornationals in March
and won the O'Reilly Nationals in Houston earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have a tremendous advantage to have Dick LaHaie as
crew chief,'' said Herbert, a four-time Top Fuel champion in the
IHRA. ``Him being a former driver, he understands what it feels
like to take a ride in a Top Fuel dragster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I joke with him and ask him if he wants to (drive).
He says, `No, I might like it too much.'''
</P>
<P>
   He's back. And that could mean trouble for the rest of the Top
Fuel drivers who watched two-time champion Gary Scelzi win for the
first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Scezli moved from 14th to 10th in the points standings with the
win and now trails leader Mike Dunn by 174.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, does it feel good to get down the track and back in
victory lane,'' said Scelzi, who made five runs in the 4.50-second
bracket and defeated Tony Schumacher in the finals of the Lone Star
Nationals near Dallas. ``Dallas was really a do-or-die situation
for (us). We knew we were at the point that we couldn't afford to
make any more mistakes, we couldn't afford to lose in the first
round, and we definitely don't ever want to go through not
qualifying ever again.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher, who comes into this weekend's national event second
in points, donated the $2,500 bonus he won for being Friday night's
low qualifier to Columbine High School, the site of last week's
shooting in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened was devastating to a lot of good people,'' said
Schumacher, who roared to a 4.596 pass. ``We stay in Littleton when
we race at the Mopar Mile High Nationals (in Denver) and it's an
All-American town with All-American people. We're going to do our
best for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
