<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-WINSTONWEST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMERON WINS POLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA -- The general consensus was one of three NASCAR Winston
Cup regulars would be on the pole for Saturday's NASCAR Winston
West 200.
</P>
<P>
   Someone forgot to tell Austin Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron, who finished second in last year's July Winston West
event at California Speedway, was the surprise polesitter Thursday
with a track-record lap of 39.853 seconds, or 180.664 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup veteran Ken Schrader, who won this event in 1997 and
last year, was a close second at 180.659. Mike Chase will start
third after posting a lap speed of 179.910.
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup regulars Ricky Craven (179.551) and Mike Wallace
(178.585) were fifth and ninth, respectively. West Covina's St.
James Davis and El Monte's Kenny Smith failed to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we left the shop Wednesday, we thought we would have a
good shot (at the pole),'' Cameron said. ``Then we heard that
Schrader was going to run. Then Craven and Wallace. I said, 'Oh,
man. It just got a whole lot tougher.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So to beat these guys, it means a lot to me. It's a learning
experience every time I go out. (The Winston Cup regulars) are paid
drivers and I just want to follow in their footsteps. I'm just
happy to run with them, so to out-qualify them ... wow. I'm
ecstatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Cameron, whose posted a 39.724 lap in practice, also did not
seem to be affected by being the first car to qualify. He even may
have been helped by his draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a big change in the weather,'' said Cameron, who
finished second at a NASCAR Super Late Model event at Irwindale
Speedway earlier this month. ``I think (going first) was to our
benefit. There was good horsepower air when I went out and my car
really loosened up. Good cold air means more horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lucky because it got breezy later and I think that may
have bothered the other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Others to qualify included Chino Hills Butch Gilliland
(seventh), Saugus Sean Woodside (15th) and Joe Bean (23rd), who
drives for Glendora businessman Joe Nava.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
