<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8876 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-PROFILING-1STLD-WR     04-29 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-PROFILING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J. TO SEEK SETTLEMENT WITH U.S. ON RACE PROFILING BY POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (subs 13th graf to clarify what charges were in 3 cities)  
 (ATTN: Pa., Ohio)   (bl)  
 By JERRY GRAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. - Trying to forestall a federal civil rights
lawsuit, New Jersey Attorney General Peter Verniero said Thursday
that the state had agreed to negotiate a settlement with federal
officials over allegations that state police engaged in widespread
racial profiling against black and Hispanic motorists.
</P>
<P>
   The state attorney general acted after the U.S. Justice
Department's Civil Rights Division informed him and Gov. Christie
Whitman in a letter Monday that it had turned up enough evidence
that state troopers used race as a basis for stopping and searching
drivers to warrant a lawsuit against the state police.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Justice Department said that federal
officials deferred filing the complaint after New Jersey officials
agreed late Wednesday night to work out a voluntary out-of-court
settlement known as a consent decree.
</P>
<P>
   Such an agreement would almost certainly require the appointment
of a civilian agency to monitor the force, a point the Justice
Department has insisted on in similar cases, as well as stricter
regulations on how troopers handle stops and searches in suspected
drug cases.
</P>
<P>
   In preparing its complaint against New Jersey, the Justice
Department was invoking a rarely used provision of the 1994 federal
anti-crime law, which authorizes the government to file civil
lawsuits against police departments that ``engage in patterns of
misconduct.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, only two law enforcement agencies _ the police
departments in Pittsburgh and in Steubenville, Ohio _ have agreed
to consent decrees, said Christine DiBartolo, the Justice
Department spokeswoman, and the police department in Columbus,
Ohio, is currently negotiating a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey State Police is the first statewide law
enforcement agency to enter into such discussions, and with 2,700
officers, it is the largest.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. DiBartolo would not provide details of the Justice
Department investigation or say how its findings differed from a
report released by Verniero last week, which found that officers in
at least two police barracks _ in Moorestown and Cranbury _ engaged
in racial profiling. ``His report is a good start for
negotiations,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But a more senior official in the Justice Department said that
the federal investigation roughly mirrored the one that Verniero's
office conducted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may not be much of a disparity,'' said the official, a
lawyer who spoke on the condition that he not be identified by name
or title. ``Much of our focus was on the same area of I-95 that
they identified in their report. We had the focus also on the
Moorestown and Cranbury stations, and that certainly was the focus
of many of the complaints of motorists.''
</P>
<P>
   The official also said that in the letter to state officials,
the Justice Department had agreed that some of the remedies that
Verniero suggested in his report on racial profiling were ``a
starting point'' for the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Those recommendations include revising the procedure for traffic
stops, including requiring that a trooper inform the dispatcher
about the exact reason for the stop before the officer leaves the
car; focusing the statewide drug enforcement strategy on larger
``impact cases'' rather than on pursuing more random ``targets of
opportunity'' like individual passenger vehicles; and making
quarterly public reports on the proportion of minority and
non-minority motorists who are subject to various actions by state
police.
</P>
<P>
   But he did not recommend an independent civilian agency to
monitor problems, a provision that the Justice Department has
insisted on in Pittsburgh, where the complaints involved police
brutality, and in Steubenville.
</P>
<P>
   In those cases, part of the settlement included hiring an
independent auditor to monitor investigations of complaints and
compliance with the consent decree. The monitor also was required
to issue regular reports to the court, the local government and the
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   In sending the letter to the Whitman administration this week,
the government was effectively signaling the end to the Justice
Department's investigation into the practices of the New Jersey
State Police. The inquiry was initiated two years ago after civil
rights leaders and Democratic members of the state's congressional
delegation complained that members of minority groups were being
unfairly singled out in traffic stops.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, New Jersey's quick agreement to settle the case
suggests that officials here were eager to to quiet one of the
worst political storms the governor has faced.
</P>
<P>
   After denying for years that troopers engaged in racial
profiling, Whitman acknowledged April 20 that a two-month
investigation initiated by Verniero had shown that some officers
routinely stopped and searched some black and Hispanic motorists
solely because of race.
</P>
<P>
   The furor over racial profiling has not only clouded Whitman's
image at the time she is gearing up for a U.S. Senate race next
year, but it has become a major issue in her nomination of Verniero
to serve on the state Supreme Court. Confirmation hearings on
Verniero's nomination begin next week.
</P>
<P>
   The administration acknowledged the consent decree agreement in
a four-paragraph statement that was issued by Verniero.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Civil Rights Division of the United States Department of
Justice has authorized the filing of a civil suit against the
Division of the State Police alleging that State Police officers
have engaged in discriminatory law enforcement,'' Verniero said in
his statement. ``As a matter of practice, it is my understanding
that this is a necessary procedural step that must be taken by the
Justice Department in order for a settlement to occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Verniero would not release the letter that the Justice
Department sent to the state, a decision that rekindled the bitter
partisan fighting over both the issue of racial profiling and his
nomination to the state's highest court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's apparent that the Justice Department has sufficient
evidence to file a civil rights suit,'' said Democratic state
Senate Minority Leader Richard Codey. ``Our concern is whether this
material, like the other evidence, is something Verniero should
have known about and stopped long ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Reginald Jackson, the executive director of the Black
Ministers' Conference of New Jersey, a group that has been at the
forefront of complaints about racial profiling, said that a senior
official in the Justice Department called him Thursday to inform
him of the developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that they had sufficient evidence to file a lawsuit
against the state,'' said Jackson. ``I think the federal government
knows it is a much deeper problem than what Verniero's report
showed. They would not have threatened a lawsuit if it was simply
the matter of a small number of troopers conducting racial
profiles.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson would not identify the Justice Department official he
spoke with by name or job description, but he said the official
promised that the black ministers would be involved in any
settlement that the federal government reached with the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''I applaud the governor and the attorney general for agreeing
to a consent decree and I hope that they can reach an agreement
that will end profiling,'' he said. ``But one of the things we will
recommend is that an outside monitor be appointed to watch the
state police.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said they would meet with state police
officials next week to begin negotiations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
