</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-LUVOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SUICIDE LINK TO KILLER'S DRUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Luvox, the drug taken by Eric Harris, one of the two students
involved in the Colorado school massacre, belongs to the same class
of antidepressants as Prozac, Zoloft and other newer medicines used
to treat depression and a variety of other psychiatric conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Although Luvox was approved by the Food and Drug Administration
specifically for the treatment of obsessive-compulsive disorder,
many doctors also prescribe it for depression, and the drug is
marketed as an antidepressant in Europe. The product is marketed by
Solvay Pharmaceuticals Inc. and Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Because people who suffer from depression have a high risk of
suicide, Luvox, like other antidepressants, comes with the routine
warning that ``close supervision of high-risk patients should
accompany initial drug therapy.'' But there is no clear evidence
linking its class of drugs, selective serotonin reuptake
inhibitors, with increased suicide risk, psychiatrists say.
</P>
<P>
   The drugs are considered by many doctors to be safer for
potentially suicidal patients than older antidepressants, because
patients have taken large overdoses in suicide attempts and have
survived.
</P>
<P>
   Also like most other antidepressants, Luvox often comes with a
warning about the use of alcohol when taking the drug. But doctors
said that, as a practical matter, many patients drink in moderation
while taking SSRIs with no bad consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Psychopharmacologists said that stopping such drugs abruptly
might cause nausea, diarrhea, nervousness, muscle jerks and tremor,
but that the symptoms usually disappeared after a week or so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
