<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-FORD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD DROPS FACTORY PLAN FOR BRAZIL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)   (jw) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ In a decision highlighting how government
overspending has hampered foreign investment in Brazil, Ford Motor
Co. has abandoned plans to build an innovative $1 billion factory
in a southern Brazilian state, which refused to honor a pledge to
provide the company with financial incentives because of a budget
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, which said it might search for another site for its
factory, called the Project Amazon, made the announcement in a
statement Wednesday after a month of negotiating with the
government of Rio Grande do Sul, a state on Brazil's southern tip
controlled by the opposition Workers Party. Ford already assembles
cars at other factories in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Citing an annual budget shortfall of roughly 1.2 billion reais,
or $723 million, Rio Grande do Sul officials reneged on an
agreement between the state's previous administration and Ford,
which would have provided the car manufacturer with about $250
million in financing and infrastructure to complete the factory by
2001. Ford had hoped to produce as many 150,000 cars a year at the
plant, providing the region, an industrial hub with convenient
links to Brazil's neighboring trade partners, with at least 1,500
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just lost one of the most important companies in the
world,'' said Paulo Antonio Zawislak, an economics professor at the
Federal University of Rio Grande do Sul who has studied the impact
of recent automotive investments in the state. ``Unfortunately,
this happens at a time when our state was emerging at the forefront
of Brazil's auto industry.''
</P>
<P>
   General Motors Corp., which is nearing completion of its own
futuristic factory in Rio Grande do Sul, has also been in
negotiations with officials over incentives for its plant. Although
the differences with Rio Grande do Sul have resulted in a six-month
delay in the inauguration of the factory, now pushed back to
mid-2000, both state and company officials have said there is
little chance that GM will abandon the factory for another
location.
</P>
</TEXT>
