<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLERK-ROBBERY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PET STORE CLERK WRESTS GUN FROM WOULD-BE ROBBERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MALCOLM GARCIA  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two robbers pointed a handgun at the clerk's face and
demanded money. They forced him onto the floor of the Waldo Pet
Center and ripped a gold chain from his neck. They demanded his
wallet. They kicked him in the face for lifting his head. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep your head down! I'll kill you! This ain't no game!'' the
robbers shouted. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I just knew I was dead,'' the clerk said Thursday, recounting
Wednesday night's robbery at the store, 8011 Wornall Road. ``My day
was gone. These guys were not joking around.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So when he saw an opportunity to grab his assailants' gun he
took it. In the struggle that followed, the clerk shot one of the
robbers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I stood over him and asked for my chain back and he gave it
back,'' the clerk said. ``I was mad. I said, `Why do you rob
people?' He apologized. He said the other guy made him do it. I
didn't know how hard he was shot.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The robber died later at a hospital. The second man fled into a
nearby residential area and had not been caught as of Thursday
night. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it was instinct, maybe it was stupid,'' said the clerk,
39, who was not being identified because the other robber was still
at large. ``I don't know. I saw an opening and I took the gun.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City police on Thursday identified the dead man as Arthur
Nelson, 18. Police said they think they know who the other man is. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nelson was on probation for a January marijuana conviction. He
had several traffic tickets pending. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame this happened, but I wasn't the one who started
this,'' said the clerk, who has worked at the store for 12 years.
``I'm just trying to run a good business. This could have been a
bloodbath.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The robbery occurred shortly before the store's 9 p.m. closing
time. About six customers and five employees were still in the
building when the robbers walked into the store wearing sweatshirts
with hoods. They had pantyhose pulled over their faces. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They were screaming, yelling in my face,'' the clerk said of
the robbers. `` `Give me your wallet, get on the ground, keep your
head down. I'll kill you.' '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After they took money from a cash register and three customers,
the robbers started to leave. Then they noticed another register
toward the back of the store. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The one with the gun put the gun on me,'' the store clerk
said. `` `Open it up. I'll kill you.' It was a bad scene.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The clerk was standing to the side of the robber at the second
cash register when he realized the man's peripheral vision was
blocked by his hood. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The clerk lunged for the gun.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was holding him and they were both trying to get me,'' said
the clerk who, at 6 feet, 3 inches and 230 pounds, was bigger than
both of the robbers. ``We were yelling and hitting and punching. He
was waving the gun. I don't know what I was thinking.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once the clerk had the gun, the robbers fled. The clerk, who
said he owns guns and knows how to use them, fired two shots,
hitting one of the robbers in the back. He fell near the front
door, but stood up and stumbled back into the store before falling
on the floor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He got up again and ran outside when he heard an employee
calling 911. He collapsed in the parking lot. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Police said the robbers fit the description of two men who have
robbed three other businesses on or near Wornall Road since April
22. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Robberies are fairly frequent around here,'' said Kevin
Alexander, an employee with Parts America, up the road from Waldo
Pet Center. ``It's not an easy feeling. I open, I close. You got
this on your mind.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors will decide whether to charge the pet store clerk
when police forward the case to their office next week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're extremely sensitive to people in peril who have to
defend themselves,'' said Jackson County Prosecutor Bob Beaird,
adding that prosecutors and state laws do not lean toward criminal
charges in such cases. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under Missouri's self-defense law a person can use force to
protect against serious injury or robbery. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an extremely dangerous endeavor,'' Beaird said of
fighting back. ``Money is replaceable; lives are not.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The store clerk said he did what he had to do. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be no hero; I was just thinking about saving
everybody else's life,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad deal. I feel sorry for the guy's mom, because
they're going to have to deal with it, but there is no doubt in my
mind they were going to kill me.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
