<HEADER>
A8885 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WTO-APPOINT-NYT &LR;      04-29 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE GROUP FACES DEADLINE ON CHOOSING NEW LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA, Switzerland _ With only hours left before a deadline
expires Friday to choose a new leader of the World Trade
Organization, bruising divisions and mistrust among member nations
were keeping them from reaching an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates from the 134-country organization that sets the rules
for global commerce planned a meeting later Friday to try once
again to find room for compromise on a choice between Mike Moore, a
former New Zealand prime minister, and Supachai Panitchpakdi,
Thailand's deputy prime minister. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The decision has taken on an urgency because Friday is the last
work day for the current director general, Renato Ruggiero, raising
the possibility that the organization will be leaderless just as it
is struggling with some contentious trade issues, ranging from
European-American disputes on bananas and beef to China's prolonged
quest to become a member.
</P>
<P>
   The leadership crisis also comes as the organization is planning
a ministerial meeting of all member nations in November that will
revise world trade regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Ruggiero has said that once his four-year term expires, ``I will
not serve another day.'' The contracts of Ruggiero's four deputy
directors general also expire Friday, adding to the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Although member representatives vowed not to repeat the lengthy,
disruptive process that surrounded the selection of Ruggiero, a
former Italian trade minister, the selection this time has been
similar. Accusations of undue influence, trading favors and
arm-twisting have swirled around the process, creating an
atmosphere of tension and mistrust, a number of trade diplomats
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It has gotten sufficiently unpleasant that a negotiator from one
important trading country supporting Moore has stopped talking to
diplomats of another nation backing Supachai.
</P>
<P>
   In part, such stresses reflect how the selection is made, which
is by consensus. All countries, or at least most, are expected to
agree on one candidate without resorting to a vote, which would put
countries on record as supporters or opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The thinking behind the process is that all countries are equal
at the world's trade regulatory body, and that huge trading blocs
like the European Union and the United States do not have
disproportionate influence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the organization is quite likely to avoid a
confrontational vote, the matter of numbers has been crucial in the
race for director general. Both sides have been using them to make
their case.
</P>
<P>
   Supachai's supporters released figures that 65 percent of
members back him. While there is no official tally, Moore's camp
says it is ``very close'' and many diplomats agree. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The true indication of who can win will come when countries with
actual objections to one candidate or the other are flushed out.
Until now, countries can decline to join a consensus, on the ground
that they have reservations about a candidate without going on the
public record. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, the only people who really knew the true position
of countries were Ali Mchumo, the trade representative from
Tanzania and chairman of the organization's general council, who
has been conducting the search, and Switzerland's trade diplomat,
William Rossier.
</P>
<P>
   Mchumo, who has tried to meet several deadlines for finding a
new director general, declared earlier this month that April 30 was
the ``ultimate deadline.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once Mchumo declares that a consensus has been formed around one
candidate, any objecting countries will have to accept his decision
or declare their objections publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mchumo will then have to explain just how he arrived at his
consensus,'' one trade diplomat explained. ``If he selects Moore,
for example, his only out is to say that the objections to Supachai
were weightier than those for Moore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Supachai supporters are likely to feel cheated,'' he added,
because of the amount of his declared support and because many
believe the organization should have a representative from a
developing country as director general.
</P>
<P>
   Supachai, who arrived in Geneva on the eve of the deadline, is
said to have the backing of nearly all Asian countries, about half
the European countries, including Britain, and many African
countries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moore, who has been in Geneva since last week, says he has
support from the United States, France, Italy and Germany as well
as Latin American, Caribbean and some African countries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   However, even if one candidate is declared victorious, emotions
are running so high there is a good chance that he will be
effectively vetoed. This would leave the trade organization in an
unprecedented situation.
</P>
<P>
   One possibility is the appointment of an interim director
general drawn from the organization's administrative staff or from
a member nation considered neutral in the struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could appoint the man-in-the-moon,'' one envoy said.
``There are no rules at that point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
