<SLUG> BC-RAC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: JOCKEYS SIGN FOR A DOLLAR AND A DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ The rain left town and the sun came out and it
finally felt like spring, like Kentucky Derby week at Churchill
Downs. But for a couple of hours Thursday, the race became
secondary for about half the jockeys in the 20-horse field. The
potential winnings, from Saturday's 125th running of the most
famous horse race there is, mattered less than a few jars stuffed
with one dollar bills.
</P>
<P>
   The jars sat on tables set up under the grandstand, out by the
paddock, affixed with yellow stickers asking autograph seekers for
a suggested donation of $1. At a time when people attach gross
inflationary value to almost anything with an athlete's signature
scribbled on it, this was a bargain in the name of benevolence.
</P>
<P>
   The cash would go straight into the Disabled Jockeys Fund, a
collection that doesn't require much explanation, only a heart. The
Jockeys Guild stages a number of promotional events around the
country to help stock the fund, which was begun in the early 1990s
and supports those who have lost livelihoods and limbs in the
matter of a horse's misstep.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are about 2,700 jockeys registered nationwide, and there
were 2,500 reported injuries last year,'' said John Giovanni, the
Guild's national manager and secretary. ``Most of the jockeys know
it's not a matter of if, it is a matter of when.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the only question is how bad it will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to complain when you fall off your horse and you wind
up losing the hearing in your right ear, like I did, but who do you
complain to when you see people who never got up again to walk?''
said Kent Desormeaux, last year's Derby and Preakness winner aboard
Real Quiet, who Saturday will ride the touted filly Excellent
Meeting for the trainer Bob Baffert, unless she runs Friday in the
Kentucky Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux's time came in December 1992, riding Judge Hammer at
Hollywood Park. He fell in the lead, which made him an obstacle to
the field. The last horse to pass kicked him in the head. He awoke
30 hours later, would get to see the son his wife was soon to give
birth to and would reclaim his career and come within a nose of a
Triple Crown in the Belmont Stakes last June.
</P>
<P>
   The 51 disabled jockeys currently under the care of the fund
weren't as lucky. They lost their careers, their ability to walk. A
jockey named Linda Hughes was recently confined to a wheelchair
after a fall at Calder Race Course in Florida. She has a daughter
to raise, a $100,000 on-track insurance policy for her medical
costs and a weekly $200 disability check. The money goes fast, and
the unforeseen needs pile up, and that is when a hand reaches into
the fund and then out to help.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Young, a disabled jockey who lives in Louisville, had
a baby recently and bought a van, but couldn't afford the $18,000
it cost to make it disabled-ready. The money came out of the
Disabled Jockeys Fund, as did a new furnace this past winter for
another former jockey in the middle of an Idaho blizzard. ``Part of
it is basic life needs,'' Giovanni said. `` But we don't just want
our disabled jockeys to survive. We want them to think: `I can get
out. I can travel.'''
</P>
<P>
   I remember going to a pre-race chapel once at the Daytona 500,
looking around at all the famous NASCAR drivers, with their wives
next to them, kids on their laps, and thinking that only a strong
sense of community, of trust, could make bearable the occasional
late-night dread. Professionalism does not allow race car drivers
or jockeys to dwell on danger, but it is always there. The Disabled
Jockeys Fund, Desormeaux said, is as much an insurance policy as it
is philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   After winning his first Derby in 1993, aboard Sea Hero, Jerry
Bailey stopped a sponsor who was awarding him a brand-new car in
mid-sentence to say he was donating it to the Disabled Jockeys
Fund. Bailey, Desormeaux, Pat Day, Shane Sellers _ the most
recognizable riding names in the sport _ signed yesterday for cash,
not for profit. A dollar wasn't much to ask, especially in the
context of what contemporary sports owners and other athletes too
often demand.
</P>
<P>
   Some fans dropped a dollar or two in the jars. Many more did
not. ``People are people,'' Desormeaux said. ``Some care, some
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   After last year's close Triple Crown call, Desormeaux was kept
at his post long after the others had gone. He signed every last
program and card, until there were no more. His jar was
three-quarters full when it was removed, its contents dumped into a
large bag. Richer for his effort, Desormeaux walked off, in the
midafternoon sun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
