<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE `GO' KNICKS BEING HELD BACK BY THE PAST
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Red Holzman was an outstanding man and a great coach
for his time. Thursday night, the Knicks celebrated Holzman in a
nostalgic halftime ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Holzman, who died last November at age 78, brought two NBA
championships to Madison Square Garden, and his legacy is
everywhere, resonating in many positive ways.
</P>
<P>
   One of his former players, Bill Bradley, is running for
president, and another, Phil Jackson, is helping in the campaign.
Walt Frazier is a television broadcaster, Willis Reed is a longtime
NBA executive and Dick Barnett earned a doctorate.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's tribute was filled with an atmosphere that
recalled the good old days and perhaps lamented that the new Knicks
can't play that kind of basketball. Lore has its place. But legend
has occupied too pivotal a role at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of a much-longed-for Knicks championship, it has
become like that musty rug or those heavy curtains that keep
memories in but fresh air out. It's a manufactured world where
memories are suspended in time _ it's 1969-70 all over again.
</P>
<P>
   That basketball no longer exists. Put it out of your mind. Look
at your kids or look at their kids: tattoos, rap, earrings. Allen
Iverson, Jason Williams, Randy Moss. This is the Go generation.
</P>
<P>
   The World's Most Famous Arena, as the Garden calls itself, is
becoming a museum, where the weight of history and nostalgia
overwhelm the present. Bad boxing matches, bad hockey team and a
well-heeled, underachieving basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, though not of their own volition, have begun a
process to let in the fresh air. Everyone talks about Marcus Camby
and Latrell Sprewell. They say Camby is too brittle and can't take
the pounding. This reminds me of critics years ago who said
Muhammad Ali couldn't take a punch to the head.
</P>
<P>
   Ali didn't want take a punch to his head. Remember ``Float like
a butterfly, sting like a bee?'' Ali restructured the whole notion
of slugging it out. The blow-for-blow, bucket-of-blood Charles
Oakley-Pat Riley era had its place _ in the museum.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of fans are still in denial about this Knicks evolution.
Coach Jeff Van Gundy was in denial, too, until Dave Checketts fired
that warning shot over his head in the form of demoting Ernie
Grunfeld. Grunfeld brought in Camby and Sprewell and began the
necessary work of renovating the Knicks, sending Oakley to Toronto
and John Starks to Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley continues to take shots at the Knicks, and core fans miss
his dramatic forays into the stands for loose balls. Truth is, in
the last few weeks Camby has routinely done things _ with riveting
blocks and thundering dunks on missed shots _ that the Oak man
couldn't begin to imagine doing. Camby's acrobatics are one major
reason the Knicks had gone on a modest winning streak before
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy changed his view of Camby. Next, he'd better begin
looking at Sprewell differently; not as an albatross, but as a life
preserver. This will require a tremendous leap of faith.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell faces barriers that go beyond basketball. Critics say
all he wants to do is run up and down the floor and score. Guess
what? That's the kind of team your Knicks have evolved into this
abbreviated season: up and down, fast moving, plenty of turnovers,
higher scores.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction against Sprewell goes beyond basketball, of course.
He attacked his coach _ an authority figure _ two years ago. In a
league dominated by black players coached by white men, Sprewell
attacked a white authority figure. The reaction to the attack,
while not solely formed along racial lines, carried significant
racial overtones. In many minds it conjured images that went beyond
mere impudence to revolt or insurrection.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Van Gundy, the Knicks and Sprewell are all linked; they are
looking for absolution. The long-suffering fans are simply looking
for a championship.
</P>
<P>
   If Sprewell finds a way to fit in, if he can mesh with Allan
Houston, the Knicks can play for the championship. There are signs
of that happening. On Wednesday, Sprewell scored 29 points in a
loss at Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   This brings us back to Thursday night's celebration. The essence
of Red Holzman was his ability to blend talent on two championship
teams. The new Knicks have been torn by internal division. If you
believe the Garden president, Checketts, things are now stabilized.
</P>
<P>
   The new Knicks are a Go team: go to the hole, go to the boards.
Run. Play solid defense, making stops when it matters. This is not
the Red Holzman team of the late '60s _ pass it around, everyone
gets a touch. Those were the good old days, but the good old days
are gone. Let's say goodbye.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
