<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PADRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS WALK ON THE PADRES' WILD SIDE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., S.C. W.Va.)   (jw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After seven innings Thursday afternoon against the San Diego
Padres, the Mets _ who had rallied from an early 4-0 deficit _ had
six runs on only three hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's efficiency,'' Mike Piazza said after the Mets had gone
on to an 8-5 victory. ``To go from leaving a lot of guys on base,
like we have been doing, to something like that, that's
productivity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets did, however, benefit from 10 walks, two of them going
to Piazza, who had won Tuesday night's game with a ninth-inning,
two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   And they got another fine relief effort from Dennis Cook, the
36-year-old left-hander who continues to be one of the most
efficient and productive pitchers in the National League this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Cook pitched a scoreless sixth inning. The Mets then rallied for
two runs in the bottom of the inning to grab a 6-5 lead, and Cook _
who has pitched only seven and a third innings this season _ won
for the fourth time without a loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's on a pretty good pace right now,'' said John Franco, who
closed out his eighth save in eight tries with a perfect ninth
inning. ``He's tied for the league lead in wins with less innings
than anybody. So he'll be well rested.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets, who received their first poor outing from Bobby
Jones this season (nine hits and five runs in five innings), could
have some problems with their starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Reed remains on the disabled list, and Thursday morning Al
Leiter caused a minor scare when he reported that he had tweaked
his left knee during Wednesday night's victory. The Mets hope he
has nothing more serious than what has been diagnosed as a slight
sprain that is not expected to threaten his next scheduled start.
</P>
<P>
   If Leiter is sidelined, the Mets are going to need even more of
the kind of production they received from their offense Thursday
along with continued efficiency from the bullpen, which turned in
four scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have the kind of bullpen and team that will allow
the bullpen to get wins,'' Manager Bobby Valentine said. ``This
year, we have an offensive team that can put a crooked number up
when we're behind in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets (13-9) have already won six games this year coming from
behind. Thursday, they came back from four runs down, helped by the
walks and two Padres errors.
</P>
<P>
   A two-run, two-out double from Rey Ordonez in the second inning
cut the deficit to 4-2. Dave Magadan, the Padres' third baseman,
helped Ordonez by missing the ball near the line with a feeble
attempt at a backhand stab.
</P>
<P>
   A two-out, two-run fifth-inning home run from John Olerud
narrowed the gap to 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, a run-scoring bloop single from the light-hitting
Ordonez _ who tied his career high with three runs batted in _ tied
the score at 5-5. A sacrifice fly from the pinch-hitter Robin
Ventura immediately followed Ordonez's second hit and gave the Mets
the lead for good.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Kinkade's first major league home run in the eighth made it
7-5. Roger Cedeno followed with a bloop single, stole second with
the aid of Ordonez throwing his bat at the pitched ball, took third
on a perfectly placed Ordonez sacrifice and scored on a bloop
single from Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have come to rely on Ventura, who leads the club with
17 RBIs, and Olerud, who has reached base in all 22 games, homered
in the last two, and leads the team in batting (.365).
</P>
<P>
   But Ordonez and Kinkade?
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez was asked which at-bat he liked best Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The line drive to left-center field,'' the shortstop said,
referring to a hard-hit ball in the fourth that was run down for an
out.
</P>
<P>
   Kinkade, a rookie who had come on as a defensive replacement for
Rickey Henderson in the seventh, needs to work on his home run
trot, which was more like a gallop.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the way I do it,'' Kinkade said with a sheepish
grin. ``Brian McRae said he was going to clap for me, but I was
already back in the dugout.''
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Cook was already back in the clubhouse. With four
victories in nine appearances this year, Cook is on a pace to win
32 games, should he appear in the same amount of games as he did
last year (73).
</P>
<P>
   Twenty victories is even being joked about around the Mets'
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hope so and I hope so,'' said Piazza, when asked if he
thought Cook could get to 20. ``For his sake, I do. But for our
starters' sake, I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   Tony Gwynn turned in the 225th three-hit game of his career,
which included his 501st double. With 2,962 hits, Gwynn is 23rd on
the career list, after passing Sam Crawford on Thursday. ... It was
determined that Al Leiter has a slight sprain of the anterior
cruciate ligament of his left knee. ``It's the same knee as last
year, but it's not the same thing,'' said Leiter, who thought he
hurt himself pushing off the rubber during his seven-inning stint
Wednesday night. ``Last year, it was the patella tendon. And I'm
totally, totally planning on not missing my next side-session and
on making my next start.'' General Manager Steve Phillips said
Leiter would be fitted with a brace and was probable for the start.
When that is depends on what the Mets do with the injured Rick Reed
and with the struggling Masato Yoshii. Reed tossed batting practice
Thursday. ``My eyes said he was OK,'' Manager Bobby Valentine said.
``But his command was a little less than desirable.'' Still, the
Mets broached the possibility of Reed's starting somewhere Sunday,
perhaps on a rehab assignment, perhaps with the Mets. Sunday is
Yoshii's scheduled day, but members of the Mets' front office said
Thursday that a demotion to the minor leagues is an option for the
Japanese right-hander, especially if he struggles the next time he
pitches. ... Tim Carr, a 21-year-old reliever pitching with the
Mets' Class A affiliate in Columbia, S.C., had a seizure in the
dugout in the second game of a doubleheader in Charleston, W.Va.,
on Wednesday night. Carr, who stopped breathing at one point before
being revived, was released from a hospital early Thursday morning
and will be flown to New York for neurological testing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
