<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8898 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-SIXERS-NYT     04-29 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SIXERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREWELL PICKS UP KNICKS AND SHOOTS DOWN 76ERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It wasn't a party until Latrell Sprewell arrived. He
supplied the music, chips and pop with a series of vicious dunks,
electric jumpers and steals that put a jolt into a Knicks team that
came out drab and discombobulated.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell lifted the Knicks with 30 points off the bench and kept
their eighth place in the playoff standing safe for another night.
The Knicks' 85-70 victory at Madison Square Garden Thursday night
against a 76ers team that had won five in a row pulled them to
within a half game of seventh place.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell took the pressure off Patrick Ewing's return after he
had missed two games with an Achilles' tendon problem. Ewing played
21 minutes, was 3 for 7 and scored 6 points. Sprewell finished 11
for 17, while Allan Houston added 22 points on a 9-for-16 night.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Iverson ended the game with 21 points. But 17 of those
came in the first half, when it looked as if the 76ers were going
to run away from the Knicks after they took a 23-8 lead.
</P>
<P>
   A little groggy from their road trip, the Knicks needed either a
strong cup of coffee or Sprewell. With an offensive lift from
Sprewell and a defensive surge from Chris Dudley, the Knicks were
able to fight back from a 15-point, first-quarter deficit and take
a 44-42 lead at the half.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell and Houston were actually working together to make a
run on the 76ers. They combined for 29 first-half points.
</P>
<P>
   Then Sprewell took over the game. He came up with two steals at
midcourt in the final minute of the third quarter, and raced alone
for two vicious dunks. He was in his own zone and the Knicks were
the happy witnesses to the 64-56 third-quarter lead he provided.
</P>
<P>
   Houston did not get lost in the fray, his offense seeming to
carry over to his defense. Without the injured Chris Childs to help
shadow Iverson, there were times when Houston took over that duty.
He was part of the reason Iverson was held scoreless in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson may have been feeling shoulder pain that hit him in the
first half. With 40 seconds left in the third quarter, he took
himself out. But he did return early in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The first-half performance of Sprewell and Houston diluted the
fancy plays Iverson had a chance to display while he could as he
worked around a slower Charlie Ward and scored 17 points.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson had his moments, like the cross-over dribble he used as
he floated through the lane on a runner in the first quarter, but
they were trumped by Sprewell's kinetic moves. He left the rookie
Larry Hughes shaking his head when he pulled up and stuck a high,
hanging jumper over his head in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks took their halftime edge on a jumper by Houston that
came off of a Sprewell miss. Although it was teamwork by accident,
it was an example of how Houston and Sprewell were able to feed off
of each other for one of the few times this season.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the first half, Sprewell and Houston were finding
each other coming off screens and looking for where the other was
on the break, and that made all the difference for the Knicks. With
Ewing limited to 1 for 5 in the first half, Sprewell and Houston
picked up the slack. Sprewell scored 17 first-half points while
Houston hit for 12.
</P>
<P>
   This was the togetherness the Knicks had hoped for when they
assembled this team. At first, it seemed nothing was going to work
for the Knicks. Playing their fourth game in five nights, and their
second in 48 hours, the Knicks began a little lethargic and clumsy.
</P>
<P>
   They were overwhelmed by the ball pressure the 76ers' defense
applied to begin the game. If they weren't turning the ball over,
Houston and Ward and Larry Johnson were driving into the face of
shot-blockers Matt Geiger and Theo Ratliff. Unwilling to move the
ball to find an open man, the Knicks missed their first 11 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly, they were down 23-8 with 3 minutes left in the first
quarter before they began to slowly reverse the situation. After
Ewing struggled to find his shot and labored as he moved around the
lane, he was replaced by Marcus Camby.
</P>
<P>
   But that did not give the Knicks the kind of physical presence
that Dudley provided when he entered the game with his team down by
19-8. Dudley's arrival meant more rebounds and fewer smooth trips
to the basket by Iverson.
</P>
<P>
   What he did on defense was complemented by Sprewell's ability to
lift the team offensively. Pulling out his wild, frenetic style,
Sprewell put pressure on the 76ers' defense once he began hitting
pull-up jumpers that, as always, seem ill-advised. But once they go
in, they are genius.
</P>
<P>
   His energy pushed the Knicks on a 6-0 run to close the first
quarter. Scoring 15 points in the second quarter, Sprewell pulled
the Knicks back into a game they seemed to have no energy to play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
