<HEADLINE>
KANSAS SENATE VOTES TO PUT COMMUNITY COLLEGES UNDER STATE REGENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLINGER and JOHN L. PETTERSON  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA _ The Kansas Senate voted 26-13 Thursday to place 19
community colleges, including Johnson County's, under the Kansas
Board of Regents, which currently oversees state universities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The higher education reform measure was approved Wednesday by
the House and goes to Gov. Bill Graves, who is expected to sign it
into law. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers from Johnson County said the Legislature's approval
was like waking up from a nightmare and finding out it was real. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   College trustees and community leaders in the county have long
opposed the idea, fearing it would lead to a loss of local control
and result in a bias toward the universities by the nine regents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All six senators from Johnson County voted against it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Senate Bill 345 will drastically change the way higher
education is governed in Kansas, but it will fail in its purpose
because the Legislature has failed to define the problems we are
attempting to solve,'' said Sen. John Vratil, an Overland Park
Republican. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Supporters said the bill's enactment would hail a new era in
higher education. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christine Downey, an Inman Democrat, said it would result
in greater integration and coordination of higher education.
Community colleges currently are under the authority of the Kansas
Board of Education. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, when someone asks who speaks for higher education in
Kansas, the answer will be the Board of Regents, because they will
truly represent all sectors of the higher education community,''
Downey said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All three senators from Wyandotte County voted for the measure,
which was endorsed by Kansas City Kansas Community College. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The measure, in addition to community colleges, would place
post-secondary vocational education programs under the regents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It also would reduce property taxes in almost all counties with
a community college, but not until fiscal year 2001, which begins
July 1, 2000. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starting then, community colleges could receive almost $2.5
million in additional state money each year to improve their
educational programs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The colleges in Wyandotte and Johnson counties would receive
almost half that amount. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. David Kerr, a Hutchinson Republican, questioned the
fairness of a formula giving Johnson County more than $800,000
while several rural, financially struggling community colleges
would get little. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just flabbergasted we have a formula with these kind of
results,'' said Kerr, who voted against the bill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Downey said the formula wasn't perfect but added that the
Legislature could return next year to make it better. She called it
a ``work in progress.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In other action, negotiations surrounding the new transportation
bill continued through the day, with Graves and key lawmakers
huddling in meetings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In order to corral the necessary votes in the House, efforts
were under way to craft compromises in the areas of school finance,
a children's trust fund and money for the juvenile justice
program. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With legislative spending already running above the governor's
recommendations, there was an increasing concern that revenue in
the 2001 budget year might barely meet requirements. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During the day, both houses approved differing versions of
catch-all spending bills that will be consolidated by House and
Senate negotiators. The resulting agreement will be considered
later in the week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both versions included money to establish a satellite Kansas
Bureau of Investigation crime laboratory at Kansas City Kansas
Community College. The exact amount and staffing will be determined
by the negotiators. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Senate upheld Graves' veto of a bill that would
have supplied $300,000 in matching money to organizations assisting
women in bringing their pregnancies to term. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 25-14. Twenty-seven votes are required in the
Senate to override a veto. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the House and Senate included money for the program in their
spending bills, assuring that Graves will have an opportunity to
veto the money again, this time after the Legislature leaves town. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
