<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-SACHS-IPO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG INTEREST EXPANDS SIZE OF GOLDMAN SACHS PUBLIC OFFERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: in reference to E(ASTERISK)Trade, replace (ASTERISK) with
the typographical symbol)  
 (bl)  
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Strong interest from fund managers and even the hint
of an Internet frenzy have prompted such a scramble for shares of
Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. that it could increase the size of its public
offering by a factor of eight and still leave some investors
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, a blue-chip investment bank, plans to list its shares
next Tuesday, formally ending its 130-year history as a private
partnership and becoming the last major Wall Street firm to go
public. The company wound up its worldwide promotional tour with a
lunch for investors at the Plaza Hotel in New York on Thursday. The
offering is at least eight times oversubscribed, people close to
the underwriting said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not your usual IPO,'' said Randall Roth of Renaissance
IPO Fund in Greenwich, Conn., which hopes to get some allocation of
shares from Goldman's underwriters. ``Everyone is into this,
whether it's tech, growth, micro-cap or big-cap buyers. Even the
day traders are interested in this one.''
</P>
<P>
   The final pricing of the shares will not take place until Monday
night, just before the offering. But people close to the deal
expect Goldman shares to sell at the top end of the range the firm
projected, or $55 a share. If Goldman's underwriters sell an extra
tranche of shares held in reserve, bringing the total offering size
to 69 million shares, it would raise $3.8 billion, which would rank
as one of the largest initial public offerings in history.
</P>
<P>
   Even at $55, Goldman's share price relative to earnings would
still be lower than its top rivals, Merrill Lynch and Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter. Goldman's underwriters, led by Goldman itself,
are determined to price shares at a slight discount to rivals. That
is in part because Goldman's earnings are less diverse than those
of Merrill and Morgan Stanley, meaning that Goldman might suffer
more than its competitors if financial markets took a sharp dive.
</P>
<P>
   But Goldman has an almost mythical reputation in some circles.
And some potential investors say it is a good buy at any discount
to rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it trades at a discount to Merrill and Morgan, I will
definitely be an owner,'' said Michael Holland of Holland &AMP; Co.,
which invests in financial company stocks. ``The question is how
long that discount will last,'' he said, adding that he expected
the shares to rise sharply after they list.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman has not yet formally made forward profit projections.
But one person who has studied the offering said that Goldman had
room to raise the share price to the top of its range and still
list at a modest discount to Merrill and Morgan. This person
projects that at $55 Goldman shares would trade at 15 times
earnings, compared with Merrill's 16.5 times earnings and 17.25
times earnings for Morgan Stanley shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goldman wants its best clients to make money on this, and they
are not going to push the limit on price,'' this person said.
</P>
<P>
   Investor demand has been strong enough that Goldman can pick and
choose the investors it wants to own its stock. Goldman has
reserved a big chunk for its own best clients, including big
pension and mutual funds that use Goldman services to trade stocks
and bonds and its own network of wealthy private clients.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman has largely snubbed the huge retail client base of
Merrill Lynch, Morgan and Salomon Smith Barney, rival firms that
are part of the Goldman underwriting syndicate. Individual
investors would have a better shot of buying shares through two
Internet brokerage houses, Wit Capital and E(ASTERISK)Trade, that
were awarded an allocation by Goldman, people close to the
underwriting said.
</P>
<P>
   Some competitors saw this as a slap in the face to full-service
brokerage houses. Goldman has long shunned the idea of setting up a
traditional brokerage operation itself, preferring to concentrate
its resources on wholesale investment banking and asset management.
Recently, Goldman has been developing links to Internet companies,
including E(ASTERISK)Trade and Wit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a bit of a signal here: Goldman is moving more toward
the Internet and away from full-service firms,'' said one person
close to the underwriting.
</P>
<P>
   Others close to the underwriting said that Goldman was simply
selecting investors it expected would hold the stock for a long
time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
