<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DICARLO-NYT </SLUG>
  
 JUDGE DOMINICK DiCARLO, 71, DRUG FIGHTER UNDER REAGAN  
 (bl)  
 By NICK RAVO   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dominick L. DiCarlo, a federal judge and a former New
York state assemblyman from Brooklyn, died April 27 after suffering
a heart attack while exercising at a gym at the federal court
complex in Manhattan. He was 71.
</P>
<P>
   DiCarlo, a conservative Republican who was also an assistant
secretary of state for drug policy in the Reagan administration in
the early 1980s, was, in recent years, a senior judge on the U.S.
Court of International Trade in New York. At his death, he was
temporarily presiding on the U.S. District Court in New York due to
a shortage of judges there.
</P>
<P>
   During his years as a member of the New York state Assembly in
Albany, DiCarlo rose to become chairman of the codes committee and
deputy minority leader. Sometimes called ``the burly bear,'' a
reference to his size and demeanor, he was known for his debating
skills and his knowledge of the criminal-justice system.
</P>
<P>
   He is also remembered as the only Republican in the Assembly who
voted against Gov. Nelson Rockefeller's legislation to toughen
criminal laws against drug offenders. Though DiCarlo was a staunch
opponent of drug dealers, he worried that the laws lumped the
offenders into one category.
</P>
<P>
   According to his son, Robert J. DiCarlo, a former state senator
from Brooklyn, DiCarlo ``was concerned that with broad-stroke
mandatory sentences, people who were not drug dealers would find
themselves in the prison system.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominick Leonard DiCarlo was born on March 11, 1928, in Brooklyn
and raised the Bay Ridge section. He received a bachelor's degree
from St. John's College and law degrees from St. John's University
School of Law and the New York University Graduate School of Law.
He was an assistant U.S. attorney in New York and a counsel to the
minority leaders of the New York City Council before being elected
to the state Assembly in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, he helped run the New York state campaign of Ronald
Reagan, and when Reagan was elected president, DiCarlo left the
Legislature to become assistant secretary of state for
international narcotics matters. He spent much of his time in that
post trying to persuade foreign leaders to supplant fields of opium
poppies in their countries with crops not used for narcotics.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Reagan appointed DiCarlo to the U.S. Court of
International Trade, and President George Bush made him chief judge
in 1991. He left that post in 1996, but still heard cases as a
senior judge.
</P>
<P>
   DiCarlo was predeceased by his first wife, Esther. Besides his
son, Robert, he is survived by his wife, Susan; two other sons,
Vincent DiCarlo of Davis, Calif., and Carl DiCarlo of Brooklyn; a
daughter, Barbara Basgaard of Brick Township, N.J.; four brothers,
James DiCarlo of Commack, Vincent DiCarlo of East Islip, Michael
DiCarlo of Melville and John DiCarlo of Shoreham; two sisters, Rose
Cucci of Wantagh and Constance Testa of Wading River and eight
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 2334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
