</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PENTAGON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Subs to insert two new grafs, about JDAMs, after 5th graf)  
 B-52s TO DROP TRADITIONAL BUT LESS-ACCURATE `DUMB' BOMBS  
 (bl)  
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With stocks of cruise missiles dwindling, Defense
Secretary William Cohen announced Thursday that the Pentagon is
providing 10 more B-52 bombers to NATO forces that would be used
for the first time to drop traditional bombs on Serbian military
targets, as well as firing guided missiles.
</P>
<P>
   A staple of the Vietnam War, when their hulking figures became a
symbol of that conflict, B-52s have been restricted to bombing with
cruise missiles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now the bombers have been allowed to carry ``dumb'' bombs, which
are less accurate in hitting their targets. Dropping bombs without
satellite or laser guidance from high levels is more likely to
cause unintended damage and injury.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are some cruise missiles remaining, the new
B-52s, which will be based in England, will carry Israeli-made
guided missiles, called AGM-142s or HAVE NAPs. The missiles have a
range of 50 miles and carry 750-pound explosives.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not as good as cruise missiles but they are very
accurate,'' a Pentagon spokesman said, ``and we have a stockpile of
120 of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force is running short not just of cruise missiles but
of another precision weapon, the satellite-guided joint direct
attack munition (JDAM) dropped by B-2 (Stealth) bombers, the
general who oversees U.S. combat aircraft told reporters at a
breakfast meeting Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Richard Hawley, head of the Air Combat Command, said that
as the bombing campaign mounts, the Air Force could exhaust its
supply of JDAMs before the next scheduled delivery of a new batch
in May. ``It's going to be really touch-and-go as to whether we'll
go Winchester on JDAMs,'' he said, using a pilot's expression for
running out of ammunition.''
</P>
<P>
   The additional B-52 bombers are part of the 300 planes requested
several weeks ago by NATO's supreme commander, Gen. Wesley Clark;
he said he needed them to wage the air war day and night and to
expand the range of targets. Earlier this week, the Pentagon
dispatched 30 more refueling tankers, to be based in Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   When the B-52s begin bombing with traditional bombs, they will
be used to strike at Serb forces in the field, which are the
hardest to hit, and at military targets, like barracks, that are
far from civilian areas, according to the Pentagon spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the reduced accuracy, the spokesman said,
``everything around it should be military, too, somewhere where
there are no civilians.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen and Gen. Hugh Shelton, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, gave the daily Pentagon briefing Thursday for the first time
since the air war began.
</P>
<P>
   This was read as a sign that the administration is trying to
combat the growing frustration in Congress and among the public
over the lengthy air campaign, which so far has failed to make
Kosovo safe for its ethnic Albanian majority.
</P>
<P>
   Their language reflected a stiffening of posture, if not
purpose, since they met with their allied counterparts in
Washington last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as keeping the American people behind this,'' Cohen
said, ``I think they only have to turn on their television sets
every day and to see the kind of horrendous suffering that is now
portrayed on the evening news,'' a reference to the Albanian
refugees fleeing Serbian forces in Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 2335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990429.0500 </DOCNO>
