<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-29 23:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8925 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOGIBERRA-AD-COLUMN-N     04-29 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOGIBERRA-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE OF BASEBALL'S MOST COLORFUL FIGURES FINDS HE IS IN DEMAND
AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., Mo., Ill., N.Y.)   (Eds: In 15th graf: Each ad features, etc., the word 90 percent
should be replaced with the symbol) 
(af)  
 By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some 35 years after he stopped playing ball, Yogi Berra is
having something of a renaissance as a pitchman. For the former
Yankee catcher, it really is deja vu all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, you can see him in television spots promoting Amtrak
and tourism in New Jersey, and in new print ads for the nonprofit
Yogi Berra Museum at Montclair State University in Little Falls,
N.J. He is also scheduled to appear in May in a funny television
commercial for Nike about baseball. Locally, Berra is appearing in
spots for Hilltop Nissan, a New Jersey dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, PBS is developing a documentary about Berra scheduled
for broadcast this summer, and his 1998 best-selling paperback,
``The Yogi Book,'' offering a collection of his famous phrases,
recently came out in hardcover.
</P>
<P>
   Marketers say the legendary Yankee is topical for a host of
reasons, ranging from the renewed popularity of baseball to the
Yankees' winning ways to the need for heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Also, his well-publicized rapprochement with the Yankees owner,
George Steinbrenner, which came after years of bad blood, was more
than just cathartic. It helped put Berra back in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has always been an interest in Yogi Berra because he has
a strong and colorful personality,'' said Nova Lanktree, president
of Lanktree Sports Celebrity Network in Chicago, who has worked
with Berra in the past. ``He just has those charismatic qualities
that transcend time. Even the younger people get him.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies may be noticing him even more now because of the
``status of the Yankees as the dream team of baseball,'' Ms.
Lanktree said. And his fans say that with the death of Joe
DiMaggio, Berra is now ``the greatest living Yankee,'' a
distinction that Berra himself dismissed, pointing to other great
living teammates of his time like Whitey Ford and Phil Rizzuto.
</P>
<P>
   It could be that Joe DiMaggio's death has simply reminded people
of that precious time in baseball history _ making all the players
from those golden days more valuable to the public. For instance,
within the last six months Phil Rizzuto been getting more calls for
promotions and appearances, Brandon Steiner, president of Steiner
Sports Marketing in New York, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are baseball's oldest living legends,'' Steiner said.
</P>
<P>
   Now 72, but still looking fit in corduroys, spanking white
sneakers and a baseball jacket with his museum's insignia, Berra
shrugged off his popularity in a recent interview, but called it
``a great honor, and it's great that it's all in the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Berra's three sons, Larry, Tim and Dale, and a daughter-in-law,
Betsy, formed LTD Enterprises six years ago to market their
father's career after they realized that Berra was inundated with
about 100 letters a week, most of them seeking his autograph.
</P>
<P>
   As sports memorabilia grew in popularity, the sons decided they
were better suited than agents to protect and promote their
father's image. LTD now runs a thriving mail-order business and has
a Yogi site on the World Wide Web, complete with a Yogi store, a
whole range of memorabilia and Yogi links to favorite sports sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't sell widgets, but I can sell Yogi Berra, it's so
easy,'' said Dale Berra, the youngest son, who played major league
ball from 1977 to 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The print ads for the museum feature a youthful Berra playing
ball in his Yankee stripes, superimposed over such items as a faded
baseball, a glove and a catcher's mask.
</P>
<P>
   Each ad features a funny malapropism that Berra might have said,
but which were actually written by Foote, Cone &AMP; Belding in New
York, a unit of True North Communications. Lines include: ``Every
time you go, it's like you've been there before''; ``We're open
until we close,'' and ``The Yogi Berra Museum: 90 percent of it is
half Yogi.'' The agency is also now working on television spots.
The tag line for of all the ads is ``It all makes sense here.''
</P>
<P>
   Berra said he sees himself as a guy who wanted to play ball. But
even in the early days of television, he was seen as much more than
a ballplayer. The famed advertising executive George Lois said that
in an award-winning television spot he created for the Quaker Oats
Company's Puss 'n Boots cat food in 1960, Berra was one of the
first athletes to be featured not as a direct pitchman, but as part
of a story.
</P>
<P>
   The spot featured Berra, amazed by a cat that had just performed
aerobics on a trampoline, talking to the cat about how to stay in
shape. The cat answers in Whitey Ford's voice.
</P>
<P>
   The irony, Lois said, was that he had trouble selling the idea
to Quaker Oats executives because they did not believe American
women, who bought most of the cat food, could identify Yogi Berra.
Lois had to conduct research to prove the ballplayer's popularity,
which he said was easy since 182 of the 200 women he interviewed
knew Berra.
</P>
<P>
   Lois, now the head of Lois/USA in New York, said the nickname
Yogi and his ``Yogi-isms'' had helped make him a household name.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably even more famous now,'' Lois said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Berra has appeared in dozens of commercials for
products like Miller Lite, Pepsi-Cola, Jockey underwear and, of
course, Yoo-Hoo, with which he had a long and famous association
until a falling out a decade ago over the brand's formula.
</P>
<P>
   Berra said he enjoys the commercial work, and remembers the days
before sports stars won big ad contracts. Back then, Berra said he
had to take odd jobs in the off-season to support his family.
</P>
<P>
   One winter after the season ended, the famous Yankee was a
headwaiter in his native St. Louis. Another season, he sold suits
alongside Phil Rizzuto at a men's clothing store in Newark. He also
said he was happy to pick up $200 or so (big money back then, he
noted) to appear at a banquet. At various times he also worked in a
shoe factory and drove a Coca-Cola delivery truck.
</P>
<P>
   He credited the late Frank Scott, one of the first sports
agents, with getting him out of the kitchen, literally, by booking
television commercials and appearances on programs like ``The Phil
Silvers Show'' and ``The Ed Sullivan Show.'' Berra recalled that he
worked with Scott for years without a contract. Business was
conducted on a handshake.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of dignity and honesty are among the traits that make
Berra so valuable today, said Christopher Paul, 31, an account
executive at Foote, Cone &AMP; Belding who works with Berra.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was growing up, there wasn't anyone that even came
close to a Yogi Berra,'' Paul said. ``Yogi holds a place in history
that not a lot of others hold. He's a national treasure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
