u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-DERBY-410&AMP;ADD-NYT     04-29 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-410&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE END OF NO. 19 POST, MENIFEE CAMP SEES A LIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Two days before the Kentucky Derby, the gloom
surrounding Barn 35 at Churchill Downs was lifting after being
pierced by the old-fashioned trust _ and maybe the piety _ of the
team inside.
</P>
<P>
   Its members needed all the uplift they could get after Menifee
drew the dreaded No. 19 post position in a field of 20, placing one
more hurdle in their path to great expectations for their hometown
horse.
</P>
<P>
   It did not help much that Vicar, winner of the Florida Derby,
drew the unfavorable No. 18. Nor that several other top horses drew
outside posts that might threaten their chances. Nor that every
stable housing a Derby horse was fighting its demons, too.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line was that Menifee, one of the favorites in the
race, would start from the auxiliary gate with only Lemon Drop Kid
to his right, and in order to muscle his way to the mainstream on
the inside, he would have to use early speed and energy to run or
barrel past some of the best 3-year-olds in America.
</P>
<P>
   Menifee would have to confront Vicar on his left, Charismatic,
First American and then, the biggest hurdle of all, General
Challenge and Prime Timber, both trained by Bob Baffert in his
quest to become the first trainer in the 125-year history of the
Derby to win three years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a stable that relies on faith, omens and karma, and
this was a predicament it had faced and survived before. Those
involved all knew that Arthur Hancock, the co-owner of Menifee, had
been plunged into a doomsday mood when he drew the No. 18 post in a
field of 19 for Gato del Sol in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shattered,'' Hancock recalled. ``I went home and lay
down on my bed, and kept asking, `Why me?' I just knew we had lost
the Kentucky Derby. I knew that Gato del Sol would use up his
energy trying to run diagonally across the track from outside to
inside. Finally, I telephoned a friend of mine who was good at
mathematics, and asked him to calculate the extra distance the
horse would have to run.''
</P>
<P>
   The friend drew a right triangle, with the long leg representing
the distance from the start to the first turn. The short leg to the
right was the distance from the rail to the No. 18 post and the
hypotenuse was the distance Gato del Sol would have to run to get
to the rail by the turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a basket case,'' Hancock said. ``Then he called me back,
and said, `The difference is two and a half feet.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gato del Sol won by two and a half lengths.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Elliott Walden, who grew up in Midway near Lexington in the
heart of the Kentucky blue grass country, was the son of the highly
respected horseman Ben Walden Sr. His brother, Ben Jr., owns and
operates the Vinery breeding farm. Elliott Walden has been the
leading trainer at Churchill Downs for the last two springtime
meetings, and last year saddled Victory Gallop, who ran second in
the Derby and the Preakness and first in the Belmont, spoiling
Baffert's bid to sweep the Triple Crown with Real Quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Walden has a second horse in the Derby _ Ecton Park, who is
owned by Mark Stanley and drew the favorable No. 3 post in the
starting gate. But Ecton Park is not given much of a chance, and
has even been relegated by the Churchill Downs oddsmaker to the
mutuel field. Menifee, meanwhile, is listed at 5-1, which isn't
much solace when you've got post No. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we had a redraw,'' Walden said Thursday without
moaning. ``I don't feel that post positions are that important when
you have a quarter mile to go to the first turn. We didn't want No.
19, no. But I had Arthur telling me about Gato del Sol with only
one horse outside him when he won the Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   In the face of the trials represented by the Kentucky Derby,
which will be won by one of the 33,000 foals delivered three years
ago, it is the core business at Barn 35 to sustain the mood and
keep the faith. Hancock, the son of the legendary Bull Hancock of
Claiborne Farm, sets the tone.
</P>
<P>
   He is joined by his partner in Menifee, the New Orleans oil man
Jimmy Stone. They are backed up by Walden and their jockey, Pat
Day, a born-again revivalist who said after he decided to take
Menifee outside and the colt went on to win the Blue Grass Stakes,
``Once the decision was made, I had great peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Walden, 36 years old, is 6 feet 5 inches tall with a boyish face
and forthright manner, and he has zoomed to the upper ranks of
trainers, somewhat the way Baffert has done. And he strikes the
ultimate note for Menifee and his stablemates when he recites his
favorite verse from Proverbs: ``The horse is made ready for battle,
but victory rests with the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   It is that faith the team in Barn 35 is counting on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
