<HEADLINE>
SUCCESS OF GAMING DEPENDS ON ENLIGHTENED INDIAN LEADERSHIP
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By TIM GIAGO (Nanwica Kciji) 
 &HT;    (Tim Giago, Lakota Indian, is CEO of book publishers Lakota
Times Publishing, Inc., located in Sioux Falls, S.D. His Indian
name is Nanwica Kciji.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    When the Indian nations of America began to open bingo parlors
and small gaming casinos on their lands the most active and ardent
of opponents were the casino operators in Nevada and New Jersey.
 &HT;    Well financed, well connected and media-wise, they began a
campaign to place roadblocks in the path of any Indian tribe daring
to venture into gaming. Their attacks included heavy donations to
members of Congress and a media-propaganda campaign aimed at duping
the American people into believing organized crime would soon
become rampant on Indian lands.
 &HT;    One very small California tribe had the misfortune of hiring a
man of questionable background and, supposedly, with connections to
organized crime. When his past began to unravel, the tribe
immediately terminated his employment. But this was the fly in the
ointment the Nevada and New Jersey bigwigs needed to point an
accusatory finger at all Indian nations _ and they used the mass
media as their instrument of fear mongering. Even Donald Trump used
a popular radio talk show to attack Indian gaming.
 &HT;    Those people most brainwashed by this propaganda were officials
and legislators in state governments fearful that the Indian tribes
within their borders would soon approach them seeking compacts to
open casinos on their reservations.
 &HT;    In South Dakota gambling was legalized when the people voted for
a proposition allowing most forms of gambling in Deadwood. This
opened the doors for the Indian nations to offer similar gaming on
their reservations. Indian tribes were not even considered as part
of the equation until the legislation passed and the lawmakers
discovered what they had inadvertently done by placing legalized
gambling in Deadwood on the ballot.
 &HT;    As casinos became commonplace on many reservations a new set of
problems emerged. Should the revenues be handed out to the people
in per capita payments? Would this create a new form of dependency?
Should members of the tribe living off the reservation be party to
the per capita money? If per capita payments are not distributed,
where do we invest our earnings?
 &HT;    One tribe decided to give out a large Christmas bonus to its
members but forgot about the Internal Revenue Service. Of course,
the IRS stepped up and asked for their share. The tribe had to
borrow the money and this placed them in a terrible financial
position. (Why do I keep hearing that Indians don't pay taxes?)
 &HT;    Because some eastern tribes did not consider their status as
sovereign entities so important they signed compacts with state
governments requiring tax payments on their gaming revenues. This,
of course, became an obstacle for many western tribes that were in
the process of negotiating gaming agreements with state
governments. State officials recognized the opportunity to increase
their tax base and refused to approve compacts unless the tribes
paid a percentage of their earnings in taxes. This amounted to
legalized blackmail. The Indian nations of New Mexico were assessed
16 percent of their casino revenues by the state.
 &HT;    Some tribes see gaming as the new buffalo. No recent event has
had such a profound impact upon their lives since the victory over
Gen. George Custer at the Little Big Horn and the Massacre at
Wounded Knee.
 &HT;    But the key to how casino gambling treats the Indian nations of
America lies in the hands of its leadership. Whether it becomes a
secure and stable business depends on the ability of the tribal
leadership to secure solid, fruitful gaming compacts with state
governments and a willingness by the U.S. Congress to help rather
than hinder the efforts of the tribal governments.
 &HT;    In the future some tribes will stretch the limits of their
status as sovereign nations while others will stand firm and
legally and physically defy any threat to their sovereignty. This
might mean that some will start gaming operations without the
benefit of a state compact. Others will be challenging the
authority vested in Congress through the Indian Gaming Regulatory
Act, an Act many tribal leaders consider to be unfair, unmanageable
and anti-Indian.
 &HT;    There are early signs of trouble just as there are early signs
of success. Tribes with traditional, educated and dedicated
leadership have dipped into the revenues produced by their casinos
to rebuild the infrastructure of their nations. They have
constructed new schools, hospitals, government buildings, museums,
colleges and earmarked money for scholarships and training programs
for tribal members. They have re-purchased land that was,
oftentimes, taken from them illegally centuries ago and thus have
expanded the exterior boundaries of their sovereign nations.
 &HT;    Of course, they have encountered opposition from state
governments at nearly every juncture. State governments have been
either blind to the improvements or reluctant to recognize them.
Tribes with 50 percent of their population on welfare 12 years ago
have reduced that percentage to near zero. The casinos have
rejuvenated economically depressed areas in some states by new job
opportunities and increased traffic to the white-owned business
located around the casinos.
 &HT;    The haste by some tribes to give out monthly per capita payments
to each member has created problems that only time can judge. On
one reservation the monthly stipend is so large that the tribe is
having a hard time convincing its young to seek the opportunities
of a higher education. In one state, the percentage of Indians
employed in the casinos was near 70 percent. In the past 5 years
that has dwindled to about 30 percent.
 &HT;    As long as that golden goose is handing out monthly checks, why
work? In some tribes in the Southwest, where the traditional and
spiritual bent of the people ensured a humble demure, a new
arrogance has arisen. It is one that clashes with the very
traditions and cultures of tribes who survived the onslaught of the
settlers with the help of and strengthened by their deep spiritual
beliefs.
 &HT;    But as the luck of the draw will have it, the largest and
poorest of the Indian nations will never be faced with this
dilemma. They are located in sparely populated regions that can
never generate the number of gamblers needed to make casinos
profitable. In 1999 only 5 percent of the gaming tribes earned 90
percent of the profits. This means that 95 percent continued to
struggle economically. The eggs dropped by the golden goose only
landed in a few places.
 &HT;    In the long run much depends on the ability of the tribal
leadership to put gaming into perspective and to use it as a
springboard to diversify their holdings. They cannot allow gaming
to become the tail that wags dog.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Tim Giago 
