<SLUG> BC-THE-ORGANIZER:CHAPMAN-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMEMAKER'S BLOCKBUSTER BOOK PUTS THE WORLD IN ORDER
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``l''
lifestyle and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By KIRSTEN CHAPMAN 
 &HT;    (Kirsten Chapman writes a weekly column for the Columbus
Dispatch in Columbus, Ohio, and is the author of three books,
including recently published ``The Way Home.'') 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ``What am I going to do?'' asked the panicked voice at the other
end of the line.
 &HT;    ``My in-laws are coming for a visit, and the house is a wreck. I
don't know where to begin.''
 &HT;    So, for the sake of her friend in need, Rosemary Brown bundled
up her young son and went to the rescue.
 &HT;    As their children played, the two women moved ``through the
house like a white tornado.''
 &HT;    ``I can't tell you how much I appreciate this,'' the friend said
afterward. ``You made sense out of it. You should write a book.''
 &HT;    ``But this isn't difficult,'' Brown said.
 &HT;    ``It's easy for you,'' her friend insisted, ``but not for
everyone.''
 &HT;    Two decades later, the 53-year old Brown continues to take
readers by the hand and show them ``how'' in her recently published
``Big Kitchen Instruction Book'' (Andrews &AMP; McMeel, $19.95).
 &HT;    ``It was as if she held up a mirror for me,'' said Brown,
recalling the comment that sparked a career. ``Everyone of us has a
gift, but, because it comes so naturally, we take it for granted.
Once you realize it's special, you can begin to share it.''
 &HT;    Share she did _ by establishing Neat Ideas which specializes in
home management; and publishing, ``Getting Your Home in Order.''
 &HT;    The Nashville, Tenn., home she shares with her husband _ H.
Jackson Brown, author of ``Life's Little Instruction Book'' _ could
hardly be more orderly or beautifully arranged.
 &HT;    ``I'm a space detective,'' she admits. ``I love order,
structure, making things fit _ showing how they relate to each
other and putting them in a meaningful whole. I like jigsaw
puzzles, cross-word puzzles, puzzle of any sort.''
 &HT;    Her 432-page Instruction Book, which weighed a hefty 12 pounds
in manuscript form, is a guide to solving one of the biggest
puzzles of all: managing a kitchen. It tells how to streamline and
organize the busiest room in the house. From recipes and menus to
food facts and tips, it offers everything including the kitchen
sink, beginning on page 21.
 &HT;    ``A lot of the information,'' Brown writes in the introduction,
``has slipped through the cracks into the generation gap between
what our mothers and grandmothers knew, and what we need to find
out.''
 &HT;    Through seminars and informal gatherings, she discovered that
people wanted to know more about the kitchen. ``That's where the
rubber met the road for them,'' she said. ``It was the place where
they had the most trouble and needed the most help ... ''
 &HT;    By creating an environment that brings harmony instead of
friction, ``I help people improve family relationships without ...
counseling. It seems like a far jump between `let me help you get
your kitchen organized' to `let me help you with your family
relationships,' but they're connected through a series of links in
a chain. If I can make a difference on one end, that ends up
strengthening that chain all the way down the line.''
 &HT;    Some weeks after the November publication of her book, Brown got
a long-distance call from a wife and mother.
 &HT;    ``Rosemary, I've been married for almost 15 years. I've never
been able to cook a decent meal, never had the courage to invite
people over. Instead, we always entertained at restaurants. And
when I'd pick up the boys after sports, I'd ask, `Do you want to go
to Wendy's? McDonald's?'
 &HT;    ``Finally my oldest said, `Mom, some night could we just go
home?'
 &HT;    ``I want you to know that I've finally put down my fear of the
kitchen. We had our first dinner party where I cooked. It was so
easy, so good ... You've made a difference in my life.'''
 &HT;    What Brown wants most is to encourage people like the caller.
She hopes to reassure them.
 &HT;    ``What they do in taking care of their families is important,''
she says.
 &HT;    ``All of us have insecurities in some areas ... and others where
we shine ... When we know something well, we want to take people by
the hand and save them from grief and embarrassment. We want to
say: It's really not that difficult. All you have to do is know
these few things and then you can feel, `I can do this.'''
 &HT;    Brown considers her book common sense, not revolutionary.
 &HT;    ``I'm surprised no one has ever written all these things down
before.''
 &HT;    One nugget: ``Plan your storage so that you have easy, single
motion access to whatever you use most often.''
 &HT;    For example, many homemakers have a favorite skillet, she said,
``that lives at the bottom of a nest of saucepans. Every time they
want that skillet, they have to take the saucepans out, remove the
skillet, put the saucepans back and close the door.''
 &HT;    Her solution? Hang the skillet on the inside of the cabinet
door.
 &HT;    Brown, who received her first cookbook at age 10, has ``always
had a real desire to do something domestic. I've always been the
homemaker.''
 &HT;    No wonder she values the importance of home. Abandoned at birth
in an Oklahoma hospital on Easter Sunday, she was adopted by a
couple in Dallas who reared her in an atmosphere of love, security
and order.
 &HT;    Many of the recipes in her book share family history _ such as
the sour-cream cookies that her favorite sitter _ ``her godmother's
mother'' _ used to bake.
 &HT;    Rescued herself, she likes to help others the way a fairy
godmother, grandmother, mother or best friend would.
 &HT;    ``That to me, is one of the greatest joys _ to take someone by
the hand and say, ``Let me show you: let me make it easy for you.''
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Kirsten Chapman 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
