<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAN-DIEGO-SUPERCONDUCTOR-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUNG-HO PAK: THE SUPERCONDUCTOR
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``e''
entertainment and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By LEE ANN KIM 
 &HT;    (Lee Ann Kim is a reporter/anchor for KGTV in San Diego,
Calif.) 
 c. 1999 KoreAm Journal 
<TEXT>
 &UR; New America News Service &QC;
<P>
   Anyone who knows Jung-Ho Pak knows not to call him maestro. Even
though the San Diego Symphony conductor and artistic director has
certainly earned the title, he refuses it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maestro means `teacher.' And since I am still learning from
the musicians, I don't like to be called that,'' Pak explains.
``When musicians call me maestro, I also call them maestro. It may
be out of respect that they call me that. But respect is more than
just words. It's about attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for me not to take myself too seriously and be
open to criticism. Keep that respect flowing back and forth.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak, 37, the youngest maestro in the symphony's history and the
only Korean American conductor of a major U.S. symphony, fears
being viewed as a tyrant. ``I've had and seen other conductors and
teachers who were really autocratic. It's very sexy to be bossy.
Very sexy to play the maestro thing. Very ego gratifying. And power
does corrupt. It turns you into a musician who thinks that (he or
she is) good. And really, that is the beginning of the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak's principal of equality carries over into his style of
conducting. Onstage, he leads the orchestra without a baton because
he sees it as a symbol of authority. He does, however, bend his
anti-baton rule when it comes to posing for pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just for publicity reasons,'' Pak explains. ``If I
weren't holding that thing, no one would know who I was. Just some
Korean guy with his hands up.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, slowing down is nearly impossible for Pak, who
conducts full concerts with different orchestras every week. On
average, he'll have one rehearsal a day, maybe two, each lasting
two-and-a-half hours.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Pak's time is also spent on the road or in the air.
Three days a week he jets up north to rehearse and teach at the San
Francisco Conservatory. Twice a week he drives to Los Angeles to
work with the University of Southern California Symphony. When he's
not pulling a statewide commute, Pak is out and about in San Diego
making noise about the symphony through fund-raising, speaking at
schools or teaching students. Somewhere within that schedule, Pak
must also find time to master musical scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to spend a lot of time looking at the score,'' he says.
``But that's so hard to do ... carve out some creative time and
study very quietly and imagine what the composer was trying to say
in a piece.''
</P>
<P>
   On the podium, a conductor's task is more complex than just the
waving of arms. ``Your basic job is to keep the tempo and show what
the pacing of a piece will be,'' Pak explains. ``When you work with
a better orchestra, tempo is less crucial. You can become more
artistic and show more subtlety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ideally, I try to keep track of all the different
instruments,'' he says. ``As I'm conducting, I'm aware of all (of
them) at the same time. I try to find a commonality and move
together as a group.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak compares the unharnessed clamor of classical instruments
with the sound of stepping into a cocktail party: ``When you walk
in, you hear many conversations going on at the same time. It's
almost impossible to understand what everyone's saying.'' Therein
lies the challenge: to create one big conversation by incorporating
many different voices.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can control things like dynamics, articulation and
phrasing,'' he continues. ``And I think having a clear beat is
very, very difficult. It's not quite as simple as it looks. You use
your hand motions, wrist and body stance to seduce and cajole an
orchestra into manifesting music.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak describes the feeling of a flawless performance to a Zen,
holistic state. He points out that when we chew food, we don't
think ``close teeth, open teeth, swallow.'' When the players hit
all the right notes, conducting springs like second nature, and
under the best circumstances, the music is carrying him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my arms hurt, it means the orchestra is going too slow,
so I'm pounding the beat a little harder,'' he explains. ``I have
to conduct bigger. Then I start to think about the mistakes. I
become conscious of the players and of myself ... like if I'm
standing kind of funny.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to his favorite composer, Pak claims it's usually
the one he's currently working on. He does, however, admit favoring
Beethoven and Brahms because ``they blend tradition and revolution
so well.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's a clear winner when it comes to his favorite
conductor: ``I love Leonard Bernstein.''
</P>
<P>
   Since no one in his family is a professional musician, it's hard
to say where Pak picked up his ear for music. He dismisses any
notion of having been a prodigy. But he does credit some of his
success to being Korean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember Isaac Stern once said that Koreans are the Jews of
the Orient,'' he says. ``I think it's true. If you notice, a lot of
the great musicians are Jewish. And from the Asian community,
Koreans are really cleaning up these days. And I think it's due to
our sense of temperament. There's a certain passion that Koreans
have. I think without that in my DNA, I probably wouldn't be as
good a musician.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak was born in 1962 in the San Francisco Bay area during an era
when being Korean in the United States was ``a bit unusual.'' His
parents emigrated from South Korea in the late 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents had your very typical rags to riches story,'' he
explains. ``My father came to this country as a translator in the
army. He studied pharmacy while working at the Van de Kamp bean
factory moving boxes. My mother went to nursing school and
studied.'' After years of struggling, Pak's father became a
pharmacist, but decided to return to school for dentistry. Pak says
it was from his parents that he learned the virtues of hard work.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Korean American children, Pak took piano lessons, but
also learned the clarinet. Yet unlike many Korean American children
for whom learning music is often a ``battle of wills,'' as he calls
it, he was never forced into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have so many stories of Korean parents forcing their kids to
play musical instruments when they don't want to,'' he explains.
``It's the clashing of two worlds. One is the Eastern world that
believes in discipline, obeying your parents, being successful and
being well-rounded. The other is Western where you have television
and sports, where leisure time is a very significant part of
childhood. That's where the battleground is.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak discourages Asian parents from forcing their children into
music, and instead encourages them to support the visual arts.
``One of the great dichotomies that I find in all Korean or Asian
families is that they'll send their children to piano or violin
lessons but they don't attend theater or concerts. So what I'm
hoping to do is get them in the concert hall and participate and
take pride in the fact that a Korean American is here.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak's first joyful moment as a conductor came at age 13, while
he was practicing with his junior high school band.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a substitute teacher, and everyone was egging me on to
conduct,'' Pak recalls. ``I was very shy, but I did it. I remember
waiving my arms, and somehow things were happening. Music was being
made, and I didn't make a fool of myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember being exhilarated and scared at the same time. All
the people were depending on me _ it was quite a thrill, an
incredible rush when all this sound comes at you. It's like a drug
and you want to do it again and again.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak found his place on the podium. He went on to lead the band
in high school, where he established the cornerstone of his
conducting philosophy. ``We used to play at halftime during
basketball games. And that experience helped a great deal because
it taught me how to deal with my peers. I learned I could not
control them by yelling or acting superior. The only way I could
get their cooperation was by being their colleague.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak was so driven by the time he attended the University of
California at Santa Cruz, that he finished his undergraduate degree
in music theory in two years because ``there weren't any
undergraduate conducting programs. I wanted to graduate as soon as
I could to go on to a master's program.''
</P>
<P>
   After earning his MA in instrumental conducting at the San
Francisco Conservatory, he landed his first real conducting job.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to Bethlehem, Pa., to become a conductor at Leigh High
University, ``turned out to be the best thing for me, because I
worked with the jazz band which helped me learn to have fun while
conducting.''
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Pak's mother frowned upon her only son's musical
endeavors. Yet he finally gained her approval in 1992 when he
became a conducting professor at UC Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bottom line, she didn't want me to go hungry,'' he says. ``My
parents went through the Korean War. Once you go through that kind
of poverty and struggling, you just don't want it to happen to your
children no matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak's claim to fame was born out of the financial disaster that
nearly decimated the San Diego Symphony Orchestra. Just
two-and-a-half years ago, the organization claimed Chapter 11 as a
result of fiscal mismanagement. The orchestra played its last note
in the spring of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego needed a miracle: someone who could regain the trust
of the music community and build morale. Someone who had a modern
perspective of a very traditional business. Someone who could make
classical music fun.
</P>
<P>
   That miracle was Jung-Ho Pak.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never any question we wanted him. Everything he is,
everything he's about is what we wanted,'' says Sandra Pay, the
symphony's board chairwoman. ``He looks a lot younger than he is,
but I tell people he's a 55-year-old man because he's done the work
of someone who is 55.''
</P>
<P>
   Last October, the symphony resurrected itself from bankruptcy
under Pak's direction. The agenda for its first full season since
the collapse includes 47 innovative performances such as the
``Light Bulb Concert Series'' in which videos, artwork and food are
used to enlighten the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I've been dreaming about for a long time,'' Pak
says about his most recent concert titled ``The French
Connection.'' During the unprecedented two-hour performance, Pak
and the orchestra led the audience back in time to experience life
in Paris during the 1920s and '30s to pay homage to the era's
greatest composers, from Igor Stravinsky to Duke Ellington. The
night included large-screen projections of French art and racy
video clips of dancer Josephine Baker. In between the music and
videos, Pak conducted live interviews with French poets, art
curators, a food critic, and even a chef who cooked French cuisine
onstage.
</P>
<P>
   Never has the symphony been so interactive and viewer-friendly.
Pak has long believed that the traditional presentation of
classical music must change or ``die and become part of a museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Pak also helped spark the idea of the ``Rush Hour Series'' for
San Diegans caught in gridlock. The hour-long concerts help quell
road rage for drivers facing a stressful commute.
</P>
<P>
   Such ingenuity and innovation have long been missing links for
the orchestra. If all goes well, the symphony will end its
inaugural season in the black. For Pak, that is an incredible
accomplishment _ one that many considered impossible.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999 KoreAm Journal &QL; 
