<TEXT>
<P>
   FINDING HAPPINESS IN THE SOLO LIFE. Columnist Bill Maxwell
didn't realize there were as many as 25 million adults in America
who live alone _ and he is but one of them _ until he read
photographer Adrienne Salinger's book, ``Living Solo,'' that
chronicles this ``unique'' way of life. ``This is the first
generation,'' he quotes Salinger, ``in which living alone is
presumed to be a legitimate choice rather than a declaration of
defeat; unprecedented numbers of people now choose to keep their
own homes, to decorate them, and to entertain in them without overt
societal pressure to adapt to specific notions of family living.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-FLYING-SOLO:MAXWELL-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   WHO ARE OUR CRIMINALS? Though crime rates are generally falling,
observes columnist Raoul Lowery Contreras, criminals come in all
shapes and sizes but tend to hail from America's poor: the rural
poor, the urban poor ... the underprivileged. The conclusion, then,
can be that most criminal activity is by minorities because most of
the poor are minority people. But that, he stresses is were
generalizations end. ``One of the main reasons for high minority
crime rates is illiteracy,'' he points out. And, in the case of
African Americans, it is ``400 years of slavery, subjugation,
segregation and hate that oppress and depress their lives and
spirit _ a condition no one can imagine without being black.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-CRIME:CONTRERAS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k'' commentary
and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   SUCCESS OF GAMING DEPENDS ON ENLIGHTENED INDIAN LEADERSHIP. Some
tribes see gaming as the new buffalo, writes columnist Tim Giago.
No recent event has had such a profound impact upon their lives
since the victory over Gen. George Custer at the Little Big Horn,
and the Massacre at Wounded Knee. But the key to how casino
gambling treats the Indian nations of America lies in the hands of
its leadership. Tribes with traditional, educated and dedicated
leadership have dipped into the revenues produced by their casinos
to rebuild the infrastructure of their nations. They have
constructed new schools, hospitals, government buildings, museums,
colleges and earmarked money for scholarships and training programs
for tribal members.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as SUCCESS OF GAMING DEPENDS ON ENLIGHTENED INDIAN
LEADERSHIP in ``k'' commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   HOMEMAKER'S BLOCKBUSTER BOOK PUTS THE WORLD IN ORDER. Rosemary
Brown didn't realize she had a gift until a friend asked for help
putting her home in order, reports writer Kirsten Chapman. Twenty
years later, the Nashville, Tenn. homemaker has a business _ Neat
Ideas which specializes in home management _ and has published the
wildly successful ``Getting Your Home in Order'' and the recent hit
``Big Kitchen Instruction Book.'' Brown considers her book common
sense, not revolutionary. ``I'm surprised no one has ever written
all these things down before,'' she says, adding ``For me, one of
the greatest joys is to take someone by the hand and say, `Let me
show you: let me make it easy for you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-THE-ORGANIZER:CHAPMAN-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``a''
general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   JUNG-HO PAK: THE SUPERCONDUCTOR. Just two-and-a-half years ago,
the San Diego Symphony Orchestra, writes Lee Ann Kim for KoreAm
Journal, claimed Chapter 11 as a result of fiscal mismanagement,
and the orchestra played its last note. San Diego needed a miracle:
someone who could regain the trust of the music community, build
morale, who had a modern perspective of a very traditional business
_ and who could make classical music fun. Read how Jung-Ho Pak, the
youngest maestro in the symphony's history and the only Korean
American conductor of a major U.S. orcestra, has turned around the
Symphony and, with his ingenuity and innovation, helped it head
towards profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-SAN-DIEGO-SUPERCONDUCTOR-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``a''
general news and ``e'' entertainment files.
</P>
<P>
