A8967 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SUBWAY-PUSH-NYT &LR;      04-29 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUBWAY-PUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBWAY PUSHING SUSPECT HAS HISTORY OF MENTAL ILLNESS, POLICE SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A homeless man accused of pushing a commuter into the
path of an oncoming subway train Wednesday has a history of mental
illness and told detectives that he spent the day of the attack
roaming city streets, convinced people were trying to kill him, a
police official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But investigators said they had found no evidence that Julio
Perez, 43, had committed any acts of serious violence before
pushing Edgar Rivera, 46, onto the tracks of the busy station at
51st Street in midtown Manhattan. The train severed Rivera's legs,
but he survived and was in critical but stable condition Thursday
at Bellevue Hospital Center, said Lorinda Klein, a hospital
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera's wife, Elizabeth, kept a vigil through early Thursday
morning while doctors tried unsuccessfully to reattach his legs.
Friends and neighbors in the Soundview section of the Bronx who
heard about the attack described Rivera, a printer, as athletic,
and intensely devoted and attentive to his wife and three children.
</P>
<P>
   Perez was arraigned Thursday on charges of attempted murder and
assault. He was held without bail and a judge ordered him to
undergo psychiatric tests.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said that Perez lived in a men's shelter with a
special program for the mentally ill in upper Manhattan's
Washington Heights. His court-appointed lawyer, David Kapner, said
that Perez had told him that he was mentally ill and said that he
had been taking medication, but did not specify the precise nature
of the illness or say what drugs he took.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives found several pills on Perez but were unable to
identify them, a law enforcement official said. In a statement to
investigators, Perez confessed to pushing the man onto the tracks,
a second law enforcement official said, and told them that he had
carried out the attack after spending the day walking the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, he said he was roaming around the streets paranoid,
thinking people were out to kill him,'' the second official said.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, a native of Puerto Rico who served in the Army two
decades ago, has been in various homeless shelters since 1995. The
authorities said he had been convicted three times for fare-beating
and twice for possessing small amounts marijuana. He was arrested
in 1996 for aggravated harassment, robbery and weapons possession,
police said, but a check of his criminal record found no
disposition of that case.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, Perez has been in the Fort Washington
Men's Shelter, a 200-bed facility in upper Manhattan, where he
lived in a shelter within the shelter serving 40 mentally ill men
run by Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center called Critical Time
Intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``He slept in our shelter the night before this happened,'' said
Martin Oesterreich, the new commissioner of the city's Department
of Homeless Services. ``You can't cover every eventuality.
Obviously the system didn't work well if we aren't able to prevent
this kind of thing. You have a tragedy like this, it makes you
re-examine everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the details of Perez's situation were far from clear
Thursday _ there remained questions about whether he had been
taking his medicine, for example, and whether he had been receptive
to treatment or had been let down by the system in any way _ the
incident revived the debate over whether the state's laws
concerning the mentally ill should be overhauled.
</P>
<P>
   It is a debate that began gathering momentum three months ago
after a similar incident: the death of Kendra Webdale, who police
said was killed by a subway train after being pushed onto the
tracks by Andrew Goldstein, a 29-year-old with a history of mental
illness. That case led state Attorney General Eliot Spitzer to
propose a new law that would enable relatives and doctors to compel
mentally ill people to receive treatment and medication.
</P>
<P>
   Under current state law, people must be judged both mentally ill
and a danger to themselves or others before they can be committed
against their will to short-term hospitalizations or longer stays
in institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Perez's case highlighted the need
for earlier intervention. ``It certainly indicates a real gap in
the way that we deal with serious, violent mentally ill people,''
he said, ``in that we allow them access to the streets for far
longer, and under circumstances where hopefully that won't be the
case in the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-99 2357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
